		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Annuities: Just Say No</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Annuities: Just Say No</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Investors can do it themselves and avoid the high fees and inflexibility of annuities<p>By Joanmarie Kalter<p>Never underestimate the power of a tax break to make investors behave irrationally. How else to explain the phenomenal growth in the sales of annuities? Investors poured $97 billion into these tax- deferred-savings vehicles in 1995, according to LIMRA International, a financial research association -- almost as much as the record $116 billion that flowed into domestic-equity mutual funds last year.<p>Yet half of those sales were to people whose money was already sheltered from taxes in retirement plans, such as 401(k)s, 403b's, and IRAs. Those investors received no tax benefit from buying annuities. They also paid higher fees and, consequently, earned lower returns than if they had simply invested in a mutual fund. "How can somebody in good conscience sell that?" asks financial planner J. Michael Martin, president of Financial Advantage in Columbia, Maryland. "The benefits don't outweigh the disadvantages," adds David Bohannon, a financial planner in Louisville, Kentucky.<p>Annuities are just complex enough to make it hard for most people to weigh costs and benefits. Most simply, an annuity is an investment contract wrapped in an insurance policy. Investors pay either a lump sum or periodic installments to buy a fixed or variable annuity. With a fixed product, the insurance company that underwrites the annuity and invests those payments guarantees a fixed rate of return, usually for a year. After that, the rate is adjusted annually, based loosely on interest rates, with a guaranteed minimum return of about 3.5 percent currently. Variable annuities let purchasers make their own choices from a menu of mutual funds.<p>The insurance part of the annuity, or wrapper, provides a small death benefit to the investor's heirs and a large tax break to the investor, allowing money in the annuity to grow tax free until it is withdrawn in retirement.<p>The payout on an annuity can take many forms. Investors can withdraw the money in a lump sum or in installments. They can "annuitize" their payout by assigning it to the insurer in exchange for a fixed monthly, quarterly, or annual payment for life. All withdrawals are taxable as income.<p>But even with the tax break, annuities underperform comparable mutual funds. The typical fund offered through a variable annuity charges fees of 2.1 percent a year, compared with the 1.4 percent assessed by the average equity mutual fund, according to Morningstar, which tracks mutual funds and annuities. The extra fees go to compensate insurers for the small risk that they'll have to pay a death benefit and to pay a commission to the insurance agent who sold the annuity. Annuities also charge a surrender fee to investors who withdraw funds early, typically a 6 percent penalty that declines over six years.<p>It's those extra fees that make annuities a poor investment -- even though the tax on accumulated gains is deferred. Consider this example: A 52-year-old (the average age of annuity buyers) in the 31 percent federal-tax bracket puts $25,000 into a variable annuity and chooses a growth fund that pays an average gross return of 10 percent a year. Fees of 1.98 percent a year turn that into a net return of 8.02 percent annually. When he withdraws the money 13 years later at age 65, he'll net $51,835 after taxes, assuming that he's still in the 31 percent federal income-tax bracket. An identical investor puts that $25,000 into a growth mutual fund with the same gross return of 10 percent. This fund charges just 1.19 percent a year in fees -- the average for a growth fund, according to Lipper Analytical Services -- so this investor nets 8.81 percent a year. Each year, he pays income taxes on dividends generated by the fund and the lower 28 percent tax rate on any capital gains. When he retires, he pays capital-gains taxes on any undistributed earnings in the fund. His total nest egg? Almost $1,000 more than the investor who purchased the annuity, or $52,749.<p>That's not the only bad news. Annuities expose investors to two large tax liabilities. First, all earnings on money withdrawn are taxed as ordinary income (at federal rates as high as 39.6 percent), even if those earnings are capital gains, which would otherwise be taxed at just 28 percent. Second, an investor's heirs will be socked with a big tax bill (on top of estate taxes) should the investor die with funds in the annuity. If the initial $25,000 had grown to $100,000, but hadn't yet been withdrawn, the heirs would owe income tax on the $75,000 appreciation. The same gain in a fund or other security would enjoy a stepped-up cost basis at death, freeing it from taxes.<p>The death benefit -- the insurance part of the annuity -- doesn't outweigh these disadvantages. It ensures that heirs will receive at least the investor's initial investment even if the stock market is down when he or she dies. But since most annuities are bought as long-term investments, a return of capital isn't a great reward for a lifetime of saving.<p>Financial planners suggest alternatives that should put more dollars in investors' pockets and that offer more flexibility than most annuities. Martin recommends that conservative investors tempted by fixed annuities (paying an average initial rate of 5.55 percent in December 1995) consider Treasurys with staggered maturities or 
a no-load, triple-tax-free municipal-bond fund. An investor can equal the after-tax return -- and retain the option to cash out before the age of 59 1/2 without a 10 percent tax penalty.<p>Rather than a variable annuity, Bohannon recommends a tax-efficient no-load growth fund, such as the Vanguard Index Trust 500 Portfolio. Its three-year pretax average annual return of 15.56 percent drops to just 14.5 percent after taxes, thanks to the very low 4 percent rate of turnover in the fund's portfolio. The fund charges 0.2 percent in fees annually.<p>Investors can find more information on annuities in The Morningstar Variable Annuities/Life Performance Report ($45 a year, 800-735-0700). It lists almost all annuities on the market, including new variable annuities with low fees and no surrender charges from such companies as T. Rowe Price Associates, USAA Life Insurance, Janus Capital, and the Vanguard Group. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry, Retirement Investing, Mutual Funds Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
