	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Guarding the Nest Egg</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Guarding the Nest Egg</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						More than ever, the safety of your 401(k) is in your own hands -- but a recent court case may shift the onus to employers<p>By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>Is your 401(k) money safe? That's the question of the hour for the 
nation's 22 million 401(k) investors -- most of them baby boomers -- who are relying on the $553 billion in their accounts to see them through their elderboomer years. Given the clout of this group, it's not surprising that First Boomer Bill Clinton, who turns 50 on August 19, recently proposed legislation intended to alleviate boomer worries about retirement.<p>Behind this concern lurks a harsh reality: As corporate paternalism wanes -- 30,000 pension plans have vanished since 1990 -- 
employers are increasingly shoving liability for the rising tide of 401(k) plans onto workers. The Department of Labor regulates the nation's 140,000 401(k) plans, but it will not bail out plans that go belly up, the way the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. saves pensions. So far, thank goodness, no 401(k)s have tanked. It's also illegal for companies to lend money to their 401(k)s in the event of a loss.<p>Critics also say that companies don't apply the same tough fiduciary oversight to 401(k)s that they apply to pensions. That could prove important: Elderboomers stuck with lousy plan choices now could face a dangerously reduced standard of living in retirement, with little recourse to make up the difference.<p>The Labor Department recently proposed new rules to clarify the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, which outlines a company's fiduciary responsibility in administering 401(k) plans. The rules describe the fine line employers must walk if they want to avoid responsibility for bad investments undertaken in their plans. For employees, this can be both good and bad. On the one hand, an employer who follows the rules (they're optional) is more likely to offer a solid plan. On the other hand, by following the rules, an employer protects itself against lawsuits and complaints, even if the employer put poor investment choices into a 401(k) plan.<p>The crucial part of the new rules sets the criteria for determining when information becomes advice. Giving investment advice makes an employer potentially liable for the performance of investments. If the employer stays on the information side of the line, you are legally and squarely in control of your 401(k).<p>By law, a boss must give workers the choice of a minimum of three investment options with different risk and return characteristics. Since employers are liable even if they give advice unwittingly, expect less individualized communication. For instance, employers should not offer individual recommendations about 401(k) assets or personal retirement-planning reports.<p>Asset-allocation models are not considered advice. Likewise, you can't hold employers responsible if they merely offer questionnaires, work sheets, and software to help you estimate future retirement-income needs, as long as the guidelines are based on generally accepted investment theories. Basically, employees should no longer expect investment guidance from benefits professionals on 401(k) accounts.<p>For the most part, employers are not liable for plan losses as long as they do all of the following: make a prudent selection of investment funds and managers; offer an array of appropriate asset classes; leave control over 401(k) money to each employee; conduct ongoing due diligence; and release periodic performance evaluations of the investments or managers. "The conventional wisdom is 'Prudence takes precedence,'" says Dennis Coleman, a principal at Kwasha Lipton, a benefits consulting firm in Fort Lee, New Jersey.<p>If an employer doesn't exercise prudence in selecting investment options, however, it can't assert that employees are responsible for their losses. That's what a federal appeals court in Philadelphia said in January when it ruled in favor of employees who are suing Unisys, the computer maker, over $100 million in 401(k) losses stemming from a guaranteed investment contract and bond fund offered in the company's 401(k) plan. The case still has to return to district court for a final decision, but the appeals decision could set a precedent on behalf of investors. This case is "indicative of how unsettled the law is," says Coleman. "When the market cracks, we're going to see all kinds of suits coming out of the woodwork."<p>Unisys got its investments from Executive Life Insurance of California, which went bust in 1991 because of heavy junk-bond losses. The employees argued that Unisys had breached its fiduciary duties of prudence and due diligence by not suciently warning them about the riskiness of the investments or about Executive Life's horrid financial situation. Employees showed that management's due diligence consisted largely of looking at Executive Life's good credit ratings. <p>Unisys employees also claimed that they lacked control over their plan because the company made them wait a year before they could switch out of certain investments. In its defense, Unisys argued that it was protected under ERISA because its employees controlled their 401(k) assets. The court agreed that Unisys had protection under the law, but also concluded that it may have violated its fiduciary duties of prudence and remanded the case back to district court for trial. "If an employer offers a rat hole of an investment," says Martha Priddy Patterson, an employee-benefits expert at KPMG Peat Marwick in Washington, D.C., "the boss's fiduciary duty does not end by merely disclosing that it was a lousy investment." This issue should become clearer when the district court reaches its decision. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Employment, Government Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
