<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Face the Future</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Face the Future</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Face the Future</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Experts<p>FACE THE FUTURE
The geek chorus (the personal-finance press) is singing the wrong tune about 401(k) plans.<p>By Susan Lee<p>I know, I know. I, too, am loath to read one more word on 401(k)s. Almost every biz magazine and financial newspaper has run a mega-lecture on these self-directed retirement accounts. Worse, this large volume of advice has been high volume as well, with writers complaining that people aren't taking these plans seriously and hectoring those who do about the "correct" investment policy. <p>But if you want a contrarian take on 401(k)s, keep reading. I'm going to argue that a casual attitude toward these plans may be sensible given current constraints, and that as these plans begin to permit a more sophisticated approach to investing the conventional wisdom on the "correct" approach becomes all wet.<p>On the surface, 401(k)s do seem like bonanzas: They let participants invest pretax earnings in a personal account, where the money can grow tax-free until retirement. Even better, some employers match these contributions. So it seems a shame that, according to BPS&M, an employee-benefits consulting firm in Nashville, 26 percent of those eligible do not participate and 95 percent of those who do participate contribute less than they could.<p>But a closer look reveals two major roadblocks. First, the amount contributed in any one year is limited by both the Internal Revenue Service and employers. The maximum allowed by the IRS for 1996 is $9,500. The IRS, however, has a complicated set of regulations that can reduce this ceiling under certain circumstances. And many employers choose to lower it even further. Second, the investment options offered by most employers are awfully motley. A typical combination might include company stock, a money-market fund, and/or a stock-and-bond mutual fund. Some employers offer only one of these options. Given the limits on contributions and investment choices, a somewhat cavalier attitude from potential and actual 401(k) participants seems rational. <p>But perhaps the most misguided view in the recent spate of commentary is that 401(k) holders are not following the correct strategy. The advice swamis carp that investors behave like little old ladies, hewing to conservative, low-return investments. The remedy offered__over and over again__is for participants to pump up their investments in stocks, often to as much as 100 percent of their 401(k) portfolios.<p>Now, if this were the end of the story, there wouldn't be much harm done. But changes ahead will transform 401(k)s into important investment vehicles, and this advice could cause plenty of damage.<p>As employers accelerate the switch from defined benefit plans to defined contribution plans (pensions and the like) and as Social Security and Medicare benefits dwindle, 401(k)s will represent a larger percent of retirement assets. Ted Benna of 401(k) Association, an advocacy firm, estimates that in five years the average account size will grow from about $30,000 today to $45,000 and will represent 40 percent of a family's retirement assets. In five years, total assets in 401(k)s will bulge from the current $640 billion to more than $1 trillion. Observers expect the number to top $10 trillion by 2020, with average accounts in the $200,000 range.<p>Also, a Department of Labor regulation that took effect in 1994 encourages these plans to be more sophisticated. Employers seeking relief from much of their fiduciary responsibilities for employees' retirements must now offer plans that provide three features: a choice of at least three asset categories, sufficient information to make informed choices, and the opportunity to transfer funds among the categories at least four times a year. Employers have responded__by the end of 1995, 80 percent of those offering 401(k)s had expanded the number of investment choices.<p>In short, by the year 2000, we'll be talking not only serious money but serious opportunities. And the exhortation to load up on stocks could become dangerous. Why? Because this advice is based on two dubious premises.<p>The first one says that stocks will produce higher returns than alternative investments in the long run. <p>Probably true, but not decisive.<p>This argument is usually bolstered with a gee-whiz chart showing that an investment in stocks would have returned an annual rate of almost 9 percent over 90 years as opposed to an annual return of 4 percent for bonds. But the performance being measured represents the overall stock market__to get those returns, you would have had to own the entire market. Returns on individual portfolios and stocks varied widely. And overall market-performance figures do not take into account the erosion in value caused by commissions and fees. <p>Moreover, tiresome as it is to repeat, past performance is no guarantee of future performance. It may be just your luck to buy equities at the start of a period of subnormal returns. Yes, the average annual return for stocks over the past 70 years has been around 10 percent. But in the 1970s, according 
to Ned Davis Research, the average return was just 5.7 percent. (By the way, bonds__that little-old-lady investment__achieved an average annual return of 12.8 percent in the 1980s.)<p>Dubious premise number two: An investment in stocks carries little risk. <p>Mostly false. <p>Usually, advice swamis don't point out that the pursuit of high returns also involves high risk. But that's the trade-off, and it should be gravely considered.<p>By switching to defined contribution plans and giving people the opportunity to manage their own money, employers are forcing employees to bear 100 percent of the investment risk. Overloading on stocks adds to that risk.<p>Higher risk, of course, means a higher probability that investments won't perform. If you have dogs in your regular portfolio, you can always compensate by saving more and pumping that money into other investments. But 401(k) contributions are capped. If your investments lose value, you can't recoup. Where's the beauty in tax-free compounding if the value of your portfolio falls to zero? Since the size of your retirement nest egg matters (a quaint but accurate notion), so does safety.<p>Depressed? Don't be. It's possible to structure 401(k) investments to generate both decent and safe returns. Even if you're stuck in a poky plan now, chances are that over the next several years, as companies continue to focus on their plans, you'll see an improvement in opportunities for managing your money. Herewith some thoughts:<p>1. Figure on investing no more than 80 percent of your entire portfolio in stocks__I don't mean stock-market mutual funds but index funds as outlined below. The rest can go into less risky, fixed-income securities, which you should hold to maturity.<p>2. In that total-stock category, squeeze out a lot of risk by putting about 80 percent of your money into a broad-stock-market izandex fund. The simplest, least expensive way to capture the broader market is to buy a fund that tracks the Wilshire 5000 Index. This strategy means that although you won't outperform the market you won't underperform it, either. And since fees for index funds are usually lower than for managed funds__there isn't as much trading and there's no churning__you won't erode the value of your money with expenses or commissions.<p>3. You can still create a frisson of derring-do and the possibility of higher returns by using the remaining 20 percent of the equity portion of your portfolio to buy funds that focus on the indexes of midsize and small companies.<p>4. And last but certainly not least__ buying your company's stock for your retirement account is definitely not cool. You should be diversified and not dependent on your company both for your employment income and your retirement nest egg and income. Yet, as David Godofsky of BPS&M says, "buying too much of the company's stock is the number-one investing mistake we see." If you're already guilty of this no-no, switch out of that stock and into another vehicle at the next opportunity. <p>The sad truth is that more and more of the responsibility for your retirement income is yours. But you can__if you will forgive the mixed metaphor__shoulder that responsibility without having to stomach excessive risk.<p>Susan Lee, a contributing editor, is an economist and the author of Hands Off!Why the Government Is a Menace to Economic Health, to be published in April by Simon & Schuster.<p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement Investing, Employment, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

