<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Paging All Pensioners</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Paging All Pensioners</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Paging All Pensioners</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> PAGING ALL PENSIONERS <p>A federal agency gears up to find missing beneficiaries  <p> By Morey Stettner  <p> Amelia Barca's husband, John, worked as a waiter in Glenwood Landing, New York, for more than 20 years. When he retired in the early 1980s, he expected to get a pension that had been setup by the owner of the restaurant where he worked. But by the time he died in 1989, he still had not received a dime.  <p> "My husband once had a lawyer look into it, but he didn't really discuss it that much with me," says Amelia Barca. "So after he died, I just forgot about it."  <p> Four years passed. In 1993, Barca received a letter from the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation, a federal agency that helps individuals retrieve pension benefits from employers whose plans are now underfunded. The PBGC asked Barca to submit a copy of John's birth certificate and complete some forms. Seven months later, she opened her mailbox to find a check for $12,000, which represented part of her late husband's retirement benefits. She also receives small monthly payments that will continue for the rest of her life.  <p> For an invisible group, missing pension-plan participants are the focus of much attention these days. Private industry and the feds both want to find them to deliver the good news--a pension check--and now they're teaming up to track down missing beneficiaries. Under regulations scheduled to take effect in early 1996, the PBGC will serve as a clearinghouse to find retirees and ex-employees owed pensions from fully funded plans that were offered by employers and then terminated (though it will search only for beneficiaries whose plans ended after the new rules take effect). Under the new mandate, private plan administrators who cannot locate participants after a diligent search can turn over the pension money to the PBGC, which will conduct its own search.   <p> There are three main categories of lost pensioners. The first don't realize they're entitled to benefits. Barca was in this category, as are other survivors who never apply for a deceased spouse's pension. A second group is made up of ex-employees who know they should get a pension but cannot locate their old company or plan administrator. The third consists of workers who know they should receive a pension but figure it's not worth much and don't bother to pursue it. "They're typically transient employees,"says Lynn Dudley, director of retirement policy at the Association of Private Pension and Welfare Plans in Washington, D.C. "They disappear and leave no forwarding address, or they suddenly quit and don't go through a normal exit-interview process, so they miss out learning about their pension benefits."  <p> Almost all companies with defined-benefit pension plans want to locate former workers to give them their money. Otherwise, federal law mandates that the employer must hold the funds and keep administrative records--which can get costly--only to turnover the unclaimed cash to the state treasury if the pensioner isn't found (usually after five to ten years of searching--the time varies by state). With an increasing number of job hoppers leaving a legacy of short stays and small pensions with a variety of employers, there will likely be more misplaced pensioners over time.  <p> That's where the PBGC steps in. The PBGC has traditionally paid pension benefits to people stuck in private plans that couldn't meet their obligations. Today it has expanded its role: It helps individuals track down benefits from companies that may no longer exist, and it hunts for missing pension holders. Case workers review records from Social Security, the IRS, and credit agencies to locate former plan participants.   <p> If you or someone you know might be due pension benefits, the first step is to gather the necessary paperwork. A plan summary benefit report or other pension documents is the best proof of owed money. If those are unavailable, employment records suchas W-2s or pay check stubs can help establish proof of benefits. <p> Once you've shown that you're due benefits, the next step is to locate your plan administrator and find out how much money is left in the pension plan. This information is available on Form 5500, which pension administrators file with the Department of Labor every year. You can get a copy of Form 5500 by writing to the Department of Labor, Pension & Welfare Benefits Administration, 200 Constitution Ave. NW, Room N-5638, Washington, D.C. 20210. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency, Retirement

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
