<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Retirees Pay for Pension Politics</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Retirees Pay for Pension Politics</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The Clinton administration is pushing pension funds to pursue social improvement before fiscal returns <p>By Jonathan Butler<p>Last fall the buyout and rehabilitation of a run-down housing project on Massachusetts Avenue in Boston's South End was rescued when the Massachusetts State Teachers' and Employees' Retirement Systems supplied $2.2 million to close the deal. The 11th-hour save was a godsend for the 73 low-income families living in the complex. It also generated glowing publicity for state treasurer Joseph Malone. "Through this investment people are going to own their own homes, a neighborhood is going to be revitalized, and people in the construction trades will be put to work," said a beaming Malone, who oversees the state pension funds. "That's a win-win situation."<p>Significantly absent from the winner's circle, however, were the people whose money was being loaned and whose futures depend on the success of the investment__the pension-plan members 
themselves.<p>The financing for the South End project is part of a trend toward using public pension-fund money (public funds in fact belong to the state and local workers who pay into them) to invest in areas the capital markets often avoid, such as low-income housing and small-business development. The growth of these so-called economically targeted investments, or ETIs, has provoked debate over the wisdom of spending tens of billions of pension dollars on investments that often yield lower-than-average returns or entail increased risks in order to achieve certain social goals.<p>Men and women 65 and over make up the country's fastest-growing age group. Simultaneously, the baby boomer population is entering middle age. This demographic surge occurs as the importance of pensions to retirees is also increasing. The national savings rate between 1981 and 1993 averaged only 3 percent, versus 7.7 percent from 1945 to 1980, and defined-benefit pension plans__in which an employer promises to pay a specified amount to a retiree__are the only significant savings many people have.<p>Many public funds are ill-prepared to meet this demographic and fiscal challenge. According to a report issued by the Wyatt Company, a Washington, D.C., consulting firm, contributions to funds in the early 1990s fell 15 percent from the early 1980s, as Congress, "in a triumph of the short term over the longer term ... gradually chipped away at the amount employers can set aside in tax-qualified retirement plans." The effects of this decline can be seen in a 1991 General Accounting Office study of 189 state and local plans that found 68 percent were underfunded, meaning they may not have adequate assets to meet future obligations. Washington, D.C., for example, has only $2 billion in assets to cover a $7 billion pension liability.<p>Underfunding is particularly worrisome because most state employees are over age 41 and expect to retire before age 60. "The proportion of pension plan participants receiving benefits rather than contributing to the plan could increase quickly in the near future," said the GAO.<p>Still, as the ability of pension funds to provide for their members grows more uncertain, the Clinton administration is pushing public-pension-fund investment in ETIs. Secretary of Labor Robert Reich is especially keen on ETIs, particularly as a way to pay for investments in housing and infrastructure the deficit-strapped federal government cannot afford.<p>To date, the $920 billion public-fund sector has sunk well over $20 billion into ETIs. What Reich and other ETI supporters play down, however, is that these public-spirited investment vehicles commonly return far less than traditional stocks and bonds.<p>ETI programs are similar to the "social investment" portfolios that invest only in "green" companies or in firms that do no business with egregious human-rights violators like Iran. Richard Ferlauto of the Center for Policy Alternatives, a progressive think tank in Washington, D.C., says that ETIs should not be judged purely on a fiscal basis, as "they provide greater overall social return per dollar invested." In addition, according to Reich and to Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration chief Olena Berg, ETIs, unlike social investments, can deliver a competitive rate of return without taking on extra risk. They argue that when a pension fund invests in a community, it boosts the local economy, ultimately increasing the long-term returns of the investment.<p>The experience of the Equitable Life Assurance Society, which has managed a $78.8 million real estate portfolio called the Community Mortgage Program for 16 years, suggests these assumptions are false. Between 1978 and 1991, CMP, which Equitable calls "the prototypical ETI program," underperformed all other major market indices. During this 14-year period, CMP, with roughly half its funds in multifamily homes, realized annualized returns of 10 percent, compared with the S&P 500's 16 percent and the Salomon Mortgage Index's 12.1 percent. Put another way, a $10,000 investment in 1978 would have grown to $37,975 in CMP, $79,875 in the S&P 500, and $49,485 in the Salomon Mortgage Index.<p>A 1994 study by Olivia Mitchell, executive director of the Pension Research Council at the Wharton School in Philadelphia, also found that investing in ETIs leads to lower overall returns. According to her calculations, a pension fund allocating 5 percent of its assets to ETIs, as their proponents recommend, would suffer a two-percentage-point decline in annual returns. This would create a serious problem for some funds, which rely on investment returns for more than 80 percent of their pension payments.<p>Nonetheless, Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Henry Cisneros testified before the Joint Economic Committee on June 22, 1994, that ETIs are a "profitable" way to play the "capital investment gaps" that exist in every market, even the huge, liquid home-mortgage market. <p>This view is echoed by Jon Lukomnik, deputy comptroller for pensions for New York City. He claims that ETI originators can make money finding underserved and creditworthy niche markets, using "specialized knowledge to take advantage of market inefficiencies in exactly the same way a biotech manager knows more about the biotech field." Lukomnik's $332.5 million Community Preservation Corporation program at the New York City Employee Retirement System, which makes low-income housing loans, has annualized five-year returns of 12.7 percent. However, he says, "Slapping the words ETI on a bad investment doesn't make it a good investment. It makes it a dumb investment." Data from both Mitchell and Equitable, however, suggest that more often than not, ETIs are "dumb."<p>Despite their generally poor performance and dubious grounding in market economics, ETIs have been approved by the regulatory agencies overseeing both public and private funds. For public funds, investing in ETIs meets the IRS's "prudent person" rule, which requires that investment decisions be made with the "care, skill, and diligence" of a prudent individual. The Department of Labor has also ruled that ETIs do not violate the Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA), the 1974 law designed to protect pensioners' rights. Both these laws require managers to invest only in the interests of pension-fund members. <p>Republican Congressman Jim Saxton of New Jersey has publicly criticized the Department of Labor on this point, saying, "The DOL seems to have abandoned its designated role as watchdog for compliance with fiduciary duties."<p>Olena Berg denies this, saying her department's role is to educate pension-fund managers about new investment options. "By no means should any of this be taken as encouraging plans to take substandard returns," she says.<p>Some pension-fund officials, however, report being "encouraged" to invest in ETIs. The chief of staff of one state fund says the federal government is using the threat of revoking pension funds' tax-exempt status to increase their receptiveness to ETIs. "They can enact tax policy to change the way people invest," says another fund official. <p>Again, the Labor Department flatly rejects such charges, but Berg recognizes that ETIs carry some inherent risks. In a department bulletin published last June, she conceded that some ETIs "may require a longer time to generate significant investment returns, may be less liquid and may not have as much readily available information on their risks and returns as other asset categories." In addition, the returns on these illiquid and often unfamiliar projects are set not in a large public market, but by a small number of interested players.<p>Despite these warning signals, the Institute for Fiduciary Education in Sacramento, California, reports that in 1992 roughly 40 percent of public pension plans participated in ETI programs. Since then, the Clinton administration has stepped up its advocacy campaign, and it seems reasonable to assume that a still higher percentage of funds today invest in ETIs.<p>Over 80 percent of ETIs are mortgage- or real estate related, and this is the one area where they have been extensively analyzed. Treasury Department assistant secretary Alicia H. Munnell, formerly a vice president at the Boston Federal Reserve, studied targeted mortgage investments in 31 states in 1983 and found almost all involved either an "inadvertent or deliberate sacrifice of return." The few states that did achieve market rates of return did little to increase the aggregate supply of mortgage funds.<p>Mortgage-related ETIs are almost always safe because they are guaranteed by state or federal organizations (in the 1980s, Alaska Retirement Systems lost millions buying unguaranteed in-state mortgages). However, many of the programs that have generated competitive returns have done so at taxpayer expense. New York City's Community Preservation program's 12.7 percent returns, for example, surpassed the 8.8 percent yields of Ginnie Mae bonds, but achieved this in part through a government subsidy of roughly 3 percent. <p>Such subsidies are essentially hidden taxes, says Roger Howeiler, head of the Seattle Employee Retirement System, which has thus far steered clear of ETIs. "Somebody's paying for it," he says. And the most common reason somebody, whether the taxpayer or the pensioner, winds up paying for ETIs is politics. The record of pension funds that invested in projects for political reasons is predictably dismal.<p>In the late 1980s, for instance, the Kansas Public Employees Retirement System, at the urging of Governor John Carlin, invested in the Home Savings Association of Kansas City and the faltering Christopher Steel company in Wichita. The subsequent failure of both of these firms, together with other ETIs gone bad, ultimately cost the state fund between $138 and $236 million and led to several convictions for criminal mismanagement, according to a Prudential Foundation report. The state now prohibits ETI investments by public funds.<p>All sorts of ETI opportunities have captured the political imagination and later wound up on some fund's books. According to Thomas Donlan, author of Don't Count On It, a book on problems within the pension industry, Governor Bill Clinton himself helped convince the Arkansas Teachers Retirement System to finance a mortgage loan for the Kappa Kappa Gamma sorority house at the University of Arkansas. "I know the daddies of those girls, and there is no way they would have let that loan go bad," the ATRS executive director later said in justifying the investment.<p>The same oil-and-water mix of politics and investing is invariably present with ETIs. Writing in the Columbia Law Review in 1993, pension expert Roberta Romano said that the political affiliation of many trustees makes public pensions especially vulnerable to pressure by state officials. One East Coast plan official said, "In many states, the office of treasurer is a quasi-political office. People who aspire to political office do things that aren't in the interest of the fund." A West Coast counterpart said flatly, "Any drive to do ETIs comes from politically active members of the pension board."<p>Thus far, ETIs have been largely confined to public pension funds; only a few plans in the $5 trillion private, or corporate, pension universe have invested in them, despite the Department of Labor's enthusiasm. Still, the nation's largest private fund, the $135 billion TIAA/CREF (a retirement fund for private-school and college teachers), set aside $25 million for ETIs in 1993, perhaps a sign that the vast private funding pool is also growing more receptive to these investments. Greenwich Associates, a Connecticut-based consulting firm, reports that 6 percent of all endowments and foundations invested in ETIs in 1993.<p>Pension-plan members are virtually never informed when their funds invest in ETIs, but Karen Ferguson at the Pension Rights Center in Washington, D.C., says private-plan members can find out about them by writing their plan administrator and requesting Form 5500. Most plans with more than 100 members must provide with this statement a list of investments that would include any ETIs.<p>Those invested in state or local public plans should ask the administrator to send the Comprehensive Annual Financial Report, says Paul Zorn of the Government Finance Officers Association. If ETIs are not mentioned, do not assume they don't exist. Write a letter to the plan administrator asking specifically about ETIs. Also, most public plans have elected board representatives who can be contacted. Public and private plan members with suggestions or complaints should write to the chairman of the board of trustees. "They should speak up," says Ferguson. "It's their money."<p>It is ironic that Labor Secretary Reich, a self-proclaimed champion of the middle class since the days when he was a graduate student at Harvard, should have led the charge for ETIs. The likely losers, after all, will be the middle-class pensioners__whose retirement may be considerably less secure and comfortable than it might otherwise have been.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Real Estate, Economy, Retirement<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

