<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Paradox Found</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Paradox Found</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Paradox Found</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Feature  <p> PARADOX FOUND <p>They aren't rich, they didn't plan and save, but they're living the retirement of everyone's dreams. Should we all follow these older Americans? Or is life on a Third World tropical island something less than the Great Escape?  <p> By Elizabeth Royte  <p> Ray Steinbach rises early, sniffs the breeze from his screened porch, and considers the small breakers riffling over the coral reef in his backyard. It's too windy to fish today, he determines, so he gets his maid, Lee--"Don't ask me her last name," he says;"I can't even pronounce it"--to fix his breakfast, and then he's off in his launch, a short hop across a crystalline channel, to get his truck.   <p> Steinbach, 67, is a robust, tall man with the placid demeanor of a rural Midwestern veterinarian, which he was. Doc, as he's known, comes from Overton, Nebraska, a town of 665. His eyes are a clear blue, his arms muscular and tanned. Seven years ago, divorced and looking for a place to retire, he scanned the globe and settled here on Roatan, a small island off the northern coast of Honduras. "In Australia, everything was so far apart, you couldn't function," he says. "Hawaii was expensive and touristy. Arizona was a rip-off. You could do two things: golf or polish rocks. I like to hunt, to fish, to travel. In the Bahamas, the people had a negative attitude; Cozumel was too touristy. You know, every other place just looked kind of stupid to me."  <p> Doc had first visited Roatan, one of Honduras's three Bay Islands, on a diving vacation in 1986. The next year he bought a one-acre beachfront plot, in the backyard of a divers' resort, for $28,000. On his simple octagonal house--two bedrooms, two baths, two hammocks on the porch, one satellite dish, and a free-standing ice machine--he spent another $45,000. "The ice is for my fish," he says.  <p> "I chose Roatan because I liked the common folk here and the weather and the fishing," Doc says. "I honestly can't say there's a single drawback. I go to Florida once a year for three days of shopping--some food items I can't get here, mechanical parts--and that's two days too long. I can't stand the traffic, the weather, the crime. Here I can do anything I want. Here I have freedom." <p> For Doc, freedom means lighting out in his powerboat and drifting around the Little Hog Islands. It means sending his down rigger a thousand feet deep and pulling up snapper, grouper, and silks. It means doctoring the locals' animals, leaving the cooking and cleaning to Lee, catching a 30-minute nap after lunch, and scuba diving with the whales if they happen to swim by.  <p> Doc Steinbach is one of a growing number of Americans looking for sand, sun, and the other tropical elements that make up an early universal retirement dream. Where in the past only lottery winners and Marlon Brandos got to drop out of society to live on a remote island, more and more older Americans are coming to realize that retiring on foreign soil isn't just an escapist option--it may be the only way they can afford to live in comfort and style.   <p> Americans today are working longer than ever before and ending up with less to show for it. As the prospects of a high standard of living in their home communities dwindle, more and more retirees--now totaling 360,000, by the Social Security Administration's last count--are moving abroad, to countries where a fixed income goes further, where younger American expats have already made inroads, the economy and political climate are stable, and trips home to the States are routine affairs. Given that prescription, it's not surprising that tens of thousands of retirees have settled in Mexico, Costa Rica, and Belize in the last decade or so and that Roatan, just slightly more difficult to reach, is beginning to catch on.  <p> Doc parks his pickup outside a hardware store in French Harbour, a bustling, cramped town with one narrow, rutted road and several dozen pulperias--small shops that sell rice, beans, polyester T-shirts, and other essentials of Honduran life. From deep in the barrio wafts the Third World smell of burning garbage and sewage. This is the other Roatan, the side most of the island's hundred or so expatriates avoid: the barefoot children, the abscessed dogs, the pigs running in the mud.  <p> But Doc isn't like most expats. He knows what Roatan is really about because he socializes with locals and works with them; he eats their food, and they eat his fish. Mornings when the wind is up and fishing isn't an option, Doc can often be found at Mac's Meat Market poking into dogs and cows and pigs, treating them for mange and parasites. "You've got to stay busy here,"Doc says. "Otherwise you start to get a little soft in the head." <p> Doc doesn't charge for his services, but he's found that helping his neighbors pays off in other ways. "I get my lobster and shrimp for free, because I doctor the fishermen's animals," he says, puffed with pride. "A mechanic works on my car and boats, because I wormed his hogs. They invite me to their houses for dinner. The treat here is iguana. I damn near threw up the first time I ate it. Now I love it."  <p> Swinging open the door of the hardware store, Doc locates Edgar Bodden, a skinny, mocha-colored man in his early 20s. Edgar, who works in the store's business office, is an eighth-generation Roatan native. He went to college in Louisiana and is among the island's solid middle class--of builders, purveyors of durable goods, and providers of upscale services--that's benefiting from the boom in Americans.  <p> With the islander in his passenger seat, Doc drives to Edgar's white ranch house, nestled among palm trees atop a small hill. Edgar retrieves a plastic rice sack, from which Doc pulls out a frosty-looking black-and-tan puppy--Doc's mission this morningis to find out why the puppy died.   <p> "She's still a little hard," Doc says, placing the puppy on his truck tailgate, "but we should be fine." Working quickly, he separates the liver from the intestines, the kidneys from the pancreas.  <p> "Kidneys look normal," he says, "but look at these spots on the liver." He points with the tip of his postmortem knife. When he sees the blood in the intestines, he knows what he's looking at: parvo. He slides the rest of the puppy into the sack, and Edgar disposes of the carcass.  <p> In Roatan, Doc Steinbach fancies himself mayor, city council member, and Santa Claus, all rolled into one tall Midwestern guy in a blue cap. It takes him half a day to pass through town, he's got so many local people to yell hello at. "Hey there,"he shouts out the window of his little red truck to a young woman."How ya doin', buddy?" he waves to a toothless old man. The man nods in greeting. "Hi, partner. Need a lift?" he asks a teenager. He flirts with elderly women, he jokes with little boys. On the main road he loads up his truck with young men waiting for collectivos, the local jitneys, but he's wary of big women. "You get a couple of those 200-pounders in there, you're in trouble," he says, winking.  <p> "Doc adapted to our lifestyle, the slower way of doing things, "Edgar had said while Doc chatted up the young women in the store. "Other Americans come and expect to bring their lifestyle here. "Doc sums up his position like this: "The locals are the ones you want to get along with. The Americans don't matter."  <p>  <p>Harvey Meyer, an American, certainly matters--if not as a presence in Doc Steinbach's daily life, then as a pioneer. If Meyer hadn't settled in Roatan 34 years ago, there might well be no Americans on the island today.  <p> Meyer, 78, tends to describe Roatan with sunny adjectives; his anecdotes about the past are rife with high times and nutty neighbors. It's up to Virginia, his wife, to sketch the shadows around Harvey's bright memories. But on one point they do agree: Roatan has provided a most successful escape from the noise, crime, and expense of the United States. "I can't stand those eight-lane freeways, the shopping till you drop," Virginia says. "We go up there to torture ourselves so we appreciate this place when we get back." <p> This place is the gracious two-story house the Meyers built in Oak Ridge, a bustling fishing port. With its sandy beaches and surf, mangoes and marlin, the Meyers knew it was paradise the minute they saw it. "I loved the people, the pace of life, everything," Harvey says, delighted, even today, when he thinks of it. He reaches for Virginia's Imperial and takes a deep drag. <p> Now she cuts in, snatching back her cigarette with a wry smile."It was grim and rustic," she says, inhaling.  <p> The Meyers moved to Roatan from Newport Beach, California, where Harvey was a sports-car dealer. Harvey first visited Honduras in 1960. He flew to La Ceiba, on the mainland, where he met a man with a Piper Tri-Pacer prop plane. "There were no boats running to Roatan then, and the island had no airport," Meyer says. "This man said, Meet me at the plane at 6 a.m., and we'll see if we can find a place to land.' " They circled, buzzed a few cows out of a pasture, and then Harvey Meyer became the first person to step out of an airplane on Roatan. The next year he would return for good, bringing with him the means to build an iceplant. At first, ice meant only one thing on Roatan: cold beer. But soon it also meant commercial fishing, which, along with tourism based on scuba diving, has become the heart of the local economy.  <p> The Meyers don't know Doc Steinbach, and in truth there's no reason they should. Doc is the expat of our imagination--eating new foods, fumbling with a new language, embracing the values of his adopted land. Harvey and Virginia, for whom Honduras holds nothing new, no longer see the charm in such exertions.  <p> But it wasn't always this way. As recently as15 years ago, the Meyers lived without hot water. Until 1993, just a dirt track connected Oak Ridge, in the middle of the island, to Coxen's Hole, the island's capital, in the west. The road snaked around the mountainous spine of the island, winding and bending up and downhill for 24 miles. It took half a day by car. Until 1991, to make a phone call, the expats had first to get to Coxen's Hole, then find a plane to take them to the mainland. If the expats wanted pork or beef, they waited until someone killed an animal. If they wanted chicken, they'd visit a neighbor and point out their dinner in the yard.  <p> Throughout the '60s, the Meyers were more or less on their own. It wasn't until the '70s that more Americans began arriving--on yachts and on diving vacations. Attracted by the weather, the low cost of living, and the endless-summer ethos, many stayed. The younger ones opened dive shops and resorts; the older ones built their pleasure domes, hired local help, and thumbed their noses at the poor slobs back in Detroit, Denver, and Chicago.  <p> A sense of adventure fueled these pioneers, and the frustrations brought them together. Over their VHF radios, they'd arrange cocktail parties, barbecues, and card games. "Everyone knew everyone in those days," Virginia says. "People were interesting; we were snorkeling, having fun." Because Roatan had no theater, gallery, movies, bowling alley, golf course, or baseball diamond--and still doesn't--house calls became the sole pastime. And because it took so long to get anywhere, visiting couples would stay at their host's for several days. It was all very 19th century,both in spirit and in the particulars.  <p> The expatriates seem to have built their houses with entertaining in mind. Their kitchens are capacious and well-stocked. Everyone has at least one spare bedroom; dining tables seat 12. As electricity became more dependable, the Americans, long deprived, rushed headlong into the 20th century. They bought electric grills, CD players, and large-screen TVs. They installed microwave ovens, blenders, food processors, and electric knives, the better to carve their Thanksgiving turkeys.  <p>  <p>As every vacationing scuba diver on Roatan quickly learns, Columbus visited the Bay Islands in 1502, though he didn't land on Roatan. For the next century, the Spanish visited frequently to shipout the local Paya Indians as slaves and to provision their ships. In 1638, Puritan settlers from Maryland became the first Anglosto set up on the islands and gave it the English identity it still has.  <p> The British laid official claim to the Bay Islands in 1742 but granted them to Spain, after struggles both military and political, in 1748. The Paya had long ago been exiled to the mainland, and successive waves of black Caribs--descendants of Carib Indians and African slaves--and white and black Cayman Islanders settled here. In 1821, Honduras won its independence from Spain but wasn't able to control the islands, and in 1852, England officially annexed them. Under pressure from the United States, Britain finally ceded the Bay Islands to Honduras in 1859.  <p> Because of its widespread poverty, lack of infrastructure, and a perception of being politically dangerous, Honduras never attracted a lot of tourism, let alone foreign investment. American retirees in Central America have traditionally favored Costa Rica and Belize. But Honduras has never had a civil war or guerrilla army, and the Bay Islands, where the people speak mainly English, still seem more Caribbean than Central American.  <p> Roatan certainly isn't the gringo retirement mecca of the Americas: Every month  56,000 Social Security checks go to Mexico alone. But as Mexico has become more industrialized and prices have risen, Americans have followed a trail south, stopping in Costa Rica, Belize, and Guatemala. About 17,000 retired Americans make their primary homes in Central America and the Caribbean.  <p> The Honduran government makes it fairly simple for Americans to move here: There is no duty charge on the first load of household goods, the first car, and the first boat, though there is a $1,000 fee for establishing residency. The government asks only that newcomers be in good health and free of AIDS (a letter from a doctor will suffice) and that their bank accounts are sufficiently padded to preclude their seeking work (it likes to see $600 a month steady). Expats pay taxes of $50 per $100,000 of their property value per year, a poll tax of less than a dollar per year, and about $3 a year to keep a driver's license. It costs about $100 a year to license a car; insurance is not required. Most expats travel on U.S. passports and pay $25 a year to renew their residency cards.  <p> The Meyers live on about $1,000 a month, which comes out of their Social Security checks and a few investments. If they rented a smaller house and lived more like Hondurans--used less electricity and ate more native foods--they could get by on half as much. Americans typically pay $40 or $50 a month for electricity, $4 for water, $10 for propane.  <p> And for another $50 a month, they get the luxury they all seeas a necessity: a maid, or as most expats call her, a girl. The girl, on Roatan, has come to symbolize the good life, the reason these Americans have dropped out of the industrialized world and accepted the myriad frustrations of a remote Honduran island. The Meyers' girl cleans six days a week, for which she is paidless than $50 a month. Two boys come regularly to help with yardwork, bathe Mr. Pickles (the Meyers' schnauzer-shaped mutt), and do maintenance around the Meyer compound--a three-acre lot with a barn-size workshop, laundry house, dock, and boathouse."We couldn't afford to live this way in the States," Harvey says."It's just a better life here."  <p> The fly in the ointment for these retirees--all of them getting on in years, most of them uninsured--is health care. Some things they take care of on trips back to the States. Pressing problems can be addressed in San Pedro Sula, on the Honduran mainland, where the hospital is clean, efficient, and staffed largely byAmerican-trained doctors. But for the most part the expats takecare of themselves, buying pharmaceuticals over the counter at the island drugstore. Better the Merck manual, they joke, than the local doctor.  <p>  <p>The Americans on Roatan do their share of good deeds for the locals--sending kids to the States for operations, putting a roof on the library, buying uniforms for schoolchildren--but a certain animosity between the two groups festers. Locals, whose first impressions of Americans came from well-heeled divers on vacation, tend to think of them as arrogant and rich, warped by superiority complexes. Indeed, expats habitually denigrate the quality of local workmanship and services; they roll their eyes at mundane inefficiencies. Though many older expats say they love Roatan because of its friendly, open people, their behavior belies this sentiment. "Oh, sometimes when we have a party, we'll invite a local," says one retiree, "but, you know, only the more affluent ones." The expats are particularly disheartened by the influx of mainland Hondurans, who are referred to, with undisguised disdain, as "the Spaniards." "We never would have gone to the Honduran mainland to retire," says one woman. "We came for Roatan. When we moved here, there were only five Spanish-speaking people on the island. And now Honduras is taking it over."  <p> To an outsider, the Americans appear isolated--from the local culture and from each other. But no expat admits to missing more than a fragment, usually a favorite food, of life in the States. Perhaps this is how it has to be--having uprooted themselves once, at a younger, more adventurous age, they now find they have no place left to go. And then there is this eternal question:Whatever the shortcomings of Roatan, who could say if things would be any better back home, especially if finances were tight? <p> "You come down here when your kids are grown up and your friends back home are fewer and fewer," says Dorothy Reid, 67, who moved to Roatan from Michigan with her husband, Bud, 71, in 1976. "And you develop your own life. People say they'll visit at first, but they don't too much. We watch a lot of TV."  <p> Despite all this, "I never feel trapped or like leaving," Dorothy says. "I missed my family at first, but not now." She pauses a moment and sighs. As if aware that she sounds a little defensive, she takes a moment to collect more evidence. In the lifestyle's favor, she announces, "I haven't had panty hose on in 20 years." <p>  <p>"Hello, Miss Audrey." the clerk in the post office looks up from her magazine and smiles.  <p> "Hello," Audrey Buderus answers breezily, not stopping but heading straight for a shelf in the back of the dark, cement-floored room. She takes a single letter from a plastic bag. "The post office once got metal boxes," Audrey says, "but they lost the keys almost immediately." When Audrey, 64, and her husband, Brooks,76, moved here 24 years ago, mail could take several weeks to get from the States to the Honduran mainland, and then on to Coxen's Hole, where it could sit another two weeks before it went to Oak Ridge and Port Royal.   <p> Twice a week, the Buderuses drive to Coxen's Hole from their house in Sandy Bay, near the island's west end, to collect their mail and shop. Today, they pass a young man with an assault rifle standing guard outside the bank and head for the municipal building to unravel some red tape concerning their yearly poll tax. Brooks waits outside.  <p> He is a good-looking man with wavy silver hair that he wears a little long. In general, he has a distracted manner, but when he talks about the past, the good old days on Roatan, he becomes animated. Today, wearing black espadrilles and dark sunglasses, he looks like Cary Grant playing an expat in some seedy foreign port. Audrey is bright-eyed and sophisticated, with smooth skin, white-yellow hair, and terrific legs. For her errands today, she's put on a turquoise batik top and pants, white sandals,three heavy bracelets, blue eyeshadow, and eyeliner. She looks like a Miami hostess.  <p> Brooks, a Chicago architect, was hired to design Anthony's Key Resort, Roatan's first hotel devoted to divers, in 1967. After Anthony's opened, its owner fed the Buderuses several martinis and asked them if they'd like to manage the place. They accepted and moved to Roatan in 1970. "We were looking forward to being culturally deprived," Brooks says. "It was a challenge."  <p> Brooks managed the resort for a time; Audrey ran a gift shop. By 1991, they were both officially retired, with no interest in returning to the States. "Chicago's Loop would kill me in a weekend," Brooks says. Now they spend their evenings watching videos; they have a library of 300 tapes. "It's our sole entertainment, "Brooks says, somewhat sourly. But he's kidding. Hundreds of audiotapes and CDs fill the built-in wall cabinets in the Buderuses' airy house.  <p> Audrey emerges from the municipalidad, and Brooks follows her to H.B. Warren, a store that, with its aisles of housewares, its dry goods, and its lunch counter, resembles a Woolworth's from the early '60s. Pat Wagner, a younger American recently arrived, turns the corner with her cart and spies Dorothy Reid. Dorothy has been in the States for a month and just got back two days ago. "Dotty!" "Pat!" They hug in front of the liquor display. Audrey smiles and picks up two ears of corn and some rusty iceberg lettuce--the boat that brings romaine from Tampa won't be here for two weeks. Brooks reaches for a gallon of rum, but Audrey says, "No, put it back."  <p> The Buderuses head next for Mac's Meat Market, then Julie's, and then Eldon's. Julie's specializes in American goods, at prices two or three times higher than in the States. A half gallon of Tropicana orange juice, for example, goes for $5. Eldon's is the place for dog food and, finally, that gallon of rum. After a brief stop at the chicken farm, Audrey is finished. She's spent four hours collecting food over half the island.  <p> Audrey and Brooks have outlived a lot of the difficulties they first encountered on Roatan. They've also outlived a number of friends and are now seriously considering moving to Antigua, Guatemala, where they started leasing a house several years ago. <p> They hope life will be a little cheaper there. More important, they know it will be familiar. "We have more friends there, other Americans we've met over the years," Brooks says. For the Buderuses, the mystique of living on a tropical island no longer obtains. They don't like the Spaniards. They aren't comfortable with the newest crop of Americans, who seem obsessed with money and are hard to get to know. The outside world, they say, is catching up with Roatan.  <p>  <p>In the last three years, real-estate agents on Roatan have seen property values triple as Americans buy vacation homes and retirees settle down for good. Ten years ago, an acre of beachfront on the island's densely populated west end cost about $4,000. Now, one developer is getting $100,000 for his half-acre sites--an unholy amount of money in a place where a typical yard workerearns about 50 lempiras, or $6, a day.  <p> Besides the social unrest such rapid change has wrought, long-time residents--locals as well as outsiders--also have environmental concerns. The swamps are disappearing, and with them fresh water. At the west end, a water shortage is keeping new lots from selling. And yet new resorts continue to rise.   <p> The paved road was begun just five years ago, electricity became reliable four years ago, and jet airplanes landed only some three years ago. Progress has become inexorable. The condos are on their way, satellite dishes and crack cocaine are here, and more and more Nissan Pathfinders are careening around the island's hills at breakneck speed, blowing past stray cattle and old men hauling palm fronds on horseback, machetes slung over their shoulders. <p> "When I first came here, there was no tourism, no crime, no pollution or drugs," says Mike Muller, sitting on the deck of his house in Oak Ridge, watching the moon rise over the sea. Muller, 42, has been traveling back and forth between Roatan and Memphis, where his family's business is located, for 20 years."I used to dream of a satellite dish, but now that I have one, I find it's not nearly so much fun. It's too much of the rest of the world."  <p> In the next breath, Muller says he is looking forward to the day he can buy his fat-free mayonnaise here. But then, he suddenly realizes, Roatan will be just like home, and he wouldn't want to live here, either. It's just one more paradox in the life of Roatan's expats, people who had the imagination and temerity to leave behind all that was familiar but ended up simply duplicating their old lives in a warmer, cheaper venue.  <p>  <p>After returning edgar to the hardware store, Doc Steinbach heads home for a nap. Maybe the wind will settle down later and he'll get some fishing in. Whatever, he's content. Doc seems the happiest of Roatan's retirees. After seven years in his octagonal house, he's sufficiently steeped in island culture to appreciate its ordinariness. Save for his outsize Midwestern personality, he brought little of his former life here. His expectations are modest, so he has yet to be disappointed with either the locals or himself. He is, after all, a man with eight fishing rods. <p> And a man with a real place in his community. It was locals, not Americans, who missed Doc when he'd been absent for two days, mounted a search, then located him adrift on a stalled boat 57 miles west of Roatan. A local pulled up to Doc on the open sea and told him to hurry up and get aboard. "We can't afford to lose you," the man said. "I might need surgery on my horse again."  <p> <p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Retirement 
