		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-The Appeal of Portable Pensions</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Simplicity is the upside, maintenance the downside<p>By Kathy Murray <p>Many employers are redesigning pensions to make them easier for employees to understand and take along with them when they change jobs. "The drive for simplicity has become a touchstone for many companies," says Jason Jeffay, benefits consultant at Hewitt Associates. "They want to attract younger workers, and these workers prefer savings plans." <p>In addition to the popular 401(k) plans, new pension hybrids with fancy names and promises of more substantial benefits are being created. These plans are usually set up so employees can easily calculate their benefits and take the balance with them if they leave the company. But how good the newfangled pensions are depends on two factors: how the employer decides to fund them, and how much time the employee wants to devote to managing the funds if he or she changes jobs.<p>Consider Duracell International, the Bethel, Connecticut, battery manufacturer. It revamped its pension in 1991, in part to eliminate inequities between salaried and hourly workers. Out went its traditional defined-benefits plan, which relied on a complex series of formulas to arrive at a final annual payout after retirement. In its place the company introduced a cash-balance plan that works this way: Every year a participant's account is credited with a percentage of his pay based on his years with the company. A five-year veteran earning $90,000 a year would receive a credit of $4,500 in his account during 1993; interest earned would be roughly 3 percent. <p>In this case, simplicity came with a catch. Salaried employees are getting less with the cash-balance account than they did under the old pension. Nevertheless, "they perceive it is worth more because they can see the account balances," says benefits director David Lutterbach.<p>Cash-balance plans can have another drawback. Measured against total annual income, they tend to reward slow-trackers more than corporate superstars, because interest compounds at a higher rate than the slow-trackers' salary increases. Of course, the superstar will wind up with a larger pot of cash, but it will be a smaller multiple of his total income than the slowpoke's. For example, if employee A has 3 percent annual salary growth, he will end up with 30 percent of his income replaced at 65, while someone whose salary rose 7 percent a year would have only 22 percent of his income replaced at age 65. <p>RJR Nabisco got around this inequity by instituting a plan that considers employees' ages and length of service. But, when the worker leaves the company, credits are multiplied by the final average salary earned. Example: If an employee was 38 when hired and left 11 years later at a salary of $100,000, he would receive $110,600. The payout is calculated this way: $20,000 times 97 percent, plus $80,000 times 114 percent.<p>This pension also benefits the midcareer hire, who may not have long years with a company but who begins his career with a higher salary and therefore a larger credit.<p>RJR pays nothing to employees who leave before five years go by. But other companies, such as Wendy's International in Dublin, Ohio, have instituted pension arrangements that allow employees to take portions of pensions after as little as one year.<p>But portable pensions mean more work for the employee. Departing employees may wind up with two lump sums to contend with, one from the pension and one from the company 401(k). They have to manage both, either by rolling the funds over altogether into a new employers' plan or an IRA. They could also buy an annuity or, in some cases, keep it at the company. To some people, this is too many choices. <p>If you're one of the fortunate few allowed to roll your funds into your new employer's plan, by all means do so. Some companies allow you to shift funds into a 401(k) or profit-sharing plan. If the choice is between this and putting it in an IRA, financial planner Terry J. Siman in Spring House, Pennsylvania, opts for the 401(k) every time. Why? The money is more accessible. "What you lose in investment flexibility you make up for in rules flexibility," he says. Glen Buco, a pension analyst in Annandale, Virginia, has another reason for choosing the 401(k). "On the whole people do not invest as aggressively as the company would," he said.<p>Most pension professionals acknowledge that employee education about portable pensions must be improved. More employers should accept rollovers--just 7 percent do now. Representative Sam Gibbons of Florida is currently sponsoring a bill that would require improvements in pensions' portability, specifically to allow departing employees to transfer the amount in their defined-contribution plan or the present value in their defined-benefit plan to another qualified plan or IRA. Some organizations are discussing setting up regional funds to manage personal pension accounts. But for now, portable pensions require more work on an employee's part. Still, it's better to be able to take 'em than be forced to leave 'em.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement Investing, Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

