	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-$26 Million in the Hole</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>$26 Million in the Hole</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-$26 Million in the Hole</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Features<p>$26 MILLION IN THE HOLE
Can you build a second life after being a fraud, a thief, and a convict in your first one? Sure! says Barry Minkow.<p>By Christopher Byron<p>In March of 1989, 23-year-old Barry Minkow, founder, chief stockholder, and chief executive officer of the ZZZZ Best carpet-cleaning company, stood in a Los Angeles courtroom and expressed deep remorse for having defrauded investors in his company out of $100 million. In response, an angry Judge Dickran Tevrizian of the U.S. district court called this show of contrition "el toro poo-poo" and sentenced Minkow to 25 years in jail, plus the burden of making restitution of $26 million. "You're dangerous," he said. "You don't have a conscience."<p>Last November, an earnest, conservatively dressed young man stood before an audience of former Securities and Exchange Commission enforcement officials who had convened at the Bellevue Hotel in downtown Philadelphia to hear him lecture on financial crime. The young man was Barry Minkow.<p>"Look at the big picture," Minkow said, warming to his subject and speaking with easy self-confidence. "Get too hung up in the minutiae and you might never see that the entire operation is a fraud."<p>This is how Barry Minkow makes a living these days. A decade ago, when he was worth around $100 million, life was very different and so were his ambitions. Minkow, who was voted "Most Likely to Succeed" and "Class Clown" in his senior year in high school, managed in short order to confirm his classmates' acumen on both scores. He started his carpet-cleaning operation with $1,000 from a local loan shark, then he stole Western Union money orders from neighborhood stores, after which he stole and hocked his grandmother's jewelry. Later, he staged burglaries to defraud his insurance company, forged $45 million worth of bank checks, and enthusiastically helped sell millions of dollars of worthless ZZZZ Best stock to investors across America. Along the way, he also managed to get caught up with organized crime by borrowing hundreds of thousands of dollars from mobsters__at up to 5 percent a week. <p>There was money all over the place, and a good part of it went into making Barry famous. "I'm going to expand like crazy. And I'm shameless," he boasted. The pictures from those days are still around: Barry, just out of high school, motoring down Sunset Boulevard in his Ferrari; Barry at his neo-colonial manse in Woodland Hills (replete with butler and bodyguard); Barry on OPRAH in the LOS ANGELES TIMES in THE WALL STREET JOURNAL and in ENTREPRENEUR MAGAZINE.<p>In 1985, Los Angeles mayor Tom Bradley honored Minkow for setting "a fine entrepreneurial Example of obtaining the status of a millionaire at the age of eighteen years old" and gave him the city's official Certificate of Commendation. The first person Minkow showed it to was his accountant. "That certificate somehow seemed to authenticate ZZZZ Best and give us legitimacy," he says. "Presumably, the mayor of Los Angeles had done his due diligence on what we were all about, or he wouldn't have given us the certificate in the first place. And if that were so, why should our accountants do what the mayor of Los Angeles had already done? That at least was the message we hoped to convey to them by showing them the mayor's certificate__just like we pointed out to them that Oprah Winfrey had had us on her show and that we'd been written up in ENTREPRENEUR MAGAZINE and elsewhere. These were all meaningless credentials, but we collected them eagerly because they seemed to be far more than they really were."<p>Of course, everything about Minkow__nicknamed the Rocky of Rugs__and his company seemed to be far more than they really were. His rise and fall took five years, beginning with his junior year in high school in 1983 and ending in December of 1987, when the court accepted his guilty plea on 57 counts of mail, wire, and stock fraud. In retrospect, the only surprising thing is that this inept crook's amazing adventure lasted as long as it did. <p>Last April, Barry Minkow was released from a Los Angeles halfway house after having served more than seven years in jail, most of it at the Englewood medium-security prison in Littleton, Colorado. He had been a model prisoner from the moment he was sentenced, when he praised the FBI, the SEC, and his prosecutors for nailing him. "This is a great day for this country," said Minkow. "This is a great day for justice. This is how America works." <p>In jail he earned two degrees in theology from Liberty University in Lynchburg, Virginia, and wrote CLEAN SWEEP(Thomas Nelson Publishers), in which he recounted his crimes in detail__as well as his conversion to Christianity__and pledged to use his future earnings to pay off his debts. In fact, Minkow's behavior was so exemplary that even his most skeptical critic, Judge Tevrizian, changed his opinion and wrote a letter urging his parole. <p>After his release, Minkow married an Arizona woman with whom he had been corresponding while in prison. <p>There were a number of famous white-collar convicts in the 1980s--Michael Milken and Ivan Boesky among them. But while Milken is again advising companies on mergers and Boesky is said to be trading stocks abroad, Minkow is making a new life out of public repentance, lecturing accountants, lawyers, SEC officials, and FBI agents on how to spot and prevent corporate fraud.<p>In fact, Minkow's life, once an enormous con job, has been reconstructed as an equally encompassing attempt at restitution. He lives modestly, in a two-room apartment in Tarzana, California, a mile from Reseda, where he grew up and started ZZZZ Best. Nearby is the gated community Westchester County Estates, where Minkow lived at the zenith of his fame, with movie stars for neighbors. He doesn't seem to miss it. "The first decent night's sleep I got after I started ZZZZ Best was the first night I spent in federal prison," he says. <p>The born-again parolee voluntarily relinquishes his speaking fees__close to $100,000 at latest counting__to a victims' restitution fund set up and administered by his lawyer. From this, Minkow draws $4,100 a month, an amount agreed upon with his parole officer. Royalties from CLEAN SWEEP will also go to the victims' fund, as will his earnings, if any, from a projected movie about ZZZZ Best and proceeds from a new video series called FRAUDO DYNAMICS. To pay off his legal fees, he works without salary as a clerk in the office of his former trial lawyer, and he spends a great deal of his time caring for his elderly mother, who lives in the same apartment complex, and his father, who suffered a stroke while Barry was in prison and is confined to a wheelchair in a nursing home. <p>As a speaker, Minkow is relaxed, personable, and funny. Using an overhead projector, he shows examples of the doctored canceled checks he used to make his auditors think the company was doing 50 times more business than it was. As the checks flash by, he says, to unforced laughter, "As a condition of my release, I had to agree that I would never come within 50 feet of a bottle of Wite-Out again in my life."<p>Minkow also teaches a Bible class at a church north of Los Angeles. He sprinkles his classes with references to Nietzsche, Kierkegaard, and Plato, and ranges across the Old and New Testaments. He tells his classes that Jesus will forgive even the worst sinner, and he certainly has credentials to make the claim. Minkow stole from his friends, from his family, from anyone who came near him, but he tells his students that from darkness can come light and from evil can come good. <p>Such unrelenting goodness can be hard to credit, or even tolerate. It's impossible to listen to Minkow say "All I really want to do is help rid the world of the crimes I know best" without feeling a rising wall of skepticism--particularly if one speaks with some of the investors whom Minkow defrauded. Elaine Orlando, for example, lost $350,000, most of it in unsecured personal loans. She lost her house and her savings, and speaks sadly of others--an 80-year-old Los Angeles woman in ill health who was bilked out of $350,000, a Florida widow who lost $75,000. Orlando says Minkow also stole things harder to quantify. "I'm more reclusive," she says. "My circle of friends is smaller. I was trusting and believed in life's possibilities. I've lost that."<p>So is Minkow's rehabilitation genuine, or just convenient? Minkow himself may not know. He has never been a reflective or moderate person. Excess seems to be his natural element. <p>Then, too, he arrived in the 1980s, the Age of the Entrepreneur, when the media were hungry for individuals through whom they could personify the heroic story 
of getting rich. In Barry Minkow they found the right image, a working-class boy who spoke with the aggressive enthusiasm of an aluminum-siding salesman and who openly, brazenly wanted to be rich. And after that, he told anyone who would listen, politics. Barry Minkow wanted to be our president one day.<p>The press loved it and heedlessly publicized the boy and his company, despite the fact that anyone who looked could see that the story of the 16-year-old CEO of one of the fastest-growing companies on Wall Street was patently ridiculous. <p>But the investor lesson of ZZZZ Best is still unlearned--and may never be learned. In the summer of 1995, software companies that basically consisted of 20 postpubescent computer nerds with a bright idea and an answering machine were selling on Wall Street for multiples that, in some cases, reached 400 times earnings. Those who bought at those prices believed that shares in companies such as Spyglass and Secure Computing were in fact cheap. It's as if investors looked at the young techies behind these companies, heard the voice of Peter Pan exulting "I am youth," and bet on the invincibility of these new changelings of industry. The collapse in technology stocks that began last autumn will presumably shake the fairy dust from investors' eyes. <p>Minkow stresses in his lectures that you cannot audit--or safely invest in--a business you don't understand. In the case of ZZZZ Best, when Minkow showed his auditors canceled checks totaling $40 million for "restoration" jobs on damaged buildings, they were unaware that one of the biggest restoration jobs in history--that of the fire-and-water-damaged MGM Grand Hotel in Las Vegas in 1981--was worth at most $7 million in fees. <p>In the case of ZZZZ Best, ignorance proved expensive. In November 1995, a class-action suit brought by ZZZZ Best shareholders was settled, with the accounting firm Ernst & Young, a number of small investment banks, and the law firm Hughes Hubbard & Reed agreeing to pay a total of $35 million, or 95 cents on the dollar, in damages. <p>Minkow's past exploits, his lectures, and his apparent good-faith effort to repay tens of millions of dollars stolen from investors are a vivid reminder that, as Congress increasingly exempts our financial markets and institutions from regulatory oversight, "caveat emptor" should be the first and last words of every 
investor's credo. After all, Minkow was only a teenager when he began breaking the law, an undersized boy for whom business was a way to impress the prettiest girl in his class. Wall Street, on the other hand, is run by well-heeled adults who should know what it is to steal a person's life savings. Nonetheless, the Street held its nose while shoveling ZZZZ Best's garbage shares into the portfolios of gullible clients and pocketing the fees.<p>But Minkow appears to have changed with the zeitgeist. Like a great many 1980s believers in the gospel of wealth, he now looks for meaning and happiness outside the marketplace and beyond the material. We may look happily or cynically on such a personal metamorphosis and on the long-term prospects of his personal reformation. Perhaps the effort at restitution will help reconstitute his being. Perhaps not. <p>In any case, Barry Minkow now appears as determined to be honest as he once was to be successful. Today, he would probably be a safer person with whom to invest your money than a good many brokers and advisers on Wall Street. Ironically, Minkow, who claims he's had many offers to return to the business world, says he would do so only if he was forbidden from handling the stuff that was once at the core of his being. "I'm not afraid I would steal it," he says. "It's just that I'm really no good with money."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
