	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Short & Ugly: Scattered Story</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Short & Ugly: Scattered Story</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Leon Greenblatt found a clever way to make millions off the LTV bankruptcy. Too clever for officials at the Chicago Stock Exchange. Greenblatt, they thought, might destroy them all.<p>By Ted C. Fishman<p>Who is the Boy Plunger? Ask a couple of the traders who hang out at Jesse Livermore's, the most popular bar in Chicago's financial district, and they might answer in one of two ways. They might say Jesse Livermore himself, the famous short seller who schemed his way to several fortunes--some say he caused the crash of '29--but ultimately went spectacularly broke and killed himself. Livermore's nicknames reflected his passion for short selling: He was the Great Bear and the Boy Plunger.<p>But they also might reply "Leon Greenblatt."<p>Greenblatt, 36 years old, has schemed his way to several fortunes, too, but what brought him squarely into Livermore's league was his spectacular selling of stock in LTV Corp. <p>As that company came out of bankruptcy in 1993, Greenblatt, through his firm, Scattered Corp., went on one of the biggest selling sprees in the history of U.S. securities markets. He sold about 180 million shares of LTV, 58 million more than actually existed. As the price fell lower and lower, Greenblatt sold again and again. When it finally hit bottom, Scattered picked up $27 million in profits.<p>But few cheered him on at the Chicago Stock Exchange, where he was a member. As officials there watched his short sales mount, they tried to move against him. Some didn't seem to grasp his complicated arbitrage play. Apparently they didn't like Leon much, either. And they refused to sit by while an arrogant upstart seemed poised to bring down not only himself but the exchange and all its members.<p>Greenblatt likes the word "stupid," and it's one he uses freely when talking about the exchange. Ask him who almost caused a financial meltdown, and his finger points squarely at the exchange. He may be right.<p>
Scattered's offices, high on top of a venerable LaSalle Street building, have the kind of defiant atmosphere officialdom hates. They're way too big for a firm with three principals and no employees. Battered office furniture and cardboard cartons sprawl helter-skelter throughout: A copy of Sun Tzu's The Art of War sits atop a pile of prospectuses and stamp catalogs; a stack of annual reports teeters on a giant pretzel tin. Buried somewhere in the clutter is the dart gun and the Jack Daniel's bottle Greenblatt brandished when exchange auditors came to look over the firm's books early in 1995. The gun might be in the office kitchen, but looking there means braving the debris of yesterday's lunch. Or is it last week's?<p>The tallest, most commanding piles in the rambling office contain more than a million pages in documents generated by all the legal proceedings surrounding Scattered's LTV play. There are papers from the class-action suit filed in U.S. Federal District Court in Chicago, charging that Scattered manipulated LTV stock. There are piles of papers from the disciplinary hearings held by the Chicago Stock Exchange, charging Scattered with fraud (among other offenses) and hoping to extract penalties of $44 million and expel the firm from the exchange. There are also documents galore from the various suits Scattered has filed against the exchange. <p>Greenblatt can place almost any document immediately. But reaching into a pile, he happens to pick up a brokerage statement. "Look here," he says with glee. "Here's one of my accounts. It's got $15 million in it."<p>Ask anyone who's ever worked for or against Greenblatt: Leon is smart. One friend describes him as "the last person in the world I'd want to be on the wrong side of. He's someone who's willing to go entirely to the mat." The son of a New Orleans dry cleaner, Greenblatt graduated in 1981 from the honors math program at Northwestern University and continued into a doctoral program, where he applied game theory and statistical methods to economics. He thought graduate school "just stupid" and left. <p>He's no less formidable physically: Greenblatt has a short fullback's build, and it might take half a team to tackle him. Yet his smile--like a dolphin's, sheepish and naughty--is disarming when he reveals something clever he's done, whether it's starting a business, buying a building, making $2 million a day in LTV, or calling his firm Scattered.<p>"Scattered" is a word that comes up often when traders quote the best prices on a stock. They ask: "Who's the market?" If a smattering of firms is vying to sell (or buy) at the same price, as is common, the answer goes something like, "Merrill on the bid, scattered on the offer." Now traders must think twice: Does "scattered" mean many firms or that gadfly shop in Chicago? Greenblatt finds the confusion delicious. <p>Greenblatt and his two partners, Andrew Jahelka and Richard Nichols, stay glued to the half-dozen computers that crowd a dim corner of their office, checking data and placing trades to their floor broker. They prefer arbitrage trading, Greenblatt says, because "anything but arbitrage is too much work." They don't try to call the direction of stocks but look for sure things, particularly in bankrupt companies. In theory, arbitrage poses little risk. The securities bought and sold are essentially the same; a trade is profitable when, for some reason, one of the securities is priced out of line with the other. "It's just like you're buying dollar bills and selling dollar penny rolls," says Greenblatt, "and for whatever stupid reason, people are paying $5 for a dollar penny roll." <p>Deep in another corner sits a computer no one bothers with until it chimes the first bar of "We're in the Money," the song it's programmed to play every time a bankruptcy appears in the news. Of the hundreds of public companies that file for bankruptcy every year, only a few really warrant music. Every couple of years, one like LTV calls for a brass band.<p>
On January 20, 1993, the Scattered computer announced that LTV Corp. had at last filed a reorganization plan with the Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York. The filing capped one of the biggest and most complicated bankruptcies in U.S. history. In its heyday, the company was one of the nation's largest diversified conglomerates, with tens of thousands of employees and interests in, among other things, steel, energy, and aerospace. LTV sought bankruptcy protection in 1986 after collapsing under enormous pension obligations and competition from foreign steel. <p>In 1990, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down LTV's first reorganization plan. When in January 1993 a viable plan was finally completed, Wall Street cheered, predicting a solid future for the restructured company. Within two days, the long-withering stock had become the most actively traded issue on the New York Stock Exchange, peaking at $2.00 a share and closing on Friday, January 22, at $1.125, double its price at the time of the announcement.<p>In bankruptcies, unsophisticated investors often rush in, thinking they can buy shares in a newly reorganized company cheaply. What they don't realize is that the stock they're buying is actually "old stock" that will often be nearly worthless in the reorganized company. Their buying drives up the price of an all-but-dead issue. "That's stupid," says Greenblatt.<p>Greenblatt's strategy in LTV hinged partly on what he figured were the public's blind hopes for LTV stock, and from his careful reading of the reorganization plan. It mandated that the shares of LTV eventually would be worth no more than 3.2 cents, a long way down from where the investing public was pushing it. "Now this doesn't happen very often, but it happens once every two years or so," Greenblatt says. He jumped on it.<p>The public's enthusiastic buying did elicit loud and frequent warnings. At 2 p.m. on that tumultuous Friday, LTV issued a news release explaining that the markets had misinterpreted the plan. The following Monday, January 25, Greenblatt was quoted in The Wall Street Journal warning investors to read the LTV documents carefully. A day later, a dumbfounded spokesman for LTV sounded an unambiguous alarm for broadcast on the nation's business wires: "I see a lot of people will get hurt. Whoever owns this stock when we come out of Chapter 11 will get 3 cents a share for it. That's not going to change for the better."<p>At first, Scattered bet small on LTV's decline, over the next five months selling a hundred thousand shares now and then. Other traders at the Chicago exchange sold, too, acting as typical short sellers, dumping stock they didn't own, hoping (and succeeding) to buy it back cheaper. Selling the bejesus out of companies in bankruptcy is a house sport at the Chicago exchange.<p>One of the short sellers and assigned market makers in LTV was David Sullivan. Sullivan, five years Greenblatt's senior, had traded on the Boston exchange--he still has a bean-thick Boston accent--before coming to Chicago. For 14 years, he worked his way up the political ladder, becoming well-enough liked to get elected to the Chicago Stock Exchange's board of governors. He eventually assumed a 2 million-share short position in LTV.<p>Sullivan would later head the class-action suit against Scattered and become one of the firm's chief adversaries on the floor. In 1992, however, short selling had been the stuff of friendly talk between the two men over drinks at Jesse Livermore's. Sullivan was intrigued by the mysteries of Greenblatt's methods. Greenblatt turned to the veteran stock trader for tips on the brute buying and selling that rule the exchange--particularly selling.<p>Scattered held off making any big moves until after May 26, when the proposed reorganization plan was ratified by the bankruptcy court--a milestone that all but guaranteed the plan would go into effect. Now, Scattered could launch the nearly risk-free arbitrage that would net it millions and eventually provoke the wrath of both Sullivan and the exchange.<p>LTV's reorganization plan called for extinguishing all the old stock in the company, and although the reformed company would issue new shares, the new would not go to owners of the old. (Only the company's creditors received new stock.) Old shares would be converted into warrants, which could be used to buy new shares at a set price.<p>In late May, old stock was still trading for 25 cents a share. According to the plan, several weeks remained before the company would wipe the stock out, but the exact date wasn't set. It also would be some time before the company issued the warrants. In the parlance of the markets, then, the warrants became "when issued" securities. And since traders will trade anything that's tradable, the mere fact that a planned security doesn't yet exist rarely gets in the way of Wall Street's willingness to price it, buy it, and sell it. The phantom LTV warrants proved hot, and a market grew almost instantly. Greenblatt helped see to it. He knew the sooner the warrant market developed, the better his chance of arbitraging it against the market in the stock. <p>The eventual price of the new stock, however, meant nothing to Scattered. The key characteristic of the warrants was that owners of the old stock would receive only 3.2 cents' worth of warrants per share, and no more. It was a lock. (According to the plan, shares would be swapped for warrants at a ratio of 92 to 1: Old common stock could never be worth more than 3.2 cents.) As long as the stock traded above its mandated worth of about 3 cents, arbitrage could be profitable.<p>Scattered's strategy was to buy the warrants at prices close to their mandated value and to sell the equivalent stock at a premium. Scattered would then wait for the LTV bankruptcy plan to wind up, deliver the warrants, and keep the difference in price. To do that, Greenblatt and his broker, Laura Bryant, got on the phone to every trading firm they could. They explained the plan to the brokers and announced they were looking to buy the warrants. While his counterparts jumped to collect a small premium for selling Greenblatt warrants, he was busy short-selling LTV stock for up to 25 cents a share, or eight times its worth. <p>From the end of May until June 28, the markets in both warrants and stock grew increasingly deep, with Scattered on one side or another of the bulk of the trades. Yet, throughout the entire period, the highest price of the warrants never exceeded the lowest price of 92 LTV shares, meaning that Scattered made money every time it traded the two securities against each other. Scattered's massive selling never really pummeled the stock; no matter how much stock Scattered sold, the public still demanded about 10 million shares a day. Prices eroded gradually over the month, yet even on June 28, 1993, the last day of the old stock's life, shares still sold for twice their true value. <p>
It was the chance to do bankruptcy arbitrage that brought Scattered to the exchange in 1991. There the partners hoped to put into play the strategies they had developed during their years at the Chicago Board Options Exchange. For Greenblatt, the move capped an eight-year odyssey through Chicago's financial markets, where he picked up both the expertise and the partners capable enough to put his plans to work. <p>At the CBOE, where he traded a variety of options and stocks, Greenblatt was known as a boat person, someone who moves into the most active pits. The worst names traders call each other--boat people, floaters, weasels--refer to ways of horning in on someone's business. In theory, markets exist to bring competitors together, but if you compete too doggedly, you're disdained. People like Greenblatt "are considered somewhat contemptible because they ruin it for the group," says Eugene Finerman, a former trader who describes Greenblatt as "reptilian, bright, and clever, though with no sense of humor." Finerman eventually left the exchange to become a writer and won more than $80,000 on Jeopardy!<p>Jahelka, Greenblatt's first partner, also went to Northwestern, and the two lived together for a time in the same fraternity. Four years Greenblatt's junior, Jahelka started in the university's accelerated medical program but he says he "didn't like blood and guts that much ... and the money wasn't that great." He switched to math and chemistry and graduated as a chemical engineer. His friendship with Greenblatt, he says, developed over 10,000 games of backgammon: "I think I won 4,999 and Leon won 5,001." In 1986, after a year of formulating specialty enamels in the lab of a paint company, Jahelka was hired as a clerk by Greenblatt, in time becoming a Scattered partner with a 30 percent stake. Jahelka, a crew-cut, lanky native of Steamboat Springs, Colorado, learned Greenblatt's approach to risk thoroughly enough to make money in the 1987 market crash that hit soon after he began. <p>Richard Nichols, Greenblatt's second partner, with a 20 percent stake, took the longest route to the firm. Nichols, a British subject with a Nepalese grandmother, was born several hundred miles north of Calcutta to a household staffed by servants, and he attended public school in England. When his best friend's brother turned down Oxford for the Wharton School, Nichols, too, applied to U.S. business schools. He chose Indiana University, where he studied finance and played rugby. After a stint with Andersen Consulting, Nichols resolved to return to England--that is, until a trader friend of his offered him a tour of the CBOE. "My eyes lit up when I saw the floor," Nichols recalls. "The place was heaving ... something exciting was going on." He worked for that friend for two years and then signed on with Greenblatt, agreeing to work for free. "He didn't have anything worth paying for," Greenblatt says. Nichols concurs. "I enrolled in the Leon School of Options Trading," he says. <p>In 1991, while playing bridge, the partners decided to move to the Chicago Stock Exchange, where they could work their bankruptcy arbitrage plays. "We'd been toying with the idea for months," Jahelka says. The move took some imagination, because few in Chicago's financial circles take the exchange seriously. Some due diligence might also have been in order. Scattered was joining a declining exchange wanting for money.<p>
Though the Chicago Stock Exchange officially bills itself as the nation's second largest in terms of the value of shares traded, by that measure it is only 1/27th the size of the New York Stock Exchange. (With the exception of ex-governor Sullivan, no one in the administration of the Chicago exchange would talk on the record regarding any aspect of this story, and all inquiries were referred to the exchange's outside attorney. Statements by exchange officials in this story have been drawn largely from sworn testimony offered in connection with the legal proceedings surrounding Scattered's stock play.)<p>In clout, the Chicago exchange hardly matters; in terms of business measured in revenue, it's puny, with only $28 million coming in last year, roughly equal to that of a sleepy Wal-Mart. In 1993, the exchange spent half a million dollars to change its name from the Midwest Stock Exchange to the Chicago Stock Exchange. With the new handle, the exchange hoped to piggyback on the prestige of the city's three financial behemoths: the CBOE, the Chicago Board of Trade, and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Homer Livingston, the new president of the stock exchange at the time, acknowledged its also-ran status in his remarks heralding the name change: "When people overseas talk about Chicago, they talk in awe of its highly innovative, technology-driven crowd.... [B]ut frequently we are not included in those conversations."<p>The Chicago Stock Exchange had been having problems for a number of years. Since 1990 it had witnessed declines in revenue from its biggest money maker, the consolidated, or broad, tape (the price reporting service that relays real-time trade data on stocks). The lost revenue has hurt. According to Crain's Chicago Business, the exchange's cash reserves now stand at only $2.5 million, down from $14.6 million just two years ago.<p>Federal regulators had also struck a blow against the exchange. In 1991, Chicago Stock Exchange officials announced they had "discovered" a 13-year practice that basically allowed a subsidiary of the exchange to wrongfully receive millions of dollars yearly in interest payments that should have gone to broker-dealers. The SEC ordered the exchange to stop keeping false records and fined it $2 million.<p>Not even the plush comforts of the exchange's home, One Financial Place, offer much consolation. Its granite tower stands on LaSalle Street, behind the CBT, and its state-of-the-art trading room spans the expressway, advertising the institution to the endless parade of cars heading downtown. But its rent, negotiated in the early 1980s, is high, at $45 per square foot, and its lease, for 20 years, is nonnegotiable. By 1990, the exchange's rent  grew so burdensome it considered bankruptcy. In 1987, membership at the exchange cost $105,000. By September 1995, a seat sold for $34,000.<p>The financial struggles of the exchange were of no concern to Scattered when it applied for membership. Its move was motivated by its desire to make money. By joining and establishing itself as a clearing member, it acquired the privileges necessary to conduct bankruptcy arbitrage. It could reduce trading costs to a fraction of a cent per share. It could also enroll as a market maker, a category of professional trader entitled to lower margins and special allowances under SEC rules.<p>One allowance is that market-maker firms can sell stock without making any attempt to borrow or deliver it. Greenblatt interpreted the Securities and Exchange Act of 1934 as meaning that Scattered could legally skirt delivery requirements and keep its LTV position intact until the reorganization plan was completed. Without that special accommodation, Scattered's LTV arbitrage would have been severely impeded.<p>Scattered's bankruptcy arbitrage also relied on the its interpretation of another allowance accorded to market makers by SEC rules: the ability to sell stock on minus ticks and zero ticks. Usually, traders can sell short only if the last price change in a stock moved the shares up. If the last price change reflected a decline in price, short sellers must hold off--except, that is, if they are either market makers, arbitrageurs, or both. SEC rules allow them to sell on minus ticks, on the theory that market making and arbitrage foster efficient and liquid markets. In the rules, such trades are considered neither long nor short, but "short exempt." Scattered claimed its trades were short exempt. The exchange would later disagree.<p>
In its first two years as a Chicago Stock Exchange member, Scattered conducted arbitrage in Orion Pictures, <a name="NYSE:USG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11529"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>USG Corp.</b></a>, <a name="AMEX:TWA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Trans World Airlines</b></a>, and the stocks of other companies in bankruptcy. The firm had no problems with the exchange's in-house regulators. But in early June 1993, those same regulators began puzzling over Scattered's huge sales in LTV stock. Something obviously had changed in Scattered's strategy. The regulators had never seen anything close to Scattered's massive trading volume, and they were worried.<p>Traders on the floor also were alarmed. Laura Bryant, the independent broker who was acting as Scattered's agent on the trading floor, recalls that on June 2, 1993, another broker in LTV approached her and asked, "When are you going to stop selling so we can let this pig pop?"--meaning he wanted the price to go up so he could sell his long shares at a profit. Later, the broker's boss approached Bryant, again pleading for her to stop selling for Scattered. Bryant says the boss then showed her a full account of Scattered's trading activity--normally detailed only in the exchange's confidential records. Bryant, a no-nonsense redhead, well-known and respected on the floor, alerted her clients at Scattered. From then on, Greenblatt expected trouble. <p>If the other traders on the floor didn't know Scattered was matching stock against warrants, they were understandably fearful. Scattered could have been selling massively in an attempt to clobber the stock and shake the longs out of the market. Those fears, however, stemmed from a backward understanding of Scattered's strategy. Scattered gained nothing from drops in the stock, because Scattered's short stock position was continually balanced against a long warrant position. <p>Old-line traders at the exchange viewed Scattered's activity through an archaic lens, one that could see a Jesse Livermore clearly but fogged when it came to the intricate strategies of modern markets. Even now, when David Sullivan talks about Scattered's strategy, he likens it to the panic caused when Edward Henry Harriman fought James Jerome Hill for the Chicago, Burlington & Quincy railroad--Livermore's first plunge into the market, at the turn of the century.<p>
Concern at the exchange came from several quarters, and in the first week of June, Scattered received a visit from two officials, Michael Cardin and Paul Smith, who work under chief regulator Allan Bretzer, and Susan Hertel, then manager of operations at the exchange's trust subsidiary. Cardin and Smith enforce exchange rules and financial requirements; Hertel was charged with monitoring risk. <p>The officials may have been worried that if buyers demanded stock, Scattered, now short about 60 million shares, wouldn't be able to deliver it without causing a big run-up in price. A run-up would cause losses not just to Scattered but to the other member firms, such as Sullivan's, that would be caught in an upward squeeze. In the worst-case scenario for the exchange, it would become Scattered's unwilling partner in a financial meltdown that could first ruin Scattered and then, possibly, wipe out the exchange. (The exchange acts as a kind of insurer, guaranteeing that members make good on trades, or if they can't, the exchange absorbs the losses itself.) Hertel, a 23-year veteran of the exchange, demanded that Scattered post $14 million to ensure the solvency of the exchange.<p>It was clear to the Scattered partners that they had some teaching to do. They say they showed the regulators the LTV plan, explained the terms of the reorganization, and, with a spreadsheet showing Scattered's exact holdings, walked the officials through their arbitrage trades. Don Hayden, a trader at the options exchange, happened to stop by Scattered that day to pick up his bicycle. In his account, the exchange visitors nodded their comprehension and laughed at the simplicity of it all. Cardin apparently said to Greenblatt, "It can't be that easy." <p>It's a moment Hayden remembers with clarity, because Greenblatt took Cardin's remark as a challenge. "Watch me," Greenblatt reportedly said. "I'll show you how easy it is." He walked over to the phone, dialed another firm's arbitrage desk and said, "I want to buy 10,000 warrants." Then Greenblatt called Bryant on the floor. Bryant, too, remembers the call, because Greenblatt told her he wanted to show Cardin, Hertel, and Smith how easy the trade was. "Say hi to Mike," she told him.<p>"Now sell 920,000 LTV," Greenblatt said. Bryant did so. Turning to his examiners, Greenblatt said: "There, you see how easy it is? And by the way, that was a quick 140 grand."<p>At the Scattered disciplinary hearing, the officials remembered little from the meeting. Smith said he and his colleagues asked for an explanation of Scattered's strategy, got one, and still couldn't understand it. "Everyone was talking very freely," said Smith. "[I]t was the middle of the day ... The Scattered people were ... conducting their business. If they had a phone call, they took the phone call.... If someone walked in, they would talk to them. Everyone took turns talking.... It's so very hard to say who said what." When Hertel was asked at the hearing if she knew what hedging and arbitrage were, she answered, "I really don't have an understanding of either one, just that they are two different things.... Give me a dictionary." <p>The following day the exchange began its effort to rein in Scattered when the clearing corporation withheld $2.6 million of Scattered's money, profits it normally would have released to the firm. <p>The following Monday the exchange demanded about $5 million from Scattered. Greenblatt asked the exchange what formula it used to arrive at that amount. Cardin told him the exchange needed Scattered to post 100 percent of the value of the stock and 100 percent of the value of the warrants. (These types of margins, which the exchange calls participant funds, typically add up to under 10 percent of the value of traders' securities. In hedged and arbitraged positions, the margin often is zero.)<p>The exchange questioned the argument that Scattered's play was risk free. It worried that the reorganization plan would not go through, meaning the phantom warrants would never become real and Scattered would have nothing to deliver against its short position. But Scattered, with its money machine running full steam, was not about to abandon its sure thing. Later, Greenblatt and his partners saw the exchange's request as a move to shut them down.<p>Instead of meeting the new margins, Scattered transferred its warrant trading to two brokerage houses. The exchange, nervous that it could no longer monitor Scattered's warrant position, agreed a week later to let the firm keep the warrants in clearing on less drastic terms. On June 16, after three weeks of selling roughly 10 million shares a day, Scattered's sales finally exceeded all the outstanding stock in LTV. <p>Scattered's selling of nonexistent shares rested on Greenblatt's understanding of the privileges the Securities and Exchange Act granted member firms. But the very idea that Scattered could sell more than LTV's outstanding stock nagged at the Chicago regulators. A note Hertel wrote to herself reflects the exchange's frustration: "[Exchange regulators] continued to feel [the] firm was not breaking any rules and no action could be taken against [the] firm." <p>
A troubled Michael Cardin returned to Scattered's office on June 21. The details of the LTV reorganization and Scattered's trading were again explained to him, and this time Cardin asked for a few minutes by himself to puzzle through the arbitrage on paper. When Cardin finished, Greenblatt remembers, Cardin asked him and Nichols to check the numbers. Greenblatt says he noted a minor rounding error and told Cardin his math was "good enough for government work." Cardin left. <p>The following day, Greenblatt says, he turned to Nichols and said, "The only way this could get fouled up now is if the [exchange] tells us to stop selling stock." Within an hour, Cardin called to order just that.<p>Whatever dangers Cardin may have discussed with his boss, Allan Bretzer, they could not have been any worse than the disaster their rescue attempt nearly wrought. When Cardin called Scattered, he demanded that the firm stop selling unless it could deliver the shares it sold. But in seeking to remove Scattered as a seller, the exchange risked a run-up in the stock. Not only were there still investors willing to bid up the stock, but Scattered was helping to provide the liquidity needed to keep the trading orderly. The exchange's records show that Scattered participated in trades accounting for 80 percent of all the volume in LTV that June. If the exchange removed Scattered from the market, it would disconnect the stock from the warrants, the anchor pulling the stock toward its true value.<p>Nichols and Jahelka rushed to Cardin's office. Nichols, whose English public-school manner perhaps offered the best chance for a diplomatic solution, spoke. "I asked him whose decision this was, and he points to the room next door, and I asked who, and he says Al Bretzer." Until then no one at Scattered had ever met Bretzer. Nichols continued: "I asked if we could see him, since he was making the decisions. So [Cardin] goes next door, and motions us to come and see him. The first thing, Bretzer is sitting behind his desk ranting and raving and says, I've been looking for a way to stop you boys from selling any more shares of LTV. I haven't been able to find a way of stopping you until now, because it looks like there is no [SEC] rule that prevents you from selling more shares than the outstanding number of the issue. But now you've got to stop.' And he points to a book, the [exchange's] rule book, and says, It says so in there, it says so in black and white.' I said, Where?' And he refused to open the rule book to show us what he was talking about." The exchange rule was cited in a letter rushed to Scattered from the exchange, demanding that the firm stop selling unless it could prove it had deliverable stock. <p>Cardin's mandate came late--when no one could deliver stock. Most of the shares were now in the hands of the official transfer agent in preparation for the stock's extinction and replacement by warrants. <p>Greenblatt called his attorney, asking him to write a letter to the exchange. "Say anything at all," he said. "Just get them to talk to us." The letter, predicting disaster, went out to the board of governors. On his own, Greenblatt phoned around, trying to rustle up governors to hear his case. He found David Sullivan. Again, the two met at Jesse Livermore's. Sullivan, who was 2 million shares short in LTV, listened carefully. "[Greenblatt] showed me the letter he sent to the exchange," Sullivan remembers, "that meant he had no intention of delivering the stock. I said that [also] meant he had no intention of delivering to me."<p>Sullivan said he regarded Greenblatt's action as a refusal to fulfill a contract, and he moved to minimize his losses. He says he also feared for the exchange, which he estimated could have lost $75 million. At the beginning of the next trading day, Sullivan bought 2 million shares, covering his short position. Later, Judge Richard Posner, ruling on Sullivan's suit, noted allegations that Sullivan based his trade on knowledge he gleaned as a governor of the exchange. Sullivan says, "My goal was to get out of the game." <p>Greenblatt decided to circumvent the Chicago Stock Exchange. He canceled all his orders at the exchange and sold only in New York. Once Scattered made the switch, however, it began to have some of the same problems with its brokerage houses as it had with the exchange. Scattered sold 920,000 shares through Rodman & Renshaw, and the brokerage house demanded immediate delivery. Greenblatt says he explained that Scattered had deliverable securities, referring to the warrants, but the broker, Michael Comerford, insisted on knowing where the shares were. The warrants weren't yet active, so to keep the trade alive, someone at Scattered lied. Greenblatt says it was he, Comerford says it was Nichols. "[Nichols] said he'd notify the bank to deliver the stock," Comerford recalled at the exchange hearings. When delivery didn't occur, Comerford called again. He was told the stock was tied up. He called again. This time, Comerford testified, he was told the stock was at the First National Bank of New Orleans and the contact was Leon Greenblatt. Rodman & Renshaw's researchers soon discovered that there was no First National Bank of New Orleans. Scattered tried once more to explain that the firm would deliver warrants, not stock. When Comerford pressed again, a week later, Comerford testified, Greenblatt grabbed the phone, and screamed, "You'll get the stock when you get it, you fucking idiot," and slammed it down. After that Rodman's CEO, Kurt Carmen, called Scattered, and Rodman & Renshaw agreed to take warrants.<p>Scattered filed for a temporary restraining order against the exchange to stop the demand that the firm have deliverable stock. Its emergency court date fell on June 28, the last day of trading in LTV. Greenblatt thought that even a last-minute disconnect in Scattered's arbitrage would cause a run-up in the stock and bring disaster. He says he instructed his partners to tell Scattered's attorney to do whatever he could to keep everyone in court until the end of the day. At 2:30, a half hour before the close of the market, the judge ruled against Scattered. But the exchange lawyers took no action that afternoon, and the market closed, after which the exchange's demand was irrelevant. LTV stock settled at just over seven cents a share. <p>In the days following, LTV extinguished the old stock, and in August, Scattered delivered the warrants. Without exception, all the stockholders accepted them. Despite the exchange's worst fears, never throughout the five-week period of Scattered's LTV play, nor in the weeks afterward, did Scattered face a demand for delivery it couldn't handle.<p>
The legal battle began. An attorney for the exchange told Scattered that the exchange was keeping $3 million of its LTV profits, because Scattered illegally sold at the close on the last day of trading to further  drive down the price. <p>Exchange regulators also decided to look deeper into Scattered's past. Greenblatt's boat-person days, it seemed, had caught up with him. Regulators discovered that Greenblatt had also crossed officials at the CBOE; the CBOE fined Greenblatt for trading too much in stocks in which he wasn't a market maker. In the trading world it's a small sin, but on one of the official forms Scattered filed with its application to the stock exchange, Greenblatt neglected to mention the CBOE action. The exchange maintains that he was legally bound to do so. Greenblatt says he later filed an amendment.<p>It was then that Greenblatt took the only action he says he regrets: He changed an old form in his files to look like a copy of the one he supposedly had amended. The ruse failed when a forensic expert hired by the exchange noticed that the signature on the form exactly matched that on another document. In late 1993, Bretzer issued a 32-page complaint against Scattered, listing fraud along with dozens of other alleged violations of securities laws and exchange rules.<p>Adding to Scattered's troubles was the federal class-action suit filed in July 1993 by David Sullivan, charging that Scattered manipulated LTV stock. Sullivan says he sued to protect the Chicago Stock Exchange, the securities markets, and the little guy: "Some [of the investors] bought $1,000 worth for their IRAs, thinking of security in old age." Sullivan alleges that Scattered used its market-maker status to mask the size of its short position, thus keeping vital economic information out of the hands of public investors. Sullivan's suit also claims that Greenblatt artificially depressed the price of the stock with Scattered's giant sell orders. "Any uptick would have taken away all his equity," Sullivan says.<p>Sullivan's suit failed in federal district court before making it to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit.<p>If Scattered had been able to choose a judge, it could have done no better than Richard Posner, an ardent free marketer, considered by many to be one of the federal judiciary's most brilliant judges. In a strident ruling, Posner wrote: "Scattered principals may be reckless gamblers, sharpies, wise guys, exploiters of loopholes, even violators of the letter or spirit of the rules of the Chicago Stock Exchange. We take no position on these questions." But, he continued, "The name for what Scattered did is not market manipulation, but arbitrage." Posner dismissed the case, reasoning that Scattered did the investing public a service. "By doing this, arbitrageurs [like Scattered] promote the convergence of market and economic values that we suggested was the central objective of securities regulation." <p>He went further, saying arbitrageurs such as Scattered help keep securities markets efficient by providing both liquidity and price information to less informed investors. Posner concluded his opinion by noting that "since the conduct in which Scattered engaged appears to have served rather than disserved the fundamental objectives of the securities laws, we are not inclined to strain to find a violation of a specific provision." <p>Posner's logic bewilders Sullivan. "It was an academician's analysis," he complains. "Posner says [Greenblatt] did a service to humanity. Well, Dr. Livingston he's not." Sullivan has appealed Posner's decision to the Supreme Court, though even his lawyer deems the chances of the court hearing the case slim.<p>While the U.S. courts refuse to strain to penalize Scattered's trading, the Chicago Stock Exchange has been less restrained. Since it filed charges in 1993, the exchange has effectively shut Scattered out of floor trading and at different times withheld varying amounts of the firm's money, ranging from $150,000 to $3 million.<p>At the exchange's hearings, held last winter and lasting two months, the regulators demanded a $17 million fine and full disgorgement of Scattered's profits. Tensions were high during that period. At one point, when exchange president Homer Livingston made his rounds on the floor, Greenblatt walked up to him and barked, "I want my fucking money." Greenblatt was ordered off the trading floor.<p>In mid-September 1995 the exchange's hearing officer, Gordon Nash, a former regulator at the American Stock Exchange, issued his judgment. The exchange was not bound by Posner's ruling, Nash reasoned,  since Posner defined "arbitrage in the general sense.... [He] was not offering a legal definition of the term as used in ... SEC rules." In Nash's reading of the rules, Scattered did not conduct arbitrage. He found the firm guilty of every major charge against it, finding that Scattered manipulated LTV stock to drive down its price, misrepresented itself to regulators and other investors, abused its status as a market maker, and recklessly imperiled the exchange. Nash also found the firm guilty of the charges relating to its application to the exchange. <p>Posner also found that "though their trading may have had an overall beneficial impact upon the market by contributing to a convergence between price and value' ...[as Posner had found in the Sullivan case], the seriousness of their illegal trading tactics cannot be ignored."<p>Nash fined Scattered and its partners about $6.4 million. He fined Laura Bryant $350,000. Scattered and Greenblatt were expelled from the exchange. Nichols and Jahelka were suspended from associating with any member of the exchange--Jahelka for two years, Nichols for one. Bryant, who says the judgment "was complete fantasy and showed a total disregard for the facts," was also suspended for a year. None of the judgments, however, take force until Scattered and Bryant have exhausted their appeals. The exchange's ruling can be appealed, first to the exchange, then to the SEC, and finally through the court system--perhaps even to Judge Posner.<p>Greenblatt says that even if the fine is upheld, "it will have no effect on us. Commercially, we're fully reserved." Scattered will continue to trade through brokerage houses, but without an exchange membership it may never again fully enjoy the riches offered by bankruptcy reorganizations.<p>The other suits around the issue are still pending in federal courts, in the Delaware Court of Chancery, and before judges in Cook County, Illinois. Scattered has already spent about $2 million in legal bills.<p>
Most of the participants expect the aftermath of Scattered's LTV bankruptcy play to go on for years. Greenblatt thinks it may outlast the exchange itself. Looking at the balance sheet in the exchange's annual report, he says, "It's going broke, and believe me, I know a little about bankrupt companies." In late September, the exchange announced plans to sell off its clearing and trust divisions, which will help ease its real estate burdens, among other things. <p>Scattered has moved onto other ventures, including setting up a company that builds plants to capture methane from garbage dumps--another way of turning trash into money. Scattered's jewel, though, is its LaSalle Street building, which was in bankruptcy when the firm bought it last year for $4 million drawn from its LTV proceeds. Greenblatt loves the place. "One and a half times [a year's] rent," he says, quoting the price, "$24 a square foot." Jesse Livermore's is now Scattered's tenant. Traders crowd the bar as much as ever, and now when talk turns to short selling, Greenblatt's name is as likely to come up as that of the original Boy Plunger. <p>
IT'S SIMPLE, WHEN YOU KNOW HOW<p>Scattered based its trading on these facts:
1. Upon retirement, the old LTV stock would be swapped for warrants at a ratio of 92 to 1 (92 shares would equal 1 warrant).
2. The price of the old stock would be valued at $0.0322 a share upon retirement.
3. As long as warrants could be acquired at a price cheaper than 92 shares of the stock, Scattered would make money.
4. Scattered would make money because it would sell stock (go short) at a high price, and buy warrants (which would replace the stock) for a low price. 
5. Scattered balanced its sales of LTV stock with its purchases of warrants. These trades negate each other upon the retirement of the LTV stock.<p>
Here is a fairly typical trade Scattered made in early June: 
It bought 10,000 warrants (representing 920,000 shares) at $3.875 for a total of $38,750.<p>It sold 920,000 shares at $0.1875 for $172,500.
Scattered sold something worth $38,750 for $172,500.
The profit: $133,750. <p>(Throughout Scattered's trading, the price of the warrants never exceeded the price of the stock times 92, making the play profitable for the whole period.)<p>

