<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Hidden Motives</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Hidden Motives</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Few investors know how much money some fund marketers pay banks to "help" sell their shares <p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Commercial banks and thrifts have been selling mutual funds in their branches for more than ten years now. And their fund sales are large. According to the most recent figures available from Cerulli Associates in Boston, banks collected 11 percent of the roughly $510 billion in new money that investors put into equity and bond mutual funds in 1994.<p>Some 3,000 banks sell funds across the U.S. Many of them do a good job either by managing funds in-house through an investment subsidiary or by selecting from the 4,500 or so outside stock and bond funds to recommend to their customers. At some banks, however, the choice of which funds make it onto so-called preferred lists isn't always based on what's best for the customer. Rather, it is based on which funds most benefit the bank. In these cases, selection becomes not so much Darwinian__only the best-performing funds get offered__as Shylockian, with a pound of flesh exacted by the bank.<p>With so much competition, it isn't surprising that some fund companies pay to get their products on a bank's shelf, over and above commissions given to bank salespeople. These incentives include sending productive bank salespeople and managers who push their funds on all-expenses-paid trips to vacation spots, such as ski trips to Colorado and Switzerland, and giving away incentives like VCRs, TVs, exercise equipment, and golf clubs. Some fund companies fork over millions, ostensibly to cover a bank's advertising and promotion costs. And some banks go even further, demanding that the fund company pay the bank 2.5 cents of every dollar of the fund sold by that bank. When you're into billions of dollars of funds sold, these pennies have a way of adding up. And, as usual with marketing costs, they are ultimately paid by the consumer in the form of lower returns.<p>Hidden incentives and payments aren't new to the investment business. Brokerage firms have been rewarding top-producing salesmen for years with lavish trips and generous gifts. But the bank-fund schemes look bad on two counts. First, customers are unlikely to know how much a fund company is paying to the bank to sell its shares. Second, with gifts and money changing hands, a fund's merit may no longer be the prevailing consideration.How do fund buyers know they're getting the best fund for their money? A source at a major fund company that is unwilling to pay the levies required by some banks says, "The selection should be based on which organization and its products are most appropriate to the customer's needs. Instead, it's 'Who's willing to pay up?' "<p>According to this source, Chemical Bank, a major player in funds, has demanded that his fund company pay extra to have its shares sold through the bank. Although Chemical, the nation's fourth-largest bank, will not disclose how much business it does in annual fund sales, it's among the nation's biggest in the business. Say Chemical does $1 billion in mutual fund sales a year, a fair guess according to an industry expert. If just half of those sales were done with fund companies who agreed to pay the 25 basis points in freight, the bank rakes in an additional $1 million a year, no-risk. Nice work if you can get it. <p>As of mid-February, Chemical's short list included nine fund families, half the number offered a year ago. All carry loads, most of them hefty__between 4.50 percent and 5.75 percent. Leonard Malkin, president of Chemical Investment Services, says the bank selects its funds after an in-depth screening process that considers, among other things, fund performance over long periods and in both up and down markets, risk profile, and the quality of the fund manager. When asked about the extra pay arrangements from fund companies, Malkin first answers, "I am not aware of that." Then he changes his mind, stating, "That's not true." Five of the fund families that deal with Chemical would not comment on specifics about their relationships with the bank. But other fund-industry sources confirm that Chemical does demand such fees.<p>Last year, San Franciscobased Prophet Market Research & Consulting surveyed 50 of the largest bank securities programs in the country, conducting 400 "mystery" shopping audits in 23 states to gauge the clarity of sales pitches in bank branches and compliance with sales regulations. Chemical's performance was woeful; it ranked third from the bottom.<p>Insisting on extra money from funds or allowing salespeople to accept resort trips is not the way of all banks, but it is nonetheless prevalent. Says another fund-company executive: "There are a lot of beauty contests going on." This, in spite of the guidelines for banks selling investments, published by the American Bankers Association and five other industry groups, stating that salespeople "should not favor or disfavor the sale of a particular investment company, group of investment companies or insurance company product based solely on the receipt of brokerage commissions or other incentives." <p>Old habits die hard. How many banks strictly follow the ABA guidelines today? Hard to tell, since financial relationships between fund companies and the banks that sell their products are kept under wraps. Until all remunerations are detailed clearly and upfront, investors will never know how much a fund company has given to a bank to "help" sell its funds.<p>According to industry sources, among the group of banks that run their fund operations on merit and appropriateness for customers are Pittsburgh-based PNC Bank Corp., Columbus, Ohio based Banc One, and Cleveland-based KeyCorp.<p>PNC offers 200 outside funds, all with loads. George Bernard, head of the bank's mutual fund group, describes PNC's selection process: First it looks at the fund company's financial strength and reputation, operations, and technological abilities. Then it considers the diversity of the company's offerings and fund fees. The bank has six fund families on its list. "We will not take money to be on our list, and we do not allow fund families to give our salespeople trips or other recognition programs," he says. "We want to be held to a higher standard." <p>Jack Kopnisky, president of KeyCorp.'s investment subsidiary, agrees that banks have to be extremely cautious in their relationships with outside fund companies. KeyCorp., a veteran in the mutual fund business, is narrowing its offerings from 50 fund families to 10. "We're trying to level the playing field so one company doesn't pay more than others," Kopnisky says. "And we are going to manage incentive trips more closely in the future. You don't want to [encourage] brokers to sell one product over another."<p>Banks should be required to divulge to customers any and all "extras" fund companies pay them to help sell their wares. This information should not be buried in the fine print of a prospectus and should be clearly stated to investors. Only then can customers make fully informed investment decisions about which fund is best for them.<p>One fund executive says that the Securities & Exchange Commission is becoming more concerned about the types of incentives handed out to bank brokers selling funds these days. But this doesn't stop banks from doing business this way. Says Cerulli Associates' Mary McAvity: "They're just more careful about how they demand incentives."  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Bond Investing, Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
