	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Fraud du Jour is Wireless Cable</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Fraud du Jour is Wireless Cable</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Fraud du Jour is Wireless Cable</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>THE FRAUD DU JOUR IS WIRELESS CABLE
Scams rise as investors look for a high-tech bonanza.<p>By Kathleen Murray<p>Two years ago, george salmon, a retiree from Hanford, California, saw an advertisement in a local newspaper touting a hot new high-tech investment. After reviewing the offering documents and talking to a salesman about promised returns of 300  percent, he put $10,000 in Broadcast Holdings, a Costa Mesa, California, company looking to develop wireless cable systems in Missouri, Tennessee, and Oregon.<p>Last May, Broadcast Holdings shut its doors after state authorities, suspecting the company of selling unregistered securities, raided its offices. Salmon remains optimistic. "I'm hopeful that this will all be cleared up soon," he said. "I still  think it's a good investment."<p>State and federal regulators, however, fear Salmon is one of thousands of investors nationwide to be taken by what they say is the "fraud du jour" -- wireless cable systems. Since 1992, unscrupulous promoters have raised over $300 million in  questionable deals to set up wireless systems, a viable technology that transmits television programming via microwave to some 500,000 U.S. homes. <p>State officials already have shuttered more than 70 illicit wireless operations. In the past year the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Federal Trade Commission have brought more than a dozen lawsuits. But the scams continue. In Southern  California alone, regulators estimate 30 boiler rooms are still bringing in $1 million a month. "People fall for it because they think you can't lose with high tech, that the information highway is paved with gold," says G.W. "Bill" McDonald, chief  of enforcement for the California Department of Corporations.<p>The pitch, according to McDonald and other regulators, seldom varies. Companies say they have a license to provide wireless cable for a region, and if you invest now, you can help build a system that might be bought out by a large company. Their  claims are bolstered by the fact that there is a legitimate wireless-cable industry. Buoyed by regulatory changes, wireless companies have raised more than $500 million on Wall Street, according to the Wireless Cable Association International.<p>There's a difference, though, between the deals investment banks are willing to put money into and those being peddled to unsophisticated investors, regulators say. Scammers typically sell unregistered shares in a general partnership or in  limited-liability companies, whereas legit companies are listed on an exchange. With that arrangement, fraudsters often sidestep regulations requiring financial disclosure. They then try to get away with charging fees and promising returns well  above those of any publicly traded company.<p>Take Continental Wireless Cable Television in La Jolla, California. An SEC lawsuit alleges that company operators lured victims with television and radio infomercials touting the wonders of wireless technology. People who called an 800 number were  later contacted by members of a 250-man sales force. If they invested immediately in systems in Nashville or New Orleans, they were told they could earn returns of as much as 500 percent in as little as three years. <p>In 16 months, Continental raised $36 million from more than 2,000 investors in 46 states. Regulators charge that only $7.1 million actually went into building the system. More than $11 million went to pay sales commissions and other promotional  expenses, and at least $1.2 million was "loaned" to officers Robin McPherson, Jay Bishop, and Gene Cardenaz. The company also used $233,000 to settle an enforcement action against it in Tennessee. Roughly $16.5 million remains unaccounted for.<p>On July 12, a California court approved a preliminary injunction against Continental. Company officials deny wrongdoing and point to a working system in Nashville with 2,200 subscribers. SEC attorney Karen Matteson, however, suggests that even if  investors try to run the systems, it is unlikely they could make a profit without putting in thousands of dollars. "You're talking about people who invested their IRA money," she says.<p>Law-enforcement officials say retirement money is particularly attractive to wireless con artists. To push $10,000 minimum investments in Wireless Limited Liability of Parkersburg, West Virginia, salesmen in one Denver boiler room told potential  investors that the IRS had suggested they call because the person had an IRA and this was a government-approved investment. Wrong, said the SEC, which closed the company down in May, but not before it had raised $11 million. <p>Not all wireless companies are fraudulent, of course. If you think you've found a good one, beware of promises of big profits, said Tom Hamill, the SEC's senior special counsel on wireless fraud. "There's no basis for these projections of 300  percent returns," he says. "Even wireless companies that are up and running go years without showing a profit."<p>If you're considering investing in wireless cable, consult an attorney or accountant before you do. Andrew Kreig of Wireless Cable Association International recommends investors specifically ask how the investment money will be spent. If the lion's  share is for promotion, not plant and equipment, pass. Be advised that the operator needs to own or lease a minimum of 20 of the 32 FCC-approved channels for a viable operation. <p>You should also check out the company, its principals, and its sales organizations with your local Better Business Bureau and securities regulator. In a recent nationwide survey, state regulators identified 267 companies and 520 individuals in  wireless and other high-tech scams that warranted looking into. Of those, 100 of the companies and 110 of the individuals had been disciplined in the past for securities violations. <p>With regulators turning up the heat on wireless fraud, some say it's only a matter of time before the fast-buck artists move on. The SEC has already filed two cases involving specialized mobile radio, and regulators predict fraudulent offerings for  personal-communications systems and interactive video may not be far behind. "The product changes," says McDonald, "but it's just the same scam over and over again."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Telecommunicatons Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
