<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-The Real S&L Scandal</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-The Real S&L Scandal</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The untold story of Scott Cone is one of regulators run amok. But it is also just one piece of a broader nightmare. Although the so-called cleanup of the savings and loan industry may have begun as a well-intentioned crackdown on abuse, it has become a witch-hunt, destroying the lives of honest operators.  The toll, in human and financial terms, is staggering. Congress should put a stop to it.<p>By Mollie Dickenson<p>In his last days, just before Thanksgiving 1992, Scott Cone had become sad, even tearful. He was also frightened, sure that the FBI was following him and tapping his phone. Cone had been chief financial officer for Landmark Land Co., a real estate  developer based in New Orleans that also owned a number of savings and loans. But Landmark had been taken over by federal regulators from the Office of Thrift Supervision. Cone, 39 years old, was jobless in a deepening recession and banned for life  from banking. He owed his defense lawyers an overwhelming sum, and he was also alone, having divorced his wife of 18 years, Debby, to distance his family from his mounting personal and professional problems.<p>"I don't think I ever thought he wasn't going to be okay," Debby says. "I thought he'd regroup. Later, I realized he'd told me good-bye and I didn't even know it. He said, 'You've always been a good mother, Deb. I love you and the girls more than anything else in the world.'" <p>For more than two years, Cone had been the point man in Landmark's battle to keep its huge real estate empire operating profitably while also keeping the company out of the hands of newly hostile thrift regulators. This enormous task had fallen to  Cone, never a major decision maker in the company, because the regulators had fired his boss and Cone knew Landmark's finances inside and out. "Scott was the sweetest, most sensitive person I've ever known," says former Landmark chairman Gerald  Barton. "But to the regulators he became a symbol of an institution that dared to question government actions." <p>Gregory Goggans, as the Office of Thrift Supervision's resident examiner, was the bank's permanent regulator. Three Landmark employees say they saw a letter Goggans had written to his superiors in 1990; in it he stated that his goal for the year was  to "bring the bank down."<p>In 1990 and 1991, while demanding that Landmark sell its properties, the government scuttled, with little explanation, two bona fide offers Landmark received for its luxury resort properties -- among them Kiawah Island, a South Carolina golf resort,  and the Palm Beach Polo and Country Club in Florida. Had regulators allowed Landmark to accept either offer, the company might have survived. Taxpayers could have saved more than $1 billion. <p>Instead, Landmark's subsidiaries declared bankruptcy in October 1991. The filing was intended to help the company liquidate properties free of government interference. Two court rulings upheld this strategy, but in August 1992 an appeals court ruled  that new S&L regulations essentially put the government beyond the law. Landmark fell into receivership under the Resolution Trust Corp., the federal agency created to handle bankrupt thrifts. <p>"Scott was consumed with getting the government out of the bank and out of our affairs," says William Thompson, Landmark's chief tax accountant and the man who hired Cone. "He was obsessed to the point that he even began to disregard his children,  whom he had always put first." <p>The OTS accused Cone of withholding company records, a bizarre charge since the government itself had confiscated the documents it was demanding. Then the government sued Cone and the thrift's comptroller for conspiring to file false reports and  fraudulently reporting more capital than Landmark had. <p>Cone's legal bills were now his, not his company's responsibility. With no money to defend himself, he signed a consent decree in return for getting the government to drop charges. His banking career was over.<p>"Scott was a sincere, honest boy from the country," says Debby Cone, who began dating Scott when he was 19. "He believed the government was looking for bad guys, and they were trying to make him and the others at Landmark into those bad guys. He  believed they could look forever, for there was nothing to find."<p>Debby wanted Scott to quit Landmark and become a country veterinarian, a dream he'd had. But he felt if he left he would let people down. "He believed in our justice system and wanted his day in court," says Debby. "Landmark's survival had become  more important to him than anything else, and he took its breakup like a death. I kept telling him, 'I love you. I'll stick by you.' But I couldn't seem to reach him."<p>The Sunday night before Thanksgiving, Scott Cone took the family's shotgun, put it to his head, and pulled the trigger. He left no note for his wife and two children, but the source of his despair was clear. He was wearing a T-shirt some Landmark  employees had made up in a moment of defiance against the government. It had RTC printed on it, circled and slashed through in red.<p>At the funeral three days later, Debby was summoned to the sheriff's office after the burial. She was shown into a back room where two FBI agents waited. "They began asking me a lot of questions. Then they told me that there was a chance that Scott  had been murdered and that they wanted to look through his apartment. That frightened me. I knew it was suicide." <p>She told them they could not search the apartment until she talked to her lawyer, but as it was Thanksgiving, the lawyer was unreachable. The session with the FBI ended, but Debby remained afraid. "I knew it would be hard to get good legal advice  given the bizarre, almost unbelievable things we'd been through," she said. <p>Debby began getting calls from lawyers and government officials asking about papers Scott might have had. And on her second visit to his apartment, she noticed that the garbage had been taken out. A month later she came home to find her door  standing open. She was subpoenaed for personal notes Scott had kept after the ordeal began.<p>
When most people think of the savings and loan crisis, they picture shady businessmen who enriched themselves at the expense of taxpayers while the government looked the other way. This view not only is consistent with popular opinion, but also  apparently jibes with the sentiments of regulators at the OTS and the RTC. OTS spokesman William Fulwider, for instance, asserts that 50 percent of all U.S. thrifts engaged in fraudulent practices.<p>There's a problem with this image, however: It's false. <p>Last fall, the National Commission on Financial Institution Reform, Recovery and Enforcement, authorized by Congress, concluded that only 10 percent to 15 percent of monetary losses sustained by taxpayers in the S&L crisis were the result of fraud.  Of the 4,000 S&Ls extant in 1980, banking experts say no more than 100 were outlaw operations. "I stand by my consistent judgment that only 3 percent of losses were due to fraud," says banking consultant Bert Ely of Ely & Co. in Alexandria, Virginia.<p>To come to an understanding of what truly happened in the S&L crisis, Worth spent a year and a half examining ten different thrift cases in litigation. The government was of little help in the process; the OTS and RTC are two of the most secretive  agencies in Washington. Although the spokespeople for these organizations say that they are simply doing what Congress instructed them to do and doing a fine job fixing an "unprecedented problem," it is their policy not to discuss specific cases  that are in litigation.<p>Government regulators have approached the so-called S&L crisis as if widespread criminality applied to anyone with a pocket calculator. In the process, it has seized hundreds of failing thrifts whose assets might have been preserved through sales  and mergers. It has deemed "insolvent" some 500 salvageable S&Ls, seizing them under interpretations of a law Congress passed to resolve the thrift crisis.<p>"The large majority of S&Ls have always been ethical operations," says Vic Simon, editor of Bank Bailout Litigation News. "All the really rogue operations were closed down by 1990. Many of the government's cases are against people who did nothing  wrong."<p>In its quest to catch crooks, the RTC became the nation's largest employer of law firms. Between 1989 and 1991, it paid $1 billion to 3,350 firms, according to informed sources. The agency also has paid $6.5 billion to more than 100,000 outside  contractors, such as appraisers and brokers of thrift assets. <p>Salaries at the OTS and RTC top out  at $158,000, according to documents supplied under a Freedom of Information Act request. Only the president, vice president, and chief justice make more among all federal workers. Congress recently sent the RTC $18 billion in new money, even though  the agency is scheduled to shut its doors at the end of 1995.<p>All told, the RTC has spent $130 billion of taxpayers' money and sold $400 billion worth of seized assets. Many of these assets, sold at discounts of 30 to 40 percent (taxpayers make up the difference so thrift depositors can be reimbursed in full),  have ended up in the hands of wealthy individuals (Texas investor Robert Bass, Revlon chief executive Ron Perelman), corporations (GE Capital Corp., Ford Motor Credit Co.), and partnerships managed by Wall Street firms (Merrill Lynch, Goldman  Sachs). Together, these asset sales constitute one of the largest transfers of wealth in U.S. history.<p>Just last March, the RTC said it would reopen "several hundred" thrift investigations that had been closed. Washington defense attorney and former federal prosecutor Douglas Lobel says, "More and more aggressive prosecutors are converting regulatory  and administrative violations into criminal convictions, using elastic statutes that know virtually no limits."<p>Perhaps the most damning view of the RTC and its litigation practices comes from a man who until 1992 was the agency's associate general counsel. Now a lawyer in Washington, Ira Parker says, "The fear of being called before Senate and House banking  committees caused the RTC to file many questionable suits against former directors and officers." Parker says he usually got cases two days before the statute of limitations ran out. "Twenty percent of them are easy, they're black and white. The  other 80 percent are in a gray area, but.. . . If you make a decision not to bring action, you know you're going to be up on the Hill being asked to explain, but if you go ahead and authorize litigation, nobody's going to criticize you." <p><p>For the sake of perspective, it's important to keep in mind that the thrift industry was plunged into crisis not because of thievery, but because of high interest rates in the late '70s and early '80s. At the time, thrifts were locked into receiving  low-yielding, long-term mortgage payments from their customers. Meanwhile, these institutions could pay no more than 5.5 percent interest to depositors, a limit set by regulators. Naturally, as uninsured money market accounts began paying interest  of up to 15 percent, the thrifts began losing depositors in droves. <p>In 1982, in a bid to help the industry, Congress changed some of the rules. It allowed thrifts to pay rates competitive with money market accounts. It also allowed them to begin making riskier investments than simple home mortgages. The amount  covered by federal insurance was raised from $40,000 to $100,000. <p>Later, the Reagan administration, under Vice President George Bush's Deregulatory Task Group, took further action. It began lifting restrictions on the kinds of investments that thrifts could make, as well as on the percentage of assets they could  put into those investments. Rather than increase the number of regulators to oversee newly freed thrifts, however, Bush's group targeted the regulatory budget for cuts. "They told 'em, 'Go do anything you want,'" says banking consultant Richard  Hohlt. "But then they forgot to hire the cops."<p>These policy changes certainly did attract some unscrupulous operators to the S&L industry. They also encouraged some inexperienced thrift managers to invest badly in unfamiliar territory. But the industry was hardly as riddled with crooks as the  public was later led to believe.<p>In 1986, Congress rescinded generous tax breaks given in 1982 to commercial real estate investors. As a result, property values plunged. Previously encouraged to invest more heavily in real estate, thrifts watched in horror as the value of their new  holdings plunged. Problems in the thrift industry had become a full-blown crisis. Commercial banking found itself in turmoil as well.<p>Amidst all the financial chaos, some abuses surfaced and Washington launched into its usual round of finger-pointing. William Seidman, former head of the FDIC and the RTC, writes in his recent memoir that Bush planned during his 1988 presidential  campaign "to attack the Democratic Congress" for easing S&L restrictions. <p>Once elected, Bush promised to put the crooks who looted the S&Ls behind bars. The law intended to help accomplish this was the Financial Institutions Reform, Recovery and Enforcement Act (FIRREA) of 1989. The Democratic Congress, cowering under  charges that it had intervened on behalf of S&L crooks, stiffened the law and authorized $50 billion as the first installment of the cleanup. For thrifts, their lawyers, and their accountants, it was the beginning of a witch-hunt that would destroy  hundreds of ethical companies and ruin thousands of lives.<p>"FIRREA, as written, wasn't all bad," says Robert O'Brien, former chief executive of a New Jersey thrift and a onetime federal banking official. "It was the way it was applied that ended the thrift industry as we know it." To hide their past errors  and protect their careers, Bush appointees and regulators ruthlessly shut down solvent and/or law-abiding thrifts, then ineptly sold their assets. <p>The law established two new agencies within the executive branch: the Office of Thrift Supervision, which regulates and determines the solvency of thrifts, and the Resolution Trust Corp., which manages seized thrifts and sells off their assets.  Their victims call them the Executioner and the Undertaker. <p>"Having to spend $150 billion allowed the administration to create an enormous political fiefdom," says O'Brien. FIRREA also turned the tables on the thrift business, redefining previously allowed investments, such as real estate, as  "impermissible." S&Ls effectively had up to five years to sell all real estate included in their capital; during that time they had to discount the value of these properties by ever-increasing percentages. Junk bonds were also written down and had  to be sold. Also, uninsured capital notes, commonly sold to bolster S&Ls' financial positions, were now disallowed. <p>FIRREA also reneged on the contracts that many S&Ls had struck with the government when they agreed to take over failed thrifts, contracts that had allowed thrifts to count as assets the money owed to depositors of the failed institution, their  negative net worth. This accounting mechanism, known as regulatory goodwill, had saved millions in taxpayer money throughout the '80s. "It was an enormous benefit to the government," says Bank Bailout Litigation News's Simon. But FIRREA took it  away. As a result, many thrifts instantly found themselves out of capital compliance. <p>As if FIRREA weren't enough, many thrifts weren't even given a chance to sell their real estate or junk bonds. The OTS marched in and arbitrarily wrote down the assets, making the S&Ls "undercapitalized" and subject to seizure. Often, OTS employees  refused to let S&Ls sell assets.<p><p>FIRREA also gave the OTS and RTC extraordinary powers to criminalize behavior that once represented standard procedure in the S&L industry. Thrift employees suddenly could be held criminally liable in S&L cases even when the financial institution  lost no money and the individual obtained no personal benefit. Edward Morris, a 51-year-old investment banker and former CEO of Germania Savings and Loan in St. Louis, discovered this the hard way. Last July 11, he was sentenced to 46 months in a  federal prison. His putative crime: Mail and wire fraud. <p>In 1987 and 1988, Germania attempted to increase its capital position by selling $16 million of its own uninsured notes to depositors and other investors. The government claimed that Morris peddled these notes to unsophisticated investors (among  them, his son) at a time when he supposedly knew the bank was in bad shape -- this even though Germania capital positions exceeded requirements by nearly $19 million.<p>At the time, issuing capital notes was a common practice. It was also permitted by regulators. FIRREA, however, outlawed the practice. The rule change put Germania out of capital compliance, inviting an RTC takeover. The notes Morris had sold his investors became worthless, and the bank couldn't pay off depositors. <p>Morris says the RTC was unable to pay depositors because its takeover of Germania caused a run on the bank. He also says the government sold the thrift's assets below their market value. Morris says he was in a catch-22: "Regulators arbitrarily  define your capital away, take over your bank, sell your assets for pennies on the dollar, then, coming up way short of money to pay off depositors and investors, say, 'See, we said this was a worthless thrift!'" <p>Before the government took over the thrift, Morris received an offer for Germania from a large St. Louis bank. The proposed acquisition would have saved taxpayers $50 million later spent on cleaning up Germania's operations. The government, however,  nixed the sale. <p>In December 1991, the RTC sued Morris for mismanagement of Germania's assets, negligence, and something called "unjust enrichment." This last charge was a strange one. To demonstrate unjust enrichment, regulators must prove a defendant stole assets  from an institution. Yet Morris had lost $50,000 of his own money in the Germania debacle. So the RTC focused on Morris's $130,000 annual salary. The RTC decided that Morris should have been making only $115,000. In his two years on the job,  therefore, the government alleged that Morris had "stolen" $30,000. Ironically, Morris's salary was less than those of many of the regulators who later hounded him. "That's when I really cracked," says Morris. The government froze Morris's assets, a  move later overturned by a district-court judge. <p>Morris's ordeal pushed him to start a newsletter, Regulatory Watchdog, which tracks thrift-regulatory actions. "My anger got focused pretty well," he says. <p><p>Regulators, in taking on what they perceive as a thoroughly corrupt industry, also have stumbled as a result of their own inexperience or ignorance. A case in point is the saga of Jess Rodrigues, president of Saratoga Savings & Loan in San Jose,  California.<p>In 1982, Rodrigues bought the charter on Saratoga Savings & Loan for $25,000 and capitalized the company with $2 million from his mortgage company. "There was no one more qualified to run an S&L than me," says Rodrigues, who had great success as a  mortgage banker. "I'd dealt with the Federal Housing Administration, Ginnie Mae, Fannie Mae, and Freddie Mac for years with never a problem." Things went well at Saratoga; he opened two branches in Silicon Valley. In 1985, the thrift had $165  million in assets and was returning 40 percent on equity. <p>Saratoga's troubles began in 1986, when the government placed the thrift under a cease-and-desist order for alleged unsafe lending practices. Feeling that he had done nothing wrong, Rodrigues fought back. Initially, he was vindicated. An  administrative law judge declared that the government's entire argument had been based on erroneous assumptions of fact, arbitrary conclusions of regulatory requirements, and a total lack of rationale.<p>The government, however, pressed on, and in 1987 the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in its favor: Saratoga had to follow the cease-and-desist order. The government then referred the case to the Justice Department for criminal prosecution. For  the next year and a half Rodrigues and his wife, Donna, found themselves under constant surveillance. Their phones were tapped on six different occasions. But the criminal investigation went nowhere. In February 1989, U.S. Attorney Joseph P.  Russoniello of San Francisco closed the case, saying, "Further investigation is not warranted."<p>The Justice Department had given up, but not the OTS. It still wanted to get Saratoga. On November 9, 1989, at 4:30 p.m., OTS officials stormed Saratoga's branches with FBI agents and security guards in tow. Bank executives were herded into a  boardroom, their briefcases searched. "They frisked everybody on the way out," says Rodrigues. "The young examiners were doing high fives in the parking lot."<p>Charging Saratoga with "unsafe and unsound banking practices," the regulators placed the thrift into receivership. Rodrigues and his lawyers fought the charges, using a spring 1989 assessment by Merrill Lynch of Saratoga's $19.7 million value to  prove the thrift was nowhere near insolvent. But this line of defense came to naught.<p>Rodrigues could do nothing as he watched the government drive his bank into the ground -- all at taxpayer expense. Before the takeover, Saratoga S&L paid its controller $48,000 a year. That person was fired; the government's controller earned  $80,000 a year. <p>Saratoga held a $1 million loan on 200 acres of land adjacent to an IBM plant in San Jose. Before the government seized the thrift, the borrower had struck a deal to sell the land for $1.6 million. But before the sale went through, the RTC grabbed  the $1 million deed and sold it to Pacific Western Bank for $100,000, or 10 cents on the dollar. The borrower then renegotiated the $1 million loan down to $600,000, only to sell the land for $1.6 million. Pacific Western made a fast $500,000, the  borrower saved $400,000, and taxpayers lost $900,000. Rodrigues was stunned: "There had to be something more at work here than stupidity."<p>The $20 million business Rodrigues had built was being destroyed. On the advice of his accountant, Rodrigues's holding company took a $2.6 million tax-loss carryback on Saratoga's books that regulators wanted to carry forward instead and put into  the thrift. After 18 months, the IRS and Congress approved the refund, with interest, to Rodrigues's holding company. <p>But a blistering regulatory response followed right on the heels of the check. In June 1992, the Justice Department used new forfeiture laws to seize Rodrigues's assets, putting liens on his house, his bank accounts, and two pieces of property he  owned. In April 1994, Rodrigues was indicted for embezzlement. He awaits his trial.<p>Banned for life from the banking industry, Rodrigues now owns and operates a nursery in northern California. "The last person in my life that I thought I'd get screwed by is my government," he says. <p><p>Franklin Savings Association of Ottawa, Kansas, the state's largest thrift, appears to have been another victim of regulatory incompetence. Throughout the 1980s, it employed a very successful hedging operation -- one that former Franklin executives  believe government agents never understood. Instead, they say, Franklin's hedging techniques were used as an excuse to seize the thrift February 16, 1990.<p>The seizure "came without warning," says Ernest Fleischer, 61, Franklin's former CEO. Fleischer requested a meeting in Washington to discuss the seizure; he says OTS general counsel Harris Weinstein told him that any settlement of his case would  require him to agree never to bring legal action against the OTS, its officers, or independent contractors it hired. Says Fleischer: "I responded that my purpose was to resolve any factual difference and to reach a settlement with the regulators,  and then, that they and I should be free to achieve any legal redress available."<p>No way, said Weinstein. "There was never a discussion of the merits of the case," says Fleischer.<p>"It was an ugly meeting," says Franklin's attorney, Charles German. "Weinstein and his people were so arrogant, condescending, and rude to all of us, including Fleischer's wife, who was there as an owner of Franklin." OTS filed a motion against  German saying that because he had represented Franklin on other unrelated matters, the lawyer was acting improperly. Says German, "Weinstein told me I was not to speak during this meeting." The motion against German was denied; government lawyers  were later sanctioned by Magistrate Judge Ronald Newman in the U.S. District Court of Topeka, Kansas, for having filed it.<p>Months ago, Judge Newman charged the RTC with litigation abuse in the Franklin case, saying it "engaged in a type of gamesmanship which will not be tolerated by the court. Due to the conduct of the RTC in this matter, the expense of litigation has  been increased, counsel's time has been wasted, and the court's resources usurped. Therefore, the court finds that sanctions are warranted."<p>The OTS's case against Franklin claimed that the thrift would be undercapitalized if it properly recognized losses such as those "resulting from hedging operations." The thrift sued to prevent seizure and was upheld by U.S. District Judge Dale  Saffels. He wrote that OTS's conclusions were "arbitrary and capricious and without reasonable basis" and that OTS "staff appeared to lack adequate training and understanding to evaluate the nature of Franklin's operations." Saffels further ruled  that the key fact used to justify the takeover was erroneous. What's more, Saffels said, OTS orders to continue writing down Franklin's assets lacked "any reasonable basis."<p>Saffels concluded that Franklin's hedging plan was "safe and sound," that regulators "acted wrongly in imposing the conservatorship." But Franklin lost its case in May 1991, when the 10th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that, as established by  FIRREA, only the government's side of the case could be considered. The Supreme Court denied Franklin's petition without comment.<p><p>One of the many ironies about the S&L story is how the government turned on the very people it had sought out to help solve the problem of America's failing thrifts. Landmark was such a company. <p>In 1982, banking regulators traveled to Landmark's offices and asked the company to absorb the failed Dixie Savings & Loan in New Orleans, a move that would prevent a federal bailout and save taxpayers some $150 million. Landmark's Gerald Barton  agreed to the transaction only when the government said Landmark could count Dixie's $150 million negative net worth as an asset and write it off over 40 years. <p>Though Landmark would have to earn an extra 2.5 percent profit a year to cover the declining value of the regulatory goodwill, Barton accepted the deal because his company would be able to fund its real estate development through the thrift at  slightly less than market rates. Still, says Barton, the decision "was a close call." <p>A year later, regulators asked Landmark to contribute all of its real estate holdings -- some $270 million worth -- to the thrift subsidiary, which had been renamed Oak Tree Savings. This was done to avoid what could have been a conflict of interest  -- a holding company that owned real estate and a subsidiary that did as well. Still, the Oak Tree deal worked so well for both sides that in 1986, the government asked Landmark to take over another bankrupt Louisiana thrift, St. Bernard Savings and  Loan. By 1989, Landmark was managing and selling $1 billion in real estate properties from 21 other failed thrifts, more than any other company in the nation. <p>But that year was also the beginning of the end for Landmark. "We went from being part of the solution [to the S&L crisis] to being part of the problem," says Barton. <p>At the time, Oak Tree was one of the best-capitalized thrifts in the nation; it possessed roughly $600 million in capital against $2.5 billion in assets. This healthy 24 percent capital ratio was way above the 3 percent required then by regulators. <p>But in 1989, to adhere to FIRREA's onerous new capital requirements, Landmark officials prepared to sell their choicest property holdings. The first offer for Landmark's luxury resorts came in April 1990 from Barry Hon, a California developer. Hon  offered $965 million: $200 million in cash and a mortgage to be held by Oak Tree for the remainder, secured by the properties underlying it. Landmark's board approved the sale. <p>Nevertheless, on May 7, 1990, Neil Twomey, Oak Tree's OTS supervisor in Dallas, rejected the Hon transaction, saying it was "unsafe and unsound." Barton asked him for further clarification but says Twomey didn't seem to have anything substantive to  add in the way of an explanation.<p>On June 6, a second offer for the Landmark properties arrived. This one was from Texas billionaire investor Robert Bass, who had previously tried to get in on the Hon transaction. This time, he offered $904 million -- $61 million less than the  initial bid. <p>A day later, Barton says Twomey advised him to sell Landmark's real estate holdings quickly, no later than the end of June. The reason, according to Twomey, was that tough new examiners were coming to town on July 1, and they'd have instructions to  write down Landmark's real estate. If that happened, Oak Tree no longer would have enough capital. <p>On June 8, Barton got a surprise. He found out that Neil Twomey was about to leave his OTS job and sign on with the Bass organization. Twomey would be working for the chief negotiator trying to buy the Landmark properties. Barton was stunned. He  recalls that this was "the man with no real estate expertise, who was solely responsible for turning down the Hon bid, and who then demanded that I have a contract for sale within 30 days."<p>Contrary to Twomey's warnings, however, the new regulators did not immediately force Barton's hand. So Landmark looked elsewhere for a buyer. A third offer came in January 1991 from Dai-Ichi, a large Japanese real estate company: $785 million, with  a down payment of $322 million in cash. For ten months, the government sat on the proposal, neither approving nor rejecting the Dai-Ichi offer. The long delay effectively scuttled the deal. <p>Finally, Barton decided his only recourse was to take Landmark into bankruptcy. The date he filed was October 11, 1991. <p>Two days later, OTS seized Landmark. At around midnight on October 13, Gerald Barton's wife was awakened by a telephone call from the OTS. The caller informed her that the government had put a lien on the Barton home and had frozen all of the  family's bank accounts, including those of Barton's mother, brother, sister, and children.<p>Later, OTS chief counsel Harris Weinstein, enraged by Landmark's attempt at self-preservation, imposed penalties of $1 million each on four Landmark officers and civil fines of $500,000 a day on the company.<p><p>In June of this year, the Tenth Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver ruled that FIRREA constituted a breach of contract between thrifts and the government. The court said this breach had occurred when the law removed the benefits of regulatory  goodwill from thrifts' balance sheets. If this ruling stands upon further appeal, the government could be forced to pay billions of dollars back to the 250 thrifts that were subjected to this tactic.<p>Also, Scott Cone, Gerald Barton, and other Landmark officials were exonerated in June when a federal judge ruled that the company had acted in good faith by filing for bankruptcy protection in 1991. The judge further required that the RTC pay all of  Landmark's and its managers' legal bills. Total litigation costs now shouldered by the taxpayers consist of more than $1 million spent by Landmark and upwards of $10 million spent by the RTC. Neither Neil Twomey nor Gregory Goggans could be  contacted to discuss the Landmark case.<p>Eight hundred days after the OTS imposed its $500,000-a-day penalty on Landmark, the government dropped the fines. It did so without comment. The fines had accumulated to $400 million.<p>What happened to Landmark's premier properties? Although some have yet to be bid on, estimates of what the RTC will fetch from Landmark asset sales total $600 million. The book value of those assets is $1.2 billion. Loss to the taxpayer: More than  half a billion dollars. If the government had let Landmark sell to Barry Hon, the company would have made $450 million and taxpayers would have lost nothing, Landmark would be solvent, 5,000 employees would have jobs, and 5,000 shareholders would  not have been saddled with worthless stock.<p>Undaunted, Gerald Barton has returned to real estate development, this time in Columbus, Ohio. He set himself up in business on borrowed money. <p>After Debby Cone found out that her husband had been cleared, she said, "They thought I'd be happy to hear the news, but I cried. It came too late to help Scott."<p><p>Former thrift officers and directors hoped that the election of Bill Clinton might bring a reexamination of FIRREA and a reining in of the inept and abusive implementation of the law. Last year, Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen outlined an eight-step program to address "waste, fraud, and abuse" in the RTC. He nominated Republican RTC critic Stanley Tate to head the agency. Damaging leaks, however,  torpedoed Bentsen's effort, and Tate withdrew his name. Meanwhile President Clinton himself appears boxed in by the Madison Guaranty/Whitewater imbroglio and is hardly in a safe position to initiate a major investigation of the bailout bureaucracies  -- at least not without substantial political risk. <p>Some observers believe this is no accident: Lamar Kelly -- the Bush appointee in charge of liquidating thrift assets at the RTC -- reopened the Madison case on his way out of the agency. Jay Stephens, an avowed Clinton political enemy, is handling  the case. <p>At present, only one Clinton appointee heads up any of the banking bureaucracies -- Eugene Ludwig at the Comptroller of the Currency. The bureaucrats running the other agencies -- RTC, OTS, and FDIC -- continue to answer to no one.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Banking Industry, Ethical Investing

