	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Global Investing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						How to broaden your portfolio's horizons. Plus, a map of the investing world's hot spots.<p>By Gregory J. Millman<p>In recent years, U.S. investors have turned into financial Marco Polos, setting out across the globe in search of stratospheric returns. In the process, they've created the biggest foreign-stock-buying binge in history. During the first nine months of 1993 alone, American individuals and institutions snapped up $99 billion more in foreign securities than they sold--a buying spree that nearly doubled 1992's record $52 billion. People who have never folded a baht or a ringgit are now counting on securities traded in those currencies to help finance retirements and tuition bills. <p>Will the global treasure hunt pay off? <p>It certainly has been a bonanza for mutual funds that specialize in foreign markets; they've been the fastest-growing segment of the fund industry. A year ago, Twentieth Century International had $223 million in net assets. Today it manages $950 million. In the same time period, Templeton Developing Markets shot from $180 million under management to $1.4 billion. Morningstar, the Chicago-based <p>fund-research firm, now lists 185 international equities funds, up from 100 three years ago.<p>This represents a major change in the way Americans invest. "Ten years ago international investing didn't even show up in statistics on asset allocation by Americans; there wasn't even enough to round it to 1 percent," says Mark Riepe, a vice president with Ibbotson Associates, an investment-research firm in Chicago. "Now, almost 10 percent of American institutional portfolios are invested internationally."<p>Investors quick to jump on the bandwagon have done well. The U.S. markets didn't exactly have a bad year--the Dow Jones Industrials were up 13.7 percent in 1993 and the Nasdaq Composite 14.8 percent--but only three of the international market indices tracked by Morgan Stanley Capital International failed to leave the domestic stock exchanges in the dust. In local currencies, the Hong Kong market was up 110 percent in 1993, the Jakarta exchange up 107 percent, Chile up 48 percent, and Taiwan up 91 percent. The stock markets in Paris, Brussels, Hong Kong, Singapore, and Manila all set records as the year came to an end.<p>For many investors, the game for 1994 involves guessing which foreign markets will soar and which will tank. Is it time to take those profits out of Hong Kong and invest them in Mexico City?<p>Some of the best investment minds of Wall Street have applied themselves to this question. Optimists like Nimrod Fachler of Paine Webber still point to Mexico, Chile, and Argentina, where deregulation and privatization have unchained the economies, he believes. He also expects continued strength in Malaysia, Thailand, Singapore, and the Philippines. He's not as excited about Europe, and he'd avoid Japan: "Japan's prices came down, but earnings came down, too."<p>More pessimistic pundits such as <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a>'s Barton Biggs find recommendations like those dangerous. In November, Malaysia's market was trading at nearly four times the book value of the assets of the companies on the exchange, and Hong Kong's was at nearly three times book value. "By contrast, the average for Europe is 2.03 and the U.S. is at 2.64," Biggs told his clients. "I want to be in Asia for the long run, but things have gone too far too fast and are too frothy. If the markets keep rising vertically, I will sell some more. If they correct and calm down, I will go back in. Buy low, sell high." <p>In early January, the hot Asian markets took exactly the kind of dive Biggs had looked for. By January 10, Hong Kong had fallen 9.8 percent from its record high. Thailand was off 10.2 percent; Malaysia 9.3 percent, the Philippines 4.5 percent, and Singapore 4.3 percent. Of course, by Friday, January 14, these markets had rebounded. Hong Kong's market index was up 5.9 percent on that day alone.<p>Boil down all of this advice, either bull or bear, and it sounds suspiciously like a recipe for international market timing--speculating on short-term price movements. Many people who would never try to time the U.S. markets and who would describe themselves as long-term, patient investors are now engaged in frantic attempts to discover the next hot international market (what about China's Shenzhen exchange?) and then to sell before the peak (is it time to dump that Peruvian portfolio?).<p>William McBride, international editor at Lipper Analytical Services, notes that 6 of the 20 best-performing international funds in 1993 invested chiefly in Asia and in Latin America. This is dangerous territory--history shows that these markets are incredibly volatile and the politics of the regions hardly qualify as stable.  Yet investors are venturing in anyway because of the lure of sky-high returns. So what if some countries in these areas ordinarily make the evening news only because of a military coup or a debt default? At least that's what they seem to be saying. In Latin America, the hot investment is Brady Bonds: bank paper secured by Mexican debt that no one used to want, now repackaged and securitized to finance golden years of U.S. retirees. Investors who wouldn't dream of buying property in a fringe neighborhood are investing through mutual funds in Hong Kong real estate that will shortly become part of the People's Republic.<p>Some of the most aggressive investors are so desperate to be in the right market that they have helped bid single-country funds up to astounding prices. On January 3, the India Growth Fund sold at a 49 percent premium above the value of the stocks held by the fund. Likewise, the China Fund sold at a 40 percent premium and the Singapore Fund at a 32 percent premium, just to mention a few. Investors, it seems, were willing to pay that much extra just to get into these hot markets.<p>There are sound reasons to invest on the international stage, but this kind of speculative frenzy isn't one of them. This is especially true right now. Why? Because many of these markets have shot upwards simply in reaction to the incoming flood of dollars from U.S. investors--and not as a result of underlying economic factors. During the past year U.S. investors shoveled more than $1 billion a week into markets in Latin America, Southeast Asia, and other parts of what used to be called the third world, according to Morgan Stanley. With that kind of money pouring in so fast, it would be difficult for any market not to move up. Stock pickers on Mexico's Bolsa de Valores have a mere 200 listed issues to choose from. Hong Kong only lists 479 stocks; the Hang Seng index tracks 33 of them, a third of which are real estate firms, which tend to be highly speculative.<p>All this overexcitement is obscuring the soundest and most compelling reason to invest outside the United States: to increase diversification, reducing risk and thus earning a superior long-term return. This has nothing to do with speculation or greed or global stock fever but is instead a prudent and effective strategy for building a solid portfolio.<p>It's the same principle taught in Investing 101: Purchase a basket of stocks just in case one of your Snapples or Boston Chickens turns out to be a Crazy Eddie or a Leslie Fay. Sensible international investing takes this strategy a step further, providing a hedge against the price volatility of the entire U.S. marketplace. In this way, global investment can improve a portfolio's return with no increase--or even a reduction--in market risk. The shrinkage in market risk comes from the tendency of national markets to move in different directions; when the U.S.'s Dow Jones Industrial Average soars, Japan's Nikkei may sink, as the experience of the past few years demonstrates. <p>In fact, academics and others have shown that, over time, portfolios with a proper mix of overseas investments invariably outperform those with no foreign exposure. The curve shown in "The International Premium" shows how international diversification would have improved returns during the ten years ended on December 31, 1992. During that decade, according to research by the Frank Russell Co., a global-assets consultant to institutional investors, a portfolio of 100 percent U.S. equities would have earned a little more than 16 percent annually. Moving to a portfolio with 80 percent U.S. equities and 20 percent foreign stocks (following  Morgan Stanley's Europe, Australia, and Far East index) would have increased the return by about 50 basis points, or 0.5 percentage points a year. That move would also have lowered the risk  in the portfolio. Currently, the Investment Company Institute reports that just 9.5 percent of all the money that U.S. investors have poured into mutual funds is in either international or global equity, or global bond funds. With that in mind, the actions of American portfolio managers and the investors who hire them look less like bold moves than frantic compensation for past sins of omission.<p>The secret to global investing is to incorporate it into a broader, long-term strategy--and to move cautiously. "You have to be skeptical," says Roger G. Ibbotson, a Yale finance professor and coauthor of Global Investing: The Professional's Guide to World Capital Markets. Ibbotson urges investors to read marketing pitches for foreign funds with a skeptical eye, especially if they stress performance. "International isn't going to add performance to a portfolio every year," says Ibbotson. "Some years it will detract from performance." <p>Because diversification should be the primary goal, the precise method for constructing an international portfolio isn't especially important. To determine how large a role international investments should play, an investor can follow one of several rules of thumb. For example, someone who wanted true global diversification could structure a portfolio so that it accumulates foreign securities in proportion to the home countries' shares of global market capitalization. As the world-market-capitalization model in "Leaving Most of the World on the Table" shows, the U.S. represented 43 percent of the global equity market in 1992 and Japan 25 percent, so a portfolio could mirror that breakdown.<p>Most people, however--and certainly most Americans--feel more comfortable keeping a disproportionate share of their investments closer to home. Professor Albert Fredman of California State University at Fullerton recommends allocating 10 percent to 40 percent of a portfolio to foreign holdings. He also suggests balancing the debt and equity portions of foreign investments just as an investor would in the domestic markets: more equity for the young, more fixed-income debt for the old.<p>There are numerous strategies for constructing a balanced portfolio. A passive investor can simply buy a global mutual fund, a type of fund that invests in all the world's markets, and leave the asset allocation to a professional manager. A more adventurous investor can mix an international with a domestic fund or combine index funds for the U.S., Europe, and the Pacific. Blending single-country funds is yet another option. Of all the methods available, the only one that may be beyond the research capabilities of the average investor is constructing a sound portfolio of international stocks. Yet even here, American depositary receipts make  stock picking accessible. ADRs are certificates that trade on U.S. exchanges and represent the shares of foreign companies. <p>The route an investor ultimately chooses isn't especially important. But it is crucial to know that each technique requires a slightly different balancing act to achieve the proper mixture of risk and reward. Each strategy also comes with potential pitfalls for the uninformed.<p>Take index funds, for example, a quick and inexpensive way to achieve global diversification. Index managers assemble a portfolio designed to match the performance of a selected market index. Portfolio turnover, brokerage commissions, and management fees are minimal. Vanguard and a few other portfolio managers offer a variety of no-load international index funds.<p>Over a long period, index funds should outperform most actively managed funds. They trade less and therefore incur fewer transaction costs as managers buy and sell--costs that investors don't have to pay. With an index fund, says Ibbotson, "you'll beat half the money managers or more after some costs, even if the markets are not efficient, as long as the index is appropriately defined." <p>But that's easier said than done. Indexing in the international market produces wide anomalies. In the U.S., investors basically only have to figure out what size company they want to track. They can choose among indexes that move with the big stocks of the S&P 500, the small-capitalization stocks of the Russell 2000, and almost anything in between. The international situation is more complex. The first question an international indexer must ask is: What mix of national markets do I want to track?<p>For most U.S. investors, the foreign benchmark remains Morgan Stanley's Europe, Australia and Far East (EAFE) index. EAFE uses a weighted index to try to accurately mirror the entire universe of public companies in those regions, based on their size. Because Japan is so dominant in Asia, however, this means the Asia portion of the index pretty much does whatever the Japanese stock market does. Three years ago, in fact, Japanese stocks accounted for 90 percent of Far East market capitalization. The EAFE index was correspondingly heavy in Japanese stocks just prior to the big collapse in the Tokyo market.<p>EAFE indexers, locked into Japan, learned the downside of their strategy as the Nikkei plunged from close to Y30,000 to below Y16,000. Active fund managers, meanwhile, sensed that the Japanese market was headed for a major correction, and they pulled out. But it wasn't only the actively managed funds that beat EAFE. Other indexes that either underweight or eliminate Japan also outperformed it--at least until 1993, when a rally in the Japanese market pushed index funds that follow the EAFE weighting toward the front of the pack again. <p>To smooth out the roller-coaster rides, investors can combine several indexes in their portfolio or even use a dual strategy that mixes indexed funds with funds that are actively managed by professionals. That's what many institutional investors do. They index the core of their portfolio and actively manage the rest in an attempt to get the best of both worlds. An individual investor can do the same thing or even improve on the strategy by using index funds in efficient markets (the U.S. and Europe) and actively managed funds in less efficient markets (Asia and Latin America.)<p>Another option: Leave these kind of regional-asset-allocation decisions to the pros by investing in a broadly defined global or international fund. Global funds put money anywhere in the world--in both U.S. and foreign markets. International funds invest everywhere but the U.S. (For a list of top performers in each category, see "The Best Picks for Building an International Portfolio.")<p>Country and regional mutual funds that stick to single national or multinational markets provide another strategic option for investors. Wall Street was busy pumping out new single-country funds in 1993. Late December brought the Pakistan Investment Fund from Morgan Stanley Asset Management, for example. The pattern seems likely to continue this year.<p>Most investors should use single-country funds only as the capstone of a well-rounded international portfolio, if at all. And remember two rules: Don't buy at the initial public offering (IPO), and don't pay a historically unreasonable premium. Most single-country funds are set up as closed-end funds that trade like stock on one of the U.S. exchanges. Like a stock, when the issue first comes out, the underwriters take a commission--deducted from the proceeds of the offering. That means an investor who buys at the IPO for $20 actually gets less than $20 in investable assets. Also, because closed-end funds issue only a limited number of shares, the price is subject to swings in investor demand--not just the value of the underlying stocks in the portfolio. A hot single-country fund can trade at a price far above its net asset value. That premium to the net asset value of the fund rises and falls. Savvy investors know that over time it fluctuates within a fairly well-established range. They buy when the premium is near the low end of the range (or when the fund actually trades at a discount to net asset value) and sell when the premium is near a peak. <p>For people who like to pick individual stocks, American depositary receipts provide a crack at global citizenship. ADRs represent ownership of corporate securities held in American banks under agreements with foreign securities issuers or with U.S. securities firms. While many ADRs of larger companies are registered with the Securities and Exchange Commission and exchange-listed, others are exempt from registration and traded only in the over-the-counter "pink sheet" market. Thorough research is a must--some companies have more than one class of ADR, and the different classes may represent different numbers of foreign shares.<p>In either case, for individual investors it's easier and less expensive to acquire ADRs in the United States than the underlying shares in a foreign market. ADRs trade at a dollar price that closely reflects the home-market price of the underlying securities at prevailing exchange rates. Most brokers won't accept orders under $25,000 for transactions on a foreign exchange. Foreign clearing and custodial arrangements are generally slower and more cumbersome than this country's.<p>Theoretically, at least, investing in an actively managed fund ought to provide some protection against a risk that even experienced domestic investors don't think about: currency fluctuation. But things don't always work out that way. <p>In 1992, the managers of short-term global-income funds sought above-market returns by buying high-coupon Italian and Spanish bonds. At the same time, they shorted the French franc and the German mark. These funds took a bath when European governments revalued their currencies en masse after the European Exchange Rate Mechanism, the continent-wide effort to fix rates of exchange between Europe's currencies, collapsed.<p>In 1993, investors saw the happier side of currency risk when the Japanese yen strengthened against the dollar and more than doubled the return for U.S. investors who had their money in Japan--from a 12 percent gain to a currency-adjusted increase of 26 percent. <p>Unfortunately, economists don't agree on why and how currency rates change. There's general consensus that long-term currency rates reflect fundamental economic realities like competitiveness. That has probably been the force that has driven the yen upward against the dollar for over a decade.<p>But over shorter periods, the currency market is full of unexplained anomalies and inefficiencies--both opportunities for profit and loss. For some big institutional investors, currency trading that seeks to capture these profits has become an investment activity all its own. About $650 billion changes hands every day in the currency markets. Currency is the biggest single investment in the world.<p>This, however, is an arena for big players with big computers and lots of information. Although individual investors can take positions in currencies through options traded on the Philadelphia Stock Exchange or the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, doing so would be a lot like using a Yugo to play chicken with a Freightliner.<p>Individuals should look at currency closely, though, when picking a mutual fund. Know that, especially for regional or single country funds, great performance from currency gains isn't likely to be repeated over time. In the long run most academic studies show that currency differences will wash out--what an investor, rather than a trader, makes one year will be lost in another. Long-term investors should look for appreciation in the value of underlying securities that a fund holds.<p>It's also wise to read a fund's prospectus to find out about its strategy for currency hedging. The ideal fund manager knows how to use all the tools of Wall Street to lock in currency gains--or at least to avoid really big losses. Be as wary of funds that hedge against all currency risks as of those that don't take any precautions for currency gyrations. U.S. investors in Japan have no reason to praise fund managers who hedged away half their gain in 1993.<p>Before revamping a portfolio to add more of a global punch, investors also need to know something else: How much international exposure do they already have? Some people are getting foreign risk without even knowing it. The Fidelity Capital Appreciation Fund, for instance, has about 49 percent of its portfolio in international securities, and it's hardly the only fund with a next-door name and large overseas holdings. "An increasing number of funds you think of as domestic have significant exposure to foreign stocks," says Amy Arnott, an analyst at Morningstar, which recently began publishing the foreign portfolio exposure of each fund it rates. (See "International Funds in Disguise" for ten big domestic funds with high foreign exposure.)<p>At the moment, with many foreign markets already scrambling to digest an influx of Yankee capital, it makes sense to move cautiously, regardless of the strategy an investor chooses. Remember, international investing is a practice that works best over the long term. There's no reason to rush in right now if the price isn't right. And there's even less reason to buy a market near its top. Smart investors worry as much about getting out as they do about buying in.<p>Says Eileen Sanders, a Morningstar analyst who covers emerging-market funds: "Fund managers are all convinced that they can get out, but I am a bit concerned. If a problem in any of these countries causes people to rush in and sell, there would be an avalanche effect." The entire Indian stock market has a capitalization of just $72 billion, according to Morgan Stanley Capital International. How many buyers would throng the Indian market in a downdraft? In comparison, <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> alone has a market capitalization of approximately $20 billion.<p>A correction in the gassiest foreign markets is bound to occur. It always does. That will burn the speculators and make the Johnny-come-latelies counting on 50 percent annual returns sour on the international markets. Long-term investors will have a very different reaction. They understand that international diversification is a sound and attractive strategy that provides solid gains over time. And they also understand that there's no reward for acting in haste.<p>Gregory Millman is writing a book on the international financial markets for the Free Press.<p>
Portfolios perform better if they include international investments. Here's how to join in the action--without getting burned.<p>
Canvassing The Globe For Attractive Bonds<p>
 Investors who want to make serious money in bonds are looking overseas. A big reason for this is that prospects for hefty returns have dwindled in U.S. markets. "It's going to be hard to make more than the coupon" domestically in 1994, says Barbara Kenworthy, portfolio manager for the fixed-income funds at Dreyfus Corp. The outlook for the U.S. market, in fact, isn't especially bright in either of the two ways that bond investors can profit.<p>In 1993, U.S. investment-grade corporate bonds offered total returns--interest plus capital gains from rising bond prices--of 12.4 percent. Investors in intermediate-term U.S. Treasury bonds took home 8.4 percent. This year, however, Wall Street's bond mavens are predicting much lower returns. And if the Federal Reserve raises rates, bond prices could even tumble.<p>Foreign bonds, though, still give investors a shot at reaping capital gains as well as higher yields. In Europe, rates are still coming down, although not as rapidly as institutional money managers thought they would. The German Bundesbank has been hesitant to cut rates quickly for fear of igniting runaway inflation. Nevertheless, the continued stagnation of the German economy has left it with little choice but to continue pruning. When this happens, the central banks of France and England are able to join in and lower rates as well. Most international bond fund managers believe that the Bundesbank will cut rates further in 1994. "Assuming European interest rates continue to decline, this could be a very attractive area," says Amy Arnott, a mutual fund analyst with Morningstar.<p>Still, Europe has been a bit of a disappointment. "Nine of ten portfolio managers expected Germany to cut rates faster," says Kenworthy. She expects that investors will get some capital appreciation in Europe in 1994, but "you'll be lucky to earn 100 to 300 basis points above the coupon." And that 8 percent to 10 percent total return will only materialize for investors who have hedged against a strengthening dollar, she adds.<p>Investors are likely to find the prospects for higher returns better in Latin America, though the risks are larger, too. Here falling interest rates are less important as a driving force than improving credit ratings for countries such as Mexico and Argentina. Better credit increases investor confidence and raises demand for bonds. The word on Wall Street is that the two big U.S. bond-rating houses will upgrade Mexican government debt to investment grade this year. At least that's the expectation. If it proves true, then big institutional investors will move in--especially the ones precluded from buying debt rated below investment grade. That, in turn, should expand the market, drive down interest rates, and drive up bond prices. If it all works out, investors could see 15 percent to 17 percent total returns from Mexican bonds in 1994. On the other hand, another uprising like the one in Chiapas, a decline in the peso, or an acceleration of inflation could demolish the fairy tale.<p>But why end the hunt with Mexico? "The search for yield has gone in successive stages to ever more exotic investments," says Paul Darosa, president of Eastbridge Capital Management in New York. Forget about Brazil, however, even with its promise of juicy 20 percent yields. The country just impeached its president, its national deficit is out of control, and the political situation is both unstable and unpredictable. Also steer clear of Nigeria. This nation is to corruption what France is to cooking. <p>What about Poland? It's obviously on its way to reform. Yet it remains risky enough to offer attractive returns. John Purcell, a managing director at Salomon Brothers in New York, notes that Poland is now putting the finishing touches on a plan to repackage its dollar-denominated bank debts as bonds with a U.S. guarantee. "Poland has a good credit trajectory, moving solidly to investment grade within a couple of years," says Purcell. <p>For the squeamish, it probably makes the most sense to sit back and accept less bang for the buck in the U.S. Those a little more daring can try Europe or Mexico. Just know that the truly intrepid are already hard at work trying to figure out how to hedge Polish zlotys.     --G.M.<p><p>U.S. investors ignore most of the world when they construct domestic-only portfolios. The U.S. equity market makes up roughly only 40 percent of the total. That other 60 percent includes the big story for the next decade: Growth in the emerging world is projected to far outstrip that in even the healthiest first-world countries.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Bond Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

