				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-The Tigers and the Bees</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						  
Asians aren't becoming U.S.-style consumers as they get richer - and that spells trouble for the region's economic miracle.<p>By Walter Mead<p>Can Asia keep growing? To anyone who has walked through Tokyo's fashionable Roppongi district late at night, the question seems almost perverse. Wealth glitters everywhere: draped on the frames of club-goers dressed in clothes that yesterday graced the runways of Paris and Milan, conspicuously displayed in the limos and status cars stacked at the curb, flaunted in the prices on the menus. This seems the future of Asia--a prosperity that has already spread to the streets of the Four Tigers of Hong Kong, Taiwan, Korea, and Singapore and is now promised by the televisions of the rural villages of China and the frantic rush-hour traffic that chokes Bangkok. <p>But economics isn't known as the dismal science for nothing. All good things come to an end, and the Asian miracle may be running into trouble with consequences both for those U.S. investors who have joined the rush to invest overseas and for everyone whose daily bread depends on the continued health of the world's economy. The next great economic slowdown may result not from some unpredictable crash or some modern Smoots and Hawleys erecting tariff barriers that send the world into another Great Depression. No, the greatest threat to continued economic growth, in Asia especially, is an impending global shortage of lazy consumers.<p>This isn't the conventional wisdom, of course. East Asia today is the most dynamic economic success story in the world--and perhaps in world history. The eight Asian economies labeled "dynamic" by the World Bank (Japan, Hong Kong, Korea, Singapore, Taiwan, China, Malaysia, and Thailand) have seen their collective gross domestic product rise from $922 billion in 1971 to $3.43 trillion 20 years later (in constant dollars). To put it another way, in 1971 the combined size of these eight economies was just 33 percent of the U.S. economy. Twenty years later they had reached 76 percent. At this rate, the eight will equal the size of the U.S. economy in 2002.<p>The few naysayers willing to cast doubt on the East Asian economic miracle almost all focus on the possibility that such rapid growth will cause the region's economies to overheat. Construction companies won't be able to build new roads, airports, and harbor facilities fast enough to handle new demand, for example. Today, telephone companies can't keep up with the desire for new lines; governments can't install new sewer and power lines fast enough to meet the needs of booming cities. Anyone who has experienced the traffic and air pollution of Taiwan's capital city, Taipei, knows that these worries are grounded in fact, but most of the governments in the region are moving vigorously to improve their infrastructures. <p>The other standard worry about Asia concentrates on its politics. Asia's economies may be dynamic, but its politics are a mess, to put it charitably. North Korea is an unstable, paranoid Communist holdout trying to build an atomic bomb amid the ruins of its collapsing economy. China's central government risks losing its grip on its restive provinces, and the ruling Communist party depends for its legitimacy on a worn-out ideology in which nobody believes. South Korea has a chip on its shoulder as the result of Japanese racism and imperialism. Japan is an economic giant but a political dwarf; the country has never faced up to its crimes against its neighbors during World War II, and it has no idea how to act in the post-cold-war world. Taiwan is legally a rebellious Chinese province; Hong Kong is a colony soon to revert to Chinese control under terrifyingly murky circumstances.<p>But neither explosive politics nor overburdened infrastructures are the true reasons to doubt that Asia will tread the straight line marked by current trends into the indefinite future. No, the real fly in the Orient is exactly the export-led strategy that has brought unprecedented growth to this region.<p>This model has succeeded beyond the wildest dreams of the Japanese, Taiwanese, and Korean bureaucrats who launched it a generation ago. The efficient, low-cost production of increasingly sophisticated manufactured goods for international markets has made much of East Asia rich. The thrifty habits of East Asian workers and businessmen--often reinforced by government policies--have generated the funds needed for new investments, and consistently low government spending keeps taxes down. <p>Asia's growth has been built upon rapid increases in trade with foreigners--and even more rapid growth in trade surpluses with those commercial partners. The $343 billion of U.S.-Asian trade in 1992 included $128 billion in U.S. exports to Asia--and $215 billion in exports from Asia to the United States, a trade surplus for Asia of $87 billion. The trade balance between Asia and the European Community was similar: exports of $96 billion to Asia and imports of $153 billion. <p>Twenty years ago trade surpluses weren't much of a problem. At that time, only a handful of Asian countries had embraced export-oriented development strategies, and with the exception of Japan, most of them were small. Their economic success had little effect beyond their own borders, and the handful of "early exporters" could enjoy a free ride in a healthy global economy. <p>Free rides are getting harder to find. As more and larger countries embraced an export-oriented development strategy, Asia's success began to change the domestic economies of its North American and European markets. Manufacturing employment in Western Europe and North America peaked in the early 1970s and began to sink; so did real wages in the United States.<p>The rise of protectionist sentiment on both sides of the Atlantic has been one response. But the current rhetorical war between the trade Neanderthals in the West--who want to return the world to an era of trade wars and costly protectionism--and the legions of free trade has failed to address the economic facts at the root of the current situation. Simply put, the Asian economies as they grow richer are showing few signs of becoming like the high-consumption, low-savings consumer economies that characterize the Atlantic countries. The Asians' massive trade surpluses are not disappearing as these economies "mature." <p>Everyone agrees that the export-led economic success of East Asia is ultimately unsustainable. It comes down to math. In 1992, Taiwan had a trade surplus with the United States of roughly $9.4 billion. With 20.7 million people, this works out to a per capita trade surplus of $454. Fair enough. But what worked for Taiwan won't work for the rest of Asia. If the other Asian tigers and wanna-be tigers--Indonesia, the Philippines, Pakistan, India, and Bangladesh, for example--achieved the same success, our trade deficit with Asia would be more than $1.1 trillion. <p>This can't happen. The U.S. and the rest of the developed West aren't rich enough to buy all these products while selling Asian economies so much less. In the long run, the world's exporters cannot grow faster than the world's importers. Some of Asia's exporters are already well aware of this fact. Japan, the lead case, can lay its current economic problems at the feet of its own export success. Its persistent trade surpluses have driven up the value of the yen, and its companies face a slowly growing world already awash in Walkmans and CD players. <p>The way out of this box was supposed to be apparent by now. Economists in Japan, Singapore, and Korea have been talking about it for years. If Asia is to continue to grow, they said, it will have to shift to growth led by domestic demand. Increasingly affluent Asian consumers will provide the huge markets that Asia's economic growth needs. Asian wages will rise, and its tightfisted governments will shell out more money for basic services like social security. Industrious, thrifty Asia, in other words, will become more like slothful, consumption-mad America. <p>But this transition is nowhere to be seen. Japan is worried about the hollowing out of its industrial base and is afraid to adopt policy changes that would lower the savings rate and increase consumer purchasing. The Japanese savings rate (gross national savings as a percentage of gross national product) was 32.8 percent in 1975; in 1991 it was 34 percent. Meanwhile, in the U.S. the rate was 18.2 percent in 1975 and 14.7 percent in 1991. Find any convergence there?<p>None of the efficient bureaucracies that have guided economic growth in East Asia wants to be the first to step off the merry-go-round. Korea and Singapore, for example, had bad experiences when they tried to raise wages and shift development strategies. Industry reacted by moving from these countries to cheaper, more "Asian" economies where wages and regulations were still comfortably low. <p>Since the citizens of the Asian economies show no signs of becoming Western-style consumers, the governments of the West have begun to adopt policies designed to cut back on consumption and raise the savings rate in their own countries. The United States is trying to reduce its budget deficit and raise the national savings rate; in Europe most policy makers now believe that the key to industrial competitiveness lies in lower wages and decreased social spending. These policies may or may not make good short-term sense in the countries where they are adopted, but they certainly exacerbate the problem facing the world's export-oriented economies. <p>Two hundred and fifty years ago, British nobleman Bernard de Mandeville wrote a shocking poem called "The Fable of the Bees." This poem, which greatly influenced Adam Smith, told the story of a hive of bees that decided to get rid of the lazy drones--bees that didn't work but lived in luxury. Like their human counterparts, they rode in carriages, dressed in silk, and spent their time at banquets and balls. One day the worker bees drove the drones out--only to face a ruinous depression. Without drones, all the carriage makers, horse breeders, silk spinners, caterers, wine makers, and musicians were ruined. The depression spread and the bees starved. <p>"Virtuous" economic policies like thrift and hard work require "vicious" policies of consumption. If Asia's tigers are to continue to grow, they must learn the lesson of the bees. Until they do, Asia's political and economic prospects will remain under a cloud, and the world's economy faces an uncertain future. <p>Walter Mead is a senior counselor at the World Policy Institute at the New School in New York City.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Politics, International Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

