<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Has Boom in Technology Waned</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Has Boom in Technology Waned</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Without cold war paranoia to fuel the drive for innovation, now is the time to look for low-tech opportunities.<p>By Leo Dworsky<p>In 1956, soviet premier Nikita Khrushchev looked the American people in the eye and declared: "Whether you like it or not, history is on our side. We will bury you." It is easy enough to say now that this was a lot of hot air, but at the height of the cold war, this kind of bravado made a lot of people nervous, especially when, the next year, the Soviets launched the satellite Sputnik and began the space race in earnest.<p>Sputnik caught the United States off guard, but a combination of surprise, fear, and good old American ingenuity soon galvanized the country. The scientists and entrepreneurs of Route 128 in Massachusetts took wing, as did their counterparts in California's Silicon Valley, and elsewhere around the nation. Semiconductors, particle accelerators, rockets, and electronic gadgets of all kinds began to take shape, aided by a sharp increase in government research spending for defense and space.<p>Moreover, Wall Street soon took notice, and the great bull market in American high technology was on, continuing with appropriate ebbs and flows ever since. Perhaps not surprisingly, some of the first technology companies out of the gate--notably <a name="NYSE:TXN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11462"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Texas Instruments</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>--have remained market leaders to the present day, leading the first stage of the bull market in 1957-1962 and its most recent phase, 1991-1993. <p>But an interesting thing has happened on the way to the future. The game has changed, with more than a hint that, broadly speaking, investment in technology has had its best innings for a while. The first hints of a technology slowdown came late last year just as speculation on the future of technology was reaching its zenith. <p>Ironically, one hint of a slowdown in American technology may have come from the former Soviet Union. Last October, an outfit called MIGS etc. placed an advertisement in the Wall Street Journal and other leading newspapers. It read, "Fly a MiG-29 at Mach 2.5 in Moscow." The company offers military flight packages and even a two-day "Military Adventure Program" with tanks and planes in St. Petersburg. For $15,000, American tourists can "experience the very best in Russian armaments," even a staged dogfight for $90,000.<p>What is going on here? Tourism and entrepreneurship aside, I read this new business as the final capitulation of the former Soviet Union, the technological shoe dropping four years after the political shoe (the fall of the Berlin Wall). If the great bull market in American technology began in 1957 in response to the launching of Sputnik, isn't it possible that the bull market in technology ended with the final surrender of Soviet military technology for the pleasure of American tourists? After all, a major impetus to government spending on technology--the Soviet threat--is mostly gone; and with it much of the potential for commercial spinoff from that spending. Note that, already, the superconducting Supercollider has been canceled and that spending for the Space Station has been reduced. Thus, a major force in the technology bull market is waning at the very moment rhetoric and expectations for the future of technology have been at their peak. <p>What about the private sector? In the very week the MIGS ads ran, we heard an important voice on the subject of consumer technology in the person of Richard L. Sharp, CEO of <a name="NYSE:CC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10343"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Circuit City Stores</b></a>, the country's leading retailer of consumer electronics. Late last October, Sharp gave an interview to the New York Times, headlined, circuit city pins growth on sales of used cars. The gist of the interview was that Circuit City had recently created Carmax, a sprawling used-car dealership in Richmond, Virginia, designed as the prototype for a foray into the used-car market. Sharp told the Times that Carmax was only created as a hedge against an aging consumer electronics and appliance market until a new wave of technology comes along. He added that high-resolution television is in the future, but that could take years. <p>Circuit City has been a brilliantly managed company for many years, closely attuned to the consumer-electronics marketplace. When Circuit City speaks (and acts), the rest of us should probably listen. Used cars may or may not turn out to be a good business for the company. But whatever the future of used cars, they are a long way from high tech. If Circuit City is preparing for a slowdown in consumer technology, perhaps investors would do well to follow their cue.<p>I am not suggesting that all growth in technology is over. After all, we still have the "information highway" and the "wireless revolution" and, if nothing else, the fertile mind and great energy of Bill Gates, et al. But I do mean to suggest that the broad-based boom--civilian and governmental--is waning, and with it the investment bull market that has been with us for many years. If this is true, investment money will move on. What is bad for technology may be good for other, more prosaic corners of the marketplace. The trend toward leading cyclicals that began two years ago will continue. Autos, rails, construction equipment, and building materials have already done well, but what about forest products, aluminum, or truckers, among others?<p>Whatever the complexion of this year's stock market, technology is probably out, overbought in last year's speculative binge and due for a long cooling-off period. We will see a few winners for sure, but they will be balanced by many disappointments--too little earnings at too high a price. If investors can adjust to this new reality, they are probably one major step toward investment success in the mid-1990s. <a name="NYSE:BEL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10197"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bell Atlantic</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, in offering tens of billions of dollars last year for Tele-Communications, Inc. and McCaw Cellular Communications, probably capped the boom in technology. The contrary opinion may be to go low tech for awhile, like Circuit City Stores.<p>Leo Dworsky is an editor-at-large for Worth.
 <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
