	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Money Wants to be Anonymous</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Money Wants to be Anonymous</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> MONEY WANTS TO BE ANONYMOUS <p>And that's just the first rule of a brave new electronic society, says David Chaum, the guru of digital cash. If he has his way, checks and coins will be obsolete and you'll e-mail your kids their allowance.  <p> By Alan Deutschman  <p> I hand the taxi driver the address: the Science Park at Kruislaan 419. She claims to know the street, but as she whisks me away from the historic center of Amsterdam and toward the city's outskirts, I grow suspicious. The dense urban landscape soon gives way to open stretches of high, unruly grass. Here the astonishingly green pasture is like a Dutch postcard: White horses canter through marigolds; water lilies float lazily in a long waterway.  <p> For a while I'm calmed until I realize the waterway isn't a canal, as I had believed. It's a moat. And the driveways across it are guarded by high steel gates.  <p> This forbidding site, I later learn, is where the Dutch conducted atomic research after World War II. Now it is a curious sort of enclave for high tech, where lush foliage obscures various computer centers and a prestigious research institute. Given the heritage of secrecy, it's fitting that this is also home to DigiCash, a company that proposes to make electronic commerce invulnerable to snooping. I am here to meet the company's American founder, a privacy guru named David Chaum.  <p> The taxi passes through an unsightly security gate and pulls up to a cheap-looking building of white brick and glass the science park in its entirety, it seems. I check in and wait, watching a procession of 11 Korean businessmen in narrow ties. Before long a heavyset, fortyish man emerges from the elevator. His straight brown hair is tied in a ponytail, his beard is piebald with patches of white and gray. He wears a button-down shirt and a softly colored silk tie painted with flowers and butterflies the get-up of a Berkeley mathematics whiz who now must dress for the suits.  <p> This is Chaum, the acknowledged intellectual genius in the field of electronic cash. An iconoclastic visionary, he has been working for 15 years on politically charged ideas that could redefine the concept of money for a wired world. Only lately, though, has anyone paid him much mind.  <p> If someone were to make an <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>-style "You Will" advertisement for digital cash, the voice-over might go like this: Ever send money to your kid in college via E-mail? Ever use your cellular phone as a cash machine? Ever keep your loose change on a microchip? You will and the people who'll bring it to you are a ponytailed expatriate and his bunch of Dutch hackers.  <p> Or at least, that's what David Chaum hopes. For years, his prognostications about digital cash seemed like science fiction to hardheaded bankers who believed electronic data could never replace bills and coins on a mass scale. But now that few dare hand out business cards without an Internet address, those same financiers are in a chaotic rush to establish standards for "E-money." An improbable number are coming for advice to a man they once scorned as a hippie with a pie-in-the-sky agenda.  <p> The Korean businessmen, for example, are here to see Chaum. They want to put electronic money on 10 million cards equipped with razor-thin microchips. "Ten million smart cards," Chaum says aloud, blown away by the size of the project. An elegantly tailored Brit idles nearby. His company wants to revamp New York's subway system and Chaum could help him replace turnstiles with sensors that subtract fares directly from commuters' pockets as they surge out to the street.  <p> These are thrilling prospects. Yet as we rise up to DigiCash's bustling suite on the top floor, Chaum looks worn out, even ill. The pace of his life has become hard to handle lately. His barefoot young programmers aren't finished working on new software for DigiCash's trial of E-cash on the Internet software that was supposed to debut the day of my visit. Besides fixing that problem, Chaum must meet an endless stream of people. He can't slow down: The coming months mark his best chance yet to realize his radical vision or to set himself back for years. He pops an allergy pill and wills himself onward.  <p> Although Chaum is a pioneer of E-money, he's best seen these days as a besieged underdog. The list of companies scrambling to trump him is a virtual Who's Who of finance and technology: the major banks, credit card providers such as Visa and MasterCard, and the ubiquitous Bill Gates and <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>. You might think it doesn't much matter who comes out on top: Digital cash, afterall, is digital cash. Who cares about the brand name, as long as merchants accept it? But in fact, the stakes in this battle extend far beyond the banal exigencies of business to touch on politics and even ethics.  <p> Virtually alone among E-money thinkers, Chaum insists on creating anonymity for all transactions building a tamper-proof system that works just as "real" cash always has, from cowrie shells to $100 bills. The key, he says, is this: Without the spender's say-so, no one should be able to trace who paid whom for what, whether a transaction takes place online or in a swipe of a card at a coffee shop. It's a libertarian approach in tune with Chaum's roots in freewheeling communities such as Berkeley and Amsterdam but it is anathema to control freaks like the FBI, the IRS, and corporate information marketers.  <p> Chaum says every digital-cash system but his has the potential to be abused or compromised and the math seems to bear him out. His competitors, however, insist their plans will prove plenty secure in practice. They dismiss Chaum as an incorrigible purist, a brilliant mathematician and innovator whose political views are hindering his chances of success.  <p> Sniffs Magdalena Yesil, vice president of marketing at CyberCash, a rival start-up in California's Silicon Valley: "We're trying to fit into today's world. Chaum is trying to create a new world." <p> Like many in the digital elite, Chaum, an unabashed utopian, does want to create a new world. To him, electronic money is just the first consumer use of an arcane field he hopes will transform society: cryptology, the science of secret codes. In cyberspace, these codes can prove a powerful way of shielding a person's identity or of verifying an identity without giving away extra information. Armed with personal computers and good software, says Chaum, ordinary people will finally have the power to do and say things without being tracked by Big Brother.  <p> As far back as the 1970s, Chaum saw that this type of technology could make for a new era in politics. Besides digital money, codes can enable anonymous electronic voting, cheat-proof tallies where no one could cast more than a single ballot. Congress could allow millions of voters to express their opinion weekly or daily on intervention in Bosnia. Pollsters could measure what doctors think about abortion, verifying that all respondents had M.D.swith out knowing how any particular doctor had voted. Like a more hands-on version of Newt Gingrich, Chaum chats about using computers to create "something more democratic than democracy."  <p> This kind of talk unnerves people and not just those who might be disenfranchised because they don't have access to technology. Throughout his career, Chaum's ideas have faced forceful opposition. At the University of California at Berkeley, for instance, Chaum recalls computer-science professors telling him to forget about electronic voting because "it was wrong to work on any technology motivated by social consequences." His political-science professors also objected, fearing the tyranny of such direct, immediate democracy.  <p> Chaum decided they were mistaken and went on to gain renown in cryptology, publishing numerous papers and receiving patents for his privacy techniques. "Chaum's papers on anonymity really made his name," says Peter Wayner, a Baltimore-based cryptology expert and author of the new book Digital Cash. Still, Chaum continued to confront antipathy from groups that might have seemed to be his natural allies. Bankers found his digital-cash message too futuristic and didn't see why they should promote a benefit their customers didn't know could be provided.  <p> Many fellow cryptologists shrank from considering the political implications of their work, preferring to concentrate on intellectual puzzle-solving. And privacy advocates in the U.S. and Europe were "at least uninterested and in many cases hostile" when Chaum lobbied their support. Many insisted that technology is no match for the law when protecting civil liberties.  <p> In 1995, as commerce flows into cyberspace, the evidence suggests that Chaum was simply ahead of his time. A recent survey found 70 percent of Americans have refused to give information to a business because they thought it was not needed or too personal, up from 42 percent three years ago. When Sandra Bullock stars in The Net, a big-budget film that exploits fears about computer databases, it's safe to assume that something is happening. <p> These days many online pioneers see cyberspace as a new kind of domain, a place of unfettered freedom where individuals go to escape the tyranny of their flesh-bound identities and of structures like business and government. For these trend-setting digerati, libertarianism is something of a secular religion. Add to this the fact that encryption is now cheap and easy for almost anyone with a personal computer, and Chaum seems positively in tune with the electronic ethos.  <p> "Privacy is going to be incredibly important in cyberspace," says Nick Donatiello, president of Odyssey, a San Franciscobased market-research firm that studies attitudes toward technology. "People aren't going to work with you unless you can guarantee them privacy. In a decade or so, privacy will be to new media what safety is to car sales."  <p> In person, Chaum doesn't  fit any preconceived notion of a crusader. There's nothing of the evangelist in him; he's not a slick promoter or a hyper-confident executive. He is soft-spoken and reflective, with a quiet warmth that emerges over time. Sometimes, when he encounters colleagues at the office, he'll just look them in the eye for a pregnant moment, as if he is in no rush to speak. When I ask him questions, he thinks about them silently for awhile. Sometimes he waits a day or two before giving me a thoughtful, detailed answer.  <p> His personality is a study in juxtapositions the acclaimed researcher who sweats the prosaic details of running a company, the man who prizes abstract mathematics but remains engaged by political issues. He represents an almost-forgotten tradition of the public intellectual, deeply engaged in both business and the controversies of his time. <p>Chaum grew up in the Hollywood Hills, near Los Angeles, on roads such as Beverly Glen and Laurel Canyon. He recalls bicycling through the city with his father, a businessman who at various points owned a retail store and worked as a stockbroker. One day they passed an industrial park and stopped to admire the distinctive architecture. His father asked, "Wouldn't it be nice to have your own company like that?" Chaum dates his abiding interest in business to that moment.  <p> The youngster went on to study computer science and specialized in cryptology, a field that has been associated with cutting-edge thought since the days of the World War II code breaker. As part of the Berkeley Ph.D. program, students were required to choose two minor concentrations. While most of his colleagues picked technical fields, Chaum minored in business administration, taking courses with the M.B.A. students. He remembers in particular a Wednesday-night course that brought in guest speakers, company founders who regaled the students with first-person stories. Chaum was so fascinated he took the course a second time.  <p> But despite his entrepreneurial bent, Chaum says he remained "deeply immersed" in academia specifically, the implications of cryptology. In 1982 he took a tenure-track appointment at the University of California at Santa Barbara but found that, like most scholars, he preferred research to teaching. Months later, when the Free University in Amsterdam offered him a half-year visiting professorship and said he wouldn't have to teach, he took a chance and moved to Europe.  <p> Once in Amsterdam, Chaum was charmed by the bohemian atmosphere and the interest the Dutch showed in his work. He found himself recruited by CWI, a high-powered research institute funded by the Dutch government. He never really intended to stay, however, so he didn't bother learning the language he simply kept stretching out his visit. "I still don't really speak Dutch," he confesses sheepishly, an accidental expat now for almost 15 years.  <p> "Why don't we come to the really important stuff?"  <p> I'm sitting with Chaum under the vaulted ceilings of the grand caf at the American Hotel, a turn-of-the-century Art Nouveau landmark. Through arched windows we can see the glorious chaos of the Leidseplein, a mad whirl of bicyclists and trams and people out for a good time. The square is significant for Chaum: It's where he used to come more than a decade ago to sip coffee and puzzle out his theories.  <p> Chaum's passion for "informational rights" was fanned by the writings of Alan Weston, a Columbia University professor who gained notoriety in the 1970s as one of the first thinkers about privacy in the computer age. But even more than academic discourse, Chaum was turned on by his own investigations and the prospect of a solution to the info-ills of the late 20th century. Offering individuals real privacy without cutting them off from society indeed, by giving them more power in society seemed a truly inspiring goal.  <p> By the early 1980s, Chaum felt confident he had proved, mathematically at least, that both electronic money and voting could work. Once he had perfected the math becoming one of the world's leading cryptologists in the process he moved on to the morals. In 1983 and 1984, he neglected most of his responsibilities to focus obsessively on the potential effects of his work.  <p> Chaum terrorized interlibrary-loan clerks. He commanded assistants to wheel in cart after cart of books. He traveled throughout the U.S. and Europe to seek out top political theorists in person, probing them to make sure his ideas couldn't backfire. In the end, he says, "I convinced myself the answer was clear enough. So I decided to devote my energies not to look back and question anymore."  <p> His first task was to write a dense manifesto entitled "Security Without Identification: Card Computers to Make Big Brother Obsolete. "The article begins ominously: "Computerization is robbing individuals of the ability to monitor and control the ways information aboutthem is used. Already, public and private sector organizations acquire extensive personal information and exchange it amongst themselves. Individuals have no way of knowing if this information is inaccurate, outdated, or otherwise inappropriate, and may only find out when they are accused falsely or denied access to services."  <p> Sketching a scenario straight out of The Net, Chaum goes onto argue that "even a small group ... tapping into data gathered in everyday consumer transactions could secretly conduct mass surveillance, interfering in individuals' lifestyles, activities,and associations." He predicts that "as the public becomes more aware of the extent and possibilities of emerging information technology, there should be a growing demand" for systems that protect privacy systems such as the one he proposes.  <p> In 1985, Chaum published his article in the journal of the Association for Computing Machinery, and for several years he gave lectures to drive the point home. But as time passed, he says, he realized that "running around giving presentations wasn't going to get this stuff into general use." Drawing on his longstanding entrepreneurial impulse, he resolved to start a company to popularize his thinking. <p> His golden opportunity came in 1989, when the Dutch government wanted to introduce automated toll collections on highways. Community groups worried that bureaucrats would have the power to track the comings and goings of motorists and so the Dutch approached Chaum, by now an expert on technological privacy. The American proposed roadside sensors that could scan a strip on passing vehicles and collect an anonymous digital payment and Chaum quickly landed a consulting contract.  <p> The windfall enabled Chaum to found DigiCash. He hired a dozen talented programmers and quickly segued into serving Europe's healthy market for smart cards, cards containing computer chips that can pay for phone calls, parking meters, and the like. DigiCash needed no other venture capital: The company, which now has 30 employees, was profitable from the start.  <p> In spite of its old world location, Digicash has the look and feel of a Silicon Valley start-up except for the occasional technochatter in Dutch. There's no hint of formality here; Chaum manages by walking around and holding ad hoc meetings in hallways, the lobby, the kitchen. Twentysomething employees leave sneakers and workboots strewn about. One programmer races off to practice with the Olympic rowing team; a manager leaves for her aerobic-dance class. This could be Palo Alto.  <p> Chaum, however, seems fascinated by Amsterdam's unique heritage. He lives on the fashionable, tree-lined Keizersgracht, a grand canal favored by wealthy merchants and traders ever since it was built in 1612. His apartment,he's single, is just down the canal from the headquarters of most of the big, old Dutch banks to which he's evangelizing his futuristic vision of money.  <p> Not surprisingly, his pitch to these old-line institutions is a practical one. Giving customers access to cash, Chaum explains, is an expensive service for banks to provide. Gun-toting guards must transport money around. Chartered planes must carry checks to clearinghouses, where clerks must look at each piece of paper several times. Branches require employees and real estate. Cash is something of a loss leader for banks the storefront from which they sell more profitable products, such as credit.  <p> But consider this: In a world that's just around the corner, consumers will be able to bargain-shop for their credit (or their investments, or their mortgage) over a computer network. Many banks will suddenly find themselves in more of a commodity market. How to keep a customer's loyalty? By being the best storefront supplier of E-money, Chaum argues. That means providing a brand of digital cash that smart people will trust cash that won't land them on a list when they spend it.  <p> It's a convincing rap, but it may not win the day. Chaum has launched a 10,000-person trial run of his E-money on the Internet, but his tiny company is up against some huge competitors, none of which are using his privacy techniques. Though Chaum say she's "seriously involved" with some major banks, no such alliances have been announced yet. Why is he so sure his vision will triumph, leading inevitably to a new sort of electronic democracy? Could he be, as his rivals say, too paranoid about privacy for his business's good?  <p> Perhaps in answer, Chaum takes me on a taxi tour of his adoptedcity, asking the driver to zigzag through the old Jewish quarter. He shows me the building where Amsterdam once maintained records of all its inhabitants a practice instituted by Napoleon. During the Nazi occupation, says Chaum, the underground tried to destroy those records, which included information about religious affiliations. But the filing cards were packed together tightly and wouldn't burn quickly enough.  <p> As the taxi drives on, Chaum points out the bank where Jewish assets were seized and concentrated. Then we pass the theater where Jews were held before being sent east to the death camps. Chaum's own family emigrated from Europe before the Holocaust, but he vividly recalls the numbers tattooed on the wrists of his father's friends. <p>We're both silent as we cross the moat back to the safety of DigiCash. Chaum has made his point.  <p>     <p> ALL E-MONEY IS NOT CREATED EQUAL  <p> The first thing you need to know about so-called digital money is that it already exists, and almost everyone's got it banks, financial markets, governments, corporations. Everyone except the little guy. When Bank of America sends $100 million to Banque Nationale de Paris, it doesn't load burlap sacks of greenbacks onto an airplane, nor does it put a check in a Federal Express envelope. It simply sends a stream of electronic data to BNP's computers over SWIFT, a network created by the Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication. So that no one changes the $100 million to $1 billion, the information is transmuted into secret code using the estimable mathematical abilities of computers.  <p> In this setup, the data is the money. And the beauty is that digital money allows for instantaneous payment of any amount, pretty much anywhere in the world, without anything physical having to move. The closest most regular folks can get to this simplicity is giving a credit card number over the phone or using a cash-machine card to buy groceries.  <p> Electronic money exclusively for the big guys made sense when computers filled a room and only major institutions could afford them. But now the Compaq on your desk is more powerful than one of those old mainframes. And even a smart card that fits in a wallet contains a tiny silicon chip that can handle encryption duties. With the proper software, you can easily code a message with the same level of security as SWIFT uses for that $100 million transfer. And it's just as well, because consumerism is comingto the Internet and we'll need a way to pay for the stuff we buy online.  <p> Currently it's hard to get paid for anything on the Internet. Granted, a number of services have thrived by charging monthly subscriptions for access or by accepting advertising. But one-time-only transactions are difficult: People don't like to give out credit card numbers over a computer network because they're scared some evil hacker is listening in. David Chaum's solution, now being tested, is simple: Build a system that allows individuals to send digital money to one another a populist version of SWIFT. People could store E-money on a home computer and transfer it to an online merchant with the click of a mouse button. They could also download the money to a smart card, which they could then use to pay for things "in real life." Chaum adds one feature that SWIFT doesn't provide: privacy. Consumers must be able to leave no audit trail, he says, just as they can always choose to pay with physical cash.  <p> This won't happen quickly. People are already comfortable with plastic, so encrypted credit card numbers will likely be the first form of payment to gain widespread use in cyberspace. The powerful trio of Visa, MasterCard, and Microsoft is trying to create a standard for this kind of transaction. But cryptocredit has its drawbacks. It's impractical for small transactions yet fees of just a few cents (to get a single stock tip online, say, or read a news story) will be big business in cyberspace. What's more, sellers must be certified and must give a cut to the card issuer. Consumers still must mail checks every month while all their purchases, down to the articles they read online, will be logged in a computer somewhere.  <p> A related strategy, promoted by First Virtual, a start-up founded by former talent agent Lee Stein, sets up an intermediary to handle transactions so that credit card numbers don't fly over the Internet. Yet the approach has many of the same hassles as cryptocredit and also results in centralized records of every purchase. A third approach, mostly for real-world transactions rather than cyberbuying, relies on special "stored value" hardware such as electronic wallets. The best example of this is Britain's Mondex, a joint venture of National Westminster Bank and Midland Bank.  <p> Mondex doesn't rely on a central computer, so its transactions a user swipes a money card in a special reader are pretty private. And Mondex cash is encrypted, so it's reasonably secure. But the system is said to use an identical code in every device: Anyone who can tamper successfully with just one unit gets the key to the whole system. It's a rather distant prospect, but a frightening one. <p>Chaum's vision addresses all these problems: It's instantaneous, secure, and final; can be used for micropayments; works in cyberspace and the real world; and has no central database. In short, it's cash. Its main drawback is that none of the big backers Chaum says his Dutch firm has lined up have yet been revealed. And with competitors like Visa and Microsoft waiting in the wings, DigiCash will likely need some help to succeed.  A.D.  <p> ---------------------------------------  <p> HOW TO MAKE E-MONEY TRULY PRIVATE  <p> To understand david Chaum's ideas about digital cash, take our short course in encryption. No math is required.  <p> We'll start with the kind of code you learned in grade school. It's called "single key" encryption: You code a message using a key, send the message to me, and I open it using the same key. As an example, the key might be to replace every letter with the next letter in the alphabet, so alan becomes bmbo. The drawback with this simple code is that you can't send secure messages to someone you don't trust with your secret key.  <p> This dilemma was solved in the late 1970s with the invention of "public key" encryption. In this ingenious scheme, you create two unique keys that work together: Each decodes whatever was coded with the other. You make one of your keys public but keep the other to yourself. Now if I send you a message coded with your public key, you're the only one with the private key to unlock it. Similarly, you can send me secure messages using my public key. This sort of encryption also provides a fool proof "digital signature." If I can use your public key to unlock asecret message you've coded with your private key, that proves you sent it.  <p> This is where Chaum comes in. He conceives of a "digital coin" as a number that can be passed around electronically like a serial number that's been liberated from its dollar bill. When a bank issues you E-money, it attaches a signature encrypted with its private key. Since you can read the signature using the bank's public key, you know it's real cash. As soon as a coin is spent,the merchant sends it back to the bank, where the number is retired so the coin can't be spent twice. (Copying is easy with computers.) The only hitch is that the bank can track where you spent every coin. So Chaum devised a way for banks to verify a coin's value without knowing the serial number. In rudimentary form, here's the concept.  A.D.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

