		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Booting Up Personal Lawyer</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Booting Up Your Personal Lawyer</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Booting Up Personal Lawyer</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995   <p>Worth  magazine/Advisor  <p> BOOTING UP YOUR PERSONAL LAWYER  <p> By Mike France  <p> If you're injured in a train crash, it isn't hard in America to find an attorney. (Trust us: One will find you.) But what if you have a less dramatic legal problem if you need to sublease the apartment above the garage, or make a contract with some college kids to paint your fence, or decide who will get your property when you die?  <p> Odds are that you muddle ahead without the help of a lawyer or any legal documentation. The majority of adults don't have a will, and most of them enter into legal relationships all the time loaning others money, joining lottery pools, hiring people without creating contracts detailing the terms of the deals. All this leaves them vulnerable: They could suddenly die, or, even worse, the holder of the winning lottery ticket could conveniently forget about the other members of the pool.  <p> Now there is an automated solution to this problem. A new generation of inexpensive software packages with names such as Do-It-Yourself Lawyer (Expert Software, $14.95) is giving lay people the power to act as their own attorney. The programs are safe to use and perfectly suited for those times when people generally do without legal documents.  <p> Although the idea of retaining a virtual attorney may be anxiety-inducing, it's certainly better than using no attorney at all. And for those traditionalists who just don't think good legal advice can come out of a computer screen, here's a little trade secret: Many lawyers now use this same type of technology themselves.  <p> Priced between $9.95 and $69.95, these programs are easy to install and require no special computer expertise (but be sure your system has the modest amount of power and memory they require). All the programs can produce certain core documents: wills, powers of attorney, leases, promissory notes, and employment agreements. Beyond that, there's some variation. Among the 61 documents that can be churned out by Quicken Family Lawyer (Parsons Technology,$49) are a premarital agreement, a letter to challenge a credit rating, and a complaint letter to the Better Business Bureau. PC Attorney (Cosmi Software, $14.95) can produce a consignment-sale contract, a child-travel permission form, and, yes, a lottery-pooling agreement.  <p> Almost all the software uses a question-and-answer format (much like the popular Turbotax and TaxCut programs). Users first select the type of document from a menu, and then a series of queries appears on the screen. To create a will, for example, the software will ask 20 to 40 questions: What bequests will be made? Who will serve as executor? Should money given to children be held in trust?  <p> If the user gets confused or wants some practical advice, help can be summoned with the click of an icon. Online legal "textbooks" have been built into each of the programs, although their quality varies. Most of the software also contains detailed instructions on how to make a document legally valid, which usually requires some combination of signatures, notary stamps, or witnesses. <p> The best of the new breed of legal software programs can produce sophisticated documents custom-tailored to the needs of the user. For example, Quicken Family Lawyer's residential lease is capable of creating specialized clauses dealing with storage, parking, penalties for late payments, and a pet-damage security deposit. In contrast, the lease offered in Legal Documents (DSR Software,$14.95) offers little more than the preprinted form you could buy in a stationery store.  <p> Of the programs currently available, Family Lawyer is the best all-around choice. The program offers well-drafted documents, and the online legal advice is comprehensive. Managing Your Money's Personal Attorney (Meca Software, $9.95) is a pretty good second choice, but it offers only 18 documents. For drafting a will,the best choice by far is WillMaker 5 (Nolo Press, $69.95). The most sophisticated legal software on the market, it makes only wills and powers of attorney, but it permits far more customization than do any of its competitors. WillMaker 5 also comes with a detailed handbook explaining the intricacies of estate planning.(Warning: No one who has an estate greater than $500,000 should use any of these programs to make a will. See a real lawyer.)  <p> Among the software packages below $20, the only recommended choice is Do-It-Yourself Lawyer. PC Attorney and Legal Documents are extremely limited in the range of documents they can generate, and the database of practical advice is scant. And for those who can wait a little while, the <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> Network Microsoft Corp.'s new on-line service will soon allow subscribers to download many of the same documents available from the programs mentioned here.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
