<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Spread Out or Spread Too Thin?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Spread Out or Spread Too Thin?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Since the beginning of 1994, 69 new asset-allocation mutual funds have been formed, according to Morningstar, Inc. These investment vehicles have been around since 1951 but became popular after Fidelity created the Asset Manager fund in 1988. Asset-allocation funds operate on the theory that owning a range of asset classes over a long period will provide good returns with less risk than investing in any single asset class, like stocks.<p><a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>'s $6.185 billion Global Allocation Fund is one such fund--a portfolio of domestic and foreign stocks, bonds, and money market securities. "We would feel relatively comfortable with this being your only fund investment," says one Merrill fund marketing executive.<p>That prospect makes investment advisor Ronald Roge cringe. "Asset allocation has to be tailored to your needs, time horizon, tolerance for risk, and tax bracket," says Roge, president of R.W. Roge & Co., in Centereach, New York. The Merrill fund "might suit the needs of someone with a small portfolio who's in his mid-50s," he says, but it would be a poor choice for a retiree in search of income and security, or for someone in his 20s or 30s looking for aggressive capital growth.<p>Moreover, while the image of these funds suggests conservative diversification, some may adopt aggressive strategies. For instance, the <a name="FUND:VAAPX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VAAPX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Asset Allocation Fund</b></a> recently held 48 percent of its assets in bonds with an average maturity of 25.6 years--a big bet that interest rates won't rise. In a flat stock market, a 1 percent rise in interest rates would hit the fund with a loss of about 5.5 percent.<p>The marketing of these funds is not always straightforward. "Diversification made simple" is the pitch appearing on the cover of Fidelity Asset Manager sales brochures. "With one investment, your money is spread across a wide range of stocks, bonds and short term instruments.... And when there are changes in the economy or financial markets, you don't have to decide what adjustments to make or when to make them." But last year, this "diversified" fund--the largest in the class with $11 billion in assets--fell 6.6 percent in value because about a fifth of its portfolio was exposed when the Mexican peso collapsed.<p>The sales brochure for <a name="FUND:FAAAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FAAAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fortis Asset Allocation Portfolio</b></a> quotes an investor saying, "I want to spend time enjoying my family and building my career--not managing my investments." But does this secure parent know that, according to Morningstar, 43 percent of the fund's stocks are in the volatile technology sector--more than three times the technology weighting of the Standard & Poor's 500?<p>One fund does not fit all, says Don Phillips, publisher of Morningstar Mutual Funds. But it can be difficult for an investor to uncover just where an asset-allocation fund has its money at any given moment. That's because many asset-allocation funds continually shift their weightings. For example, <a name="FUND:DWSTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/DWSTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dean Witter's Strategist Fund</b></a> started in October 1988 with 75 percent of its money allocated to stocks and 25 percent to fixed income. In February 1989, it held 48 percent in equities, 48 percent in fixed income, and 4 percent in money markets, but returned to 75 percent stocks and 25 percent fixed income by August 1989.<p>These portfolio shifts can cause problems, says Roge. "If you're close to retirement and the manager decides to load up on gold or to be bearish on bonds, and the manager bets wrong, you've done yourself a real disservice." To avoid this trap, ask funds for a list of their largest tactical shifts over the last three years, or find a fund, such as USAA Investment Cornerstone, committed to a certain allocation mix, in this case 22 to 28 percent of assets in each of four classes: value stocks, U.S. Treasurys, foreign stocks, and real estate.<p>The asset-allocation category may soon address the investor's evolving lifetime needs more directly. The Stagecoach LifePath Funds, for example, are a series of five funds pegged to investors who will retire in 2000, 2010, 2020, 2030, and 2040. They invest in 14 different asset classes and tactically allocate 25 percent of the portfolio. As the portfolio's target date nears, the fund gradually moves to a mix of roughly 20 percent stocks, 65 percent bonds, and 15 percent money markets. Another alternative is <a name="FUND:VSMGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VSMGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard's LifeStrategy</b></a> Funds, a set of four funds with asset-allocation mixes directed at growth, moderate growth, conservative growth, and income investors, and achieved by investing in other Vanguard funds. "These new asset-allocation funds aren't custom fits, but they are coming a lot closer to giving you the size you need," says Phillips. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MER">Merrill Lynch & Co., Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:VAAPX">Vanguard Asset Allocation Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:FAAAX">Fortis Asset Allocation Portfolio</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:DWSTX">Dean Witter's Strategist Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:VSMGX">Vanguard's LifeStrategy</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
