<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Beyond Checks and Balances</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Beyond Checks and Balances</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Beyond Checks and Balances</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Feature  <p> BEYOND CHECKS AND BALANCES <p>Quicken software changed the way we track our money. Now Scott Cook, its cocreator, is getting more ambitious. Will your next financial advisor be a computer?  <p> By Thomas E. Weber  <p> Scott Cook started up <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a> Inc. back in 1983 with hopes of creating a personal-finance tool that would tap the power of personal computers. The former marketing executive asked consumers what they wanted, and the resulting program, Quicken, was a computer geek's dream: an easy way of storing and categorizing every last detail of your financial life. To those who were getting along just fine with paper and pencil, the software may have seemed laughably anal. But no one's laughing now. With more than 6 million users, Quicken is a juggernaut. Late last year, software mogul Bill Gates endorsed Cook's vision--and triggered an antitrust fight--by agreeing to pay $1.5 billion to bring Intuit into the <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> fold. Will the 42-year-old Cook, with or without Gates, change the way we handle our finances? Associate editor Thomas E. Weber spoke to Cook and found that the future of money maybe closer than we think.  <p>  <p>WORTH: Many people fear that computers will complicate their lives--not make things easier. As you try to put Quicken in everyhome, how will you erase people's memory of flops like home banking? <p> COOK: Home banking turned out to be one of the stupid uses of a computer--that and storing recipes. Banks invested something north of $100 million on the idea, and they lost every penny. At the core, it stemmed from not delivering what customers wanted. One New York bank ran a television commercial that showed a guy telling his wife he was going to the bank. He puts on his overcoat, looks at the snow coming down, turns around, and turns on a computer. The message was "You don't have to go out of your home anymore. "But what's the most common reason you go to a bank? To get cash, right? And what's the second most common reason? To make a deposit. Could you do either of those with home banking? Of course not. No wonder consumers didn't buy it.  <p>  <p>So what can computers deliver?  <p> You have to ask, "What do consumers want?" First of all, they don't like financial work. They want to take care of their money in as little time as possible. Another thing they want is answers to the questions they're asking. One question they ask is "How much money do I have that I can write checks on?" Well, banks don't know that number. Banks only know the checks they've processed; they don't know the checks you've written that are still outstanding. Our software helps.  <p>  <p>What else?  <p> People want to know "Where'd my money go?" Not just from my main checking account, but also if I'm using an account at another bank, or especially if I'm using several credit cards. They want to track their investments. And everything has to work together very easily, so you don't have to be a nerdo and figure out alot of advanced technology.  <p>  <p>Are you saying there's no such thing as home banking, then? That you just need software like Quicken, not some special service from your bank?  <p> I don't want to get tied up on names. "Home banking" just confused everything. The future is in software that runs on a consumer's PC. The software drives a link with the financial infrastructure--your bank, your credit card. And it uses CD-ROM for all the richness that's available there: graphics, video, sound.  <p>  <p>And what'll make all this catch on?  <p> Well, we don't want to force things on anyone. I have yet to see the Microsoft police in software stores with guns, forcing you to buy their titles. The only way a product will sell is if customers like it and tell their friends about it. The intersection between what people really want and what technology does really well--that's where true greatness is found. Let's say you're looking at your stocks and you want to get the portfolio's value updated. With most online services now, that's a real pain. What people want is to push a button called "update portfolio" and--poof!--instantly have all of those stock prices updated.  <p>  <p>That's pretty easy to explain. What else will make people love using computers?  <p> Well, that's just one example. In the future we'll be able to track all of your transactions--credit cards, stocks, even cash--so that you don't even have to type in the fact that you bought or sold something. All this information will enter your records automatically from the financial infrastructure. We have this capability today on Quicken with credit-card transactions, for instance.  <p>  <p>But it still boils down to just one thing: record keeping. That isn't very glamorous. Is it enough to convince real technophobes to try a computer?  <p> No, but an equally important part of people's financial lives is planning for the future. Things like "What kind of insurance should I have, and how much?" Right now, people rely on two sources of help: books and magazines like Worth, and other people. Books and magazines are unbiased, wonderfully complete, and low cost. Unfortunately, matters have gotten very complex over the last 30 years. For instance, there used to be one kind of mortgage, the 30-year fixed rate, and it was pretty easy to price shop. Today, there are so many kinds of mortgages. Even a great magazine puts the burden on its readers: How does this apply to me? There's no way a typical consumer can piece together a retirement plan based on a book or magazine.  <p>  <p>That's why people turn to professionals.  <p> The problem there is the reverse. Financial advisors give you very good advice and a very complete plan, custom-tailored for you. But they're not low cost. A true financial planner will set you back hundreds, even thousands of dollars. The other kind of financial planner is a commissioned salesman, who can cost even more. The most frequently consulted financial expert in the country is the insurance agent. Many are honest, great people. But unfortunately, there are many other who are more influenced by commission.  <p>  <p>And you think personal computers will solve this dilemma by giving personalized advice that's cheap and unbiased?  <p> Yes. For not much more than the price of a book or magazine, you'll be able to get a program that will ask you questions about your financial condition. It'll then apply wisdom from the best experts to your data. It'll suggest which parts of your portfolio you should look at and even suggest actions for you to consider. <p>  <p>That sounds like a big threat to banks, brokers, insurance salesmen--people who make money by giving advice. Why would they help you usurp that business by funneling financial data into the PCs of folks who run your software?  <p> There will be a happy solution. As a software company, we're not going to provide the sort of financial products our software might suggest for you to consider. We're not a bank or a mutual fund company or an insurance company. What this will do is create a new way for financial companies to reach consumers. It's a very low-cost channel. Many customers will be self-service. In that cost saving there is an opportunity for gain for everyone. Consumers don't want to be locked into a single company's services. They don't trust that. It's not in our interest to try to force people to buy only Intuit financial products. Consumers would exit stage right in droves. They want the choice they have now. Who do they trust with their money? They trust the people they're already using. That's not us.  <p>  <p>As you say, trust is vital when it comes to money--so let's talk about privacy. If my financial data must zip around electronically for this new world to work, how do I know my whole life won't end up in Big Brother's database?  <p> In my scenario, the only place all your data is stored is on your own PC at home. There's no central repository at Intuit or anywhere else. And you'll be assembling your own information from people who already have it. Your credit card companies, for example, know all about your spending habits. Your broker knows all about your investments. If you're worried about that, that's a separate issue. We're doing nothing to increase your exposure. In fact, we may be diminishing it slightly. Instead of having that stuff sent through the mail, it'll be sent electronically. Anyone can go to your mailbox, but making electronic links very secure is trivially easy.  <p>  <p>Okay, another trust issue. If I talk to a broker, I know he or she has passed the Series 7 exam. I also know I can complain to the SEC or the NASD--or even sue--if I'm mistreated. Should software pass an exam before it can provide me with these services? <p> All of those safeguards are in place today. In order for a computer to accept a stock trade, the people who manage that trade on the other side must have Series 7 registration. If it's another type of transaction, they must have certification for that. And if someone writes financial advice or guidance--someone like Andrew Tobias, for example, or Worth magazine--that's an unregulated business, in software or in print. Well, it's actually regulated by the market. If you give bad advice, people tend to have bad experiences.  <p>  <p>You believe technology will transform the way we handle our finances. How far along that path are we? What percentage have we explored so far?  <p> Ten percent. We will look back 20 years from now and be amazed by how people did financial work in 1995--how burdensome it was, how hard it was to make decisions.  <p><p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Financial Products

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
