<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Reviews:  Inside the Packages</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Reviews:  Inside the Packages</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Our panel of experts took the leading financial software on a hard drive. Here's their report. <p>Edited by Jim Jubak<p>Mutual Funds:<p>* Morningstar Mutual Funds On Floppy (Version 1.0)
You've seen the stars (in virtually every mutual fund ad), now use the database. That's both the draw and the drawback of this program. It's tempting to skip all the analytic features and just scan for the five-star funds. That would be too bad. The ranking system is the weakest part of this software. There's more than enough data here, though, for an investor to create his own ranking of funds.<p>Specs: $45 for one-time disk, $95 for quarterly updates, $185 for monthly updates from Morningstar Inc.; IBM only; 800-876-5005.<p>
* Mutual Fund Expert Pro Plus (Version 2.03)
Most investors have never heard of this program, but it's better than Morningstar's. The graphics are far superior--they're brighter and have more options for graphing funds and indexes against one other--and it features better data for calculating risk too. Best value probably isn't the Pro Plus version, however; the Personal version gives data on just 900 fewer funds for $400 less.<p>Specs: $399 with quarterly updates or $599 with monthly updates from Steele Systems Inc. (Personal version with monthly updates costs $185; Professional version costs $499); IBM only; 800-237-8400, ext. 752. <p>
* Markex II Plus (Version 6.0)
This program looks like hell, but it works and the price is right. Ignore the dubious investment strategy. A Windows version of the program is scheduled for a September release. Users can update fund data by modem.<p>Specs: $59.95 from Huntington Associates Financial Inc.; IBM only; 800-883-3863. <p>
* The Mutual Fund Investor (Version 5.2)
This software integrates a mutual fund database and portfolio manager, a plus if you're one of those investors who actively trades mutual funds. One big warning: The instruction manual contains an error on page 17 that gives the wrong information on how to start the program. A Windows version of the program is scheduled for December.<p>Specs: $295 from American River Software; IBM only; 916-483-1600.<p>STOCKS:
Fundamental--<p>* Macro*World Investor (Version 7.0)
A software dinosaur. The program is slow, clunky, and not particularly user-friendly. On the other hand, it won't crash or hog memory, and beneath that primitive surface lurks what one of our reviewers called "one of the most sophisticated programs for portfolio analysis." Using its database of real-world economic indicators, Macro*World correlates the price movement of individual stocks with conditions in the economy.<p>Specs: $699.95 ($200 discount to members of the American Association of Individual Investors), which includes six monthly updates ($39 a month after that), from Macro*World Research Corp.; IBM only;  800-841-5398 <p>
* Telescan Analyzer (Version 3.0)
Easier to use than less powerful programs--our reviewer even logged on without having to call customer support--and able to leap tall portfolios in a single bound. Telescan provides it all: both fundamental and technical data, news, S&P company reports, sample issues of 22 newsletters, complete insider-trading filings, and even--for a surcharge--access to Morningstar and Macro*World stock data.  The $45 a month flat rate only covers unlimited nonprime use. Anyone who wants to log on before 8 p.m. is going to get socked for 94 cents a minute. Better have a fast modem.<p>Specs: The software is free ($12.75 for shipping and handling), and data costs either $45 a month (off-hours) or 94 cents a minute (prime time) from Telescan Inc.; IBM only; 800-324-8246.<p>
* SSG Plus (Version 1.2), The NAIC Investors Toolkit (Version 2.0), and Take Stock for Windows (Version 2.0)<p>The great thing about this software, available through the National Association of Investors Corp., is that you can actually talk on the phone to Ellis Traub, the guy who wrote it. Unfortunately, you'll need to talk to Traub a lot. We couldn't do the simplest things in SSG Plus without calling technical support. Which is a shame. NAIC's method for picking stocks is a great approach for beginning investors; we suggest reading the association's magazine instead.  Each revision of this software has been slightly better; the next version is due later this year.<p>Specs: SSG Plus costs $114 (NAIC member $79), Investors Toolkit costs $160 (member $125), and Take Stock costs $175 (member $150) from National Association of Investors Corp.; SSG is IBM only, others are for IBM or Mac; 810-543-0612, ext. 330.<p>
* Quant IX (Version 5.0)
A cheap program that combines good portfolio management with solid fundamental analysis. The program's six different models let an investor estimate the value of a stock using such tried-and-true methods as earnings growth. A "what if" function projects the effect of such events as an earnings surprise or a change in interest rates on estimated valuations. A great way to become a disciplined fundamental investor.<p>Specs: $59 from Quant IX Software Inc.; IBM only; 800-247-6354.<p>
Technical--
* MetaStock (Version 4.0)
If you want to learn about technical analysis, this package is the place to start--and we  guarantee that you'll never outgrow it. This may be the most well thought-out and easy-to-use package that we reviewed--the tutorial will get an investor up and running in just four hours. The program comes with 80 predefined indicators for predicting the price movement of a stock or group of stocks. A system tester lets you see if the strategy you've developed would have made money, and the explorer feature searches for stocks that pass your screens.<p>Specs: $349 (for version that analyzes end-of-day prices) or $495 (for version that uses real-time pricing data) from Equis International Inc.; IBM only; 801-265-8886. <p>
* TradingExpert (Version 2.5)
Everything about this program is heavy, from the nearly $1,000 price to the 700 pages of documentation, which weighs almost 5 pounds. TradingExpert uses some of the techniques of artificial intelligence to produce a bullish-to-bearish ratio on each stock it analyzes. To judge from our experience, the program will cycle through two or three buy and sell signals a year on each stock. That means a user will either do an awful lot of trading or he must be able to use other technical indicators to separate the really profitable signals from those that are just noise. A new version, with fundamental analysis and mutual funds, was due last month.<p>Specs: $996 from AIQ Inc.; IBM only; 800-332-2999.<p>
* Personal Analyst (Version 1.7)
One of the few Macintosh programs in the <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>-dominated world of technical analysis. Features real-time charting, advanced analysis with all of the indicators that technicians dream about, trading models that make buy and sell recommendations, and access to data through the usual sources. <p>Specs: $395 from Trendsetter Software Inc.; Macintosh only; 800-825-1852<p>
* Windows on Wall Street (Version 2.1)
Technical analysis comes to the mass market. Despite the package's claim to be "your complete personal investment solution," you can't use the software to call down basic fundamental information--such as price-to-earnings ratios--even if you want to. The strengths of Windows on Wall Street are in its incidentals. Some of the best graphics we've seen make the charts addictive. And the built-in software for downloading stock-price information was among the easiest to use in our sample.<p>Specs: $295 from MarketArts Inc.; IBM only; 800-998-8439.<p>
Portfolio Management:
* Quicken (Version 7 for DOS, Version 3.0 for Windows, and Version 4.0 for Macintosh) and Quicken Companion (Version 2.0)
There's a race under way among the mass-market financial software makers--they're all trying to catch Quicken. The graphics are intoxicating. It's easier to set up and use than CA-Simply Money, it's more comprehensive than Managing Your Money, and it's better at integrating all of an individual's finances than Reality's WealthBuilder. Quicken isn't perfect, though. It anticipates too much. For example, it has trouble dealing with the whole idea of paying rent. When you tell it that you make a rental payment on the first of the month, it assumes you're receiving rental income. (Nice thought, but c'mon.) The new addition, Quicken Companion ($29.95, IBM only), organizes a home inventory, estimates taxes, and downloads stock and mutual fund prices.<p>Specs: $69.95 for IBM versions, $34.95 for Macintosh version, from Intuit Inc.; 800-624-8742.<p>
* WealthBuilder by Money Magazine (IBM version 3.1, Mac version 3.0)
A real mix of the good, the bad, and the ugly. Starting the program is like wandering through a maze. A user can't move on to the next stage until he's filled out the current worksheet or portfolio or whatever. But be patient. The terrific fundamental stock-picking tools make the whole program worthwhile. These screens constitute the best fundamental analysis software we reviewed. (Warning: If you choose the program's most expensive option, you get a monthly price update via disk. That's too long a delay for some investors.) Reuters just bought a majority stake in Reality, and the information giant has already moved to overhaul the newsgathering and on-line services that come with WealthBuilder. We look forward to the next version.<p>Specs: $109.95 from Reality Technologies Inc.; IBM and Macintosh; 800-346-2024.<p>
* Managing Your Money (IBM version 10.0, Mac version 6.0)
Graphics aren't everything. The star of this program is its prose. The program takes the time to explain assumptions and discuss the principles of financial planning and investment in detail. In the retirement planner, for example, the program explains how much money a retiree should expect from Social Security. Although the program won't help you pick individual stocks, its sections on asset allocation, buying life insurance, buying a mortgage, and retirement more than justify the price of admission. <p>Specs: $79.95 from MECA Software Inc.; IBM and Macintosh; 800-820-7457.<p>
* <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> Money (Version 3.0)
Microsoft is clearly serious about entering this market, but wait for the next version. There's no single part of the package that's so good that it's worth buying the whole to get at just that single function. <p>
Specs: $34.95 until April 15, $69.95 thereafter, from Microsoft Corp.; IBM only; 800-426-9400.<p>
* FolioMan (Version 1.3)
It's harder than it should be to find portfolio-management software that accurately calculates investment returns. Many programs treat capital gains as the only kind of gains, which slights income-oriented investments. FolioMan does the best job of any program we reviewed in giving an investor both a capital gains and a total return calculation for income investments. The program also does a good job of tracking the cost basis of an investment--a tricky problem for mutual fund investors trying to figure out capital gains for tax purposes. This version has no graphics, just simple printed tables. A version with graphics was just about to hit the market at press time.<p>Specs: $89 from E-Sential Software; IBM only; 213-257-2524.<p>
* Allocation Master (Version 3.2)
A professional-level program for asset allocation that uses a very straightforward graphic presentation to give any investor access to the secrets of modern portfolio theory. Allocation Master shows that the point of investing is not simply to go for the highest possible return, but to create the best mix of risk and return. At $800, this is certainly too expensive for casual use, but anyone who actively moves investments among asset classes in an effort to get top performance out of a portfolio ought to seriously consider this tool. <p>Specs: $795 from Frontier Analytics Inc.; IBM only; 310-301-3988.<p>
* StreetSmart (Version 1.0)
Trading software from the two biggest discount brokerage firms, Schwab and Fidelity, keeps getting better. Schwab's newest , a Windows upgrade from the DOS-based Equalizer, links extremely easy on-line trading with ledgers that keep track of positions and trades in each portfolio. The impressive communications software can also be used to pull in research reports and download stock and mutual fund prices. Of course, you'll need to open an account at Schwab, too. <p>Specs: $59 from <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab & Co.</b></a>; IBM only; 800-334-4455.<p>
* FOX (Version 2.1)
This was the best, but Schwab raised the bar by adapting StreetSmart for Windows. Fidelity Investments hasn't yet announced its update; the current DOS version provides historical and real-time quotes, performance analysis, and company news. And, yes, you'll need a Fidelity brokerage account.<p>Specs: $49.95 from Fidelity Investments; IBM only; 800-457-1769.<p>Written by Jim Jubak. Software reviewed by Andrew Feinberg, Jim Jubak, Richard Maturi, and Tim Middleton. Additional reporting by Marie D'Amico, Jim Melloan, and Kevin Caliendo.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Mutual Funds Investing, Stock investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
