	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Getting Technical</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
A low-priced computer program brings the power of technical analysis into the home<p>By Robert N. Veres<p>The stocks of basin exploration and Noble Affiliates, two publicly traded oil-drilling companies, looked virtually indistinguishable earlier this year. Both were selling at price-to-earnings ratios in the middle to high 20s. Both had a 97 percent rating on the Investor's Business Daily EPS ranking system, which compares earnings growth to the market as a whole. "The fundamentals were about as close as you can get," says David Vomund, who runs a fax market-timing service called Stock Alert. "They could have been mirror images of each other."<p>Not so to technical analysts. Using computer programs from AIQ, Vomund blended various technical indicators into a single rating; Noble Affiliates got a buy signal on May 18, but Basin did not. Over the next three months, Noble's stock price rose 20 percent, while Basin's inched up only 1.5 percent.<p>Since the days of Benjamin Graham, the granddaddy of fundamental analysis, most investors have bought stocks based on fundamentals--figures, ratios, and other tangibles drawn from company financial reports or other intelligence sources. But anybody who invests in the stock market knows that fundamentals don't always point the way to stocks that go up. Two companies may have experienced good earnings growth, each may be selling at a relatively low price-to-earnings ratio, and both may be carrying very little debt on their books. Yet one stock price might fall while the other takes off.<p>People who claim to understand this strange behavior are called market technicians--mathematically oriented traders and analysts whose conversations are largely unintelligible to the general public Rather than relying on fundamental concepts such as price-to-earnings ratios, book values, or earnings growth, technicians will look for opportunities in the trading pattern of a stock--usually in its price movements and volume of shares traded. <p>In times past, technicians studied their reams of statistical data like medieval scribes, drawing their own charts and analyzing numbers on slide rules. Now computers have taken over, making some of the technicians' arcane mysteries accessible to individual investors.<p>Technicians talk in intimidating terms about "trend-line breakouts," "MACD oscillators," "stochastics," and "trading-channel indices." Don't be confused. What they're really talking about are the basic laws of supply and demand. "If a lot of people want to buy a stock and not many people want to sell, then the price should increase," says Mitch Legarza, an executive with AIQ Inc., a computer-software manufacturer located in Lake Tahoe, Nevada, that specializes in technical-analysis programs. <p>How can investors measure supply and demand in a constantly fluctuating market? "If the price is increasing and the trading volume is high, that means enthusiasm for the stock is increasing," Legarza explains. "If volume is going up and prices stabilize or drop, that suggests that sellers are beginning to outnumber buyers."<p>At last count, there were some 60 different ways that technicians measure a stock's upward or downward movement, also known as momentum. AIQ software calculates and tracks about 30 of them. One of the simplest is a program that tracks a stock's current price and its average price over the last 200 days--called, appropriately enough, the 200-day moving average. When the moving-average line rises above the current price, that simply means that the stock has traded higher over the past 200 days than it does now. A technician might buy at the moment the moving average falls below the current price and sell when it starts to turn back upward.<p>A slightly more complicated way to view the same data is to compute the 10-day and 49-day moving averages. If the price of a stock is moving up at an increasing rate, then the 10-day line will move above the 49-day line--a bullish signal for technicians. <p>In the past, technicians and fundamentalists were a little like the Hatfields and the McCoys: Fundamentalists thought that technical analysis was numerical voodoo, while technicians pointed out that most fundamental analyses involve predictions about future corporate earnings based on statistics from the past. But shrewd investors use both approaches. "I don't even consider a stock technically until I'm satisfied with the fundamentals," says Tom Barrett, director of research for Comprehensive Capital, a regional brokerage firm in West Palm Beach, Florida. "We find a group of stocks to pick from that are very strong fundamentally, and then we look at their strength technically to see when to get in or out."<p>In 1991 and 1992, Barrett used AIQ programs to generate monthly buy and sell recommendations on what he perceived to be the strongest ten stocks on the New York Stock Exchange. As if technical analysis weren't already complex enough, Barrett found that different technical indicators seem to work best with different stocks. For instance Barrett found the MACD--moving-average convergence/divergence indicator, a graph of the differences between two moving averages--using the 10-day moving average and the 49-day moving average seemed to work best in predicting future movements in Disney shares.<p>For <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>, Barrett prefers something called stochastics: a graph of the range of the stock's price over the prior 21 days. "If today's price is in the lower 20 percent of the stock's trading range, then chances are pretty good that its next move is going to be up," says Barrett. Why? Because, according to Barrett, a stock will trade in a spectrum that's 30 percent above or below the middle of its 21-day trading range 90 percent of the time.<p>Legarza believes that most investors will use technical analysis as a kind of junior partner to their fundamental investigation. This is exactly the approach taken by the regional brokerage firm Edward D. Jones & Co., which has recently begun using technical analysis in the stock recommendations it offers to clients. "If a stock is fundamentally sound, the next question is, is this the right time to buy it?" says Legarza. "Let's say we're looking at a $40 stock, but the technical indicators suggest a minor correction. If, over the next two weeks, the stock goes from $40 to $38, and then our technical analysis says that it has found a little support--we just saved the client 5 percent." Saving another 5 percent on the sell side is even better.<p>With its three software programs ranging in price from $249 to $996, AIQ is well within the reach of individual investors. While most investors are probably better off buying mutual funds than they are buying and selling stocks based on some wiggly lines on a computer screen, it's still good to know that the same tools used by professionals are now available to the rest of us. Individual investors are getting more and more equal all the time.<p>Robert N. Veres edits and publishes Inside Information, a monthly newsletter for professional financial advisors. <p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
