<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-An Investing Slap Shot</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-An Investing Slap Shot</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Keep your money in the neighborhood. Canada is about to experience an economic revival.<p>By Jim Rogers <p>Canada hasn't exactly been an investing hot spot during the past 25 years. In 1971, the Canadian dollar sold at a premium to the U.S. dollar, at $1.09. Today it sells for 73 cents, a fall of 33 percent during a time when U.S. currency has taken its lumps in world markets.<p>Canada's leaders are partly to blame for the nation's sorry economic performance. But Canada, as an economy based on natural resources, has also suffered to no small degree from the great commodities price slump of recent years.<p>What is Canada's place in the parliament of nations? In geographical size, it's second only to Russia. It has roughly one-tenth of our population, 28.8 million people -- slightly fewer than California. Only one-third of its vast area has been developed.<p>Among the world's manufacturing nations, Canada holds a prominent position. However, it is dependent on the U.S. not only for investment capital but also for markets than can absorb its big surpluses of petroleum and agricultural and manufactured goods. In addition to large petroleum reserves, the nation is a leading producer of asbestos, nickel, zinc, and potash, as well as a major source of uranium, aluminum, titanium, cobalt, gold, silver, copper, platinum, iron ore, lead, and molybdenum. Canada's forests provide more than one-third of the world's supply of newsprint. Its farms and ranches produce vast quantities of wheat and beef, much of which is exported.<p>Fully half of Canada's exports are industrial machinery, agricultural machinery, cars, trucks, engines, parts, and office machines. In 1994, 82 percent of these goods were exported to the U.S. Its next largest trading partner is Japan, to which it ships less than 5 percent of its output. Economically, Canada might as well be our 51st state.<p>Canada's labor force is educated and has a strong work ethic, and Canada has a solid infrastructure with a large manufacturing base. It is chockablock with natural resources. Despite paying higher hourly wages, <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> has found it cheaper to build cars in Canada and the U.S. than in Mexico.<p>So why has the Canadian economy done so poorly? Simple: The country has run up a huge national debt. On a per capita basis, its citizens owe more in public debt than U.S. citizens. National deficits and debts are the twin crippling diseases that afflict all too many developed countries, including most of Europe and the U.S.<p>Canada's heritage could have given it the best of all worlds -- English government and politics, French culture, and American technology. Instead, it has adopted a far less appealing blend: English technology, French government, and American culture. Just how this came to pass is a mystery for sociologists and historians to sort out.<p>Despite all this, I believe that this could be a good time to invest in Canada. First, Canada should benefit as the world moves from a declining market in natural resources to a boom -- a subject I've harped on often in these pages. The giant stockpiles that the Russians have been dumping on the world economy have all been dumped, and worldwide prosperity in developing economies is demanding more raw materials than the world can currently produce. It will take time for new supplies to come on board. Countries with abundant supplies of timber, oil, agricultural products, and mine ores, such as those in Africa and South America, are going to do very well. Canada should do well, too. <p>Second, there's a good chance the political climate in Canada may have taken a turn for the better. In the most recent election in the province of Alberta, the current state premier, Ralph Klein, ran on an unusual platform. Elect me, he told Alberta's voters, and I will fire the province's excess workers and balance the budget. Alberta said okay, and Klein kept his campaign promises. Amazingly enough, his popularity has soared. Klein has been so successful that he recently wrote to his province's voters for advice on how to spend the growing surpluses.<p>Following Alberta's example, seven of Canada's other nine provinces have balanced their books in the fiscal year ended March 31 or are likely to do so in 199697. Ontario (the biggest non-sovereign borrower in the international capital markets in the early 1990s) has taken an ax to public spending. Under the Conservative government that took office in mid-1995, welfare payments have been cut and business subsidies frozen. Even in Quebec, Lucien Bouchard, the new premier, has said that the province's economic problems have a higher priority than does a renewed drive to secede from Canada. <p>The federal government may also be headed in the right direction. In 1993, it had a deficit of 5.9 percent of gross domestic product. This should be lowered to 2 percent in 1997 -- a vast improvement. The finance minister has promised to balance the books. If the country can do this according to plan, the deficit will be down to 0.7 percent of GDP in 199798 -- the lowest of the Group of Seven, an association of the world's leading industrialized nations.<p>In short: The revolution that started in Alberta is growing in influence across Canada, and if it goes all the way, the country will become an economic powerhouse during the coming commodities boom. And this revolution will be none too soon, either. It 
is a transformation every G-7 country must go through -- 
or perish.<p>There are yet other advantages to Canadian investments. For about five years, Canada's rate of inflation has been lower than that of the U.S. Also, Canadian corporations have been undergoing the same sort of fundamental restructuring as their U.S. counterparts. Canadian firms have been investing large amounts of capital, positioning themselves to make steady gains in productivity. Indeed, unit-labor costs are down by almost 25 percent since 1991, and only three countries have a better record: Sweden, Italy, and Finland. In the U.S., unit-labor costs are declining at only half the Canadian rate. <p>How to invest in Canada?<p>One easy and safe way is to buy the Canadian dollar. Purchase a Canadian money-market account, CD, T-bill, or simple savings account. Canadian bonds at this point yield more than U.S. bonds, so bright investors might be able to achieve a double whammy: earn higher interest payments and ride an increase in the Canadian dollar against that of the U.S.<p>When our stock market falls, Canada's will, too, but probably not as much. Also, its subsequent rise is likely to be more robust. According to the 1994-95 G.T. Guide to World Equity Markets, Canada's equity market is the world's sixth largest. "It's well developed, liquid, heavily researched, and an important provider of corporate finance," the guide says. There are five stock exchanges in the country: in Toronto, Montreal, Vancouver, Calgary, and Winnipeg. The markets in Toronto and Montreal are the primary trading venues for the securities of major Canadian corporations and handle 95 percent of the total value traded in Canada, while the Vancouver Exchange has a reputation as a wild venture-capital market for companies with smaller resources. There are 1,288 companies listed on the Toronto Stock Exchange.<p>The market in Canada is sometimes compared to the South African and  Australian markets because of the influence of the prices of natural resources, but the largest and most active stocks listed in Montreal and Toronto include "a heavy representation of communication companies, diversified industrials, utilities, and banks," according to the G.T. Guide.<p>A savvy investor might buy Canadian natural-resource companies, of which there are hundreds and which should produce Canada's biggest success stories over the next ten years. And if you are of a mind to buy bank stocks, consider Canadian banks. If you like retailers, why not research Canadian retailers? <p>A note of caution, however. Like most countries assembled by empire builders, Canada was put together without much thought to the region's natural geographic, ethnic, and linguistic borders. At some point, I believe, Canada will split up, and not just into two parts (French speaking and English speaking) but probably into four. 
A map quickly shows why. If Quebec takes itself out of Canada, it leaves a wide tear right down the country's middle. Cut off from the other provinces by hundreds of miles, the maritime provinces in the east will find it difficult to form an alliance with those in the west and may well seek an alliance with the U.S. to become -- what? The state of North Maine?<p>Western Canada -- British Columbia, the Yukon, and Alberta -- has the same rugged approach to life as our own west, and it is not likely to want to associate itself with the big spenders back east. Vancouver today is full of Asians who have brought a work ethic that puts Anglo-Saxons to shame, as they believe strongly in saving and investing for the future. They'll be reluctant to pay for somebody else's sluggardly lifestyle. I expect the separatist movement that eventually succeeds will originate in the west and not among the French speakers of Quebec.<p>To sum up, Canada's body politic is changing rapidly, and the country's  natural resources are about to pay off big. With prosperity likely to arrive, the French separatists will not be as eager to push away from their brother states. Indeed, I don't believe Canada's breakup will happen for another 10 to 15 years -- until the coming commodities boom is over and the next downturn arrives. <p>What does history tell us about such situations? Unfortunately, we have little relevant past to examine. The last 200 to 300 years have been a period of empire building, not empire breaking, and the rise of huge central-government debts is a phenomenon of only the last 100 years.<p>Canadian investments may be good for the next ten years or so, but don't put them away and forget about them, because the country's current problems will come back to haunt it. Canadian investments are not the sort you sock away for your estate or your grandchildren.<p>
Jim Rogers is a contributing editor and the author of Investment Biker (Adams).<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Economy, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
