<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
The Japan Question -- Again<p>By Todd G. Buchholz<p>When I last wrote about the Land of the Rising Sun, in October 1995, dawn appeared to be indefinitely postponed. Bad debts in the banking sector were estimated to total about $800 billion, around four times higher than those racked up by the U.S. during the savings-and-loan crisis of the 1980s. At the same time, economists couldn't find a pulse in the Japanese economy, and consumer prices were falling in a deflationary spiral that the Japanese referred to by the forbidding phrase "price destruction."<p>Why, then, have investors been on a stock-buying spree? The Nikkei, Japan's key stock index, jumped over 26 percent in the year ended May 10, 1996 (though U.S. investors would have seen all but 0.49 percent of that gain evaporate because of the dollar's rebound against the yen).<p>Clearly, buyers of Japanese equities see an economic recovery, and the evidence suggests there may be one on the horizon. The Japanese shopper, after an extended hibernation, is once again stirring, sending department-store sales up by 6 percent year over year. Car sales are up 7.7 percent. After the deflation of the past few years, Japan's consumer price index actually showed a plus sign (+0.1 percent) in March, giving business leaders reason to increase investments in order to raise production to meet burgeoning demand.<p>It appears, then, that Japan's battered economy is slowly on the mend, helped by an astoundingly low official discount interest rate of 0.5 percent and by the rise of the dollar against the yen, which makes Japanese exporters more competitive.<p>So, is it time for investors to jump in and catch the rising wave? I think not. Japan's government is in a policy dilemma. For two years, the Bank of Japan has been stomping on the monetary accelerator, trying to add liquidity to the banking system -- thus, the 0.5 percent discount rate (compared with a 5.25 percent Fed Funds rate in the U.S.). Fiscal policy has also been loosened by the Ministry of Finance, with one stimulus package after another riding through the Diet, Japan's congress. The fiscal expansion has been so great that Japan's budget deficit now stands at just under 8 percent of gross domestic product, compared with a U.S. budget deficit at under 2.3 percent of GDP.<p>The easy-money policy of the Ministry of Finance and the Bank of Japan's support of low official interest rates (which makes the central bank appear subservient to the government's political needs, unlike the independent Bundesbank in Germany or the Federal Reserve Board in the U.S.) worry many market analysts, who fear a sharp slowdown will hit in the fall. That's when last year's stimulus spending runs out. In addition, Bank of Japan chief Yasuo Matsushita has said he expects interest rates to rise over the course of the year.<p>The big question is whether Japan's private sector will pick up the slack or slide back into a recession after the government stops pumping up the economy. The June 7 tankan report, which takes the temperature of private-sector sentiment to gauge expectations for economic activity, will be closely scrutinized for answers to that question. A strong report will push the Nikkei stock index higher but punish the Japanese bond market, which will look back at today's 0.5 percent discount rate as a distant memory.<p>You can hear the bond bears snarling across the Pacific.<p>Contributing editor Todd Buchholz is a managing director of a New Yorkbased international investment fund and the author of From Here to Economy: A Shortcut to Economic Literacy.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
