<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Look South</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Look South</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Anne Field<p>After 1994's peso debacle, Latin-American funds have come roaring back in 1996 with an average return of 16.1 percent through April 30. "We think Latin-American markets will continue to outperform the U.S.," says Jon Teall of Lipper Analytical Services. The mutual-fund rating company Morningstar lists the following five among the best of the 26 open-end Latin-American funds.<p><a name="FUND:BTLAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BTLAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BT INVESTMENT LATIN AMERICAN EQUITY</b></a>. The managers of this fund, supported by 15 New York based emerging-markets analysts, pick investments strictly top down: first by country and then by theme. In Argentina, the theme is growth, played through financial services and cyclicals. Started by Bankers Trust in 1993, the fund has a 1996 return of 20.4 percent as of April 30.<p><a name="FUND:MSLAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MSLAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MORGAN STANLEY LATIN AMERICAN A. </b></a>Manager Robert Meyer's strategy at this two-year-old fund varies among the seven countries in which he invests. He'll buy high-growth stocks in stable Chile and bargains in rocky Mexico. His portfolio is up 23.1 percent for 1996. Currently, 43 percent of assets are in Brazil, and 34 percent are in Mexico.<p><a name="FUND:SLAFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SLAFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SCUDDER LATIN AMERICA</b></a>. The bottom-up stock pickers at this four-year-old fund are backed by 36 industry and country analysts. A cash cushion of 5 to 15 percent helps mitigate volatility. Most of the fund's 16.7 percent return has come from a 40 percent weighting in Brazil. The fund is also overweighted in Argentina.<p><a name="FUND:PRLAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRLAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. ROWE PRICE LATIN AMERICA</b></a>. Managers from Rowe Price Fleming International, aided by six analysts in Latin America, diversify across more countries (11) and more stocks (109) than most of their peers. The two-and-a-half-year-old fund has returned 15.4 percent in 1996 with bets on Brazil and Mexico. <p><a name="FUND:WEMEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WEMEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>WRIGHT EQUIFUND-MEXICO</b></a>. Run by a 34-year-old money-management firm specializing in open-end single-country funds, Equifund-Mexico has returned 23.2 percent in 1996. Its bottom-up stock pickers look to buy growth when it's cheap. With bargains hard to find now, 16 percent of the fund is in cash. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
