	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Japan's Skeletons</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Japan's Skeletons</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The gurus say Japan is back, but the country hasn't solved its biggest problem: It still saves too much<p>By Walter Russell Mead<p>The conventional wisdom on Japan moves almost as fast as one of the country's famous shinkansen bullet trains. Seven years ago, investment gurus argued that the Tokyo stock market wasn't overvalued when the Nikkei Index moved above 35,000.<p>Then, in 1992, the stock market and the country's real-estate boom both collapsed. Japan, said the gurus, was all washed up. Newly competitive U.S. corporations and aggressive competition from the Asian tigers had struck a mortal blow to Japan's industrial giants.<p>Now, say the same experts, Japan is back. The long economic slump is over, and the stock market -- still 44 percent below its 1989 peak -- looks tempting. Bill Clinton's spring trip to Tokyo revealed a new, confident Japan, one ready to take a higher security profile in the region.<p>Ten years ago, nothing could stop Japan. Three years ago, nothing could save it. Is the financial press going overboard on Japan again? You bet. Japan has not solved any of the deep economic and political structural problems that took the country on that wild boom-bust ride in the 1980s. In fact, it seems unlikely that Japan will rejoin the ranks of the world's high-growth economies anytime soon.<p>I understand why it feels like Japan is firmly launched on a course of recovery. I know it feels like the excesses of the boom are being wrung out of the system, that banks are regaining solvency, that investors are newly sober. It's easy to draw a fairly convincing analogy between what is happening in Japan today and the cycle of financial excess, pain, and recovery that characterized the U.S. savings-and-loan crisis of the 1980s. But that analogy is dangerously deceptive. A system of traditional attitudes and relationships makes capitalism in Japan essentially different from the version practiced in the U.S. And the nature of Japanese capitalism prevents the kind of healthy cleansing that occasionally sweeps through U.S. financial markets.<p>Back when Japan Inc. was working, Americans stood in awe of its dynamic industrial system. Products of amazingly high quality -- selling for remarkably low prices -- poured out of factories run by legions of dedicated workers operating the latest in robots. U.S. executives at company after company launched crash-course programs to catch up, often adapting Japanese methods of production (such as just-in-time inventory) that seemed responsible for that country's success.<p>But U.S. business leaders were powerless to duplicate the nationwide thrift that was the ultimate source of Japan's industrial edge. Japan was the world's most awesome savings-and-investment machine. Here's how it worked.<p>Every year, Japanese consumers and businesses managed to sock away about 33 percent of the country's gross domestic product -- 155.8 trillion yen, or about $1.5 trillion, in 1992, for example. (In comparison, the U.S. savings rate that year was 15 percent.) Japanese companies used the resulting tidal wave of low-cost capital to continuously upgrade their production processes and products. The low cost of capital was a major source of Japan's advantage in international markets. In 1978, for example, Toyota was able to borrow money at 6.42 percent interest in Japan, while its rival General Motors faced a prime rate of 9.06 percent in the United States.<p>In the glory years, the average Japanese citizen's thrift was part of a virtuous cycle. High export earnings -- made possible by the manufacturing efficiency financed by domestic savings -- fueled corporate profits and wage increases; these allowed the Japanese to save still more; in turn, this lowered the cost of capital to Japanese companies, enabling them to expand production and increase export earnings. While it worked, Japan posted remarkable rates of economic growth -- an average of 17 percent annual increases in GDP in the 1960s, 14 percent in the 1970s, and 7 percent as late as 1990.<p>So what went wrong?<p>The virtuous cycle, it turned out, had a weak link: export growth. As Japan grew larger and its export share in key industries -- such as VCRs, TVs, and automobiles -- increased, it ran up against a basic but bitter truth: No country can grow faster than its markets forever. For example, by 1988, the Japanese had captured 75 percent of the global market for VCRs. But by that time, the market was mature. In the U.S., the market for VCRs actually shrank by 9 percent between 1988 and 1989. To help keep the Japanese home economy growing at 10 percent a year, Japanese VCR makers struggled to capture more of this market -- a difficult task for companies facing competition from cheaper VCRs made in South Korea and Taiwan.<p>As Japan's growth slowed, the hunger for capital abated, but the country's savings machine rolled on, pumping ever increasing amounts of liquidity into a system that didn't need it. For a while, Japanese companies, believing that the era of rapid growth would one day return, continued to pour more money into expansion. But once new factories were built, many were forced to run below capacity. Gradually, companies began to scale back capital investment.<p>Which left a lot of capital looking for a home. From 1985 through 1993, the Japanese added a total of about 1.2 quadrillion yen -- or about $12 trillion -- to their national savings, an amount equal to twice the value of goods and services produced in the U.S. annually.<p>Imagine a huge fire hose writhing out of control as it spews water in every direction. That's how Japan's surplus savings, no longer absorbed in financing industrial expansion, flooded Japanese and world markets. Investors and speculators sent the value of the country's real estate soaring until the paper value of a country slightly smaller than California was four times that of all the real estate in the U.S. Valuations on the Tokyo exchange climbed and then climbed some more -- Tokyu Corp., for example, hit a price-to-earnings ratio of 500 in October 1989.<p>Japan's banks joined in the orgy. With the price of everything in sight going up, up, up, there seemed no way for a bank or its customers to lose money making real-estate loans. Banks felt especially flush because, like German banks, Japanese banks can take equity positions in industrial companies. With their portfolios bursting at the seams with rapidly appreciating stock, banks had plenty to lend.<p>Industrial companies got in on the act, too. They were no longer able to make money by expanding their share of foreign markets, but they could still make plenty of money at what the Japanese call zaiteku, a short-term investment strategy that puts excess corporate cash into futures, options, and other derivatives. Company treasurers played the stock and property markets -- and made fortunes. Those earnings then drove stock prices up -- and the higher stock prices drove earnings up again. This "bubble economy" resulted in the biggest bout of financial speculation since the 1920s.<p>The bubble may have burst, but the buddy-buddy financial system that produced it remains intact. Efforts at reform are at a standstill. Even something as simple as writing down bad investments has not proceeded very far.<p>No one knows just how bad the problems are at Japanese banks. Officially, the Japanese government estimates that bad loans in its banking system amount to $350 billion. Outsiders believe that this is wildly optimistic and that the real figure is $800 billion -- and may well go higher. (Compare this with the U.S. savings-and-loan disaster, where the best estimate puts the level of bad loans at $52 billion in an economy a third larger.) An alarmed Japanese government is keeping interest rates low and allowing banks to hide problems while frantically casting around for a long-term solution.<p>Meanwhile, Japan's political gridlock persists. An unbelievably corrupt and unresponsive political class can't come to grips with the painful decisions that need to be made. Lobbies and corporations with vested interests in the old system have blocked any real progress toward structural reform.<p>Essentially, Japan has three choices today. It can muddle on with an economic strategy that no longer makes sense. It can lower its savings rate until it is like those in other advanced countries. Or, and this increasingly seems the most likely course of action, it 
can boost spending and cut savings through expanded military spending. By increasing military spending over the next decade from its current level (between 1 and 2 percent of GDP) to something like 3 to 5 percent of GDP and investing in high-tech aerospace industries, Japan could revive its economy, challenge the U.S. and European duopoly on civilian aviation, and guard itself against the possibility that the U.S. will someday retreat from Asia even as China becomes stronger.<p>Although this last approach risks angering the many Japanese who remain pacifist and anti-militarist, their anger may be easier for politicians to face than the power of the vested interests who don't want the serious domestic reforms that are required. The increasing nationalism of Japanese politics and growing opposition to the U.S. military presence in Okinawa suggest that the Japanese consensus may be moving slowly toward what Americans used to call military Keynesianism.<p>In the short run, that might be good for Japanese stocks. In the long run, it is unlikely to be good for U.S.Japan relations, or the peace of East Asia.<p>Walter Mead is the presidential fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance provided by Tomas Matza.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Economy, International Banking, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

