<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Todd G. Buchholz<p>Venezuela Hears the Fall of the Wall
The Berlin Wall came crashing down in 1989, but the reverberations from that symbol of socialist economic collapse continue to spread, most recently to Venezuela. <p>Populist president Rafael Caldera came to office in February 1994 promising a mixed socialist/capitalist economy. But after successive years of a declining gross domestic product, inflation that hit 70.9 percent in 1994 and 56.6 percent in 1995, and constant rumors of coups and riots, he has accepted a deal with the International Monetary Fund that requires him to end controls on interest and exchange rates.<p>How did Caldera manage to retain power despite such a dismal performance? In a word: oil. Venezuela exports millions of barrels of oil every year, producing a source of foreign revenue that keeps the nation's trade account in surplus.<p>In many ways, oil has been a curse for Latin America, allowing countries like Mexico and Venezuela to prop up huge and inefficient state-run industries. In the case of Venezuela, oil revenues also let the government curry favor with the public by maintaining artificially low gasoline prices. Now, however, Caldera has agreed to a gasoline sales tax, which will raise an estimated $1 billion annually. This revenue is badly needed to fight the government's deficit, which last year hit a worrisome 5.9 percent of GDP.<p>In return, the IMF, the World Bank, and the InterAmerican Development Bank have pledged up to $2.5 billion in aid, allowing Planning Minister Teodoro Petkoff to float the bolivar against the U.S. dollar. Previously, Caldera's exchange-rate-control policy pegged the bolivar at 290 to the dollar, overvaluing it by about a third. The expected devaluation should help Venezuelan exports.<p>Caldera will also allow interest rates to float, and they should rise as a result. This means that borrowers and the banking industry will experience a near-term crunch. The average Venezuelan will feel it, too, as prices increase, government spending falls, and the bolivar buys less on the international market. In fact, under this plan, there is a good chance that Venezuela's 1996 numbers for GDP and inflation will be worse than 1995's.<p>So what's the point? Only by establishing fiscal credibility can emerging-market countries like Venezuela afford to borrow the money they need to build factories and create wealth. In fact, the announced reforms have already produced some positive results. Back in December 1995, Venezuela had to pay 6.4 percent more than the U.S. to borrow in the international Brady-bond market. By April 16, a few days before Caldera's reform speech, the spread had narrowed to 5.5 percent. That's a 14 percent cut in borrowing costs. The equity market has also embraced the reforms, with the Caracas Stock Exchange up about 85 percent since January 1. American depositary receipts traded in New York for Venezuelan steelmaker Sivensa and chemical maker Mantex have jumped by about 100 percent and 30 percent, respectively, since December 8, 1995.<p>Of course, much could go wrong. Savers may send their bolivars out of the country, which would devastate the financial sector. It's a touchy situation, but in the past five years, the Argentine and Brazilian markets have fought back against even higher inflation and longer odds. <p>Contributing editor Todd Buchholz is a managing director of a New York based international investment fund and the author of From Here to Economy: A Shortcut to Economic Literacy.<p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, International Politics, Government
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
