		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-The International Scene</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The International Scene</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-The International Scene</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> THE INTERNATIONAL SCENE  <p> By Pamela Black   <p> Last year the U.S. stock market returned 37.14 percent, leaving the rest of the developed world in the dustall those other markets combined returned just 11.41 percent, according to Morgan Stanley Capital International. But the ten-year figures show a very different picture: After corrections for the decline of the dollar, the U.S. barely makes the list of the ten developed countries with the highest average annual returns. Hong Kong, driven by hot growth in the Pacific basin, tops the lists in both local currency and dollars. But the U.S. also trails such slow-growth/strong-currency markets as Switzerland, where the market returned 9.55 percent annually in francs but 16.18 percent in dollars.  <p> Although the comparative performance of the U.S. market will improve if the dollar strengthens, Latin-American markets could be the new growth stars, according to Bill Wilby, director of Global Equities at Oppenheimer Mutual Funds. <p>
KEYWORDS: U.S. Economy, International Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

