<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Safety Nyet</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Safety Nyet</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Safety Nyet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Columns  <p>  <p>SAFETY NYET <p>Conventional wisdom on Russia's future isn't worth a ruble. And have you priced the ruble lately?  <p>  <p>By Jim Rogers  <p>  <p>A popular investment refrain making the rounds today is that the former Soviet Union is an economically alluring place, perhap seven another Southeast Asia in the making. Franklin Templeton Group, an internationally savvy investment outfit, has started a Russia fund. Huge Western oil companies have sledded into Siberiato drill. Plans are afoot to export tens of millions of board feet of clear pine from Siberia to the U.S. Even <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's </b></a> is doing a brisk trade selling Quarter Pounders to the Russians.What's not to like? The opportunities seem immense; gargantuan fortunes are ripe to be plucked.  <p> Not with my money. As far as I'm concerned, the former Soviet Union is still the world's great economic, political, social, and military disaster in the making. It will be so for years, if not decades. It's not a good place to run a business, conducttours, operate a charity, have an artistic career, be a bureaucrat, or invest.  <p> The most important thing to understand about this part of the world is also the most obvious: It was an empire created from a collection of 170 separate nations and ethnic groups. It was the largest contiguous empire the world has ever known, covering more land mass than the empires of the Chinese, the Romans, the Spanish, or the British. The Soviet Union stretched across half of Europe and all of Asia, from the Baltic and the Danube to the Bering Sea and the Pacific, 9,000 miles in total--a span equal to the distance between London and Honolulu.  <p> It grew over the course of a thousand years. The czars pulled most of it together. But it was the Communists who finished the project of unifying--or attempting to unify--these 170 separate groups under one umbrella, the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics. Given the current difficulties Russia is having policing Chechnya--a province the size of Connecticut, with 1.5 million people--I would say that keeping all of Russia's disparate groups together is going to be next to impossible.  <p> The Western press, however, appears to disagree with me. It believes that the time has come for healing now that the Soviet Union has split into 15 separate nations. The best and brightest  Russians are at the Harvard and Columbia business schools, and once they've mastered the lessons taught there, they will return to Russia, where, after a year or two of transition, they'll turn the country into a democratic powerhouse--or so the theory goes.  <p> I'm dubious. I predict further unraveling. Before it is over,I expect to see 50 countries, 100 countries. At the moment, few citizens in the former Soviet Union are paying attention to the empire's central government. I had a strong sense of this when I motorcycled across Russia on both the northern and southern routes--9,800 miles of mystery, beauty, and misery. I saw evidence everywhere of a collapsing society: rusting missiles, dilapidated military trucks, crops rotting in the fields, lakes filled with sewage, oil rigs in disrepair. Thanks to the Central Intelligence Agency, the U.S. never recognized that the Soviet Union was no more than a third-world country with a fine space program and a savvy chess team. We should have learned from the Soviets' war in Afghanistan that there wasn't much left to the once great Red Army. After all, Afghanistan has only 16.5 million people, and it's right next to the Soviet Union, not half a world away, as Vietnam, with its 70 million inhabitants, was for the U.S. <p> Authority in the former Soviet Union has devolved into the rule of the warlord, that political leader who always surfaces with the breakdown of central power, particularly during the crack-up of empires.  <p> History tells us that no empire lasts forever. With regard to the Soviet Union, a number of factors contributed to its breakdown, not the least of which was its effort to be a superpower on a third-world budget. Relying on a wacky economic theory didn't help matters, either.  <p> The larger the empire, the greater the disruption when it blows to pieces. We're still feeling the turbulence from the breakup of the Ottoman empire seven and eight decades later, through the unrest in Iran, Libya, Iraq, and Algeria. Only in the past few years have Mexico and Peru approached stability, more than a century after the Spanish empire crumbled in Latin America. <p> When an empire becomes unstable and lawless, a period ensuesin which warlord fights warlord. Today, Soviet warlords include gangs, the Mafia, dictators, liberators, and Communists. The so-called entrepreneurial spirit in Russia, about which we read so often, is actually nothing more than a spirited bout among thugs.  <p> There's an old investing adage, supposedly uttered by Nathan Rothschild: The best time to invest is when blood is in the streets. What he meant, probably assuming it too obvious to spell out at the time, was that the only smart time to invest is when a political and social situation is about to become stable, predictable. <p> But in the former Soviet Union, it's just the calm before the storm, the lull before total disaster. Much of Russian society is angry, bewildered, unable to understand what is happening. Very likely, the Russian people will welcome whichever demagogue makes the most lavish promises. Only a few years ago, the ruble was worth roughly a dollar; today, it takes about 5,000 rubles to buy a dollar. Inside a year, it will require 10,000; within three years, 100,000.  <p> Perhaps you're tempted to invest in a project to drill for oil in Siberia. Any such project will have to be developed under what will soon become yesterday's management. When the next provincial governor arrives, he'll explain that no one understood that your enterprise planned to take oil out of the province.  <p> You simply can't win when there is no court, no rule of law, no stability. At the Irkutsk Aluminum plant, which produces ingots that command foreign hard currency, the last six managing directors have been murdered. Scores of Soviet bank presidents have been shot as well. Meanwhile, the mafiosi, the warlords, the nomenklatura, the apparatchiks, and the insiders will be working hard to get their own money out of Russia and into Switzerland or some other haven. Shouldn't that tell you something?  <p> Profits made by foreigners will be taxed away, inflated away,or taken away, with the emphasis on "away." Own shares? The share register may be altered overnight. Or the Duma, the parliament, may declare contracts such as yours fraudulent.  <p> Insiders have already grabbed whatever buildings, factories,and stockpiles of raw materials were available--helping to trigger worldwide fire sales in titanium, uranium, gold, zinc, lead, platinum, and palladium--plus tanks, missiles, and planes.  <p> These sales won't go on much longer, because the whole infrastructure is falling apart. Plants are closed. Electricity, fuel, trucks, roads, phones, spare parts, rail cars, and rail track are all in short supply. Grain production has fallen drastically, and what is produced can barely be gotten to market before it rots. <p> Nobody knows precisely how bad things really are. None of the figures on trade, budgets, tax collection, and currency reserves under the Communists could be trusted, and it's worse now, as there's no central authority to gather the information and no cooperation from the former empire in collecting it. The Russians haven't made any meaningful payments on their debt in years. <p> Paradoxically, only maps of the former Soviet Union accurately foretell its future. If you look at a map for each of the past ten centuries, you'll notice a continent in constant change--borders shifting, alliances merging and separating. Tragically enough,the inhabitants of the former Soviet Union have been at war and killing one another for centuries.  <p> What might rise from the ashes of the USSR? Scores of phoenixes: brightly colored birds that can still be found in full plumage in the old maps. They include various linguistic, religious, tribal, and nationalistic groups, such as the Buriat Mongol tribes, the Tatars, and the Moldavian Republic.  <p> The only way I see an investor profiting from the situation in Russia is by buying commodities. As the raw materials produced chiefly by Russia dry up, an investor, expecting shortages, might purchase the materials or the means to produce oil, uranium, gold, zinc, lead, platinum, palladium, and titanium.  <p> I'm often asked why, if I'm so sure this is a bad time to invest in Russia, I think this is a good time to invest in Africa and Latin America. Surely the latter two regions are as destitute as any place on the planet.  <p> Little is as it appears. It's important to look not just for an emerging country but for emerging stability as well. Africa and Latin America have had their collapses and have learned their lessons; they've experienced unworkable theories and chaos. Their peoples want stability and are willing to fight for it.  <p> This summer, the Russians may hold an election to select their first president since the breakup of the union into 15 separate parts. But don't be fooled. The American press will have predictions about this election, handicapping who's ahead and who's behind--but the results will be totally meaningless. An enormous historical force is playing itself out. The collapse of the Soviet Union has only just begun.  <p> Jim Rogers is a contributing editor and the author of Investment Biker (Adams).  <p><p>
KEYWORDS:International Mutual Funds Investing, International Economy<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
