	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Sifting Through the Ruins Abroad</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Sifting Through Ruins Abroad</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> SIFTING THROUGH THE RUINS ABROAD <p>Finding a foreign fund can be tricky after two years of lousy returns  <p> By Andrew Feinberg  <p> Prognosticators of all stripes are touting the return of international stocks this year. The argument is pretty simple: The U.S. market is due for a breather, and foreign stocks are cheap after two tough years. The average European issue now trades at five times cash flow, notes Jean-Marie Eveillard, manager of the <a name="FUND:SGENX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SGENX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SoGen International</b></a> and <a name="FUND:SGOVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SGOVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SoGen Overseas funds</b></a> funds. "In the U.S., the multiple is ten for the Standard & Poor's 400 industrials," he says. In January,the average international fund outpaced the S&P 500 Stock Index, returning 3.81 percent compared with 3.4 percent for the S&P, according to Morningstar.  <p> But the mutual-fund investor who finds that scenario convincing or who simply wants to diversify a portfolio heavy with domestic securities still has to decide which international fund to buy. Certainly the average fund doesn't look too appealing. In 1994 foreign funds returned a negative 2.05 percent on average, according to Morningstar. Last year, the average fund earned an underwhelming 6.54 percent, trailing the S&P 500 Stock Index by some 30 percentage points. Although it's tempting to buy the fund that recently earned the highest return, this is not the best way to pick a foreign fund for the long haul.  <p> Instead, our selection formula starts with a close examination of performance (and what caused it), subtracts points for high sales charges, and then adds a bonus for  experience and an extensive overseas network of analysts.  <p> Foreign funds come in many flavors. Some invest mainly in the industrialized countries of Europe and Asia. Others add volatile emerging markets, such as Turkey and Brazil. International funds don't invest in the U.S., but global funds do.  <p> Why is this important? Because a fund's return depends on the combination of countries represented in its portfolio. Some funds, such as <a name="FUND:OEIAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/OEIAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>One Group International Equity Index</b></a>, approximate the country allocations of the Morgan Stanley Capital International Europe, AustralAsia, and Far East Index (EAFE). These are heavily skewed toward Japan, to which the EAFE allocates 40.3 percent of assets. Other funds, such as  GAM Asian funds, underrepresent Japan --  their portfolios more closely match a benchmark such as <a name="FUND:MSJEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MSJEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley's Far East</b></a> ex Japan index. The difference? EAFE  returned 9.42 percent last year compared with a negative 3.53 percent for Far East ex Japan.  <p> Country choice isn't the only strategic decision that influences performance. There's also asset allocation. <a name="FUND:GAMNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GAMNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GAM International</b></a>'s flexible charter lets the fund switch between stocks and bonds. In 1995, manager John Horseman buried the competition, returning 30.09 percent --  almost six percentage points better than the 24.39 percent earned by <a name="FUND:FPSSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FPSSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Founders Passport</b></a>, the second-best-performing international fund --  by placing heavy bets on German bonds and British utility companies. In fact, only 11 percent of GAM International's assets were in stocks. Founders Passport ran a completely different portfolio: 75 percent stocks and no bonds.GAM's performance varies so much from that of other foreign funds that Morningstar recently moved it to  a category called Multi-Asset Global, composed of funds that move freely between stocks and bonds.  <p> These differences make some funds more erratic than others. The more concentrated a fund is in a few countries, the more volatile it is likely to be. Right now, many funds have over40 percent of assets in just two. <a name="FUND:VWIGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VWIGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard International Growth</b></a>, for instance, had 29.2 percent of its assets in Japan and 13.6 percent in the U.K. as of February 15.  <p> To assure more consistent returns, start with funds that have at least a five-year track record. "Don't buy a fund with a record built on three great years and five mediocre ones," advises Ken Gregory, editor of The No-Load Fund Analyst  in Orinda, California. "The more consistency you see, the more likely that the record is based on talent, not luck."  <p> Standard deviation, a number found in Morningstar Mutual Funds and other investment newsletters, is one way to measure consistency. A high standard deviation means that annual returns vary more. <p> For example, GAM International has delivered average annual returns of 20.15 percent over the past five years  versus 14.7 percent for <a name="FUND:HWINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HWINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hotchkis & Wiley International Fund</b></a>. But GAM is farmore volatile. At 14.51 percent, its five-year standard deviation was third highest among foreign funds with five-year records as of December 31, 1995. Hotchkis & Wiley delivered its returns with a standard deviation of 12.27, which was near the group average.  <p> But standard deviation alone will not tell an investor which funds best combine return and consistency. That can be gleaned in part from a formula such as the Sharpe ratio, which calculate show much performance a fund delivers per unit of risk. Putting volatility and return together gives a slight edge to GAM International: Its Sharpe ratio is 1.21 to Hotchkis & Wiley's 1.11, which means GAM delivers more return per unit of risk.  <p> Unfortunately, neither standard deviation nor the Sharpe ratio considers sales charges, called loads. GAM International's class-Ashares carry a load of 5 percent, whereas Hotchkis & Wiley has no sales charge. The longer an investor holds a fund, the less the load matters, but in the short run, it can take a substantialbite out of returns. For example, GAM International's 5 percent load reduced the one-year rate of return for an investor who bought into the fund on January 1, 1995, to 23.59 percent from the 30.09 percent listed by Morningstar.  <p> No investor should rely solely on numbers to judge a fund's consistency and potential. International markets  are relatively inefficient, so managers can earn extra returns by finding undiscovered stocks. Here experience and  in-country contacts can make a big difference. The standard for investment expertise has been set fairly high by such old hands as Hakan Castegren and Mark Mobius. Castegren, who manages <a name="FUND:HAINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HAINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Harbor International</b></a>, has been buying foreign stocks for 35 years. "He has an incredible frame of referenceand a network built up around the world over time that a 28-year-old manager can't have," says Susan Belden, senior editor of The No-Load Fund Analyst. Mobius, who manages $7 billion in emerging-market funds for the Franklin Templeton fund group, travels ten months of the year to visit some 300 companies.  <p> Although Mobius researches most of the stocks he buys through personal visits, other fund managers can deliver  a similar degree of expertise by exploiting a network of foreign offices. For example, Rowe-Price Fleming, a joint venture between T. Rowe Price Associates and Robert Fleming Holdings, an investment-banking firm based in London, gives the T. Rowe Price International Stock fund access to more than 100 analysts located in 14 countries who follow 4,000 companies.  <p> When all these factors are considered, <a name="FUND:WIETX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WIETX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Warburg Pincus International Equity Common Shares</b></a> (800-257-5614), Hotchkis & Wiley International (800-346-7301), and <a name="FUND:PRITX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRITX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price International Stock</b></a> (800-638-5660) are among the few funds that make the grade. Each has been around at least five years, cranking out consistent returns in the 14 percent range. Like the others, Hotchkis & Wiley has an experienced management team. Four managers, each  specializing in different countries of Europe and Asia, seek high yields and good values with the help of a network of about 100 overseas analysts.  <p> Of the three, Warburg Pincus has the highest five-year standard deviation, 13.94 percent, in part because it has the most exposure to volatile emerging markets. Hotchkis & Wiley has the lowest volatility: It uses high-yielding stocks as a cushion against downdrafts in the market.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
