	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Tour of Japan's Stock Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Tour of Japan's Stock Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Japan's stock market is changing as industrial giants give way to more consumer-oriented companies  <p> By Marlene Piturro  <p> The Japanese market appears to be on the mend. After many gyrations,the widely followed Nikkei 225 stock-market index climbed from a new low last July of 14,485 to 20,751 on February 6, 1996. Thinking the worst was over, investors poured money into Japan mutual funds at a rate of $35 million to $40 million a week in January 1996, about twice the $18 million a week of a year earlier,according to AMG Data Services in Arcata, California.  <p> But Japan, like the U.S., has more than one stock market, and last year, these markets took different turns. Japan's Nikkei 225, which is similar to the Dow Jones Industrial average of 30 large-cap stocks, showed a total return of .74 percent in1995. The Topix, a more comprehensive market benchmark that resembles the U.S. Standard & Poor's 500, returned 1.19 percent. The Jasdaq, or over-the-counter market, lost 11.06 percent.  <p> Investors interested in buying a Japan fund that invests in a specific combination of these stock markets should know that Japan's market is undergoing a transition similar to that in the U.S. in the late 1970s. Older industrial giants are losing ground to younger, more consumer-oriented businesses, says Dan Duane, Pacific Basin portfolio manager for Prudential Securities. Although large-cap stocks may do well in the near term, he says, the best long-term picks are larger consumer-driven issues and over-the-counter stocks, particularly in electronics, real estate,and nonbank financial services such as credit cards.  <p> The 17 Japan funds now available to U.S. investors run the gamut of these markets. <a name="FUND:PRJPX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRJPX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Japan Fund</b></a>, which declined 3.12 percent last year, according to Lipper Analytical Services, buys Japanese blue chips such as NEC and Mitsubishi, at discounts if possible. Co-manager Chris Alderson believes these companies are currently undervalued.   <p> By contrast, <a name="FUND:WEITX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WEITX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Warburg Pincus Japan OTC Fund</b></a> scours the over-the-counter market for fast-growing small-company stocks. Co-manager Shuhei Abe likes companies that serve niche markets --  especially small retailers, computer makers, and construction firms --  and cancircumvent the inefficiencies of the Japanese economy. His 1995 return of negative 1.09 percent easily beat the Jasdaq.  <p> <a name="FUND:GAJCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GAJCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GAM Japan Capital Fund</b></a> manager Paul Kirkby takes an eclectic approach, starting with an industry group and then zeroing inon stocks he considers a good value. That strategy won him the top return among Japan funds last year (6.34  percent), when he favored technology, business services, and retail stocks over cyclicals. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

