<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01S-As the World Turns</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-As the World Turns</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						While the nations of the First World stumble along in search of growth, some of the roller-coaster emerging-market economies will find it in 1996. Will it be China in the Year of the Pig, or Brazil in the year of low inflation? And what if Russia and the ruble melt down? Take a trip and find out.    <p>
 By Todd G. Buchholz  <p>
 Nineteen Ninety-five could have been written off before it began, so far as the emerging markets were concerned. That was due entirely to the December 1994 collapse of Mexico's economy and financial markets. Investors quickly transferred their loyalty, money, and attention to the mature markets and to such old reliables as U.S. Treasury bonds and the Standard & Poor's 500 Index. The U.S. did well in 1995, buoyed by long-term interest rates that fell throughout the year. But overall, the global investor had little to cheer about. Europe stayed stuck in the mud, with Germany's economy barely inching ahead and French unemployment stagnant at a dizzy 11.5 percent. Japan, meanwhile, looked on glumly as its economy continued to stall and the yen continued to climb.  <p>
 Unfortunately, 1996 is likely to be pretty much a repeat of last year, when the industrialized nations averaged roughly 2 to 2.5 percent growth. In fact, both Europe and the U.S. risk a slowdown, since consumers have piled up formidable amounts of debt, and though Japan may pull itself out of its funk by the second half of the year, its debt-ridden banking sector will limit any recovery.  <p>
 For investors, this means a return to emerging markets, which are able to rev up growth rates faster than the much larger mature economies. In fact, with their immense and rapidly growing populations, the emerging markets could, if all goes well, be the engine that pulls the rest of the world economy in 1996. I've focused below on five countries, including three in the the crucial Latin American region. As always, the enormous risks inherent in investing in these volatile markets loom above the rich rewards they sometimes provide.  <p>
 RUSSIA Even Russophiles find it difficult to make a convincing argument on behalf of Russian monetary policy. The reason is that no one is firmly in charge. Acting central bank chairwoman Tatyana Paramonova has restored credibility to the ruble after its 20 percent nose dive in value on Black Tuesday, October 11,1994, by resisting pressure to print more money and raising there serve requirements for banks. As a result, monthly inflation fell from about 15 percent in October 1994 to just over 4.7 percentin October 1995. Likewise, tradable Russian debt prices rallied impressively during the summer of 1995. The worry, given Paramonova's provisional status, is that she will be ousted and a more pliablefigure installed. If this happens, the markets domestic and foreign will see it as a signal that Yeltsin has sacrificed his monetary policy on the altar of politics.   <p>
 There's further reason for concern on the political front. On October 26, Yeltsin's heart problems brought debt prices down 2 percent, and the December 17 elections are sure to show a resurgent Communist yes, Communist party. Though these Communists claim they won't renationalize the economy but will merely stop further privatization, an electoral turn away from democracy will slow reform and discourage investors. And the importance of the December ballot pales beside the June presidential election.   <p>
 Obviously, investors in Russia need to keep an eye on these events, but so do those with holdings on the Continent. Crises in Russia tend to hurt the German deutsche mark and help the dollar (as a safe haven). Since Russia exports key commodities such as aluminum and oil, stocks of such companies as Alcoa and <a name="NYSE:XON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10537"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Exxon</b></a> may very well rise or fall depending on whether or not the elections suggest Russian industry will continue to modernize. In addition, there is always the fear that Russia's problems will spur massive emigration, creating political and fiscal problems for Germany. Finally, in an Eastern European version of the Tequila Effect (see Argentina below), Polish and Czech investments will certainly suffer if Russia erupts.   <p>
 CHINA Rumors about 91-year-old Communist leader Deng Xiaoping's health circulate constantly, while China sits in vigil and the world wonders what will happen after his death. With that enormous uncertainty in mind, we again can expect to find a central bank working to curtail credit and rein in inflation. Like Alan Greenspan at the Federal Reserve Board, Zhu Rongji (former governor of the People's Bank of China) and current governor Dai Xianglong have tried to engineer a soft landing for China's economy. Zhu successfully slowed inflation from about 25 percent in 1994 to near 1995's target of 15 percent. The growth rate of the gross domestic product seems to be around 9 percent. (The Chinese government does not have a reliable data-collection system, but anecdotal evidence consistently suggests prices are rising more slowly than last year and that the economy has lost some steam.)   <p>
 Tight money has pinched state-owned enterprises, which make up 40 to 50 percent of GDP. Even the Chinese government acknowledges that about half these ventures lose money, so the true percentage is far higher. This means hundreds of millions of Chinese work for unprofitable companies, which presents the government with a dilemma. It must downsize to stanch this fiscal hemorrhaging, but if it does so, the sheer number of people thrown out of work would threaten the legitimacy of the government. The state factory problem multiplies when you consider that smaller firms, often ruled by local warlords, supply components to the larger enterprises.  <p>
 The banking system is in equally bad shape. Four banks make up around 80 percent of all lending, which is heavily influenced by Beijing's interest in certain industries and provinces. The big four are holding an estimated $88 billion in bad debts, lent at artificially low rates to keep the state enterprises afloat. This sum is roughly half the size of the U.S. savings and loan bailout of the early 1990s. But the U.S. economy is many times the size of China's.   <p>
 China, like the U.S. (and Japan), must decide who will pay for the coming bailout. I have little doubt the government will ease credit conditions in late 1995 or early 1996 to alleviate, but not solve, some of its economic problems. The political costs of closing factories and banks are just too great. Meanwhile, on November 6, shares of China's state enterprises that trade in Hong Kong fell by as much as 13 percent on fears that the People's Bank would jack up interest rates.   <p>
 With nearly a billion citizens, China affects the entire global economy. In particular, China now imports agricultural goods, so a good year for China's GDP could mean more exports for farmers around the world. Capital investment from the industrialized nations, all of which want early access to this huge market, has grown explosively from around $7 billion in1992, to $34 billion in 1994. The Japanese have seemed more intent on building new factories in China than at home, and U.S. firms from <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> to <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> to <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a> to <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a> can't wait to sell, or sell more, to the "middle kingdom."   <p>
 But while cheap consumer goods like cigarettes and soft drinks are likely to generate immediate profits, the outlook for capital-intensive industry is unclear, and the stock prices of these companies may come to reflect this uncertainty as their investment in China grows.   <p>
 MEXICO The great economist Joseph Schumpeter once said that economies sometimes can find a recession reinvigorating, like a cold shower. But the Mexican peso crash was more like drowning in a polluted river. It produced a 10.5 percent contraction in the second quarter of 1995 and a record number of bankruptcies. Even efficient firms can go out of business when short-term interest rates hit 45 percent.   <p>
 In 1996, with unemployment rising and his political mandate in doubt, President Ernesto Zedillo will be tempted to inflate the economy. In fact, without further foreign aid or domestic pump-priming, the economy is headed for, perhaps, 2 percent GDP growth in 1996 woefully inadequate for a country whose population is climbing rapidly and whose workers have seen only meager wage gains over the past 15 years.  <p>
 Meanwhile, the peso seems to be evaporating. Before its collapse in December 1994, it traded at about 3.5 to the U.S. dollar. By spring, the government thought it might be able to establish a stable trading band at around 6 pesos to the dollar. Right now, the government would be lucky to make 7.25 a credible, durable number. Finally, Mexico's recovery also requires a strong U.S. economy. A slowdown here, which many economists expect, could doom Mexico's chances of positive growth in 1996.   <p>
 ARGENTINA The Mexican peso devaluation debacle created a so-called Tequila Effect, a shock wave of investor disenchantment that depressed the stocks and bonds of all the other Latin American markets.   <p>
 The Tequila Effect hit Argentina particularly hard, causing a recession and unemployment of nearly 20 percent, up from 6 percent as recently as 1991. The Merval stock index began recoveringnicely during late July and early August, but it has since dipped sharply. This was a surprise to many analysts, who looked forArgentina to diverge from Mexico with its drastically different economic policies. Mexico's central bank, officially independent, remains under the influence of the finance ministry and the president, while Argentina, under Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo's "Convertibility Plan," directly links the supply of Argentine pesos to the supply of foreign reserves held by the central bank.   <p>
 After Mexico devalued its peso, Cavallo feared a run on his nation's banks. To forestall this, he offered to redeem Argentine pesos for U.S. dollars on a one-for-one basis, since each peso is effectively backed by a dollar in reserves (in fact, Cavallo exaggerated the extent of the backing). This convertibility arrangement boosted confidence in the currency but leaves Argentina at the mercy of foreigners to fund growth, since the bank can't print more pesos. There's the rub: When foreigners don't feel like investing in your country, and your country falls into recession, what can you do? Pray, pretend, and wait.   <p>
 That's been the Argentine policy since December 1994. Argentines have prayed for foreigners to come back in, at least to purchase floating-rate bonds paying around 15 percent. They have pretended that the economy was growing, with Cavallo insisting on a 3 percent growth rate in 1995, even as the numbers were rolling in on the negative side. And they have waited for the world economy to pick up, which would spur exports and capital inflows.   <p>
 So far, however, not much has worked, and in 1996 Argentina must pay the U.S. $10 billion in outstanding loans. In sum, Cavallo has developed a policy that creates great sympathy and credibility among foreigners he's a virtual poster boy for the International Monetary Fund but that doesn't help him or President Carlos Menemget the country back on its feet. The situation is complicated because Menem and Cavallo, longtime political rivals, seem to enjoy undercutting each other.   <p>
 Each time Cavallo has visited Wall Street, the analysts have been taken in by his charm and competence. But the luster is wearing off and, with it, so are the hopes for a good year in the Argentine market.  <p>
 BRAZIL Not all Latin economies are shrinking. Brazil was humming along too fast in the spring of 1995, creating inflation worries with first-quarter GDP growth over 10 percent. Consumers went on a buying spree, quickly dissipating a $10 billion trade surplus, but over the summer and fall, the economy slowed to a sustainable 5 to 6 percent growth rate.   <p>
 Why, then, has the stock market performed so miserably since September? First, the Tequila Effect. Second, the central bank may have squeezed the money supply too hard in order to strangle the double-digit growth of the first quarter. Retailers now have stockpiled inventory, bankruptcies have jumped, and jobless numbers are up in Sao Paulo. Third, the government raised import tariffs, causing domestic producers to raise prices. Fourth, nobody knows if President Henrique Fernando Cardoso has the power to push his free-market reforms through congress.  <p>
 This is the big issue for Wall Street. The smart money knows that the Brazilian economy is in pretty good shape, and that alone is quite an accomplishment. As recently as June 1994, Brazil's monthly inflation was 50 percent. Today it's down to around 1 percent. Still, investors want proof that Cardoso can convince congress to bust the state oil monopoly, reform the mining industry, open up financial services, and privatize more of Brazil's still huge public sector. Cardoso is a quiet, scholarly persuader and consensus seeker, but 1996 will show whether nice guys can finish first in Brazil.   <p>
 Overall, Latin America presents a mixed picture this year, particularly with the drag on the region from Argentina and Mexico. A good year would mean no calamities. Perhaps the headline for December31, 1996, will be "Narrow escape!"  <p>
 In 1995 U.S. investors reaped enormous gains amid a sluggish world economy. This performance will be tough to repeat. Our success was based on two key factors: the continuing fall in interest rates, and the competitiveness of U.S. firms stealing market shares around the world. Our exporters will still have the edge in 1996, though we can't expect interest rates to continue their march toward zero. It's shaping up as a sluggish year for big trading partners in the developed world, which could slow exports, at least until the second half. While the emerging markets could shift into dramatically higher growth rates, they standan equal or better chance of falling apart. In sum, families around the world just don't feel good about their job prospects or their spending plans. (Will our circus-like presidential election year lift or quash spirits?) It's a tough environment in which to be an optimist.   <p>
 Todd G. Buchholz is the president of the G7 Group Inc., an international economic-consulting firm, and the author of From Here to Economy(Dutton, 1995).  <p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, International Economy, International Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

