<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Lands of Disenchantment</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Lands of Disenchantment</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Lands of Disenchantment</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> LANDS OF DISENCHANTMENT   <p> By Walter Mead  <p> Is the emerging-markets boom over? Returns from investments in up-and-comers such as Mexico, Thailand, and Brazil have been lousy this year. Mexico is down 37 percent, in dollar terms, for the year (through early September), Brazil down 21 percent, and Thailand down 4 percent.  <p> But performance numbers like those don't signal the end of anything. In fact, they represent business as usual for the emerging markets. Investors in these markets are used to meltdowns, and to the brutal, hard months being balanced by torrid seasons of two-digit and even three-digit returns. In 1993, for example, Hong Kong was up 117 percent and Turkey up 220 percent.  <p> In the long run those who stayed with emerging markets made more money because of those extremes. Ride out the volatility, said the best investment gurus. A market crash is a buying opportunity. Those who listened, prospered. Investors, of course, behave like Pavlov's dog: Before long, every time the bell rang to announce a new emerging market, investors began drooling. For example, the Templeton Developing Markets fund saw a 678 percent increase in net assets in 1993 (from $180 million to $1.4 billion).  <p> But as difficult as it is to discern a trend when the month-to-month numbers show more ups and downs than a Coney Island roller coaster, I detect signs that the mad doctor is changing the nature ofthe experiment. First, volatility seems to be increasing. Strangely enough, the end of the Cold War may be to blame. Second, and more important, developing nations are becoming hostile to foreign portfolio capital. U.S.based mutual fund investors may in the future find it harder to put money into the most attractive markets. <p> At the end of the Cold War, many investors leapt to the conclusion that the world would be a peaceful, stable place now that it was no longer divided into two armed camps poised to annihilate each other. Today, that no longer looks like such a safe bet. When leadership struggles in China cloud the future, Hong Kong's stock market drops like a stone. When China tests missiles in Taiwan's neighborhood, stock markets swoon all over Asia. And well they should. A war there could wipe out all the paper profits investors have made over the last 20 years.   <p> This isn't just fantasy. It happens. In the 1920s, Western journalists gushed about Shanghai, the "city of the future," and Western investors poured money into China. The world's largest market! The giant of the future! You can't afford to miss it! What the Japanese didn't destroy, the Communists took. Investors lost every dime.  <p> Local wars have affected stock markets more than did the threat that the superpowers would turn the world into a radioactive cinder, maybe because it's hard to figure out a safe haven for money in a postapocalyptic world. And with the East/West balance of power no longer a restraint on the ambitions of client states, the outcome and extent of local wars are far more uncertain. The war in Bosnia, for example, is so intractable because Russia doesn't have nearly the clout with the Serbs that the old Soviet Union would have had.  <p> Still, investors will get used to this increase in volatility, given enough time. The more risk averse will leave emerging markets. Investors with stronger stomachs will demand higher rates of return to make up for the increased uncertainty.  <p> But investors will have a much harder time adapting to the second change in emerging-markets investing. Call it disenchantment risk. Emerging markets are not as interested in emerging as they used to be, and the governments of developing countries want foreign investors to pay a higher price to participate in their growth. Third-world countries and Eastern European nations are starting to realize that foreign portfolio investment can lead to chaos in their financial markets and economies.   <p> The recent Mexican crisis has played a major role in this seachange in thinking about foreign investment. It wasn't just U.S. investors who got a nasty shock when Mexico's stock market crashed. Companies throughout Mexico suddenly found themselves unable to raise capital at reasonable cost--or at all. The average Mexican saw his standard of living plummet.   <p> In Mexico, the loss of faith is palpable. The boom-and-bust cycle of the 1990s followed the boom and bust of the '80s, and the economy has been undergoing "reforms" since the debt crisis of 1982. During all that time, Mexico has faithfully, if slowly, heeded the advice of the United States and of international financial organizations like the International Monetary Fund. But the Mexican strategy--opening domestic-goods markets to spur competition, keeping the currency at a high level, and opening capital markets to attract investment--no longer looks very attractive.  <p> "We told you so," say the Chileans, who rejected this model after their economic crash in 1982. The Chileans never had much faith in this approach--since 1982, Chilean policy has been almost the opposite of Mexico's. The key is the currency. Mexico tried to keep its currency high to cut inflation, but the result was a gradual accumulation of risks that finally triggered a massive slide. The high, apparently stable value of the Mexican peso helped lower inflation. Foreign goods, made artificially cheap by the high peso, rushed into the country, forcing Mexican producers to compete with the world's best. As the high peso forced Mexican industry into a major restructuring, foreign capital poured in. <p> For a while, this strategy worked, and long-standing problemsseemed unimportant. Corruption, inefficiency, one-party rule: nobody cared. President Carlos Salinas de Gortari got himself elected to the board of directors of Dow Jones--where he still sits today, to the considerable embarrassment of the company's flagship publication, The Wall Street Journal.   <p> But fundamentally, this was a development strategy based on hot money, the easy-in, easy-out flows controlled by mutual fund managers and individual investors who can abandon a market with a phone call. The high peso exchange rate, supported by the government, contributed to a current-account deficit. (The current account is the net of exports minus imports plus investment income.) Mexico's prosperity therefore depended on a positive flow of investment capital. The amount of money foreigners invested in the country had to be greater than the total of the trade deficitand the amount Mexicans invested abroad.   <p> When the crash finally came, many observers blamed it on foreigners fleeing the Mexican market. In fact, the story was more complex. Initially, it was the flight of Mexican capital that caused the crisis. Big Mexican investors looked to the future of the peso, and they didn't like what they saw. They cashed out of Mexico and took their money elsewhere.   <p> And then the foreigners started to bail out. Mexico's peso and stock market collapsed, and the economy followed. Mexico's economy shrank by more than 10 percent from mid-1994 to mid-1995; there is more still to come. Meanwhile Mexico must now listen to the Monday-morning quarterbacks of the economic-policy world. The same people who used to praise Mexico and tout it as an example to other developing countries now can't say enough about how wrongheaded the Mexicans were and how much harder they've got to work before they genuinely manage to reform their economy.  <p> The lesson wasn't lost on developing and transitional countries. Dependence on hot money is bad, many have concluded.  <p> Take Hungary. Once it was the Eastern European darling of foreign investors, but after Mexico everybody took another look. With a serious current-account deficit balanced by inflows of hot foreign capital, Hungary suddenly looked like Mexico with goulash. Meanwhile, Hungarians began to have second thoughts about selling equity control of major enterprises to foreign interests. As disputes between Hungarian and foreign bidders mount, Hungary's once-promising privatization program has slowed to a crawl.  <p> Then there's Taiwan. Long under pressure to open its capital markets to foreign investors, Taiwan recently passed a law that ostensibly does just that. Foreign money-fund managers have been shocked to discover that the new law actually tightens key restrictions. More surprising still, Taiwan took this risky step while its market was weak. Keeping foreign investors happy just wasn't a priority.   <p> Brazil has also changed its ways. I was there last February, and I returned this August to a very different country. In order to avoid Mexico's fate, Brazil was taking strong steps both to close its current-account deficit (by protecting key industries like auto making) and to restrict the influx of foreign portfolio capital. President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, whose successful anti-inflation program and commitment to economic reform made him a hero to foreign money managers, recently announced plans to impose a 15 percent capital-gains tax on foreign portfolio investors.   <p> Other countries, including Russia, India, Cuba, and the Philippines, are examining whether rapidly opening their capital and goods markets is such a good idea. Sometimes for reasons of national pride, sometimes for economic reasons, policy makers in these countries urge more caution.   <p> Countries such as Brazil are switching to other development models. Many of these involve tight controls on foreign capital, and most can trace their roots back to the successful Pacific Rim economies of East Asia.   <p>  In the last generation, countries like Taiwan and Japan have moved from poverty to affluence with a policy mix that to a large extent is the opposite of what Mexico adopted in the 1980s. While Mexico welcomed foreign goods and foreign portfolio investment and kept its currency artificially high, these countries kept foreign goods out, zealously limited the role of foreign portfolio investment, and kept their currencies as cheap as possible against the dollar. Instead of relying on foreign portfolio investors, these economies generated the investment capital they needed through domestic savings. Savings rates in these countries show how this worked: In 1993, the savings rates in Japan and Taiwan were, respectively, 32.7 percent and 28 percent of gross domestic product. Compare this with the U.S. at 15.2 percent, Mexico at15.9 percent, and Argentina (another hot-money economy) at 16.5 percent. (This measure of savings, unlike the more commonly cited household savings rate, includes all corporate savings, investment in plants, equipment, etc.)  <p> Historically, countries have had another reason for wanting to control access to their capital markets. It wasn't just that they wanted security from the side effects of huge hot-money tides sloshing in and out of their economies; they also wanted national control of their national economies. The Japanese did not want the Americans to own the crown jewels of their economy. The South Koreans still don't want to see Japanese investors taking over the commanding heights of their economy.   <p> This motivation remains very strong--at least outside Japan, where there is no longer much fear that foreigners will buy up all of the country's stocks--and has produced some of the capitalist world's most restrictive investment policies. The American investor cannot call his broker to order a stock in Taiwan or in China today. Direct ownership of stock remains difficult for foreigners, and there are limits the equity stakes foreign investors can own.   <p> American mutual funds and their investors are likely to find the welcome distinctively chillier in many developing countries as the countries adopt this Pacific Rim strategy. The speed of the liberalization of capital markets in these countries will slow down; in some cases the liberalization process could actually move into reverse. And, to the chagrin of foreign investors and money managers, some of the most closed markets may be among the most attractive.   <p> In fact, this makes sense--from the standpoint of a developing country. If your policies and accomplishments make your country one of the most promising places in the world to invest, why shouldn't foreigners pay a premium to invest in your market? If your people are developing the skills to run their own world-class enterprises, and if they are saving enough to generate most of the new capital your industry needs, why shouldn't you ensure that control of local business remains in local hands?   <p> The old paradigm of economic development assumed that as more countries around the world developed, global capital markets would become more integrated. National governments would lose control of their economic policies as the international capital markets forced all countries to compete for scarce investment capital. But suppose high savings rates--as in East Asia--reduce the need of successful economies to import capital from abroad? In that case, economic development could lead to a new era of independent national capital markets with relatively high barriers to foreign portfolio investors.   <p> If that begins to happen, wise foreign portfolio investors will want to move to the sidelines. The only foreign economies that would need massive portfolio investment from abroad would be weak ones that could not rely on internal savings. Investors could do worse than to remember the classic investment advice of Groucho Marx: "Please accept my resignation," he wrote. "I don't care to belong to any club that will accept me as a member."  <p>  <p>Walter Mead is the Presidential Fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance: Tomas Matza.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, International Politics, International Economy
