	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Journey to the Center </b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The U.S. right and left would both be uncomforable if they truly understood why Chile's economy if booming.<p>By Walter Mead<p>It didn't take me long to lose my bearings in Chile. <p>I stepped out of a cab in the capital city, Santiago. Across the street I could see the presidential residence, still scarred from fighting during the 1973 coup. Looking up at a street sign, I realized I was in trouble.<p>I had asked the taxi driver in my best gutter Spanish to let me out at the corner of Teatinos and Alameda for an appointment at the foreign ministry. But here I was with just five minutes to spare, and I seemed to be at the corner of Teatinos and Avenida O'Higgins, an enormous street named, like almost everything large and impressive in Chile, for Bernardo O'Higgins, who liberated Chile from Spain in 1817. "Donde esta la Ministeria de Relaciones Extraneros?" I asked the military guards in front of the Presidential Palace. Helpfully, the guards pointed to all points of the compass.<p>I cursed the taxi driver, the wretched state of my Spanish, the baffling city, and, most of all, my own stupidity in assuming that I knew where I was going.<p>
As I passed the Plaza de Armas, again, I began to hunt for a pay phone, a sure sign of desperation in South America. The statue of Pedro de Valdivia, the Spanish conquistador who founded Santiago, caught my eye. Unlike his colleagues Corts and Pizarro, Valdivia never actually conquered the local indigenous tribes. After founding the city in 1541, he lived to see it reduced to a smoldering ruin. Valdivia himself was captured by his native opponents and dispatched by having molten gold poured down his throat.<p>Suddenly I heard my name. "Senor Mead?"<p>It was my contact at the foreign ministry, come down to look for me. As it turns out, Avenida O'Higgins is the official name of the street; Alameda is what everybody calls it. I had been wandering around in circles. <p>Chile has been baffling North Americans for a long time. Usually, it's our own fault. We lump the country together with the rest of Latin America. Like Valdivia, we know almost nothing about the locals. And we see everything as either black or white. <p>That's what happened to Amasa Delano, whose tale of self-deception inspired "Benito Cereno," a short story by Melville (and later an opera by Britten). In 1803 an American sealing ran into the Benito Cereno, a becalmed and bedraggled Spanish ship with a cargo of African slaves. The Americans offered the Spaniards provisions and sails, but the Spanish captain was strangely ungrateful--so much so that Delano, the Yankee captain, began to suspect that the captain intended to murder the Yankees in their sleep. The Americans discovered the truth only when the slaves, who had mutinied, attacked them by surprise. The slaves had kept the captain alive to sail them back to Africa.<p>In Melville's story, Delano was haunted for the rest of his life by his actions: He realized that his own assumptions about the natural order of things had blinded him to the possibility that the slave had become the master, and while he knew he had acted in self-defense in his bloody suppression of the revolt, he had also condemned the surviving slaves to a life of horror.<p>Contemporary Americans approach Chile with their own blinders. The country has become a counter in the continuing argument in this country between right and left about the proper role of government in an economy. In 1973 the United States supported a military coup against the freely elected Marxist government of Salvador Allende. The military regime, headed by Agusto Pinochet, restored order by torturing and killing its opponents.<p>But the Pinochet government, unlike, say, the similarly repressive and contemporaneous military regime in Argentina, also rebuilt the Chilean economy. It pioneered radical free-market policies in everything from telecommunications to public finance. Although Chile was hit badly--and the Pinochet regime deeply shaken--by a major economic crisis in 1982, over the last decade Chile has enjoyed an economic boom. Growth has averaged 6.3 percent for the past ten years. In 1990 Pinochet turned over power to an elected successor.<p>Free-market economists and policy gurus in the United States see the Pinochet dictatorship as a painful but necessary period of reform. Want to know how to "fix" Mexico? Look at Chile. Get the government out of the economy. Put a strong central bank in charge of creating a sound and unmanipulated currency. Privatize wherever possible. There are even lessons here for the United States, they argue. The Chileans have recently privatized their old-age pension system; wouldn't something similar solve the Social Security crisis in the United States?<p>But I couldn't shake the tale of poor Amasa Delano as I listened to these experts and their opponents. I wondered whether, once again, we North Americans were seeing Chile only in terms of our own domestic categories of white and black. I wondered whether, in our anxiety to settle our domestic political battles over the role of government in the U.S. economy, we had again misinterpreted Chile.<p>To understand Chile and Chilean economics, start with the giant open-pit copper mine at Chuquicamata--the largest man-made hole in the ground in the world. Like much of the American West, Chile has had an economy based on mining for the past hundred years, with booms, busts, and violent social protests exploding with the discovery of new deposits, the exhaustion of old ones, and every swing in international commodity prices.<p>Chile's most important mines lie in the vast deserts of the north. Imagine an American West without the fertile fields of coastal California--one where the waves of the Pacific break directly on the dry sands of Death Valley. And then think drier, a lot drier.
To get to Chuquicamata, I set out from Antofagasta, an important port city in northern Chile that once belonged to Bolivia. The cold Pacific currents create a rich fishery offshore, but they also block any eastward flow of moisture. The mountains behind the city provide rich mineral deposits, but they cut off any stray moisture from the Atlantic. The resulting desert--the Atacama--is the driest spot on earth.<p>Nitrates, once used both as a fertilizer and as an ingredient in gunpowder, first made this region a cockpit of international politics. British investors, interested in exploiting the region's rich deposits and alarmed at the unstable, xenophobic policies of Bolivia, tacitly supported Chile's annexation of the region in the 187981 War of the Pacific. Nitrate mining, largely controlled by the British, boomed after the Chilean conquest--until German chemists, cut off from natural nitrate by the British naval blockade, learned to make synthetic replacements during World War I.<p>Fortunately for Chile, the copper boom started just as nitrate mining went bust. Huge copper discoveries early in the 20th century led to the development of the largest copper reserves anywhere and what remains Chile's largest industry. Mining at Chuquicamata, now a half mile deep, two and a half miles across, and a mile and a half wide, began in 1917.<p>As I wandered among the huge ore-crushing machines and watched enormous buckets of molten copper being poured into molds, I realized how much of Chile's future will be shaped by its past. This single copper mine still produces 20 percent of Chile's total export earnings. With huge untouched reserves, Chile will be a major copper producer for the foreseeable future.<p>For almost a century, Chilean miners battled foreign mining companies--often U.S.--over control of the wealth that came out of this ground. The Chilean government, dependent on foreign financiers for its capital, usually sided with the mining companies. In 1907, for example, hundreds of miners and their relatives were killed by government forces after a long, bitter strike.<p>
For most of the 20th century this logic of confrontation has determined Chilean politics. Many Chileans viewed foreign investors as cynical, ruthless exploiters; the Chilean bankers and politicians who worked closely with foreign capital were seen as Benedict Arnolds willing to oppress their own people to keep their high-paid jobs. The country's economic elite, on the other hand, believed that giving in to the economic and political demands of the poor would ruin the country. Desperately and without success, some politicians, most notably the Christian Democrats, tried to create a "third way."<p>Chuquicamata played a central role in the most recent reenactment of this confrontation. In 1970, when the Socialist party candidate Salvador Allende was elected by a minority (36 percent of the vote in a three-way race) and tried to put through a radical program that would have given Chile a Cuban-style economic system, one of his first acts was to nationalize the Chuquicamata mine. During the Pinochet years, the military turned one of the ghost towns that had housed militant miners into a concentration camp for political prisoners. Today that town has returned to the ownership of its ghosts. As I toured it on foot, passing the parade ground, the theater, the barracks where both miners and prisoners had lived, I could make out the graffiti left on the crumbling walls. More than 1,000 people were killed in Pinochet's coup, and thousands more were arrested and tortured while Pinochet was in power.<p>Today, 22 years after the coup, the mine still belongs to the national government. Far from selling off this crown jewel of Chilean industry or returning it to the original owners, the military has reserved 10 percent of the state copper earnings for its own permanent budget.<p>Codelco, the state company that runs the mine, is much better managed than the average state-owned enterprise in South America. The payroll isn't nearly as bloated with make-work jobs. Staff layoffs have cut 7,000 jobs from a payroll of 27,000 since 1990, and restructuring continues. Mature mines like Chuquicamata are usually less efficient than newer ones, yet at 64 cents per pound and falling, Chuquicamata's costs are well below the international price of copper. The mine's managers know that it must remain competitive on the world market.<p>I noticed the same pragmatic mix elsewhere in Chile. Government-sponsored television ads call on Chileans to make the elimination of poverty a national priority at the same time that Chile's technocrats and businessmen preach that the free market can transform Chile.<p>After decades of class warfare, has the "Concertacion"--the five-party coalition that now governs Chile, led by the same Christian Democrats whose pre-Pinochet quest for a "third way" ended in costly failure--finally found that middle path?<p>Just as the mine at Chuquicamata stands for the old Chile, the telephone symbolizes the new. The innocent-looking pay phones and hotel telephones of Latin America have broken many a North American heart over the years. In my travels in South America, I've repeatedly had to abandon the phone in my hotel and do what the natives do: go to telephones at the post office and stand in line.<p>Chile these days reminds me of home--that wonderful country where the phone companies send me checks so I'll change my service. Billboards on the road from the airport are plastered with the salvos of a good old-fashioned price war among telephone carriers. International telephone calls are easy to make and inexpensive. Chile may have the cheapest international telephone rates anywhere in the world outside the U.S.<p>It is all, explained Jorge Rosenblut, a bearded and energetic young official in the Chilean telecommunications ministry, part of the government's strategy to gain a competitive advantage for Chile in international markets. Telephone service is a basic cost of doing business; if the nation lowers telephone costs and makes new lines easy to get, business will boom.<p>The classic Latin American approach to fixing the phone service would be to invest government funds in the telephone monopoly. In Chile, the government provides occasional subsidies and favorable deals for telephone companies that meet social needs--such as providing service in rural areas--but generally restricts its role to creating a favorable regulatory climate for private companies. Competition does the rest.<p>For Rosenblut, this is only the start. Telecommunications, he told me, is a linchpin of Chile's broader modernization strategy. In the coming "third wave" service and information-based economy, Chile hopes to position itself as a communications hub for Latin America. With the government pushing a new transpacific cable to improve links to Asia and with Chile already handling calls from neighboring countries with inadequate telephone services, Rosenblut said, Chile is poised to serve as a "hinge" between Latin America and Asia in the emerging new era.<p>It was all visionary and exciting, but I was somewhat perplexed. Third wave, competition, a level playing field--those all sounded like Newt Gingrich. But the government targeting telecommunications as a crucial future industry? That sounded like--dare I speak the words--industrial policy. In a country that had become a potent international symbol of laissez-faire economics, Rosenblut's ministry was picking winners, a strategy derided by free-market economists.<p>Well, I thought, what else could I expect from a bureaucrat? Things would be different at that traditional home of free-market orthodoxy, the stock exchange. Founded in 1893, the Santiago Stock Exchange has enjoyed some stellar returns lately--notably in 1991, when the general index rose 166 percent in a year. Surely I wouldn't find any critique of the free market there.<p>
Pablo Yrarrazaval, the chairman of the exchange, wasn't having a good day when I arrived. Stock markets throughout Latin America were in a free fall as a result of capital flight following the Mexican crash. The Chilean financial markets were near panic as I sipped my hot sweet coffee in an office cushioned by Yrarrazaval's collection of Oriental rugs.<p>Chile's investment policies, as Yrarrazaval explained them, are simple but, once again, hard to classify. If you are a foreign direct investor, Chile wants you badly. New factories build up the country, and as Yrarrazaval and others reminded me, if foreign direct investors panic, they can't take the factory with them. <p>On the other hand, Chile views portfolio investors, such as U.S.run mutual funds, with a certain suspicion. Hot money can pour in from abroad in good times and pour out in bad, doing damage either way. Too much foreign money in a small country like Chile can change the supply and demand equation for the local currency and drive the value of the currency up so far that the country's exports are no longer competitive. On the other hand, if foreigners panic, hot money can leave the country even faster than it came in. Just look at Mexico.<p>So a foreign investor is free to put money into the Chilean stock market, but that money has to stay in the country for a year. This doesn't affect long-term investors, but it does discourage speculators. The country can afford to be choosy now. In 1994 almost $5 billion in foreign investment came into the country. This all seems eminently sensible, but it isn't laissez-faire.<p>Nor, it turns out, is the vaunted Chilean experiment in privatizing the country's old-age pension system. Sometimes mentioned as a model for reform of the U.S. Social Security system, the Chilean private pension system has been praised as an example of how to get government out of the pension business. Instead of paying Social Security tax to the government and then drawing a pension in retirement, Chilean workers are required to invest a fixed percentage of their pay in one of a number of licensed pension companies. These companies act as money managers, investing the savings of Chilean employees in stocks and bonds.<p>It looks like another retreat by the Chilean state out of the business of managing the economy, but once again initial impressions are misleading. The pension funds have to be regulated, Yrarrazaval explained; otherwise funds might take too many risks and go bankrupt--leaving thousands of people with no income in retirement. Most of these regulations are commonsensical and might well be warmly welcomed by investors in U.S. mutual funds: limiting the types of bonds pension funds can buy, restricting their stock purchases to well-established blue-chip companies, and so forth. But most crucially, the pension funds must invest no less than 90 percent of their assets in Chilean stocks and bonds. <p>From a portfolio manager's perspective, this is a foolish regulation; it actually increases the chance of a fund crash. Few money managers would recommend a portfolio that put 90 percent of assets in Chile and only 10 percent in the rest of the world.<p>But what is bad for individuals can be good for the group. The large pool of captive savings represented by the investment in Chilean pension funds can be used for the expansion of Chilean businesses. Furthermore, this pool of savings gives Chile some insurance against capital flight. Rich Latin Americans are notoriously quick to get their money out of a country when trouble threatens. The regulations of the Chilean pension system deny poor Chileans this safety valve, but by ensuring that some capital will remain in the country they also insulate Chile from the worst effects of capital flight. A Marxist might say that the Chilean elite is using the savings of the poor to safeguard the wealth of the rich--and the Marxist would be right. On the other hand, the Chilean pension system also helps protect the jobs of the poor by cushioning the effects of economic shocks.<p>The more I learned about the Chilean economy, the more I felt it reflected a careful strategic plan rather than market forces. An interview with one of the chief architects of the contemporary Chilean economy, Roberto Zahler, president of the Central Bank, cemented that conviction.
According to Zahler, 1982 was a watershed in modern Chilean economic history. That year the country, which had adopted a free-wheeling financial system influenced by the monetarist and free-market teachings of the Chicago school of economics, plunged into a deep depression. A set of policies that might have worked well for a developed country with control over its own currency instead produced a dependence on foreign portfolio investment and a radically overvalued currency.<p>After a period of indecision and debate, Chile's economic strategists moved decisively away from these doctrinaire free-market theories to something much more like the economic model practiced in East Asian countries such as Taiwan, one that stresses control over capital flows, discourages domestic consumption, and systematically promotes exports and savings.<p>For example, while Mexico, Argentina, and Brazil in recent years have all tried to keep their currencies at high levels, Chile has deliberately chosen to push the value of its peso down, keeping Chilean exports competitive in international markets. At the same time, Chile's central bank works to prevent the domestic economy from overheating by keeping domestic interest rates high. <p>The results so far have been more than encouraging. "We may not be a tiger yet," one businessman told me, referring to the economic tigers of East Asia, "but we are already a jaguar."<p>Santiago, a city of 5.5 million people at the foot of the Andean mountains, stretches out for miles like a Los Angeles without freeways. To get around, I spent a lot of time in taxis. My drivers saw a very different economy than was visible from the offices of the central bank. In fact, they sputtered with rage when I told them what I was hearing from economists and government officials. In a country that less than 30 years ago tore itself apart because it couldn't agree on an economic contract, that anger is important.<p>
"Look at me," said one. "I work 50 hours a week to support my family, and still we don't manage. I used to be a university professor!"<p>A tourist in New York could get the same comment from one of that city's cabbies, to be sure, but even in the city's poorest areas he wouldn't see slums like those in Chilean cities. Some of the housing I saw was on a par with the shanties I'd seen outside Johannesburg and Cape Town. Unpainted shanties leaned against one another at crazy angles; half-naked children ran barefoot in filthy, unpaved streets; families picked through piles of burning trash at the city dump.<p>In the heady days of the Allende regime, the Communist party of Chile had organized the discontent of the have-nots and moved inches from power. Pinochet's years of repression never managed to destroy the Chilean communists, but the return of democracy to Chile and the collapse of the Soviet model in Europe have driven the party into the political wilderness.<p>But Jorge Insunza, a harmless-looking, chain-smoking member of the Central Committee, insisted that his party's eclipse was not permanent. The days of protest and revolution are not over. Chile, Insunza told me, remains dependent on the world market, and the world market remains vulnerable to chaos and catastrophe. Listening to him, I thought back to my conversation with some bitter university students a day earlier. "It gets better for the rich," said one, "but for us there is nothing." If enough Chileans feel this way, then Insunza is right and the days of protest and upheaval will return.<p>In the bad old days, all it took was a collapse in the world market price of copper to plunge the Chilean economy into depression. The technocrats of Santiago are determined to create a new Chilean economy based on telecommunications, agricultural exports, and tourism. They talked glibly about Chile as the "telecommunications hub" for Latin America--but exactly how many jobs would it create?<p>I drove out one afternoon to the Santa Rita vineyard, about an hour south of Santiago. Here I ate and drank the fruits of the new Chilean economy. For lunch I had Chilean salmon from the farms along the southern coast, exquisite and delicate fruits from Chile's famous orchards, and an impressive selection of Santa Rita wines. Winery executives told me they were about to introduce new, premium varieties to the U.S. market. <p>For the moment, the Chilean glass seemed half full. Chile can join the trading bloc created by the North American Free Trade Agreement and, unlike Mexico, would experience the benefits of lower tariffs for its exports without a reverse flood of U.S. products. The country's small size and underpriced currency would see to that.<p>A day later and much farther south the wine of the new Chilean economy turned sour. Like the Santa Rita vineyard, resorts such as the Hotel Explora in the far south are a key part of the new Chilean economy, too. With its soaring mountains capped by pristine snow and a landscape full of exotic animals, Chile has the raw materials for a thriving tourist industry.<p>On my first morning at the resort I asked another guest, a distinguished-looking Brazilian, what he did for a living.
"Oh," he said, "I'm mostly retired now. I grow orchids. I suppose I'm a bit fanatical about them. Over the years I've collected 20,000 varieties."<p>A hotel can do a good business attracting clients like this. He probably found the empty Chilean mountains a refreshing break from the crowds in the Swiss Alps. Besides, the undervalued Chilean peso made this vacation a bargain.<p>But the Hotel Explora, for better or worse, will never attract the crowds of a DisneyWorld or even a St. Moritz. How many people would do what I had done to reach the Explora? The flight from Santiago to Punta Arenas--on the Pacific side of the Strait of Magellan--was a rough and bumpy four hours' ride. From the airport to the hotel was another six hours across, mostly on dirt roads.<p>Chile is not really on the way from anywhere to anywhere. Enthusiastic chamber of commerce types rant on about how Santiago is inevitably destined to become a managerial and financial-services center for Latin America. But nobody could ever tell me why Santiago was a better location for the Latin American office of a multinational than, say, Miami.<p>The boosters, it seems to me, are wrong. Chile isn't going to become the Germany or the Japan of South America. Chile today is a moderately sized Latin American country with an economy one eighth that of Brazil and one fifth that of Argentina. Despite its remarkable progress, Chile cannot suddenly transcend its history. It will still depend on its mines and its natural resources. Its overall level of prosperity will, to a large extent, be controlled by external forces. And the aspirations of Chile's poor will still run up against the demands of international investors for profits.<p>But Chile doesn't have to become Japan or an international telecommunications hub for its people to live a better life. The horror of the Pinochet years--and the twin failure of the extremes of free-market and command-market economics--have produced a remarkable consensus behind an economic system that, while borrowing from many models, is uniquely Chilean. No Latin American country I have visited has such a well-organized partnership between business and government; no Latin American government that I have talked to has thought as deeply about its economic reforms. Few countries anywhere have thought as deeply about the social purpose of their financial markets.<p>North Americans seem to vacillate between euphoria and despair when they consider the future of South America. At one moment these countries all have learned the lessons of the marketplace and represent amazing opportunities; the next they're all corrupt casino economies trapped in boom-and-bust cycles.<p>Chile, like each of the other countries on the continent, is unique, a product of its own geography and history. And, at the moment, Chile's glass is both half full and half empty--this promising, fast-growing economy cannot possibly fulfill all the dreams of its boosters, but then maybe it does not need to. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, International Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
