<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Get Rhythm</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Get Rhythm</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Wall Street tells a great story about emerging markets like Brazil. Experience tells a different one.<p>By Walter Mead<p>Forget poring over charts and graphs. throw those economic statistics from the ministries of trade and finance into the trash. Wall Street research on emerging markets? Who needs it? To invest successfully in Brazil, learn to samba.<p>This idea came to me in February as I stood high in the stands of Rio de Janeiro's Sambadrome and watched the city's premier samba schools march past as part of the pre-Lenten carnival madness. As naked dancers on elaborate floats gyrated to the thunderous rhythm of the drums and the Brazilians around me performed jubilant sambas and bellowed out the lyrics to their favorite carnival songs, I realized I was learning an important financial lesson. Investment markets in Brazil work more or less like carnival. Brazilians understand the rhythms of their national economy, and foreign investors who don't feel the beat usually stumble.<p>I could see this in the crowds below me. It isn't hard to spot the foreigners during carnival. Partly it's skin color. By carnival everybody in Brazil who wasn't born black sports a dark and luxurious tan, while most foreign tourists are either fish-belly white or boiled-lobster red. The Brazilians, somehow familiar with even the newest carnival sambas, twist to the music. The foreigners mumble and shuffle.<p>Foreigners who want to make money investing in Brazil don't literally need to take dance lessons, of course, but they do need to learn how to follow the unique beat of a specific national economy. (And that advice goes as well for investors in Thailand, the Philippines, and Turkey, among other markets.) Almost no one on Wall Street called the indiscriminate selling panic that swept through the Latin American stock markets last February and March__just as almost no one warned investors during the overheated panic buying of 1994 (though I can't resist noting that I did warn Worth readers against the Latin America boom in September 1993). And I think I know why. Wall Street gurus were so busy analyzing the global macroeconomic trends that they forgot to immerse themselves in the details of day-to-day life in countries far from New York City. A smart investor could have learned more about the reality of the Brazilian economy__and still can today__by buying a coconut on Copacabana Beach than by reading volumes of Wall Street reports.<p>Before you dismiss this as the kind of hindsight so often passed off as investment advice, let me tell you what I learned about Brazil on my latest trip. In February 1995, the green coconuts on sale at the kiosks on the beach cost almost U.S.$2 each; the Brahma Beer was $1.20. So what, you say? Well, the last time I'd been in Rio, in 1992, the coconuts cost just 50 cents and the beers were a quarter. In dollar terms, the price of coconuts was four times higher than in 1992.<p>What had changed between 1992 and 1995? Had the Brazilian economy taken off? Were the shoe-shine boys four times better off? Were the taxi drivers moving up to First World standards of living? <p>Well, no. Brazil was as poor as ever last winter. Little kids still mooched leftover food at the beachside restaurants. Crippled beggars still hung out at the busy intersections. The hotel maids still lived in the favelas__the squalid slums of Rio.<p>But on my previous visits, the Brazilian price structure had been normal for a poor country. Services provided by Brazilians__shoe shines and taxi rides__were cheap, and so were goods produced in Brazil for sale in Brazil. But anything imported was expensive: Levi's jeans cost more in Brazil than in New York. In 1995, imported goods and machinery were still expensive__but domestically produced goods and services weren't cheap. In dollar terms, a shoe shine in Rio cost the same as in New York. Something was out of whack.<p>A Brazilian, of course, would have understood this instinctively, even though I didn't. In an effort to overcome Brazil's chronic and crazy inflation, the government was running a massive currency scam. It had abolished Brazil's old and worthless currency and replaced it with a shiny, overvalued new one. Brazil's real__a new currency introduced after previous currencies such as the cruzado, the cruzeiro, and the cruzado novo had all inflated to worthlessness and fallen out of circulation__was valued last winter at the insanely unrealistic price of U.S.$1.20 to one real. Hence $2 coconuts. Hence also the soaring prices of shares on the So Paulo and Rio stock exchanges.<p>This kind of exchange-rate madness costs money to sustain. Foreigners who hold reals rush to sell them, both because they get a lot of dollars when they do and because they're not sure how long this favorable price will last. If no one bought reals, the price would fall and the government's domestic inflation policy would lie in ruins. So the government has to buy its currency if no one else will.<p>When the new currency was introduced in mid-1994, Brazil had $40 billion in foreign-exchange reserves__enough by far to defend the value of the real. But while the overpriced currency and tariff reductions did keep the lid on domestic inflation, they took a toll on the country's balance of payments. As the overvalued currency made imports relatively cheap for Brazilians and made Brazilian exports more expensive abroad, Brazil's balance of payments swung into deficit, and foreign reserves began to dwindle.<p>Clearly, the real would have to come down. Anybody who had bought a coconut recently would know that. But when and how? As I sipped my caipirinas by the beach (financial journalism is a dirty job, but someone has to do it), I discovered part of the answer: Devaluation would begin after the foreign tourists, who were now exchanging dollars at a rate of $1.20 to the real, had gone home from carnival. In fact, the Brazilians devalued the real soon after the last tourists had taken their hangovers north.<p>This one example illustrates an important principle. Scenarios of inflation and currency devaluation of this magnitude don't run through the heads of people about to put money into U.S. markets, nor should they. Brazil, on the other hand, has a history of currency manipulation, inflation, and shock therapy. Between the 1940s and the 1990s, rampant inflation__often as high as 2,000 percent a year__forced the Brazilians to drop 12 zeroes from their currency. In other words, it took 1,000,000,000,000 cruzeiros of the 1940s to buy one real of the 1990s.<p>Rich Brazilians know this history. They know that Brazilian money in their pockets and Brazilian stocks in their investment portfolios are susceptible to sudden and irrational changes in value. Over decades and generations, they have mastered the art of dealing with chronic economic instability.<p>U.S. investors are accustomed to markets and currencies with very different rules. The U.S. hasn't had this kind of instability since the 19th century, and the models of investment risk that all U.S.based investors carry around in their heads are based on our own national economic rhythms.<p>It doesn't help that U.S.based investors approach markets such as Brazil wearing the blinders of currently fashionable economic jargon. During the last few years, Wall Street has been telling investors that they haven't been buying shares of companies in Brazil or Argentina or Mexico. Instead they've been buying pieces of a beautiful story: the Emerging Markets Scenario.<p>The narrative is simple. Latin America's poverty was the result of bad economic policies. These included restrictions on imports, overregulation of private capital flows, inefficient state-owned industries, rigid labor markets, and other consequences of too much state intervention in the economy. Now, however, say the gurus on Wall Street, Latin American leaders, having learned from the mistakes of the past, are replacing bad, statist policies with good, free-market policies. Once the new policies are in effect, these economies will gradually come to resemble those in the U.S. and Europe.<p>But this is just a story, and if you doubt that, remember that not so long ago we didn't talk about emerging markets at all. Instead we called these countries underdeveloped. The economists of underdevelopment theory used to contrast the countries at the periphery of the capitalist system__like, say, Haiti and Brazil__with countries at the core, like France and the United States. Core countries progressed through stages of industrialization and modernization to the affluent consumer democracy found today in Western Europe and the United States. Peripheral countries didn't. Their economies and their political systems were stuck in backwardness. Just as the American South remained dependent for decades on cotton and tobacco, so too were countries like Brazil doomed by their dependence on raw materials and agriculture.<p>Underdevelopment theory, unlike the current way of thinking about these countries, didn't assume that a country like Brazil could simply reform itself into the First World. It emphasized how difficult it is for a country that had received its capitalism from abroad to control its own economic fate.<p>Take Brazil. First valued by the Portuguese for its mineral wealth, Brazil ultimately developed into a sugar colony. Brazil's planters imported slaves from Africa and sold sugar to Europe. When sugar prices began to fall, Brazil found new crops__rubber and coffee__to sell on world markets, but the pattern was always the same. Like most underdeveloped countries, Brazil sold raw materials and imported manufactured goods. And the world market in which Brazil traded was dominated by foreign countries__by Portugal and Spain in the early colonial period, then by Great Britain in the 19th century, and finally by the U.S.<p>Underdeveloped countries cannot control their economies like developed market economies do. In countries like the United States, Germany, and Japan, central banks have enormous powers to control short-term interest rates and to influence long-term ones. Other branches of the governments in developed market economies set fiscal policy in ways calculated to enhance domestic prosperity. Brazil isn't this lucky. International economic developments__especially developments in the U.S. economy__overshadow most decisions made by Brazilian institutions. When the Fed raises interest rates in the U.S., rates rise in Brazil__and, often, the stock market falls. When U.S. mutual funds and other investors decide Brazil is the next Taiwan, they flood the country with capital, producing a boom, which comes to a crashing halt when international capital flows out to the next hot spot.<p>The result is that both policy and economic conditions tend to lurch from one extreme to the next in Brazil__and in many other underdeveloped economies. Governments don't have the luxury to pursue moderate, long-term policies; they must react to sudden external shocks. Chronic inflation is one very common response to this situation; so is alternating between closed, protectionist economic strategies and free trade. Throughout Latin America, policy has swung between protectionism and free trade; last winter's turmoil in international currency markets forced both Brazil and Argentina to move toward a less open, more protectionist stance. No Brazilian or Argentine would assume this is a permanent condition.<p>Patient investors with the time and money to investigate local conditions and with strong stomachs for risk and long time horizons can do well in these markets. Very well. But investors who don't learn how to dance to the pulse-pounding beat of Brazil__or the very different rhythm of any other emerging market__run much higher risks than they realize. Over time, tone-deaf outsiders will underperform insiders in an underdeveloped economy. That is the Golden Rule of Latin American investing. Samba lessons, anyone?
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 
Walter Mead is the Presidential Fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance: Adam Feibelman.<p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

