<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Think Locally, Act Globally</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Think Locally, Act Globally</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Think Locally, Act Globally</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>THINK LOCALLY, ACT GLOBALLY<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>To maximize long-term performance, an investment portfolio must be globally diversified, with at least 20 percent foreign exposure. We've said this many times in these pages, and our reason for doing so is pretty basic: Over the long haul, the world economy is simply going to grow faster than the U.S.'s. The only way to take advantage is to participate.<p>One way to do this, of course, is to own foreign stocks--buying them either directly or through mutual funds. This is decidedly not a risk-free strategy, as recent events in Mexico and some Asian markets have underscored yet again.<p>An altogether different approach is to acquire stocks in U.S. companies that do business either in foreign lands or with foreign partners. This option has been eclipsed amid the global-investing craze of the last several years. To this day, in fact, most asset-allocation models, including those at private banks, count all U.S. stocks as 100 percent domestic investments, regardless of the amount of revenue or assets from foreign operations.<p>Nevertheless, more than 200 companies among the Standard & Poor's 500 get at least 20 percent of their revenues from exports or overseas operations. By buying the right ones, an investor can build a portfolio that, for all practical purposes, is as global as that of an investor who owns a mix of international stocks.<p>Such an all-domestic "global" portfolio also has a number of advantages, including minimum exposure to foreign stock market risk, reduced currency risk, accounting under U.S. standards, and, in some cases, lower taxes.<p>Several money managers--like Edward Bousa, a manager in Putnam's basic-value equity-fund group--are putting new emphasis on the concept of investing globally through U.S. stocks. Bousa believes the strategy has become more attractive because so many U.S. companies are now in a position to compete effectively worldwide, having raised quality standards and lowered costs in recent years. He also notes that U.S. companies continue to be superb marketers and technological leaders. Adds Madhav Dhar, head of emerging markets at Morgan Stanley: "The [global economic] revolution is a consumer one, not a producer one. Don't underestimate an emerging market's consumers and overestimate its producers." In other words: Buying shares of companies in foreign markets may not always be the best way to play.<p>By their nature, multinational companies also offer their investors certain buffers against market gyrations through things like currency-risk management and international tax planning. A multinational can react quickly to global opportunities and can shift investment levels if business conditions deteriorate. "If you're Colgate and you're having a problem in Mexico, you can take your assets and put them into Taiwan in a heartbeat," says Bousa. "A Mexican toothpaste producer just has to stay put"-- with its investors presumably suffering the consequences.<p>We asked Bousa--whose funds include Putnam Managed Income, <a name="FUND:PGEOX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PGEOX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>George Putnam Fund of Boston</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:PEYAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PEYAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Putnam Equity Income</b></a>--to put together a sample portfolio of seven U.S. stocks that would give an investor a substantial degree of global diversification. His choices are shown in the table below.<p>As a group, the stocks in Bousa's portfolio get 47 percent of their revenue from overseas sales and operations. They also represent a combination of what Bousa describes as "the safety of your home market as well as a once-in-a-generation opportunity for U.S. companies to grow overseas." All seven are also among the leaders in their fields, at home and abroad. For instance, Colgate is the second-ranked seller of toothpaste in the U.S. (behind Procter & Gamble) and No. 1 in toothpaste overseas, and has overall annual growth of 15 percent abroad. <p>Bousa also believes each of the seven stocks are attractively valued now. "If you buy 100 shares of each, you can get the entire portfolio for less than $40,000," he says. "The companies provide good growth rates, respectable dividend yields, and good market positions in the U.S. and overseas." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
