<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Why Fear Cuba?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Why Fear Cuba?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Why Fear Cuba?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Experts<p>WHY FEAR CUBA?
We guarantee billions in loans for Mexico. At the same time we force ordinary Cubans to live on $5 a month.<p>By Walter Mead<p>It would make a great Jeopardy question. "Latin America for $100, Alex." And the answer is, "The currency of this Spanish-speaking neighbor of the United States recently tumbled. But despite mounting international debts and a domestic economic crisis, efforts at political reform have been frustrated by the resistance of entrenched members of the ruling party. So many of its citizens have fled its poverty that immigration from this country has become a burning political issue in the U.S."<p>Forget about returning as defending champion, however, if you said, "What is Mexico?" The country I have in mind is Cuba.<p>Not that the mistake isn't natural. For example, both neighbors of the United States are suffering from declining standards of living, and the regimes in each use nostalgia for the revolutionary past to cling to power.<p>And yet, despite these similarities, the United States pursues radically different policies toward the two countries. In the case of Mexico, U.S. policy for the past ten years has worked to promote stability and prosperity. Forget the human-rights abuses, we have said. Forget the widespread corruption, the rigged elections, the murders of political opponents. None of these matter. The No. 1 U.S. goal in Mexico is political stability__and we have decided it is in our self-interest to promote the prosperity necessary for that stability, even if it means putting U.S. taxpayers' credit behind the peso. The alternative is to accelerate the flow of Mexicans looking for work in El Norte.<p>Contrast this with our Cuba policy. Not only does the United States look on with indifference at Cuba's economic crisis; our policy is to do everything we can to wreck Cuba's economy and destabilize the government.<p>Why isn't the sauce for the Mexican goose also sauce for the Cuban gander? And, for that matter, why has the United States been willing to defer democratic progress for the sake of economic growth in Mexico (as well as South Korea, Taiwan, China, and even Vietnam) while insisting on democratic progress as a precondition for trade with Cuba? I think that riddle is best answered by looking at the emerging postcold war world order and the legacy of more than a century of U.S. policy toward Latin America.<p>Now, I don't believe that all of Cuba's economic problems are our fault. Quite the contrary. On a recent trip to Cuba, I saw the same structural problems created by 35 years of central planning that I've seen in Eastern Europe. Too many of its factories produce things nobody wants, for example.<p>Cuban president Fidel Castro bet the ranch on a trading relationship with the Soviet Union and its Warsaw Pact allies. For a while, the bet paid off handsomely. The Soviet Union lavished subsidies and credits on Castro's Cuba. Soviet importers paid more for Cuban sugar than prevailing world market prices and offered subsidized oil in exchange. Cuba got so much oil from the Soviet Union that it was able to earn extra money by selling the surplus. <p>This arrangement worked reasonably well for much of the last generation, and fortunately, unlike some of the other recipients of Soviet largesse, the Cubans invested some of their money well. Even today, Cuba's health and educational levels are far higher than those of Latin American countries at a similar level of development. At 10 per 1,000 live births, Cuba's infant-mortality rate is lower than the rates in Detroit, Poland, and South Korea. The literacy rate is 99 percent, compared with 90 percent in Mexico and 81 percent in Brazil.<p>But Soviet subsidies also severely distorted Cuba's economy. Consider the sugar industry. To raise productivity, Cuba decided to mechanize its sugar industry during the 1970s. Unfortunately for Cuba, that made the industry more dependent on imported oil and spare parts. When the USSR collapsed, Cuba lost much of its ability to earn hard currency. With imported oil, fertilizer, and spare parts in short supply, the sugar harvest collapsed. Sugar production in Cuba fell from a peak of 8.4 million tons raw value in 198990 to an estimated 4 million in 199394. Per capita gross domestic product is estimated to have fallen from $3,125 in 1983 to $1,684 in 1993.<p>Cuba has responded to this crisis with some of the measures that U.S. experts have recommended for Eastern Europe. Cuba has tried to replace its former Soviet markets with increased trade with Western Europe, Latin America, Canada, and Japan. It has identified tourism and biomedicine as industries where it believes it can be competitive and has supported them with generous credits. Tourism arrivals are up from 225,000 in 1988 to more than 540,000 in 1993, and Cuban biomedical products such as a meningitis B vaccine are now internationally competitive.<p>The regime has also opened the door to private enterprise. Foreign investors can now retain in excess of 50 percent of the equity in joint ventures and repatriate profits. Private markets have made more goods available to ordinary Cubans.<p>Rationally speaking, this should all make the United States happy. No sane American could want political chaos or economic collapse on this island of almost 11 million inhabitants 90 miles from our shores. However, U.S. companies still cannot invest in Cuba, and U.S. citizens cannot legally invest in foreign-investment funds in Cuba that are openly bought in the rest of the world.<p>It's hard to walk the streets of Havana and of rural villages as I did on a recent visit and feel that this policy is rational. Instead it feels like revenge. Elderly ladies with arms as thin as broomsticks begged for handouts in Havana's Old City; in the provinces, I saw regional hospitals with fewer scientific instruments than a good high school chemistry lab. I spoke to doctors who had no medicine to give to their patients; I spoke to dozens of ordinary Cubans frantically trying to survive on a monthly income of less than five dollars at the then-prevailing black market rate of exchange.<p>What exactly did Cuba do to call down this punishment on its head? Much of the U.S. national-security bureaucracy simply cannot forgive Castro. It was bad enough that he thumbed his nose at Washington and said nice things about Moscow. Worse still, he sent Cuban troops to Angola and Ethiopia. Washington was infuriated by Cuba's pursuit of a foreign policy that was independent of the U.S.<p>But Castro didn't just back anti-American forces in faraway countries. He had the temerity to support revolution in Latin America, a region the U.S. has claimed as its own since the days of James Monroe. For example, he aided the legitimate government of Nicaragua in its fight against U.S.funded rebels.<p>Now that the cold war is on at least temporary hiatus, the world map is no longer colored just red and white to Washington. Not every war is a sign of a domino ready to fall: We intervene in Kuwait because of Middle Eastern oil; we don't intervene in Rwanda. The Angolan civil war still sputters, but in a post-Soviet world it no longer shows up on Washington's radar.<p>But Cuba still does. Some in the national-security establishment fear that Castro's survival challenges the new world of economic spheres of influence just as much as his Cuba threatened the cold war's divisions of the globe. Cuba is the first and so far the only state in the Western Hemisphere to have defied Washington's vision for the region. Cuba must pay.<p>But others in Washington, and probably the majority, are guided by inertia and cowardice. Inertia, a never-to-be-underestimated factor in explaining the behavior of bureaucracies, fights change; cowards are afraid to take risks, however small. With bureaucrats ruled by inertia and politicians by cowardice, Washington dithers while Cuba waits.<p>Oddly enough, the biggest push for changing U.S. policy toward Cuba now comes from the U.S. business community__which smells profits and understands that U.S. power and interests in the Western Hemisphere have nothing to fear from Castro. Lee Iacocca visited Cuba last July; both Merck and Johnson & Johnson have sent representatives. Bilateral U.S.Cuba trade could easily hit $1 billion in the first year after the blockade ended, experts estimate.<p>Change is inevitable in Cuba__the only question is whether it will come easy or come hard. Sooner or later Fidel Castro, born in 1926, must go, as Mao put it, "to meet Marx." From the standpoint of selfish American interests, six months or even six years more of Castro is a small price to pay for an orderly transition.<p>And I'm telling you, the beaches in Cuba are sublime, the people are friendly, and the food is terrific.<p>
Walter Mead is the Presidential Fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance: Adam Feibelman.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Government, Internatoinal Politics
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

