<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-The Mutual Fund Shell Game</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-The Mutual Fund Shell Game</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
People trust their money to the mutual funds that rank highest each year. But the rankings may lie.<p>By Gary Hector<p>In 1994, <a name="FUND:WGITX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WGITX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Warburg Pincus's Growth & Income fund</b></a> was the fourth best performer among the 387 growth and income funds tracked by Morningstar, Inc. Investors received a handsome 7.6 percent total return in a year that saw the average growth and income fund decline 1.4 percent in value. What's more, Warburg Pincus returned 17.18 percent on average in each of the last three years--good enough to place second in its category over that period. <p>The only flaw in this apparently flawless investment was revealed in an interesting qualification from a Morningstar analyst in Morningstar's annual rankings. The Warburg Pincus fund, said analyst Adam Wright, wasn't really a staid growth and income operation at all, but rather "an aggressive-growth fund in disguise."<p>In fact, the fund achieved its impressive record by investing in low-dividend, high-risk stocks like <a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micron Technology</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:NSM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11058"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>National Semiconductor</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:STK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11407"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Storage Technology</b></a>. Why, then, was such an aggressive investor to be found in the growth and income category? <p>One possibility is that Warburg Pincus was "gaming" the rankings--miscategorizing itself in such a way that its riskier investment strategy would loft it to the apex of the performance pyramid. Fund managers can accomplish this sleight of hand in part because fund categories are so loosely defined, and because funds are commonly listed under the heading suggested by the vaguely worded investment objectives found in their prospectuses. This allows managers, in effect, to choose the heading under which their funds will be ranked, a cozy arrangement from the not-too-distant time when the whole industry was small and stodgy rather than the cutthroat world of 5,700 or more funds it has become.<p>Wall Street professionals have suspected for years that gaming was widespread. Until recently, they haven't had much evidence to back them up, but two independent studies now appear to confirm that gaming not only exists but may be more widespread than anyone imagined. Both research efforts concluded that more than half of all mutual funds are misclassified in performance rankings. And more than one out of ten is listed inaccurately enough that investors could be misled about their true nature, according to one study.<p>Together, the reports suggest that a growing number of funds operate according to a Wall Street axiom: "The best way to win a contest for largest tomato is to paint a cantaloupe red."<p>Lots of painted fruit shows up in a study by Erik Witkowski, who as a Harvard undergrad wrote an honors economics thesis examining the performance of 709 equity funds for the five years ended November 1993. He looked at the standard categories--growth, aggressive growth, small capitalization, international, growth and income, and income--searching for funds whose performance patterns over time diverged from the patterns of their categories as a whole. Witkowski found that an astonishing 394, or 56 percent, of the funds were misclassified. Eleven percent, or 75, were at least two categories of risk away from where they ought to have been--enough to make a big difference to investors.<p>More disturbing, a five-year performance review revealed that of the 20 top-ranked growth funds, 14 were actually high-risk aggressive-growth or small-capitalization funds in disguise. And of the top 20 growth and income funds, a still lower-risk category, 9 belonged in those two high-risk groups.<p>Witkowski, who now works for Northfield Information Services Inc., a Boston-based provider of analytical software and information to institutional investors, noted that other research has shown that most consumers simply accept performance rankings at face value and act upon them. In other words, Witkowski says, "The reason that a fund manager might intentionally misclassify a fund is easily understood." <p>Dan DiBartolomeo, president of Northfield Information Services, describes Witkowski's results as "the wolf in sheep's clothing problem, or vice versa." High-risk wolves disguise themselves as low-risk sheep to outperform their "peers" when markets are booming, while low-risk sheep slip into high-risk categories to look stellar when markets tumble.<p>"An awful lot of funds act differently than their peer group." says DiBartolomeo. "Either it's purposeful misclassification or there is something dramatically wrong with the classification system. Nobody in the industry would be surprised to find out that it was purposeful."<p>In another study of mutual funds, two finance professors, Stephen Brown of New York University and William Goetzmann of Yale School of Management, analyzed mutual fund returns between 1977 and 1988 to see if the funds fell naturally into classes or categories. Like Witkowski, Brown and Goetzmann focused on monthly returns over time rather than portfolio composition.<p>After analyzing the returns on 758 funds, they found they fell into eight distinct clusters: growth and income, income, growth, value, small company, market timers, hedgers, and international. Most of these categories sound familiar, but their composition diverges greatly from the older classifications. <p>For example, Morningstar's growth category, with 282 funds, splintered into five different groups. Only 99 remained in Brown and Goetzmann's growth category. The remainder shifted into growth and income, value, small cap, and income. Funds from Morningstar's growth and income category fell into four distinct groups, with barely half staying in the growth and income area.<p>Brown and Goetzmann found their share of wolves. In Morningstar's growth category, 49 funds turned out to be more volatile small-company funds. Morningstar's growth and income group included 26 funds that belonged in the new growth or value groups. Their study also identified two new groups--funds that attempt to time markets, switching from cash to stocks and back, and hedge funds that invest primarily in precious metals.<p>The bottom line of both these studies is that annual performance rankings may be dangerous to the financial health of investors. The categories are too broad, and because fund managers can choose to be included in any category they wish, the rankings wind up comparing pineapples with kumquats, not apples with apples. This doesn't surprise market veterans like John Bogle, chairman of the Vanguard Group, who calls rankings "the greatest bunch of baloney foisted on the American public in years."<p>The only good news for investors is that most of the misclassifications the researchers found are neither serious nor intentional. Bogle points to <a name="FUND:VEXMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VEXMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard's Extended Market Portfolio</b></a>, an index fund that tries to match the Wilshire 5,000. That fund is classed as a growth fund though it might better be described as a midcap fund. <p>"If someone said it shouldn't be [a growth fund], I'd say, 'You are exactly right,' " Bogle says. But given the limitations of the fund categories, that is where the Extended Market Portfolio appears.<p>Similarly, Anthony Orphanos, manager of the Warburg Pincus Growth and Income fund, says, "To say that we are in the wrong category is incorrect. It's very difficult to take 1,600 or 1,700 funds and divide them into five categories."<p>Steve Rung, a Warburg spokesman, also notes that the fund last year had as much as 9 percent of its portfolio in bonds, an abnormally high percentage for a growth fund. This year, it's moved more into short-term instruments, giving a yield higher than most growth funds. <p>"The fund might not fit in the growth or the aggressive-growth category either,'' said Orphanos.<p>Other problems are a result of the mutual fund industry's ceaseless effort to create new kinds of funds. Patrick Geddes, the director of quantitative research at Morningstar, points to the <a name="FUND:MERFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MERFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merger Fund</b></a>, which buys shares of likely takeover targets and fits no standard system of classification.<p>Many funds that are drastically out of place are spotted by the data gatherers. Morningstar, Lipper, and others work diligently to find badly misclassified funds. Morningstar, for example, changed 205 listings in 1994, Lipper 154.<p>Investors should be particularly cautious about small funds, which tend to be misclassified most often, says Witkowski. Small funds have higher expenses as a percentage of assets and face potentially larger withdrawals as a percentage of total assets. As a result, their cash balances are relatively high, giving them relatively high income, which makes them look more like income funds than risk-tolerant pursuers of high growth. <p>Here are two examples from Morningstar of funds whose investment strategies might skew their performance within their chosen categories:<p><a name="FUND:ANABX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ANABX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alliance North American Government Income</b></a> sounds like a cast-iron widows-and-orphans investment, but don't be misled. Its charter calls for investments in the U.S., Canada, and Mexico--risky enough these days--and, according to Morningstar, it had 24 percent of its funds in Argentine securities as of December 1994. <p>The fund's yield was 15.36 percent (for class A shares) during 1994. It not only sought out high-yield investments but, like Orange County, borrowed to buy them. The fund's three classes of shares took a bath last year, ranking 99th, 100th, and 101st out of 101 funds in Morningstar's worldwide-bond category.<p><a name="FUND:CAIBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CAIBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Capital Income Builder</b></a> ranked fifth over five years in the equity-income group, supposedly a low-risk category. But while other equity-income funds stay close to home, according to Morningstar, at last count Capital Income had 35 percent of its assets in foreign markets and 14 percent in small-cap U.S. stocks, as of December 1994. <p>These funds and many others will probably never be properly classed until the current ranking system is overhauled. "The academic evidence is mounting that traditional classifications, including what we use, may be too limited a way to categorize mutual funds," says Geddes of Morningstar.<p>The rankings, then, are pretty much unusable. Here's how an investor can inform and protect himself nonetheless: <p>Get the total returns for the last five years. Then deduct the front-end sales charge for a good performance gauge. <p>Look at year-to-year consistency. Inconsistent performance spells increased risk.<p>Compare relative volatility. How much more--or less--volatile has your fund been than the market in general? <p>Compare portfolio activity. How much  buying and selling is the fund doing, compared to others in its category? The more churning that's going on, the more unpredictable the fund is likely to be.<p>Check how fast assets are growing. Is the money coming in too fast to be managed effectively? Remember, highly ranked funds often get a flood of new investors. <p>Find out the average tenure of the fund manager. The more often the name on the boss's door changes, the less consistent the fund's investing philosophy will be. <p>This information should be yours for the asking at any reputable fund. If a fund won't readily answer your questions about how and how well it invests, that is probably the clearest signal of all that you ought to take your money elsewhere. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
