<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-The Good, the Badla, & the Ugly</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Good, the Badla, & the Ugly</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-The Good, the Badla, & the Ugly</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> THE GOOD, THE BADLA, & THE UGLY <p>What does it mean, really, to be an emerging market? Come to, where the rules are unwritten and the traders deserve danger money.  <p> By Richard Todd  <p> The bombay stock exchange opens at 12 noon on weekdays and closesjust 120 minutes later. The reason for such circumscribed business hours, it is said, is record keeping. The exchange, which trades more individual issues than any other in the world, generates seven hours of paperwork for each two-hour trading session. <p> "Paperwork" is no metaphor here in Bombay. Every transaction involves a physical transfer of stock, complete with certificates of ownership, bills of sale, and some 121 separate stamps and sign-offs. Twice a month the market shuts down altogether--it closes sporadically anyway--for a daylong patavat, or exchange of shares. The stock certificates are swathed in red cloth bundles and carried around from broker to broker in a huge hall. So the Bombay market certainly has its logistical difficulties. But I suspect the real reason it doesn't stay open longer every day is more basic: No one could survive it.  <p> The Bombay Stock Exchange operates as an open outcry market. The outcry takes place in the regional language of Gujarati,the traditional language of India's trading caste, and with as many as 3,000 traders on the floor at any moment the noise is considerable. Traders wear hospital-blue smocks, moving at somespeed and only in straight lines. If you're in the way, you are moved aside. It looks like an emergency room full of deranged orderlies.  <p> For communication amid the chaos, traders use the traditional hand signals of their vocation--but those often don't do the trick. The preferred gesture here seems to be the cheek pinch, followed by the chin hold. On my first visit to the market, I saw a wholesale jobber being assaulted by no fewer than ten brokers, each looking for a part of his cheek to pinch. They all leaned into him, and soon they were atop him and each other. It wasa little like a rugby scrum, except that everyone carried a notepad and was screaming. From time to time the man in the middle--as lender fellow with long hair and a strangely serene look on his face--would rise with his notebook over the heads and make an entry. Then someone would grab his hair and pull him down again. The whole thing looked as if it could end only in orgasmor death. Instead it ended on schedule (and not a moment too soon) at two o'clock.  <p> My guide, a tall and gentlemanly Bombay broker, apologized for the scene. "I am sorry we are having such a quiet day," he said in that syncopated Indian English. "The market is stag-nant, you see."  <p>
Money flows with the logic of water--and pays as little attention as water does to where it ends up. Even so, Bombay seems an unlikely place for a stock market boom. Everywhere you look, squalor greets you. The crumbling streets still swarm with beggars, the maimed, the emaciated, the babes in arms. Seen from a distance, with a bit of a cocked eye, the place looks like a modern seaside city. But up close the buildings are shoddily built and maintenance nonexistent. Black streaks of mold deface their walls and, within, inadequate plumbing yields a frequent stench. Infrastructure is wanting. Phone service now works in the financial district, but long distance is spotty. As for the post office, you're better off leaving a letter on the street and hoping some kind soul delivers it. Half of Bombay's 12.5 million citizens live in sheet-metal hovels or in storm drains or under bridges. The yellowish coastal waters of the Arabian Sea are so polluted that no one dares swim at the city's beaches. Sanitation in general is primitive. Neither food nor water may be fully trusted.  <p> Yet India is the very model of an "emerging market," Bombay is its financial bazaar, and I guess if you are in this game a lot of things become more or less invisible. After lumbering along for 40 years as a closed socialist economy, India recently opened its doors to foreign investment. With the encouragement of Prime Minister Narasimha Rao, capital has begun pouring in and the Bombay exchange is ascendant: Its index of key stocks,the Sensex, has risen from a 1979 base of 100 to something like 4,000 today. Mutual fund investors in Scarsdale and Grand Forks are helping to drive this market higher--though one wonders how many of them know where their dollars are tonight.  <p> In the marble lobby of the Oberoi hotel complex, an island of grotesque luxury in the city, you now see men from <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, Templeton, and Morgan Stanley. Before long, foreign industrialists will be a significant presence here--Kellogg, <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric</b></a>, <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota</b></a>, and others are entering the market--but for the moment the action is mostly in finance, where the bright eyes of foreign analysts see unlimited prospects. Morgan Stanley alone has pumped $2 billion of Americans' money into Bombay through funds, including its India Magnum Fund; in five years that fund's per-share price has gone from $15 to $60. One of the firm's young bankers, as lender and harried Englishman named John Porter, assured me,"Even if the market crashes, you'll be able to get your money back in one to two years on the basis of earnings alone."  <p> In the minds of many, it seems, India's primacy among Asia's emerging markets is a certainty. Over the ritual afternoon coffee in his office, Nimesh Kampani, a prominent Bombay broker, ticked off for me the reasons. It was a list I would soon discover is standard wisdom: language and democracy, a long-standing legal system, a superior knowledge of accounting. "There are two tigers in Asia, India and China," said Mr. Kampani. "India will win." He also mentioned in passing, as everyone does, the great problem: population, the 900 million whose generally miserable existence is acknowledged almost superstitiously--"Of course, we must do something about the population problem."  <p> India's annual GNP is only about $310 per capita. However, it has an extraordinary savings rate, estimated at about 25 percent for wage earners. Even the very poor tend to have a small stash of gold, still a favorite repository of wealth for all classes. In the barren socialist economy that prevailed for two generations, only a minimal consumer society could develop. Those who own real estate tend to do so outright. So despite the abjectness everywhere, there is less debt and more liquidity than one might guess.  <p> And of course, even small percentages of the Indian population add up to rather big numbers. Fortunes are to be made by bringing small investors--and Western money, of course--into a Bombay market that may still be in its infancy. Mr. Kampani himself is a good example: He built his brokerage house, J.M. Financial & Investment Consultancy Services, from start-up capital of just $500. "We have e-du-cated the public," he told me. For many, the breakthrough came in 1993 when J.M.'s bond offering for Reliance Industries, the energy and chemical giant, raised well over $100 million and turned away many times that much in oversubscriptions. "The issue went like hotcakes," said Mr. Kampani. "Everybody realized there is money in India."  <p> There is also room for growth. Of India's 900 million people, just 25 million currently invest in stocks. As recently as 1980 only about 1 percent of the country's savings was in stocks; today the figure has climbed to 12 percent. In the U.S., the number is 45 percent.  <p>
Iguess the market was stagnant when I was there; daily fluctuations of 15 to 20 percent are not uncommon in Bombay. But lately the race had been run under a yellow flag. Owing to certain "irregularities," some trading practices had been suspended. By the time I discovered this, however, I had concluded that finding irregularities in Bombay's market was much like finding gambling at Rick's.  <p> The Bombay Stock Exchange, in a modern high-rise, dominates seedy Dalal Street. Dalal means broker in Hindi, and it has traditionally been a word of shady connotations; the same word serves for pimp. But brokers are rising in the Indian world as the public becomes fascinated with stocks. Today on Dalal Street hawkers mingle with food vendors, passing out prospectuses for new issues in the bazaarlike atmosphere. Throughout the city, billboards trumpet share offerings.  <p> Mrugank Sanghvi, a lean, amiable young man, runs a trading concern across the street from the exchange, one small enough that the difficulties of doing business in Bombay can be seen in microcosm. We met in his office, which had the atmosphere of a garment-district sweatshop, with six clerks laboriously stamping yard-high piles of documents. The heat was unbearable, but that was not the only reason Mr. Sanghvi motioned me down the stairs and out to the street. Come, I must explain something to you.  <p> What he told me was that the seeming inefficiencies of the Bombay Stock Exchange--the mountainous paperwork, the endless delays--are not inefficiencies for everyone. For one thing, with all those shares to transfer, there are excellent opportunities for counterfeiting. A few false shares stuck into the middle of some genuine ones give many a player a little extra profit. But that's crude thievery. More subtly, there is the creative use of delay. All those signatures that must be obtained before the stock can be transferred: Should one of them be missing, then the transaction doesn't happen.If things haven't gone your way, you can buy time. Also, the fewer shares that are traded, the more a stock's price may be influenced by any one trade.  <p> Mr. Sanghvi wanted me to understand that only a small minority of brokers use such techniques. And anyway, it's mostly small potatoes, he said, people manipulating the prices of minor stocks. But when you add this to the other practices I was told of--and realize that with 8,000 listings the exchange provides a wideplaying field--you begin to imagine a market full of rogues. <p> Yet oddly enough, in my wanderings I kept meeting gentlemen, none more accommodating than Mahesh Khubchandani, who operates a small but prosperous brokerage just off Dalal Street. With his partner he shares an office as spare as an officer's stateroom on a warship. The brokerage employs 53 people, most of them not selling stocks but stamping them, checking their signatures, organizing them into bundles. Mr. Khubchandani stands about six feet three inches and carries a comfortable girth. He must have an aggressive side, but in conversation he was soft-spoken and likable. A certain softness of manner seems to characterize businessmen on Dalal Street--those who aren't actually on the floor mauling one another.  <p> "Between brokers there is a strong ethical code," Mr. Khubchandani told me. "Word is all." This is actually a practical measure: The one fast rule of an otherwise mostly lawless Bombay market is that brokers bear full responsibility for their trades. If a client doesn't pay up, the broker must make it good. As a result, Mr. Khubchandani acknowledged with a smile, the brokers' code doesn't always extend to dealings with their clients. He knew that some of his fraternity, fearing a certain amount of default, provide their own "insurance." The primitive state of recordkeeping makes it easy to execute trades at any time during a session--but to report them to the client at a price that is most advantageous to the broker.  <p> Ethical looseness may be rampant here, but some of it appears to be a matter of definition. Two and a half years ago the exchange, suffering from corruption and mindful of stricter Western sensibilities, passed its first regulations against insider trading. The new rules are vague, and there has so far been little litigation. To most brokers here the very concept of insider trading seems absurd, like trying to play tennis without a ball. "This is a market that functions on insider trading," Mr. Khubchandani said to me. "Everybody who has made money has done so on nonpublic information. I hope they do not eliminate insider trading altogether. The market will be no fun without it."  <p> Of course, there are insiders and insiders. The ultimate inside information in Bombay is knowledge of what the "cartels" are up to. It's an open secret on Dalal Street that, at any moment, the fate of many stocks is controlled by a handful of brokers--including some at the best-known firms--who unite to manipulate share prices through the futures market. In an amusing and characteristically Indian twist, there is no futures market on the stock exchange. But there is something just as good: badla.  <p> In Gujarati, badla means "instead of." It's the name given to the fee paid to defer taking delivery on a stock one has agreed to buy. Badla is an informal way to make it possible for traders to take long and short positions on stocks. But this definition doesn't capture the aura of power that seems to emanate from the word. Badla is the enabler, the magic that makes possible control of the market. It's a rough magic that so far has survived the best efforts of both regulators and rascals to civilize it. <p>
Clearly, the Bombay exchange is no place for innocents. Yet innocents streamed in throughout the late 1980s. They were rewarded by the market's inexorable rise until 1992, when an event widely known as "the Scam" reminded everyone that there's a downside to the rawer forms of capitalism.  <p> The Scam was the work of an ambitious--some might say visionary--young broker named Harshad Mehta. It was Mr. Mehta's avowed purpose to break open the market by snatching control away from Bombay's cartels. To do this, he needed both large amounts of cash and the same weapon his foes were using: badla. Mr. Mehta's quixotic goals became well-known, and he briefly enjoyed life as a popular hero. The stocks he backed rose, cartels be damned; the entire market surged several hundred points over the course of just a few months as many investors followed his lead. But there was a difficulty. Where was this upstart getting his money?  <p> To understand what really happened in the Scam, I sought instruction at a table of well-connected financial types in the Bombay Cricket Club, one of the many places in India where you get the sense that though the oppressor has left, his manners, like his language, have been left behind to govern. I was told that Mr. Mehta's dealings had not been confined to the stock market--and that this had ultimately doomed him to failure.  <p> For his assault against the cartels Mehta assembled an initial war chest of some 100 million rupees (about $3 million) through unsecured bank loans. Some of it, I was told, was obtained viabribes involving 100 or so cars he bought for the purpose. Then he used his success--and, prosecutors have charged, fraudulent documents--to borrow yet more. It was, said one of my distinguished instructors, "a game of pass-the-pillow. In the end, Standard Chartered [a bank that lent Mr. Mehta money] got the pillow and lost $300 million."  <p> Mr. Mehta's empire went the way of all pyramid schemes. Many banks and thousands of individual investors were burned, and the ensuing scandal caused the Bombay market index to lose almost half its value. (It has since recovered.) Mr. Mehta's crowning mistake, it seems, was to claim publicly that he had given an illegal campaign donation of $300,000 to Prime Minister Rao, precipitating a political crisis that has yet to fully pass. My informants' view on this: "He should not have spoken of it."(Mr. Rao has denied taking any money from Mr. Mehta.)  <p> Aprs Mehta, the deluge. Major investigations followed; Mr.Mehta says he broke no law, but he awaits trial on a multitude of charges, including forgery and bribery. The Security Exchange Board of India was established to end the glory days of buccaneers on the Bombay Stock Exchange. Speculators' wings were clipped,and the magic of badla was suspended.  <p> "So there is no futures trading?" I asked a Cricket Club tablemate. <p> "Well, I would not say that, exactly. No."  <p> "But how do they do it without badla?"  <p> "Well"--smiling--"they do it with badla."  <p> Among friends and cartels, it seems, a little badla is always possible.  <p> I subsequently met Mr. Mehta. The reader, never having heard of him until now, will not be impressed. I'm afraid I wasn't sufficiently impressed myself; in Indian culture Harshad Mehta occupies a place of exalted notoriety.  <p> Mr. Mehta looks like a very big and well-fed teenager. He griped to me that his bank accounts had been frozen, but he was hardly cutting back on his lifestyle. In a city where it's singularly hard to achieve comfort, let alone luxury, Mr. Mehta was still striving to transform his waterfront duplex, in a posh neighborhood known as Breach Candy, into a pleasure dome. Some 20 workers chipped away at tile in one room as we met in what looked like a children's playroom decorated in Crayola tones of purple and yellow. It was, I slowly realized, his study. The tables were heaped high with books on money--American management tomes, along with an illustrated volume called The World's Richest People. <p> Naively, I had hoped Mr. Mehta would give me his side of the story. I had forgotten that a good hustler is always moving on. With the supreme mental health of that breed, Mr. Mehta had simply defined his troubles away. True, the authorities were nagging him about his past endeavors, but he was thinking about new things--"how to make India a superpower," for example.  <p> "How did Japan succeed?" he asked me, not rhetorically but in the insistent way of a teacher. I gave the usual answers: culture, technology, industrial policy.  <p> "Bullshit. They borrowed money at 5 percent and let their currency appreciate by 10 percent a year." I didn't fully follow the argument, but he seemed to be saying that <a name="NYSE:SNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sony</b></a> is the inevitable result of knowing how to borrow and lend.  <p> Mr. Mehta may be right. He may also be in jail soon. Ironically, he may do some good for his cause either way: The reforms he inspired could make Indian markets a better magnet for foreign investors.  <p>
Outside my window in the Oberoi Towers, I could see in the misty harbor 20 or 30 cargo ships riding at anchor. I began to imagine they were full of money. There is something inevitable about the appearance of restless Western capital here; this is its next port of call. It may be useless to think of the consequences. <p> Yet there seems to be an uneasiness here about all the money flowing into the Bombay Stock Exchange. The finance minister frets that it's "hot money," destined to leave as fast as it arrives. Others worry it won't benefit the country as a whole. I met one woman, an artist, who wishes the whole mess would just go away. "I think we are going to be colonized all over again,"she said.  <p> The optimists, meanwhile, hope for sustained growth that will be driven by foreign capital, internal investment, and India's famous "middle class," which everyone loved to describe to meas "250 million people--as big as your whole country." Just looking around, I had to wonder about this middle class: Who and where was it?  <p> I received a useful caution on this subject from a well-known Indian entrepreneur named Dilip Thakore, CEO of Datamatics Direct, India's largest direct-mail marketing database. When I asked Mr. Thakore what counts as a middle-class income, he said about $1,200 a year. It is quite possible to belong to the Indian middleclass and to have no refrigeration. You can look at this two ways. One: This middle class can't afford much. Or two: We've got a great market for refrigerators here. The latter seems tobe the approach of General Electric, and that could be the startof something big. It's certainly a powerful argument for those who pitch the Bombay Stock Exchange to U.S. investors. At the same time, it's hard for me to forget that 650 million still live in desperation. No one could make the drive into Bombay from the airport, 26 kilometers of unrelieved wretchedness, and have any illusions that capitalism will amount to a cure anytime soon.  <p> One of the more bathetic ways to spend your life is getting sad at the passing of things you never knew, and I'm afraid I do a certain amount of this myself. Of all things to get nostalgic for, I found myself feeling a bit that way about the Bombay Stock Exchange. Surely, they were about to solve the paperwork problem. Screen trading would begin. The floor traders would find less hazardous work. There would be a central depository for stock, and soon it would be wrapped not in red cloth but in electronic signals.  <p> I made my final visit to the exchange floor accompanied by a young trader named Rahul Patkar. Rahul looked to me like a Yale sophomore, lean, with an intelligent face and an insouciance about his gaze and gait. He had already traveled to the U.S.,where, I suspect, he bought his stylish oval-framed glasses. We met just before the market opened, and I wondered how he would survive on the floor, where soft-spoken good manners are a marginal asset. Rahul sauntered into the swirl notebook in hand--the only trader, I noted, not wearing a regulation blue smock. He had on a striped shirt with his sleeves rolled partway up each forearm. <p> "You want to see a deal. Please. Come."  <p> Rahul explained that he had to buy some fertilizer stock--quite a lot in fact, 20,000 shares. He would buy from more than one jobber so as not to reveal the extent of his need. He was authorized to pay up to 217-1/2 a share. As I watched, a strange transformation occurred: Rahul started to bellow in Gujarati, a guttural roar that sounded like Alleluia Alleluia Lock your home LockyourhomeLockyourhome. He was also waggling two fingers.  <p> This seemed to get the attention of a nearby jobber, and in a few minutes they were settled into conversation. Unfortunately, six other people were battling for the same jobber's attention. Rahul yelled louder: Peaseporridge Peaseporridge! Then he grabbed the man's chin and turned it toward him. It appeared the fellow understood, but there was clearly no deal.  <p> Rahul grasped the jobber's neck and squeezed tight on his chin so that all movement ceased. He yelled straight into the man's face. Out came the notebook.  <p> "You did the deal."  <p> "Yes. Would you like to see another? Come. Please."  <p> At odd moments in the trading Rahul explained to me how he was working in concert with other traders to assemble blocks of stock. But there was something he knew he couldn't explain about the whole process, and it was something I expected would carry him far.  <p> Later, I asked Rahul about his plans. He said he wants to go to a U.S. business school and then--well, who knows? I found it nice to think of him entering American corporate life. IfI were running a division of <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, I would sleep better knowing Rahul was on my sales team. I can see him at the piano bar of some Radisson, chatting amiably about a client's kids. I imagine him, as the evening draws to a close, standing up and grabbing my client by the nape of his neck, squeezing his chin while the pianist plays "Raindrops Keep Falling on My Head," and screaming Alleluia Alleluia Lockyourhome!  <p> He'd get the deal. And thus would the West fail to crush the admirable spirit of the Bombay Stock Exchange.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing
