	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Valuing the Sacred</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Valuing the Sacred</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> VALUING THE SACRED  <p>In our economics everything has a monetary value. But in the Middle East some things are still priceless.   <p> By Walter Mead  <p> "Go ahead," said my guide, "you can touch it." I was standing on the holiest spot of ground in the world, Mount Moriah in the Dome of the Rock Shrine in Jerusalem. It is here that Abraham is said to have offered his son Isaac as a sacrifice to God, here that King Solomon built the First Temple, and from here that the Prophet Mohammed was carried into heaven.  <p> Jewish, Christian, and Islamic traditions all say that the Last Judgment will take place here. In the Muslim version, the most picturesque as well as the most alarming, a thread will be stretched from Mount Moriah to the Mount of Olives; the flames of hell will belch out from the valley below, and all human souls will have to walk across to enter paradise.  <p> The image aptly characterizes the entire Middle East at the moment. The seething emotional hatreds that constantly threaten to engulf the region in renewed violence continue to burn, but paradise tantalizingly beckons: Peace between traditional enemies seems possible. Decades of U.S. policy are bearing fruit. Careful cajoling has convinced the Jordanians, the Egyptians, and the Israelis to compromise, to give up territorial claims in exchange for the economic benefits of trade and millions in U.S. aid. But I have returned from my recent trip to the Holy Land deeply pessimistic about the ability of this process to succeed. Asan economist I find this awkward to admit, but after traveling through the region I doubt the power of rational economics--grounded in Western assumptions about human nature--to bring final peace. <p> I expected to find rage in my travels, and I wasn't disappointed. "Look at this!" said a Palestinian sociologist, pointing to avacant lot in the otherwise-crowded urban landscape of a refugee settlement in the West Bank. An entire family had been driven from its home after a teenage son was accused of throwing stones at Israeli cars. "The Jews came to this country 100 years ago and said they wanted only a few farms. Ever since then they have been taking and taking, and still today they don't stop. How can we live with such people?"  <p> I could see his point. Fortress-like Israeli settlements cluster on the hilltops around Jerusalem and throughout the West Bank. In many of them construction proceeded at a frantic pace as the Israelis struggled to, as they put it, "create facts on the ground." <p> But while I felt that some of the Palestinians' complaints were justified, I knew that the realities of the Holy Land are more complicated. On a visit to Auschwitz a few years ago, I met some Israeli high school students on a school trip. Many of their families had originally come from Poland; I asked them what they thought of the country.  <p> "It's not so good," said one. "The other day, we went to the memorial to the Warsaw ghetto. And there were some Polish kids there, and they shouted at us,  Jews go home!' " If these Jewish children are to have a home, it won't be in Poland, where their families had lived for 800 years.  <p> Terror attacks on Israeli citizens by Palestinian extremists remind Israelis just how fragile their security is. A retired general in the Israeli Defense Forces told me that his daughter had missed a bus by five minutes; that bus was destroyed by a suicide bomber. "Israel is a small country," he said. "Every army base that is attacked, every terrorist attack, touches us all."  <p> American policy in the Middle East is based on a secular logic peculiar to our own historic experience. Into a Middle Eastern politics of blood feuds and religion the United States has tried to insinuate a politics of compromise and economic progress. If the Israelis and Palestinians stopped fighting and started working together, they would both be better off, say the Americans. Lavish grants and loans underwrite our diplomacy: Israel and Egypt today are the two largest recipients of American foreign aid.  <p> In the U.S., the economic value of compromise is unassailable. But as I discovered in the Middle East, nations are capable of economic behavior that can only be considered self-destructive by American standards.  <p> Consider the Israeli economic policy in Gaza and the West Bank. "The Palestinians," Yasser Arafat told me only hours before fighting erupted between Arafat loyalists and militant Hamas supporters in Gaza, "have gained nothing from the peace process." Arafat and other Palestinians told me about clauses in the peace agreement that strangled the Palestinian economy and about how Israel undermines the new Palestinian authorities by withholding money and such critical computer files as tax records on the West Bank.  <p> Economics can't explain this behavior. Certainly, the Israelis understand that violence is more likely to appeal to a starving and hopeless Palestinian than to a prosperous one. But Western economic logic isn't ascendant here; the sacred is.  <p> In economics, assets tend to be fungible. Everything has a monetary value, and monetary values can be freely exchanged. A farm has a price, for example, and if two farms have the same price, they are equal assets from an economic perspective.  <p> Life isn't really that simple, of course, even in the United States. If the government wants to build a highway through my home, it offers compensation based on the market price of my property, but my home is worth more to me than the market price. Therefore, I take the government to court and spend thousands fighting the highway, even though my actions are irrational from a strictly economic point of view.  <p> But to a visitor, what is economically irrational seems the norm in the Holy Land. The value of many things--most obviously real estate--is set on an entirely different scale. For Christians, Muslims, and Jews, for Palestinians and Israelis, Jerusalem is more than a beloved city. There is only one City of David, and it has no price.  <p> The Bible tells how the wicked King Ahab went to Naboth and said, "Give me your vineyard, that I may have it for a vegetable garden, because it is near my house; and I will give you a better vineyard for it; or, if it seems good to you, I will give you its value in money." Ahab is acting like an economist, or an American--making what any realtor would call a fair offer to Naboth.  <p> But Naboth obeyed religious logic. "The Lord forbid," he told the king, "that I should give you the inheritance of my fathers. "The usual Biblical consequences flowed from this act: Naboth was stoned to death on orders of Ahab's wicked wife, Jezebel,who was then killed on orders from God. Dogs ate her flesh.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
