		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Fairness in Closed-End Funds</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Fairness in Closed-End Funds</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Fairness in Closed-End Funds</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Experts<p>FAIRNESS IN CLOSED-END FUNDS
Does your stock-fund manager serve more than one master?  If so, you and your investment might be secondary priorities.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Do the managers of closed-end funds provide the same caliber of performance to the small, individual investors in their funds that they do to their institutional or private clients?<p>We wondered about this because equal treatment and fairness are important when it comes to maintaining investor confidence in the capital markets. All investors -- large and small -- should be treated with an even hand.<p>This isn't just good business practice; it's the law. John Heine at the Securities and Exchange Commission says,"If all clients are not treated fairly, that would be a violation of an advisor's fiduciary responsibility." Fund managers who run a single portfolio, of course, have no such conflict. For better or worse, their investors get the same result. When a money manager serves several masters, achieving equal treatment can be a tricky matter. An example: A manager who runs a closed-end growth-stock fund while managing private growth-stock accounts.<p>To find out whether this practice is cause for concern, Worth examined the returns of funds whose managers do investment-oriented moonlighting on the side. What we found wasn't reassuring.<p>We began by isolating managers who run closed-end funds and also manage private or institutional accounts. This meant excluding Baker Fentress and Bergstrom Capital, whose managers stick to a single portfolio. We also removed managers of funds whose investment objectives did not match those of their private clients.<p>Why limit our study to closed-end funds? Because these investment tools have been growing in popularity. Morningstar reports closed-end fund assets of $75 billion last year, 12 times 1985's level. <p>Another reason we stuck to closed-end funds: Their value doesn't fluctuate with inflows of new capital or outflows from redemptions, as with open-end funds. Assessing the NAV of a closed-end fund gives a clearer view of a manager's skills. <p>We also wondered whether it was right to worry about the accountability of closed-end fund managers, especially in comparison with the operators of open-end funds. Open-end funds are always looking for new money -- they're paid on the basis of assets under management -- and the best way to attract fresh cash is with good returns. Poor returns can result in lost business for open-end funds.<p>This is not quite the case in closed-end funds, whose managers are not beating the bushes for new money on the strength of their returns. They sell a fixed number of shares to the public, usually through a brokerage, which then trade on an exchange. Though closed-end fund managers earn more fees if a fund's shares increase in value -- they are also paid as a percentage of assets under management -- they don't have to worry about not being able to raise money from new clients. Neither must they fret about having cash to meet shareholder redemptions. If you want out of a closed-end fund, you sell your shares to another investor, not back to the fund. <p>To be sure that our study compared apples to apples, we limited our focus to managers whose private accounts and closed-end funds have identical objectives as reported in Morningstar and Nelson's Directory of Investment Managers. For example, we compared the returns of the <a name="FUND:MGISX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MGISX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Grenfell Smallcap Fund</b></a>, with $67 million in assets, to the composite performance of Morgan Grenfell Capital Management's $763 million in small-cap managed accounts. Both seek long-term capital appreciation through investments in small-cap companies; their ten largest stock holdings were identical.<p>When we had completed our selection process, we were left with eight closed-end funds. Our list in place, we then turned to see how their managers performed -- both for the fund and for their private accounts. We used compounded average annual returns for one-, three-, and five-year holding periods that ended December 1993.<p>What we found was that of the eight funds, four were either fairly consistent or even outperformed their managers' other accounts. These were Charles Allmon Trust, run by veteran fund manager Charles Allmon; Blue Chip Value Fund, run by Denver Investment Advisers; Morgan Grenfell Smallcap Fund, managed by Robert Kern; and <a name="FUND:RYVFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/RYVFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Royce Value Fund</b></a>, managed by Charles Royce and Thomas Ebright. Royce and Allmon consistently beat their managers' private results.<p>The four remaining funds, <a name="FUND:GABEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GABEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gabelli Equity Trust Fund</b></a>, <a name="FUND:JGFAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JGFAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Jundt Growth Fund</b></a>, Z-Seven Fund, and <a name="FUND:ZAPAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ZAPAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Zweig Fund</b></a>, reported returns that lagged the composite performance of the managers' other accounts. Disparities ranged from a low of around 12 percent in the Gabelli Equity Trust to 3,000 percent in the Zweig Fund. Each lagged in at least two of three periods. <p>What explains the disparities? There are a number of possibilities; only a fund manager knows which ones apply to him. One source suggested that investment managers may hype returns in their managed accounts. Still, such practices aren't kosher; any manager who did so would eventually end up with some pretty angry clients. <p>Another possible explanation: The managers of the closed-end funds were hampered by trading restrictions necessary to retain their tax-qualified status. For example, closed-end fund managers must follow what is called the short-short rule, which states that gains in fund holdings cannot be taken before three months have elapsed from the time of purchase. Also, the custodial and administrative costs of running a closed-end fund may be a bit higher than those of private accounts.<p>Yet if any of these explanations holds water, then why did four of the funds we studied not succumb to these difficulties?<p>When we asked the fund managers to explain the discrepancies, most of them turned to the "apples and oranges" defense, that all portfolios are different. Maybe so, but the top holdings in three of the four laggard funds exactly mirrored the top holdings in the managers' composite accounts, according to Nelson's and Morningstar. In the fourth fund, no stocks were identified. <p>James Jundt, of Jundt Associates, says,"I think you're talking about numbers that aren't meaningful. One or two percent around a composite are what I call noise." Noise or not, in 1992, his fund lagged his private accounts by almost half. <p>Closed-end funds cannot engage in hedging practices, such as short-selling, which private money managers may. But hedging is uncommon among the managers in our list. According to Nelson's, only Zweig International Managers uses hedging. This may explain part of the gap in the returns, but it's unlikely that hedging alone gives the private accounts gains so far above those in the fund. <p>There's reason for concern here. Why? Because there's no escaping the fact that managers have more incentives to outperform markets in their private accounts than they do in their funds. If they do well for existing institutional clients, they'll find it much easier to snare new ones. What's more, fees earned on private accounts can exceed fees for running a closed-end fund. <p>Some advisors get up to 20 percent of realized gains in their clients' accounts if they beat the market by a set amount. Zweig International Managers, for instance, earns 1 percent annually on private accounts, plus an incentive of 18.5 percent of net new profits earned quarterly. In its fund, Zweig earns 1 percent.<p>We wonder what happens when a manager gets his hands on some shares of a hot IPO. Fund managers usually get around 10 percent of the shares they ask for, so how are these goodies divvied up? How are any big winners or big losers allocated among their clients?<p>"We are very careful about this; we try to keep our accounts in balance at all times," says Charles Allmon, whose fund is an outperformer. "Our in-house ethics committee meets quarterly to discuss it." Of performance inconsistency, he says,"I wouldn't want to embarrass my board of directors by showing up with something like that."<p>Discrepancies in a fund manager's returns should raise some eyebrows. If you're an investor in one of these funds, it may not be reason enough to get out, particularly if you've been content with your returns. But it is something to watch.<p>Investors who own shares in or are considering buying a closed-end fund should ask whether the management firm runs other portfolios. Compare how the firm gets paid on those portfolios with fees earned on the closed-end fund. Ask also whether past returns in the fund and private accounts are consistent and request documentation of this. Think twice about paying a premium for a fund whose returns lag its manager's other portfolios. Recently the Gabelli, Z-Seven, and Zweig funds all carried premiums. Inconsistency in a fund manager is not worth paying for.<p>Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

