<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Expanding Your Fund Horizons</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Expanding Your Fund Horizons</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
How to buy country funds that are normally off-limits.<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>American investors have been pouring money into emerging markets, buying up country-fund shares as quickly as American brokerages can print them. But there may be even better places to stash your overseas investment cash. Foreign-issued mutual funds, not registered for sale in the U.S., often are undervalued and have higher returns and lower costs than their American counterparts. <p>Although these funds are supposed to be off-limits to investors in the States, they are by no means impossible to buy. In addition to their lower costs and, in some cases, higher returns, overseas funds offer stateside investors pure plays on developing countries that they wouldn't otherwise have access to. <p>Case in point: Vietnam. Despite the recent lifting of the U.S. embargo against Vietnam, there is not one SEC-registered Vietnam fund available. American retail investors, technically speaking, cannot directly partake of the country's economic promise. <p>Meanwhile, a London investor can buy Beta Vietnam Fund, of Ireland and Vietnam Fund Ltd., of Hong Kong. These funds trade at high premiums to net asset value -- Beta Vietnam at a 45 percent premium and Vietnam Fund at 65 percent over NAV -- and are expensive considering that Vietnam has no stock exchange and few private corporations. But they do allow investors to get in on the ground floor of a country ready to develop economically.<p>Want to invest in Korea? U.S. investors can choose from just three funds -- Korea Fund, Korea Equity Fund, and Korean Investment Fund. All trade at high premiums, averaging 20 percent, 12 percent, and 11 percent respectively, at mid-year on the New York Stock Exchange. Good luck.<p>Non-U.S. investors have 14 other Korea funds to choose from. The Clemente Emerging Growth Fund, on the London Stock Exchange, trades at a discount of 10 percent. Daehan Korea Trust shares are trading at their NAV. <p>Big premiums on U.S.-issued country funds are the result of limited offerings and heavy taxes on offshore investments. "In London, investors get six times as much choice on country funds," says Eric Roseman, editor of Impartial Global Mutual Fund Investor in Montreal. "The 467 U.K.-listed country funds are trading at an average 8 percent discount to net asset value, versus the 76 U.S. country funds that are trading flat or at a 0.5 percent premium." <p>One reason it's tricky for U.S. investors to buy offshore funds is that the Investment Company Act of 1940 prohibits offshore funds from soliciting business here. That means these outfits can't send offerings to a U.S. address unless it's a private placement, and those are usually limited to institutional investors or high-net-worth individuals. Offshore funds also decline checks from U.S. citizens, so investors must have an offshore bank account, hold property overseas, or be expatriates. In the last case, they must sell the fund when they come home.<p>It is the IRS, however, that keeps most American investors out of these funds. Most offshore country funds qualify as passive foreign investment companies, according to the Internal Revenue Code. Unlike U.S. funds, which distribute capital gains and income to shareholders every year, offshore funds make distributions only when investors exit. So after ten years, an investor is likely to be stranded with huge taxable gains. Because taxes haven't been paid annually on the unrealized gains, the IRS charges interest on the taxes owed and penalties for late payment. It also taxes the gain as ordinary income, at a much higher rate than that of a long-term capital gain. If there is a loss, it cannot be offset against investment gains.<p>All this is enough to put even the most determined investor off the whole idea of investing in an offshore fund. Except that the funds are, according to Harvey Fireman, partner of mutual fund taxation at Ernst & Young, "a really tremendous investment that will make up for the tax liability."<p>Both the IRS and the SEC can be gotten around. Ian Wilson of Micropal, a global-fund tracker in London and Boston, says, "With a little bit of work, you can get enhanced returns, an interesting portfolio, and stay ahead of the game." If you don't want to give up your citizenship, the best way to invest in offshore country funds is through a tax-qualified retirement plan, like a 401(K) plan. Joel Adler of the New York law firm Sutherland, Asbill and Brennan has been legal counsel for numerous offshore funds. Last year, he invested in the Siam Fund and the Malacca Fund (both managed by Indosuez and traded in London) through his retirement plan and received a 100 percent return on his money. By being in a 401(K), he skirts the tax on ordinary income.<p>If you buy one of these funds, be prepared to do some extra bookkeeping. Funds familiar with U.S. tax law will break down income and distribution on an annual basis and issue a pro forma statement. This way, if you buy a fund outside of a tax-deferred account, you pay the usual capital gains tax and avoid IRS interest and penalty costs. If the offshore fund does not provide this service, save yourself a headache and get a good accountant, impute annual income and gains on your portfolio, and pay taxes on it.<p>You can buy shares in open-end funds directly through the management company that issues them, or you can buy both open- and closed-end funds through private overseas banks that can be nominated to hold the shares in trust for foreign investors. For example, Royal Trust Bank in Vienna or Bank von Ernst in Bern, Switzerland, will act as nominees for a minimum investment of $15,000 and $40,000, respectively.<p>U.S. brokerages offer no facilities for American investors to buy offshore country funds. But for a minimum $10,000 investment, U.S. investors can deal directly with overseas brokers like Olliff & Partners in London, experts in closed-end country funds. U.S. brokers charge an average 5 percent transaction fee above the fund's management fee for country funds available in the U.S. Orlando, Florida-based International Assets Advisory Corp. charges average commissions of 2.75 percent for offshore funds; brokers like Olliff charge a 1 percent commission.<p>Another way to participate in offshore investment is through a bank or broker in the country you're interested in. An open-end Mexican stock fund, Accival, returned 37 percent in the last 12 months, much better than the popular Mexico Fund, listed on the NYSE, which gained 28 percent. To buy Accival shares, American investors can set up an account with the U.S. arm of Banamex, the Mexican bank that manages and distributes the fund. These funds typically levy a load of around 1.5 percent but incur no local capital gains tax. Unless you put the shares in a 401(K), you can't escape the IRS, which regards this as an offshore investment to be taxed accordingly.<p>Since offshore funds cannot solicit business in the U.S., how can you find out about them? For $119, you could subscribe to the Impartial Global Mutual Fund Investor, which monitors offshore funds' performances and provides bimonthly price and NAV updates. Better still, benefit from a good relationship with your broker and have him help with your homework. <p>The hurdle is getting hold of a prospectus of a fund you like, as it cannot be sent to a U.S. address. A friend overseas could receive it in your name, then send it to you. Or your foreign bank or broker can mail it to you.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing, International Politics, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

