<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Far East? Or Wild West?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Far East? Or Wild West?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>It seems like a terrific, timely idea: a new forum for listing Asian stocks so that North American investors can buy into Pacific Rim markets more easily. But when the innovator is the notorious Vancouver Stock Exchange, investors should beware.<p>Canada's government has been studying proposals to rein in the freewheeling VSE, where too many listees are famous for being -- to put it tactfully -- of questionable investment value. As a result, the VSE's new Asian Board of Exchange, set to open this summer, is getting something of a cold eye from Canadian regulators. Says Dean Holley, superintendent of brokers for the British Columbia Securities Commission: "We don't know whether this will be the last resort for every scoundrel in Hong Kong and the Far East."<p>Well, what kind of companies have applied to list on the Asian Board? The VSE won't give a full accounting, but so far there seem to be few heavy hitters. For instance, there's a $3 million Vancouver-based telecommunications concern that wants to buy a Chinese cement company. And there's a taxi company that operates 150 cabs in China and wants to expand into minibuses and gas stations.<p>In fact, the Asian Board may prove most attractive to companies that can't get listed in Hong Kong or other Pacific Rim exchanges with stringent entry requirements. The VSE's standards also are less demanding than rival North American exchanges. The fee to list on the Asian Board, for example, is $2,400. By contrast, foreign companies pay $18,000 for a listing on the Toronto Stock Exchange -- and $100,000 for the New York Stock Exchange.<p>The VSE's Asian Board requires compliance with Canadian or international accounting standards. But it also promises to be "responsive to the special circumstances of substantial Asian companies." With such an accommodating stance, low entry requirements, and British Columbia's cheap legal fees, the VSE believes its Asian Board can act as "an extension of the Chinese market," says VSE vice president John Boddie.<p>Regulator Holley, however, frets that the Asian Board could worsen the VSE's cowboy reputation. He warns that investors playing on the Asian Board should be "sophisticated, well-advised investors who appreciate risk." A first step toward such sophistication: When you're pitched the next great Asian investment, remember to ask where it's listed.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
