<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Adventures in Carpetbagging</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Adventures in Carpetbagging</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The Quest: To Turn $100,000 Into $10 Million ... In Siberia<p>By Curtis Hartman<p>It's snowing, the temperature is minus 27 degrees celsius, and sunrise has yet to come to Moscow as John Boynton steps out of his hotel and into a cab on this February morning. The 28-year-old president of Diomedes Inc. is headed for the airport and Aeroflot Flight 209, due to depart at ten o'clock for the Siberian city of Novokuznetsk. The cab driver peers silently through a defrosted half-moon on the icy windshield as he punches the accelerator. The view outside is bleak: block after squat block without billboard, neon sign, or lighted storefront. Here and there, small groups of workers shiver patiently in lines at the bus stands. The cab weaves around cars abandoned in the snowy streets, then passes though miles of gigantic flats laid out in concentric rings.<p>Boynton is so full of adrenaline he can hardly sit still in the rattling cab. He flew in from Boston only last night, but he's been up for hours already, bundled in his long underwear against the cold, planning, making notes, strategizing an assault on the frontiers of capitalism. For more than four years, he and his Moscow-based partner and high school best friend, Robert Stubblebine, have been on an elusive quest: to strike it rich in Russia's bewildering free-market economy. Already, the two aspiring carpetbaggers have pursued more than a dozen schemes in post-Soviet Russia, but so far they've had only limited success. They've sold used cars and auto parts, run a marketing consulting firm, sourced walnuts for Ben & Jerry's ice cream, and traded in rugs, tungsten, bee venom, and vodka. They've had to cope with Russian privatization and the start of reform, an attempted coup, an attempted putsch, and the defeat of reform. Their biggest success to date involves the sale of U.S.-made computers. But hawking technology has been anything but a bonanza; it's paid just enough to keep alive hope of a big score just around the corner. <p>Boynton is convinced the frozen reaches of the east will yield the long-awaited breakthrough. He and Stubblebine will be boarding a creaky Aeroflot jet (just weeks prior to their trip, an Aeroflot plane crashed in Siberia, killing all 120 passengers) and flying into deepest, coldest Siberia. Novokuznetsk, today a decaying industrial town, was once the industrial heart of the Soviet empire. If Russia is to rise again as an economic player of any importance, towns like Novokuznetsk must be reborn. And Boynton and Stubblebine figure that to do that Russians will need some basic heavy equipment -- like forklifts and snowplows. <p>Boynton gets to the airport before his partner. Inside the Aeroflot terminal, there are no other foreigners in sight, but the walls of the transit halls are covered with small advertising stickers for such companies as Unimex Computers, Texas Pipe and Supply, and Conroe Taxidermy.<p>By 9:30, when Stubblebine arrives -- just a half-hour before the flight -- the room is filling with smoking men in fur hats, all of them Russians. Stubblebine hasn't had a full night's sleep in a week, and his exhaustion shows on his face. His baby son, Nicholas, has been sick, and he and his Russian wife, Masha, have taken turns getting up to soothe him. Still, Stubblebine is nearly as wired as Boynton. While Boynton has lined up dealership agreements with American equipment suppliers from Diomedes' Boston office, Stubblebine has been mining his contacts from his outpost in Moscow: old computer customers from the Urals to the Baltics and computer sales agents from Siberia to the Ukraine. He hopes they can open the doors that lead to heavy-equipment customers. They've already taken a few modest orders: $250,000 worth of snowplows for an oil company in the Urals and $2,050,000 worth of forklifts to a Siberian mine. They've also just obtained a loan for $50,000 from some U.S. investors, with another $50,000 promised.<p>All that's left is the hard part: finding a customer who can buy into a multimillion-dollar deal in a country that is essentially bankrupt.<p><p>In 1991, former ambassador Robert Strauss said that if he were a younger man with a $100,000 stake, he'd come to Russia and turn it into $10 million. Back then, before the reformers failed and the economy collapsed, that might have been a reasonable notion. Russia was a market that appeared primed for Western capitalism. Strauss thought nervy Americans would sweep in and make deals right and left. Oil, gas, minerals, and timber were waiting to be extracted. An educated workforce was desperate for jobs. <p>Today, everything in Russia is up for grabs, and the rules keep changing. The country is in the midst of a revolution, a depression, and a gold rush -- all at the same time. The language is notoriously difficult to learn. Trustworthy business partners are scarce, and the Mafia is pervasive. Due diligence in the new Russia is far more complicated than simply looking at a balance sheet. An investor needs a personal intelligence apparatus to figure out which companies have enough money or potential to be worth pursuit. <p>Joking back and forth in the airport transit lounge, Boynton and Stubblebine look like an incongruous pair. Dressed in a bright red CB Sports parka, a monogrammed Lands' End bag at his side, Boynton has the chipper, displaced look of a newly arrived exchange student.  Stubblebine is harder to place; not Russian, obviously, he's often mistaken for a prosperous Latvian. The two friends grew up in Concord, Massachusetts, and discovered Moscow together on a high school class trip in 1983. Boynton traded some of their shirts, his sneakers, and his Walkman for fur hats and rubles, and cut loose on the Red Arrow overnight train to Leningrad, drinking vodka mixed with Tang and dancing in the aisles in a sheet. <p>In 1988, Stubblebine returned to Moscow to study at the Pushkin Institute during his senior year at Williams College. That year, he fell in love. Over his parents' objections, he married Masha nine months later in one of the old Soviet wedding halls .<p>Stubblebine lost $1,000 on his first business deal in Russia. It involved swapping $23,000 worth of pumpkin seeds with a German company for American computers. Despite the financial setback, he was immediately hooked on the challenges of deal-making in a country with no money, no commercial law, and no experience with capitalism. When his business started to take off, with first-year sales over $900,000 and margins between 20 percent and 30 percent, he asked his old friend Boynton to handle the supply end. Two years out of Harvard and still stuck in his father's real estate office, Boynton jumped at the partnership idea, maxing out his credit cards for a stake. They called their company Diomedes, after the two islands in the Bering Strait -- one Russian, one American -- just two miles apart, and wrote out a four-page business plan. "We were so naive," Boynton laughs today. "We didn't have a real niche or any strategy. We just thought we were smart and aggressive."<p>Boynton thought they had a winner in 1991 when some of their customers started asking for used cars. Stubblebine worked out the contracts while Boynton trooped to auto auctions all over the East Coast, snapping up late-model Ford Escorts. Diomedes shipped 200 cars to Leningrad and had another 400 to 600 in the pipeline. But then disaster struck. The letter of credit from Diomedes' main customer reached the company's Soviet bank on August 21, which just happened to be the day that tanks rolled through Moscow's streets in the attempted coup against President Mikhail Gorbachev. When the gunfire stopped, the bank and Boynton's and Stubblebine's profit had disappeared, along with the Soviet system. <p>Next, Stubblebine uncovered a Russian metal factory hidden outside of Moscow, a former defense supplier that could make high-quality stainless steel. Boynton negotiated a deal to supply Farberware, a Bronx cookware and small-appliance company, with bottoms for its frying pans -- 2 million pounds of stainless steel discs a year at $1.50 a pound with a 15 percent margin. The deal would have earned Diomedes $450,000 a year in profit.<p>It took months to arrange; Diomedes even flew the Russian plant managers over to New York to meet Peter Cameron, Farberware's chief executive officer, and cement the transaction over dinner at Manhattan's Russian Tea Room. But then, just as the Russian factory was about to begin production, its supply of nickel mysteriously vanished.<p>Politics thwarted Diomedes' biggest potential deal, an export-import swap of $5 million in forklifts for $6 million in copper that took most of 1993 to arrange. The company signed a contract with a huge Russian mining operation north of the Arctic Circle, then lined up financing from a U.S. lender, found a copper buyer in Rotterdam, and ordered 100 customized forklifts from Toyota. But then the Russian who signed the contract ended up on the wrong side of a power struggle over control of the mine. Diomedes almost sank as a result. The partnership was out of money, and Toyota insisted the company take delivery of 23 forklifts that already had been manufactured.<p>Russell Johnson, a Moscow-based Commerce Department official, estimates that some 500 U.S. companies have at least a modest presence in Russia. But not many Americans cross Stubblebine and Boynton's path. Americans "are too conservative and not as willing to take risks as the Europeans and the Orientals," Stubblebine says. Large U.S. consumer companies have blanketed the city with advertising for cat food and Uncle Ben's rice, and McDonald's is booming, now expanded to three outlets. But the expected bonanza in oil, gas, and timber has yet to materialize. <p>"You can't say yet when the country will finally stabilize; it may not be until 2010," Boynton says. "Nowhere else in the world can little guys with no-name companies like Diomedes come over and deal with the major players. We've come close on deals that could have made us a million dollars at one time. If I were working for some big company in the States, I would have job security, but I wouldn't have that chance."<p><p>Boynton's wife was worried when he left Boston; she'd read the newspaper stories about Aeroflot safety standards and all its crashes in Siberia. So he is glad she can't see what happens when their plane is finally called and all 120 passengers rush outside together. The runway is unplowed. The tires are bald. No one has deiced the plane. "Someday these guys are going to need airport plows," Boynton says happily as the crowd shoves up the slippery metal staircase.<p>"At least they're showing us which plane to get on," Stubblebine replies. "The last time I flew to Siberia, I had to go from plane to plane, yelling up to the cockpit, asking which one was going where." <p>The aircraft is jammed, walls smudged, carpets torn up, and seat belts broken or missing. "Cozy, isn't it?" Boynton jokes as Stubblebine tries to force his six feet, seven inches into 12 inches of leg space. Beer cans are popped and vodka bottles screwed open after takeoff, and the narrow aisle fills with drinkers fighting their way back to the bathrooms, past the smokers, who cram together in a blue haze in front of the toilets. But Stubblebine and Boynton work, sipping mineral water from plastic cups, reviewing papers, and making plans. Siberia is immense: four hours flying over four time zones and 2,000 miles of snow and forest and tundra to go just halfway across. <p><p>Boynton's first glimpse of Novokuznetsk is majestic: a giant construction crane, towering three stories over the airport hangar, silhouetted against the sunset. But the reality, Stubblebine tells him, is more mundane. Last year the area's major industries banded together to build an international airport, pledging dollars and rubles to a Yugoslav concern for the construction. The dollars disappeared into dozens of pockets, the rubles lost their value, and Yugoslavia dissolved; now the crane sits idle, sheathed in ice.<p>In the glory days, when the city was still called Stalinsk, the surrounding hills were the heart of the Soviet empire's industrial might, site of two of the nation's largest steel mills, and near the biggest coal mines and iron-ore deposits in the world. The rails for the Moscow metro were made here, as were the armor for the tanks that rolled into Berlin at the end of World War II and the construction rods for the Soviet missile silos. <p>Vladimir Kissel, the partners' 47-year-old Russian technical advisor, is waiting for them at the airport gate -- impatiently. A welcome dinner for "important visiting delegations" is scheduled to start in an hour and is part of a trade show they have come to attend. Their presence is absolutely required. Kissel is a former Diomedes computer customer who is now a part-time Diomedes employee. Still officially a lab director at Moscow's Institute of Steel and Alloys, he has friends and former colleagues throughout the industry. <p>Kissel had arrived in Novokuznetsk a day early to finalize meetings and to hire a car. Although crime in the provinces isn't yet as bad as it is in Moscow, Kissel has assured them their driver will be carrying a gun. <p>The Evening of Getting Acquainted, the trade show's kickoff event, is well underway. A dozen Russian men in their 50s and 60s line one side of a long table, while on the other side sit members of visiting delegations, including a man from a German construction company, a French business consultant, and an Italian financial advisor. The two young Americans and Kissel sit at the end of the long table, which is awash in platters of red caviar on brown bread, deviled eggs, beets, pickles, herring, cold chicken, kielbasa, and cheese. <p>This is a formal affair: The vodka is 90 proof, tumblers turned bottoms up with each toast. One by one the Russian officials get up and welcome their foreign guests in the endless exhortatory style learned over years of party congresses. Then it is the guests' turn. Stubblebine alone speaks without a translator, introducing Boynton as "the president of Diomedes, who has come to this occasion of the trade fair all the way from Boston."<p>Finally, the organizer gets up, steadying himself on his chair as he calls for order. "I want to apologize," Vladimir Tabatchnikov, the show's director general, says. "There were supposed to be more important people with us tonight, but they weren't able to travel here because of the current economic conditions." He concludes, however, in pep rally fashion: "Let us make Novokuznetsk a NovoPittsburgh! Or a NovoNew York! Or a NovoLondon!"<p>"It's all such grandiose bullshit," Stubblebine says quietly as the organizer sits down, apparently overcome by emotion. "And we'll have to listen to it 13 more times for each potential sale."<p>"It's just like Rotary," Boynton says.<p>The next morning's breakfast is a cardiologist's delight: sausage, cheese, potatoes and chicken in gravy, and pancakes stuffed with sour cottage cheese. The bill for the meal is 22,000 rubles --  under $14 -- cheap by Moscow standards, where prices are higher than in New York, but a good gauge of Russian inflation. In 1989, breakfast would have cost less than $1, and 22,000 rubles would have bought a Russian-made car. <p>Zapsib, today's sales call, looks like a hot prospect. The largest steel factory in Novokuznetsk, it was privatized two years ago and is Russia's major supplier of construction rebar. It is even exporting, modestly, and the mill is running on all three shifts. <p>Until two years ago, Russian purchasing was centralized in Moscow, where officials would decide each year how many forklifts the country needed and who should get them. Today, with central planning dead, equipment manufacturers have no way of finding who needs or uses their products, while Russian factories, newly privatized, have to learn how to find and negotiate for equipment. <p>Boynton and Stubblebine have discovered that, until 1992, most of Russia's forklifts and lift trucks were imported from Bulgaria, some 100,000 units annually. These were cheap machines that rarely lasted more than a year. Plus, Bulgaria is now going through its own convulsions, and forklift production has fallen below 15,000 units annually, so the potential for others to win business appears huge. Boynton had looked for machines to sell that would be durable enough to cope with the Russian climate. Diomedes was already, inadvertently, a Toyota agent. Taylor Machine Works, a $95 million manufacturer in Louisville, Mississippi, gave the partners exclusive rights to market its 10- to 70-ton lift trucks, list price starting at $60,000, plus transportation. Boynton also worked out a similar arrangement with Clark Material Handling in Lexington, Kentucky, which makes less expensive one- to six-ton lift machines. <p>To find buyers, meanwhile, Stubblebine relies on telex, sending off 400 messages to identify 20 prospects, a Russian variant of direct mail. There are no phone books, no switchboards at most companies, no way of knowing if mail gets through. Zapsib is still a bureaucracy, requiring Stubblebine to obtain approval from six levels of hierarchy. He has been climbing this ladder since a meeting last summer with a Zapsib purchasing official. Today's call on Gennady Arykov, Zapsib's deputy general manager, is his first face-to-face contact with a decision maker.<p>Russians have been ambivalent about Western merchants since the days of Ivan the Terrible, and are particularly wary of carpetbaggers today. They're unfamiliar with the idea of outside investors earning a return, sensitive to their own relative weakness, and quick to take affront. Stubblebine and Boynton are young; they'll have to win Gennady Arykov's trust and convince him they have his long-term best interests at heart. Boynton brings a more concrete agenda. He wants information. Concepts like return on investment and projected earnings are new to the Russians; most don't have those kinds of numbers, don't know how to find them, and wouldn't share them if they did. But Boynton needs at least a few facts to figure out whether or not a deal can work. <p>As they drive into Zapsib, Boynton imagines Pittsburgh 25 years ago. The complex spreads over 19 square miles, 35,000 workers at 81 plants, seven coke ovens, three open-hearth furnaces, five converters, four rolling mills, and a wire factory, vertically integrated and apparently self-contained. Before 1989, Zapsib's only concern was meeting Moscow's production quotas; today, with privatization of the steel industry nearly 80 percent complete, its managers have to find their own raw materials and paying customers. That's hard, with 90 percent of the enterprises in Russia functionally bankrupt. Steel output has dropped 40 percent in the last four years, while the cost of industrywide modernization has risen from an estimated $8 billion to $12 billion. <p>What is to be done, they ask in Moscow: keep the plants afloat with subsidies, risking even higher inflation and the specter of political unrest, or let most of them die, leaving many more millions newly unemployed and the specter of even worse unrest? As far as Boynton is concerned, it doesn't matter: Zapsib could be one of the few survivors, and a potential customer, under either scenario. He needs to know what is happening today. What is Zapsib's annual investment plan? Are forklifts part of it? And, most important, how does Zapsib expect to pay?<p>Gennady Arykov surprises Boynton and Stubblebine. They'd expected a Soviet-era apparatchik, unpolished and secretive, but the deputy general manager is glad to talk numbers. With his open smile, tailored suit, and Rolex, he could pass for a senior American executive. His office is done in Italian leather with a laser printer, fax, two phones, and a TV, along with a radio broadcasting the plant's daily production report. "Everything is running smoothly, except the bread factory," he tells them. It hasn't yet gotten the flour it was promised and has shut down. <p>Stubblebine outlines Diomedes's history and describes the Taylor and Clark forklifts they have come to sell. "We have a few proposals we want to discuss with you, freely and frankly," he concludes. "But first we'd like to understand what problems you have with your business."<p>The Quest: To Turn $100,000 Into $10 Million ... In Siberia<p>By Curtis Hartman<p>It's snowing, the temperature is minus 27 degrees celsius, and sunrise has yet to come to Moscow as John Boynton steps out of his hotel and into a cab on this February morning. The 28-year-old president of Diomedes Inc. is headed for the airport and Aeroflot Flight 209, due to depart at ten o'clock for the Siberian city of Novokuznetsk. The cab driver peers silently through a defrosted half-moon on the icy windshield as he punches the accelerator. The view outside is bleak: block after squat block without billboard, neon sign, or lighted storefront. Here and there, small groups of workers shiver patiently in lines at the bus stands. The cab weaves around cars abandoned in the snowy streets, then passes though miles of gigantic flats laid out in concentric rings.<p>Boynton is so full of adrenaline he can hardly sit still in the rattling cab. He flew in from Boston only last night, but he's been up for hours already, bundled in his long underwear against the cold, planning, making notes, strategizing an assault on the frontiers of capitalism. For more than four years, he and his Moscow-based partner and high school best friend, Robert Stubblebine, have been on an elusive quest: to strike it rich in Russia's bewildering free-market economy. Already, the two aspiring carpetbaggers have pursued more than a dozen schemes in post-Soviet Russia, but so far they've had only limited success. They've sold used cars and auto parts, run a marketing consulting firm, sourced walnuts for Ben & Jerry's ice cream, and traded in rugs, tungsten, bee venom, and vodka. They've had to cope with Russian privatization and the start of reform, an attempted coup, an attempted putsch, and the defeat of reform. Their biggest success to date involves the sale of U.S.-made computers. But hawking technology has been anything but a bonanza; it's paid just enough to keep alive hope of a big score just around the corner. <p>Boynton is convinced the frozen reaches of the east will yield the long-awaited breakthrough. He and Stubblebine will be boarding a creaky Aeroflot jet (just weeks prior to their trip, an Aeroflot plane crashed in Siberia, killing all 120 passengers) and flying into deepest, coldest Siberia. Novokuznetsk, today a decaying industrial town, was once the industrial heart of the Soviet empire. If Russia is to rise again as an economic player of any importance, towns like Novokuznetsk must be reborn. And Boynton and Stubblebine figure that to do that Russians will need some basic heavy equipment -- like forklifts and snowplows. <p>Boynton gets to the airport before his partner. Inside the Aeroflot terminal, there are no other foreigners in sight, but the walls of the transit halls are covered with small advertising stickers for such companies as Unimex Computers, Texas Pipe and Supply, and Conroe Taxidermy.<p>By 9:30, when Stubblebine arrives -- just a half-hour before the flight -- the room is filling with smoking men in fur hats, all of them Russians. Stubblebine hasn't had a full night's sleep in a week, and his exhaustion shows on his face. His baby son, Nicholas, has been sick, and he and his Russian wife, Masha, have taken turns getting up to soothe him. Still, Stubblebine is nearly as wired as Boynton. While Boynton has lined up dealership agreements with American equipment suppliers from Diomedes' Boston office, Stubblebine has been mining his contacts from his outpost in Moscow: old computer customers from the Urals to the Baltics and computer sales agents from Siberia to the Ukraine. He hopes they can open the doors that lead to heavy-equipment customers. They've already taken a few modest orders: $250,000 worth of snowplows for an oil company in the Urals and $2,050,000 worth of forklifts to a Siberian mine. They've also just obtained a loan for $50,000 from some U.S. investors, with another $50,000 promised.<p>All that's left is the hard part: finding a customer who can buy into a multimillion-dollar deal in a country that is essentially bankrupt.<p><p>In 1991, former ambassador Robert Strauss said that if he were a younger man with a $100,000 stake, he'd come to Russia and turn it into $10 million. Back then, before the reformers failed and the economy collapsed, that might have been a reasonable notion. Russia was a market that appeared primed for Western capitalism. Strauss thought nervy Americans would sweep in and make deals right and left. Oil, gas, minerals, and timber were waiting to be extracted. An educated workforce was desperate for jobs. <p>Today, everything in Russia is up for grabs, and the rules keep changing. The country is in the midst of a revolution, a depression, and a gold rush -- all at the same time. The language is notoriously difficult to learn. Trustworthy business partners are scarce, and the Mafia is pervasive. Due diligence in the new Russia is far more complicated than simply looking at a balance sheet. An investor needs a personal intelligence apparatus to figure out which companies have enough money or potential to be worth pursuit. <p>Joking back and forth in the airport transit lounge, Boynton and Stubblebine look like an incongruous pair. Dressed in a bright red CB Sports parka, a monogrammed Lands' End bag at his side, Boynton has the chipper, displaced look of a newly arrived exchange student.  Stubblebine is harder to place; not Russian, obviously, he's often mistaken for a prosperous Latvian. The two friends grew up in Concord, Massachusetts, and discovered Moscow together on a high school class trip in 1983. Boynton traded some of their shirts, his sneakers, and his Walkman for fur hats and rubles, and cut loose on the Red Arrow overnight train to Leningrad, drinking vodka mixed with Tang and dancing in the aisles in a sheet. <p>In 1988, Stubblebine returned to Moscow to study at the Pushkin Institute during his senior year at Williams College. That year, he fell in love. Over his parents' objections, he married Masha nine months later in one of the old Soviet wedding halls .<p>Stubblebine lost $1,000 on his first business deal in Russia. It involved swapping $23,000 worth of pumpkin seeds with a German company for American computers. Despite the financial setback, he was immediately hooked on the challenges of deal-making in a country with no money, no commercial law, and no experience with capitalism. When his business started to take off, with first-year sales over $900,000 and margins between 20 percent and 30 percent, he asked his old friend Boynton to handle the supply end. Two years out of Harvard and still stuck in his father's real estate office, Boynton jumped at the partnership idea, maxing out his credit cards for a stake. They called their company Diomedes, after the two islands in the Bering Strait -- one Russian, one American -- just two miles apart, and wrote out a four-page business plan. "We were so naive," Boynton laughs today. "We didn't have a real niche or any strategy. We just thought we were smart and aggressive."<p>Boynton thought they had a winner in 1991 when some of their customers started asking for used cars. Stubblebine worked out the contracts while Boynton trooped to auto auctions all over the East Coast, snapping up late-model Ford Escorts. Diomedes shipped 200 cars to Leningrad and had another 400 to 600 in the pipeline. But then disaster struck. The letter of credit from Diomedes' main customer reached the company's Soviet bank on August 21, which just happened to be the day that tanks rolled through Moscow's streets in the attempted coup against President Mikhail Gorbachev. When the gunfire stopped, the bank and Boynton's and Stubblebine's profit had disappeared, along with the Soviet system. <p>Next, Stubblebine uncovered a Russian metal factory hidden outside of Moscow, a former defense supplier that could make high-quality stainless steel. Boynton negotiated a deal to supply Farberware, a Bronx cookware and small-appliance company, with bottoms for its frying pans -- 2 million pounds of stainless steel discs a year at $1.50 a pound with a 15 percent margin. The deal would have earned Diomedes $450,000 a year in profit.<p>It took months to arrange; Diomedes even flew the Russian plant managers over to New York to meet Peter Cameron, Farberware's chief executive officer, and cement the transaction over dinner at Manhattan's Russian Tea Room. But then, just as the Russian factory was about to begin production, its supply of nickel mysteriously vanished.<p>Politics thwarted Diomedes' biggest potential deal, an export-import swap of $5 million in forklifts for $6 million in copper that took most of 1993 to arrange. The company signed a contract with a huge Russian mining operation north of the Arctic Circle, then lined up financing from a U.S. lender, found a copper buyer in Rotterdam, and ordered 100 customized forklifts from Toyota. But then the Russian who signed the contract ended up on the wrong side of a power struggle over control of the mine. Diomedes almost sank as a result. The partnership was out of money, and Toyota insisted the company take delivery of 23 forklifts that already had been manufactured.<p>Russell Johnson, a Moscow-based Commerce Department official, estimates that some 500 U.S. companies have at least a modest presence in Russia. But not many Americans cross Stubblebine and Boynton's path. Americans "are too conservative and not as willing to take risks as the Europeans and the Orientals," Stubblebine says. Large U.S. consumer companies have blanketed the city with advertising for cat food and Uncle Ben's rice, and McDonald's is booming, now expanded to three outlets. But the expected bonanza in oil, gas, and timber has yet to materialize. <p>"You can't say yet when the country will finally stabilize; it may not be until 2010," Boynton says. "Nowhere else in the world can little guys with no-name companies like Diomedes come over and deal with the major players. We've come close on deals that could have made us a million dollars at one time. If I were working for some big company in the States, I would have job security, but I wouldn't have that chance."<p><p>Boynton's wife was worried when he left Boston; she'd read the newspaper stories about Aeroflot safety standards and all its crashes in Siberia. So he is glad she can't see what happens when their plane is finally called and all 120 passengers rush outside together. The runway is unplowed. The tires are bald. No one has deiced the plane. "Someday these guys are going to need airport plows," Boynton says happily as the crowd shoves up the slippery metal staircase.<p>"At least they're showing us which plane to get on," Stubblebine replies. "The last time I flew to Siberia, I had to go from plane to plane, yelling up to the cockpit, asking which one was going where." <p>The aircraft is jammed, walls smudged, carpets torn up, and seat belts broken or missing. "Cozy, isn't it?" Boynton jokes as Stubblebine tries to force his six feet, seven inches into 12 inches of leg space. Beer cans are popped and vodka bottles screwed open after takeoff, and the narrow aisle fills with drinkers fighting their way back to the bathrooms, past the smokers, who cram together in a blue haze in front of the toilets. But Stubblebine and Boynton work, sipping mineral water from plastic cups, reviewing papers, and making plans. Siberia is immense: four hours flying over four time zones and 2,000 miles of snow and forest and tundra to go just halfway across. <p><p>Boynton's first glimpse of Novokuznetsk is majestic: a giant construction crane, towering three stories over the airport hangar, silhouetted against the sunset. But the reality, Stubblebine tells him, is more mundane. Last year the area's major industries banded together to build an international airport, pledging dollars and rubles to a Yugoslav concern for the construction. The dollars disappeared into dozens of pockets, the rubles lost their value, and Yugoslavia dissolved; now the crane sits idle, sheathed in ice.<p>In the glory days, when the city was still called Stalinsk, the surrounding hills were the heart of the Soviet empire's industrial might, site of two of the nation's largest steel mills, and near the biggest coal mines and iron-ore deposits in the world. The rails for the Moscow metro were made here, as were the armor for the tanks that rolled into Berlin at the end of World War II and the construction rods for the Soviet missile silos. <p>Vladimir Kissel, the partners' 47-year-old Russian technical advisor, is waiting for them at the airport gate -- impatiently. A welcome dinner for "important visiting delegations" is scheduled to start in an hour and is part of a trade show they have come to attend. Their presence is absolutely required. Kissel is a former Diomedes computer customer who is now a part-time Diomedes employee. Still officially a lab director at Moscow's Institute of Steel and Alloys, he has friends and former colleagues throughout the industry. <p>Kissel had arrived in Novokuznetsk a day early to finalize meetings and to hire a car. Although crime in the provinces isn't yet as bad as it is in Moscow, Kissel has assured them their driver will be carrying a gun. <p>The Evening of Getting Acquainted, the trade show's kickoff event, is well underway. A dozen Russian men in their 50s and 60s line one side of a long table, while on the other side sit members of visiting delegations, including a man from a German construction company, a French business consultant, and an Italian financial advisor. The two young Americans and Kissel sit at the end of the long table, which is awash in platters of red caviar on brown bread, deviled eggs, beets, pickles, herring, cold chicken, kielbasa, and cheese. <p>This is a formal affair: The vodka is 90 proof, tumblers turned bottoms up with each toast. One by one the Russian officials get up and welcome their foreign guests in the endless exhortatory style learned over years of party congresses. Then it is the guests' turn. Stubblebine alone speaks without a translator, introducing Boynton as "the president of Diomedes, who has come to this occasion of the trade fair all the way from Boston."<p>Finally, the organizer gets up, steadying himself on his chair as he calls for order. "I want to apologize," Vladimir Tabatchnikov, the show's director general, says. "There were supposed to be more important people with us tonight, but they weren't able to travel here because of the current economic conditions." He concludes, however, in pep rally fashion: "Let us make Novokuznetsk a NovoPittsburgh! Or a NovoNew York! Or a NovoLondon!"<p>"It's all such grandiose bullshit," Stubblebine says quietly as the organizer sits down, apparently overcome by emotion. "And we'll have to listen to it 13 more times for each potential sale."<p>"It's just like Rotary," Boynton says.<p>The next morning's breakfast is a cardiologist's delight: sausage, cheese, potatoes and chicken in gravy, and pancakes stuffed with sour cottage cheese. The bill for the meal is 22,000 rubles --  under $14 -- cheap by Moscow standards, where prices are higher than in New York, but a good gauge of Russian inflation. In 1989, breakfast would have cost less than $1, and 22,000 rubles would have bought a Russian-made car. <p>Zapsib, today's sales call, looks like a hot prospect. The largest steel factory in Novokuznetsk, it was privatized two years ago and is Russia's major supplier of construction rebar. It is even exporting, modestly, and the mill is running on all three shifts. <p>Until two years ago, Russian purchasing was centralized in Moscow, where officials would decide each year how many forklifts the country needed and who should get them. Today, with central planning dead, equipment manufacturers have no way of finding who needs or uses their products, while Russian factories, newly privatized, have to learn how to find and negotiate for equipment. <p>Boynton and Stubblebine have discovered that, until 1992, most of Russia's forklifts and lift trucks were imported from Bulgaria, some 100,000 units annually. These were cheap machines that rarely lasted more than a year. Plus, Bulgaria is now going through its own convulsions, and forklift production has fallen below 15,000 units annually, so the potential for others to win business appears huge. Boynton had looked for machines to sell that would be durable enough to cope with the Russian climate. Diomedes was already, inadvertently, a Toyota agent. Taylor Machine Works, a $95 million manufacturer in Louisville, Mississippi, gave the partners exclusive rights to market its 10- to 70-ton lift trucks, list price starting at $60,000, plus transportation. Boynton also worked out a similar arrangement with Clark Material Handling in Lexington, Kentucky, which makes less expensive one- to six-ton lift machines. <p>To find buyers, meanwhile, Stubblebine relies on telex, sending off 400 messages to identify 20 prospects, a Russian variant of direct mail. There are no phone books, no switchboards at most companies, no way of knowing if mail gets through. Zapsib is still a bureaucracy, requiring Stubblebine to obtain approval from six levels of hierarchy. He has been climbing this ladder since a meeting last summer with a Zapsib purchasing official. Today's call on Gennady Arykov, Zapsib's deputy general manager, is his first face-to-face contact with a decision maker.<p>Russians have been ambivalent about Western merchants since the days of Ivan the Terrible, and are particularly wary of carpetbaggers today. They're unfamiliar with the idea of outside investors earning a return, sensitive to their own relative weakness, and quick to take affront. Stubblebine and Boynton are young; they'll have to win Gennady Arykov's trust and convince him they have his long-term best interests at heart. Boynton brings a more concrete agenda. He wants information. Concepts like return on investment and projected earnings are new to the Russians; most don't have those kinds of numbers, don't know how to find them, and wouldn't share them if they did. But Boynton needs at least a few facts to figure out whether or not a deal can work. <p>As they drive into Zapsib, Boynton imagines Pittsburgh 25 years ago. The complex spreads over 19 square miles, 35,000 workers at 81 plants, seven coke ovens, three open-hearth furnaces, five converters, four rolling mills, and a wire factory, vertically integrated and apparently self-contained. Before 1989, Zapsib's only concern was meeting Moscow's production quotas; today, with privatization of the steel industry nearly 80 percent complete, its managers have to find their own raw materials and paying customers. That's hard, with 90 percent of the enterprises in Russia functionally bankrupt. Steel output has dropped 40 percent in the last four years, while the cost of industrywide modernization has risen from an estimated $8 billion to $12 billion. <p>What is to be done, they ask in Moscow: keep the plants afloat with subsidies, risking even higher inflation and the specter of political unrest, or let most of them die, leaving many more millions newly unemployed and the specter of even worse unrest? As far as Boynton is concerned, it doesn't matter: Zapsib could be one of the few survivors, and a potential customer, under either scenario. He needs to know what is happening today. What is Zapsib's annual investment plan? Are forklifts part of it? And, most important, how does Zapsib expect to pay?<p>Gennady Arykov surprises Boynton and Stubblebine. They'd expected a Soviet-era apparatchik, unpolished and secretive, but the deputy general manager is glad to talk numbers. With his open smile, tailored suit, and Rolex, he could pass for a senior American executive. His office is done in Italian leather with a laser printer, fax, two phones, and a TV, along with a radio broadcasting the plant's daily production report. "Everything is running smoothly, except the bread factory," he tells them. It hasn't yet gotten the flour it was promised and has shut down. <p>Stubblebine outlines Diomedes's history and describes the Taylor and Clark forklifts they have come to sell. "We have a few proposals we want to discuss with you, freely and frankly," he concludes. "But first we'd like to understand what problems you have with your business."<p>
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

