<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-The Recession That Ate Tokyo</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-The Recession That Ate Tokyo</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The sudden visibility of discount stores signals a major shift in Japan's economic and political balance of power.<p>By Gregory J. Millman<p>Where years of U.S. jawboning and a score of trade missions have failed, the deep, painful, and shocking Japanese recession has succeeded. Two years of economic turmoil have done more to open Japan to imports than two decades of U.S. pressure. And that's good news both for those who watch U.S. exports and those who worry about the long-term health of the world economy.<p>But this recession is accelerating a microeconomic revolution that will do far more than change Japan's trade balance. It's producing a Japanese consumer startlingly sensitive to prices. New companies, practicing U.S.-style discounting, are grabbing a larger and larger share of the market. As some old-line companies shrink into insignificance, the financial relationships that have kept the Liberal Democratic Party in power have begun to erode, and the unquestioned Japanese consensus on public and private spending is being questioned. The next economic upturn will reveal a profoundly and unpredictably different Japan.<p>The pain that has produced this change is clearly visible on the streets of Tokyo. Sanya, a grimy, gray quarter of Tokyo, is the shock absorber of Japan's economy. Here, just beyond the district that houses the burakumin, Japan's caste of untouchables, the depth of the country's two-year-old recession can be measured in the milling numbers of directionless men waiting in loose queues on street corners for construction contractors who don't come anymore.<p>The scene is a common one in the third world or even in the inner cities of the United States, but shocking after a decade in which prosperity seemed assured in Japan. From a small friary next door to a safe house belonging to Japan's feared gangsters, the yakuza, Brother Nathaniel of Mother Teresa's Missionaries of Charity helps serve a free hot meal every Saturday. About 300 men begin to line up in the snowy alleyway hours before the doors open. The number of men living on the streets has doubled here in the past year, Brother Nathaniel says, and they are getting younger.<p>Outside of Sanya, the effects of the country's  recession are more subtle but just as powerful. A young man leaving Tokyo on an early-evening train says he works for an air-cargo company and he used to get home at 9 p.m. Now he gets home at 7. The company cut his hours and his pay to cope with the decline in business.<p>Companies aren't spending like they used to. Everyone remarks how easy it is right now to get a taxi at night in downtown Tokyo. In the good old days, that was impossible - companies had booked them all for drinking parties. Now, at lunch hour and in the evenings, in plastic-roofed noodle stalls and tempura stands under the railroad tracks, suit-and-tie-wearing salarymen eat standing up and pay out of their own pockets. During the boom years, they lounged in posh restaurants on the company tab. "Consumption has gone completely grunge," grumbles Peter Tasker, a Tokyo-based analyst at investment banker Kleinwort Benson.<p>Women's magazines that used to feature dream shopping trips to Paris now advise their readers how to dress stylishly on a budget. Yoshinoya Beef Bowl, a clean, no-frills eatery where a huge bowl of beef and rice costs only 680 yen ($6.40), is thriving. Skylark, a Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) company, expanded down-market from its already inexpensive Skylark restaurants to the Gusto chain, which offers even more inexpensive fare. Investors obviously endorse the strategy - Skylark shares outperformed the TSE average by 65 percent in 1993.<p>Nowhere is the change more obvious than at Kawachiya, a liquor discounter that sells imports like Jack Daniel's for less than half of what department stores charge. "The price is great," says Tatsuo Kishi, a vice president at <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan Bank</b></a>'s Tokyo branch. But before the recession, low prices didn't matter. "The Kawachiya store in my neighborhood used to be empty," says Kishi, "but nowadays it's always packed." <p>For decades, would-be exporters to Japan have complained that the complicated distribution system shuts foreign products out of the retail market no matter what their price. The Japanese consumer paid more for almost everything - Japanese-manufactured spark plugs sell for $2.82 in Japan and $1.16 in the U.S.; a U.S.-made electric shaver sells for $90.14 in Japan and just $44.95 in the U.S. Thanks to the recession, that system is crumbling. In January, one evening news program in Tokyo ran a lengthy report on a novel phenomenon: the discount store. Reporters interviewed delighted consumers pushing full shopping carts under big yellow sale signs.<p>The Robespierre of this price revolution is Goro Aoyama, president of Aoyama Trading. Aoyama started out building small roadside stores in the 1980s, selling suits to suburban salarymen for as little at 30,000 yen ($283). By 1993, Aoyama was selling 10 million suits a year - that's one out of ten suits sold in Japan. Although Aoyama sells at lower prices than department stores, he gets higher margins - more than 50 percent. The average department store is lucky to get 20 percent. <p>Aoyama's secrets are commonplace in U.S. retailing. Aoyama imports a quarter of the suits he sells. He has factories locked into exclusive supply contracts, cutting out several layers of middlemen. The company's stock price has nearly quintupled since 1989. <p>End runs around the traditional supply-and-distribution system have helped make a success of companies besides Aoyama, says Hirokazu Ishii, a retail analyst at Nomura Research International. Shimamura sells basic women's underwear cheap. Senshukai is a catalog retailer of upmarket women's wear. Shimamura outperformed the Tokyo Stock Exchange Index by nearly 23 percent last year; Senshukai beat the index by 57 percent.<p>There's more to life than clothes, of course. There's cars. "One of my best recommendations is Autobacs Seven," says Kaori Hasegawa, Salomon Brothers vice president for equity research in Tokyo. Autobacs undersells its competitors on everything auto-related, from oil changes to computerized navigation systems.<p>Hasegawa also likes Tsutsumi Jewelry, a small company sold over-the-counter. Tsutsumi imports gold and gemstones directly from India. Drawn in by super bargains like earrings for merely 480 yen a pair ($4.52), Tsutsumi's customers spend an average of 30,000 yen ($283) each. "It's the kind of place where I'd shop for myself, my mom, or my sister," says Hasegawa. <p>Like many affluent young Japanese women, Hasegawa used to fly to Hawaii once a year and stock up on cosmetics. The savings on a year's supply made the trip a bargain - for example, a European perfume that cost $57 in the U.S. cost $81 in Japan. Now the trip would be more difficult to justify. The liquor retailer Kawachiya has begun going head to head with Shiseido, Japan's leading cosmetics manufacturer, by selling cosmetics for less than the manufacturer's recommended retail price. <p>The price wars are creating new opportunities for foreign brands, as control shifts from manufacturers to retailers. Traditionally, manufacturers were able to control prices by cutting off supplies to retailers who undercut the manufacturer's suggested retail price. Demand was usually greater than supply. The recession reversed the supply-demand equation. Meanwhile, the stronger yen made imports a better bargain for consumers.<p>Although some optimists expect a turnaround in Japan's economic statistics by year end, no one expects a living, breathing recovery for at least a year or two. Professor Takaaki Wakasugi of Tokyo University thinks it might be another six years before the economic problems are over. And the microeconomic revolution won't end when the economy eventually turns.<p>The new discount stores are just the most visible signs of a profound shift in the balance of power in Japan. Japanese consumers are voting with their wallets against a system that charges them too much. They aspire to the higher standard of living that many of them have seen in their travels, and they're willing to flex their economic muscle to achieve it.<p>It will take time. Don't expect TV news reports tomorrow of consumers storming the Diet, Japan's parliament, with demands for cheap rice and thick Angus steaks. Japan's microeconomic revolution will be more like a protracted guerrilla campaign that gathers strength on the economic periphery before laying siege to the central seats of power. In some cases - food is the best example - price will still be second to national security. Many Japanese still remember that President Nixon embargoed soybeans and shudder to think what would happen if a Japan dependent on food imports faced a similar embargo on rice.<p>But the old consensus in which consumers accepted overpriced goods and undersized houses as the cost of prosperity is crumbling. That consensus worked for the same reason any compromise works: Everyone got something. Farmers and manufacturers had protection, politicians had votes, and consumers had jobs. Now the recession is dealing Japan's workers out. They have less to gain from the compromise, and they are rejecting it both when they shop and when they vote.<p>Last year's electoral defeat of the Liberal Democratic Party shook up the carefully balanced structure of compromise but did not demolish it. Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa may be committed to deregulation, but the bureaucrats and the interest groups the regulations protect are still fighting hard to keep their special protections. As the recession grinds on, they will argue that this is no time for the government to relax protection.<p>Consumers will ultimately decide this debate. This group is the new face at the table of power in Japan, and it doesn't share the interests of the established players. The long-term health and success of big companies aren't so important to people who are losing what they thought were lifetime jobs at those companies. Retirees in rapidly graying Japan know that the strong yen makes it harder for Japanese companies to compete, but they also know that it makes their pensions go further.<p>Consumers can cast two ballots for change: one at the checkout counter and another at the voting booth. They are throwing away an old distribution system by not buying from it and old politicians by not voting for them.<p>Viewed this way, the long-term success of the microeconomic revolution seems almost assured. There will be a new economic organization, and in that new organization consumers will have the right to decide how much quality they want and for what price. That won't be good news for all U.S. exporters - only for those who can win a fair fight.
---------------
Gregory Millman is writing a book on the international financial markets for the Free Press. He visited Tokyo in January.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

