<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Dialing for Dollars in Phone Stocks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Dialing for Dollars in Phone Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>West is best among the world's phone companies<p>By Derrick Niederman<p>Way off the spreadsheets that most securities analysts use, and way off the New York Stock Exchange too, there's an intriguing emerging-market telephone speculation called Telebras. It's the Brazilian telephone company. Telebras and western-hemisphere telephone stocks in general now seem much more attractive as investments, or speculations, than those in the Pacific Basin.<p>That's a conclusion reached by ranking telephone companies using two measurements. One is the number of telephone lines in service per 100 residents--let's call it teledensity. The other is the market capitalization of the company divided by the number of installed lines. The lower the teledensity, the greater a market's potential for growth. The greater the market cap per line, the greater the probability that investors are hyping the potential.<p>With around 8 telephone lines for every 100 people, Mexico seems to be one of the least developed markets around. But similar low rates of market penetration also apply to Brazil, Chile, and Argentina. China has less than one line per 100 residents.<p>These figures correlate roughly with per capita incomes. To realize their potential, the telephone companies need economies with solid production gains and rising incomes. When Telefonos de Mexico was listed on the New York Stock Exchange three years ago, Mexico's teledensity was 6.6 percent. Since then, a stronger economy with lower inflation has stimulated the telephone business, and teledensity has increased by 21 percent. In response, Telmex shares have more than tripled.<p>Shrewd investors should look for either low prices per line, representing a reasonable price for the business, or a low teledensity, representing potential. It would be unrealistic to expect both, simply because the fewer the lines already installed the greater the capital investment per line. Looking at conventional price-to-earnings ratios helps complete the profile.<p>Such measures suggest that U.S. investors should stick to their part of the world. Valuations for Asian telecommunications companies are much more frothy than their western counterparts. Hong Kong Telecommunications is a comparatively expensive stock, valued at $7,300 per installed line, nearly 20 times expected 1994 earnings. That doesn't suggest much near-term price growth. Hong Kong Telecom's desirability as a long-term holding depends on its success in mainland China. As of last year, China accounted for 47 percent of Hong Kong Telecom's international traffic.<p>By comparison, Telefonos de Mexico still looks good. While its capitalization relative to installed lines is no bargain, its profit margins are high and its price-to-earnings ratio appealing. Telmex shares have been trading at less than ten times expected 1994 earnings of $7 a share; the stock has dropped to $63, down from its 52-week high of around $76. Telmex's margins will shrink in 1997, when it loses its long-distance monopoly in Mexico. But one investment firm believes it will remain the sole supplier of local phone services.<p>Telefonica de Espana also looks like a buy at its current market valuation, just over ten times expected 1994 earnings, $973 per installed line. Through an investment in Telefonica Internacional, the company has large interests in Latin America: 8 percent of the Argentine phone company, 43 percent of Chile's, 6.4 percent of Venezuela's, and 79 percent of Puerto Rico's. Those holdings account for nearly one quarter of Telefonica de Espana's market capitalization, which means that the price investors pay for the Spanish franchise is even cheaper than it appears.<p>For the truly adventurous, there's Telebras. With its stock trading at about $1,300 per installed line, and just seven lines per 100 people, Telebras is one of the cheapest phone stocks around, statistically speaking. Of course there are negatives; otherwise the stock wouldn't be so cheap. Illiquidity and high inflation, with an associated currency risk, come quickly to mind. Yet it could continue to grow, and grow profitably, for years to come.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
