<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Running With the Bulls in Brazil</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Running With the Bulls in Brazil</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Why one of the hottest markets looks undervalued<p>By Liliana Nealon<p>Recent downdrafts in Brazilian stocks present nervy investors with an interesting opportunity. Any decline in prices on Bovespa, Sao Paolo's volatile stock exchange, looks to some investors like the beginning of a bear market in Brazil. After all, investors raked in gains of 111 percent in these stocks last year and another 27 percent in the first ten weeks of this year. Even so, the Brazilian stock market is by no means the world's most overvalued. It is, in fact, undervalued, if measured against other international bourses. <p>Most companies in the Bovespa trade at about 75 percent of their book values. Compare this to the S&P 500, which currently trades at more than three times book value. Price-to-earnings ratios today average 20 in Brazil. Even though that number is rising, it remains lower than the p/e's in many other emerging markets; it's just under the U.S.'s average of 21. Price - to - cash-flow ratios in Brazilian equities are less than 8 on average, compared with ratios as high as 27 for other emerging markets and 11 in the U.S. <p>American investors have obviously discovered Brazil. Net purchases of Brazilian equities by U.S. investors amounted to some $1.4 billion in the first nine months of 1993, according to the investment firm of S. G. Warburg.  Also during that period, Americans purchased stocks worth 1.4 percent of Brazil's total stock market capitalization.  <p>The cloud on the horizon in Brazil is inflation, the country's biggest and most persistent problem. Since 1987, inflation in Brazil has increased more than 800 percent annually; it's currently running at around 40 percent per month. <p>"I would not know what it would be like to live without inflation," says Nami Tavares Neneas, senior investment analyst at Banco Tendencia in Sao Paolo. Indeed, Brazilians are masters at adapting and adjusting to inflation, indexing, and keeping ahead of rising prices. But inflation takes its toll on the business environment, creating high interest rates and currency concerns as well as uncertainty over future product pricing. <p>The country's privatization and economic plans, however, have raised investors' confidence in Brazil. The first part of the country's economic-stabilization plan only recently passed Brazil's congress. It includes a temporary Brazilian currency - indexed to the U.S. dollar - known as the URV, which was created in early March. Once the currency is stabilized, new and beneficial debt agreements with the international community should follow. <p>A further improvement in Brazil's economic situation will come as a result of the privatization of around ten government-owned companies this year. These deals will provide much-needed cash for the government and should create additional investment opportunities for investors, both foreign and domestic. The Brazilian economy should grow more than 8 percent this year. <p>Between 1959 and 1980, Brazil experienced strong economic growth, but then the economy, weighed down by hyperinflation, began to falter. Per capita GDP in 1992 was actually 9 percent lower than in 1980.<p>Now that Brazil's economy appears back on track, can investors capitalize on the nation's turnaround? Besides the highly publicized Brazil Fund and the Brazilian Equity Fund, investors are limited to a handful of American depositary receipts (receipts for shares of foreign-based corporations, traded on U.S. exchanges) that are not too closely watched or researched by the U.S. investment community.  <p>That means investors must do much of their own legwork. One idea: Look into future Brazilian privatizations that may result in U.S. - listed ADRs. Upcoming privatizations are likely to include electric-utility and telecommunications companies. Auto, textiles, electronics, and steel companies are particularly promising because many of them are prepared technically and financially to meet increasing demand for their goods.<p>For example, Cia Siderurgica Nacional, known as CSN, is the largest steel company in Latin America in terms of production; it was privatized last April. According to research from Banco Tendencia, strong earnings expectations, an improving financial condition, a diversified product base, a strong competitive position, and export growth are some of the reasons to expect solid performance from CSN in 1994. Its shares recently traded around $34.50 over the counter. <p>Other stocks to consider include Cemig, the electric utility in the state of Minas Gerais, the second largest state in Brazil in terms of GNP contribution and population. Cemig recently traded at around $26.50, 76 percent of book value. <p>Petrobras Distribuidora PN, an oil and energy distributor, is another company investors should watch for. The market leader in oil-derivatives distribution, Petrobras is planning to issue an ADR later this year. It has solid financials and has been trading in Brazil recently at ten times its 1994 forecasted earnings.  <p>Fits and starts notwithstanding, the Brazilian market should maintain its strength throughout 1994. But the Bovespa is not for the faint of heart: Like a good steamy samba, the market is sexy but unpredictably spasmodic.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

