<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-The Dragon Is Stirring</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-The Dragon Is Stirring</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Pictures from a revolution: All over China, a thousand markets bloom as a billion consumers build the world's next great  economy.<p>By Richard Bernstein<p>Mao's mausoleum on a shopping bag? For someone who lived in China in the early 1980s, it is the irresistible emblem of change. Back then, with great uncertainty, the country was starting its lurch toward a market economy. From his vast, kitschy home in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, the embalmed Great Helmsman glowered disapprovingly as China tried to consign his anticommercial puritanism to the past.<p>Now this forbidding image has been transformed to a design motif, a selling tool for the new consumer culture. Truly, Maoism is dead.
The measure of change is in the details. Only a few years ago, foreign residents of Beijing delighted at the first shoots of a budding capitalist China. It was a visual experience above all. A riot of colorful silk began replacing the drab gray-blue uniforms. Women perched in long rows under archaic hair dryers, getting perms in state-run beauty parlors.<p>Such everyday matters struck heavy hammer blows to the self-abnegation preached by Mao. In Beijing 14 years ago, the government caused a sensation by allowing the first family-run private restaurant to open. Until then, dining out for most Chinese meant visiting a grimy public enterprise to partake of standardized grease. Many of the country's greatest chefs, meanwhile, had been cashiered during the Cultural Revolution for embodying the bourgeois sin of eating well. <p>In the street, yearnings became palpable. Another thrill in those days was to be found in the basement of the National Minorities Palace. There, for a time, the more daring of China's young people came to dance in a discotheque sometimes frequented by foreigners. Plainclothes police stood in the shadows, watching as a primitive cultural exchange played out without official sanction.<p>More earthshaking, the first free markets in nearly 25 years were approved. Suddenly peasants appeared in the cities with the kind of fresh produce that had been available only to foreigners and the Communist Party elite--and then only in the hard-currency shop. Quick, colorful trade exploded to fill the psychic gap felt by a population that had stood for years in long, sad lines at state outlets.
It was all monitored and controlled by the state, of course. And it is still. Nevertheless, this new nation of spenders, 1.2 billion strong, has emerged as the fastest-growing venue for foreign investment in the world. In 1992, nearly $12 billion flowed into China--more than in the three previous years combined. The 116 companies listed on the Shanghai stock exchange, authorized only four years ago, are now capitalized at $24 billion.<p>Cities that hadn't changed in half a century are suddenly the centers of a nationwide construction boom. And the hot core of the new capitalism is a former peasant village on the Hong Kong border: Shenzhen, once a somnolent place of mud-brick homes and rice paddies.<p>The transformed Shenzhen is still a semiforeign realm; ordinary Chinese folks can't go there without a special pass. But amid its ranks of high-rise towers and modern plants producing circuit boards is a vision of what China is about to become. The message is of remarkable hidden power: This muscular metropolis grew from nothing in just 15 years.<p>Even outside the special zones, China is building its new economic engine--a huge consumer class. Phalanxes of Avon ladies are descending on doorsteps around the country. Parents are stocking up on Gerber baby food, made in Shenzhen. The ban on owning private cars has been lifted; Chinese families troll in Polish-made Fiats or, for the powerful and newly wealthy, Mercedes-Benzes.<p>For anyone who knew the old China, there is a miracle in all this--a miracle beyond even the recent proclamation from Deng Xiaoping, who just five years ago sent tanks into Tiananmen Square, that change could be coming even faster. It's the sight of Mao, who once made a nation tremble, on a shopping bag.  <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
