<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Toss Out the Dartboard</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Toss Out the Dartboard</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Managed funds may have an edge in tough times<p>By Robert N. Veres<p>During the ten-year bull market that began in 1982, a balanced portfolio of blue-chip stocks consistently offered better returns than two thirds of all equity-fund managers (fewer than a third of whom beat the S&P 500 index). This trend caused a lot of investors to bypass active managers altogether, and either invest in index funds, to match what the markets offered, or pick individual stocks. Even the old dartboard tactic made more sense than paying hefty fees for fund management. <p>The market climate that investors face today, however, calls for a different approach. Either do more homework, or find somebody to do it for you. For one thing, small-company stocks have outperformed large ones over the last two years (the Russell 2000 index was up 17 percent for 1993), placing a premium on the ability to locate successful companies from among a wider array of issues. At the same time, blue-chip companies that were once considered too big to fail weren't fast or flexible enough to compete in the 1990s markets. In recent years, <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> all fell on hard times and were forced to restructure. Finally, international investing has grown dramatically. U.S. stocks no longer make up a majority of the world's equities--or of the world's best investment opportunities. <p>These are trends that reward investors who pore over annual reports and talk frequently to management and who are conversant in the accounting principles of offshore locales. Which, of course, is exactly where fund managers have an advantage. These are folks with access to big research departments and communications pipelines to company management. For instance, Peter Van Dyke, the manager of T. Rowe Price's <a name="FUND:PRSIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Spectrum Income</b></a> and <a name="FUND:PRSGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Spectrum Growth</b></a> funds, receives over 20 reports each day on markets, companies, and economic factors (of those, he admits to carefully reading 8 to 10) and another 10 to 15 faxes from various sources around the world both inside the company and outside. <p>At T. Rowe Price, there are 50 analysts (29 for equity and 21 for bonds) who cover specific sectors, industries, and companies and who are available to Van Dyke for additional reports, formal opinions, or just impromptu brainstorming sessions. And the firm receives reports from some 100 analysts around the world in offices from Hong Kong to India to Tokyo. "People forget that even traditional domestic-growth funds are allowed to have up to 25 percent of their assets invested internationally," says Ron Roge, a financial planner in Centereach, New York. <p>Already, the performance figures are bearing out the importance of these advantages. Last year, nearly 70 percent of all equity funds outperformed the S&P 500. That's a sharp turnaround from 1989, when only 20.4 percent of equity funds beat the blue-chip indices. <p>The market also has gotten tougher for bond investors. Putting money into certificates of deposit or other short-term instruments is unattractive. At the same time, interest rates have grown more volatile, and there's more low-grade paper around. That means bonds now jump around almost as much as stocks, and investors have to venture beyond the obvious investments in order to get any kind of return at all. <p>The safest way to navigate through this fixed-income jungle may be to let more than a single manager lead the way. One option would be to pick good managers in several categories: one for intermediate governments, another for high-grade corporates, and still another for unrated corporates (junk). These sectors seem to take turns offering the best risk/return characteristics. So with all three covered, investors can stabilize the bond side of their portfolio.<p>The bottom line: Markets are becoming increasingly complicated and increasingly dangerous for the part-time investor. This, too, is probably no more than a turn of the cycle; five or ten years from now, we'll probably be hearing a lot about the neglected virtues of CDs and blue chips.<p>With a lot of research, individuals can ferret out the future <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>s and <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>s from the small-cap crowd, locate investment opportunities on the Eurasian continent, or determine which unrated corporate paper is a diamond in the rough. But for most investors, the dartboard won't be as effective as it was in the past.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
