<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Higher Returns, Lower Risk</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Higher Returns, Lower Risk</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
A strategy that combines growth and value investing<p>By Robert N. Veres<p>The management styles of stock mutual funds break down into two broad camps--growth investing and value investing--that periodically seem to fall into and out of favor. When the economy was healthy back from 1983 to 1986, value stocks (and value managers) outperformed their growth-oriented colleagues. But during the recession, growth stocks tended to outperform the market. And with the recovery, value stocks have taken the lead again. Says John Rekenthaler, editor of Morningstar Mutual Funds, a Chicago-based mutual fundtracking service, "They give you better returns at different times." <p>Growth managers buy stocks of healthy companies with a history of increasing earnings, on the theory that as the company grows, so too will the price of its stock. Value managers buy companies whose stock is selling below its real value, either because of a recent setback, poor earnings, or a combination of factors, hoping these companies will eventually rebound. Says Stephen Gibson, director of national retail marketing at the Boston-based mutual fund giant Putnam Investments, "A growth manager is trying to have big up years and outperform the market during its bull runs. Value managers, by and large, build their performance by outperforming on the downside of the market."<p>It takes a little research to determine whether a fund takes a growth or value approach. Growth managers will tend to own stocks that are selling at a higher price-to-earnings ratio than the market average, on the theory that future earnings will be even higher. For the same reason, the growth fund's average earnings growth will be higher than the market. A good example is the <a name="FUND:BEONX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BEONX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Berger 100</b></a> fund. According to the latest data available from Morningstar, Berger's stocks are selling at about 37 times earnings on average, nearly twice as high as the current market averages. Berger is paying over eight times the current book value of the companies it buys, which is more than twice as high as the S&P 500 norm, and five-year earnings growth is up around 35 percent--five times as high as the average stock.<p>Value managers, in contrast, tend to keep their price-to-earnings ratios much lower. And, since their goal is to buy a dollar's worth of company as cheaply as possible, their price-to-book value will be low as well. One of the better value funds over the last ten years, Mutual Shares, currently has an average price-to-earnings ratio almost exactly equal to the market, a price-to-book ratio at 2.2 (40 percent below the market averages), and five-year earnings growth around 5 percent, which is below the market as well.<p>In some cases, investors might want to emphasize either value or growth in their portfolios. Young investors with a lot of time to build a nest egg might be more comfortable with a growth-oriented style. Investors in a high tax bracket might also prefer to invest with a growth orientation because most of the return is coming in the form of capital gains (28 percent maximum federal tax rate) rather than dividends (39.6 percent maximum rate). On the other side, conservative investors or those with shorter time horizons might prefer the protection that value funds offer during market downturns. <p>Some investors, of course, try to guess which style will be on top in the near future and buy those funds. But the better financial advisors have tended to blend both styles into the same portfolio as a way of increasing returns while limiting losses. A simple approach for investors with a large enough portfolio is to divide the equity portion equally between a top growth and a top value fund. The result will be a portfolio with fewer ups and downs.<p>The most convenient way to create a mixed growth and value portfolio would be, of course, to find a mutual fund that blends the two styles. For some reason, fund companies have been reluctant to take this approach. One notable exception is the <a name="FUND:LSSCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LSSCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Loomis Sayles Small Cap</b></a> fund. Half of its cash inflow is invested in growth stocks selected by manager Barbara Friedman, while the other half is picked according to manager Jeff Petherick's value orientation. Both managers look for companies with high insider ownership and dominance of a market niche, and both tend to favor smaller companies over corporate giants. But while Petherick pays between 11 and 13 times projected earnings for a 15 percent annual growth rate, Friedman will buy price-to-earnings multiples half again as high as the market, looking for 20 to 35 percent earnings growth per year. "The intent," says Friedman, "was to reduce the normally high risk in a small-cap fund and at the same time get the high returns."<p>The result is a fund with an average price-to-earnings ratio almost exactly equal to the S&P 500, but an earnings growth rate of over three times the market average. This approach beat the S&P 500 by 5.5 percent in 1992--the fund's first full year of operation--and Friedman and Petherick were comfortably ahead of the indexes again in 1993.<p>Nobody knows whether growth or value will be the dominant theme for the next few years, but with one foot in both camps, whichever way it goes, you're bound to get some good news.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
