	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Feudalist Tools</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Feudalist Tools</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						What Americans don't understand about the chaos convulsing modern Russia<p>By Walter Mead<p>Trapped inside the rebellion that rocked moscow last fall, I had a splendid opportunity to ponder the economics of Russia today. My view of the meltdown was front and center. Barricades went up on the road outside my hotel. Tractor trailers, three deep, blocked the street against the terrorist squads that were attacking City Hall. A radio announcer reading a list of closed Metro stations, roads, and other facilities sounded like an American deejay announcing school cancellations for snow in Duluth. I couldn't even call Delta Airlines to confirm my flight; the building housing Delta's office had been hit by gunfire and a stray shell. <p>Some Russian friends and I walked along the Garden Ring Road, picking our way across barricades and around bonfires. At the Tass building, troops in ski masks and camouflage outfits waved machine guns at us and shouted something in Russian. We left. <p>The cafes--what few there are--were all closed. No <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a>, no Pizza Hut. As we wandered the streets looking for something to eat, a machine gun started up some distance away. The gunfire came closer. Victory celebrations? A firefight? Who knew? <p>Rarely has a moment in history been as closely watched as the rebellion in Moscow. Now that I am home, I am struck by the gap between Russia as it actually is and Russia as the Western press describes it. <p>The discrepancy is rooted in the fact that Westerners mistakenly assume Russia to be "in transition" to something like the world we know, to the type of democratic capitalist society that characterizes the West. In every Russian crisis, Western observers try to differentiate between the good guys (the "reformers" and "democrats") and the bad guys ("hard-liners"), who want to keep Russia poor and authoritarian to preserve their own power. We use the same yardstick to measure policy proposals: The good guys favor "market reforms"; the bad guys oppose them. If the good guys win, Russia will take the capitalist road to Western prosperity. Like Belgium, only bigger. <p>This beautiful and inspiring morality play unfortunately has little to do with Russian realities. Russia is a wilder and more dangerous country than it appears on TV; economically, culturally, and psychologically it is more remote from Western Europe than most Americans suspect. Beneath its thin veneer of franchise restaurants, Russia remains unique. Dostoyevsky, not Dan Rather, should report the news from this front.<p>To understand Russia, we must see it as it is, not as we wish it to be. Russia is the last feudal society in Europe, and it has never really known capitalism. In the last half of the 19th century, czarist reformers attempted to lay the groundwork for capitalism. But faced with the competition of more advanced countries and the shocks of World War I, Russia's nascent capitalism collapsed. The Communists marched backward into what one can only call industrial feudalism. <p>As a result, the Communist boss of a Soviet factory had more in common with the barons of medieval Europe than with Western factory managers. Managers of collective farms exploited peasants precisely as czarist nobility exploited the serfs. All property in the industrial feudal society was owned by the state. Where medieval barons received temporary ownership of manors and fields in exchange for service and loyalty to the king, Russian commissars and managers received factories in return for loyalty and service to the state.<p>Social relations in Russia are still shaped by medieval patterns of domination and submission that flourished under feudalism. The humblest clerk in the sleaziest hotel identifies with authority; her work takes precedence over you, the humble petitioner who stands before her desk, waiting for assistance. But if you manage to impress on her (or him) that you represent an even greater authority, arrogance changes to cringing humility instantly. <p>Another manifestation of the heritage of feudalism: Russians put their faith in and give their loyalty to people more than institutions and to institutions more than abstractions. Any authority in Russia is considered unreasonable and unjust--but it is evaded, not opposed. The manager gives orders; rather than dissent, the employees disobey. Russian institutions are more arbitrary and weaker than those in the West: more arbitrary because they answer to the logic of power more than justice, weaker because the habit of lawbreaking is universal. <p>Recent events in Russia are playing out a common feudal scenario: the struggle for succession when the king dies without leaving a strong successor. The struggle between Boris Yeltsin and Alexander Rutskoi was a classic battle for the throne. The powerful regional barons took advantage of the rivalry to fortify their own positions and trade their support for concessions. Now that Yeltsin has defeated Rutskoi, he faces a long and difficult struggle to force Russia's feudal lords to accept his leadership.<p>The feudal struggle for power masks a much deeper social change: Russia's second attempt to move from feudalism to capitalism. Ironically enough, Karl Marx described this process best. He called it "primitive accumulation"--the process by which would-be capitalists acquire the capital that allows them to build fortunes and enterprises. Five years ago, virtually everything valuable in Russia was owned by the state. Today, everything is to be privatized, but the ownership process is unequal. Some Russians have ended up owning factories and natural resources; most will come out of the process owning little more than their skins. <p>The rich are getting richer and the poor poorer. This is the bottom line in Russia today, and the goal of Western intervention is to accelerate this process. Some people have lost everything. At anti-Yeltsin demonstrations I was surrounded by elderly ladies who have nothing to live on but their pensions and savings--both made worthless by Russia's inflation. They screamed their anger in my face, pointed to their worn-out shoes and tattered coats, and denounced Boris Yeltsin and his Western allies for deliberately reducing them to poverty after a lifetime of toil. They have a point. <p>I also met businessmen. Some were more than shady--they were outright thugs busily building commercial empires through violence and intimidation. Others were as honest as is possible under Russian conditions; that is, they routinely evade tax laws that would be ruinous if enforced, and they do most of their work in the twilight zone of a legal system that is disorderly, illogical, unjust, and unclear. Everybody knows that Russian business today is a free-for-all, but the private sector has very little to do with business as we know it in the West. Memo to Harvard M.B.A.s: Stay home. <p>Every factory, every apartment, every farm, every oil field in Russia is up for grabs. Dividing the spoils drives Russian politics. The local authorities want to divvy up all the state property in the neighborhood so they can give it to their friends. This brings them into conflict with the city authorities, who want to do the same thing on a citywide basis. Regional authorities want to override the city authorities, and the national government wants to control the whole process. <p>Losers in the struggle try to overturn the system by making demagogic appeals to the people. That these appeals work at all proves that for Russia, the center has not held. Five years ago, the country had the most centralized government of any major power. Today, whole regions of Russia are trying to go their own way. The Soviet state had four powerful centralizing institutions: the party, the government bureaucracy, the economic mechanism of planning and control, and the armed forces. All today are weak, dead, or dying. <p>The party is essentially dead. Its brighter members have gone off to enrich themselves in the privatization wars. Dimmer members grumble about the decline of all things Soviet and read mimeographed leaflets about Yeltsin's alleged ties to international Judaism. <p>The government bureaucracy isn't dead, but its loyalties have split. Russia's bureaucrats are no longer wealthy members of a privileged elite; their incomes have fallen, and they can no longer impose their decrees on local authorities. In fact, many government officials depend on regional authorities for salaries and perks. <p>The state economic machine is extinct. Planners in Moscow, who once set prices for the whole country, can't even maintain accurate statistics about Russia's GDP. <p>That leaves the armed forces, whose decisive though tardy intervention enabled Yeltsin to destroy his parliamentary opponents in October. But don't assume that Russia's army is strong or united enough to maintain order. <p>In Vladivostok, the headquarters of Russia's proud Pacific fleet, I spoke with Russian officers, cadets, and sailors. Their stories were appalling. Ships are rusting in the harbor, and maneuvers are canceled for lack of fuel. Sailors' wives and children complained of deepening poverty. Some said wages were three months overdue. <p>Former soldiers and civilian observers tell similar horror stories. Nobody really knows whether Russia's soldiers would obey their officers in an emergency; many and perhaps most would refuse to shoot on command. <p>Analysts looking at these problems divide into optimistic and pessimistic schools. The optimists believe the present process of disintegration will end when primitive accumulation creates a new capitalist class. These capitalists will need a strong, effective national government to guard their property and, like their counterparts abroad, will prefer at least a facade of democracy and legality for their actions. <p>Pessimists think that primitive accumulation will fail and that Russia will lapse back into something like feudalism. Some believe fiefdoms will emerge whose rulers will pay little more than lip service to the "national" government in far-off Moscow. An even bleaker view suggests that Russian nationalism will supply the ideological cement for a new powerful central government: feudalism again. Russia's nationalists will organize a new authoritarianism and again parcel out industrial and political fiefdoms to those who agree to serve the state. <p>Few if any Russians I encountered in my month of travel through Siberia and into Moscow shared the view so common in the West that a few economic reforms and a couple of elections are all that stand between Russia and the kind of peaceful democratic life that we all take for granted. Fasten your seat belts, ladies and gentlemen: The road ahead will be bumpy. <p>Walter Mead is a senior counselor at the World Policy Institute at the New School in New York City.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

