<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Southern Exposure</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Southern Exposure</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By John Rothchild<p>After years of trying to influence latin americans to become more like us (the Good Neighbor Policy, the Alliance for Progress, etc.), it's now obvious that we've become a lot more like them. There are signs of this everywhere:<p>We can't drink the water. this predicament has sneaked up on us. For decades, gringos in Latin America have survived on <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> and beer. Now gringos in the United States are surviving on Coca-Cola, Evian, Perrier, and beer. This has been very bullish for the bottled-water industry, which now does $1.23 billion in annual sales in U.S. supermarkets alone. We've gotten so sold on the trendiness of bottled water that we tend to overlook the reason we're drinking it--we don't trust what comes out of the tap. <p>We live behind barricades. In Latin America they put a wall around every house, and in the United States we put walls around entire subdivisions, but the idea is the same: to put up one more obstacle to the invading hordes. Our executives practice kidnap avoidance, a traditional Latin American folk art. We've also adopted bars on the windows, home-surveillance equipment, and if we can afford them, private security guards. This is quite a time for the home- and personal-protection industry, which now does $3.5 billion in annual sales.<p>We're hooked on their drugs. this makes us equal partners. The drug business is the most successful example of how free trade and interhemispheric cooperation can provide jobs and stimulate both economies. The price of cocaine has come down from the yuppie level to the point that the poorest consumer finds it affordable. The delivery system is a model of efficiency. It's run like <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>.<p>Meanwhile, the prices of pharmaceuticals have soared, and these are legal and regulated by the government. So maybe we ought to legalize cocaine and outlaw heart pills.<p>We've fallen in love with the lottery. in South America, they've been in love with lotteries for decades. There the tickets are sold on street corners, which is more sensible than selling them in stores the way we do. It's hard to buy toothpaste when you're caught behind 20 gamblers in the cash-register line.<p>There are lotteries in 36 states and casino gambling in 28, including casinos on 68 Indian reservations in 24 states. Add that to the horses, the dogs, jai alai, off-track betting, Las Vegas bookmaking, and offshore betting on cruise ships. Altogether, the wagering business has grown at 10 percent a year since 1982--faster than computers, faster than health care, faster even than lawyers, who have been increasing at 3.5 percent a year. <p>In 1992 alone, U.S. residents placed $330 billion worth of legal bets. In terms of this total handle, we're risking the annual Pentagon budget. The end result is that we lost $30 billion to the gaming establishments. Add to this the estimated $30 billion in illegal bets, and our domestic gambling habit exceeds the global sales of <a name="NYSE:MOB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11006"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mobil</b></a>, which ranks sixth on the Fortune 500 list of companies.<p>Our government is the world leader in heavy borrowing, taking its cue from the Latin American governments. The difference, so far, is that we pay back our loans. Since the 19th century, Latin American governments have made a regular habit of suckering billions out of U.S. banks. The routine is as follows: The banks lend, the governments default, the banks stop lending, the governments promise never to default again, the banks start lending, the governments default. It happened twice in the 1800s, once in the 1930s, and again in the 1970s, and by the same clockwork, the next sucker cycle will begin in 2010, after the lenders have forgotten the last.<p>Along the way, we've learned more about borrowing than Latin American governments have learned about repaying, so one of these days, maybe we'll be defaulting on their banks.<p>More and more of us are living beyond our means, imitating those Latin American governments. In 1992, 900,000 individuals filed for personal bankruptcy in the U.S. This was a modern record.<p>More of our companies, too, are living and then dying beyond their means. In several cities, the skyline is a deadbeat's graveyard. <p>Dallas has the Bank One Center, built by the now insolvent MBank and later foreclosed on, and the InterFirst building, headquarters of InterFirst Bank, which merged with another bank before the new entity failed.<p>The creditors foreclosed on San Antonio's tallest office building, NBC Bank Plaza, and the owners of the tallest building in Indiana, Bank One Center Tower of Indianapolis, had to scramble to avoid foreclosure. The three tallest buildings in Miami--CenTrust, Southeast Bank, and the Intercontinental Hotel--were tied up in bankruptcies. Everywhere you look, there's red ink in the sunset.<p>We are no longer shocked by tales of corruption.The S&L swindles did us in. Ten thousand bank-fraud cases, many of which will never be brought to trial, have shorted our outrage circuits.<p>We're parking more of our money abroad in foreign stocks and bonds. Pension funds and institutions are buying foreign equities in record numbers. While it may be sensible to diversify, too much investing abroad can rob a country of its development capital.<p>That's long been the story in Latin America: The rich have stayed rich by sending their money to Europe or the United States. Money that has gone into condos in Miami and bank accounts in Switzerland could have been put to work at home. People who find safe havens abroad may be less inclined to get involved in their own country's problems.<p>We have an underground economy (cash under the table, barter, etc.) that is growing faster than our aboveground economy. By current estimates, it may be as much as 10 percent of the official GDP.<p>We have replaced america first with Me First.This is less out of selfishness than out of cynicism. We no longer trust the government that is asking us to do the sacrificing. Latin Americans have felt this way since the breakup with Spain.<p>This brings us to the North American Free Trade Agreement and all the U.S. factories that are relocating on the Mexican side of the Rio Grande. When U.S. workers begin to cross the border in a southerly direction, looking for jobs, we'll know that we've become fully Latin Americanized.<p>Contributing editor John Rothchild is the author of Going for Broke (Penguin/Viking), the story of financier Robert Campeau.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, Banking Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:KO">The Coca-Cola Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:T">AT&T Corp.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:MOB">Mobil Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
