<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Young Fogies</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Young Fogies</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Some investors are simply beyond mutual funds. Don't you love these old-fashioned types?<p>If you've mastered the VCR, are obsessive about taking antioxidants, and no longer send snail mail, you probably think of yourself as a 1990s kind of person. But look at your investment portfolio. Do you see what I see? Stocks? Individual stocks? Well then, your portfolio is a throwback. Buying individual stocks is an ancient ritual that investors were forced to practice before one of the all-time great financial inventions: stock mutual funds. <p>Of course, this ancient ritual still has its supporters. Especially the advice swamis who scream at you from financial publications -- "The 10 Top Stocks to Buy Now!" That's mindless hype, pure and simple. But there are also more thoughtful swamis who take the higher ground. They argue that individual stocks belong in small-investor portfolios because there is virtue in the practice of buying equities itself. Here are the main points of their case. <p>Taxes: With individual stocks you can take your gains and losses when you want to, and you can make sure that all your gains are long-term gains. In fact, you can hold on to your stocks until death releases your grip, never realizing any gains and never paying any taxes. With mutual funds, however, you have no discretion over the timing; many capital gains are short term and thus subject to higher taxes (as shareholders in the <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Magellan Fund</b></a> found out in May, when the fund declared a big distribution from its sale of technology stocks). <p>Costs: With stocks, there are only two transaction costs -- when you buy and when you sell. Mutual funds, on the other hand, involve yearly costs of fees and expenses, some of which can be quite high. <p>Image: For one thing, it's considered more macho and thus more satisfying to drop the names of your stocks around the watercooler, as in "I just bought 100 shares of Macro-Zip-Micro-Tech at $3 a share, and it's already up 50 cents -- man, this little baby is hot." For another, it's more fun to pick stocks; there is undoubtedly a flush of knowing pleasure from buying Macro-Zip-Micro-Tech that buying shares in a mutual fund can't deliver. <p>Performance: This is mostly a negative argument; it runs that since most mutual funds regularly underperform the market you are better off with individually selected stocks. (There is also a component of raw greed, the belief that one lucky pick will put you on Paradise Island for the rest of your life.) Also, champions of stock picking like to point to what they call the highly specialized and profound knowledge that the amateur develops from his or her daily experience. This, they say, gives just about anyone the ability to identify companies with good potential.<p>Those are the arguments for individual stocks, and each is half right. But consider now the other half, which favors mutual-fund investing.<p>Taxes: You could, instead, invest in stock-market index funds, which are very tax efficient. Indeed, tax bills are minimal, because stocks in an index fund are rarely traded. <p>Costs: Stocks have the advantage in only the starkest cases, such as with an infrequently traded equity portfolio versus an expensive mutual fund. But in-and-out costs, even at a discount broker, can be very pricey, especially if you trade actively. On the other hand, it's possible to find a low-expense mutual fund without extra marketing, sales, and exit charges. For example, <a name="FUND:VTSMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VTSMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard's Index Trust Total Stock Market Portfolio fund</b></a> (which mirrors the market as a whole) will cost you 0.22 percent a year.<p>Image: Excitement over stock picking and gabbing about it are usually just the beginning of the story. What follows is having to drag around a bunch of dogs whose provenance eventually becomes a mystery to you. And then there's a deeper image problem -- being called an amateur. In 1992, according to the New York Stock Exchange, 24 percent of the people who held equities owned only one. Consider what William Silber, professor of finance and economics at New York University, says about those who hold less than the market portfolio (an index fund): "The reason why people buy one or two stocks has nothing to do with investing. It's for cocktail-party conversation." <p>Performance: Nobody knows how small investors do on average -- whether, as a group, they tend to outperform or underperform the market in any year. A reasonable judgment -- and the best face -- is that risk-adjusted returns for small investors as a group mirror the market because they hold the market in aggregate and thus their pattern of returns is similar. In other words, some investors will do better than the market, some will do worse, and the more diversified the portfolio, the closer it will come to hitting the market return.<p>At least that's a theory. In practice, however, mutual funds have one crucial advantage over individual investors: Transaction costs are a fraction of those faced by individuals. Thus, after costs are subtracted, it's reasonable to assume that mutual funds have higher risk-adjusted returns than do individual investors.<p>Also, in practice, just as there are individual investors who beat the market year after year, there are fund managers who log sensational returns over the long haul. Since performance records of mutual funds are readily accessible, it is easier to fasten onto one of those stars than to try to pick star stocks.<p>As for the "capitalize on your expertise" school of thought, well, maybe. But ultimately, your expertise is only as good as the returns it affords. And as John Markese, president of the American Association of Individual Investors, points out, this type of thinking can easily turn into what he calls product investing: "You go to a restaurant and love the product, so you buy the company," he explains. "But good products do not translate into good stocks." <p>(If the performance question worries you, there is a remedy: Buy a stock-market index fund and get guaranteed market performance. You won't do better than the market -- but by golly, you won't do worse, either.)<p>Simply put, the standard reasons for preferring individual stocks over mutual funds are hardly compelling. And they pale even more when compared with the benefits afforded by mutual-fund 
investing. Consider these other factors.<p>Instant, cheap diversification: This is no small matter. Diversification is a way of reducing risk without reducing return. By conservative estimates, it takes 50 to 100 individual stocks to diversify a stock portfolio. Figure on spending almost a million bucks. Even if you cleave to the less strict rule of 30 stocks to diversify, it'll still cost you several hundred thousand dollars. But buy into the average mutual fund for a fraction of that money and -- presto -- you have a portfolio of a hundred stocks. <p>By the same token, mutual funds can also provide a way to focus your portfolio. If you like to market-time the business cycle, for example, you can rotate your money from sector fund to sector fund while maintaining a well-diversified position within sectors.<p>A no-fuss, cheap way into foreign markets: If you want to buy individual shares in foreign firms, then you usually have to buy something called an American depositary receipt, which represents the ownership of such securities. The banks that issue these receipts charge a small fee, which is taken out of the dividend payment, and ADRs typically trade with a slightly wider spread than stocks. But buying shares in an international-stock mutual fund will provide you with a much simpler entre and -- again -- instant and cheap diversification.<p>(There is, however, one bogus argument in favor of mutual funds that bears mentioning: the professional-manager idea that, for a small fee, you get a highly trained, plugged-in, workaholic stock picker. Maybe. But whatever the attributes of this professional manager, he or she is only as good as his or her numbers.)<p>In sum, those dollars that keep flooding into stock mutual funds are not dumb money. Mutual funds may not be as thrilling as individual stocks, but if you consider the two crucial categories of investment -- risk and return -- they represent a quantum leap. For risk, mutual funds offer even the smallest investors a no-brain way to diversify their portfolios. For return, you're better off in a mutual fund where performance is helped by lower transaction costs.<p>Be there or be square.<p>
Contributing editor Susan Lee writes "Mind Your Own Business" monthly. She is an economist and author of Hands Off: Why the Government Is a Menace to Economic Health, just published by Simon & Schuster. E-mail her at sclee12@aol.com.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
