<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Two Fund-Data Giants Square Off</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Two Fund-Data Giants Square Off</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Morningstar has prevailed on the printed page, but Value Line has stolen the lead in software<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Morningstar is probably more famous among investors than most of the 7,000 mutual funds it rates. The Chicago-based company's star rankings, from one to five, are ubiquitous in fund ads. The opinions of analysts who write for its flagship publication, Morningstar Mutual Funds, are de rigueur in any article that evaluates a fund.<p>This makes it all the more surprising that Morningstar is facing a serious challenge in its core business of providing fund information to investors. At the moment, while Morningstar's print publication clearly remains on top, its software program has dropped to second best. Value Line's Fund Analyzer now offers investors better tools at about half the price.<p>The battle between Morningstar (800-735-0700) and Value Line (800-284-7607) began in 1993 when the latter, a New York company well known for its Value Line Investment Survey, which profiles individual companies, launched The Value Line Mutual Fund Survey to evaluate individual funds. Morningstar wasn't pleased. In March 1994, the company alleged that Value Line had plagiarized the synopses of a fund's strategy prepared by Morningstar's analysts. "That was a little surprising given that Morningstar's flagship product is so thoroughly predicated on a format" that Value Line has used for its stock profiles since 1931, says Stephen Savage, Value Line's director of mutual-fund research.<p>Morningstar first staked its claim as a fund rater in 1984, when founder Joe Mansueto, then a 27-year-old stock analyst at a fund advisory firm and now Morningstar CEO, began publishing a quarterly Mutual Fund Sourcebook out of his apartment on the North Side of Chicago. The field was wide open. The only potential rival, Lipper Analytical Services, stuck with the more lucrative market for institutional investors.<p>Value Line could have entered the fray then but instead chose to stay on the sidelines. For one thing, Value Line itself owns a small family of funds, so tracking funds could appear to be a conflict of interest. For another, the market was quite small: As late as 1990, Morningstar had fewer than 10,000 subscribers. "The size of the market didn't justify our entry until the early 1990s," says Savage. But by that time, Morningstar already ruled the field. "They've secured the market on the print side," concedes Savage.<p>It's not surprising that Value Line hasn't really been able to dent Morningstar's dominance in the print market. Despite strikingly similar publications, Morningstar produces a superior product in crucial areas.<p>Both companies' newsletters -- Morningstar Mutual Funds, with a circulation of 27,682 and an annual subscription rate of $425, and The Value Line Mutual Fund Survey, with 5,000 readers and an annual price of $295 -- present important data on performance: trailing 3-, 6-, and 12-month returns and 3-, 5-, 10-, and 15-year annualized returns. Both publications rank each fund according to risk and return, and describe each fund in a written synopsis accompanied by graphs and tables of data, such as asset size, fees, and portfolio holdings.<p>But Morningstar gives the reader sharper tools for dissecting a fund. For starters, it lists quarter-by-quarter returns for the past five years of a fund's life. "Looking at quarterly figures helps you to better understand the fund's performance pattern," says Paul Greenwood, senior research analyst at Frank Russell Co., an investment consulting firm in Tacoma, Washington.<p>Although both newsletters compare every fund's performance with the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index of big blue-chip companies, Morningstar also measures each fund's trailing returns against a more specific benchmark -- such as the Russell 2000 Index for small-company funds -- that more closely parallels each fund's investment style. Both newsletters provide boxes showing the investment style of a fund -- whether it invests mostly in small, medium, or large companies and whether it has a growth or value orientation, or a blend of the two. But Morningstar goes a step further with a style box for each year of a fund's history going back to 1985. This chronology allows investors to see if the manager has shifted strategies over time.<p>Unable to defeat Morningstar on the print battlefield, Value Line has shifted the contest to new terrain: the burgeoning market for mutual-fund software. "This is the real growth area," says Value Line's Savage. And this has indeed turned into Morningstar's Achilles' heel.<p>Morningstar actually created the opening that Value Line is now trying to exploit when it upgraded its software from products that used the aging DOS interface to a Windows product called Principia. "Over the last few years, as we heard from users, we were tugged in two directions," says Morningstar's Mansueto. "Individual investors wanted one thing, and professionals wanted something else." Morningstar aimed Principia at financial professionals and priced the complete program with all its modules at $795 a year, significantly more expensive than the DOS version and well above the $395 annual price tag for Value Line's Fund Analyzer. "Principia is too high priced for what they offer relative to Fund Analyzer," says John Markese, president of the American Association of Individual Investors.<p>Both software products provide the standard data that investors can find in the newsletters, such as annualized returns, objective, rank, risk, and more -- but the programs also give users the ability to manipulate this data, a serious advantage over either print version. For example, users can create bar charts to compare the risk and return of any two funds or screen the universe of funds for, say, all no-load funds with a price-to-earnings ratio of less than 15 (Morningstar covers more than 7,000 funds, while Value Line currently offers 5,000).<p>But Fund Analyzer is not just less expensive than Morningstar's Principia. It also provides weekly data updates (downloaded on-line) -- as opposed to Principia's monthly updates (via software sent by mail) -- is a bit easier to use, and offers several more-powerful features. For example, on Fund Analyzer's screen, eight windows beneath the toolbox icons call up specific fund comparisons. One pulls up graphs comparing price performance; another, pie charts showing asset allocations. Principia users must click on a specific fund and navigate a menu to retrieve the same information. But even then, Fund Analyzer offers more kinds of graphs than Principia.<p>Fund Analyzer combines all its features in one integrated program. It lists top portfolio holdings for up to 3,200 funds and a 400-word strategy analysis for each of 1,550 funds. It also allows users to print out a page exactly as it appears in the newsletter and create a hypothetical portfolio.<p>The basic program for Morningstar's Principia, which costs the same $395 a year as Fund Analyzer, provides none of these features. To print out a newsletter-page facsimile or get fund analyses and top holdings, users must buy Principia Electronic Binder. Investors who want to run hypothetical portfolios need Portfolio Developer, due out in June. Yet a fourth program, Principia Advanced Analytics, with data for advanced users, is scheduled for release in late 1996. The whole package costs $795.<p>Morningstar CEO Mansueto defends Principia and its cost, claiming that his offerings "will be the best package out there -- and often the best products carry premium prices." Nonetheless, Morningstar isn't about to let Value Line steal its user base of individual investors, either. Ascent, a scaled-down version of Principia tailored for individuals, is due out in May for $195 a year. From a test version of Ascent provided by Morningstar, it's clear that the program, though less expensive than Value Line's product, is also much more limited. Users can't compare standard deviation of fund 
returns, for example, because Ascent rates risk only by labeling funds "average," "above average," or "below average." Ascent provides no written analysis of fund strategy or list of top portfolio holdings and offers only three kinds of graphs.<p>Value Line has already launched its answer to Ascent, the No-Load Analyzer, which costs $149 a year with monthly updates. But the fight is still in its early rounds. The future clearly holds a lot more counterpunching. Ultimately, the hands-down winner will be the individual investor.<p><p>SIDEBAR: TAKING THEIR SHARE OF THE PIE
The names of these companies may be unfamiliar, but investors use their data on mutual funds every day<p>The battle between Value Line and Morningstar may be generating most of the noise, but other companies are quietly fighting for their share of the data turf, too. Although Lipper Analytical Services, Micropal, and CDA/Wiesenberger primarily sell their fund information to institutional investors, each also provides data to a surprisingly large number of individual investors.<p>For example, most of the mutual-fund returns that investors see in their daily papers come from Lipper Analytical Services, based in Summit, New Jersey. Lipper, which dominated the mutual-fund-data industry before Morningstar seized the initiative, distributes performance data via the Associated Press news service to many papers, including The Wall Street Journal and The Washington Post. The listings show a fund's net asset value, load, expense ratio, and returns for periods from one month to five years. Lipper sells more-detailed data to its primary clients, the 590-odd mutual-fund families, which order specialized reports to help them set fees for managers, gauge the competition, and develop marketing ploys. Lipper tracks 19,000 funds worldwide, including some 8,000 U.S. stock and bond funds. <p>Data from Micropal, a British financial publisher with offices in Boston, appear on Prodigy, in software programs, and in such publications as Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine. Micropal tracks 35,000 funds in 24 nations, including many that are available in just a single country. Micropal (http://www.micropal.
com/~invest) sells its data on software to U.S. fund families and pension-fund managers, but its information also turns up in software packages, such as Steele Systems Mutual Fund Expert and the American Association of Individual Investors' Quarterly Low-Load Mutual Fund Update. <p>CDA/Wiesenberger, based in Rockville, Maryland, is a division of CDA Investment Technologies, which is owned by Thomson Financial Services, a financial-publishing powerhouse based in Boston. CDA/Wiesenberger provides data on returns, dividends, capital gains, risk, and yields on 7,000 funds for its HySales software, used by some 80,000 brokers to explain funds to clients. Besides competing with Morningstar in the lucrative brokerage-information arena, CDA/Wiesenberger also publishes an annual Investment Companies Yearbook and a monthly Mutual Funds Update ($295 a year for each or $30 per issue of Mutual Funds Update; 800-232-2285).  -- A.G.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

