<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-When Is a Fund Worth Its Fee?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>When Is a Fund Worth Its Fee?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-When Is a Fund Worth Its Fee?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p>  <p>WHEN IS A FUND WORTH ITS FEE? <p>Investors in the most expensive large-cap growth funds pay high fees for low returns  <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> Investors in <a name="FUND:VEIPX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VEIPX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Equity-Income Fund</b></a> pay the Vanguard Group 0.45 percent of the value of their portfolio every year for running that fund. Investors in <a name="FUND:SBABX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SBABX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SunAmerica Balanced Assets Fund B</b></a> pay their management company 2.12 percent annuallyalmost five times as much. What do investors in the more expensive fund get for their money? Certainly not higher returns. Over the five years ended December 31, 1995, the Vanguard fund returned 16.23 percent annually and the SunAmerica fund just 13.54 percent.  <p> Most investors ignore expenses when they choose a mutual fund. Fees are deducted from a fund's assets before earnings are distributed to shareholders, so investors never write checks to pay for the accountants, lawyers, bookkeepers, toll-free telephone services, and other annual operating expenses. Further obfuscating the matter, the costs are expressed as a percentage of the total assets of the fund. With the average stock fund among the 883 that Worth rated last November showing an expense ratio of just1.33 percent, the charge can seem too small to worry about. <p> But that average disguises incredible variation. The cheapest fund in that universe charges just 0.17 percent a year in expenses; the most expensive soaks investors for 8.9 percent annually. Many studies, most recently one by Burton Malkiel, the author of A Random Walk Down Wall Street, have shown that, in general, there is no connection between the amount investors pay in expenses and the returns they receive.  <p> But a Worth study that compared equity-fund expenses and performance over the past five years at the cheapest and most expensive funds found that, at the extremes in two major fund categories, investors aren't getting nothing in exchange for high fees: They actually receive lower performance. Among the large-cap growth and large-cap value funds that charge the most in expenses and those that chargethe least, performance is directly connected to fees. We discovered that in these two categories the returns on the cheapest 10 percent of mutual funds were higher than the returns on the most expensive10 percent. "Investors often pay Cadillac prices for a Yugo," says Charles Trzcinka, a finance professor at the State University of New York at Buffalo and a former senior economist at the Securities and Exchange Commission.   <p> For our study, we divided the 883 funds evaluated in our 1995 mutual-fund issue into five styles: large-cap growth, large-capvalue, small-cap growth, small-cap value, and global. We then ranked the funds in each style based on their expense ratio and broke that ranking into ten groups, or deciles, ranging from most expensive to least. For instance, the 130 small-cap growth funds were divided into deciles containing 13 funds each, with the lowest-expense funds in the first decile and the highest-expense funds falling into the tenth decile. Then we averaged the expense ratios and five-year annualized returns of each decile and looked for a pattern in the relationship between fees and performance. <p> We eliminated two style categories off the bat. Among global funds, we found no orderly rise or fall in returns as expenses increased. Another style, small-cap value, contained too few candidates: With just 28 funds in this category, the deciles were too small to allow a meaningful judgment.  <p> But the study clearly showed that investors who pay high expenses for funds that purchase large-cap growth stocks don't get their money's worth. The 44 large-company growth funds in the priciest10 percent of this style showed an average expense ratio of 2.35 percent and an average return of 13.83 percent a year from 1991 to 1995. But the cheapest large-company growth funds, the lowest-cost decile in this category, had an average expense ratio of 0.58 percent and a return of 16.06 percent annually.  <p> That average difference in yearly returns of 2.23 percentage points may not sound like much, but it certainly adds up overtime. Someone who invests $25,000 today and earns 13.83 percent annually would have $91,308 after ten years versus $110,858 foran investor earning 16.06 percent a year.   <p> Why are high expenses so detrimental to total return in this category? The market for large-cap growth stocks is relatively ecient and very limited in size, theorizes Jeffrey Keil, anassistant vice president at Lipper Analytical Services in Denver,which provided the data for this study. "In the large-cap- growth universe, a lot of players are chasing a group of about 600 stocks."With almost all other things being equal, Keil says, the difference in expenses is often what makes one large-cap growth fund perform better than another.  <p> But the results for small-company growth funds seem to show that in a less ecient part of the market higher expense ratios may be linked to higher returns. Despite their extremely high 2.3 percent average-annual-expense ratio, the highest-priced small-company growth funds outperformed the cheapest small-company growth funds by about 1.21 percentage points a year, or 21.34 versus 20.13. Some of the best-performing small-company growth funds of the past five years are among the 14 most expensive, including Kaufmann Fund, which sports a 28.6 percent annual returnand a 2.29 percent expense ratio, and <a name="FUND:MEGBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MEGBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MFS Emerging Growth Fund B</b></a>, with a 30.51 percent annual return and a 2.08 percent expense ratio.  <p> "That makes sense," according to fund-industry consultant GeoffBobroff. "With small-cap growth funds, investment selection is much bigger." A small-company fund manager has 3,000 to 4,000 stocks to choose froma much larger universe than that available to a large-company fund manager. In addition, Wall Street an-alyststend to give small companies a lot less scrutiny than they give large-cap stocks such as <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>. That means there are more undiscovered gems among small companies to ferret out.  <p> A fund's total expenses include fees for accounting, shareholder services, and other ongoing operating costs. But the management feethe largest component of a fund's expense ratiois what the adviser gets paid for picking stocks and deciding when to sell them. To find out if small-cap-growth-fund managers are putting investors' money to work researching stocks or simply pocketing higher fees, we ranked the funds in this style group based solely on management fees.  <p> It turns out that it's better to buy small-company growth funds that are spending more on picking stocks than those funds that are skimping on their research and analysis. The cheapest 26 funds, the bottom two deciles, returned an average of 18.75 percent annually.   <p> But the 26 small-cap growth funds that spent the most on their managers gained an average of 20.87 percent annually, 2.12 percentage points more per year than the cheapest funds. Expensive small-cap growth funds can be worth the price.  <p> Large-cap value funds showed a more complicated pattern. Like funds in the large-cap growth category, the 10 percent of large-cap value funds with the lowest expenses outperformed the 10 percent charging the highest fees, with returns of 15.36 percent versus 14.92 percent.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS:  Mutual Funds Investing<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
