<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Losing with Last Year's Winners</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Losing with Last Year's Winners</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Buying yesterday's hotshots is a bet that the market will love the same kind of stock two years in a row.<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Resist Temptation. Every year many mutual-fund investors rush out to add the previous year's rockets to their portfolios. The urge is especially strong after a year such as 1995, when the <a name="FUND:ACAPX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACAPX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alger Capital Appreciation Fund</b></a> , the best-performing diversified equity fund, recorded a total return of 78.57 percent. There's even a credible-sounding strategy that makes the rounds at times like these: On January 1, buy the top ten no-load diversified stock funds from the previous year and hold them until December 31. Then sell them and buy the top ten funds from the year just ended. The returns are supposed to be amazing.<p>Don't do it. Over the past ten years, the returns from that strategy trail those an investor would have earned by simply sticking with the <a name="FUND:VFINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VFINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vanguard Index 500 fund</b></a>, which mirrors the performance of the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index. Worse yet, 1996 looks like an especially dangerous time to pursue yesterday's hotshot funds.<p>To test the top-ten strategy, we used the Morningstar Mutual Funds On Disc database of 6,877 funds. To avoid burdening the top ten with sales fees, we looked only at true no-load funds. We also screened out sector and international funds because, while they often dominate the top ten, they come with so much risk that no investor should build a portfolio solely from these types of funds. Finally, we excluded funds that, in the year the strategy recommended buying them, were available only to institutional investors, were closed to new accounts, or restricted purchase or sale. <p>Then, for each year, we ranked the funds by their one-year returns and bought the top ten. So on January 1, 1986, for example, we purchased the top ten performers of 1985. On January 1, 1987, we sold those funds and bought the top ten of 1986. We repeated this tactic every year until 1995, when we bought the top ten funds of 1994. At the end of December, we calculated our ten-year return.<p>While the outcome of this strategy wasn't terrible, it wasn't particularly good, either. This approach showed a total return of 277 percent cumulatively compared with 300 percent for the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index. That lower return came with more risk, too. As measured by standard deviation, the S&P 500 had an average annual risk of 14.6 percent, compared with 15.9 percent for the funds in the top-ten portfolio. (All performance data assume that the top-ten strategy is carried out in a tax-deferred retirement account. The tax inefficiency of such a heavily traded portfolio would otherwise put it even further behind the S&P.)<p>Why does this strategy stop? Not because it picks funds that are doomed to failure. For instance, the 1992 portfolio included long-term winners such as <a name="FUND:BEONX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BEONX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Berger 100</b></a>, <a name="FUND:TWCUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TWCUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>20th Century Ultra Investors</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus</b></a> Twenty. The 1990 portfolio included 20th Century Vista Investors, <a name="FUND:RSCOX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/RSCOX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Robertson Stephens Emerging Growth</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:FRINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FRINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Founders Growth.</b></a>
But one year's winner tended to be the next year's loser__or at least mediocre performer. In 1991, the top ten funds had an average return of 84.3 percent, nearly triple the 30.48 percent gain for the Standard & Poor's 500. But in 1992, those same funds underperformed the market, earning 3.74 percent versus 7.62 percent for the S&P 500. This pattern recurs. The top ten funds of 1989 returned 45.1 percent, trouncing the 31.68 percent performance of the S&P 500. In 1990, the same funds were a disappointment, losing 4.49 percent versus a 3.12 percent loss for the S&P 500.<p>The strategy doesn't fail just because stock pickers inevitably come back to the pack. In fact, by buying last year's hottest funds, an investor isn't betting that specific fund managers will keep their hot hands. Instead, the investor following this strategy is hoping that the investment style most favored by the market in the previous year will remain favored in the current year. (Or that the top ten fund managers will accurately forecast which investment style will perform best over the next 12 months and switch to it.) The strategy is too linked to style, concludes money manager Jeffrey Mortimer of Higgins Associates in Cambridge, Massachusetts.<p>Take 1987. That year the Russell 2000, a small-company stock index, declined 8.8 percent. The S&P/BARRA index of large-company growth stocks gained 6.5 percent. The top ten for that year included just one small-company stock fund.<p>But the hot style of 1987 proved unlucky in 1988, when the market rewarded a different approach. The small-capitalization stocks in the Russell 2000 outperformed large-company stocks, returning 24.9 percent versus 12 percent in the large-company growth stocks. Unfortunately, the 1988 top-ten portfolio, loaded with 1987's winners, was invested almost totally in large-cap growth stocks. The 1988 portfolio, while increasing in value by 13.54 percent, underperformed the Russell 2000 and the 16.6 percent return on the Standard & Poor's 500.<p>The pattern repeated itself the next year. The portfolio for 1989 reected the strong small-company performance of 1988. So five of the funds in the 1989 portfolio were small-company or aggressive-growth funds. But in 1989 large-company growth was the best-performing category. The large-company growth index returned 36.4 percent and the Russell 2000 just 16.2 percent. The 1989 portfolio returned 24.41 percent, lagging the 31.68 percent gain of the S&P 500. 
"Mutual funds go through streaks and slumps, like sports teams," says David Kudish, president of Stratford Advisory Group in Chicago. "It's not because a fund manager was smart and became stupid." It's because a style stops leading the market.<p>For example, "when cellular, cable TV, computer chips, and other technology stocks do very well, then growth-style managers do well," says Kudish. "When the economy is coming out of a malaise, industrial companies and cyclicals such as autos and transportation stocks tend to do well, and value managers do well."<p>The top-ten strategy, says Nola Williams, senior investment strategist at Frank Russell Companies in Tacoma, Washington, "goes against the buy-low-and-sell-high approach. It's more like buy high and bet it will go higher." <p>A stock investor would not adopt a strategy of buying the ten stocks that had the biggest gains in the previous year for his current year's portfolio, says Ronald Kahn, director of research at BARRA, a Berkeley, California, investment consulting firm. The failure of the top-ten strategy to outperform "tells you that looking at past-performance numbers alone isn't enough," says Kahn. (There is, however, an effective strategy that involves buying the Dow Jones Industrials stocks with the highest dividend yields each year. See "Opportunities" on page 116.)<p>In fact, looking only at past performance can lead an investor seriously astray. "Because the extreme winners are volatile funds, their propensity to repeat isn't that strong," says Roger Ibbotson, a Yale University professor and founder of the consulting firm Ibbotson Associates in Chicago. The big winners tend to be funds that not only practice an extreme style but that also get lucky when that style dominates the year. Of course, those funds are also likely to underperform when their style loses favor.<p>Ibbotson says investors will do better by eschewing the extremes. "I've suggested that perhaps you buy funds performing in the 90th percentile [the top 10 percent of all funds] rather than the very best ones__to avoid the volatile, very best performing funds."<p>How will the top-ten strategy play out in 1996? Probably not very well, in part because winning funds are now struggling to juggle a pile of new money from investors. The top ten of 1995 included such funds as <a name="FUND:WAAEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WAAEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wasatch Mid-Cap</b></a>, whose assets shot from $1.2 million to $131 million last year, and Robertson Stephens Value + Growth, whose assets soared from $132 million to $1.3 billion. Much of the top ten's average 53.25 percent return as of December 31, 1995, was also built on two sectors, technology and finance, which turned downward even before the end of the year. For the last quarter of 1995, the large-company stocks of the Dow Jones Industrials thoroughly trounced these sectors. After the 1995 top ten's amazing run-up driven by a narrow range of stocks, investors chasing last year's hot funds could be courting disaster this year.<p>
OPPORTUNITIES: EMI STOCK KEEPS ON TRUCKIN'
Looking for growth in a down-and-out industry? Too many truckers and not enough freight have driven trucking-company stocks off the road. But analysts expect some of the scrappy companies that survive this industry recession__many of which are poised to grow by acquiring ailing rivals__to soar as supply and demand come back into balance in the second half of the year. These companies use innovative strategies for delivering goods within tight deadlines, catering to the just-in-time inventory-management techniques adopted by big retailers and manufacturers. With companies such as <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a> and DuPont increasingly farming out these services and using fewer trucking outfits for more jobs, there's lots of upside for companies that deliver.__Pamela J. Black<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
