<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-They Call This Service?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>They Call This Service?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-They Call This Service?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996 
Worth magazine/Features<p>THEY CALL THIS SERVICE?<p>By William P. Barrett<p>Face it: we'd all like our mutual funds to double in value about, oh, every year or so. When they don't, however, it's at least some comfort to be treated with respect by your fund family. With that in mind, Worth investigated how well the top 20 companies perform in three areas of customer service: requests for documents, clarity of account statements, and responses to investors' questions over the phone.<p>
PAPER TRAIL<p>Just after Thanksgiving, a Worth reporter called each family's published toll-free number, identified specific funds, and asked that three documents about each be sent to a home address: the current prospectus, the current statement of additional information (SAI), and the latest semi-annual report.<p>As the mail arrived, the reporter logged in each document. Prospectuses and SAIs older than a year without recent amendments were considered nonresponsive, as were semi-annual reports more than eight months old. The overall results were underwhelming. Only 54 percent of the requested documents arrived. Just one mutual-fund family, Twentieth Century, provided 100 percent of the solicited material. Next in line were Franklin (93 percent), American (92 percent), Fidelity (88 percent), Van Kampen (86 percent), Oppenheimer (82 percent), and Putnam (77 percent). <p>Seven families__IDS, Janus, <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, T. Rowe Price, Kemper, Smith Barney, and Dreyfus__didn't come close to meeting our requests. And AIM, Dean Witter, and MFS sent nothing at all. An AIM spokesman said the telephone worker at its Houston headquarters who had taken our call abruptly resigned that very day without processing the order. An apologetic MFS said it could find no record of our request. Dean Witter offered no explanation.<p>
SECRET CODE<p>Account statements sometimes read like coded messages sent behind enemy lines. To judge how well each fund family presents its information, we developed a list of 21 possible characteristics or items of information__easy-to-understand language, cost basis, percentage breakouts of holdings, among others__and then obtained actual account statements.<p>Our winner: Dean Witter, whose mutual-fund statement, which is also used in its brokerage business, was the only one that met well over half our requirements, including the estimated yield and income of each holding as well as the actual change in total account value since the last statement. (For most of the others, an investor would have to do the math using a previous statement.)<p>In second place was Kemper, the only family that furnished total-return information for individual holdings. A close third: Scudder, whose statement was one of just three that calculated the original or average cost basis for each position, which can be useful in determining tax consequences. <p>Three companies shared last place: American, Franklin, and Van Kampen, the last of which sent us two sets of forms, one dating back prior to a 1994 merger.<p>
POP QUIZ<p>This was the fun part. most of the fund families spend a lot of time training people to answer questions over the phone from customers__even really dumb questions. So we created a list of nine utterly basic queries. We then dialed up company sales representatives__and fired away. We counted "I don't know'' as wrong, but otherwise graded fairly generously.<p>Our quiz included the following: What's the difference between yield and total return? What's the difference between a Treasury bond and a Treasury bill? What's the difference between a long-term capital gain and a short-term capital gain? What's a repurchase agreement?<p>For each family we also picked one fund and asked: What's the maximum sales load? Is there a deferred load if you pay the maximum load? Can this fund use put or call options?<p>The results: Better than one out of every five of our really dumb questions produced a really dumb answer. Dreyfus telephone rep Jeff Lang was the only one to answer all nine of our queries correctly. He didn't even hesitate when asked if a certain Dreyfus fund uses puts or calls: "Yes, they all use them.'' (Nine of the 20 families got this wrong.)<p>Four firms tied for second with eight correct answers: American, Franklin, Putnam, and Scudder.<p>The Fidelity rep thought T-bills could have maturities of up to two years (instead of one). The Kemper rep thought an SAI was "the latest quarterly update.'' The AIM agent thought the breakpoint between long- and short-term capital gains was six months instead of one year. The Van Kampen rep said he "wasn't familiar'' with repurchase agreements, which are sales of securities__often by fixed-income funds__to be repurchased at a specific time and price. A Janus person said yield and total return "are basically the same.'' Several reps offered a more-or-less accurate definition of total return, but couldn't coherently explain how it differed from yield.<p>All 20 knew their own maximum sales charges and deferred loads. But five couldn't provide the portfolio turnover rate__the percent of fund holdings sold in a year, which affects fund expenses__which usually appears in the prospectus or semi-annual report. And 11 stumbled on the T-bill/T-bond distinction. To a person they were polite and patient. But there were a lot of long pauses, we were frequently put on hold, and several times the line went dead.<p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

