<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Rating the Fund Families</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Rating the Fund Families</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Rating the Fund Families</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> RATING THE FUND FAMILIES <p>The first-ever ratings of the top 20 mutual fund companies  <p> By Jim Jubak and William P. Barrett  <p> You know the names: Dreyfus, Fidelity, Putnam, Janus, Scudder,T. Rowe Price, and the others. But do you know what lies behind them? Do you know how one mutual-fund family differs from thenext?  <p> We felt a little uncertain on this subject ourselves, and whenwe embarked on this survey, we quickly found out we had lotsof company. Even fund-family CEOs became tongue-tied when pepperedwith questions about what distinguished their own operationsfrom the rest of the pack.  <p> The focus in the mutual-fund industry has always been on individualfunds and their managers, such as Jeffrey Vinik at Fidelity Magellanor James P. Craig at Janus Fund. The companies behind the fundshave remained largely anonymous, though significant differencesexist among themin everything from investment strategy to theresources devoted to research. Cynics might say this obscurityallows mutual-fund salespeople to say what their potential customerswant to hear. Is Company X aggressive? Sure. Are its funds safeinvestments? Absolutely.  <p> The truth is that no single company does everything perfectly,or with the same degree of commitment. Some concentrate on conservativeinvestors; others seek risk takers. Some do well in equities,and others in fixed-income markets. These are distinctions prudentinvestors should know about before deciding where to put theirmoney. The problem has been that, to our knowledge, no one hasever surveyed the fund industry in this way.   <p> Our solution: compile the first-ever ratings of the 20 largestfund families in the U.S., helping investors identify the firmswhose style and record match their needs, while also giving thema reality check to use when reading a fund family's literatureor listening to a salesperson extol its infinite virtues.   <p> We based our lineup on total stock and bond assets under managementat each company (excluding money-market funds), as measured byMorningstar, the Chicago-based fund-analysis company. The listranges from 1st-place Fidelity Investments ($269 billion in assets)to 20th-place Janus Group ($23 billion).   <p> (Capital Publishing Limited Partnership, Worth's parent company,is a unit of FMR Corp., which also owns Fidelity. Fidelity, however,has no connection with or influence over Worth's editorial content.) <p> To conduct our research, we dispatched a team of reporters totalk to people at each company, as well as to the leading specialistsin the field. Only Dean Witter refused our requests for information;the other 19 fund families were fully cooperative. The 20 individualprofiles on the following pages are the fruit of this effort.  <p> Naturally, we took a hard look at the numbers, starting withyear-end 1995 performance data from the six top equity funds(based on total assets) and the six top bond funds at each company.(Janus, with four bond funds, was the one family that had fewerthan six in a category.) Limiting our investigation to a dozen funds at each company, we felt, helped level the playing field between the very biggest companies on our list and all the others.(Even so, the 240 funds we measured account for an impressive$769 billion in assets.)  <p> Using total-return figures from Morningstar, we then separatelyranked each company for the performance of its stock and bondfunds over the most recent one-, three-, five-, and ten-yearperiods. These rankings are contained in the tables that accompanyeach fund profile. Overall, the number-one performer in equitieswas the Houston-based AIM family. Smith Barney came out on topin bonds.  <p> Keep in mind that our survey represents a contest among industryleadersthe 20 largest fund families. A ranking as low as 20in any category, therefore, doesn't necessarily constitute apoor showing in the context of the $2.7 trillion universe of6,900-plus mutual funds.  <p> To discover which companies pursue performance most aggressively,we looked at portfolio turnover and average price-to-earningsratios for each family's equity funds. This means our aggressivenessrating for stock trading mirrors a family's investing stylehowrapidly it moves in and out of the marketalong with its willingnessto chase high-priced stocks. Market timers and momentum playersgenerally run portfolios full of stocks with high p/e ratios;conservative outfits, the reverse.  <p> On the bond side, we looked at the five-year standard deviation(essentially, how often performance varied from the norm). Forbond funds, standard deviation is a good measure of a portfoliomanager's willingness to assume risk in the pursuit of high yields. <p> As might be expected, Vanguardthe king of index fundsliesin the cellar in aggressiveness for both equities and bonds.The bottom of the equity list is dominated by the traditionallyconservative wire houses, the big brokerages with hundreds ofoffices. Prudential is 15th (due to its mix of utility and equityincome funds), Merrill is 16th, and Smith Barney is 18th. Franklin,at 19th, is even more conservative. We didn't expect this, because,among its six equity funds we measured, four were foreign funds,and overseas investing tends to increase risk. Still, the Franklinforeign funds have extremely low portfolio turnover; their managersare very patient investors.   <p> We assessed stability by measuring the average tenure of fundmanagers at each family. In the case of team-managed funds, weused the most senior manager. This gave a significant advantageto Capital Research, which relies on the team approach for virtuallyall of its American funds. But it also made Merrill Lynch's third-placerank all the more impressive, given its heavy reliance on individualmanagers. Fund families in the midst of substantial change, suchas Kemper and Prudential, bring up the rear, as do Fidelitydueto its pressure-cooker environmentand Janus, which has beenrapidly starting new funds.  <p> Lastly, we ranked the fund families based on how much they chargetheir customers, dividing the average maximum sales charge (firstfor bonds and then for equities) by five (to simulate the averagefive-year holding period) and then adding the result to the averageexpense ratio for each category. The wire houses tend to clusternear the bottom of this listmeaning they are expensive placesto do business. MFS also shows up as pricey. Fidelity and Dreyfus,meanwhile, were cheaper than we expected.   <p> We knew from the beginning that low-cost Vanguard was likelyto lead in this category, but we were still surprised by itsmargin of victory.   <p> To compute an overall rating for every fund family, we tabulatedthe rankings in each category. These results were decisiveandreinforced by more subjective factors (customer service, diversityof fund offerings, and management strength) uncovered in ourbroad reporting efforts. The four companies with the best combinationof rankingsAIM, Fidelity, T. Rowe Price (No. 1 overall), andVanguardearned our top $$$$$ rating. The worstDean Witter,Dreyfus, Franklin, and Prudentialgot only one $.  <p>- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - -   <p> <a name="FUND:AAGFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AAGFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AIM</b></a>  <p> Founded in 1976, the Aim family of Funds is the youngest companyamong our top 20and acts like it. Its fund managers favor thehigh-octane thrills of momentum investing. The strategy: Buystock in companies expected to post a string of sharply improvedquarterly earnings; pay a premium price if necessary, and holdon until the first sign of a setback; then cut and run. "If there'san earnings disappointment, we will move in seconds," says CharlesT. Bauer, AIM's co-founder and chief executive. "History tellsus that one disappointment is likely to be followed by one ortwo more."  <p> This strategy may make conservative investors uncomfortable,and when the market is declining, it may not even serve thosewho like to take risks. But AIM is very good at what it does,and its aggressive strategy has been well suited to the risingDow Jones Industrial Average of the past several years. It hasthe best overall equity performance numbers of any company onour list. The firm is also moving to protect itself against marketdownturns by broadening the products it sells through outsidebrokers.   <p> Stocks remain AIM's strength. It purchased most of CIGNA's lineupof fixed-income and equity funds in 1992, but 85 percent of itsoverall portfolio assets remain invested in equities. The 76-year-oldBauer may retire by year's end. His job will likely go to RobertH. Graham, who is 49. Don't expect major changes; Graham is alongtime Bauer confidant.   <p>  <p></wam-co FUND:AADBX>AMERICAN</b></a>  <p> Capital Research & Management, the Los Angelesbased parentof American Funds Group, rests its faith in the virtue of diversificationtothe point of applying this basic investing tenet to the managementstructure of its funds. Under Capital's "multiple-portfolio counselor"system, no single person bears sole responsibility for a mutualfund. Instead, managers run one or more subsidiary portfolios;an average of five of these portfolios, in turn, compose eachfund. A section of every fund is also controlled by the company'sresearch department, a practice largely unheard of elsewherein the industry. But Capital's research department is far fromordinary. With an annual budget of $75 million, it's one of thelargest in the business.  <p> Capital's managers favor long-term, value-oriented investingand shun risk. They emphasize stocks that have low price-to-earningsratios or that appear to be undervalued for other reasons. Thisstrategy has produced an enviable track record. The steady performanceof Capital's funds in tough or deteriorating markets is a strength.  <p> Capital's two largest fundsInvestment Company of America andWashington Mutual Investorscurrently rank second and third intotal assets behind Fidelity's Magellan fund. Investors who seekto preserve wealth will be happier with Capital than those whoexpect lofty returns. The company sells its American Fund lineupthrough outside brokers.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:DWIVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/DWIVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DEAN WITTER</b></a>  <p> It may be true that mutual-fund investors today are better informedand more focused on bottom-line results than ever before. ButNew Yorkbased Dean Witter InterCapital, a unit of Dean Witter,proves that mediocrity still sells, given a well-known brandname and a hard-driving force of commissioned salespeopleinits case, a network of more than 8,500 in-house retail brokers.The fund products peddled by this wire house share attributesonly a spendthrift could enjoy: lackluster performance, stiffloads, and high expenses.   <p> Despite the poor numbers, though, Dean Witter has more thantripled its equity assets under management in the past five years,excluding investment gains, according to Kanon Bloch Carr, aBoston-based fund-analysis company. No wonder it was the lastmajor wire house to discontinue the practice of paying its brokershigher commissions on in-house brands. And no wonder this wasthe only mutual-fund family that refused our requests for interviewsand information. Investors might consider taking their moneyelsewhereat least until Dean Witter demonstrates it is as seriousabout performance as it is about sales.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:DREVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/DREVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DREYFUS </b></a> <p> Dreyfus Group, which is based in New York, owns one of the mostwidely recognized trademarks in the fund business: the shaggylion that appears in its television commercials. Exactly whatlies behind this regal symbol is uncertain.   <p> Reputations today are fixed in the stars that appear regularlyin magazine and newspaper rankings of top-performing funds. Consideringits size and number of fund offerings, however, Dreyfus has beenconspicuously absent from these lists. Indeed, of the 20 fundfamilies we looked at, it has the worst overall performance ratings. <p> The firm has recognizedand acknowledgedits shortcomings. "Wehaven't told our story well, and we haven't always had a storyto tell," says Christopher M. Condron, president of the firm.In August 1994, Pittsburgh-based Mellon Bank bought Dreyfus andinstalled a new management team, headed by Condron. After arrivingin May, Stephen Canter, the fund family's first chief investmentofficer, divided his fund managers into five teamsgrowth, value,small-cap, international, and growth-and-income. He also institutedwhat he calls "quality-control loops" to ensure that funds adhereto specific investment disciplines.   <p> Revitalizing Dreyfus may take time. Its primary strength isits money-market operation, with $40 billion under management.But its equity funds have been among the few that haven't benefitedfrom the huge influx of investor cash in recent years. Four yearsago, the flagship Dreyfus Fund had $2.9 billion in assets; todayit has just $2.6 billion.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:FFIDX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FFIDX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FIDELITY</b></a>  <p> Our rankings place Fidelity Investments well below par for theperformance of its biggest equity and bond funds in 1995a surprise,given the firm's historic strength in these areas.  <p> Still, when it comes to size, clout, and resources, this Boston-basedcompany is tough to beat. It currently manages 84 percent moreassets than its nearest rival, Vanguard Group, and is one ofonly a few companies on our list whose calls can move markets.  <p> Fidelity's corporate culture emphasizes the survival of thefittest. The company compensates its fund managers handsomelyand supports them with lavish research and gee-whiz computersystems. But it also pits them against one another in gladiatorialcombat, creating a high-stress environment that results in above-averagefund-manager turnover.  <p> "Our philosophy is to give them every tool and then measurethem by their results," says Roger Servison, executive vice president.Hotshots move up to larger funds; laggards take their bottlesof Tagamet with them out the door. The result is an aggressivestock-picking operationone of the best in the business. Thecompany is also strong in high-yield bonds and convertible securities(which have given a big boost to its growth-and-income funds),but its methods haven't worked as well in overseas and emergingmarkets. The company, which runs one of the most effective telephone-salesand service organizations in the business, generally receiveshigh marks from customers.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:FIARX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FIARX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FRANKLIN </b></a> <p> Municipal-bond funds are the specialty of the Franklin TempletonGroup. Its fixed-income managers focus on the things that count.When Orange County, California, filed for bankruptcy in late1994, Franklin's California Tax-Free Income fundits biggestportfolio, with $13 billion in assetswas one of the few of itstype that didn't get hit. Known for painstaking research, theFranklin muni operation wields a big stick; municipalities oftenask it to preview the structure of new issues before they arebrought to market. The muni group emphasizes current income asopposed to total return; it prefers to buy and hold.  <p> When it comes to mainstream equity and bond funds, however,Franklin's performance has been mediocre. "We try to create fundsthat don't surprise investors," explains vice president GregJohnson, the son of Charles B. Johnson, Franklin Templeton'schief executive for nearly four decades.   <p> Unfortunately, this apparently applies to surprises on the upsideas well. Franklin's equity managers tend to be a timid bunch,sticking with tried-and-true investment principles. This hascost them dearly in the can't-miss market of the past severalyears.  <p> Franklin did get a boost with the purchase of Sir John Templeton's$21 billion family of global-stock funds in 1992. Since then,shrewd promotionplus increased investor enthusiasm for internationalmarketshas helped to nearly triple the Templeton assets. TheJohnsons have also had the good sense to avoid meddling withthe Templeton managers.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:IBLUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/IBLUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IDS</b></a>  <p> IDS Mutual Fund Group, a Minneapolis-based unit of AmericanExpress, sells its  <p>mutual-fund offerings through the 8,000 financial planners employedby its corporate parent. The AMEX horde also peddles insurance,variable annuities, and uninsured certificates of depositsothe IDS funds must compete for attention.  <p> As a fund family, IDS deliberately avoids innovation. At best,says Jim Punch, vice president for client services, "we liketo be an early follower." IDS also spends little on marketingand promotion. But it does support a good-sized research department,with 50 analysts and an unlimited travel allowance for interviewswith company managements. "We get out and kick the tires a lot,"says G.Michael Kennedy, director of research and a restaurant-industryanalyst. "I even steal menus."  <p> The company's conservative approach has served it best in thefixed-income arena; its bond funds performed second-best overallon our list. "We run our bond funds on a total-return basis,"says Fred Quirsfeld, senior portfolio manager. "We don't lookfor the highest current income because historically that approachunderperforms a total-return strategy."  <p> IDS stock funds, though, have been laggards. The company's $2.6billion Managed Retirement A fund, for instance, fell behindthe Standard &Poor's 500 Stock Index last year because a heftychunk of its holdings were invested in an odd mix of foreignsecurities and cyclical stocks. Similar problems afflicted the$2 billion Stock A fund and the $1.5 billion Equity Value B fund. <p>  <p><a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>JANUS </b></a> <p> Janus Group is the smallest outfit on our list in more waysthan one: The Denver-based company manages $23 billion in mutual-fundassets with 11 fund managers and 24 analysts. Perhaps nowhereis more money managed by fewer people. This may make Janus aworkaholic tribe, but it also enables the entire investment staffto gather once a day to swap ideas.  <p> Company founder Thomas Bailey likes to hire youth. "You geta highly energetic workforce," he says. Bailey himself is 58twodecades older than most of his senior employees.  <p> In the mid-1980s, Bailey turned the stock-picking operationover to Jim Craig and Tom Marsico, two managers with a demonstratedknack for identifying companies with accelerating earnings. Ingeneral, Janus managers rely heavily on in-house technical analysisand computer screens to identify promising picks, but don't buya stock unless they've met with the company's management.   <p> Janus funds have reasonably good long-term records. But thisis an aggressive outfit that is willing to take risks and shellout premium prices for stocks (its equity funds have higher overallprice-to-earnings ratios than those of any other major fund family),so its results should be even better than they are.  <p> The flagship Janus Fund, which at $12.3 billion accounts formore than half of the company's assets, stumbled early last year.Its portfolio was invested at an abnormally low 60 percent instocks at the start of 1995, so it missed part of the year'sbig surge in the market.   <p>  <p><a name="FUND:KADAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/KADAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>KEMPER </b></a> <p> Chicago-based Kemper Funds, purchased earlier this year by ZurichInsurance Group, trades on its expertise in fixed-income investingand its reputation as a plainspoken Midwestern money manager.Says Stephen Timbers, president of Kemper Financial Services(which will change its name to Zurich Kemper Investments on March1), "We like to think of ourselves as smart but not glitzy." <p> Kemper's glitz quotient rose last year, though, when it acquiredthe three-fund, $74 million mutual-fund operation run by notedcontrarian and value-style investor David Dreman. It also raidedAlliance Capital Management to hire Steven Reynolds as chiefinvestment officer. Reynolds promptly instituted a new in-houseritual under which fund managers challenge one another's picks.  <p> "Research is our major strength," says Reynolds. "We're alsogetting better at using market psychology and volatility to ouradvantage." For example, when Home Depot was trading in the mid-30slast October, the company's funds sharply increased their holdings.When the stock then rose to $48 in December, Kemper cut its position. <p> Reynolds says Kemper uses a proprietary computer model to aidits investment decision-making. He says that last September themodel warned that technology stocks were nearing a peak. So thecompany's growth funds cut their technology holdings in halfwellin advance of the high-tech sell-off that began later in theyear.   <p> "We never use cash as a risk adjuster, the way other funds do,"says Reynolds. "Instead, we alter the mix of stocks."  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:MAAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MAAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MERRILL LYNCH</b></a>  <p> Of the major wire-house firms, Merrill Lynch Group has arguablythe best mutual-fund operation. Arthur Zeikel, the longtime bossof Merrill Lynch's Princeton, New Jerseybased fund operations,sets clear benchmarks for his managers and rewards them for performance.  <p> Each Merrill Lynch fund has a lead manager and one or two researchassistants. There's no centralized research department, no governinginvestment committee, and no staff economist. There is also noformula to the company's spadework: Some managers get out tosee companies firsthand; others don't. Zeikel is the author ofseveral textbooks on investing, but says he resists any temptationto micromanage. "I don't care if they use tea leaves or chartsor fundamental research," he says. "The autonomy our managershave is unique."  <p> The Merrill Lynch investment approach is generally conservativeand risk-averse"We want to limit the anxiety level," says Zeikel.He's loath to do anything that might compromise the Merrill Lynchname. He says this is also why the fund group doesn't pursuevolatile sector funds or single-country funds.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:MFALX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MFALX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MFS</b></a>  <p> Back in 1924, the MFS family of funds gave birth to the U.S.'sfirst mutual fund. Given the historic ups and downs of the mutual-fundbusiness, the mere longevity of this company is an accomplishmentof sorts. Of course, in the intervening years, MFS also has beenpassed by 18 other fund families in total assets.   <p> Today, it's a solid concern owned by Sun Life Assurance of Canada.MFS offers a broad base of funds, a number of which have someof the longest track records around. Standouts include the EmergingGrowth B fund, which has achieved average annual returns of justover 30 percent during the past five years.  <p> The Boston-based MFS is a collegial, cooperative place, unlikecrosstown rival Fidelity. Annual bonuses are based not only onperformance but also on how often managers contribute good ideasto other funds. "We have one of the best team atmospheres inthe world," says MFS president Jeff Shames.  <p> The equity-fund managers in this shop tend to be long-term players.It's rare that an MFS portfolio includes more than 5 percentcash. The primary objective, according to Shames, is to pickstocks that will rise the most in a surging market and fall theleast in a declining market.   <p> The fund managers generally pay little attention to such macroconsiderations as the outlook for the economy, the markets, orthe U.S. presidential elections. Instead, the emphasis at MFSis on fundamental corporate analysis. "We learn more about theeconomy from talking with companies than any economist couldever tell us," says Shames. MFS has 30 full-time analysts. Eachis assigned to cover two or three industries and keep tabs onan average of 40 companies in which MFS funds own a stake. Inkeeping with the company's team approach, each analyst worksfor the fund group as whole, not for individual managers.   <p>  <p><a name="FUND:OPPFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/OPPFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>OPPENHEIMER </b></a> <p> "We're the Ford Explorer of mutual-fund companies," says JonFossel, Oppenheimer Funds' chairman. "It's not the fastest vehiclearound, but it can take you where you are going in any kind ofweather."   <p> Fossel emphasizes the importance of outperforming comparablemutual fundsand compensates his managers accordingly. He doesn't,however, believe in shooting for the highest possible returns.In his view, the added gains aren't worth the added risksparticularlyfor a company such as Oppenheimer, which has a conservative,older clientele. As a result, the Oppenheimer name rarely appearson annual lists of top performers. But it also rarely shows upamong the industry laggards.  <p> The one exception to this rule used to be Oppenheimer's MainStreet Income & Growth Fund, an extraordinary, anything-goesfund run by star manager John Wallace. Wallace, however, leftlast summer in a messy split to join Robertson Stephens. Fosselhimself may also leave soon. Defeated in a bid for the U.S. Congressin 1982, he has recently hinted that he'll make another stabat politics.  <p> In the meantime, Oppenheimer remains one of the most accessibleand customer-oriented organizations in the fund business. Fossel,who answers his own phone, says Oppenheimer employees constantlyhear the comment "You're really friendly. You don't seem likeyou're from New York City."   <p>  <p><a name="FUND:PFCAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PFCAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PRUDENTIAL </b></a> <p> President Richard Redeker arrived in 1993 to find almost nothinggoing right  <p>at Prudential Mutual Funds. The product line was nondescriptand performing no better than average. The parent company wasawash in ugly publicity from a scandal involving the sale ofbillions of dollars of limited-partnership interests.   <p> Many of the problems with the family's mutual fundslike thosewith the limited partnershipsresulted from Prudential's 1981purchase of brokerage firm Bache Securities. After the purchase,Prudential began adding new funds to feed the Bache brokeragesystem, but the fundssuch as the Short-Term Global Income Fund,which played on a temporary fad for international money-marketfundswere driven by brokers' demands for salable gimmicks. Theresult was a motley collection of offerings that had little connectionto one another and that made little sense to investors.  <p> Redeker has pared the lineupphasing out single-state muni funds,for example, while adding othersin an attempt to give Prudentiala more rational product line. At the same time, he's hired sometop managers from other firms, including bond manager BarbaraKenworthy from Dreyfus and international guru Dan Duane fromFirst Investors. Late last year, the company, which had beenlacking a single aggressive growth fund, launched the JennisonFund, managed by Jennison Associates, a separate unit of Prudentialwith a strong history as an institutional money manager.  <p> Still, the firm has a long way to go. Despite a vast lineup,there still isn't a superstar fund in the house, and few areabove average. The company's biggest offering, the $4.1 billionPrudential Utility Fund, ranks in the bottom quarter of its peergroup over the past five years because of a so far unsuccessfulstrategy that gives up traditionally high yields for capitalappreciation.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:PAMBX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PAMBX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PUTNAM </b></a> <p> In 1830, a Boston judge created the famous "prudent-man rule,"granting fiduciaries considerable discretion to act for theirclients. The judge's name: Samuel Putnam. More than a centurylater, great-great-grandson George Putnam founded Putnam Investmentswith the country's first "balanced" mutual fund, investing inboth stocks and bonds. In 1970, George Putnam's descendants soldtheir sleepy, still-modest business to Marsh & McLennan, thepublicly held New York insurance brokerage. Putnam Mutual Fundshas been on a tear ever since.  <p> The company is still just average in the fixed-income arena,but its group of equity funds is the only one on our list whoserankings approach those of AIM. The credit goes to Lawrence J.Lasser, a blunt, demanding leader who joined Putnam as an analystand rose to become chief executive in 1981. He has overseen Putnam'smarketing, emphasizing aggressive stock-market performance andestablishing a national brand name.   <p> Lasser has extracted above-average results for most of Putnam'sequity funds without a star-manager system. Indeed, Lasser hatesstars, and a number of Putnam funds are now run by teams. Theflagship Voyager fund, for instance, is controlled by three people,each assigned to stocks in different categories. Putnam is hierarchical:Thinking "outside the box" is a no-no.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:SCBAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SCBAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SCUDDER </b></a> <p> Scudder funds launched the first no- load mutual fund in 1928,and in 1953 opened the first U.S.-based mutual fund to investinternationally. Nonetheless, this firm has a surprisingly lowprofile among U.S. investors. Maybe that's because its research-intensiveinvesting style produces solid results but rarely earns any ofthe family's funds a top rating.   <p> Scudder seems to revel in anonymity, eschewing the star-managersystem in favor of collective management. "They're very privateand low-key," says Louis Harvey of Dalbar, a Boston publisherof financial-services market research. "They manage their fundsthe same way."  <p> Unlike other fund companies, where an analyst's position isoften a stepping-stone to portfolio manager, Scudder views its67 research slots as lifelong careers. The company's two-prongedapproach divides researchers into two categories: country analystsand industry analysts.  <p> Mutual-fund consultants describe Scudder as old-line and conservative.But this view is not shared by Dudley Ladd, Scudder's co-chairman:"Are we conservative investors? We would say no," he says. "Somefunds are specifically positioned as conservative, but we alsohave some very aggressive funds, particularly in the internationalareas."  <p> Ladd seems to have a point: The conservative Growth & Incomefund is Scudder's best-rated U.S. equity fund. On the high-riskside, though, Scudder also opened the first U.S. funds to investexclusively in Latin America (1992) and Korea (1984).  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:ARMGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ARMGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SMITH BARNEY </b></a> <p> "Gray hair in the investment business isn't a bad thing," saysJessica Bibliowicz, executive vice president of Smith BarneyMutual Funds, a unit of the Travelers Group. Bibliowicz is juststarting her second year on the job, so the gray hair belongsto her fund managerseach with an average of 25 years in thebusiness.   <p> This experience has paid dividends for the company's bond funds,which have done well. Its equity funds, however, are anothermatter. As a group, they've performed dismally in comparisonwith the other fund families on our list, although there aretwo exceptions: International Equity A and Premium Total ReturnB. Both bonds and equities, however, are sideshow acts next toSmith Barney's huge money-market operation, which tends to drawits in-house  <p>investment expertise.  <p> Smith Barney used its merger with Shearson Lehman to restructureits fund complex, says Bibliowicz, merging weak funds with strongerperformers and eliminating theme funds. The new product linepursues a middle-of-the-road strategy, says Michael Lipper, presidentof Lipper Analytical Services. Each fund seeks to capture theperformance of its asset class. "The strategy is to get on basetryto hit a single, if not get a walk. But don't strike out," Lippersays.  <p> For her part, Bibliowicz vows that Smith Barney "isn't goingto be a typical wire-house operation." She has a long way togo before reaching that goal, but as the daughter of Travelerschairman Sanford Weill, she just might get there.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:PRSUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. ROWE PRICE </b></a> <p> This company was one of the early pioneers of no-load, low-costfundsand it still offers its retirement-plan clientele someof the best bargains in the business. In fact, T. Rowe PriceFunds achieved the highest overall rankings of the 20 fund familieswe measured.  <p> This family's biggest and most successful fund is its $6.9 billionInternational Stock fund, which it manages via a joint venturewith the London investment firm of Robert Fleming. But T. Rowe'sstrength in picking small-cap stocks has given it an edge inits domestic-equity funds as well.  <p> Within the industry, T. Rowe is also well-respected for itsteam of 40 analysts. Each covers a specific sector and is responsiblefor making sure that fund managers get new investment ideas.In fact, much of a researcher's end-of-year evaluation is basedon how successful he or she was at disseminating ideas. Eachfund is run by a lead manager and supervised by an investmentcommittee. Manager trades are broadcast daily over an internalcomputer network.  <p> In some ways, T. Rowe Price is lucky to be around at all. Thefirm struggled mightily in the mid-1970s when its growth-stock-investingstylepioneered by founder Thomas Rowe Price Jr.cost it 50 percentof assets in the only three funds it had. In response, Pricebroadened the company's product range and investing style, thoughthe management still shuns anything it regards as a temporaryfad. Its fixed-income operation also earned impressive scores. <p>  <p><a name="FUND:TWBIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TWBIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TWENTIETH CENTURY </b></a> <p> In the early 1970s, Twentieth Century Family of Funds founderJames Stowers Jr. became the first mutual-fund manager to publiclyembrace the now famous tenet "money follows earnings"the underlyingtheme of momentum investing. Stowers's insight helped make TwentiethCentury one of the hottest equity shops of the past decade.  <p> As recently as 1980, Twentieth Century still had just two dozenemployees and only $42 million under management. Today, it has2,200 employees and $14 billion in a single portfolio: TwentiethCentury Ultra Investors.  <p> Ultranow team-managed by a group including Stowers's son, JamesIII is still a highly rated equity fund, as are at least threeother Twentieth Century portfolios (Giftrust Investors, GrowthInvestors, and Heritage Investors). Nevertheless, the company'soverall equity performance has slipped in comparison with thatof its rivals.   <p> Stowers was an early user of computers in the mutual-fund business,and Twentieth Century relies heavily on database searches andcomputer analyses to identify stocks with positive earnings outlooks.But portfolio managers, not spreadsheets, make the final calls.  <p> Twentieth Century recently acquired the well-regarded Benhambond fundsa move that should substantially improve the family'sfixed-income performance over the long haul.  <p>  <p><a name="FUND:VAITX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VAITX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VANGUARD </b></a> <p> "Vanguard's approach is unique among top mutual-fund companies,"says Cebra Graves, of Morningstar. Few investors fully appreciatethis. Most know of Vanguard Group's dedication to low fees (atan average of 0.3 percent, Vanguard's expense ratios are thelowest in the industry by a wide margin). And they probably knowthat Vanguard is the leading proponent of passively managed indexfunds. The flagship Vanguard Index Trust 500 Portfolio, the country'sfourth-largest stock fund, with $15 billion, was designed toduplicate the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index and over fiveyears has trailed it by less than 0.2 percent, an achievementmost actively managed mutual funds can't match.   <p> But few investors know that Vanguard is the only fund companyset up like a nonprofit organization, the result of a falling-outin 1974 between founder John Bogle and the top management ofa predecessor organization. That means customers, in effect,own the management company and don't have to pad someone else'sprofits or pay corporate income taxes. "We are a mutual mutualfund," says chief executive John Brennan.  <p> Vanguard contracts out the management of the majority of itsnon-index equity funds, such as the $13.5 billion Vanguard/Windsorfund, to independent managers. Wellington Management's John Neff,who used a value-investing style to beat markets for 31 years,ran the Windsor fund until the end of last year, when he retired.His successor is longtime assistant Charles Freeman. "A lot ofmanagers call on us," says Brennan, "but we hire only two tothree a year. Last year we hired two." About $80 billion of Vanguard's$180 billion assets are now managed by outsiders.   <p>  <p><a name="FUND:ACSTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACSTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VAN KAMPEN</wam-co>  <p> The six largest equity funds managed by Van Kampen AmericanCapital bested our field in 1995with an average return of 36percent. It remains to be seen, though, whether this was a fluke. <p> When the Chicago bond-fund manager Van Kampen Merritt mergedwith Houston stock-and-bond-fund manager American Capital in1994, critics wondered whether an alliance of two weaklingsneitherhad especially good performance records prior to the mergercouldcreate a Goliath.  <p> The company's showing last year may at least temporarily silencethese detractors. Still, several factors continue to weigh againstVan Kampen. It has a small research department of only 6 equityanalysts (versus 30 on the bond side). Its sales charges andexpense ratios are high. And it takes a middle-of-the-road approachto investing (it creates model portfolios by looking at competingfunds with similar styles and at the appropriate indexes).  <p> The merged outfits still have separate headquarters. CEO DonPowell is in Houston; much of the back office is in Chicago.Says Dennis Dolego of Financial Research of Chicago: "They haven'tbeen able to differentiate themselves from their competitors." <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -  <p>Reporting assistance by Pamela J. Black, Jonathan Butler, AndrewFeinberg, John Fried, Andrew Gluck, and John Kearney. <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
