	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-How to Adopt a Newborn Fund</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>How to Adopt a Newborn Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-How to Adopt a Newborn Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Investing  <p> HOW TO ADOPT A NEWBORN FUND <p>The best rewards often come from mutual funds that have yet to prove themselves. The key is knowing how to pick them.  <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> New or relatively young mutual funds are phantoms to many professionals who advise investors. Requiring data that only an established track record can provide, they won't recommend a fund that hasn't been around for at least five years. Although Morningstar Mutual Funds will follow a fund from inception, it won't bestow a star ranking for three years, and Worth requires a five-year cutoff for its rating system.   <p> The tenure restrictions aren't necessarily bad, given that there are thousands of well-established funds and lack of choice is hardly a major complaint among investors these days. Nevertheless, they do mean that tantalizing opportunities can slip through the cracks--including funds with top-flight managers already at the controls. Investors who spot such opportunities can earn big rewards.  <p> How to do it? The key is knowing that managers can have established track records even when their funds don't.   <p> Two notable examples are Donald Yacktman and Louis Navellier. Although both managers have enviable records as investors and are admired among their peers, the funds they manage haven't been around long enough to pop up on most tables that rate funds.  <p> Yacktman established his credentials working as the manager of a fund called <a name="FUND:SLASX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SLASX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Selected American Shares</b></a>, now located in Sante Fe and managed by Selected/Venture Advisors. From 1983 to 1992, he logged an estimable 17.8 percent annual return, a performance that prompted Morningstar to name him Manager of the Year in1991. In 1992, however, Yacktman suddenly disappeared from the charts--not because his star had plummeted but because he had struck out on his own. He had launched the fledgling and track recordless <a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a>, a venture that has since proved to be another solid performer. (The Chicago-based Yacktman Fund was up 24 percent through the first nine months of 1995.)  <p> Navellier started his mutual fund--the <a name="FUND:NASCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NASCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Navellier Aggressive Small Cap Growth Fund</b></a>--in April 1994. This was no novice operation, either. For ten years, Navellier had been recording average annual returns of close to 20 percent as a manager of private money in Incline Village, Nevada. He also had become one of the best-known financial newsletter writers in the country, topping the ten-year performance list for August 1995 in the Hulbert Fincancial Digest. So it was far from a surprise when Navellier's new fund recorded a 65 percent return during the 12 months ended last September.  <p> In such cases, "you don't need five years of observation," says Donald Trone of Callan Associates in San Francisco, one of the nation's largest investment consulting firms.   <p> Trone does recommend waiting a year to see how well a new fund gets out of the blocks, noting that Yacktman's fund lost 6.6 percent in 1993, its first full year. Investors also need to recognize that some fund-manager transitions are likely to be smoother than others. A manager who jumps from investing in Treasurys to junk bonds, for instance, could be asking for a rough time. On the other hand, a manager who moves from a mid-cap fund to small caps, or from small to micro caps, would probably represent a fairly safe bet.  <p> Roy Komack, a fee-only adviser in Natick, Massachusetts, says he is recommending that his clients invest in a five-month-old fund called <a name="FUND:WMICX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WMICX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wasatch Micro-Cap</b></a>. Why? Because his favorite small-cap fund, <a name="FUND:WAAEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/WAAEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wasatch Aggressive Equity Fund</b></a>, closed to new investors on July 15. He feels confident that the new fund will employ the same bottom-up, fast-growth strategy practiced so successfully over time by Sam Stewart, founder of Wasatch, which is based in Salt Lake City.  <p> Securities regulators don't allow mutual funds to advertise a manager's record from handling private money or from running another fund, but investors can obtain such information simply by calling a fund and asking for it. Investors can also ask for the manager's rsum and a list of institutional clients to learn more about the manager's skills. The data is most likely to be reliable if it has been audited by an independent accounting firm or if it complies with standards set by the Association for Investment Management and Research in Charlottesville, Virginia.  <p> Yacktman Fund (800-525-8258) <p>Navellier Aggressive Small Cap Growth (800-887-8671) <p>Wasatch Micro-Cap (800-345-7460).  <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

