	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Minimums Come Down to Earth</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Minimums Come Down to Earth</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover   <p> MINIMUMS COME DOWN TO EARTH  <p> By Manjeet Kripalani  <p> Imagine this: You read about the management expertise of a fund run by California-based PIMCO. The returns are terrific. You rush to buy into the fund, to live happily ever after. But this is just a fairy tale, for the fund you love has a minimum investment of $1 million; what's more, it's available only to institutional investors.  <p> Weep no more. Thanks to discount broker Jack White and the fund supermarkets of <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> and Fidelity, some institutional funds with high minimums are now available at much lower minimums to retail investors. It's not that the higher-minimum players have relented; it's simply that they now choose to regard the broker rather than the retail investor as the client. The broker meets the minimum by combining small parcels. Everybody benefits: the fund company and broker get more money and clients; the individual investor gets a wider-range of funds. Some of Federated Investors' institutional funds, normally offered at a minimum of $25,000, are available through Schwab and Fidelity for $1,000. PIMCO's institutional funds, which normally carry $1 million minimums, can be had through Jack White for $25,000. Three Invesco funds that normally carry $1 million minimums can be had through Fidelity for a $2,500 starter.  <p> For the fund groups, it's a matter of survival. "Federated participates because of those over 4,000 investment advisors who clear through Schwab and maintain over $40 billion in custody through them,"says John Fisher, head of institutional investments at Federated."We don't care about retail investors; we care about those investment advisors."  <p> All right, so that's not the warmest welcome a small investor ever got. As long as they'll take a check. <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
