	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Is Bigger Better - for Whom?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Is Bigger Better - and for Whom?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Is Bigger Better - for Whom?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover   <p> IS BIGGER BETTER--AND FOR WHOM?  <p> By Jonathan Butler  <p> The number of mutual funds keeps climbing. According to the Investment Company Institute in Washington, D.C., there were 5,642 funds at the end of July, up more than 5 percent from the 5,357 at the end of 1994.  <p> But fewer and fewer companies own that growing multitude of funds. While the banks have been stealing the headlines with their high-profile megamergers, the mutual-fund industry has also been consolidating at a rapid pace. Some mergers--like New England Investment Companies' purchase of the Oakmark Funds--have involved household names, while others--such as ARM Financial buying SBM Co. and <a name="NASD:NSFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46031"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Northstar</b></a> teaming up with <a name="NYSE:ADV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10038"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Advest</b></a>--have involved lesser-known players. Through the first seven months of this year, there were 17 deals in which a fund company either merged or was acquired, according to the newsletter Fund Action. By comparison, there were only 19 such deals in all of 1994.  <p> The companies are looking to get three things from greater size: economies of scale, new products, and new channels of distribution. These goals are not, you'll notice, primarily about the investor.(Nor do you see many companies pass on the savings from economies of scale in the form of lower fees.)  <p> And sometimes investors are caught in a crunch--particularly investors who have been picking the right funds. After a merger, for example, funds with similar investment objectives are often combined. This has the effect of burying the performance record of the weaker fund, since the surviving fund will generally assume whichever track record is better (as well as the name of the better-performing fund, if possible). Investors in the poorer-performing fund can't complain: They get new management. But investors in the better-performing fund are stuck with whatever portfolio baggage came with the poor performer and can be hurt long-term by the inflexibility of a larger asset base.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:NSFC">Northern States Financial Corp.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:ADV">The Advest Group, Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
