<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Fund Selection System</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>A Fund Selection System that Works</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Fund Selection System</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 
<p>
Worth magazine/Cover   
<p>
 A FUND SELECTION SYSTEM THAT WORKS 
<p>
Here's how we picked five stock funds with the best prospects<p>
<p>
 By Jim Jubak  
<p>
 Last year, we set out to build a better system for picking mutual
funds. Our goal was to devise a rational, defensible method for
selecting equity funds--one that would take the roulette wheel
out of the equation. Predictability was our primary focus. What
we wanted, more than anything, was to find out which of the better-performing
equity funds were merely lucky and which possessed the strategies
and skills to provide investors with a true edge. No other selection
method we know of does this.  
<p>
 So how did our picks fare? Not too shabbily--especially considering
our conservative approach.  
<p>
 The four U.S. stock funds we highlighted last year averaged
a total return of 23.1 percent for the 12 months ended August
31, outdistancing the performance of the broad market as measured
by the Russell 3000 stock index. Each of our four domestic picks
also beat the average for its peer group--ranging from Mutual
Beacon (1.47 percentage points above the average large-cap value
fund) to Heartland Value (10.96 percentage points above the average
small-cap value fund).  
<p>
 The lone disappointment was our 1994 selection for best global
equity fund: Warburg Pincus International Equities, which fell
4.32 percent. Although most global and international funds posted
negative results during our measurement period, we expected better
from this pick. (See "Last Year's Picks")  
<p>
 Still, even with Warburg as part of the mix, we continue to
feel sanguine about the prospects for our 1994 choices. Why?
Because our focus, from the beginning, has been on the long term.
And in that context, one year's worth of results only means so
much, good or bad.  
<p>
 All told, the system we devised last year worked the way we
wanted it to, selecting a diversified group of top-notch, reliable
performers. Sure, it would have been nice to have singled out
the Seligman Communications and Information fund a year ago.
It clobbered our picks, rising 91.5 percent through August 31.
But even if we had picked Seligman last year, we wouldn't recommend
it again now.  
<p>
 Funds that achieve No. 1 status in any given year rarely turn
out to be consistent performers over time. In fact, a lofty ranking
based on performance alone may be a sign of an extreme and therefore
risky investment style. The best funds (including Fidelity's
Magellan when it was run by Peter Lynch) rarely hit No. 1 in
any single year. Our system attempts to identify consistent performers--funds
worth hanging on to year in and year out.   
<p>
 Any investor who has been in the game for a while knows how
much damage a poor market can do to one's patience and resolve.
But strong markets like this year's can also be tricky. Invariably,
some investments rack up eye-popping numbers. Even if your holdings
are doing well, it's tempting to abandon a carefully laid strategy
and chase after these bottle rockets--only to arrive just as
they begin to fizzle.  
<p>
 Of course, it's still important to test even long-range predictions
against the most recent data. So we gave our methodology the
once-over using a computer analysis program called Stastica.
We used this program, developed by StatSoft Inc., to evaluate
the correlation between the rankings of the 777 equity funds
we looked at in 1994 and their actual performance over the following
year. Based on this test, we elected to make only minor adjustments
to our selection system for 1995.  
<p>
 To begin this year's process, we once again asked Morningstar
Inc. to supply us with raw data. This year's information included
two new categories: the earnings growth rate for each fund's
portfolio and the percentage of each portfolio invested outside
the U.S. Our in-house research team filled holes in the Morningstar
numbers and double-checked 25,000 bits of data. A total of 883
equity funds met our minimum listing requirements of a five-year
track record and assets totaling at least $25 million.   
<p>
 Analyst Kevin Maloney at Frank Russell Co. helped direct our
listings of U.S. equity funds into a matrix of four groups: large-cap
value funds, large-cap growth funds, small-cap value funds, and
small-cap growth funds. (Cap in this context refers to the median
market capitalization of the stocks in an equity fund's portfolio.
It is calculated by multiplying the share price by the number
of shares outstanding.) High cap numbers mean that a fund invests
primarily in large corporations. We designated a fund as large
cap if its median market capitalization was over $1.5 billion.
Small-cap funds fall below that level.   
<p>
 We then split each of these two groups based on their investment
style: Does a fund lean toward selecting stocks based on their
potential growth or based on intrinsic value? The yardstick we
used was the median price-to-book ratio (the relationship between
the price of a stock and its underlying asset value). Among large-cap
funds, a median price-to-book ratio above 2.87 put a fund into
our growth category; anything below went into value. For small-cap
funds, we used a median price-to-book ratio of 2.29 as the dividing
line.  
<p>
 Our fifth category, global funds, covers only those funds that
invest at least 40 percent of their assets outside the U.S. <p>
<p>
 To us, these five categories represent an effective way for
investors to diversify their equity portfolios--balancing large-cap
funds against small-cap, value against growth, and domestic funds
against those that invest around the globe.  
<p>
 After we grouped the funds, we began the process of identifying
the best fund in each category based on scores in three areas:
performance, risk, and predictability. We started with performance,
taking the five-year total return of each fund, subtracting the
impact of front-end sales charges, and then ranking the result
against the fund's peers. Our tables, beginning on page 127,
list this score, as well as each fund's raw one-, three-, and
five-year returns and the fund's performance against a benchmark
index. Four Russell indexes served this purpose for the U.S.
funds. We pitted the global funds against one of two Morgan Stanley
Capital International indexes: the Europe, Australasia, and Far
East index (EAFE) for funds with more than 75 percent of their
assets outside the U.S., and the World index for funds that combined
major holdings inside the U.S. with substantial overseas investments.
The split benchmark was new to our calculations this year, but
necessary, we felt, because the U.S. market had so outperformed
the rest of the world. That meant that global funds, which mix
U.S. and overseas stocks, substantially outperformed foreign
funds, limited by their charters to overseas stocks. (The EAFE
index returned 0.79 percent for the 12 months; the World index
scored a 8.78 percent return.)  
<p>
 Next, we looked at risk. Here we focused on three different
measurements of fund characteristics: standard deviation, which
shows the degree of variance in a fund's performance over time;
beta, a measure of a fund's volatility in relation to the entire
stock market; and turnover, a measure of how actively a fund's
portfolio is traded by its manager. We like each of these three
because none of them pogo-stick in sync with the market. This
year, we also decided to factor a fund's load and expenses into
our risk assessment. That's because we wanted to reflect a simple
reality of mutual-fund management: High sales charges and fees
put additional pressure on fund managers to justify high premiums.
After completing the risk measurements, we again compared each
fund with its peers. The final risk rating appears in our listings,
with 100 representing the lowest level of risk.  
<p>
 Our predictor rating, a feature found in no other ranking system,
provides an assessment of how likely a fund is to repeat its
performance in the future. To derive this score, we first checked
the tenure of a fund's manager during the five-year study period.
A new manager might be better or worse than the one responsible
for the fund's track record, but there's certainly no way to
divine which. Our predictor rating also considers the growth
of a fund's net assets from 1992 to 1995, on the theory that
it is harder to manage a rapidly growing fund. In the current
market, we also worry about funds that must invest lots of new
cash at high prices. Finally, we compared each fund's current
beta and price-to-book ratios with those ratios three years ago.
Big changes could signal shifts in a fund's style. This year,
we concluded that while movements in price-to-book and beta ratios
are important indicators for all funds, they aren't as significant
for growth funds as for value funds. To reflect this, we slightly
modified our formula for calculating the predictor rating for
each type of fund.  
<p>
 Our final overall rating, expressed by dollar signs, combines
the risk, return, and predictor results into one score--$ for
laggards to $$$$$ for the very best, based on our objectives.
Only the top 5 percent of the funds in each category is deemed
worthy of our $$$$$ rating.  
<p>
 Readers should keep in mind that the criteria we use embody
an intentional bias. Our rating system, for instance, tends to
penalize sector funds, because they are more risky and less predictable
than other types. Our reasoning: Sector funds, which normally
invest in a single industry, aren't well-suited to a portfolio
of only four or five funds. Instead they are meant to track a
fairly narrow segment of the market. They appeal either to people
with specialized knowledge of an industry or to investors who
already hold broadly diversified portfolios and are looking for
some extra return.  
<p>
 Our system is designed to produce a balanced portfolio, and
we think the adjustments we've made in our method this year should
yield even better results for investors  in the future. They
are intended to help push the investment styles in our portfolio
further apart, improving diversification.  
<p>
 For example, on the small-cap end of the portfolio, our top
growth fund, T. Rowe Price New Horizons, is substantially different
from our top value pick, T. Rowe Price Small Cap. The growth
fund shows a beta of 1.2--indicating a volatility above that
of the entire market--while the value fund's beta is just 0.62.
The median annual earnings growth rate of the stocks in the portfolio
of the growth fund is nearly 30 percent; the median growth rate
of the stocks in the value fund's portfolio is 13.4 percent.
As investors might expect from those numbers, the price-to-earnings
ratio of the growth fund is almost 33. In the value fund it's
just 19.1.  
<p>
 The two top large-cap funds present an even more dissimilar
picture. Mutual Qualified, the pick of the value funds, has a
beta of 0.8 and a standard deviation of 2.1. Its median stock
shows earnings growth of a scant 3.8 percent a year--and carries
a price-to-earnings ratio of just 16.7. Growth fund Harbor Capital
Appreciation shows an above-market beta of 1.3 and a standard
deviation of 3.6 (reflecting a higher rate of variability in
its performance). The median stock in the portfolio has earnings
growth of almost 23 percent annually and has a p/e ratio of 27.<p>
<p>
 Of course, though we wanted the changes in our system to make
it easier to diversify, we didn't want to end up simply adding
high-risk funds to our portfolio. So we compared these growth
funds with their peers by examining some of their basic characteristics.
Harbor Capital Appreciation, for example, was certainly riskier
than the average large-cap growth fund, which showed a beta of
0.93 and a standard deviation of 2.73. But it wasn't the riskiest
in the category--it trailed well behind such highflyers as Seligman
Communications and Information (beta 1.57). T. Rowe Price New
Horizons didn't make the top of the risk charts in the small-cap
growth category either--it finished behind 26 other funds with
higher betas,  including earnings-driven bellwethers such as
Twentieth Century Vista Investors (beta 1.47).  
<p>
 Actually, in analyzing the five funds that wound up as our top
picks, we found only one surprise: Founders Worldwide Growth,
a global fund with substantial U.S. investments (almost 38 percent,
according to Morningstar). Founders had to overcome a matchup
with the higher World index, which includes U.S. and foreign
stocks, while some of its peers had only to best the EAFE index.
Frankly, we didn't expect a fund facing that kind of handicap
(on a five-year basis the difference between the World and the
EAFE Index is about 2.9 percent annually) to rise to the top.
But there's no arguing with Founders' numbers. Over the past
five years the fund has returned more with less risk than any
other fund in its class. And that--finding the best mix of high
reward and low risk for the long haul--is what our fund selection
method is all about.  
<p><p>
<p>
LAST YEAR'S PICKS: A RECAP  
<p>
 All five of our 1994 fund picks fell slightly in this year's
ratings--not because they didn't perform well, but because investors
smothered them with affection. Heartland Value Fund, our top
choice for small-cap value fund last year, demonstrates just
how difficult it is for even a great fund to stay on top. In
1995 Heartland kept up the performance that earned it our top
$$$$$ rating in 1994. The fund returned 25.63 percent for the
12 months ended August 31, 1995--and yet still dropped a rank
to $$$$ in this year's list. How come? Despite closing its doors
to new investors in July 1995, Heartland grew to $1.05 billion
in assets, up from $261 million last year and just $35.7 million
in 1992. As a result, the number of stocks in its portfolio leapt
from 48 in 1990 to 244 in early 1995, according to Morningstar.
Price-to-earnings ratios and price-to-book ratios both rose as
well.  
<p>
 Ditto for Wasatch Aggressive Equity, our top small-cap growth
fund. Its 29.30 percent total return for the 12 months actually
bettered the fund's average annual return for the last five years.
But climbing assets--up to $293.7 million from $39.4 million
in just one year--lowered the fund's risk and reliability ratings.
Manager Samuel Stewart closed the doors to money from new investors
on July 15.  
<p>
 Both of last year's top large-cap choices, Fidelity Disciplined
Equity and Mutual Beacon, performed almost exactly as predicted--yet
still lost just enough ground to earn $$$$ ratings. Fidelity
Disciplined Equity returned 21.59 percent, beating the average
large-cap growth fund by 2.46 percentage points, but its assets
about doubled. That, plus a big increase in the median price-to-book
ratio of stocks in its portfolio--up to 4.66 from 2.77 three
years ago--hurt the fund's reliability rating. Last year's large-cap
value choice, Mutual Beacon, sported a favorable risk rating
that offset a slight lag in performance. But surging assets this
year lowered its risk score.  
<p>
 Even Warburg Pincus International Equity Fund Common Shares
fell in our ratings. This happened more because of an influx
of investors (more than doubling its assets) than because of
lagging performance. Manager Richard King's heavy weighting in
Japan--about a quarter of the fund's stock portfolio in May 1995--certainly
dragged down return, but the fund still scored in the 93rd percentile
overall, barely missing the $$$$$ category.  
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
