		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>So Much for Economies of Scale</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-So Much for Economies of Scale</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover Story  <p> SO MUCH FOR ECONOMIES OF SCALE  <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> The mutual fund boom has been a bust when it comes to lowering expenses for investors. More than 1,700 new mutual funds have been launched in the past 18 months, but competition hasn't forced funds to slash costs to attract investors. Nor has the tremendous influx of money into the industry. Just the opposite.   <p> According to data from Lipper Analytical Services, there are six times more funds now than in 1985 and assets have grown fivefold, from $466 billion to $2.35 trillion. But the median expense ratio of the 5,632 mutual funds that have reported a full fiscal year of operations is 96 basis points, Lipper data show, up from 91 basis points in 1990 and 87 basis points in 1985. So far this year, it's gotten worse, with the median expense ratio rising by 6 basis points over 1994. All retail categories--from equity to fixed-income funds--show expenses creeping up.  <p> Even the largest funds, which have swelled in assets the most over the past ten years, have not passed on any savings from economies of scale. According to Lipper, the median expense ratio of the nation's ten largest funds is 69 basis points, up from 57 basis points ten years ago.  <p> Fund expenses go to pay lawyers's fees, commissions to transfer agents,  directors' fees, the salaries of telephone representatives, and other costs of running a fund company. But the biggest component of the expense ratio is the fee an advisor gets for managing the fund's securities. The next largest expense is often the12-b1 fee levied by some broker-sold funds to defray marketing costs and to give brokers an annual stipend for looking after a customer's investment. With nearly half of funds launched over the past 18 months carrying 12b-1 distribution charges, the picture isn't likely to improve anytime soon.  <p> Charles Trzcinka, a finance professor at the State University of New York at Buffalo, has studied mutual fund expenses and says fund companies have been able to avoid cutting fees because consumers are confused. "The only other consumer product where this happens is medicine," Trzcinka says. "It's because knowing you have a better mutual fund is about the same as knowing whether you have a good surgeon."  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
