<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Best Small-Cap Value Fund</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Best Small-Cap Value Fund: T. Rowe Price</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Best Small-Cap Value Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover Story  <p> BEST SMALL-CAP VALUE FUND: <a name="FUND:PRSVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. ROWE PRICE SMALL CAP VALUE</b></a> <p>The key to the least-researched market segment? Preston Athey likes his companies very small and not very exciting.  <p> By Andrew Gluck  <p> When Preston Athey began managing the T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value Fund four years ago, it was an average performer with just $45 million in assets. "T. Rowe wasn't earning enough on the fund to pay my salary," Athey says. Small Cap Value now has assets of more than $750 million and is the most efficient of the nation's 342 small-company stock funds: No small-cap fund has been less volatile over the last five years (it's been only two thirds as volatile as the average fund in the sector) and delivered as much return. Small Cap Value has averaged a 15.6 percent gain annually in the period.   <p> Athey buys micro-caps, stocks with a capitalization no larger than $250 million. The fund's median market capitalization is just $116 million--1/38th the size of the companies in the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index. Not only won't Athey buy a company with a market cap of more than $250 million, he won't hold onto a company, even a good company, when its capitalization gets above $500 million.  <p> Academic studies have shown that micro-caps offer the most rewards over long periods, but it's a difficult segment of the market to operate in. The stocks are expensive to trade, because brokers charge fat spreads to make up for the low volume. The small capitalization creates liquidity risks for big investors. And the companies get little or no coverage from Wall Street anlaysts.   <p> So Athey spends a quarter of his time visiting companies--100 in the past year. He limits commissions by being a long-term investor, averaging a 21 percent turnover rate, less than a third the rate of the average stock fund. And he reduces liquidity risk and diversifies investment risk by holding 175 companies. <p> That's a lot of legwork, but Athey has help. A T. Rowe analyst spends 50 percent of his time on the fund and is responsible for 30 stocks in the portfolio. Athey tracks about 45 stocks, and the rest of the portfolio ideas and research are generated by T. Rowe Price's pool of 25 analysts.  <p> This is a completely bottom-up strategy: Judgment rules and quantitative screens don't decide what gets into the portfolio."If you're going to own stocks for a long time, you better know what you own because some stocks deserve to be cheap," says Athey. "Some companies are abysmally managed and some are in dying industries. If you just buy off a computer screen, you'll buy stocks that will be cheap forever."  <p> Athey believes he minimizes risk by buying companies that he is pleased to call boring. "The beauty of my kind of investingis that you don't have to kick these tires that often," he says."I'm not investing in semiconductor companies, and I don't live or die by some analyst changing his earnings. These stocks seldom fall out of bed."  <p> Take the fund's largest holding, <a name="NASD:ELRC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13294"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Electro Rent</b></a>, which leases computers and other electronics to Fortune 500 companies. "How exciting is it to rent personal computers to businesses?" asks Athey. "We're not talking rocket science or digital telephone or the hottest toy for kids. But management makes money, and they buy their stock back and grow the earnings." Athey's Dow Jones News/Retrieval screen says no analysts have issued earnings estimates on Electro Rent and none are listed as following the company. Small Cap Value owns 7.3 percent of the company, and Electro Rent has gained 73 percent in the past year.  <p> Athey often adds a touch of contrarianism to his disciplined value approach. "When the rest of the world hates it, that's when I get interested," he says. Athey's evaluation of <a name="NYSE:TRR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12364"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TRC Companies</b></a> is an example of how he sees stocks. TRC is a tiny ($50 million market capitalization) environmental engineering company that studies air-pollution emissions for utilities and other industries. In 1992, investors were willing to pay 2.7 times more for a dollar of sales at TRC than they were for a dollar of sales of the S&P 400 index of mid-cap stocks, and TRC stock hit an all-time high of $17. It's now trading at about $8, which means the market is paying just 0.6 times as much for a dollar of TRC sales as for a dollar of S&P 400 sales. Earnings at the company have grown for seven consecutive quarters, and two top managers recently purchased about $500,000 of their company's stock. "I've been buying it all year," says Athey. "Nobody cares about it; it's totally out of favor."  <p> Athey joined T. Rowe in 1978 as an analyst and managed small-cap growth funds for pension accounts before taking charge of Small Cap Value. Along the way he became one of those fortunate people who can claim to have bought stock in Warren Buffett--in <a name="NYSE:BRK.A"></a><b>Berkshire Hathaway</b>, that is--as early as 1980. Investing for himself, Athey paid $325 a share for Buffett's company; it now sells for about $29,000. He still follows Buffett's lead where he can, but his own fund is by far the largest regular investment he makes. <p> Small Cap Value was closed to new investors in March 1993 after assets rose to $404 million, and it didn't reopen until last January. It's now at $750 million in assets, and new cash is flowing in so rapidly that Athey has put 5 percent of the fund's assets into Russell 2000 futures, which provides market exposure without costing a lot, and has another 15 percent in cash. "To the extent cash comes in faster than I can prudently put it to work, I am willing to put it into futures and leave it in cash," he says. Based on the fund's history, it's safe to assume that unless market conditions change, the fund is likely to close again to new investors soon.  <p> Athey contends that the bull market is on its last legs, but this is often when small stocks perform best. "If I believe the market will do reasonably well between now and the presidential election," he says, "then I feel very confident that small-capstocks will do even better."  <p>  <p>T. ROWE PRICE SMALL CAP VALUE   <p> Net assets: $643 million <p>Median price-to-earnings ratio: 19.12 <p>Median earnings growth rate: 13.42% <p>Beta: 0.62 <p>Standard deviation: 2.12 <p>Top five holdings: Electro Rent, <a name="NASD:FOTO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14680"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Seattle Filmworks</b></a>, <a name="NASD:GREY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Grey Advertising</b></a>, <a name="NASD:UICI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15009"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Insurance</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CSS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11790"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CSS Industries</b></a> <p>Best year: 1991, up 34.17%  <p>Worst year: 1990, down 11.2% <p>Manager tenure: 4 years <p>Minimum initial investment: $2,500 <p>Load: No load, no 12b-1 fee <p>Phone number: 800-638-5660 <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing<p>

