	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Best Small-Growth Fund</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Best Small-Growth Fund: T. Rowe Price</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Best Small-Growth Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover   <p> BEST SMALL-CAP GROWTH FUND: <a name="FUND:PRNHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRNHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. ROWE PRICE NEW HORIZONS</b></a>  <p>What is this small-company fund doing with so many large companies in its portfolio? Proving Jack LaPorte right, primarily.  <p> By Jonathan Butler  <p> There's a reason this small- cap fund is full of big companies: Jack Laporte bought 'em small, and they just won't stop growing. <p> In other words, things are working according to plan for Laporte and T. Rowe Price New Horizons Fund, the $2.5 billion fund he's managed for eight years. For the year to date through September15, New Horizons was up 45.1 percent, over 14 percentage points better than the Russell 2000 growth index. Over the past five years, he has racked up annualized returns of 24 percent, versus the Russell's 17 percent.  <p> Laporte focuses primarily on earnings, looking for new small companies (defined for his purposes as those with market capitalizations between $50 million and $500 million) that can grow at 30 percent or better over five years or more. He's not obsessive about a company's valuation. "If a company's growing at an above-average rate, unless it's selling at a ludicrous level, we'll want too own it," he says. For example, last March he added to his position in <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b> when it was trading in the high 30s, despite the fact that T. Rowe expected this to represent a forward price-to-earnings ratio of about 60. Laporte believed in America Online's ability to maintain its high growth rates over the long haul. As of September15, the stock was trading at $66.   <p> Laporte's portfolio strategy combines discipline with experimentation. Though New Horizons holds roughly 280 stocks, the three largest holdings--<a name="NASD:PAYX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14388"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Paychex</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12858"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CUC International</b></a>, and <a name="AMEX:VIA"></a><b>Viacom</b>--make up roughly10 percent of the fund. Another 20 or so names take up 1 to 2 percent of the portfolio each. The remaining 70 percent of the fund comprises 250-odd names.  <p> These small positions allow Laporte to learn about the new companies better by giving him the access to managements. And with a personal"multiple six-figure" position in the fund, Laporte has incentive to keep up with all the names.   <p> Despite the large number of stocks, the fund has an annual turnover rate of just 44 percent, less than half that of the average small-company growth fund. This is in part because Laporte doesn't necessarily bail out when a company outgrows the small-cap designation. "I do not automatically sell a stock when its capitalization hits some arbitrary number, like a billion dollars," he says. "That's a real inhibitor of performance." More than 60 companies in the fund now have capitalizations of over $1 billion.  <p> According to T. Rowe Price, the median size of companies held by New Horizons is $350 million, well within the bounds of the typical small-company description. The fund-research company Morningstar, however, asserts that this measure underemphasizes the impact on performance of the top holdings. According to Morningstar,the dollar-weighted median gives a more accurate picture of the size of the median company: $1.16 billion.  <p> Laporte calls himself a bottom-up investor, meaning he picks each stock based on its own story with little regard for economic trends. The one macroeconomic view he does subscribe to is that the small-company universe performs in five- to seven-year cycles. The current cycle, in which small caps have easily outpaced larger stocks, began in October 1990, but Laporte thinks small caps still have a ways to go. What gives him such confidence is the level of New Horizons' relative price-to-earnings ratio. This proprietary indicator, which is computed by dividing the New Horizons p/e ratio by that of the S&P 500 stock index and isused by just about everyone who invests in small stocks, givesa picture of how cheap or expensive small stocks are versus larger stocks. When the ratio gets down to 1, as it did most recently in 1990, small stocks are very cheap and the cycle is likely to turn upward. When the ratio nears 2, it is a sign that small stocks are expensive and are running out of gas.  <p> The relative p/e is rising--it was 1.34 on June 30 and up to1.40 by mid-September. Though Laporte doesn't think it will get as high as 2 this cycle, he is confident that it will get above1.5 before turning. Even if it does turn soon, Laporte's strategy won't change drastically. "I don't think investors own New Horizons to have me be a market timer," he says.  <p> With Laporte's reluctance to invest according to a macroeconomic view, the only real indication of his outlook is his cash position. For the past five years, the fund has held an average of 5 percent cash. This number was at 6 percent at the end of June, at which point Laporte lowered the fund's position in technology 2 percentage points to 21 percent because he thought the sector was looking "a little frothy." With new money pouring in as well, he's up to a relatively cautious 9 percent. There's not much further to go, either: He promises not to exceed 10 percent, even in the worst market environment.  <p> T. ROWE PRICE NEW HORIZONS   <p> Net assets: $2.3 billion <p>Median price-to-earnings ratio: 32.8 <p>Median earnings growth rate: 29.3% <p>Beta: 1.2 <p>Standard deviation: 4.2 <p>Top five holdings: Paychex, CUC Int'l, Viacom Cl B, Maxim Integrated Products, Synopsis <p>Best year: 1980, up 57.56%  <p>Worst year: 1984, down 9.63% <p>Manager tenure: 8 years <p>Minimum initial investment: $2,500 ($1,000 IRA) <p>Load: No front load, no back load, no 12B-1 fee <p>Phone number: 800-638-5660 <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing 
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

