<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Best Large-Cap Value Fund</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Best Large-Cap Value Fund: Mutual Qualified</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Best Large-Cap Value Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover  <p> BEST LARGE-CAP VALUE FUND: <a name="FUND:MQIFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MQIFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MUTUAL QUALIFIED</b></a> <p>Well, if it isn't Michael Price again, this time with a fund that makes the most of bankruptcies and--especially in 1995--mergers  <p> By Manjeet Kripalani  <p> Michael Price smiled all day on August 28, the day <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a> announced its merger with <a name="NASD:CHFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12961"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chemical Bank</b></a>. His big stakes in Chase and Chemical had just become bigger: Profits for shareholders in his Mutual Series Inc. funds were pushed up to a cumulative $400 million.  <p> The strategy, and its success, were vintage Price--put money into stocks in merger or bankruptcy situations, and then wait for them to make you rich. But in this case he was even more involved: He sits on the Chase board of directors.  <p> Price's aggressive approach has taken him to the top of our charts in the large-cap value category for the second straight year--and has earned him some controversy along the way. In 1994 Price's <a name="FUND:BEGRX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BEGRX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mutual Beacon Fund</b></a> was one of our five top picks; this year it's a sister fund, Mutual Qualified, with $2.56 billion in assets.  <p> One of the keys to his approach is consistency. Price, 44, has doggedly adhered to the investing principles of his guru and former partner, the late Max Heine of the firm Herzog, Heine & Geduld. Heine made money from investing in bankruptcies, and so has Price. "Combine 8 percent bankruptcies, 22 percent cash,and 10 percent [merger and acquisition] deals with 60 percentin cheap stocks--that's my calculation," he says. As an added bonus, the fortunes of bankruptcy stocks aren't usually tied to general market conditions, so their presence helps insulate the fund from the market's swings, both down and up.  <p> Insulated? Mutual Qualified has kept up with the rising market,jumping 25 percent through September 15 of this year. "That's atypical," Price says. He attributes the gains to the spurt of merger and spin-off action in 1995. In addition to the Chase-Chemical deal, Price made money on <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a> when it spun off Allstate and also benefited from Seagram when the company purchased MCA. He likes <a name="NYSE:VO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41797"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Seagram</b></a> better now that it owns MCA--"it's more interesting"--and thinks the $36 stock could be worth $50. He also looks for the stock of the combined Chase-Chemical entity to rise further,bringing even more profits from his investments in those banks.(Incidentally, Price acquired his shares in Chemical throught he company's previous merger with Manufacturers Hanover.)  <p> One interesting element in Price's strategy is the high cash allocation. It makes sense when you consider that Mutual Qualified was closed to investors from 1989 to 1994. Since it reopened, $1 million to $3 million has been flowing in daily. Because Price does most of his shopping when the market is down, much of the cash has been piling up during the current rally. But not all of it: "I'm finding things to buy from day to day," Price says."Not a lot, but a few. We're putting the money to work."  <p> Assisting Price in that process is a team of 15 research analysts who crunch numbers and scrutinize companies' accounting. Price describes himself as "very balance-sheet oriented." He believes in conservative accounting, looks for hidden assets and liabilities,and doesn't care about quarterly earnings at all.   <p> Price does care about the quality of a company's management. On any given day, as many as 12 members of the Mutual Series staff are on the road, visiting corporations to find out which are well-run. "Bad management can make you a good buy, because there can be a turn around situation there," Price says.  <p> Price is on the board of several companies, including Chase, causing some to label him an activist investor and raising the specter of conflicting interests. But Price is unrepentant. "With my investing approach, sometimes you help value get realized,"he says. "You suggest to management that they should spin off some operations." He pauses, then adds: "They're always constructive suggestions."  <p> Mutual Qualified isn't limited to bargains in the U.S. The fundholds 12 percent of its assets in foreign stocks, and in February Price will open an office in London. He says the move isn't an attempt to diversify by nation or any other measure; he simply wants to cast his bargain-hunting net wider. "We don't buy industries or countries," he says. "We're company-specific. We look for the same things as with U.S. stocks, but because it's foreign, we'll want it cheaper." For instance, Price bought Dutch confectioner Van Melle at a price-to-earnings ratio of 10 at a time when Hershey was trading at a multiple of 25. (Van Melle produces, among other candies, Mentos mints.) The fund also has positions in such European giants as <a name="NYSE:PHG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41823"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philips</b></a>, Bayer, Nestle, and Ciba Geigy.  <p> Picking stocks to buy isn't that hard, Price says. Knowing when to sell--well, that's another story. "Oh, God," he says, "we make so many mistakes." He laments the number of occasions on which he's sold early, such as last year, when he unloaded his holdings in <a name="NYSE:UAL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11520"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>UAL Corp.</b></a> at around $100 a share. Now the stock trades at $170.  <p> But despite the occasional missed opportunity, Price has plenty to crow about. Mutual Series, which he launched in 1989 after buying out the remainder of his partnership with Max Heine from Heine's estate, now runs five funds. The company manages nearly $13 billion in assets, up from $8 billion last year. And Price--whose largest personal investments are tied up in Mutual Series funds--seems to be enjoying himself to boot. Managing the funds, he says, gives him "the freedom of being creative."   <p> After years of consistent growth, Price knows there's no magic path to profits. Instead, he praises the virtues of simply doing critical investment homework. "I read the paper every day to see what's cheap," he says. He is also reluctant to predict the market's future direction and careful to avoid sounding cocky. A bull market like this one "makes everyone a genius," he says."They make mistakes but don't notice because the market's saving them."  <p>  <p>MUTUAL QUALIFIED  <p> Net assets: $2.6 billion <p>Median price-to-earnings ratio: 16.7 <p>Median earnings growth rate: 3.8% <p>Beta: 0.8 <p>Standard deviation: 2.1 <p>Top five holdings: Chase, US West, Sunbeam-Oster, ITT, Tenet Healthcare <p>Best year: 1983, up 34.5 % <p>Worst year: 1990, down 10.1% <p>Manager tenure: 15 years <p>Minimum initial investment: $1,000 <p>Load: No load, no 12b-1 fee <p>Phone number: 800-553-3014  <p><p>
KEYWORDS:Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:CMB">The Chase Manhattan Corporation</a><br>

