	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Best Large-Cap Growth Fund</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Best Large-Cap Growth Fund: Harbor Capital</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Best Large-Cap Growth Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover  <p> BEST LARGE-CAP GROWTH FUND: HARBOR CAPITAL APPRECIATION
The point, says Spiros Segalas, is not that he buys technology stocks--it's that he picks the right ones for the right reasons <p> By Ken Kurson  <p> Spiros Segalas likes to keep things simple. "I don't believe in derivatives," he says. "I don't believe in hedging. I don't believe in a lot of these esoteric techniques."   <p> He likes to share the credit. "Quite honestly," he says, "I've surrounded myself with some very, very bright people. I may be a better people picker than a stock picker."  <p> And he likes technology. A lot. Through confident, aggressive buying in the tech sector, <a name="FUND:HACAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HACAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Harbor Capital Appreciation</b></a>, which Segalas has managed since 1990, has gained an average of 22.7 percent annually for the past five years, outperforming the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index every year. (For 1995, the fund was up 40 percent through September 15.) Forty-two percent of Harbor Capital Appreciation is invested in technology, and seven of the fund's top ten holdings are tech stocks.  <p> Of course, technology has been this year's go-go sector, and to some investors that suggests it will soon be the worst place to have money. If you own a company for the right reasons, Segalas says, that's the wrong way to think. He believes that many investors miss the crucial distinctions between solid blue chips and high-flying start-ups.  <p> "People are quite concerned about technology companies these days," Segalas says. "But the only rap I see is that they're up a lot. But the earnings are up a lot, too. I look at our holdings, and the price-to-earnings ratios on our estimates look very, very reasonable, even though the stocks have done quite well. Where you're getting a lot of the speculation is in some of the smaller companies that haven't been in business more than a few years. Internet-type companies. In fact, some of those stocks are out of sight, and I'm sure there's going to be a correction there. People say technology,' and they throw everything in there."  <p> A life-long New Yorker, Segalas came upon his love of stocks in an unlikely manner. His father, a Greek immigrant who owned a general contracting business, would often finance his clients' purchases of building materials. The elder Segalas would post a mishmash of stock certificates as collateral, and it fell to Spiros, who was then in high school, to track the daily close of his father's securities.   <p> Joining the family business, however, was another story. "My father was a very bottom-line, hard-nosed guy, and I had no aptitude for that kind of business," Segalas says. "Here I thought I was a hot shot Princeton graduate, naval officer, and he had me sweeping floors and driving lumber to jobs."  <p> Segalas's interest in stocks resurfaced when a gamble with his college graduation money paid off. "RJ Reynolds was coming out with a filtered cigarette--and it's ironic because I've never smoked in my life--so I put the $1,000 in RJR," Segalas says."The stock went way up, and I said, Hey, I kind of like this.'"It was just the first example of a technological breakthrough working for him.  <p> His favorite companies in his favorite sector? "I look at <a name="NYSE:MOT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11023"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Motorola</b></a>,"he says enthusiastically, "and I think this company could show better than 20 percent earnings gain. They're in an explosive part of the marketplace--wireless communication--and the whole world seems to want more of it. It's very reasonably priced. The same thing's true of <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>. My largest holding is <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a>. The stock's up a lot this year. Yet, our estimate puts [HP's price-to-earnings ratio] at something like 14.7 for 1996. Here's a company I think can grow 20 percent, selling at a discount multiple to the market. Can it have a correction? Sure, because it's up a lot this year, but the multiple doesn't disturb me that much."  <p> Harbor Capital Appreciation has more than quadrupled in size in the past 12 months, to $900 million in assets, but Segalas has kept the fund fully invested and says he's had no trouble finding good companies to buy. He is at pains to portray himself as strict bottom-up investor--one who buys a company based on its merits, not any belief about its sector or the broader market. He says the best companies happen to be in technology because it's "the only industry that's a declining-cost industry," a factor that "can only broaden the market for its products."  <p> Because of the fund's 14 percent exposure to foreign stocks and its large technology holdings, Morningstar has flagged Harbor for its volatility, which is about 26 percent greater than that of the S&P 500. That places it just inside the riskiest quartile of large-cap funds. Segalas acknowledges this aspect of his fund but argues that the reasonable valuations of the companies in his portfolio make it well worth the risk. He's certainly putting his money where his mouth is: a sizable piece of his own portfolio, as well as money for his four children and five grandchildren, are in the fund he manages.   <p> Many of Harbor Capital Appreciation's best plays have involved ultramodern companies whose strengths have been revealed through old-fashioned due diligence. Perhaps the best example is a German software company called SAP-Systeme. The company came to Segalas's attention when Harbor's biggest holding, Hewlett-Packard, began using SAP software. "I sat down with SAP and listened to this management, and I said, Wow, I want to own this one,'" Segalas says. "I just thought these guys are so smart and so with it and the market is so large and I think this company could grow 40 percent a year, maybe for some time to come. Now this is a for-real company, a billion dollars in sales. But if I hadn't met that management, I probably would have disregarded it." The stock rose 50 percent in the three months after Segalas bought it in mid-1995.  <p> To be sure, Segalas has endured his share of mistakes. Harbor's exposure to foreign stocks is high for a large-cap growth fund, and the fund took a body blow when Segalas failed to anticipate the devaluation of the Mexican peso last year. Other companies, such as the American carpet marker Shaw Industries, simply proved disappointing, so Segalas sold and moved on, in the way a manager with more than 30 years of experience is able to.  <p> Segalas sees little reason for pessimism over the next several years. "The reason I like the market, the key to it," he says,"is inflation and interest rates. I think we've seen the peak in profit gains. They'll continue to grow, albeit at a somewhat slower rate. So profits are not going to be the catalyst here as they were last year. Last year, the S&P 500 had a better than 23 percent increase in profits. That's slowing down; it has to. The reason I'm comfortable with the environment here is that I see the economy slowing but not heading toward a recession. As a result, we don't have to fight the Federal Reserve, which always causes problems when it's in the mood to tighten."  <p>  <p>HARBOR CAPITAL APPRECIATION  <p> Net assets: $785.2 million <p>Median price-to-earnings ratio: 27.3 <p>Median earnings growth rate: 22.8% <p>Beta: 1.3 <p>Standard deviation: 3.6 <p>Top five holdings: Hewlett-Packard, Intel, Motorola, <a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:LSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13932"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LSI Logic</b></a> <p>Best year: 1991, up 54.8%  <p>Worst year: 1990, down 1.8% <p>Manager tenure: 5 years <p>Minimum initial investment: $2,000 <p>Load: No load, no 12b-1 fee <p>Phone number: 800-422-1050 <p>
KEYWORDS:International Investing, Mutual Funds Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
