	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Best Global Equity Fund: Founders Worldwide</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Best Global Equity Fund: Founders Worldwide</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						In Michael Gerding's line of work, there's no substitute formiles traveled, questions asked, and numbers double-checked <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> This might not match your picture of a top-of-the-world international investor, but Michael Gerding works in Denver, carries his research reports in an Eddie Bauer satchel, and leaves the office whenever he can to go fly-fishing. He's handy with a fishing metaphor ("Not only do you have to be in the right creek," he notes about stock picking, "you have to know where to direct your fly.") and is generally as down-to-earth a guy as ever managed $200 million.  <p> On the other hand, Gerding does grill management at no fewer than 300 companies in at least ten countries every year. At age33 he is in his sixth year as manager of <a name="FUND:FWWGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FWWGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Founders Worldwide Growth Fund</b></a>, which through September 15 turned in a brisk 20 percent total return for 1995--"crushing," as Gerding notes, the benchmark Morgan Stanley Capital International World Index, which stood at 12 percent. Since Gerding took the reins in May of 1990, Founders Worldwide Growth has returned an annual average of 14.6 percent. Investors have rewarded this performance by pouring $100 million into the fund in 1995 alone.  <p> Gerding (who was profiled as an up-and-comer in last month's Worth) has a straightforward investing philosophy: It's the company, not the country, that matters. "A lot of funds are making conscious country bets, and we just don't do that," he says. He looks for companies whose earnings will grow faster than the earnings of other companies worldwide in that industry; faster than other companies within that country; and faster than the company's own price-to-earnings ratio. His particular affection is for "companies that are trying harder to be No. 1, because I want to grab an emerging brand name."   <p> He got one in Polygram, which he first noticed in 1986 while working as an international fund manager at a Dallas bank. The Dutch company (owned at the time by Philips, N.V.) was toiling away in the quiet waters of the music industry as a classical-music label. In late 1990, not long after coming to Founders Worldwide, Gerding put 1 percent of the fund's money into Polygram, which was then trading at around $20. Soon after, the company decided to update its image. It bought out the Motown and Island labels, then signed new artists such as the Cranberries. Today, Polygramis the No. 1 recording label in the world and trades at about $65.  <p> Gerding's international travels occupy up to two and a half months of his year. Wherever he goes, he behaves like a roving proletariat, eating at fast-food outlets, talking to locals, and all the while checking the country's local market for success stories.   <p> He also checks the government's stories, because he rarely trusts official numbers. A recent study by Credit Lyonnais supports him in this: The study found that statistics from foreign governments on their emerging economies are often a farrago of confusion.What's more, most governments don't adhere to a strict schedule of monthly or quarterly publication dates--in fact, they often release data that is a year old.  <p> A couple of classic examples of bad information have come from Mexico recently. In June 1994, the Mexican government claimed to have $17 billion in monetary reserves. By December it turned out the real figure was $6 billion--before the peso was so famously devalued and the economy so famously swooned. In the second quarter of 1995, Mexican officials were estimating gross domestic product would be down 5 percent. But Gerding remained skeptical, so he paid a trip to 30 firms in Mexico. "What the Mexican companies told me didn't jibe with what the government was saying," he says. "For example, we met with a retailer whose sales were down 15 percent from the month before. Those are monumental numbers. "Mexico's second quarter GDP was down 10.5 percent.  <p> When he visits a company, Gerding likes to see evidence that company officials have a lot personally at stake--that they'll feel it financially if the company's stock takes a hit. He expects investors in his fund to hold him to the same standard; half his money is in Worldwide Growth. "If it's good enough for shareholders," he says, "it's good enough for me."  <p> Like most managers, Gerding has had his share of investing nightmares. In 1991, he put about half of a percent of the assets of Worldwide Growth into Pollypeck, a British conglomerate that owned a host of businesses, including Delmonte Fruit. Pollypeck eventually filed for bankruptcy. "The Pollypeck stock just blew up," Gerding remembers with a groan. "As a fund manager, I hated the fact that I missed its problems. I felt I had done everything right and still got nailed big."   <p> Trying to do everything right takes a ton of work. Gerding begins his day at 6:30 in the morning, when he checks up on the world through Bridge Quote System and Bloomberg's news service. He then scours The Financial Times, The Wall Street Journal, and The New York Times, and spends an hour talking on the phone to a cabal of Wall Street brokers and analysts as well as stockpickers at Deutsche bank in Germany and CCF in France and even small local brokers in the countries he visits. He finishes off his day by rifling through as many as 50 research reports and interrogating his two research analysts for ideas.  <p> If investors are uneasy about Worldwide Growth, it's likely to be because of the relatively small number of stocks the fund holds and the relatively small market values of the stocks. Gerding does own some big name brands, including <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota</b></a> and Nestle, but the fund's companies have a median market value of roughly $3 billion--about half the median for other global funds. And it holds just 70 stocks, not many for this field.  <p> So why should investors give him their money? He doesn't answer that challenge with a fishing metaphor. "Because we've proven ourselves," he says firmly. "It's been me, the same guy who's put the numbers on the board for the last five years. And it will be me, hopefully, running the fund for a long damn time." <p>  <p>FOUNDERS WORLDWIDE GROWTH  <p> Net assets: $201 million <p>Median price-to-earnings ratio: 27.6 <p>Median earnings growth rate: 22.9% <p>Beta: 1.0 <p>Standard deviation: 3.4 <p>Top five holdings: <a name="NYSE:NOK.A"></a><b>Nokia</b>, Wolters Kluwer, S.A.P. Preferred, SGS-Thomson,Next PLC <p>Best year: 1991, up 34.79%  <p>Worst year: 1994, down 2.16% <p>Manager tenure: 6 years <p>Minimum initial investment: $1,000 <p>Load: no load, 12b-1 fee of 0.25 percent  <p>Phone number: 80<p>
KEYWORDS:Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
