<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Oddball Funds That Make Sense</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Oddball Funds That Make Sense</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Oddball Funds That Make Sense</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>ODDBALL FUNDS THAT MAKE SENSE<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Oddballs may be socially maladroit and sartorially bizarre, but when it comes to mutual funds, weird can be beautiful.<p>So-called oddball funds, whose performance doesn't correlate with U.S. markets and which fit no established category, can boost portfolio returns and lower risks. Professional portfolio managers recommend that investors diversify with one or two, but few do.<p>"If you lined up a thousand people and measured their portfolios, you would see a concentration in large-company growth funds and in bond funds," says Lynn Hopewell, an investment advisor who manages fund portfolios for individuals with the Monitor Group in Falls Church, Virginia.<p>Mike Kresh, a principal at the Medford, New York, firm Snyder Kresh Financial Services, says the vast majority of people who come into his office for the first time own "well-advertised, mainstream mutual funds that get a lot of attention in the press and are in the public eye." Kresh thinks most people don't take the time, or don't have the skill, to hunt for oddball gems. "Unless you're a fairly sophisticated investor," he says, "you won't look for four-leaf clovers."<p>Mainstream fund categories, of course, are the core of any sensible portfolio (see "A Good Word for the Class System"), and no fund, however singular, can insulate an investor from a severe market downturn. But placing up to 30 percent of a portfolio in three to five oddballs will smooth the road to respectable returns. And a mere 10 percent allocation in one or two such funds will improve the ten-year performance of most portfolios. <p>Oddballs spread risk because they don't closely track the widely watched stock, bond, and foreign market indexes that most funds resemble. "The Holy Grail of portfolio design is to find noncorrelated asset classes," says Hopewell. "If you have a fund that is not correlated with the other funds in a portfolio, it will squeeze the risk out of that portfolio."<p>We asked investment advisors to name their favorite oddballs--funds that over the next five years are likely to lower the risk of an investor's portfolio, add some return, or both. Here are their picks.<p><a name="FUND:GAMNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GAMNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GAM INTERNATIONAL</b></a><p>GAM International is almost certain to add a risk-return pattern unlike any other fund because it bears little resemblance even to other foreign-stock funds. The fund's charter could not be much less restrictive, requiring only that at least 65 percent of fund assets be placed in at least three countries. It must mainly buy foreign equities, but it can also move heavily into investment-grade foreign bonds. In fact, as of March 31, it invested 47 percent of its assets in bonds, 34 percent in cash, just 11 percent in stocks, and the rest in convertibles and other securities.<p>"The manager can go anywhere in the world looking for opportunities, and he has a track record for wandering into the right places," says Jeffrey Mortimer, vice president of the Cambridge, Massachusetts, investment advisory firm Higgins Associates.<p>GAM International manager John R. Horseman's contrarian tilt leads to big bets in unlikely places. He recently landed 31 percent of fund assets in German bonds, his analysis bucking the fears of many that a hike in interest rates would bash deutsche bonds. GAM has been right most of the time over the last decade, providing investors with a 23 percent average annual return over that period.<p>Not bad for a true oddball. Consider the fund's R2, a measure from 1 to 100 of how closely a fund correlates to a particular benchmark index. GAM's five-year average versus the Standard & Poor's 500 is a mere 6. Moreover, GAM International comes no closer than a 46 R2 to any foreign-stock index. The 337 foreign-stock funds tracked by Morningstar average an R2 of 76 against foreign- stock indexes.<p>Jeffrey Mortimer calls this fund an "aggressive oddball" and a "sleeper" because, despite its $286.9 million in assets as of June 30, "no one has ever heard of it." The fund is just right for a growth investor, says Mortimer, adding that its growing asset base and consistent performance ensure it won't remain anonymous much longer. <p>Not all of GAM's big bets have succeeded. After soaring 80 percent in 1993, the fund plunged 10 percent in 1994 before briskly rising 22 percent so far this year.<p><a name="FUND:CSRSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CSRSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>COHEN & STEERS REALTY SHARES </b></a> <p>Among real estate investment managers, the team of Martin Cohen and Robert Steers has a good reputation. But it's not just as a sector play that Cohen &Steers Realty Shares appeals to Eliot Williams of The Williams Investment Counselors, a Windsor, Connecticut, manager of fund portfolios for wealthy investors.<p>"Not only is real estate an independent asset class, but it's been on a downward drift in the last five years and has been reappraised in the marketplace, and it's now more fairly valued than it was ten years ago," says Williams. "So for diversification and return reasons, this fund is attractive for a portfolio." He believes Cohen & Steers would fit well with an income or growth portfolio.<p>The fund started in July 1991, but even with just four full years of performance data, its oddball status is evident. In 1992, it gained 20 percent, more than double the S&P 500, and it gained 18.8 percent in 1993--8.7 percentage points more than the S&P 500. In 1994, when 80 percent of the 4,764 stock and bond funds with track records for the full year lost money, Cohen & Steers gained 8.3 percent.<p>One caveat: Williams says that an investor should take a pass on this fund if more than 70 percent of his or her net worth is tied up in a residence and/or vacation home. These investors already have enough real estate exposure in their portfolios. <p><a name="FUND:VAITX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VAITX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VANGUARD EMERGING MARKETS PORTFOLIO </b></a> <p>Emerging (also known on the Street as submerging) markets climbed 72 percent in 1993, according to Morningstar, but sharply rising interest rates in the U.S. induced investors to bring their money home. Then came the Mexican peso crisis, followed by the Japanese earthquake.<p>As liquidity evaporated, emerging-markets funds went on a year-and-a-half-long nosedive. The second largest fund in this category, the $1.4 billion Fidelity Emerging Markets Fund, plunged 18 percent last year and was down another 13.8 percent at one point earlier this year.<p>Still, Eliot Williams says owning an emerging-markets fund in the coming decade will bring diversification and growth to a portfolio. Investing exclusively in the developed world, Williams says, "is not enough."<p>"We will see above-average growth in emerging markets," predicts Williams, "and more and more institutional investors will be heading into these markets and recognizing their legitimacy over the next ten years."<p>Through the rest of the decade, less developed countries are expected to grow at twice the rate of developed countries, according to Vanguard International Equity Index Fund sales literature. This index fund buys a total of 300 stocks in 12 different LDCs, including Turkey, Mexico, Thailand, and Indonesia.<p>LDC economies are in different stages of development and are growing at different rates. So their stock markets don't move in sync with equity markets in developed countries or with one another.<p>"The stock markets of these countries over any short period of time are most influenced by flows of funds primarily from outsiders," Williams says. "Over the longer period, the fundamentals will win out, and the investment community will increasingly allocate modest amounts to these markets and lift their prices. For those who can tolerate some risk, it's attractive."<p>The Vanguard fund was basically flat for the 12 months ended May 31. But the fund only started up in May 1994, so its track record does not mean much. The 60 basis point expense ratio (a fee for management and operating costs) is less than a third of the average of its peer group, making it the cheapest way to play the emerging markets.<p><a name="FUND:MERFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MERFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MERGER FUND</b></a><p>The only mutual fund investing exclusively in deal stocks--corporate mergers, takeovers, and capital restructurings--Merger Fund would provide a good fit with an income-oriented or growth-stock portfolio.<p>After the terms of a takeover are announced, the share price of a takeover target often rises, but it usually trades below the price an acquirer proposes to pay, because of the chance the deal will fail. Merger Fund buys the target company before the deal is done. The strategy, known as risk arbitrage, exploits the difference between the deal price and the pre-takeover stock price.<p>The fund is a true oddball, with virtually no correlation with any of the 13 stock indexes against which Morningstar matches stock funds. Merger Fund has an R2 of 1 in relation to the S&P 500, one of the lowest of any of the 1,400 stock funds tracked by Morningstar.<p>As a result, Merger Fund has been only about half as volatile as the S&P 500 stock index over the last five years, according to data from Morningstar, but it has delivered 81 percent of the S&P's returns--an average of 9.8 percent annually. "It is extremely efficient," says Mortimer.<p><a name="FUND:FCVSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FCVSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FIDELITY CONVERTIBLE SECURITIES FUND</b></a><p>Convertibles are a hybrid of stocks and bonds (see "Convertibles from the Top Down"). While their prices don't run in the opposite direction of stocks and bonds, they do behave differently and can smooth out a fund portfolio's returns.<p>Convertible securities return a higher dividend yield than growth stocks. According to Andre Ratkai, a chartered financial analyst in Denver managing about $20 million in fund portfolios, the dividends cushion a portfolio when the stock market drifts downward. "The fat dividend tends to limit downside risk," he says.<p>Convertibles are generally issued by small- and medium-sized growth companies. Firms of this size favor convertibles--securities that pay regular interest, like bonds--because they offer investors slightly lower interest rates, in return for which the convertibles can be converted into stock. This metamorphosis is triggered by a rising stock price. <p>Also, convertibles are unsecured debts--so they don't have to be paid back if the company happens to go belly-up, nor do they encumber a balance sheet. Investors are usually willing to pay for convertibility because it allows them to profit from a stock run-up, which is not a possibility with straight bonds.<p>The securities are usually most attractive when medium-sized and small companies are posting the largest share gains on the stock market. And that's where we've been most of the year.<p>Ratkai expects small-cap companies to outperform blue chips over the next five years because they remain cheap by historical standards. Since 1961, whenever the price-to-earnings ratio on the <a name="FUND:PRSVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price New Horizons Fund</b></a>, a small-cap stock fund, has grown to double the price-to-earnings ratio of the S&P 500 index of blue chips, large companies have begun to outperform small ones. Right now, Ratkai says, the price-to-earnings level on the New Horizons fund versus the S&P 500 is about 1.3 to 1--up from a low of about 1 to 1 in 1990. So the small caps still have a long way to go in their cycle versus the large caps.<p>A portfolio holding equal investments in the Vanguard Index 500 (which mimics the S&P 500), the Vanguard Index Small Capitalization Stock Fund, and the Vanguard International Equity Fund for the last five years has a five-year standard deviation (a measure of a fund's volatility) of 12.1 and a 10.4 percent average annual return. Add the Fidelity Convertible Securities Fund to the portfolio and put 25 percent of the assets in the four funds, and the portfolio's standard deviation falls to 11.2 percent and its annual average returns rise to 11 percent.<p>
A GOOD WORD FOR THE CLASS SYSTEM STYLE
Oddball funds should supplement, but not replace, the portfolio diversity gained by dividing fund holdings among six basic asset classes<p>Studies have repeatedly demonstrated that portfolio diversification--spreading bets across a broad spectrum of stock and bond mutual funds--is the most prudent and efficient investment strategy.<p>Stock funds fall into five categories: large-growth companies, small-growth companies, large undervalued companies, small undervalued companies, and foreign stocks. The sixth class of assets is bond funds. Most advisors recommend short-term bond funds because short-term bonds usually hold up well during downturns in the stock market, buffering the volatility of the stock funds.<p>"Once you get these different asset classes in your portfolio, you get some real diversification," says Lynn Hopewell. Going beyond the basics and adding oddball funds is likely to cut risk and boost long-term returns still more.<p>While portfolio diversification means giving up on trying to handicap which market will go up or down the most in any given time span, it lowers the chances of a loss and smooths out overall returns.   --A.G.<p>
ODDBALL DEMO<p>Jeffrey Mortimer, vice president of Higgins Associates, constructed a $100,000 portfolio using GAM International to illustrate how oddballs can help a fund investor. A growth investor who five years ago invested 50 percent of his money in T. Rowe Price Equity-Income Fund, 25 percent in <a name="FUND:BRWIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BRWIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Brandywine Fund</b></a>, and 25 percent in <a name="FUND:MUTHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MUTHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mutual Shares Fund</b></a> would have had an average annual return of 13.6 percent and a standard deviation of 10.48 (standard deviation measures a fund's volatility based on its historical returns).<p>However, if that investor took $25,000 from the low-risk T. Rowe Price Equity-Income Fund and invested it in the more volatile GAM International, the portfolio's standard deviation drops to 10.43 and the average annual return rises more than a percentage point, to 14.8 percent. Interestingly, GAM International's standard deviation is higher than any of the other three funds in the portfolio, but adding it lowers the portfolio's overall standard deviation.<p>The fund carries a fairly steep 5 percent load, but it may be available as a no-load through institutions that make investments of $500,000 or more. Mortimer suggests looking into placing it in a tax-deferred retirement account because of its history of generating large capital gains. The fund gets a five-star rating from Morningstar.   --A.G.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

