	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Birth of a Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Birth of a Fund</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> BIRTH OF A FUND <p>John Wakeman was sharp enough, at age 31, to be given control of  
a risky new fund. and he's realistic enough, at age 32, to know he can't relax for a minute.   <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald   <p> "I come to work scared every day," says John Wakeman, a man with 26 million reasons to feel exactly that way.  <p> Twenty-six million and counting. Obsessively. A year ago Wakeman was an equity analyst at the Baltimore-based mutual fund company T. Rowe Price. Now, at 32, he's the manager of Price's seven-month-old <a name="FUND:PRCOX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRCOX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Capital Opportunity Fund</b></a>. Last November he took control of $2 million in Price seed money. As of late April, he had attracted and earned another $24 million. The net asset value, or price per share, of his fund had risen 19 percent. He's hot. So of course he's scared.  <p> T. Rowe Price Capital Opportunity is one of 1,844 mutual funds born last year, and history confirms the suspicion that not all of them can make it. Wakeman knows that his fast start is no kind of guarantee. His bosses know it, too. And, though they might prefer not to believe it, so do his investors. Here's the story of how one young manager got his fund started which is very much the story of how he intends to keep it going.  <p> John Wakeman was on the right bus at the right time. It was October 1993, and the bus was headed toward a gaming conference in Las Vegas. Wakeman's seat mate was Jack Laporte, president of T. Rowe Price's equity division and manager of its <a name="FUND:PRNHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRNHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New Horizons Fund</b></a>. At the time, Wakeman, a frenetic, obsessive worker with a face and voice like a young Andy Rooney, was primarily an analyst specializing in the leisure industry. But he was also managing a $5 million private account for T. Rowe Price, and making a bit of a reputation doing it.  <p> Wakeman realized it wasn't every day a lowly analyst has a senior company official, one who can sanction new fund ideas, trapped on a bus. He quickly made his pitch. "I said to Jack, A concentrated stock-picking fund seems like a good idea,' " Wakeman says. "I've been managing one like it for over a year now. We've always talked about an aggressive-growth fund that would leverage all of our research capabilities. What do you think of a mutual fund that would capture the best ideas of all of our funds?' "  <p> Laporte said simply, "Let's do it."  <p> That didn't exactly mean "Let's do it," but it did mean Wakeman and his idea would be taken seriously. T. Rowe Price is the fifth largest no-load fund company and the 14th largest fund company overall, with about 1.5 million shareholders and $57.8 billion under management in 71 funds. Its retirement-plan clientele prefers no-load funds, and management values above all the company's reputation for a cautious, no-baloney approach to investing. "We don't want fad funds," growls George Collins, T. Rowe Price's chief executive officer.  <p> But T. Rowe Price is also a company in which a young man with a good track record and a strong idea can get a hearing. Since Collins, a former air-force commander and semi-pro baseball catcher, took over the company in 1984, he has been at pains to ensure that. "We don't have a single strategist or investment guru who sets the pace for management of the funds," Collins says. "We don't want a lot of sameness thinking."  <p> Fund ideas float up from all quarters of the company. One of Collins's early moves was to dump the formal committee that approved new funds. Back then, the company may have gotten one idea out in five years. Collins put into place an informal but powerful executive committee comprising four like-minded people. They met, and still meet, twice a week to talk about new fund ideas."We don't use macroeconomic, scientific analysis," says Collins. "Today, the approval process for new funds has a much shorter turnaround time." Since Collins took over, T. Rowe Price has introduced 60 new funds.  <p>  <p>Six months after his bus ride with Jack Laporte, Wakeman received approval to write a formal proposal for the fund. How did the company conclude that its young analyst, who joined the company straight out of the University of Wisconsin business school and had never even seen a bear market, was qualified to become a manager? "Wakeman won it because he proved to us he could pick stocks as a research analyst," says James Kennedy, T. Rowe Price's chief equity research director.  <p> Company records show that from mid-1990 to mid-1993, Wakeman's buy and sell recommendations outperformed the indexes for the industry groups he researched by an average of 7 percentage points. Over that three-year period, Wakeman earned well over $100 million for the T. Rowe Price mutual fund shareholders. He was also 
the No. 1 research analyst three years straight for an in-house mock equity fund. Finally, Wakeman had served on the advisory committee of three very successful equity funds.  <p> Wakeman's first act as manager-designee was to write a memo to Ken Rutherford, assistant director of investment services, proposing a fund that would take large, aggressive positions in stocks. He wanted to invest in just 30 to 50 stocks quite a bit fewer than most equity-fund managers carry. "Warren Buffet towns just nine stocks," Wakeman says. "I really want to dig into ideas, get my hands around them, and own them big. I can't dig into and know 100 stocks."  <p> T. Rowe Price policy dictates that every proposed new fund meet three criteria: It must have investment merit; the company must have the expertise to manage it; and it must benefit both shareholders and the company. In early September, the management committee concluded that the fund described in Wakeman's memo met these standards. The proposal was approved.  <p> In mid-September, Rutherford, along with company lawyers, members of the marketing department, and a team of copywriters, quizzed Wakeman on his vision of the fund what its holdings would be, how aggressive it would be. Then Rutherford and Wakeman huddled with communications director Jane White to write the prospectus, the document that contains federally required disclosure information about the fund.   <p> The prospectus, filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission at the end of September, said the Capital Opportunity Fund would require the standard T. Rowe minimum $2,500 initial investment and carry no load. It could invest up to 10 percent of its assets in derivatives and up to 20 percent in foreign securities. Most of the rest would go toward domestic growth and value stocks. Investors would read on nearly every page that the fund was highly risky.  <p> Meanwhile, Rutherford and Ronae Brock, the company's marketing manager for equity funds, roughed out a marketing plan, deciding the key selling point would be flexibility, "that [the fund] can invest in any industry, any size company, foreign or domestic, "says Rutherford. The SEC gave its approval in mid-November, and the fund was launched on November 30, with T. Rowe Price's standard $2 million in seed money from company coffers.   <p> T. Rowe Price began stuffing advertising supplements touting the new offering into shareholder statement mailings. The company then placed advertisements in niche magazines such as Better Investing and Personal Investing News, as well as mainstream financial magazines and newspapers. Brock hired a direct-mail broker in Atlanta to send the offering to the 170,000 readers of the magazine Individual Investor and the 16,000 readers of Today's Investor. The cost for the entire launch came to roughly$150,000 to $200,000, low by industry standards but about average for T. Rowe Price.  <p> Then they waited. Was anybody out there?  <p>  <p>At first it was hard to tell. By the end of 1994, just 50 investors had plunked down a total of $400,000 into the fund. Then there turn began to raise the fund's profile, and Capital Opportunity took off. By March 17, Wakeman's fund had $20 million in assets and 2,233 investors with more than half of the fund's assets coming from other T. Rowe Price funds. The average account size was $9,000. Clearly, investors were chasing after the fund's early return. The return is chasing John Wakeman.  <p> On a typical day, Wakeman arrives at his office at 6:30 a.m. to scour five newspapers. He then skims the Dow Jones and Bloomberg databases on his computer, plus between 25 and 50 research reports on the company's electronic "bluesheet," a Lotus program that carries in-house and Wall Street research reports. "I also get calls from <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> and Goldman Sachs analysts who are touting a certain stock," he says. Wakeman spends seven to ten days each month visiting companies and attending conferences or trade shows. Executives from five to ten companies a day visit T. Rowe Price headquarters to tout their firms' virtues.  <p> Wakeman is emphatic about what moves him as an investor. He is biased, he says, "toward a management team that has experience and a track record, which I find out about from the company's proxy statements, 10k's, and annual reports. I want to know everything about their ownership. And I definitely want their incentive and compensation structures, which includes options, stock ownership, salary, and bonuses, tied to the company's cash flow and earnings. If they screw it up, I want to know, do they get hurt, too?" <p> The final weapon at his disposal is his colleagues. Wakeman spends three to four hours a day talking to other fund managers. He regularly badgers Price's 26 research analysts for ideas. His old department, he says, is nothing less than a "gold mine." <p> Gold mines do have their risks. The department recently directed him toward, and then steered him away from, a catastrophic stock pick: <a name="NYSE:EX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16278"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Exide Corp.</b></a>, a Michigan company founded by Thomas Edison that makes and sells batteries for cars and boats worldwide. The stock had been a Wall Street favorite since going public in late 1993, and it shot from $20 per share to $56 by year-end1994. Near the end of January 1995, when the stock dipped to $48, an analyst brought the stock to Wakeman's attention and suggested he take a look. Wakeman started researching it. But another analyst, William Stromberg, talked Wakeman out of the stock in early March. Stromberg warned that the company could have earnings problems because of the warm weather being experienced throughout the Northeast.  <p> Stromberg was right: North America had the second warmest winter on record, and Europe experienced its warmest winter in 400 years. Batteries weren't dying, customers weren't buying, and Exide's earnings fell below expectations. "Now it could lose a lot of money, and I may buy it when it settles in the $30 range," Wakeman says.  <p> Wakeman's best pick so far has been <a name="NASD:ADBE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12518"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Adobe Systems</b></a>, a Silicon Valley graphics software company that he bought at $30 in December. "The stock looked cheap to us," Wakeman says. "At that time, it was selling at 17 times earnings, which is not expensive for technology stocks, which usually sell at 20 times earnings."By late April the stock was trading at $50.  <p> Wakeman has needed the success with Adobe to balance his worst pick: retailer <a name="NYSE:DH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10440"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dayton Hudson</b></a>. In early January, Wakeman invested $850,000 in the company. "But Christmas was bad," he says, shaking his head. "And the first quarter went soft again because consumer spending was down." By mid-March, Dayton Hudson had fallen off its perch in the low 80s to settle in the high 60s.  <p> It was a crucible for Wakeman; he literally wrings his hands as he describes it. "I thought at first, managing a fund is going to be great when it's working well," he says. "But when the big stocks blow up, how will I deal with it? Managing a new fund sounds really neat on paper, but once I get in the real world, how am I going to do?"  <p> He won't, he hopes, give in to what he knows is his biggest flaw as an investor. "I tend to overanalyze," he says. "Fund managers, like everyone else, now face information overload, and analysis can lead to paralysis. Sometimes I sit here and look at information about a stock and don't move on it." Last December, for example, Wakeman missed out on the <a name="NASD:APOL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apollo Group</b></a>, an online education and testing service that was trading at $12. Since he wanted more information on it, he never got around to buying it. "It went to $25 in my face within three months," he recalls with a grimace. "Good move, John."   <p>  <p>Wakeman routinely returns home around 8 p.m. after a last round of debates with his fellow fund managers. Then he works a couple hours more. "We're not well diversified in our personal life," he says with a smile.  <p> To wind down, Wakeman listens to the BBC and Radio Free Europe on one of his four shortwave radios. He also keeps a police scanner in his office so he can listen to the police and fire frequencies. "He's naturally curious," says his wife, Barbara, who's 28 and works in T. Rowe Price's institutional client-services division. "He's an information junkie." "Obviously it's one of those quality versus quantity issues," he says. "But she's used to it, she puts up with it."  <p> "I understand it," says Barbara. "Since I'm involved in the industry, and I don't expect him at home more often."  <p> It's an odd life John Wakeman has earned for himself. Ethical issues are never far from his mind. "In this business ethics slide by," he says. "That frustrates me, because I have pretty high morals." But ultimately, he's a fund manager, he'll consider himself a success in life if he makes a ton of money. T. Rowe Price doesn't have superstar managers, and there's probably no place for one in the corporate culture but what would George Collins want John Wakeman to strive for other than to get rich?" I want to have a billion-dollar fund," Wakeman says. "There are very few managers that manage billion-dollar products. If I build a big fund, it would be a win-win for everybody, both T. Rowe Price and the shareholder."  <p> He knows he'll have to get tougher. New funds at T. Rowe Price don't get prefer ential allocations of rising stocks and hot new issues, but Wakeman says he knows he's competing against funds that do. One small-cap fund manager told Wakeman at an institutional conference in 1990 that he was up 180 percent, "which was four times what any other fund was doing, because he packed his fund with every IPO the company got a hold of in a three-year period." <p> "A lot of these fund managers are athletes," Wakeman says. "Now that they're too old and out of shape, they're taking that aggression and they're trying to beat each other picking stocks. Instead of looking up box scores, they'll pull up each other's net asset values every night in the paper."  <p> Wakeman is still getting used to his higher profile. And to the amount of money his own and especially other people's he has put on the line. "When my fund's NAV started showing up in The Wall Street Journal's mutual fund tables in March, that's when it hit me," he says, his voice nervously breaking. "I said to myself, There it is, John, this is the real world.' Everyday I can only think of this page. I tell everyone, if you don't love the intensity and competition, get out, because it will bury you."   <p>  <p>Once a fund is started at T. Rowe Price, company chieftains leave portfolio managers alone. "Each manager is an entrepreneur, and we expect them to perform," says James Kennedy. "Wakeman's the guy who's running it daily. I'm not going to tell him he can or can't do a certain trade." However, each and every trade is broadcast daily on the T. Rowe Price computer network, so the four-person executive committee can watch Wakeman's trades closely. If they don't like his picks, the committee "plays devil's advocate with him," says Kennedy, a committee member. "We'll go in and debate his ideas."  <p> Collins and the management committee will exert more control on a fund, or even yank the fund manager, for any one of three key reasons: if a fund's performance starts to slip, if the investing patterns go haywire, or if the manager strays too far from the fund's charter. "We are religious about staying with the charter of our funds," says Kennedy.   <p> At their annual evaluation, fund managers must answer three questions. First, how did they help clients make money? Second, how did they help the company make money? And third, because the company strongly values collegiality, which other funds did they help? "If I see one idea goes into one fund but didn't go into more portfolios, I'll bring it up in their evaluations," says Kennedy. If the fund managers have slipped in any of these three key areas, their bonuses will be docked by up to 30 percent. <p> So far, Collins and other Price executives have kept mum about Wakeman's performance, but he knows he's being watched. "I think they're happy it's off to a good start, but they realize it's an aggressive product," he says. "There's not a lot of fanfare. I would expect to hear nothing from them, because they told me what to do and I'm going to do it. We're not out there high-fiving each other."  <p> The job is changing too much for that. Wakeman is now learning how to invest a lot of money a different job from investing relatively little. "When small funds start, you tend to put your best ideas in there first because you want it to work well," Wakeman says."As the fund gets larger, it's not as mobile and flexible. Now I may only need to buy 1,000 shares. As the fund gets larger, I'll need to buy 30,000, which is hard to find from any company." <p> It used to be a custom at T. Rowe Price to break out a cake whenever a fund passed $100 million in asset size. So far, 40 funds have surpassed that mark, but lately the cake knife has been stashed management now waits for their funds to hit $150 million. Wakeman can't wait to eat his slice. "I'm always nervous," he says. "How can I not be? My wife says I should celebrate everyday I have a good day. But it's so hard to enjoy the highs because the lows are very, very low. I worry for the investors. Hopefully, in a couple years, I'll really take care of them."   <p> - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -- - - - - - - - -   <p> they grow up fast <p>The ten fastest-starting mutual funds of the 1990s  <p> Fund   Date of  Assets after  Current Description <p>   launch first year  assets*  <p>   <p> <a name="FUND:FDEGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FDEGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity</b></a>  12/28/90 $724.3 $700.7 Large- & small-Emerging Growth     cap U.S.growth         companies    <p><a name="FUND:PRARX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRARX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price</b></a> 09/30/91 720.4 112.3 Mortgage-backed  <p>Sht. Term US Govt      securities  <p> <a name="FUND:SPHIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SPHIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Spartan</b></a> 12/27/90 702.4 359.1 Ginnie Maes <p>Ginnie Mae  <p> <a name="FUND:SGENX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SGENX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sogen Overseas</b></a> 08/31/93 326.7 440.5 Small- &           medium-cap       international equities   <p> <a name="FUND:PHNAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PHNAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PIMCo</b></a> Mgd.  12/30/91 293.6  397.0 Corporate debt, Bond & Income      mortgage-backed          securites  <p> <a name="FUND:BESCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BESCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Berger</b></a> Small 12/30/93 291.2 362.9 Small- and  Company Growth      midcap U.S.        & int'l equities of        emerging industries  <p> <a name="FUND:ACEHX"></a><a href="ht