		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-New Fund Mania!</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>New Fund Mania!</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-New Fund Mania!</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Cover  <p> NEW FUND MANIA! <p>Investors now have more than 7,500 mutual funds to choose from. Every day, several new ones are created. Is the fund industry picking up speed or running off the rails?   <p> By Manjeet Kripalani  <p> Financial maternity wards are full up these days. In the last 12 months, they've been delivering new mutual funds at the rate of three and a half a day. There were 1,844 newborns last year, up from 1,405 in 1993.  <p> Nearly one in three American investors now owns at least one mutual fund, creating an enormous and still-growing pot of gold, one worth $2.3 trillion based on the assets currently under management. The start-ups, of course, need capture only a tiny share of this pot to succeed.  <p> The new offerings aren't coming just from Fidelity, Vanguard, and the other industry powerhouses. Regulatory changes and the advent of discount brokerages in the mold of <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab & Co.</b></a> have simplified the registration, approval, and marketing process, making it easier for everyone, banks, insurance companies,financial advisors, exportfolio managers to invent their own funds. There are now more than 550 companies in the business. <p> Among the big fund families, determined both to maintain dominance by increasing their assets and to retain existing clients, new funds often represent attempts to create an exclusive investment niche or to ensure that the competition doesn't have one. A 1994 Goldman, Sachs study on the mutual fund industry reports that the number of fund categories had increased 50 percent in the prior eight years. This has only encouraged the creation of new funds, as a single successful idea is likely to trigger a flood of copycats. More than 120 new asset-allocation funds, for instance, followed Fidelity's launch of the first such fund in 1988.  <p> As of the end of March, the number of U.S. funds stood at 7,631, of which 4,783 were started in the first half of the 1990s, according to Lipper Analytical Services. The market is crowded and competitive, yet there appears to be no end in sight.  <p> These days, says Jeffrey Nachman, a vice president at  Dreyfus, a fund family has no choice other than to be a "financial supermarket" to satisfy the customer.  <p> When it comes to marketing and promoting new funds, deep-pocketed outfits like Fidelity, Dreyfus, and Vanguard enjoy a huge advantage over their smaller rivals. They have higher name recognition, more credibility, and clout with brokers, who earn commissions from selling big funds' products. And they spare no expense. <p> According to Lou Harvey of Dalbar, Inc., a Boston-based research firm specializing in financial services, to create the legal entity, including federal and state registration and legal fees, it costs a relatively modest $250,000. The big money is spent over months or several years on phone banks, direct mail, online notices, newspaper advertisements, and marketing to brokerages. These costs, says Harvey, can run anywhere from $2 million to $5 million per launch, sometimes more for industry leaders. <p> Smaller companies and stand-alone funds may spend as little as $150,000 to create a fund, with perhaps another $100,000 to set up the basic infrastructure for operating it, says Arthur Don, an attorney at the Chicago firm of D'Ancona & Pflaum, which advises new funds. Small operations also try to carve out clearly defined niches, especially ones the big fund families might ignore. The <a name="FUND:PARNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PARNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Parnassus Fund</b></a>, founded by Jerome Dodson in 1985 to invest in socially responsible companies, such as <a name="NYSE:CUM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10423"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cummins Engine</b></a>, <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:IAD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10786"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Inland Steel</b></a>, is one notable example.  <p> Rather than advertise in pricey national financial publications, Dodson says, he invested $6,000 in a page in an environmental magazine. As of March 31, his fund had average annual returns of 18.5 percent for the past five years, compared with 11.4 percent for the S&P and 11.0 for the average growth fund. It has $208 million under management.  <p> Another case in point: Donald Yacktman, formerly manager of Kemper Securities' <a name="FUND:SLASX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SLASX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Selected American Shares</b></a> fund, started the no-load equity growth <a name="FUND:YACKX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/YACKX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Yacktman Fund</b></a> in 1992 with $150,000. Today it has about $550 million under management.  <p> "We spent peanuts," Yacktman says. "A few thousand for access to a public relations wire service, $10,000 on printing prospectuses, $30,000 on lawyers' fees."   <p> Yacktman succeeded where many have failed because, he believes, the manager sells the fund. "It's the person at the throttle," he says. Yacktman, named 1991 Portfolio Manager of the Year by Morningstar, Inc., also received good notices in the financial press. That prominence helped pull in $29 million in the first two months.   <p> To survive in this game, small operations like Yacktman's need $30 million to $40 million in the first year to be viable. According to last year's Goldman Sachs report, a new fund from a large family must hold assets of $75 million to $125 million on an ongoing basis to break even. Typically, if it doesn't reach that level in three to five years, it will be merged into an established fund.   <p> One reason start-up costs vary wildly is that every fund family goes about it in a different way. Some firms incubate funds, pilot-testing their ideas for six months to two years before their debut. Incubation, done only with equity funds, is intended to minimize failures and create a track record, making the fund easier to sell.  <p> Incubating funds invest only between $100,000 and $1 million, but they are the genuine article, registered with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Those that do well are brought into the world; those that don't, never see the light of day.  <p> Putnam and Fidelity incubate their funds, and the practice has worked well for them, but only a big firm can afford to do it. Incubation has helped popularize a form of computer modeling called back-testing.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
