	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Running the Rights Fund Risks</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Running the Rights Fund Risks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>RUNNING THE RIGHTS FUND RISKS<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Even if you invest in good mutual funds, you don't necessarily have a good mutual fund portfolio. Consider two investors. One made equal investments in <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Magellan</b></a>, <a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a>, <a name="FUND:PVOYX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PVOYX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Putnam Voyager</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:TEMWX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TEMWX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Templeton World</b></a>--well-known funds rated between three and five stars by Morningstar Mutual Funds and three and five $'s by Worth. The portfolio gained an average of 8.24 percent annually over the five-year period ended December 31, 1994, while taking slightly more risk than the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index, which rose an annual average 8.69 percent over the same period. <p>Our other investor bought equal amounts in several smaller funds: American Capital Emerging Growth, <a name="FUND:MERFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MERFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merger Fund</b></a>, <a name="FUND:PEQUX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PEQUX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Putnam Global Growth</b></a>, and <a name="FUND:FDESX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FDESX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Destiny I</b></a>. This portfolio took less risk than the S&P 500 but gained an average 8.74 percent annually over the same period.<p>How could one portfolio take less risk than another yet produce a higher return? The answer: Diversification. If some funds zig when the others zag, the whole portfolio can be less risky than any of the parts.<p>That's the central idea behind Modern Portfolio Theory, regarded as among 20th-century finance's most important analytical tools. While MPT relies on mathematical formulas, you don't need to know calculus to understand and apply its basic concepts. MPT statistics on 1,300 funds are listed in Morningstar's reports, which can be found in most libraries.<p>MPT grew out of a notion put forward in a 1952 doctoral dissertation by Harry M. Markowitz, a 25-year-old graduate student at the University of Chicago. Markowitz, who won the Nobel Prize in economics in 1990 with William F. Sharpe and Merton H. Miller, showed that you could quantify risk as an element in returns and that diversifying lowers risk.<p>Risk can be measured in any number of ways. One of them is called beta (one measure used to assess the relative risks of the two portfolios above). It shows a security's volatility relative to the market. Historically, a fund with a beta of 1 goes up and down in concert with the Standard & Poor's 500. A fund that has a beta of 0.5 can be expected to go up or down, in percentage terms, half as much as the S&P 500. In our opening example, the fund portfolio that gained 8.24 percent a year had a beta of 1.08, while the more diverse portfolio that gained 8.74 percent had a beta of 0.89.<p>The four funds in the higher-risk portfolio are too much like the S&P 500, which means a lack of diversity. One clue to this was that the betas of the funds--ranging from 0.94 to 1.31, three of them within 10 percent of the S&P beta of 1--are too close to the index. The betas on the lower-risk portfolio range from 0.21 to 1.36, and none are within 10 percent of the S&P 500 beta. But beta spreads, while useful for assessing a portfolio, aren't reasonable measures of diversity. <p>"The only way you get diversification is by buying classes of assets that have good performance and bad performance at similar times," says Edwin Elton of New York University's Stern School of Business and the co-author of Modern Portfolio Theory and Investment Analysis. Elton says a diversified fund portfolio can be created by investing in each of six basic asset classes. Stock funds fall into five classes: growth, value, large capitalization, small capitalization, and international. All bond funds, excluding those investing in high-yield, or junk, issues produce the same diversification in a portfolio, so Elton considers them a single asset class.<p>How much an investor allocates to each asset class depends a lot on age and risk tolerance, Elton says. Investors in their early 20s should overweight toward more volatile growth-stock funds. Someone 10 years from retirement should start shifting an additional 10 percent or 20 percent of fund assets into less volatile, income-producing bond funds. "Fine-tuning diversification isn't nearly as important as having diversification," says Elton.<p>So how does the average investor know which funds belong to what asset class? To create the low-risk portfolio that gained 8.74 percent annually versus the 8.69 percent on the S&P 500, money manager Jeffrey Mortimer of Higgins Associates in Cambridge, Massachusetts, began by scouring Morningstar data for an MPT statistic known as R2. "R2 is a good tool for making sure you have investments in different asset classes," he says.<p>R2 shows what percentage of a fund's return is explained by movements in a market index. For instance, Fidelity Magellan has a 90.61 R2 in relation to the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index, according to Morningstar data. That means the index explains 90 percent of Magellan's returns. <p>Magellan, Voyager, Janus, and Templeton World all have high R2 versus the S&P 500, compared with other funds in their asset clases, and that was this portfolio's shortcoming. It had too many eggs in one basket. So Mortimer, whose firm manages $150 million in mutual fund portfolios, found funds with the highest R2 against indexes other than the S&P 500.<p>Morningstar now compares every stock fund it rates with 13 different market indexes--plus the S&P 500. The index against which a fund has the highest R2 is the "best fit" index. For instance, Putnam Global Growth has just a 33 R2 versus the S&P 500, but its R2 is 85 versus the <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a> Europe Australia Southeast Asia index.<p>Investing in funds with the highest R2 to different indexes gives an investor purer plays on different asset classes, which makes the portfolio more efficient from a risk-reward standpoint. Morningstar's best-fit indexes unfortunately don't offer direct proxies for two of Elton's classes--value and growth equity funds. To find a reliable substitute for value, Mortimer's firm searches for equity income funds whose investing style is highlighted in the "value" section of Morningstar's "style box." Similarly, he looks for funds with an aggressive-growth or growth objective and then refers to the style box to make sure the growth section is highlighted.<p>To pick the best fund in each asset class, you still must analyze consistency of return, investing style, expenses, turnover, and all the other factors underlying a fund's performance. But you can make decisions easier by using the simple technique explained in "Plotting Out Your Risks and Rewards." It gives a good indication of how efficient a fund is at balancing risk and reward. <p>As a proxy for risk, use your fund's standard deviation, a measure of risk that can be used with any kind of fund, from equity to fixed income. That's because unlike beta, it measures fund volatility not against a market index, but against the fund's own performance history. <p>Standard deviation shows how much a fund's returns vary from its average return; a high standard deviation equals high volatility. The riskier of our two model portfolios had the much higher standard deviation. <p>Statistically, a fund's return will come in above or below its standard deviation 68 percent of the time. Doubling a fund's standard deviation shows the range of returns that can be expected from that fund 95 percent of the time. <p>An example: <a name="FUND:PTNAX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PTNAX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PIMCO Total Return Fund</b></a>-Institutional Shares, which is rated five stars by Morningstar, has a three-year average annual return of 7.19 percent and a standard deviation of 4.41 percent. So 95 percent of the time, this fund's annual return should range from a loss of 1.63 percent to a 16.01 percent profit. Used judiciously, MPT techniques are an important tool in achieving diversification, the biggest piece in the investment jigsaw puzzle. <p>---------------------------------------<p>PLOTTING OUT YOUR RISKS AND REWARDS<p>Are your funds performing as well as they should? Arnold Langsen, a retired professor of finance at University of California at Hayward and the editor of Prudence and Performance Newsletter in Danville, California, says individual investors can find out by gauging the risk and return of a group of funds by plotting them on a scattergram. <p>A pencil, a sheet of graph paper, a ruler, and the readily available Morningstar mutual fund statistics are all you need to plot your own scattergram and get a visual representation of the relative efficiency of your group of funds in balancing risks and rewards. First, look up your funds' three-year average annual returns in Morningstar Mutual Funds. Also jot down the funds' standard deviation. Next, on a piece of graph paper, draw a horizontal and a vertical axis. Mark them off as shown at right, extending both axes as far as necessary to accommodate your funds. Then, draw a vertical axis and mark off every five boxes from zero to 40. Mark the vertical axis "annual returns," and the horizontal axis "standard deviation." Plot each of the funds you own.<p>The result may surprise you. "What people often find when they do this exercise is that they're investing in two funds with the same objective and style, but one of them is taking half the risk to get the same returns," says Langsen.<p><a name="FUND:VFINX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VFINX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>The Vanguard Index 500 fund</b></a>, with a three-year average annual return of 8.61 percent through February 28, 1995, and a standard deviation of 8.10, is our benchmark, or "bogey," as it closely tracks the action of the Standard & Poor's 500. When comparing a group of funds with the same investment objective, you may also want to plot the return and standard deviation of the average fund within that sector of funds. These numbers are also in Morningstar.<p>Of the five growth and income funds charted here, it's clear that Paine Webber Dividend Growth A, which gained an average 0.9 percent annually over the past three years, has not adequately rewarded investors for their risks compared with the Vanguard Index 500, which gained 8.61 percent annually while running less risk than the PaineWebber fund. Another revealing observation: <a name="FUND:GATEX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GATEX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gateway Index Plus</b></a>, an index fund that hedges risk with stock options, took roughly half the risk of the Vanguard Index 500 over the past three years but posted an average gain just 1.79 percent less.<p>Whether an investment in <a name="FUND:BEGRX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BEGRX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mutual Beacon</b></a> or <a name="FUND:MSIGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MSIGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oppenheimer Main Street Income and Growth A</b></a> is more efficent is a little more difficult to visualize. Oppenheimer Main Street has gotten higher returns but has taken more than twice the risk. Since the winner of this matchup is hard to see, simply divide a fund's return by its standard deviation to find its risk/reward ratio. Mutual Beacon has a 2.56 risk/reward ratio, far better than Oppenheimer Main Street's 1.35. This is a simplified version of an MPT statistic known as a Sharpe ratio. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing Strategies<p>

