	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-1994 Rankings of Best Funds</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
With so many mutual funds to choose from, it can be tough to decide which are best for you. That's why Worth screened a total of 777 funds to compile our annual performance ratings for Novembers cover story. Our report tells you which funds came out on top.<p>---------------<br>
<br>
Introduction<br>
---------------<br>
By John Koten<p>Jonathan Swift once observed that "There is nothing in this world constant, but inconstancy." This view will draw few arguments from mutual fund investors in 1994. Jostled by a jittery market, the value of the average stock fund has risen, fallen, and then jumped back up again. Unsettling, to say the least. But the gyrations are likely to continue, as we've pointed out more than once in Worth. Now more than ever, investors need to make wise choices. <p>This guide should help. We begin by examining the risks inherent in today's market -- and then show what you can do to make sure your funds are reasonably safe. (See "Best Funds: The Forecast For Risk" further down in this file.)<p>Next, we explain how not to pick mutual funds (by relying solely on past-performance numbers). (See "Best Funds: Why Past Isn't Prologue" further down in this file.)<p>We also take you through the methodology we use to evaluate funds -- a breakthrough system that looks at risk level, performance against a benchmark, and an entirely new measurement that focuses on predictability. (See "Best Funds: How We Picked Them" further down in this file.)<p>Information on our top five choices (see "Best Funds: Best Of The Best - LIST") and a list of 47 funds that received our $$$$$ rating (see "Best Funds: Top-Rated Funds - LIST") complete our package. In our December/January issue, we'll take a similar look at bond funds. <p><p>The Forecast for Risk
Equity funds may actually be safer investments now than they were a few years ago. Still, it  pays to know the signs of danger.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>A decade of enviable returns in stock funds lulled many investors into believing there was only one risk associated with these investments -- the risk of being left behind. Who could chance missing out on the stellar performance these funds were sure to provide? By contrast, the microscopic yields of money market funds and certificates of deposit appeared a much greater threat to capital formation. <p>Not anymore. As investors in bond funds and aggressive stock funds found out earlier this year, risks are very much evident in mutual funds. Declining net asset values have prompted previously complacent investors to wonder: What are the risks inherent in my stock mutual fund? Are there hidden perils lurking in my equity-fund holdings? Do stock funds carry greater or fewer risks today than they did five years ago?<p>Contrary to the shrill stories that have appeared recently in the press about mounting risks in mutual funds, equity funds are probably safer now than they were five years ago. One reason: Most highflying stocks have had their wings clipped this year, reducing most funds' exposure to overvalued securities. Managers who still own and believe in these stocks have been able to buy more shares cheaper, reducing average costs of ownership. <p>A second reason: Although the major market averages have been adrift, corporate earnings have escalated. This means most funds now hold stocks with slightly lower price-to-earnings ratios, making them less risky than before.<p>Third, equity funds are more diversified today. Robert Markman, a Minneapolis money manager who advises clients on mutual funds, says, "Funds went into international investing, which, if anything, reduced risk." <p>Equity-fund investors worried about potential time bombs in their portfolios should keep in mind, too, that most of this year's hair-raising fund losses were recorded in bond, not stock, funds. Although it might seem a good assumption that greater risks in bond-fund portfolios mean similarly higher risks in stock funds, this simply isn't true. <p>What decimated many bond funds was a reliance on exotic fixed-income securities -- hatched by Wall Street wizards -- known as derivatives. When interest rates rose, this exotica was almost impossible to get out of and even harder to value. Some bond funds are still sitting with their derivative holdings, waiting for the market to come back. They could be waiting for some time.<p>Equity-fund managers, however, don't need to stoop to such tactics. In their game, stock-picking prowess alone can vault a manager to the top of the class. "Derivatives are strictly on the bond side," says Jonathan Teall of Lipper Analytical Services.<p>This is not to say that equity funds in today's environment are totally safe. There is one very real risk associated with an investment in a stock fund right now: market risk.<p>Market risk is the risk that an investor will be caught owning a broad spectrum of stocks that only decline in value. Or that the overall markets will go down and take all stocks with them. Market risk remains a concern because current market valuations, though lower than they were at the start of the year, are still high by historical standards.<p>Consider the ratio of stock prices to corporate earnings, a classic yardstick. During the last 45 years, the median price-to-earnings ratio on the Dow Jones Industrial Average has been 14.6. The current ratio is 20.8. What about dividend yields? The median for DJIA stocks for the past 45 years is 4.06 percent. Lately, these stocks have yielded 2.69 percent. <p>Two other key statistics tell the same story. The 45-year median ratio of market value to book value -- a measure of a company's stock price to its assets -- is 1.59. The current measure is 3.51. This means investors are paying an average three-plus times book value to buy the Dow industrials, double the historical rate.<p>Some analysts also wonder whether the market hasn't gotten ahead of itself recently. From 1926 to 1990, stocks averaged a 10 percent annual return to investors. Since 1991, though, returns have averaged 13 percent. This suggests that stocks' growth may slow, or even drop, to bring them in line with history. Clearly, market risk is an issue for investors today. But short of selling all stock holdings, there's no way to eliminate it. There is, however, much that can be done to reduce exposure to market risk. First, investors should assess exactly how much risk is currently in their portfolios. Only then can one determine vulnerability to a market swoon and whether adjustments are needed.<p>Market risk is not equally perilous to all investors. Those investing their money for a very long-term goal -- for a retirement 30 years hence, say -- have less to worry about in a market decline than investors who are trying to meet a short-term goal. Over the long run, stocks should rebound in line with historic growth rates. But to someone investing to pay for a 15-year-old's college education, market risk can be dangerous. <p>To pinpoint your exposure to market risk, delve into the portfolios of your funds. Is a manager a prudent steward or a reckless daredevil? To find out, check:<p>-> THE FUND'S AVERAGE PRICE-TO-EARNINGS RATIO. Because stock prices have fallen in relation to corporate earnings this year, funds that still hold a lot of stocks with high price-to-earnings ratios are effectively taking on greater market risk than funds with few such stocks. <p>When looking up the average for your fund, make sure you compare it with those of funds in a similar investment category. Value-oriented funds, for instance, generally tend to hold stocks with lower P/E ratios than growth funds do. But value funds aren't necessarily the safer of the two. The tipoff occurs when one value fund carries a much higher P/E ratio than other value funds.<p>Also consider comparing your fund's average P/E with that of the market index that best represents the fund's holdings: the S&P 500 if it's a large-capitalization stock fund or the Russell 2000 if it's a small-cap fund.<p>-> THE AVERAGE PRICE-TO-BOOK RATIO. A stock that trades near the book value of its assets is generally safer than one that trades at some multiple of that valuation. <p>Which type does your fund prefer? If you own ABT Emerging Growth fund, the average price-to-book ratio is almost 6. But if you own Alliance Quasar fund, the price-to-book ratio is 2.6. All else being equal, Alliance is the safer of the two funds.<p>-> PORTFOLIO DIVERSIFICATION. Aggressive concentration in one sector of the stock market suggests higher risk. Thomson Opportunity fund, for instance, currently has 45 percent of its portfolio invested in technology stocks -- a bet that this area of the economy will outperform all others. Although Thomson's wager could eventually prove a good one, its strategy is relatively perilous. <p>-> OBSCURE STOCK HOLDINGS. Another tipoff to outsize market risk is a fund that invests in little-known securities. Whenever the market encounters turbulence, investors typically flee smaller stocks for blue chips. A fund heavily into no-name stocks might find it hard to exit these shares without huge losses.<p>Check the contents of your fund's portfolio by asking for a copy of the fund's latest annual report. If you can't find some of the fund's largest holdings printed in the major stock market tables, it means you've got some serious market risk.<p>-> RISK HISTORY. Has the fund's style changed? Movement in any of the four categories above may be significant. A fund manager who has become more aggressive buying pricier stocks or investing more heavily in a single industry could be headed for a fall.<p>-> THE ESCAPE PLAN. Read the latest quarterly report and see what the plans are for market upheaval. Is the fund prepared to move out of equities and into cash if things get rough? A manager with a strategy for a bad market is better able to respond when one hits. <p>Gauging the risk in your holdings is useful only if you have ascertained how much risk you feel comfortable with. David Tice, a Dallas money manager who pens Behind the Numbers, an investment report, says, "If [people] have invested their savings substantially into an equity fund over the past two years, they should understand the risk. They should be willing to lose 30 percent over the next 12 months."<p>That's not a prediction about 1995. It's a reminder that large short-term losses are always possible. If you can't live with the risk, don't invest in equities. Use Tice's number to assess your financial state and your nerves. <p>Here's another way to think about risk. Assume stocks return an average of 10 percent a year, a gain your fund mirrors. Annual fees and expenses of around 1.25 percent drop your return to around 8.75 percent. Now consider that three-year, risk-free Treasury notes currently yield 6.67 percent. Do you want to take on substantial market risk to earn an extra 2 percent a year? <p>Of course, earning 10 percent in stocks is no guarantee, either. It is simply an average return over a 64-year period.<p>Money manager Markman believes fund investors are largely unaware of the risks they're taking. "People have loaded up with aggressive funds," he says. "Eighty percent have no idea how much they can lose."<p>Market risk in stock funds may not seem as treacherous as risks in derivatives that decimated bond funds this year. But market risk is nothing to sneeze at. While some investors roll with market punches, other investors cannot. Which investor are you?
---------------
Gretchen Morgenson is executive editor of Worth.<p><p>Why the Past Isn't Prologue
Last year's numbers won't get you very far when it comes to picking the right funds.<p>By Gary Hector<p>Mutual funds are like a box of chocolates: You never know what you're going to get. Or so it must seem to investors who buy a highflying fund just in time to see it nose-dive. Of course, advertisements do nothing to discourage this approach -- they talk incessantly about recent returns. Many of the fund rankings published in magazines and newspapers do the same.<p>As a strategy, though, favoring funds based on past performance is highly suspect. What works in the handicapping of football teams and racehorses comes up short in the markets. All things being equal, a mutual fund that did well last year isn't any more likely to turn in an inspired performance in the future than one that did poorly. <p>"No analysis of the past, no matter how painstaking, assures future superiority," says John Bogle in the book Bogle on Mutual Funds. He knows whereof he speaks; Bogle is the chairman of the Vanguard Group, one of the nation's largest fund companies.<p>The predominant influence on most equity funds, of course, is the rise and fall of the market itself. Studies using a technical formula called R2 have determined that, over time, the general movement of stock prices accounts for about 80 percent of the performance of most funds. When a fund diverges sharply from the market's performance, the difference can usually be explained by the fund's investment strategy. Essentially, this is a matter of a fund being in the right segment of the market at the right time. A fund that invests in small companies will outdo the market when small-cap stocks are hot. Funds investing in companies with low price-to-earnings ratios and high dividends will outpace the market when value companies are in vogue. <p>But these differences tend to even out. In the long run, most equity funds earn a return close to the average for all stocks. The range of performance among funds narrows dramatically the longer the funds operate. Funds that do well for a few years eventually begin to underperform, bringing their long-term results back in line with those of other funds. This process is known as regression to the mean.<p>The long-term tendency of funds to cluster around some average level of performance also suggests that it may even be hazardous to buy last year's hot property. Take the Fidelity Emerging Markets Fund, which did extremely well in 1993. It rose nearly 82 percent, not tops among international funds but still a very impressive result. An investor who jumped on this fund's bandwagon late in 1993 was in for a big shock during this year's first half. In a tough period for overseas funds, Emerging Markets fell nearly 20 percent -- dead last in performance in the category of general international funds.<p>Should this investor now race to sell? Not necessarily.<p>Suppose, for a moment, that the thousands of funds currently in existence were all placed squarely in the hands of random chance. Under this scenario, the performance distribution for all funds would, over time, grow to resemble a bell curve -- with the vast majority of the funds clustered around the median and a diminishing number stretched toward the high and low ends of the scale.<p>To academics and others who have studied mutual funds, it's no coincidence that the real-world chart of fund performance almost perfectly fits this hypothetical pattern. As long ago as 1968, the Journal of Finance published a classic study of mutual funds. After examining industry results over a 20-year period, the study concluded that individual fund performance was no better than mere random chance might predict.<p>People have been trying to poke holes in that conclusion ever since, but without success. From time to time, a fund manager gains fame for appearing to turn the theory on its head. The manager racks up big gains year after year. The critics say the streak could end at any time, but it doesn't. It goes on and on. <p>The fund manager, of course, hasn't really beaten the laws of mathematics at all. With more than 4,000 mutual funds, there are bound to be a few spectacular performers at any given time. The fund manager may indeed be a gifted stock picker, and some percentage of his or her results may be the result of those gifts. But for a fund to perform at the very top of the heap also requires a large measure of good fortune. The markets are simply too efficient to allow anyone much of an edge. <p>The problem comes in forecasting which fund managers will maintain their good fortune and which are about to begin their regression to the mean. At any given moment, probability theory suggests the odds are 50-50 that either could occur.<p>What about the former laggard that emerges from nowhere to beat all the favorites? Or what about the brilliant manager who simply has suffered a lot of bad luck? Certainly past performance wouldn't help to identify either of these cases. Nor would any of the currently devised yardsticks of fund performance and investment styles -- beta, standard deviation, and the like. No one has come up with a system that can reliably identify the funds that will top next year's ratings.<p>This is not to say that some of these measurement tools aren't useful when it comes to picking funds. Nor does it mean that a fund manager can't make smart choices that will provide an edge for his or her investors over time. But it does mean that spectacular performance in the markets requires a great deal of luck. Recognizing this, a rational investor will try to select funds that instead offer reasonable odds of either keeping up with or modestly beating the market indexes. This is the approach that we take at Worth.<p>If fate grins and turns a solid choice into a rocket ship, of course, then so much the better. <p>Despite overwhelming evidence of its limitations, past performance continues to play a prominent role in the choices that most fund investors make. Although this is mostly true of investors in search of a potential winner, it's also become common for cautious-minded folks: They look at how various funds did in down markets to gauge whether their choices are safe. <p>"The usefulness of track records is taken for granted by most participants in the investment industry," writes William Goetzmann and Roger Ibbotson in a recent study of mutual fund behavior. Goetzmann, an assistant professor of finance at the Columbia Graduate School of Business, and Ibbotson, a professor at the Yale School of Management, add, "For most [fund] clients, questions about the money manager's record are among the first questions asked."<p>We did some tests ourselves on the predictive ability of past performance. Using Alexander Steele's Mutual Fund Expert software program, we studied the performance of the top growth funds during each of the last five years. We selected the ten funds with the top annual performance record in each year, including both growth and aggressive-growth funds to ensure there was no bias toward large or small companies. Then we tracked the performance of these funds in the years after they made the top ten. <p>What did we find? The funds that made the top ten in 1990 did no better than the average growth or aggressive-growth fund the following year. Half of 1990's top-ten growth funds actually placed in the bottom third of the category in 1991. Of 1991's top ten funds, half beat the markets the following year and half didn't.<p>After the first year, performance deteriorated steadily. By 1993, for instance, only one of 1990's top ten beat the markets -- and that fund came in 125th out of the 444 funds included in the Steele program for that year. The worst ranked 437th. In the first half of 1994, none of the 1990 winners beat the markets.<p>We also found that it doesn't help for investors to look at longer track records. Selecting funds by looking at three-year or five-year horizons -- with no consideration of any other factors -- produces the same sort of results as looking solely at one-year performance records. "If you have two managers with equal skills," says Ken Gregory, editor of the newsletter No-Load Fund Analyst, "which of them will do better in the next five years doesn't have much to do with the last five years."<p>The bull market of recent years has shielded investors from this reality. Most funds did pretty well during the market's run-up, so the vast majority of investors scored gains whether they picked goods funds or not. Maybe their star performer didn't remain a star, but at least they didn't lose money.<p>More recently, however, the markets have been less forgiving, and most funds no longer generate spectacular returns. In this climate, the penalty for making a poor choice is likely to be more harsh.<p>The smartest investors won't be obsessed with catching a ride with the next Peter Lynch or John Neff. They'll be looking for consistency rather than spectacular performance. Our fund ratings will help get these investors started. <p>We claim only to have identified funds that are most likely to beat certain market benchmarks year in and year out. Given the risks of any other approach, we believe this is what a smart investor should be looking for.
---------------
Gary Hector is a contributing writer for Worth.<p><p>How We Picked Them
Our method rates funds based on three key measures: risk, predictability, and performance against a  benchmark. First make smart picks. Then combine  them in an effective portfolio.<p>By Jim Jubak<p>It's ironic that mutual funds are supposed to make investing easier -- because there is certainly nothing simple about deciding which ones to buy. In some ways (but not all) it's easier to pick and choose among stocks. There are fewer of them, and there's more to distinguish one company's shares from another's. With stocks, a potential investor can examine the quality of a company's balance sheet, the savvy of its management, the workability of its business strategy, and the prospects for its industry. These are substantive matters that lend themselves to productive research. In contrast, mutual funds offer a much hazier set of attributes. <p>We've already explained how misleading fund track records can be (see "Best Funds: Why Past Isn't Prologue" earlier in this file). But there's also considerable debate on the significance of the manager's role, as well as on the predictive value of beta and standard deviation -- especially either of these viewed alone. Anyone who has spent a lot of time trying to figure out why one growth fund might be better than another knows just how frustrating the task can be. Consulting the stars doesn't help. Neither does voodoo.<p>We set out to cut through this murk and devise a rational, defensible system for selecting equity funds. We didn't delude ourselves into thinking that we could pick next year's number-one performer. We knew that would be either fruitless or dishonest. So we focused on a more reasonable goal: identifying funds that have consistently beaten their peers in the past and that display concrete evidence of being able to repeat this performance. What we wanted, more than anything, was a system that would provide some sense of a fund's predictability. Specifically, we wanted to know which of the better-performing equity funds were merely lucky and which possessed the systems and skills to provide a true edge for their shareholders.<p>Modest as this goal may seem on the surface, accomplishing it actually would represent something of a breakthrough in fund analysis. So far as we know, no one out there has really done it yet, despite various public pronouncements to the contrary. <p>Our focus was on developing a system that would provide solid medium- and long-term results. Given recent increases in interest rates -- and the resulting improvement in returns offered by fixed-income instruments -- we assumed few of our readers would still be interested in buying equity funds for short-term purposes (less than five years). At the moment, the risks of equity funds outweigh their potential advantages as short-term investments.<p>To begin our quest, we asked Morningstar Inc. to provide us with complete data on every equity fund with at least a five-year track record and no less than $25 million in assets. Then we filled holes in the numbers and updated important statistics such as average price-to-earnings ratios and manager tenure. In the end, we collected more than 20,000 pieces of data for 777 funds. We loaded these statistics into a spreadsheet of our own design and enlisted the aid of a computer analyst to help us manipulate the numbers.<p>One thing we knew we wanted to look for right off the bat: Funds that displayed a consistent approach to investing. Mutual fund managers such as Tom Frank of Dreyfus New Leaders talked to us at great length about this key attribute. Dreyfus, for instance, hires an outside advisory firm for the sole purpose of providing the company with feedback on whether its funds invest consistently. <p>That made good sense to us when we thought about what factors produce the performance record of any fund. Above all, mutual fund results are influenced by the movement of the stock market -- not the individual buy-and-sell decisions of fund managers. When the market goes up, most funds do better. When it goes down, they do worse. Simple as that.<p>Funds with certain investment styles also benefit from cyclical changes in the types of stocks that are driving the market. When small-cap growth stocks are red hot, for instance, funds that invest disproportionately in these securities soar along with them. Such strategies are normally defined in a fund's charter; managers don't get to pick and choose. So there's no sense rewarding funds that just happen to be in the right place at the right time.<p>This meant that to find the best and most consistent funds, we had to be able to eliminate market factors. We wanted funds that do better than average because their managers actually contribute something to the fund's performance. Solution: Pit equity funds with like investment strategies against one another. <p>In recent years, the mutual fund industry has made a show of this by dividing the universe of funds into a seemingly infinite number of style groups. This allows investors to compare the performance of a particular fund against peers who presumably all rise and fall with the market in similar fashion.<p>The industry's sectors are so narrowly defined, however, that we wonder about the true motive behind it all. It could be that the fund companies just want as many opportunities as possible to win number-one rankings in different categories. All the better for their advertising efforts.<p>But not necessarily helpful for investors, who are then faced with an extra step in the fund-selection process -- before considering which funds to buy, they must first decide which of the myriad fund groups to focus on. This is useless, we think.<p>We decided to go back to the drawing board and chalk out our own fund categories, holding the number to no more than five. Ken Gregory editor of the No Load Fund Analyst newsletter in Orinda, California, and Paul Greenwood, senior research analyst for U.S. equities at the Frank Russell Co., helped us split U.S. equity funds into a matrix of four groups, defined by whether they invest primarily in large companies or small companies and whether they look for value or growth in stocks. We called a large-cap fund one that generally invests in stocks with a median market capitalization of at least $1.03 billion -- the same definition Russell currently uses. Small-cap funds were those that generally invest in anything smaller. We used price-to-book ratios (the relationship between the price of a stock and its underlying asset value) to separate value and growth funds. Once we decided on the right groupings for our U.S. funds (small-cap growth, small-cap value, large-cap growth, and large-cap value), we added a fifth category, global funds, to include funds that invest at least 40 percent of their assets in foreign securities.<p>The next step was comparing the returns of our 777 funds to an appropriate stock index. We used four Russell-designed indexes as benchmarks for the U.S. funds, and the Morgan Stanley Europe, Australia and the Far East index for global funds. Then, we subtracted the performance of the appropriate index from each fund's one-, three-, and five-year returns.<p>But we also needed a single rating number for returns that we could plug into a final overall score for our fund evaluations. For this purpose, we took the five-year figures and deducted the impact of each fund's front-end sales charges. We felt this gave us a number that best reflected the true returns each fund provided its investors.<p>Presumably, the more risks a fund takes, the lower the odds that it will be able to repeat its performance in the future. So we wanted to know what sort of gambles funds had taken to achieve their levels of performance. After looking over many of the current popular formulas for evaluating risk, however, we felt unsatisfied. Most of them simply look at how many down quarters a fund has had and how severe these drops were. In other words, they try to judge future risk based simply on the fund's past performance. We wanted something better. The risk model we designed relies on three different measurements of fund characteristics that don't bounce around with the market: standard deviation, a way of looking at past performance that examines the degree of variance in a fund's performance over time; beta, a measure of a fund's volatility in relation to the entire stock market; and turnover, a measure of how actively a manager trades his portfolio. Again, we compared each fund with those in its peer group. The final result was a rating from 1 to 100, with 100 representing the lowest possible level of risk. <p>We also used our spreadsheet to calculate a separate predictability rating for each fund, a feature found in no other ranking system. To do this, we looked at changes in fund managers during the five-year study period -- a new manager might be better or worse than the one responsible for the fund's track record, but there's no way to know which outcome is the more likely. We also investigated a fund's growth in net assets from 1991 to 1994. Excessive growth would cause us to worry about the fund manager's ability to manage the additional cash while maintaining the investment style that had served the fund well in the past. We also compared each fund's current average price-to-earnings and price-to-book ratios to past ratios to determine the types of stocks it purchased over time. And we also looked at loads and expenses, knowing that high charges tend to reduce performance. In combination, these characteristics gave us the ingredients for a new rating, which we called the predictor.<p>As an overall rating for each fund, we combined the return, risk, and predictor numbers into one score, which we then translated into dollar-sign ratings, from $ for laggards to $$$$$ for the very best. Only 5 percent of the 777 funds scored a top rating.<p>Once we were finished, we conducted a number of seat-of-the-pants tests to evaluate our results. Would we feel comfortable buying the funds that ranked high on our list? Were these managers we knew and trusted? How did our results compare with those of other fund-ranking systems? To the extent that there were any apparent anomalies, we wanted to know the reason.<p>Certainly there were some surprises. Some well-regarded funds, such as Fidelity Magellan, received only a $$$ rating (ranking it in the middle 40 percent of the fund universe). In Magellan's case, this happened despite a relatively high return rating of 86. When we looked closer, however, we saw that a middle-of-the-road risk rating and a low predictor had pushed Magellan down in the final rankings. The predictor had detected a change in the fund's p/e ratio -- to 21.74 from 17.12 in 1991 -- and also took into account the fund's change in managers. Our score was fair.<p>The case of SteinRoe Prime Equities shows exactly how our predictor worked. The fund would have rated a top $$$$$ on the basis of an 80 return rating and a 79 risk rating, except that its longtime manager Ralph Segall left to start another fund this year. That lowered the fund's predictor rating to 18 and gave the fund an overall rating of $$$$. Or take the case of another highly regarded fund, Crabbe Huson Special Equities. The fund's extremely high return rating of 94 couldn't carry the fund above $$$ because of its poor risk rating (reflecting an above-average standard deviation) and a low predictor (a result of the fund's rapid asset growth).<p>Finally, we tested our system by examining each fund that scored $$$$$ to come up with our choices for the five best funds (see "Best Funds: Best Of The Best - LIST" further down in this file).
---------------
Spreadsheet design and analysis by Jim Jubak and Robert Lipton.<p>
Best of the Best - LIST
These five funds came out tops among the 777 we examined.<p>Our annual survey of mutual funds screened a total of 777 different funds. Of those, only 47 received our top rating of $$$$$ (see "Best Funds: Top-Rated Funds - LIST" further down in this file).<p>We then delved into each fund that scored $$$$$, conducting an in-depth analysis of performance charts and fund statistics to see if our screening had missed anything. We ended up picking the two best funds in each of five groups and dispatching a team of reporters to interview the managers. After reviewing the results, we selected the five best funds, which are listed below.<p>A portfolio of these five would be balanced for style, hedged against risk, and, best of all, likely to deliver better-than-market returns to an investor. Not bad for any system, we think.<p><p>WORTH'S TOP FIVE FUNDS
---------------
