				<font size=5><b>Bank Funds Hit an Ethical Snag</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Bank Funds Hit an Ethical Snag</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994 
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>BANK FUNDS HIT AN ETHICAL SNAG
Some banks are in hot water over mutual fund sales.<p>By Elizabeth MacDonald<p>At first, the explosive growth of the mutual fund industry was bad news for banks -- depositors fled in droves to the newly popular instruments. Then the banks came up with a way to fight back: They'd sell their own mutual funds. <p>Yet allegations have surfaced that, in the battle to retain depositors, some banks may have acted too aggressively. A series of recent lawsuits filed by disgruntled investors and former bank employees allege a host of ethical and legal infractions committed by certain bank brokers, including the payment of kickbacks to bank tellers for referrals. While there is no indication that these practices are widespread among the 3,500 or so banks that sell their 1,700 house-brand funds, the lawsuits illustrate potential conflicts that didn't exist until banks started selling their own mutual funds.<p>A lawsuit filed June 21 in U.S. District Court in Tampa, Florida, by former NationsBank broker David Cray illuminates the issues. Cray alleges that NationsBank's two-year old brokerage, NationsSecurities, a 50-50 partnership between NationsBank, the country's fourth-largest bank, headquartered in Charlotte, North Carolina, and Dean Witter Financial Services, used misleading sales tactics, violated securities laws, and breached depositors' privacy rights when selling funds. <p>Cray's suit says that after he outlined his allegations in a June 1994 letter to bank management, Cray, a broker for 16 years, was fired. On July 27, two former NationsSecurities brokers -- Catherine Hovis and Robert Lewis -- joined Cray in a separate arbitration suit charging similar violations. The brokers are each demanding $20 million in compensatory damages, plus $500 million total in punitive damages. <p>Furthermore, on June 23, three NationsSecurities investors filed a class-action suit against the bank in U.S. District Court in Tampa, charging the same state and federal securities law violations. NationsBank says it "vigorously denies these claims."<p>However, in late July, 18 former and current brokers also filed arbitration claims against NationsSecurities with the National Association of Securities Dealers in New York for its "illegal commission-sharing arrangement." The brokers' suit says that when tellers referred a customer to them, the brokers were required to split their commissions with the tellers, in violation of SEC and NASD rules, which say unregistered dealers are not qualified to give investment advice. The bank's official reply: "We can state unequivocally that NationsSecurities is a professional brokerage firm dedicated to meeting the needs of consumers through more than 600 account executives in nine states and the District of Columbia."<p>According to Cray's lawsuit, the bank's alleged missteps, begin with its training methods, which encourage bank tellers to tip off fund salesmen to activities of big depositors, possibly violating a customer's right to privacy. Cray, who has since started up Cray Financial Group in Safety Harbor, Florida, charges, "It was popular for the bank to train tellers to inform [brokers] immediately when a sizable deposit was made." In addition, Cray says NationsSecurities brokers gained access to confidential customer-account information without their clients' consent, including "the types of investments held by each NationsBank customer, the maturity dates of certificates of deposit, the dates and times of deposits and withdrawals, the identities of joint-account holders, and addresses, telephone numbers, ages, and incomes of the customers." <p>Armed with this information, Cray says, brokers stalked clients. "One day a depositor plunked $300,000 into a savings account at the branch," he recalls. "By the time he got home from the bank, there was a message on his answering machine from a NationsSecurities broker." <p>Cray explains how the bank's referral system operated. "In order to keep their jobs and even win prizes, customer-service representatives got one point for every new NationsSecurities account they referred to brokers. Employees who racked up the most points, typically 100 or more in a quarter, won televisions or trips to Acapulco, the Cayman Islands, or the Caribbean."<p>Furthermore, the complaint claims, NationsSecurities brokers were discouraged from selling non-NationsBank and non-Dean Witter funds with the threat of reduced commissions. For example, on a $100,000 new account placed with an outside equity fund, the bank would rake in 3.25 percent of the purchase amount in gross commissions. According to the bank's scoring system, on an external fund, it would pay a broker 18 percent of that $3,250, or $585. If the broker instead sold the bank's equity income fund, "which doesn't have an established track and isn't rated by Morningstar," says Cray, the bank would get $5,000 and pay brokers up to 25 percent of that amount, or $1,250. Cray also claims depositors often had no clue that these funds carried back-end loads (dubbed "early withdrawal penalties," a term used for CDs), since such charges accrue only when the funds are cashed out. <p>Leilani Demint and her 27-year-old autistic son, Edward Ringwald, of St. Petersburg, Florida, are two investors who claim they succumbed to NationsBank's aggressive selling. Last year, NationsSecurities placed $70,000 of Demint's CD and savings-account money in a 6 percent Dean Witter U.S. Government Securities trust and a 7 percent Putnam bond fund. The two funds had 5 to 6 percent back-end loads, described to her as "early withdrawal penalties." "I would never have put my money in a mutual fund or a securities trust. I was told it was going into a savings bond and that my principal was safe," says Demint. She lost $6,000, and is now a plaintiff in the class-action suit. <p>NationsBank isn't alone in facing angry depositors. On June 28, Richard C. Hilton, a real estate investor, filed a $60,000 lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Tampa charging Barnett Bank with "breach of fiduciary duty," "[breach of] financial privacy," and "wanton, willful, and malicious" actions. Hilton's suit says in May 1993 a Barnett banker shared his confidential money market-account information with Barnett Securities. Soon after, a Barnett broker made a sales pitch, which Hilton resisted. <p>The broker, says Hilton, took his $60,000 money market balance "without [his] full knowledge and fully informed authorization or consent" and stuck that amount into a bond fund. Hilton later lost $3,400. After learning that his new investment was not insured and that he had been charged a sales commission, Hilton tried to get his principal back, but the bank allegedly refused to reimburse him. Barnett Bank says in an official statement: "Customers buying mutual funds through Barnett are required to sign forms clearly stating that these investments are not federally insured" and that it "found [Hilton's] allegations to be without merit." <p>Mutual funds have a strong appeal for banks partly because of the fees the banks can charge. Besides sales commissions, annual fees pour in whether investors are buying or not. Perhaps because bank funds' average expense ratio of 0.84 percent lags the typical fund's ratio of 1.16 percent, bankers pulled in $274 million in charges in 1993, up from $150 million in 1992, according to Michael Lipper, president of Lipper Analytical Services. <p>Bankers "are also interested in maintaining an account relationship," says Lipper. "They don't want to see those accounts walk down the street to a broker."<p>If you like the idea of one-stop financial shopping at your neighborhood bank, protect yourself. Stick with funds that have existed for at least five years, in both up and down markets, and have historically outperformed the average in their category. This may be tough, however, since many bank funds are two years old or less. <p>Ask the bank broker for reports from independent rating firms. If he doesn't have them, he's ill-informed, so head for the exit.<p>Compare a bank fund's fees with those of similar funds. Many bank funds are freighted with back-end loads. Stay clear of deferred charges that surpass these averages: 3.9 percent for growth funds, 5.0 percent for growth and income funds, and 4.3 percent on balanced funds. If the fund carries a front-end load, don't pay more than 4.3 percent.<p>Finally, don't put all your money in one bank fund. "Test drive the bank fund first," says Lipper. "Invest 10 to 20 percent of your money, then see how it performs." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Mutual Funds Investing, Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

