<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Rising Risks in Foreign Funds</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Rising Risks in Foreign Funds</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Will the dollar continue to juice returns? Probably not. <p>By Liliana Nealon<p>In 1985, when the dollar was hitting a historic high against the world's major currencies, investors in the United States decided to venture out into the world's equity markets. Their timing was impeccable.<p>Since then, the dollar has lost about 50 percent of its value against the European currencies and the yen, giving international investors a double bang for their buck. Yet few international-fund owners realize how much of their overseas portfolio's returns are the result of a falling dollar. Now is a good time to remember that investing in foreign equity and bond mutual funds is really a two-part investment: a bet on the underlying asset and another bet on the currency in which the investment is domiciled.<p>The currency portion can be substantial. Consider the performance of <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a>'s Europe, Australia, and Far East (EAFE) index, the foreign benchmark for most U.S. investors. According to research conducted by Virginia Parker of Ferrell Capital Management in Greenwich, Connecticut, close to 65 percent of the return of the EAFE index since 1986 has been attributable to currency fluctuations. Parker says it is not unusual to find that in any given year, half or more of EAFE returns are due to currency alone and not to the returns of the underlying assets.<p>This doesn't mean investors should abandon international funds. Economic and business cycles peak and trough at different times in different countries, and the only way to capitalize on these cycles is to be invested in the countries in which they occur when they occur. Several studies have shown that over time a portfolio with a good mix of international holdings will outperform a portfolio invested solely in domestic holdings. <p>But now more than ever, it's crucial for investors to know just how big a role gyrating currencies can have on a fund's return. That's because it's unlikely that investors in foreign markets will continue to reap currency gains at a level anything like the last five years. And if the dollar stabilizes or begins to rise in value, investors will face the possibility of currency losses. <p>Consider this result of the declining dollar: During the period from 1970 to 1990, $1 invested in Japanese equities returned over $39. But about $24, or 61 percent, of that return was due to the yen's appreciation against the dollar. Similarly, an investor who bought a German equity portfolio worth 100,000 deutsche marks at the dollar's high against the mark in February 1985 would have paid $28,965. At today's exchange rates, without any appreciation or depreciation of the underlying assets, that portfolio would be worth $60,500, a return of more than 100 percent. Smoke and mirrors? Derivatives with hidden losses? None of the above: Simply a dollar in steep decline against the deutsche mark. <p>The dollar has fallen since 1985 partly because of the drop in U.S. interest rates and partly because of the large supply of dollars held abroad. The dollar was also grossly overvalued in 1985, which prompted massive dollar selling by the world's central banks as they sought to defend their own currencies. Now the greenback is at historic lows against the yen. Against European currencies, the dollar has been in so steep a tailspin that the Federal Reserve Board and other central banks recently bought dollars to prop up the currency. The administration's efforts to prop up the dollar may not fuel much of a rally in the currency. And it's quite possible the dollar will slide even further. But it is highly unlikely that the greenback will fall as far as it did in the 1980s.<p>A stagnant or rising dollar can very easily mean diminished returns for investors in overseas portfolios. Since U.S. fund managers did not venture into the world of global investing until the mid-'80s, the beginning of the dollar bear market, they have little or no experience managing portfolios in dollar bull moves. Ezra Zask, president of Ezra Zask Associates, a fund-management and consulting firm in Norfolk, Connecticut, says that about two thirds of U.S. international fund managers do not hedge their currency risk. While this passive approach may have been a boon to returns in this period of dollar weakness, it will have the opposite effect if the dollar turns around. "Look for managers who take a more active role in hedging their portfolios," recommends Zask. "Avoid the more passive, no-hedge policy managers."<p>Keep in mind, too, that emerging-market funds are usually at full currency risk, particularly because of the danger of currency devaluation.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, International Investing, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
