<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-The Mutual Fund Leap of Faith</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-The Mutual Fund Leap of Faith</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Net asset value is no guarantee. Sometimes it's simply management's best guess, and sometimes management is wrong.<p>By Gerald Perritt<p>If you're like most mutual fund investors, you check the progress of your investments once or twice a week in the business pages. You head straight for the NAV -- or net asset value -- column and quickly calculate how much your net worth has risen or fallen since you last checked.<p>But investors in open-ended mutual funds are sorely mistaken if they believe that all funds' NAV listings are just as reliable as closing prices on the New York or American stock exchanges. The fact is, the determination of a fund's net asset value can be much more subjective and malleable than most investors know. What you see may not be what you'd get if you were to sell your shares. <p>The soundness of a fund's NAV depends on a couple of things: the method used by fund management to price lesser-known securities and the ease with which those securities can be sold, or liquidity. <p>Few investors realize how much leeway a fund's management has when it comes to valuing lesser-known securities. Similarly, few realize how large a role liquidity plays in their fund's valuation. With thinly traded securities, there's no telling what price a fund manager's sell order will fetch if it disrupts the market in that security. An illiquid security, if sold, could very likely trade at a price much lower than its value in the prospectus.<p>Daily share prices of open-ended funds are determined, in most instances, by the value of the funds' holdings at the close of a day's trading. Net asset value is calculated by adding the value of all the securities held in a fund, including cash and other assets, subtracting liabilities, and dividing the remainder by the number of shares outstanding. Since these are the prices used for share purchases and redemptions, mutual fund managers take great pains to assure they are statistically correct. <p>Each security that trades daily on a national stock or bond exchange and is held by a fund is valued at the last sale price. Those are the easy ones. Securities that don't trade during the course of a business day are trickier; they're valued at the mean between the then-current closing bid and offer prices. Less liquid securities are the toughest of all. These are valued "at a fair value determined in good faith by the board of directors." <p>Should you be worried that your fund's net asset value may be subject to interpretation by management? Not if you own a fund that trades shares of big, public companies or highly liquid securities, such as Treasurys. These markets can absorb large buy and sell orders without incurring much, if any, disruption.<p>But investors in several other types of funds -- particularly those that invest in municipal bonds, thinly traded over-the-counter stocks, and emerging overseas markets -- should be aware that their holdings' values may not be all that they seem. <p>This point is worth making now, given the markets' negative reaction to rising interest rates. As large numbers of investors race to exit mutual funds, managers are forced to liquidate their holdings. Without a lot of buyers on hand to even out supply and demand, prices decline, sometimes severely. Net asset values in funds holding less-liquid securities are most vulnerable.<p>Such liquidity troubles have creamed fund investors before. Back in 1989 and 1990, junk-bond funds took it on the chin when the liquidity in that market all but dried up. This was largely the result of the demise of Drexel Burnham Lambert, the biggest junk-bond underwriter and market maker. As junk-bond prices began to fall, investors headed for the door. With the major market maker basically out of business, fund managers had to sell their bonds into a woefully illiquid market. This drove already depressed prices down further, and the snowball started rolling. <p>How bad did it get? Through the first nine months of 1990, not one of the 20 high-yield funds I studied had a return in the plus column. The investment objective of all 20 funds was to earn high income. The best any of them did during the period was a loss of 1.8 percent, turned in by the <a name="FUND:OPPHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/OPPHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oppenheimer High Yield Fund</b></a>. Compared with the others, Oppenheimer's results were standout: <a name="FUND:ABUSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ABUSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alliance's Bond Fund High Yield Portfolio</b></a> lost 15.6 percent, <a name="FUND:MHITX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MHITX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MFS Lifetime High Income Fund</b></a> was down 11.9 percent, and Pacific Horizon High Yield Bond Fund lost 13.7 percent. <p>Junk bonds came roaring back to life a few years later. But the example illustrates what can happen to the net asset values of funds when liquidity in a market disappears or when sellers far outnumber buyers. <p>Today the worry is that few fund shareholders realize to what extent their funds may hold securities that are not exceedingly liquid. We're not talking exotic securities here. Neither are we talking about the increasing numbers of funds that invest in illiquid private placements (see "Easy In, Uneasy Out," Worth, December/January 1994). <p>Municipal bonds, small-cap stocks, and emerging-market equities have all become wildly popular with investors in recent years. There are now 185 international stock funds available to investors, up from 100 three years ago. Aggressive growth funds that invest in small-cap stocks, one of which I have run since 1988, have exploded in number recently, from 186 to 233 since 1990. Municipal-bond funds have also been on a tear: According to a report by Moody's Investors Service, there are 1,027 tax-exempt funds available to investors today, up from 208 in 1984. Thirty-two billion dollars flowed into these funds in the first nine months of 1993, a 54 percent gain over the same period in 1992.<p>Unfortunately, all three areas are ripe for liquidity problems, which could translate into unpleasant NAV surprises for fundholders.<p>Take thinly traded over-the-counter stocks, for instance. Again, stocks and bonds that rarely trade are valued at the average of their bid price -- what you'd get if you sold -- and offer or asked price -- what you'd pay to buy. But this methodology can produce highly misleading fund NAVs. In early March, before the market started to trade down, I priced my small-cap fund's shares two ways -- based on then-current bid and offer prices. Pricing at the bid -- the only side of the market a seller is concerned about -- caused the NAV to decline by 1.5 percent. Pricing it at the offer raised its price by 1.9 percent. That's a 3.4 percent spread -- a sizable swing -- between existing bid and offer prices. And that spread was calculated on a typical day in the markets, not during a market break.<p>There's another reason investors in funds holding obscure OTC stocks should be concerned about what their shares might fetch. Market makers in these types of securities usually limit the size of the orders they will accept for execution. An OTC dealer is obligated to accept no more than a 100-share order at the bid or offer price. Putting out an order to sell 50,000 or 100,000 shares -- both typical fund holdings -- would cause current bids to plunge.<p>Even when markets are calm, OTC stocks trade with more volatility than other stocks. A story in Forbes last August compared the average trade-to-trade percentage price changes on stocks traded on the New York Stock Exchange, the American Stock Exchange, and Nasdaq during the course of one month. Prices changed, from trade to trade, on average 0.5 percent on the New York, 1.1 percent on the Amex, and almost 2 percent on Nasdaq. <p>Many shareholders found out about the disruption that results when you sell into an illiquid market during the stock crash of 1987. Over-the-counter market makers, under extreme stress from heavy selling, walked away from their bids. <p>Buyers, believe it or not, also found a hostile environment during the market meltdown. The fund manager of a smallish Noddings Convertible securities limited partnership tried to buy some thinly traded convertible bonds when the market was tanking, only to have the offer prices substantially increased before his orders could be filled. <p>Such stories show that many bids and asks on the OTC market were bogus. And fund-share prices based on these quotations were bogus as well. <p>Of course, certain funds have more to worry about than others when it comes time to sell. Funds holding bushels of stocks that trade infrequently will find themselves in hot water if faced with mass redemptions. <p>One fund holding large numbers of obscure or thinly traded stocks is the Transamerica Capital Growth Fund, previously the Capital Appreciation Fund. Transamerica has returned almost 19 percent since its inception in 1985, but it lost almost 5 percent in the first quarter of this year. The fund's June 1993 annual prospectus showed that 28.6 percent of its $84 million in assets were securities too obscure to be listed in a recent Standard & Poor's stock guide. By contrast, in the <a name="FUND:ALSCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ALSCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alger Small Capitalization Portfolio</b></a>, another small-company fund, 3 percent of its assets could not be found in the S&P guide. <p>Not being listed in the S&P guide doesn't mean a company isn't worth owning, but it does mean that its shares trade much less actively and are therefore less liquid than those of other companies that are listed by S&P. <p>Municipal bonds also present liquidity problems. These bonds are rarely traded; historically they've been sold to investors as very long-term holds, to be put away in the lockbox. Thus, the difference between their bid prices and their asked prices tend to be wide. With wide spreads, it's all the more likely that the actual price to buy or sell a block of bonds will be significantly different from the quotation supplied to figure NAV.<p>To try to minimize the huge spreads, some municipal-bond issuers are listing their bonds on the New York Stock Exchange. But these listings will be limited to only higher-quality issues. <p>"Fund portfolio prices may be distorted," Moody's analyst Stephen Schoepke warns, "because the market is too thin to obtain a representative range of price bids." Investors recently got a taste of how distorted prices of municipal bonds can get. For the month of March, Vanguard's long-term insured municipal-bond fund declined 4.5 percent; its intermediate-term muni funds dropped 2.1 percent. As interest rates increase further, more losses will result. As Schoepke says, "Mutual funds may not have adequate information to accurately price their portfolios."<p>Investors' blooming love affairs with emerging-market stocks also raise liquidity concerns. First of all, these markets lack the regulatory and surveillance sophistication of U.S. markets. Thus the possibility of price manipulation is high. But more important, most equity markets in developing nations are so tiny that minor changes in investor sentiment can send share prices reeling. <p>For example, the entire market capitalization of the Indian stock market is roughly $72 billion. But the assets held by just two offshore, open-end funds that invest in Indian stocks -- the India Opportunities Fund and the Indian Investment Co. fund -- total almost $500 million. When the managers running those funds want to dump shares, they're going to have trouble drumming up buyers. <p>What about the so-called "other" securities that can find their way into fund portfolios? Valuing these is a real crapshoot. The fund's board of directors has sole discretion to set the security's price for NAV purposes. Although the directors are charged with determining a "fair value in good faith," there are few guidelines for establishing such mechanisms. If no secondary market exists for a security, fund managers may set the price where they wish. <p>To protect yourself from unpleasant NAV surprises, consult your fund's most recent prospectus. If it is a small-cap or aggressive-growth fund, check the holdings for companies whose names you recognize. If the unknowns -- loosely defined as stocks that don't show up in an S&P stock guide -- total 10 percent or more of the portfolio, your fund may have liquidity problems.<p>As for municipal-bond and emerging-market funds, liquidity issues are a fact of life. Just don't bank on your net asset value being stable when the fund is faced with throngs of sellers. <p>It would be helpful to investors if fund managers created a way of measuring a fund's liquidity and then published it in their prospectuses. But this won't likely happen unless we have a big break in stock or bond markets. <p>During fair and orderly markets, there's little cause for liquidity concerns -- the price of one transaction should give you a reasonable estimate of the price of the next. But when markets are disorderly, your mutual fund investments may not be worth what you think.
---------------
Gerald Perritt is head of Investment Information Services, a money management firm in Chicago. He also publishes the Mutual Fund Letter and Investment Horizons.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
