<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Mortgage Wars</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Mortgage Wars</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
When morgage lenders battle over market share, home buyers find great deals.<p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>Ready! Aim! Fire! The mortgage industry is going to war, and it's a fight that will benefit consumers. Examples: In the 12 states in which it operates, customers of Home Savings of America can now put down as little as 5 percent on a $300,000 mortgage, and Home Savings will waive the normally required mortgage insurance. Its rates start as low as 6.6 percent.<p>In Greenbrae, California, a mortgage lender recently offered a broker at Pacific Guarantee Mortgage a rebate of one full point--that's 1 percent of the mortgage loan amount, or $2,000 on a $200,000 loan--to get the firm's business. Other lenders have offered rebates of a quarter point to a half point.<p>In Fairfax, Virginia, George Mason Bank is offering home-equity credit lines at prime minus half a point for a line of $50,000 or more. The annual rate: 5.5 percent on owner-occupied homes.<p>Wait a second... Aren't these developments contrary to the recent news about rising interest rates?<p>Well, yes, they are. Back on October 15, 1993, the average interest rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage was just 6.83 percent, according to HSH Associates of Butler, New Jersey, which tracks mortgage rates nationally. By March 18, the rate was 7.85 percent, and the prognosis is for more of the same. Rates on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages will be 8.1 percent by the end of the year, predicts David Lereah, chief economist of the Mortgage Bankers Association.<p>Yet at the same time, mortgage lenders have stepped up efforts to gain, or hold on to, market share. They know that rising rates inevitably will slow new financings and bring an end to the boom that saw more than 10 million mortgages refinanced in 1992 and 1993. So they are striking back with a sale just in time for spring, the traditional peak of the home-buying season.<p>Unlike the deals that got the savings and loans into trouble in the 1980s, the mortgage industry this time around is trying to practice restraint. Thus, most of the bargains that lenders are offering focus on upfront terms rather than on cutting interest rates on 30-year loans. Lenders are stretching out payments and reducing the amount buyers must put down --in some cases, to zero. Lenders have slashed introductory rates and then slashed them again. Points, the cost of getting a new mortgage, have in many cases disappeared. <p>Comparing all the new packages is time consuming, but certainly worth the effort. The skirmishing in the mortgage industry has also given borrowers more leverage. "Today's consumer is much more in the driver's seat than he has been in recent years," says Keith Gumbinger, an analyst with HSH Associates. "Especially if you have triple-A credit, you should ask, 'What can you do for me that's better?' Play one lender off against another. Realize that six months ago, there were 500 people at the lender's door ready to write contracts, and now there are only four or five."<p>Before plunging into the complicated task of comparing mortgage options, buyers should keep a few things in mind about the state of today's real estate market. Yes, home-sales activity has picked up, but clearly, housing prices haven't yet run away from would-be buyers. So there's reason for patience. Nationwide, the median price of existing homes rose just 3 percent last year, to $106,800. The median cost of a new home crept up 3.7 percent to $126,000. Prices will move up another 3.5 percent and 5 percent, respectively, in 1994, predicts Lereah.<p>Of course, national numbers don't always apply. In hot markets like Richland/Kennewickasco, Washington (up 21 percent in 1993); Green Bay, Wisconsin (up 11.8 percent); Salt Lake City/Ogden (up 11 percent); and Boise, Idaho (up 10 percent), it may seem as if prices are leaping 3 percent a month. In Los Angeles (down 7.1 percent in 1993); Orange County, California (down 6 percent); and Hartford, Connecticut (down 4.1 percent), the bottom, apparently, hasn't yet been glimpsed.<p>A potential borrower who hasn't been in the market for a decade faces a bewildering array of new mortgage sources. For example, in 1987 the U.S. survived with only 7,500 mortgage brokers. By the end of 1993 there were 18,000. And in contrast to ten years ago, the industry is a lot less local. In 1984, S&Ls, by and large small local lenders, controlled 53.5 percent of all mortgage lending for one- to four-unit properties. But their share eroded to 19 percent by the end of 1993. Aggressive mortgage bankers, such as Countrywide Funding, which often operate on a national rather than local scale, now control 52 percent of the overall mortgage market. All those lenders mean that no market is too small for cutthroat competition.<p>"I was surprised how badly the lenders seemed to want my business," says a Maryland man who recently closed on a new home. He shouldn't have been; the battle lines are clearly visible--especially in realtors' offices.<p>"Every week now, 50 different lenders try to call on me," says Joan Reilly, manager of Coldwell Banker Realty Pros in Potomac, Maryland. "They're getting more aggressive about offering gourmet lunches, setting up cocktail parties, or just stopping by to drop off food."<p>And, of course, cheap money. "If Countrywide notices on a certain day of the month that we haven't done our normal amount of volume, they'll be on the phone saying, 'We miss your business,' and offering rebates," says Bob da Costa, president of Indian River Mortgage, a Vero Beach, Florida, lender. <p>Smart home buyers should take advantage of all this. "These days," says John Lucas, vice president with ARCS Mortgage, a Bank of New York company headquartered in Calabasas, California, "everything is negotiable." But everything is much more negotiable with some lenders. Generally speaking, it's easier to wheel and deal with mortgage bankers and mortgage brokers than with large banks and S&Ls.<p>Adjustable-rate mortgages, or ARMs, are a place, however, where S&Ls are likely to be aggressive. Surviving S&Ls see rising rates and the end of the refinancing frenzy as their best chance to regain market share for ARMs, traditionally their strongest product. Adjustable mortgage rates are likely to stay artificially low this year, and the spread between adjustable and fixed mortgage rates has widened by an average of more than three eighths of a percentage point. <p>Borrowers looking for a bargain on rates might also check out home-equity loans. During 1992-93, home-equity lending lost market share to refinancings. In response, lenders have actually dropped home-equity rates. Instead of offering credit lines at the once prevailing rate of prime plus one and a half percentage points, many lenders are now dangling lines at prime.<p>The industry has also introduced a crop of exotic mortgage options designed to pull in business without cutting profit margins too severely. Some of these may actually be great opportunities for specific home buyers.<p>For example, a 40-year mortgage, a product just reintroduced in many markets, makes a home slightly more affordable in the short term by reducing the monthly mortgage payment. But the added cost over the life of the loan makes sense only for buyers who don't plan on staying put long and need the extra cash flow now. The monthly payment on a $200,000, 30-year, 7.75 percent fixed-rate mortgage is $1,433. For a 40-year deal it's $1,353. Over the life of a 40-year mortgage, however, the home buyer will pay $133,000 more. <p>Borrowers who want to keep their monthly payments down might also consider another alternative, the delayed first-adjustment ARM. These can lower the initial interest rate by 0.375 to 0.5 percentage points. Then, after a specified period, the fixed rate on this mortgage becomes adjustable. For example, a borrower might pay a fixed jumbo mortgage rate of 7.375 percent for ten years, after which the interest rate becomes adjustable at one-year intervals. On a $275,000 loan, using this alternative (called a ten-one because it looks like a fixed mortgage for ten years and then becomes an adjustable-rate mortgage with a rate that changes once a year) could save $13,800 over the first ten years--a great deal for a home buyer who can predict when the family will be moving on to another house.<p>A no-equity refinancing is another option that may be a good deal for the millions of homeowners who have the worst of both worlds: a high-rate mortgage and a house that has declined in value. Many of these homeowners lack the 20 percent equity stake traditionally required to refinance.<p>No-equity refinancings cost about one point more than prevailing 30-year rates, and while refinancing at 8.75 percent isn't everyone's idea of a great offer, it might be a godsend for people stuck with higher-rate mortgages.<p>Interest rates aren't the only rates that matter. Income taxes need to get factored into any decision about how big a mortgage to take, how little to put down, and what rate is best. Rising income-tax rates mean that carrying tax-deductible debt, such as a mortgage, costs less than it did last year. Making a somewhat smaller down payment makes sense, since the value of the mortgage deduction is greater this year. A buyer can actually afford a little more house because of changes in the tax code. Those same changes slightly diminish the appeal of 10-, 15-, and 20-year mortgages. But the tax code still hasn't made a 40-year mortgage a good deal for most home buyers. <p>No matter how how many numbers you've crunched, don't forget to check out the lender. Doing business with an obscure outfit offering a seemingly miraculous package may be asking for trouble. One quick way to check on a lender is to call your state banking department to find out about any recent complaints. (Checking out a mortgage broker is more difficult in the 13 states that don't require a broker to obtain a license.) Once the lender survives this initial screen, ask for the names and phone numbers of satisfied clients. Then roll up your sleeves and get ready to drive a hard bargain.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Real Estate Investing, Homeowner, Mortgages, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

