<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Want to Break Up With Your Fund?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Want to Break Up With Your Fund?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Finally, strategies for selling get some attention <p>By Jim Melloan<p>The topic of when to sell a mutual fund has been given nowhere near the amount of ink as when to buy one. But the subject is slowly coming to the forefront of public consciousness as more investors conclude that "buy and hold" might not be the wisdom of the ages after all. <p>Just as there are a variety of theories on when and which funds to buy, so are there numerous strategies for selling. To some specialists in this area, maintaining a predetermined structure of asset allocation is paramount. As H. Lynn Hopewell, a financial planner in Falls Church, Virginia, puts it, "We know that by combining different kinds of asset classes we reduce risk. So if one fund suddenly comes to dominate the portfolio because it's done so well, to stick with it would be to increase the risk of the portfolio substantially."That, of course, is the opposite of what investors are trying to do. So, says Hopewell, "Always control for risk--sell off those suckers and get your portfolio back into balance."<p>Then there's Jay Schabacker, editor of the Mutual Fund Investing newsletter, who says he's never been that precise on his allocations. He also says that his thoughts on proper diversification change fairly often anyway. His advice is "Never sell a winner unless it looks like it's not going to become a continuing winner." It's certainly hard to dispute that counsel, vague though it may be. <p>Daniel Weiner, editor of the Independent Adviser for Vanguard Investors, suggests that investors should stick with whatever style they're comfortable with. But he also cautions that selling off hot performers too often will result in a lot of taxable gains that are not offset with losses. Annual adjustments to rebalance a portfolio should be sufficient, Weiner believes.<p>Some of the most important considerations for selling a fund have to do with the changing needs and feelings of the investor. Someone approaching retirement may wish to sell aggressive funds and put the money into more conservative investments. Sometimes it's time to sell a fund simply because you need the cash--to buy a house, say. Taxes can provide another motive. Sheldon Jacobs, publisher of the No-Load Fund Investor, points out that taking a loss on a fund and switching to another can let the government share in the loss by providing an income-tax deduction. And it may be appropriate occasionally to correct for past overzealousness. Weiner cites the case of the investor who is starting to lose sleep over that stalled or sinking emerging-markets fund he excitedly bought a year ago in the midst of a meteoric rise. It may have been too aggressive an investment for him in the first place and not worth the continuous nail-biting. Readers have also written Weiner concerning their 18-fund portfolios. A number that high, he tells them, is more appropriate for a basket of stocks than a portfolio of mutual funds. It almost certainly indicates unnecessary duplication of asset classes, which means it's time to simplify. <p>Then there are times when it's necessary to react to changes in performance, personnel, or the overall economy. Experts are nearly unanimous in warning against selling a fund based on as few as one or two down quarters. The pros further agree that comparisons with benchmarks like the S&P 500 index are less valid than comparisons with other funds in the same asset class. If a fund goes for a whole year underperforming its brethren with similar objectives, it's time to "start scratching your head and find out why," says Hopewell. The consensus is that two full years of inferior performance are enough to force a switch. Also, reports Jacobs, net redemptions "are almost always symptomatic of serious problems."<p>Another consideration: Is your fund still playing its original role in your portfolio? A fund may undergo a metamorphosis into something with a style or objectives different from those for which it was originally bought. For example, a successful small-cap fund may find itself with more assets than it can prudently invest in small-cap companies and so turn into what's really a mid-cap fund. <p>Or something more radical may be going on, such as a wholesale move from utilities into health care. Then it's time to perk up and decide whether you want to get back to a fund that represents your intended asset class. Here your investment personality will come into play again: While Hopewell advocates getting rid of a fund that is "no longer behaving like it's supposed to," Schabacker says, "Sometimes I want a fund to change if this world is changing. The funds that don't change their style I don't think will do very well."<p>A change in managers deserves attention, too. Sometimes a new manager has been groomed by his predecessor and will carry on with similar objectives and a smooth transition; other times a novice or someone with radically different views will take the helm. Whatever the signals, it's usually okay to give the new manager a little time. Says Jacobs, "You want to see what the new person does. Even if the new person is incompetent, it takes him a while to screw it up."<p>Everyday nuisance-type problems, like late or inaccurate statements or dividend checks, may be a sign of overall incompetence at a firm and provide sufficient cause to switch. Differences in expense ratios are generally too piddling to worry about except in the lowest-yielding funds, such as money market or tax-free bond funds. "I'm looking at Fidelity Pacific Basin, which has a 1.8 percent expense ratio, on average [over the past three years]," says Schabacker. "So what? Because of the economic activity, they're going to make 20 to 30 percent. Expense ratios are not the buy or sell decision makers." <p>Finally, there's the economy--where you think it's going--and whether you want to be more active. Most experts agree that trying to time the stock market makes little sense. Jumping in and out as an investor rarely pays off. But that doesn't mean investors can't be more aggressive when the future looks bright, and more conservative when things look a little dim. Pros like Schabacker counsel investors to "get to know how the economy and inflation affect future markets, and you'll be a winner." Over time, though, the most reliable strategy is to stick with a solidly diversified portfolio, secure in the knowledge that, as Hopewell puts it, "every dog will have its day."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Fund Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

