	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-House of Horrors</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-House of Horrors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Buying a newly built house today requires an ally<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>The term caveat emptor couldn't apply more to any class of consumer than to the people who build their own homes. "A crew of misfits, ex-felons, and drunkards labored on alternate Tuesdays to build our house while we stood by in horror," wrote Alan and Denise Fields in a book about the home they built in Monument, Colorado, in 1991. Adds George Birmingham Jr., a home inspector in Durham, North Carolina: "Probably 75 percent of homes built today are built badly." <p>The flight from quality in new-home construction places buyers in a precarious position these days. They're not only making the biggest investment of their lives, but they're also entrusting their family's comfort and safety to people who may not care as much as they should. "Thirty years ago, contractors had strict standards and put their reputation on the line with each house," says Birmingham. "Nowadays, many just subcontract the whole thing out and never look back." <p>But there's a way people building a new home can protect themselves: Hire an expert to sit on your side of the table. Independent inspectors can help homeowners avoid some of the most prevalent problems. These include shoddy work (improper site grading, incorrect installation of materials), ignorance of local building codes (walls too thin, stair clearances too low), and outright fraud. "Contractors substitute cheaper products all the time in places where the owner can't see them," says Peter Hollander, director of operations at the Portland, Maine, office of Criterium Engineers, a national home-inspection firm. A home buyer who pays for a moisture barrier in the exterior walls, for example, may get only felt paper, or nothing. Who's to know once the siding is up? <p>Homeowners need someone with a solid construction and engineering background but without ties to anyone involved with building the home to visit the site at key times: after the lot is graded, before the foundation is poured, after the rough framing is done, and after each subcontractor has finished. Most inspectors who provide this service charge $100 to $200 per visit, a cheap price to pay for peace of mind.<p>Some builders bar independent inspectors from their sites, while others try to influence the buyer's choice of whom to hire. Even those who say they are willing to work with an inspector of the owner's choosing sometimes "forget" to mention that the foundation is ready to be poured or the framing is done until the construction covers over the work. (Some contractors even try to convince home buyers to rely on the construction insurance. But since policies are bought and paid for by the builders, insurers have little incentive to see problems from the homeowner's side. "Some insurers deny practically every claim," Hollander says.) <p>Consequently, it's wise to engage the inspector before signing any construction contract or even making the final choice of a builder. "As a protection, spell out in the contract when inspections are to occur and the penalty each time your inspector is not notified," Hollander says. It's also not a bad idea to require the builder to get the inspector's approval before proceeding to the next level of construction.<p>Creating the right incentives can also help manage the contractor. Builders who offer financing usually have arranged with a lender to give them access to construction funds without "bothering" the buyers. "I have seen several builders draw out the money but never do any work," says Birmingham. Rather than financing through the builder, buyers should arrange their own construction loans so they can control when the contractor is paid. But controlling the purse strings provides little security if the buyers have no idea whether the work has been done properly. They still need an independent inspector in their corner, advising them when the builder deserves to be paid.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Real Estate Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
