<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-When to Use Sector Funds</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-When to Use Sector Funds</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>They can boost returns or serve as a hedging tool <p>By Robert W. Casey<p>The best-performing mutual fund? Odds are this quarter, like most quarters, it will turn out be a sector fund.<p>The worst one? Probably another sector fund. Maybe even one that was a stellar performer a few quarters back.<p>And that's the knock on these funds. Critics see them as a collection of shooting stars, rocketing to the top of the charts one quarter, plummeting the next. On average, sector funds seem to go nowhere. So why take the risk?<p>Let's acknowledge right here that sector funds are not CDs. Most are set up as nondiversified investment companies, meaning that they can__and often do__put more than 5 percent of their portfolios in one stock. They also concentrate on a single industry or economic sector. If it tanks, so does the fund. The result: A double dose of risk that's simply not appropriate as a stand-alone investment.<p>But what if you already have a well-diversified portfolio? In that case, sector investing can add horsepower to your returns. "It's essentially more juice for your dollar," says Ken Enright, portfolio manager for MFS Managed Sectors, a fund that rotates among a handful of promising sectors. They also can be used as a hedging tool.
Sector funds have been around for years, but sector investing came of age in 1981 when Fidelity introduced the first batch of its Select funds at the dawn of the bull market. Since then, the number of sector funds has mushroomed to a recent total of 176, with about $45 billion in assets, according to Morningstar Inc., the mutual fundtracking service.<p>While the sector-fund ranks always include big winners and big losers, investors on average have done well by them recently. For example, the average return for the domestic sector funds tracked by Morningstar was 28.8 percent for the year ending December 3, 1993. Compare this to a 7.8 percent return for the S&P 500.<p>How can you make sector investing work for you? Alfred M. Waddell, an investment advisor in Memphis, watches for sectors that start to perform better than the rest of the market, then looks for fundamental factors that will sustain the trend. He saw these factors in 1991 in regional banks. "If the Federal Reserve was going to get the economy healthy again, it had to get the banks healthy first," says Waddell. "We thought the regional-bank funds would continue to benefit from that trend and they did."<p>When you find an attractive sector, don't assume that every fund in that sector will perform similarly. For example, health care funds will perform differently depending on the relative weight they give to pharmaceuticals, biotechnology, and medical-delivery stocks. Another example is utility funds. You might buy one expecting a good yield only to discover that the fund goes for growth by emphasizing telecommunications utility stocks. "There's a tendency to think of sector funds as homogeneous," says Don Phillips, publisher of Morningstar Mutual Funds. "If utilities is in the name, it must be the same as any other utilities fund. But that's not true at all."<p>Before investing in a sector fund, think about how long you'll want to hold it. There's no reason, for example, why a high-quality energy fund such as Vanguard Specialized Energy might not make a good buy-and-hold investment. Yet sector investments are widely viewed as cyclical in nature. That's because the stocks of many industry sectors tend to rise and fall as investors anticipate the expansion and contraction of the economy. <p>Perhaps most importantly, consider how a sector fund will complement your investment portfolio. "The challenge for many investors in the '80s was how to analyze and select one fund," says Phillips. "But for people who already have a couple of funds in their portfolios, the question now is what to add to make it a better mix. And that's where sector funds can fit in very nicely."<p>A small investment in a technology sector fund, for example, can boost your return, says Phillips. On the other hand, adding exposure to sectors that do not move in sync with the market, such as gold or real estate, can reduce overall portfolio risk. "Funds that perhaps you wouldn't want to hold in isolation can be a great addition to an already diversified portfolio," he says.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
