<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Managing the Money Pit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Managing the Money Pit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
If you've lost money on your home, don't sell it<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>Uncle sam doesn't like people who lose money on their homes. And homeowners who don't realize it can end up digging themselves an even deeper hole. "People shouldn't think of residential real estate as an investment," says Kyn Dellinger, president of Bay Area Tax Consultants in San Bruno, California, "because the Internal Revenue Service doesn't view it that way." <p>When a homeowner makes money on the sale of a home, there's no problem. The profit is treated as a capital gain, just like any other investment and is taxed at 28 percent rather than at the owner's individual tax rate, which usually is higher. What's more, a home seller can usually avoid paying any tax at all by rolling the sale proceeds into a new home within two years or by taking a residential capital-gains exclusion (up to $125,000) available to everyone over 55. <p>Losers, however, are treated very differently. When a stock or bond is sold for less than it originally cost, an investor can use that loss to offset other investment income. But when a home sells for less than the owner originally paid, the loss is non-deductible.<p>Sellers who have refinanced to get at some of the equity in their homes are in for an even bigger shock. If the mortgage balance is larger than the sale price, not only is the loss non-deductible, most sellers are resigned to never seeing a penny because the lender has first claim on the sales proceeds. In fact, they'll have to dip into personal savings to make up the difference between the sales proceeds and the mortgage balance. And of course, if they want to buy another home, they also must scrape up enough extra cash to make the new down payment. But it can be quite a shock to find out that not one of these out-of-pocket costs is tax deductible.<p>Simply walking away from the whole mess or halting mortgage payments until the lender forecloses usually isn't a viable solution because the IRS considers such actions to be "sales," with the outstanding mortgage balance becoming the "selling price." In a supreme irony, owners who owe more on their mortgage than they paid for the house are even deemed to have made a profit when they abandon a property or let it slide into foreclosure. "People who refinanced for more than the original purchase price would not only lose their home and their good credit rating but also have to pay tax on the gain from the money they don't pay back," Dellinger says. <p>People stuck with their homes have only two realistic courses of action. They can sell at a loss, write it off to experience, tighten their belts, and move on. Or they can hang on to the property until the real estate market improves and values rebound. <p>From an investment standpoint, the latter is not a bad alternative. With property prices still low and interest rates poised to climb, it's a good time to buy real estate, so it stands to reason it's also a good time to hang on to real estate. Remember, because your investment is your down payment, not the value of the house, even a low rate of inflation will translate into very attractive returns. For example, a $50,000 down payment on a $300,000 house appreciating at 3 percent a year is earning 18 percent a year, tax free. <p>Homeowners who have had to move out (due to a job transfer, for instance) face a more complicated but potentially more lucrative situation. A house enjoys more favorable tax treatment as a rental than as a personal residence. In addition to interest, rental real estate can be depreciated, and other expenses (management fees, utilities paid, brokerage fees, maintenance costs, etc.) can be deducted against income.<p>With the rental market strong in many areas, homeowners who refinance at current low rates may find they can charge close to their monthly mortgage payments. When tax benefits are added in, that can provide a relatively painless way to wait for real estate values to recover. The only drawback is that when a home is rented, the owner's basis in the property is adjusted to fair market value at the time of conversion, if this is lower than the original purchase price, for the purposes of calculating depreciation. <p>But with rental property, the original purchase price less depreciation is still used to figure the capital gain or loss from sale. Thus, there will be no taxable gain if the home is sold for more than the value at the time of conversion to rental but for less than the original price. As usual, however, none of the loss is deductible.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Homeowner, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
		<a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  
		<a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  
		<a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
		<font size=-1><i>&copy; 1996 Capital Publishing Limited
		Partnership</i></font>
		

		</center>
	
	</td>
