<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Easy In, Uneasy Out</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Easy In, Uneasy Out</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Fund managers, reaching for higher returns, are buying restricted securities. Anybody remember what happened the last time they did this?<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Conventional wisdom says that it takes roughly one generation before folks forget a scandal. What seems unforgettable today--Charles Keating's theft of millions from his unsuspecting bank depositors, for example--is soon time out of mind, destined only to be repeated some years hence. Time heals all wounds, after all; even those created by Wall Street scalawags and schemers. <p>Conventional wisdom, so often wrong, is right on about this. Investors' memories are shorter than a firecracker's fuse. Otherwise, why would no one be concerned about the new trend among mutual fund managers to buy restricted securities? More and more of them are doing it today, say our sources, in the search for higher yields and "cheaper" stocks. <p>Restricted securities are known as such because they trade relatively infrequently among institutional investors only and are not, therefore, easily dumpable. Restricted securities include stocks or bonds issued by private or foreign companies; they also may be stocks and bonds issued by well-known public companies but not registered for sale to individual investors. <p>The Securities and Exchange Commission relaxed the rules surrounding the sale of restricted stocks in 1990, and since then the number of issues has exploded. In the first half of 1993 alone, $73.2 billion was raised in private placements, an increase of 35 percent over the first six months of 1992. Companies like to float restricted stock or bond issues because they're a cheaper way to raise money. Registering securities for sale to individuals--in an initial public offering, for example--is a costly process. <p>Institutional investors have eagerly bought up these so-called private placements of restricted securities in recent years. Because issuers of these securities avoid registration costs, they pass some of these savings along to investors: Bonds or preferred stocks usually carry slightly higher yields than comparable securities, and stocks typically trade at a discount to freely swappable issues. In an overheated stock and bond market like ours, good values are harder to come by; so fund managers go off the beaten path to try to find them. One thing they found: Restricted securities.<p>As long as stock and bond prices are generally rising--as they have been recently--restricted securities are not highly risky because they are in demand among buyers. The only trouble comes when stock and bond prices start to fall and buyers start to evaporate. Then, restricted stocks decline in price further and faster than their more easily traded brethren. This is because the holders of these securities--institutions like mutual funds or brokerage firms--are limited in whom they can sell to: The buyer must be another institution. Sure, the institutional market is a huge one, but it is still smaller and more limited than the entire market of stocks and bonds that trade free and clear of restrictions. The fewer the buyers, the more difficulty the seller has unloading a position.<p>The last time fund managers were buying heavily into restricted stock proved how disastrous this can be. The year was 1968, exactly one generation ago. It was a period eerily like ours, in that investors were positively tripping over themselves to buy shares in hot mutual funds. Fund managers were becoming celebrities, and money flooded fund coffers. <p>One of the men of the moment was Fred Mates, a fund manager who had opened the Mates Investment Fund in August 1967. Mates was one of the "Three Freds"--Fred Alger and Fred Carr were the other two--famous for their aggressive and winning fund-management styles. (Of the three Freds, only Alger remains in the fund-management business today; Carr was disgraced by the fall of his junk-bond-laden Executive Life Insurance Co., and Mates died in 1982.) <p>Right out of the gate in '68, Mates's fund was a star performer; assets under management increased almost 100 percent in its first year of business, forcing Mates to close the fund to new investors. In September 1968, Mates bought 300,000 restricted shares of Omega Equities, a smallish conglomerate, in a private transaction. Omega was trading over-the-counter at around $24 at the time, but because the shares Mates was buying were unregistered, he paid only $3.25. A bargain. <p>Realizing that his Omega shares could not be sold, Mates valued them in his portfolio not at the $24 price that fully registered shares would command, but at a discounted price of $16 a share. Still, that gave the fund's net asset value a huge instantaneous profit of 500 percent in the Omega holding alone. Mates Fund assets, thanks in part to the Omega investment, were up 168 percent for the year. Shareholders were thrilled.<p>Mates was not alone in buying restricted stock. The late John Brooks recounted the tale in his splendid book The Go-Go Years: "The startling thing is not that Mates did it, but that it was being done all the time in 1968, by mutual funds and hedge funds...."<p>Disaster struck when the SEC halted trading in Omega Equities that December. Unable to liquidate his position in the stock, Mates suspended redemptions of his fund's shares. Investors were trapped. When they were finally allowed out of the fund six months later, Omega's stock was 50 cents a share, down 85 percent from Mates's original discounted price. The fund manager, up to that time a hero to the investing world, became an outcast.<p>That was then. A generation later, investing in restricted shares is back in vogue. <p>How can you tell if your fund is getting in on the restricted stock or bond act? Most funds have steered clear of investing in illiquid securities until now and are precluded from buying them by their own investment rules. If a fund manager changes his strategy to include investing in these issues, he must first ask for approval from shareholders. If your fund is one of those interested in purchasing restricted or, as they are sometimes called, Rule 144a securities, a discussion of this change in investment policies must come up for a vote in your fund's annual proxy statement. <p>Such a change was made last May by the <a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a>, a $1.3 billion (assets) fund that invests in mostly bonds or preferred stock for income-oriented investors. Its shareholders approved the move into restricted issues and, four months later, the fund's management had invested almost 5 percent of its assets in unregistered bonds or preferred stocks. Eric Ryback, manager of the fund, says he likes restricted securities because they carry yields that are 1.5 percent to 2 percent higher than comparable, liquid issues. <p>Lindner Dividend is a top fund. It was ranked number one among medium-term funds in last month's Worth mutual fund guide, in part for its stellar historic returns: up an average 14.5 percent in each of the past ten years. What's troubling is that its management, eager to maintain those high returns, believes it must turn to more exotic securities, thereby increasing its risk level. <p>Soon to follow suit is the Lindner Fund, a $1.4 billion (assets) growth fund that has had an enviable average annual return of 13 percent in the past five years. In its proxy dated September, fund comanager Ryback asked shareholders to approve changes in the fund's investment objectives to permit investments in restricted securities.<p>Ryback, 41, who has been comanaging the Lindner Fund since 1984, expects shareholders to approve the change in objectives for the fund. As for the problems that a down market might bring to his illiquid holdings, Ryback says he has no worries. "There's a market for [restricted stock]," he says. "With the explosion of mutual funds there is no shortage of buyers."<p>If shareholders in the Lindner Fund approve the change, its management will be allowed to invest up to 25 percent of the fund's assets in restricted securities. Interestingly, this is quite a bit more than what the SEC suggests fund managers buying illiquid securities should limit themselves to. When it relaxed the rules on trading in restricted securities among institutional investors three years ago, the SEC said that mutual funds should invest no more than 10 percent of assets in "illiquid assets." <p>Ryback says that the types of restricted shares he'll be investing in shouldn't be considered "illiquid"; therefore he can justify his 25-percent-of-assets limit. "They trade just about every day. We have sold large blocks; we're not worried," he says. Still, they are restricted securities not listed on a securities exchange and can only be bought and sold by institutions. This limits the universe of buyers available to someone who might want to sell a restricted stock.<p>Part of the reason Ryback sounds so unconcerned is that a computerized quotation system has been developed--called the PORTAL Market--which acts as a kind of clearing system for the trading of restricted securities among institutional investors. Portal provides greater liquidity to investors in restricted shares than existed in 1968. But no amount of computerized quotation systems can prevent a free fall in stock or bond prices when panicky sellers outnumber buyers.<p>Maybe there won't ever be another free fall in stock or bond prices. Maybe investors won't again experience the horror of watching their mutual funds' shares plunge in value because no buyers can be found for their restricted securities. Maybe this time the bubble won't burst.<p>Gerald Perritt, a Chicago-based small-cap stock-fund manager and editor of the newsletter Investment Horizons, isn't so sure. When he saw the change in the Lindner Dividend Fund's prospectus, he advised his newsletter readers to sell the fund's shares. Says Perritt: "Anytime I see a fund manager changing his objectives to fit into the current market environment, I head for the hills."<p>Fred Mates may be dead and gone, but the world should long remember the lessons his shareholders learned way back when. You know what they say about history and being doomed to repeat it. Let the investor beware.<p>Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
