<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Illusions of Grandeur</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Illusions of Grandeur</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Fund companies use tricks to make their returns seem better than they are. Here, some of the popular ones.<p>By Derrick Niederman<p>Everyone knows that mutual funds are sold largely on the strength of their past performance. Never mind that the past isn't prologue in the fund industry. Fund marketers know that good returns have an undeniable appeal to fund shoppers. <p>This puts pressure on fund managers to produce the kind of good numbers that make a fund hot. Nothing wrong with that--good numbers benefit shareholders as well as the fund-management company.<p>Trouble is, the obsession with returns has created an incentive for managers and marketers to take little liberties with their performance, to make it look perhaps even better than it is. For investors, it's helpful to know the tricks the trade uses to dress up results. That way, you can find the unvarnished truth about a fund's numbers.<p>
The Big Return: 
A mutual fund with a big aggregate return over a long time, say 200 percent over ten years, looks pretty good. After all, investors in the fund tripled their money. And dividing 200 percent by ten suggests an annual return of 20 percent, better than the S&P 500's 14.7 percent on average during the period. <p>Those assumptions are way high. Thanks to compounding, 200 percent over ten years represents an annual return of just 11.6 percent. Nothing to be ashamed of, but not 20 percent.<p>This confusion works to the advantage of marketers who advertise big numbers over long periods. They figure that dividing by ten is about as much math as a typical investor is willing to do.They're probably right.<p>Ads for the <a name="FUND:TEPLX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/TEPLX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Templeton Growth Fund</b></a>, for example, state that a $10,000 investment on November 29, 1954, would have been worth $1,844,602 by June 30, 1993. Powerful stuff. Less powerful is the fact that this is a 14.3 percent annual return. It's not misrepresentation--a 14 percent return is sensational if kept up. Still, $1.85 million looks more impressive than 14.3 percent annually ever will.<p>The more woeful the fund's performance, the more likely its performance will be stretched out over many years. Unless you can calculate square roots in your head, ignore the big numbers and look for compounded annual returns.If they're missing from the ads, ask for them when you call for information.<p>
The Ten-Year Drop-Off:
At the end of 1991, the ten-year compound annual return of the <a name="FUND:LOMCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LOMCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CGM Capital Development Fund</b></a> was 25.6 percent. That made it the single best growth fund in the country for that period. But by the end of 1992, that ten-year return dropped to 20.6 percent. Still impressive, but what happened to the extra 5 percent included in the previous year's numbers?<p>The obvious explanation would be that the fund did terribly in 1992. Not so. In 1992, CGM returned 17.5 percent--a little lower than its past annual standard but well ahead of the S&P 500's return of 7.6 percent. What actually happened was that at the end of 1992, the ten-year record no longer included 1982, a year in which the fund rose by 78.9 percent. <p>In this case, reported figures--using the ten-year magic number--do the fund a disservice. Remember, although long-term performance may be the best indicator of a good fund, high returns may be linked to an unusual event or market aberration. Look at the returns for each year. Uniformly good performance is better than a high ten-year figure that came from a few stellar years.<p>
The All-Important Time Period:
If a fund's marketer is clever about the time period he chooses to highlight, he can make a fund look much better than it really is or was. Between late 1990 and late 1992, for example, the five-year returns for almost any equity mutual fund would have been worse than the three-year figures. That's because, while the 1990 numbers included the 1987 crash, 1992's did not. Five-year figures are now safe from these games, since the crash is six years past.<p>Is a fund advertising its performance relative to some arbitrary point in market history?Take a moment to check. For example, as of the end of 1993, three-year return figures will no longer include the recession of 1990, in which the market dropped sharply during the second half. Because the Persian Gulf war rally began in mid-January, 1991 was an unusually good year to invest--but not a representative one. For funds that focus on a particular investment area (over-the-counter, gold, or health-care stocks), the choice of time period can have an even more misleading effect.<p>While we're talking numbers games, a word about percentages: Mutual funds and brokerage firms often brag in their ads about how their managers or analysts have outperformed the market averages. While all claims are vetted for accuracy, careless investors may think the returns more dazzling than they are. <p>In 1992, for example, Smith Barney  reported saying that its analysts' top stock picks for the previous year beat the market by 48 percent. Since the S&P 500 rose 30 percent that year, that meant the firm's picks gained by 44 percent.<p>Most investors would think that was just fine. So it is. But some, in a moment of lassitude, might think the wizards at Smith Barney had beaten the market by 48 percentage points--producing a 78 percent return--rather than 48 percent. Which would be, as the saying goes, too good to be true. <p>Contributing editor Derrick Niederman is a mathematician turned securities analyst.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
