<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Bond Funds on Steroids</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Bond Funds on Steroids</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Today's highest-yielding funds may look muscular, but many are hooked on risk.<p>By Gregory Millman<p>June 25 was a black day for investors in Hyperion 1999 Term Trust. After months of denial, the bond fund's managers finally came clean. In a letter to the trust's shareholders, they laid out the facts: Hyperion's investors had lost 15 percent of their assets and could lose more. <p>Why? Because the supposedly conservative bond fund had taken a big risk and lost. In June 1992 its sponsors had raised $521 million by promising investors an 8 percent return at a time when most bond funds were yielding 7 percent. To achieve this boost in performance, the trust's managers had wagered nearly a third of its assets on a rise in interest rates by buying high-risk securities called interest-only strips. Instead, interest rates fell, and the price of the strips did too. As a result, for every $10 invested in June 1992, investors held shares worth just $8.38 on August 9, 1993. On top of that loss in principal, the fund's managers cut distributions to 7.25 percent.<p>That's quite a dive for a bond fund that seemed safe. In the words of the Hyperion prospectus, "all securities in which the Trust will invest will be either (i) issued or guaranteed by the United States government or one of its agencies or instrumentalities or (ii) at the time of investment, rated in the highest category by a nationally recognized rating agency--e.g., AAA by Standard & Poor's Corporation or Aaa by Moody's Investor Service, Inc." But these assurances aren't quite what they seem. The prospectus does not explain that government securities can be riskier than junk bonds, that a triple-A rating doesn't mean a thing, nor most significantly that fund yields won't survive the next turn in rates--and neither will an investor's principal.<p>Hyperion 1999 is just one example of what can happen in the current ultracompetitive climate for fixed-income investing. Traditionally, bonds and bond funds have been the choice of conservative investors. But as interest rates on everything from savings accounts to certificates of deposit to bonds themselves have declined, these conservative investors have become ravenous for higher yields. And bond marketers know it. That's why newspaper ads trumpet current yields in big, bold type--even though those yields can change sharply at any time. The financial press plays the same game. Endless lists tout the funds with the highest yield. In August, for example, one national personal-finance magazine touted the superior yield of <a name="FUND:MGIGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/MGIGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Managers Intermediate Mortgage Fund</b></a>. At 12.7 percent, it yielded a third more than the second-best performer in its class.<p>But there's no free lunch in the bond world. Bond-fund managers know that nothing is easier than pumping up a fund's yield with a dose of financial steroids--although that means taking on risk that may lead to long-term financial debility. And at the moment Wall Street is awash in a kind of financial steroid called either a derivative or a synthetic. These are a new kind of security created by the financial revolution of the last decade.<p>Most of the time no one mentions just how risky these investments can be. The article on Managers Intermediate, for example, never said anything about risk--even though more than 20 percent of the fund is invested in derivatives whose value could nose-dive on the next rise in interest rates. The stakes are so high--winning a top ranking in a category for even one quarter of the year can add tens and often hundreds of millions in new assets to a fund--that managers aren't about to stress the downside of their products.<p>But something else is at work here besides predictable human greed. So new are many of these derivatives that none of the managers using them can predict their returns with any certainty. And so complex are these instruments that the average investor can't calculate the risk added to a bond fund by using derivatives. "There is hidden risk in these high yields," says Mark Cunningham of Buck Consultants, a New York firm that analyzes fixed-income securities. "But it takes a fortune in computers just to figure out what these funds are worth."<p>"Embedded in many of the bond funds now are IOs, POs, inverse floaters, some insane investment that no sensible person would buy with their own money if they knew they were really there," says Paul DeRosa, president of Eastbridge Asset Management, an institutional money manager in New York. And DeRosa is one of the people who helped invent the derivative markets while at Citibank in the early 1980s. The situation is so laden with the potential for abuse that one mutual fund expert, Ron Santangelo of Prudential Securities in New York, suggests that investors avoid the highest-yielding funds. "If one fund yields 50 to 100 basis points [100 basis points make up one percentage point] higher than similar funds, that's a flashing red light," he says. Investors in conventional bond funds worry about losing their capital if rates go up. Investors in funds that rely too heavily on derivatives can lose their shirts no matter which way rates head before they even know they are in danger.<p>The old-fashioned way to deliver higher than average yields is simply to buy bonds that don't mature for 10, 20, or 30 years. Long bonds usually pay higher interest than short bonds to compensate investors for the substantial risk that inflation and interest rates could surge before their bonds mature, which would erode the value of their investment. "In 1985 or 1986 we had a lot of money coming into long government-bond funds," says John Rekenthaler of Morningstar, a mutual fund advisory service. "A lot of money came into the funds in '87, and then interest rates rose and scared hell out of those folks." After that experience, brokers started offering shorter-term funds.<p>But interest rates, especially rates on short- and intermediate-term bonds, have fallen steadily during the last five years. "In 1989, the standard intermediate-term bond fund offered yields of 8.5 percent to 9 percent," says Paul DeRosa. "Under present circumstances that same fund would probably have difficulty delivering more than 5.5 percent." Short-term funds show even lower yields.<p>To many fund managers, derivatives seem like a heaven-sent way out of this bind. Derivatives, which don't behave at all like traditional bonds, are by-products of a financial revolution that has gone unnoticed by most people who don't work for investment banks. During the 1980s, as financial deregulation made trading stocks less profitable for Wall Street's big firms, these investment houses began to create new services--products actually--that they could sell to the institutional money managers. Hotshots, called rocket scientists, with engineering, physics, or math degrees from MIT or UCLA divided financial instruments the way physicists analyzed subatomic particles.<p>For example, mortgages pay principal and interest for as long as 30 years. But most investors aren't inclined to hold on to a security for that long. The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Association and the Federal National Mortgage Association, the quasi-governmental agencies that buy mortgages from banks and savings and loans, and the agencies' investment bankers have designed derivatives to meet the demand for long-, short-, and medium-term investments. First, the mortgages are turned into securities called collateralized mortgage obligations or CMOs. The cash flows from a pool of mortgages are divided up into pieces, each with specific characteristics such as duration (a number that measures how long investors have to wait for the cash that an investment throws off), yield, and risk. For example, investors who bought a security that was backed by a specific part of the pool might look to get all their principal back in seven years.<p>To turn this instrument into a derivative, an investment banker will then customize it. For example, maybe an institutional investor wants a lump sum at regular intervals with the chance for some extra return if interest rates fall. Sell that client just the principal payments on a pool of mortgages. Such a derivative is called a PO, for principal only. Or how about buying just the interest payments, a derivative called an IO, for interest only. Or an inverse floater, which pays more when rates fall and less when rates rise. In June, the newsletter Inside Mortgage Securities estimated that more than half of all mortgage securities outstanding were in the form of derivatives--nearly $730 billion of $1.4 trillion. <p>Like electrons and protons, each derivative behaves differently. For example, anyone who expected interest rates to fall would buy a PO, because homeowners would refinance their mortgages as rates went down. The investor would thus get his cash payments of mortgage principal more quickly. By contrast, someone who expected rates to rise would buy IOs, because homeowners would be unlikely to refinance and the investor could look forward to a long stream of interest payments.<p>Any investor who buys an IO or a PO or any other derivative is making a highly leveraged bet on the future--which is why these securities can go up or down so much faster and so much further than plain vanilla bonds. What is the right price to pay for a stream of payments that might last 30 years--or maybe just 15? "Everybody is guessing, making judgments on the basis of past experiences and expectations," says Thomas Poor, managing director of Scudder, Stevens & Clark, a Boston mutual fund company that uses derivatives in its fixed-income funds. "But it's an inexact science. That's why collateralized mortgage obligations yield more than treasuries."<p>In the right interest-rate environment and in the hands of the right manager, these exotic securities are everything an investor could ask for and more. <a name="FUND:SCSTX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SCSTX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>The Scudder Short-Term Bond Fund</b></a> shows a total return of 7.6 percent during the past 12 months. About 10 percent of the fund's holdings consist of inverse floaters, says Poor. The closed-end TCW/DW Term Trust 2002 fund, though AAA rated by Standard & Poor's, is more than 40 percent invested in inverse floaters. Investors think so highly of the fund's prospects that its shares trade at a price above the value of the bonds it holds. "The only way you can outperform in the marketplace is by buying things that are not as well understood [by the average money manager] or by taking massive guesses," TCW's Philip Barach says. "It's very hard to get inverse floaters [now]. They were probably one of the cheapest fixed-income securities of the 20th century. Now they're incredibly desirable; everyone in the world wants them. TCW overall probably owns close to a billion dollars of them."<p>The results at these funds have encouraged other fund managers to follow suit. According to data provided by Morningstar, nearly three dozen open-ended fixed-income mutual funds have committed from 5 percent to 40 percent of their portfolios to such volatile and illiquid instruments as IOs and inverse floaters. (For a list of these funds, see "High on Derivatives?") Closed-end funds, which issue shares that trade on stock exchanges and often borrow to leverage their assets, are even more aggressive. It's not unusual to find closed-end funds with 20 percent to 40 percent of their portfolio in these instruments. (For a list of these funds, see "The Worst Addicts.")<p>So if these funds have done well with derivatives, what's the big problem? Shouldn't investors just go out and buy shares in a "good" fund? From his cramped 23rd-story office at Buck Consultants in midtown Manhattan, Mark Cunningham has developed a frightening answer to that question. Cunningham, whose office is cluttered with heaps of math and engineering textbooks, is a kind of reverse rocket scientist. Big institutional clients pay him to apply mathematical tools like Bayesian analysis, the same technique that discovered the link between smoking and cancer, to figure out where the rockets launched by the Wall Street hotshots will come down. These methods tell him that investing in some of these funds is like buying a ticket in the interest-rate lottery.<p>For example, Cunningham's analysis of the Scudder Short-Term Bond Fund shows an 80 percent increase in volatility in the fund over the last year. After perusing a list of the securities it held in 1992, Cunningham says, "Looking at this portfolio, we can't tell how the fund will behave. A lot of these will zig when they should be zagging." <p>If Cunningham can't figure out the risk in one of these funds, what hope is there for the average investor? Most investors don't even understand what kinds of risk to look for, says Rick Siedband, assistant vice president at Piper Capital Management, a money-management firm based in Minneapolis. The average investor thinks of risk only as credit risk, he notes, and looks for a government guarantee that the issuer of the paper won't default. But a government guarantee is no protection against interest-rate risk. If the security is an inverse floater and rates go up, cash flows to investors will plummet with or without the government guarantee. A top rating from S&P or Moody's also guarantees only the creditworthiness of the issuer.<p>Investors who would never gamble in the roll-the-dice world of commodities and options have put money into derivative-laden mutual funds because they have read the reassuring words AAA rated and government guaranteed. But they are actually playing the same sort of game. Buyers of IOs, for example, pay today for what they hope will be a long stream of interest payments tomorrow. IOs don't pay any principal, so when a homeowner prepays his mortgage, the interest payments stop cold and the IO holder gets nothing. Like an option buyer, an IO buyer pays up-front for an instrument that may expire worthless. But in one way, IOs are even riskier than options. The options trader needs only to be right about the price or rate direction. To succeed in IOs, it's not enough to be right about rates; the buyer also needs to be right about what homeowners will do when rates move up or down.<p>Recent experience shows that behavioral patterns are a lot harder to predict than Wall Street's rocket scientists initially thought. After studying the ways in which millions of homeowners paid or refinanced their mortgages for the past few decades, Wall Street was pretty confident that the homeowner's threshold of pain was about 2 percentage points. As long as there were fewer than 200 basis points--or 2 percentage points--between the rate on a homeowner's existing mortgage and current mortgage rates, homeowners wouldn't refinance. As long as homeowners endured the pain, everyone's investment would behave predictably and no one would lose serious money.<p>But last year Wall Street suddenly realized that the rule of thumb wasn't true anymore. When the financial scientists weren't looking, fee-hungry mortgage bankers made refinancing a lot easier. "Some of our contacts are seeing people refinance at as low as a 75-basis-point spread between the current mortgage on their property and what's available in the marketplace," says Prudential's Ron Santangelo. "In this environment we've seen IOs decrease as much as 50 percent in value just over the last 12 months." <p>Many investors were drawn to Hyperion 1999 by the name of Lew Ranieri, the legendary Salomon Brothers mortgage-bond trader. Ranieri founded Hyperion Capital Management in 1989 after he was pushed out of Salomon by then-chairman John Gutfreund. Despite Ranieri's fame, his massive gamble on IOs shocked some of the gutsiest managers in the fixed-income world. "Anybody managing money would know it's not prudent, logical, or a good bet to make," says TCW's Philip Barach, who attended Hyperion's road show.<p>Anybody managing money would spot the risk, but how about the average individual investor who bought into this fund--or any of the others that are heavily into these derivatives? Hyperion, which would not comment on its fund's performance, certainly disclosed its investment strategy. The initial offering prospectus states that the fund will invest in IOs, for example, which have "significantly greater price and yield volatility than is the case with traditional debt securities." The fund's November 1992 annual report says that 32.7 percent of the fund's portfolio is invested in these stripped mortgage-backed securities.<p>But experts who work with these funds doubt that this kind of disclosure is sufficient. "A lot of times I will see pie charts with portfolio breakdowns that don't always represent the true risk of the pieces of paper they own," says Prudential's Santangelo. A Scudder brochure, for example, simply lists the holdings of the Scudder Short-Term Bond Fund as 1 percent cash, 22 percent mortgage, 18 percent asset-backed, 9 percent collateralized mortgage obligation, 21 percent corporate, 9 percent reverse floating rate, 9 percent government, 6 percent foreign pay, and 5 percent Yankee/Supranational Agency. And would the majority of people who see the name FBC Mortgage Securities Trust 18 CMO Series A in another fund's financials recognize that it is a residual, one of the riskiest derivative instruments?<p>"I'm not sure if it's deliberate action on the part of many fund managers or the fact that it's not required of them to list it as such, so they don't," Santangelo says. "I think all the risks of a piece of paper should be properly disclosed, especially if it's not of the normal nature you would expect." <p>The regulators and the raters contribute to the problem. There's nothing illegal about disclosing a list of securities without explaining precisely what they are or how they behave. "As long as you disclose what you're going to do, you can do almost anything," says Eastbridge's DeRosa. "I can say I'm going to put one third of the fund's money in high-coupon IOs. High-coupon IOs may be one of the riskiest investments on the face of the earth, and the SEC may or may not appreciate that potential investors don't have even the slightest idea of what a high-coupon IO is. But so long as it's revealed in the offering document, it goes through."<p>The SEC's effort to encourage the mutual fund industry to produce clearly written, easily understood prospectuses has left the agency with little wiggle room. "It seems to be contrary to go back to funds and say, 'Use a page for every derivative you're going to do,'" says Gene Gohlke, associate director for compliance in the SEC's Investment Management division. "If you do that, you probably come out with a 20- or 30-page document nobody would read. How do you convey the essentials of these very complex instruments so the average person who doesn't even know what a stock is can understand it?" He says that the agency has directed its inspectors to "look more closely at funds that are using derivatives in a major way and compare that to the disclosure in the prospectuses," but notes that "based on our experience doing inspections, we haven't had any significant problems with the disclosures that funds have in comparison with what they're doing."<p>Investors shouldn't expect much help from the rating agencies either. Even the riskiest funds can secure a AAA rating for credit quality. Russell Long, director of Standard & Poor's mutual fund ratings group, says, "Right now our analysis is a credit-risk analysis; it doesn't incorporate the other type of risks that are in bond funds." Fitch Investors Service in New York recently launched a rating service that could tell investors at a glance about those other risks in a fund. Not surprisingly, fund managers aren't exactly lining up to have their portfolios rated by Fitch. <p>A few financial regulators have admitted that they're as confused as investors. They've formed a support group formally named the Financial Innovations Study Committee but known by everyone as the Weird Instruments Committee. This group of tax lawyers, economists, accountants, bankers, and regulators is trying to understand the implications of several hundred new high-tech financial products. "It's clear that the IRS and all the other regulatory agencies are behind the curve in figuring out what to do with the new instruments," says Joanne Medero, former general counsel to the Commodity Futures Trading Commission and now a partner with the law firm Orrick, Herrington & Sutcliffe. No one expects any concrete recommendations from this group soon.<p>In the meantime investors are on their own. And maybe they would do best to follow the rule of thumb suggested by one analyst who knows the market well: "If I can't explain it to my mother, I won't buy it."<p>
Gregory Millman is writing a book on the international financial markets for the Free Press.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement Investing, Bond Investing, Mutual Funds Investing

