	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Trouble With Fund Wraps</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>Trouble With Fund Wraps</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Trouble With Fund Wraps</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Advisor  
<p>
 TROUBLE WITH FUND WRAPS 
<p>
What to ask  
<p>
 By Andrew Gluck  
<p>
 With some 3,700 mutual funds to choose from, putting together
a portfolio of more than a couple of funds can be a daunting
task. So investors who don't have the time to become mutual fund
experts have little choice but to pay for some help.  
<p>
 Traditionally, fund investors have gotten advice in exchange
for paying commissions. But growing numbers of investors are
seeking no-load funds that forego the up-front commissions and
allow more investment dollars to start earning from day one.
So the big Wall Street brokerages, with their huge sales forces,
are changing their stripes. The brokerages and mutual fund companies,
which till now have given fund advice only on a commission basis,
are rolling out no-load fund advisory packages. They're billed
as mutual fund wrap accountsa name that suits them well, since
some basic information about them is being kept under wraps.<p>
<p>
 On the surface, mutual fund wrap accounts are a great idea.
They combine all the advantages of no-load mutual funds with
the commission-free investment advice of wrap accounts. Investors
who want to put at least $25,000 in no-load funds can get advice
about which funds to buy, in most cases for an annual fee of
1.5 percent of the amount invested plus all the usual fund operating
expenses, which usually range up to another 1.5 percent. The
brokerages say investors get custom-tailored, long-term investment
programs that are reviewed and updated quarterly.  
<p>
 Unfortunately, many mutual fund wraps come up short when compared
with the available alternatives. They can be more costly and
less personalized, and they offer only a limited number of funds
from which to build a portfolio. The people who sell them aren't
always clear about the total fees charged, and perhaps worst
of all, performance figures for comparison shopping can be difficult,
if not impossible, to get.  
<p>
 In November 1991, the Consulting Group of Shearson Lehman Brothers
(now part of Smith Barney) introduced the first of the brokerage-house
wrap programs, the TRAK Personalized Investment Advisory Service.
It's been a marketing success, attracting 40,000 investors and
$1.5 billion. In January of this year, Prudential Securities
launched Target, its version of the fund wrap account.   
<p>
 Brokerage rival Kidder, Peabody & Co. in March began offering
Insight, its fund wrap account, using Kidder's existing family
of funds to build client portfolios. Merrill Lynch expects to
roll out its version of the fund wrap this fall.  
<p>
 Although some programs are more personalized than others, the
broker-sold products all work basically the same way: The investor
fills out a questionnaire that asks about personal financial
goals and investment history, and the answers determine the client's
risk tolerance. (Prudential's and Shearson's questionnaires consist
of eight and nine questions respectively, while Kidder's includes
30.) Based on their answers, clients are scored and categorized
by their risk profiles.   
<p>
 Each risk category has a different mix of stock, bond, and money-market
funds. Going beyond the basic classifications of conservative,
moderate, and aggressive risk profiles, Shearson and Kidder each
have seven risk categories and Prudential has 20. After a client
is classified into one of the risk categories, the mix of recommended
funds gets fine-tuned by a stockbroker. Investors receive a quarterly
report on their performance and, if needed, recommendations are
made about which mutual funds to switch out of and into.  
<p>
 But rather than allow investors to pick from all the no-loads
already on the market, Prudential created a family of nine funds
and Shearson created a family of 12 funds that are used exclusively
for the fund wrap programs.   
<p>
 While the workings of fund wraps are easy for a broker to explain,
investors buying them may not be told exactly what they're getting.
That's because the brokerage firms often won't disclose how the
various portfolios have performed. Both Prudential and Shearson
declined to provide performance data on the risk categories their
programs use. "Some firms appear to be going out of their way
to keep investors from having the information necessary to make
an informed decision," says Don Phillips of Morningstar, which
tracks fund performances. "They're attempting to go back to the
dark ages of investing, where they control the data flow to clients.
From an investor's point of view, it's nuts."  
<p>
 Shearson and Prudential have not only refused to tell prospective
buyers how their portfolio recommendations have worked out, but
they've also declined to publish total returns for the funds
used in their wrap accounts. Nor does either firm provide total
return statistics to mutual fund research firms, such as Lipper
Analytical Services and Morningstar. Kidder Peabody was the exception,
saying it would provide the press and customers with quarterly
performance data on its Insight mutual fund wrap program.   
<p>
 Shearson and Prudential are not alone in making it hard to get
performance figures on fund wraps. Fidelity Investments, the
nation's largest mutual fund company, offers its Portfolio Advisory
Services for investors with at least $100,000. PAS uses Fidelity's
funds to design portfolios, and its fees are a bit lower. But
like its competitors, Fidelity does not provide prospective investors
with performance data on its eight portfolios.   
<p>
 With only one of the major firms that offer fund wraps disclosing
how the product is performing, investors are likely to have a
tough time shopping for the best program. But if the difficulty
of getting performance data isn't enough to turn off potential
clients, they also need to be wary of a salesperson's inaccurate
description of fees for a fund wrap account.  
<p>
 A Fidelity sales representative told a Worth caller recently
that the charges for Portfolio Advisory Services would include
a 1 percent wrap fee plus the management expenses on the mutual
funds selected. Actually, PAS charges a 1 percent wrap fee plus
the fund's total operating expenses, which could mean an annual
fee that's 30 percent to 40 percent higher than what Fidelity's
representative indicated.   
<p>
 Indeed, Fidelity even went so far as to publish a chart in its
PAS Fact Sheet that compared its 1 percent fee to the 3 percent
that equity wrap accounts charge. The chart failed to mention,
however, that the 3 percent includes all costs, while investors
in the PAS also pay fund expenses that raise the comparable figure
to about 2.5 percent.  
<p>
 Calls to Shearson and Prudential branches in New York also yielded
inaccurate information about fees for their programs. Brokers
at both firms assured a caller that the total expenses on TRAK
and Target included only the 1.5 percent wrap feenothing else.
Even when asked about additional fees, the brokers didn't mention
the charges for the funds' total operating expenses, which add
about .8 percentage points a year for a bond fund and as much
as 1.5 percentage points for a stock fund.  
<p>
 Despite the difficulty of getting accurate expense information
and any performance data, the fund wrap accounts being offered
by the major players may turn out to be sound investments. But
investors may do better getting fee-only advice from a financial
planner or money manager. Investors generally pay between .5
percent and 1.5 percent of assets per year for an independent
advisor to select and manage a portfolio of mutual funds. These
advisors are likely to work with hundreds of well-known no-load
funds whose performance is published in magazines, newspapers,
and fund services. And they usually provide more personalized
help with building and monitoring a mutual fund portfolio.  <p>
<p><p>
<p>
Andrew Gluck is a Worth senior writer based in New York.  
<p>
  <hr>  
