<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-The Mutual Fund Time Bomb</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-The Mutual Fund Time Bomb</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
CD investors have finally joined the mutual fund bandwagon--that's not good news<p>By Jonathan Burton<p>Grand central station, 8 a.m. bleary commuters pour from packed trains to flow into thick Manhattan crowds. Breaking free for a moment, Thomas Derderian stops at a nearby Dreyfus investment center. His certificates of deposit are maturing, and the 48-year-
old president of the Redding Group, a New York advertising agency, bristles at the meager yields he is getting from his bank. For the first time ever, he is considering mutual funds. Derderian is no home-run hitter; 8% a year would do just fine. He takes a prospectus for the <a name="FUND:DGRIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/DGRIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dreyfus Growth & Income Fund</b></a>, which gained 20% in 1992. Yes, he says, stocks are risky, but name an alternative. "If I could get the same rate in the bank," he admits, "I wouldn't be here."<p>Say hello to one of Wall Street's latest believers. For the last 18 months, people like Derderian have been pouring billions into equity mutual funds, those that invest in stocks. In 1992 alone more than $71 billion flowed into these funds__that's $71 billion net after subtracting the money that flowed out as investors sold funds to pay for college, retirement, or a vacation, or just to lock in profits. And the flood shows no sign of retreating. In the first quarter of 1993, $27.2 billion of net new money gushed into the pool. This new money has considerably expanded the ocean of money in equity mutual funds__only $529 billion in all.<p>This flood hasn't gone unnoticed by the pundits who vie to explain Wall Street. In late March and early April, for example, the economy seemed sluggish, but the market wouldn't stop its assault on new heights. Why? All the liquidity in the market from mutual funds, the analysts answered. "Beyond any question of improving economic growth and corporate profits, just about any Wall Street analyst will tell you 'liquidity' is what's keeping the stock market afloat right now," opined the Associated Press on April 12. In fact, several analysts suggested, the market couldn't fall while all this excess cash needed to be invested.<p>What may be more significant than the amount of this inflow, however, is the kind of people behind it. People like Thomas Derderian, who are lifetime savers rather than investors. These CD refugees held onto their federally insured accounts while interest rates shrank from 8% to 7% to 6% and then to 5%. Only when rates plunged below 4% did they start to consider trading safety for yield. They have been virtually pushed into mutual funds. And that's precisely what worries some mutual fund managers and industry observers. This new money is hot money. It moved massively into the market, without much fundamental conviction, when the deal got too good to turn down. Implication: It could flow out just as quickly.<p>"These are conservative investors," warns Eric Kobren, editor of the "Fidelity Insight" newsletter. "If the market does take a tumble here, we could see them head for the hills."<p>Richard Hoffman, chief investment strategist at Cowen & Co., agrees. "The money that's coming into the mutual fund industry is not long-haul money," he surmises. "Once they hit that first pocket of volatility, these people will become frightened, and it will just accelerate the volatility."<p>"The new investors are savers, and they don't understand risk," explains Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp. "They have moved from a CD to a mutual fund, and many of them think they have price stability__and they don't." Adds Johnson warily, "I don't want to be around when they find out."<p>In other words, when the market hits its next bad stretch__call it a correction or a bear market__this money could stampede out of mutual funds as fast as it's flowed in. The money that came in near the top, that may even have kept the market creeping those last few inches higher, could make the downdraft all the stronger. Panicky shareholders could jam the toll-free telephone lines of the giant mutual fund families, demanding an instant divorce. Fund managers, who on average are keeping about 10% of their holdings in cash, would then use this supply to absorb the initial shock wave. Once cash positions run low, the funds would have no recourse except to liquidate securities into a declining market. That in turn could exacerbate the downward spiral and encourage even more share redemptions over a period of several demoralizing days. "It could be," ventures Barbara Morrow of Barronett Global Investors, "like a big margin call on the whole market."<p>THE DANGER SIGNS<p>In 1991 health care and biotechnology stock funds were on fire. That year, 26-year-old Charles Mangum guided <a name="FUND:FSHCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSHCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity Investments' Select Medical Delivery Fund</b></a> to a 78% gain, and investors clamored to get aboard. Mangum remembers watching the money roll in. First the fund hit $50 million, up from $38 million in 1990. Then $100 million. Then $200 million. As the money arrived, he funnelled it into ever more expensive health care and biotechnology stocks. The glowing stories in the business press started to make him wince. He wondered how many new investors were adding their money to his fund without understanding the risk. Finally in early 1992, the bubble burst. Investors who had bought into the fund in mid January bailed out in February__after losing 15% of their investment. After peaking at $1.7 billion in December 1991, assets of <a name="FUND:FSPHX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FSPHX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity's Health Care Fund</b></a>, which Mangum started to manage in early 1992, plunged to $500 million by the end of April 1993. The sobering experience left an indelible mark on Mangum. "If you met me, you'd swear I was 40," he says.<p>That example, of course, involves just a small sector and a single industry. Is such a bleak scenario likely for equity mutual funds as a whole? Well, part of that scenario is absolutely certain to happen. There will be an end to the current bull market, and that end will be marked by a correction of noticeable magnitude. The question isn't if. It's when. Peter Lynch, who ran <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity's Magellan Fund</b></a> for 13 years and who writes a column for this magazine, is a long-term investor who has little use for attempts to time the market. But he does observe that major stock market corrections do appear with a surprising degree of regularity. On average, he states bluntly, "every two years the market has a 10% decline. Every six years: 25%." When was the last time the Dow Jones Industrials were zapped for 25% of their value at one sitting? October 1987. The average bull run lasts 37 months. This one is already 33 months old.<p>Some of the smart money is clearly rattled at the moment. "I've got more cash in my personal account than I usually have," concedes a veteran Wall Street stock picker who prefers to remain anonymous. Says M. Kimelman & Co. director Bernadette Murphy, "Usually we have a summer rally. I'm concerned this year we might have a summer sell-off." Investment sage Warren Buffett has told his flock that "the rewards from investing over the next decade will be significantly smaller than they were in the last." Lord Abbett partner John Walsh observes euphemistically that in the equity market ahead, "selectivity's going to be much more important."<p>Individually several mutual fund managers are reducing their own exposure by shutting the barnyard gate. This at least might minimize the amount of money coming in that must be invested at current high market valuations. <p>During the first few weeks of this year, <a name="FUND:STCSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/STCSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Strong Common Stock Fund</b></a> was deluged with $5 million in new commitments every day. From January through March the fund more than doubled in size, to $390 million from $179 million, according to managers Richard Weiss and Carlene Murphy. "We can't find enough stocks to soak up all that money," Weiss said just before they closed the fund to new investors on March 19.<p>Many managers have made similar decisions for their portfolios. Eric Ryback closed the <a name="FUND:LDDVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/LDDVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lindner Dividend Fund</b></a> on March 4 when assets reached $1 billion. In February Thomas Marsico stopped taking deposits for the Janus Twenty Fund, citing a desire to run a concentrated portfolio. Robert Bacarella closed his popular Monetta Fund to new investors in March, when its assets reached $500 million.<p>"This is a stressful period for us managers," says Lawrence Auriana, co-manager of the <a name="FUND:KAUFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/KAUFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kaufmann Fund</b></a>. His fund took in $200 million in the first ten weeks of 1993, or about $3 million a day. "When things are going well, we're very nervous. We know the market is both cyclical and volatile, and we've been through enough bear markets over the last 25 years that we've seen it all. Hopefully a lot of these investors will be able to withstand a decline, but we're not betting the fund that they will." <p>Of course, most of the big money isn't getting out of the market. It can't afford to. Money managers aren't paid to sit on the sidelines for months while they wait for the inevitable correction. No, even though everyone knows market timing is a fools' game, much of the big money is betting it can call the turn. In March, equity fund managers had just 9.9% of their assets in cash. That's up from 8.9% in January, but not by much. Says Barton Biggs, who's in charge of global asset allocation at <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a>, "It's the sixth or seventh inning of the game, not the ninth inning. In our business, we can't afford to leave the game in the sixth or seventh inning." <p>The numbers suggest that it is indeed late in the game. For most of the past two decades, companies have traded, on average, at a modest 12 times what they were expected to earn per share over the year to come. But stocks in the first few months of 1993 hovered near a heady 22 times forward earnings per share. This is among the highest ratio since these figures were first collected in 1926. How can a slow recovery, with the economy barely ticking upward at 1.8% a year (according to the first quarter 1993 figures from the Commerce Department) justify these prices? And what about suggestions that we're sliding back into recession or that inflation is returning? Is anything more than excess liquidity__the torrent of money into equity funds included__propping up the market?<p>Rest assured there's a lot more liquidity where the first quarter of 1993's $27.2 billion came from. About $3.3 trillion is idling in short-term instruments. Dominating this landscape is a mountain of CD dough more than $700 billion high, say Federal Reserve surveyors. In April alone, $110 billion of CDs came due.<p>Yet in the absence of economic and earnings growth that would catch the market up to its current valuations, all that liquidity is just expanding the bubble and raising the decibel levels of the bang when it bursts. The long-term investor__and all the numbers still say that equities are the place to be long-term__needs to understand how a short-term puncture of a speculative bubble or a longer-lasting bear market affects a portfolio.<p>NAME YOUR SCENARIO<p>If the hot money in mutual funds poses a danger to mutual fund investors, the magnitude of that danger__and any decision on what to do about it__depends on the size of any correction. A short, sharp nosedive like that of October 1987 is very different from the long grinding bear market of, say, 1973 through 1974. The ramifications would be very different too.<p>The October 19, 1987 crash, which slashed 22.6% off the Dow in a single day, collared a bull market already in its fifth year. So many investors were led to the guillotine, says Ralph Wanger, manager of the Acorn Fund, that it seemed Wall Street had taken a page from the French Revolution. "One day you felt fine," Wanger observes. "The next day your head was in the basket."<p>Few people predicted the fall. Equity mutual fund assets had doubled between January 1986 and August 1987, soaring to $243 billion from $120 billion. Eric Ryback was managing the Lindner Dividend Fund in St. Louis when the crash came. "Everybody was saying the market was too high, but no one was reacting to it," he recalls. "There was a lot of euphoria." <p>When the October surprise came, many shareholders bailed out of Ryback's and most every other fund. That emotional decision forced many fund managers to liquidate securities in order to satisfy skittish investors who wanted to sell, even if they were convinced that the damage was done and the market would bounce back. Fidelity's Magellan Fund, for example, had been 98.6% invested on October 19. As the market went into a free fall that day, it raised cash by unloading $1 billion worth of stocks. Most fund investors wanted no part of the stock market. Industrywide, redemptions outpaced new sales by $1.2 billion in October, and investors continued to redeem more than they put in for all of 1988, pushing the total for that year to $8.5 billion in net redemptions. Investors closed almost a million equity-fund accounts that year.<p>But some investors couldn't panic in October; they were saved by jammed phone lines and overwhelmed mutual fund staffs. Forced to stay invested during the crash itself, they didn't sell at the panicky bottom. Within three months the market had recovered all that it had lost in October.<p>Ryback actually went fishing in Idaho for a week. When the market tanked, Ryback told his boss, Kurt Lindner, that he would cancel the trip, but Lindner urged him to go. "He said, 'I can't think of a better thing to do,'" says Ryback. <p>But the 1987 crash, while certainly traumatic, wasn't the classic bear market: a market that goes down, and down, and down__and stays down. "Once every 20 years, we have a secular bear market," says Barton Biggs. "They're a real killer. The Dow and the S&P go down 40% to 50%. That's when people in those mutual funds are going to get their clocks cleaned. The last one we had was in 1973-'74. A secular bear market really does a lot of emotional damage." Adds Kenneth Tarr, president of Credit Suisse Asset Management, "There is an event in every generation's lifetime that separates people from their capital. We have not had one yet."<p>Those who have been through a bear market never forget it. As a young clerk on the floor of New York Stock Exchange in the early 1960s, First Albany's Johnson recalls, "I thought it was onward and upward forever. Boy, oh boy, did I learn."<p>That bear, like the 20 others since 1890, eventually ended, but not before most investors threw in the towel in disgust. Of course, Johnson explains, "that's when you want to buy." Trouble is, that's precisely when investors have neither the stomach nor the cash to take the plunge. "It's easy for us to talk about it now," says Johnson. "But when it's happening, believe me, emotions often tend to interfere with good strategies. That's why you try your best to develop discipline." Yet investors caught in the fierce grip of a bear tend to react without much creativity or discipline. They despair. <p>The extended downturn of January 1973 through December 1974__the last significant bear market__shaved 45% off the Dow Jones Industrial Average. Sickened investors dumped equities, swamping the funds with redemptions. Many of today's investors, too young to remember the early 1970s, think of the October 1987 crash as the epitome of a bear market; they have difficulty comprehending a drawn-out, debilitating decline. The Dow Jones closed on January 2, 1973 at 1031.68; on December 31, 1974 it stood at 616.24. The numbers that track equity mutual funds show a grim similarity. Immediately before the end, the industry enjoyed record popularity. Equity-fund assets hit $56 billion in 1972, up smartly from $51.6 billion the year before. But when the market sank in 1973, frightened investors jumped overboard. By December 1974, equity funds held just $31 billion in assets. Redemptions would continue to outweigh sales for four of the next six years.<p>In April 1972, Ralph Wanger's <a name="FUND:ACRNX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/ACRNX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Acorn Fund</b></a> was two years old, and Wanger managed $22 million of other people's money. "Things just kind of unwound very gradually" during the bear market, Wanger remembers. "It was a deadly, grinding sort of thing. The slow motion of it kept everybody paralyzed. You just hated to come to work." Investors also hated to be in stocks. By September 1974, Acorn's assets had dwindled to just $9.5 million. "If you lost only half your money during that two-year period, you were doing pretty well," says Wanger. "There were a lot of guys who lost all of it and ended up working in their uncle's shoe store. We should've known better, and we didn't."<p>Some money managers worry that the current high level of complacency makes mutual fund managers and investors remarkably susceptible to a secular bear market. The stock market is coming off one of its longest bulls ever, 33 months of upward momentum as of the end of July. At 16.2% a year, according to Ibbotson Associates' calculations, returns over the period from January 1, 1982 through December 31, 1992 have been well above the historic annual average of 10%.<p>Market mavens insist that cash from the small investor will continue to push the market higher. But few of these experts were active investors during the last bear. The typical equity fund manager is a 45-year-old male who has been running his particular portfolio for just five years, according to Morningstar Inc. Of the 2,559 funds that Morningstar follows, only 48 have had the same manager for 20 years or more. Another 34 have been on the job for at least 15 years. "There's a baptism out there for a lot of folks," says Marshall Acuff, portfolio strategist for Smith Barney Shearson. "I don't know whether the waters will be very kind." <p>SO WHAT TO DO?<p>Hanging by the tail of a bull isn't much fun; neither is being caught in the gaping mouth of a bear. Therefore, this might be a better time than most for investors to evaluate their portfolios and their own goals, horizons, and risk tolerance. Put away the Ouija board and start studying the statements that come in the mail. Trying to time the market is virtually useless, so don't bother. "It does weird things to your brain," cautions Ralph Wanger. Adds Hugh Johnson, "Most people are not good enough to time markets. If you own high-quality growth stocks, companies that have a long record of relatively uninterrupted earnings and dividends, then in the long term you'll be just fine." <p>Of course, that's the challenge, isn't it? Right now, any investor ought to be able to make a case for each stock in his or her portfolio. Why will it go up? How strong is that case? When in doubt, sell into the next rally.<p>The same principles apply to mutual funds. Now's the time to consider the details of a fund's performance. How well does it do in a down market, and how quickly does it recover? (See chart on page 56.) How volatile is the fund? Some funds, index funds in particular, track the market. Investors can expect them to be as risky as the market as a whole. Other funds (earnings momentum funds being a prime example) outperform the market on the way up and dive much faster than the market on the way down. Investors who can ride out these swings do well over the long term. Investors who can't stand the drop and who sell at the bottom shouldn't be in funds like this. (Worth's "The Ultimate Guide to Mutual Funds" [October/November 1992] lists performance consistency and the biggest quarterly loss for 20 top funds for long-term investors.)<p>Nor should short-term investors. A buy-and-hold strategy works well__given enough time. But investors need to consider their real timeframes. When college tuition or retirement loom on their own inevitable schedules, buy-and-hold may be just wishful thinking.<p>The 1980s may have been the decade when the rising market lifted all equity funds. The initial evidence is that the 1990s will be a stock picker's market, if folks like Warren Buffett are to be believed, anyway. Equity funds that lagged their category brethren during the 1980s are suspect. If a fund couldn't outperform similar funds during that decade, the manager may not be much of a stock picker__even if the fund did well. Remember, the market as a whole returned more than 16% a year on average for a decade. Also think about the size of a fund. Can a manager__no matter how smart__with $7 billion effectively pick stocks?<p>Finally, this may be an appropriate moment to consider alternatives to U.S. equities. "It might not be a bad time to look at Europe," observes Bernadette Murphy, "just because their markets are depressed." Others advocate investing in Asia, where most economies outside of Japan's are growing rapidly. Japan itself, despite the current high returns from Japan funds, may not be a great bet. Price/earnings ratios in the Tokyo market have crept up toward levels close to those that prevailed before the bubble burst in 1990.<p>Any investor considering putting money in an equity fund for the first time ought to pause. Cash isn't trash, even at 3.2%. Wanger, who manages an equity fund, would avoid buying stocks "just because your CDs are [paying] lower [interest rates]." Barbara Morrow points out that, in any case, taking on new risk at this point is a dubious proposition. "There are a lot of question marks in the world, in our economy, and in our government," she says. "That's all making me very wary." Those who can't resist getting wet in the equity funds now should certainly look for a fund with a relatively low minimum investment and then practice dollar cost averaging by investing the same amount each month.<p>Above all, don't become complacent. Unlike the later stages of most previous bull cycles, currently there is a glaring absence of pure old-fashioned greed. In its place is the misguided notion that betting on mutual funds is a no-lose proposition. But greed actually has its good points__for the savvy investor. Greed alerts cooler heads that a market top is imminent; it is the flashing red light before the car overheats. Complacency, however, dulls the investors' ability to act. A complacent market is a docile herd moving on faith. That's dangerous. A bear on the prowl isn't hungry only for pigs. A pasture full of sheep will do. <p>Jonathan Burton is the New York correspondent for The Far Eastern Economic Review.<p> <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Banking Industry

