	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-Alphabet Soup</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Robert N. Veres<p>Way back in the olden days, ten years ago or so, there were two ways to buy mutual funds. Investors could pay a broker an 8.5% commission to find the right fund and keep an eye on its performance (called a load fund because of the commission), or they could find a no-load fund, pay no commission, and keep tabs on its performance themselves.<p>Since then, computers have liberated the creative minds in the mutual fund industry, allowing them to offer a broader array of choices. Now there are "A" shares, "B" shares, "C," and even "D" shares; deferred sales charges, 12(b)-1 fees and trail commissions; wrap fees; no-loads, low-loads, and level-loads. It's an array that can bewilder even brokers and financial advisors. The bottom line, however, is that they're all terms to describe how mutual fund companies put our money into their pockets. Although none of these methods is necessarily bad, today's investors must be careful they're getting what they're paying for.<p>Let's start with no-load funds. Financial planners are beginning to make a distinction between "true" no-loads and look-alikes. Investors who don't want or need the services of a broker or investment advisor, or those working with a fee-only financial planner (who charges them directly for advice), should read the prospectus to make sure they are in a true no-load fund, with no sales commissions paid up front, or deferred and charged to their portfolio in subsequent years.<p>On the other hand, investors who need the services of a broker or planner to help find a fund, and who are willing to pay for it through commissions, will face a wide range of load fund options. In recent years, the 8.5% commission has become an endangered species. At this writing, only about 30 funds still pay brokers 8% or more; most others have dropped their front-end commission to under 5.75%, with some as low as 3%. At the same time, they've added annual charges (known as "12(b)-1 fees" or "trail commissions") of between .25% and 1.25% of each investment. Paying brokers less up front and a little something every year gives them an incentive to provide ongoing service__handling the paperwork if an investor moves or gets married, for example, and checking to see if they're still on track for a fully-funded retirement. <p>So the first rule of thumb is, make sure to get service from brokers or financial planners in return for the commissions paid. Rule number two: Keep up-front loads at 5.75% or less, and keep the trail commissions at .4% or less. That would leave out, for example, four of the Rightime funds, <a name="FUND:NUSFX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/NUSFX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New USA Mutual</b></a>, Progressive Environmental Fund, and <a name="FUND:GRGSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GRGSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Voyageur Growth Stock Fund</b></a>. They all pay front-end commissions of 4.5% or more and pay a trail commission of .9% or more a year. <p>While front-end commissions were being scaled down, brokerage houses such as <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> and Shearson were discovering that a lot of investors didn't want to pay any up-front commission at all, but that they still wanted professional advice. So the brokerage world created what are now called "B" share portfolios__funds that look like no-loads but still pay a commission to the broker. <p>To understand how this works, let's consider a $2,000 investment in a "B" share portfolio. All $2,000 goes into the fund from day one, just like a traditional no-load product. However, when the investor writes his check, the fund company reaches into its pocket and pays a front-end commission__ranging from 3% to 6% of the $2,000__to the broker. This $60 to $120 is treated as a "loan" that has to be paid.<p>Who pays? The investor. The fund company recoups the money through higher annual fees taken out of the account. What's more, if the investor wants to withdraw the money before this "loan" is paid off, he has to pay off the loan in what's called a back-end charge. In the first year, it's usually equal to the amount of the commission, decreasing to zero after six or seven years, when the fund has been paid back.<p>Today's securities market includes more than 250 different "B" share funds. Not surprisingly, the size and terms of the "loan" can vary greatly from company to company. The Kemper B funds, for example, offer a 3% commission to the broker and collect .75% for six years. The Alliance B funds pay a 5.5% commission and collect 1% a year for six years; IDS pays 5% and takes back 1% over seven years. Perhaps the most aggressive is Keystone, which pays 4% but then assesses 1.25% a year for seven years. If each of these funds earns a 10% yearly return, the annual loan rates would be approximately 13%, 7%, 12.3%, and 21%, respectively. <p>At the end of these various periods, IDS, Kemper, Alliance, and Keystone convert their "B" shares to "A" shares, which means the deferred sales charges stop. Not so the "B" funds offered by Prudential-Bache, Merrill Lynch, Dean Witter, Eaton Vance, and John Hancock. These fund companies keep collecting on the "loan" indefinitely__or until the shares are sold. Investors who are confused about whether their fund converts or keeps paying interest forever may have a hard time finding out; when contacted recently, a Merrill Lynch shareholder services representative did not know.<p>So what's the third rule of thumb? Invest only in "B" share funds that convert to "A" shares after a reasonable period. A "B" fund that takes 1% or less a year out of the portfolio and converts after six years will probably cost about the same as a front-end loaded fund. Except, that is, for investments of more than $50,000 in any one fund family.<p>On front-end commissions, mutual funds offer what's known as break-points__essentially discounts for high-volume customers. Investors pay the standard (published) commission rate on the first $50,000; for the next $50,000, they'll usually pay about a percent less, and for the next $100,000, another percent will get lopped off. At the $250,000 point, another percent goes away, until they get to $1 million. Investors with more than $1 million to invest can pretty much dictate terms. As an example, a $170,000 investment in the <a name="FUND:CABDX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CABDX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Alliance Capital Growth & Income A Fund</b></a> costs the published 5.5% rate for the first $50,000, a 4.5% rate for the next $50,000, and a 3.5% rate for the remaining $70,000. The effective overall commission rate would be 4.38%.<p>With "B" shares, there are no break-points. Most__but not all__fund families have rules against putting more than $100,000 into "B" shares. What most investors don't realize, however, is that money put into "B" shares doesn't count toward a total break-point calculation. Thus, if an investor puts $55,000 into a "B" share fund and $145,000 into an "A" share fund with the same company, the company will credit only the $145,000 toward its break-point calculations.<p>"B" funds are also poor vehicles for moving money in and out of a fund on a regular basis. Wes Bigler, a financial planner in Atlanta, reports a particularly vexing problem with his retired clients. If the portfolio is generating $400 a month in dividends, he might have the fund send $300 to the client and reinvest the remainder, so the account will grow with inflation. However, some fund groups will credit a commission "loan" to the reinvested amount and take a back-end charge out of the distributions. "They tell me they're working on the problem," he says. "But it isn't fixed yet."<p>Despite all this, there are some instances when "B" shares make sense. Consider, for example, an investor who's over age 5912 and wants to roll money from a company pension plan into mutual funds in a personal Individual Retirement Account. Many fund groups will waive the surrender charge for distributions from a retirement plan. That means that the broker will get paid by the fund company, but the investor may not have to pay back all of the loan. The same is true for older investors. Any "B" fund surrender charge will be waived if the investor should happen to die before the "loan" is paid off.<p>As the mutual fund industry moves from 8.5% front-end commissions to low-loads with trails to "B" shares, the trend is pretty clear: Funds that are sold through brokers are eliminating the front-end commissions in favor of ongoing compensation for (theoretically, at least) ongoing service. This trend first reached its logical conclusion with so-called "wrap fee" accounts, which are managed portfolios sold primarily through brokerage houses. <p>In most cases, wrap accounts are sold without a front-end sales charge but with a fixed annual fee that covers all expenses__the broker's commission, the portfolio manager's salary, and all the costs of buying and selling stocks. Brokers will often say that this eliminates any incentive to run up trading costs and churn an account. But the fees charged by wrap accounts are astronomical by mutual fund standards__typically up to 3% of assets. The theory seems to be that if investors pay managers and brokers as much as they would make by churning the account, these advisors won't have any reason to cheat them. <p>Recently, a number of fee-only financial planners have created a more reasonable version of this concept. They'll assemble a portfolio of the top-performing no-load funds and charge between .6% and 1% of assets each year to watch over the money. Typically, investors also get ongoing financial planning service included in the deal. Add in the expenses for the funds, and this brings the total cost to below 2%__and possibly much lower. A number of commission-based planners are now doing the same thing with load funds. By offsetting any commissions they earn against the fee, they offer exactly the same price to their clients.<p>A number of mutual funds are offering essentially the same deal. The funds are so new that the nomenclature is still being worked out; some companies call them "C" shares, some call them "D" shares, and some call them "level-load" funds. In any case, they pay no up-front commission to the planner or broker, but instead deliver a somewhat higher trail commission of between .65% and 1.25% a year. At this writing, there are more than 50 of these funds on the market, including nine managed by the Thomson Fund Group. The American Capital Group in Houston has recently announced that it will offer its full family of funds with a level-load option. <p>As the creative juices flow in the mutual fund industry, it has become increasingly difficult to tally up how much investors are paying through the alphabet soup of "B," and "C," or "D" shares. Investors should get in the habit of toting up the amount being billed out of the portfolio either directly by a fee-only planner or through various front-end, deferred, and trail commissions. If they have trouble with the calculations, they should ask their advisor to sort them out. Chances are, they'll get a straight answer. If not, then they should take their money elsewhere. <p>Robert N. Veres edits and publishes a monthly newsletter for professional financial advisors.<p>-----<p>A FUND SHOPPER'S GUIDE<p>Here's a breakdown of how today's brokers can get paid for selling mutual funds.<p>"A" Shares. The traditional load fund arrangement, where the investor pays a commission to a broker right off the top of his investment.<p>"B" Shares. The broker still gets a commission for selling these funds, but the fund company fronts the money and then gradually recoups it out of the investor's account.<p>"C" and "D" Shares. Sometimes called level-load funds, the broker gets no commission up front. Instead, he gets an annual payment called a trail commission out of the investor's account.<p>Wrap Fees. Mutual fund accounts that pay no up-front commission, but rather a fixed annual percentage of assets that covers the broker's commission and all fund expenses.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

