		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Cover: A History Lesson</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Cover: A History Lesson</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Land vs. Stocks<p>
By John Fried<p>
Superman's foe, Lex Luther, thought he had a surefire plan for turning a profit on land: buy property along the San Andreas Fault and then sink the western half of California with a nuclear device. Result: instant beachfront. Short of such extreme measures, land speculation can be an unpredictable enterprise. The outcome can vary widely, as some of the following examples show:<p>
Portland, Oregon: 1975, $10,000 per 10,000-square-foot lot; 1995, $50,000. Appreciation: 400 percent.*<p>
San Jose, California: 1975, $14,500 per 10,000-square-foot lot; 1995, $200,000. Appreciation: 1,279.3 percent.*<p>
Wisconsin farmland: 1975, $434 an acre; 1995, $1,065 an acre. Appreciation: 145 percent.**<p>
Texas rural land: 1975, $461 an acre; 1995, $727 an acre. Appreciation: 57.7 percent.***<p>
These prices are typically the kinds of quotes bandied about when people are touting their land investments. But factor in taxes and inflation, and these increases can deflate rapidly. Also, return on land is based primarily on the income generated from it -- timber, crops, real estate.<p>
The price indexes compiled by the National Council of Real Estate Investment Fiduciaries come the closest to doing for land what the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index does for stocks. The NCREIF indexes are widely used as benchmarks by institutional managers to track the total return of properties across the U.S., and they take into account the appreciation as well as income derived from the property. But for purposes of comparison, NCREIF's statistics date back only nine years. For this period, the annualized total return has been 21.87 percent for timberland, 6.26 percent for farmland, and 3.74 percent on property.<p>
During the same period, the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index has returned 14.8 percent annually, according to Ibbotson Associates. Land, though, has literally proved more precious than gold, which has returned an average of only 1.7 percent a year since 1985.<p>
*Data from the Urban Land Institute. 
**Data from the USDA, Economic Research Service. 
***Data from the Real Estate Center at Texas A&M University.<p>
KEYWORDS:
Investment, development, property

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

