<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Home-Run Stocks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Home-Run Stocks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jonathan Butler<p>Manufactured homes aren't just for trailer parks anymore. In 1995, the number shipped increased 11.7 percent from 1994; it should jump 5 to 10 percent in 1996. Why? Manufactured homes can cost half as much per square foot to build as traditional homes. Manufactured-home stocks may be good buys now, too, since rising employment means more demand for low- to mid-priced homes, says John Diffendal, an analyst at J. C. Bradford in Nashville. Look for companies that sell and finance what they manufacture -- they're less vulnerable to rising interest rates.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

