	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Atherton's Little Acres</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Atherton's Little Acres</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>Atherton, California, one of America's ten wealthiest communities, lies in a world of its own. It has sports heroes, silicon tycoons, attentive police, and million-dollar acres.<p>By James Conaway<p>I am riding in a silver Mercedes through the twilit byways -- there are no "streets" -- of Atherton, California. My driver, a real-estate agent, wears a pink linen suit with a gold, diamond-encrusted bee pinned to one shoulder; she is smiling. "I just sold this one," she says of a nice but not extraordinary house, "and the lot, less than four acres, for about four. They'll tear it down and build something larger. They won't subdivide."<p>Her name is Barbara Tyler, and last year she brought in more money than any Coldwell Banker agent on earth -- "just under 50," as she  
puts it, the missing noun being million. <p>"Most of the buyers are from Silicon Valley, but we also get stockbrokers, attorneys, bankers. We get Taiwanese, some from Hong Kong, Japan. We get sports stars. We get the VCs and the start-ups."
VCs are venture capitalists, and start-ups are the founders of companies, usually in electronics. The house standing before us in massive granite splendor, however, was built not by a VC, start-up, or sports star but by an Asian investor who has never lived in it. A "spec," it is priced at just under ten and is Barbara's costliest offering: six bedrooms, pool, tennis court, gym, a "Den or Worship Room," according to the brochure,  gold chandeliers from Italy, wood paneling from South Africa, and a ten-car underground parking lot with a driveway sloped so as not to scrape the undercarriage of a Ferrari.<p>Two large houses are going up on verdant lots to the west; whether ultimately Tudor or Mediterranean, they are presently just tons of upended plywood and stacks of roofing tiles. Nearby is a copse of unplanted trees, their root balls wrapped. "This lot sold for about one point six. They'll have about five in it.... This one cost four point six, just for the land."<p>We pass a vibrant green polo field where a groom is walking a horse draped in a blanket. The bell tower on an old Spanish-style convent is visible in the background, a pastoral scene suffused with soft light. "The Menlo Circus Club," says Tyler of Atherton's curiously named country club. "It defines prime."<p>An acre is worth at least $1 million in Atherton. It is one of the wealthiest communities in America, according to Census Bureau figures for income and property value. I have come here, 30 miles south of San Francisco -- "mid-peninsula," as they say -- to see what sort of people live in this maze of lanes, drives, avenues, courts, even a "forest."<p>It isn't the 2,500 houses that distinguish the place but the fecundity of what obscures them: trees, flowering shrubs, walls and iron fences draped with ivy. Atherton's 7,400 residents include remnants of old money -- like Madeleine Haas Russell, an aging member of the Levi Strauss family -- and inheritors of fortunes made in various endeavors, from hardware to toothpaste. But those that attract the most attention are the athletes -- Willie Mays, San Francisco Giant Barry Bonds, former 49er Joe Montana and 49er wide receiver Jerry Rice, former Raider Jim Plunkett -- and businessmen, such as <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> and Don Fisher, founder and chairman of the <a name="NYSE:GPS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gap</b></a>. There are also 72 horses. All take advantage of Atherton's natural cover and protean photosynthesis.<p>Atherton is also distinguished by what it doesn't have: businesses, a cemetery, a golf course. A resident has written a fantasy about outer-space visitors in the year 3500 who discover vestiges of a "culture...distinctly different from that of the more advanced civilization of others who adjoined the area.... Small groups of perhaps no more than a single family occupied plots having a surprising uniformity of area of approximately one acre."<p>With the exception of some heavily built upon hills to the west, Atherton is flat, which adds to the seclusion of individual residences. It is bounded on the west by Woodside -- also expensive, but, as one Athertonian puts it, "too...remote" -- and by Interstate 280. To the south lies Menlo Park, highly coveted by new-home buyers but not quite Atherton, either. To the east lies the Bayshore Freeway and to the north Redwood City, a gritty dose of service-industry-cum-bungalow reality that Athertonians must confront at Woodside Road.<p>The one-acre zoning, the rules that houses be set well back from property lines and screened by trees, and the limits on the square footage of houses -- 18 percent of the total property -- have stimulated ongoing negotiations among real-estate agents, builders, planning commissioners, architects, and lawyers, a mano a mano financed mostly by new money.<p>The mayor, Didi Fisher -- no relation to Don -- attributes the influx to executives profiting from initial public offerings of stocks. "IPOs have brought a lot of new people to town," she explains. "They can easily commute to San Francisco, San Jose, Silicon Valley, and Palo Alto.... The school populations are booming. There are more kids in Little League than ever."<p>She wears slacks and a navy blazer, the daylight ensemble of choice; she serves without pay. "This is a scenic and rural area," she adds, but civilization lies all around. The town is having trouble getting new citizens to attend meetings about crime prevention and to appreciate the value of knowing how many children and what sorts of cars their neighbors have.<p>She gives me a copy of the Atherton Resident Handbook, which provides a brief history -- "This area of ancient live oaks, mild climate, and accessible fish and game was once the traveling ground of the small tribe of Costano Indians. It came under Spanish rule in 1769." The handbook also advises me to leave a house key at the police station and to have my children fingerprinted in case they are kidnapped.<p>The plate on Marion Oster's car -- TREGDDS, for "tree goddess" -- was a gift from her husband in recognition of her efforts in getting an ordinance passed that preserves the oaks, pines, cedars, ash, redwoods, eucalyptus, and exotics, such as puzzle trees, that were planted during garden competitions of yore. "Anything that is four feet in circumference or more and at least four feet from the ground can't be cut. Real easy," she explains.<p>Marion is supervising the filing of index cards by another volunteer in Heritage Room, the history wing of Atherton's pretty little Spanish-colonial town hall on shady, residential Ashfield Lane, across the street from the train station and the modern, one-story, commendably low-impact municipal office building and police department. A children's picture book showing what people do all day in Atherton would have pages devoted to agreeable, middle-aged women like these, attending meetings of the Tree Committee, the Friends of the Atherton Community Library, the Lindenwood Homes Association, the Holbrook Palmer Park Foundation, the Woodside-Atherton Garden Guild, or the Atherton Dames, who sponsor the summer barbecue, the Halloween and Christmas parties, and the Easter-egg hunt at Holbrook Palmer Park.<p>The same book would show a train stopping at the quaint station with the tile roof. The train whistle would be tooting. Young, hungry execs would be boarding the 6:30 a.m. to San Francisco, vice presidents the 7 o'clock, and, just before the 9 o'clock, graying CEOs would be stepping out of cars, some of them chauffeur-driven, their sartorial bias -- pinstripes, subdued glen plaid -- more Greenwich than West Coast. <p>Domestics get off at this same station, having come from South San Francisco and elsewhere, though most of Atherton's "help" live in rooms and cottages built for the purpose.<p>Among the town's support staff are 24 police officers, some of whom are leaving the police station next door to ticket drivers out on El Camino -- mostly passersby from Redwood City and Menlo Park. As recently as two years ago, Atherton's police officers were among the least compensated in San Mateo County, before the town agreed to bring the salaries into parity. The beefy force is paid for by a surcharge, approved by the voters. "It allows us to give a more personal service," I am told by the chief, Steve Cader, who wears 
a jacket and tie. Personal service includes returning keys left in the ignitions of parked cars and picking up newspapers for those who have gone to Hawaii or "the desert."<p>More than half the homes -- 1,400 -- have alarm systems wired to the police station, and most other residences have arrangements with private security agencies. Apparently the word is out, for robberies are rare in Atherton, and there has been only one murder, back in the 1950s; it involved a husband and wife. "Our guys know at night who's moving around and who belongs here," says the chief.<p>In 1860, Faxon Dean Atherton -- described in a pamphlet published by the Atherton Civic Interest League as "a native of Massachusetts, engaged in commodities" -- bought some 500 acres south of San Francisco. It was part of what had been the immense Rancho de las Pulgas; in the summer, he and his family traveled down by coach and then by train to escape the fog and cold of the city. They were joined by other wealthy San Franciscans -- the metals smelter Thomas H. Selby, the banker Joseph A. Donohoe, and, later, the mining magnate James R. Flood, who built what is still described as "that awful wedding cake of a house," which was demolished in 1934.<p>Atherton's property was divvied up among his children. Those and other estates were self-supporting, although fine comestibles were regularly brought down from San Francisco. Accounts of the period recall a lavish Brigadoon -- full of good horseflesh, optimism, and the pleasures of country life.<p>In 1923, the town was threatened with absorption by Menlo Park, and Atherton's fathers rushed to incorporate. The name they favored, Fair Oaks, had already been assigned, so they used the founder's name instead to define their 4,486-acre retreat with its 650 souls. The town's independence thus preserved, the fathers banned commerce and set one acre as the zoning minimum, unusual at the time. The acres were measured to the middle of the roads that fronted them, giving rise to what is known today all over America as "the Atherton acre."<p>Nan chapman, the first female member of the town council, holds a book of photographs, Gabriel Moulin's San Francisco Peninsula: Town & Country Homes, 19101930. One photograph shows a couple in a garden: he in white trousers and shoes, she in a white chiffon dress and broad-brimmed hat. "That was my friend's grandmother," she says of Mrs. Clarence R. Walter, wife of a wealthy San Francisco merchant who summered in Atherton. The first time Nan went to dinner at the Walters', as a child in the 1940s, she "didn't know what a fish fork was. I certainly wasn't accustomed to a footman standing behind my chair while I ate."<p>Atherton was then, and still is, a haven from the city, from "its weather and hustle and bustle," as Nan puts it. "The average summer day here was 75 degrees and sunny." Today, when she walks around Atherton, it smells the way it always did, "the blossoms, the redwoods," she says. "The old berry bushes are still on the fence down by the club. People still cherish their privacy; each yard is its own little piece of paradise." What distinguishes it from earlier Atherton are that most people live here year-round now and share a degree of wealth. "Then, the rich were very rich -- there wasn't much in between. It's more of an even playing field now."<p>Athertonians still tend not to think about how much money somebody has; they are used to celebrity. "We don't go chasing Joe Montana down the street for his autograph," Chapman says. She remembers watching the 49ers practice at nearby Menlo School, before they moved to their own quarters, and talking with quarterback Frankie Albert on the grass. "One of the hardest things," she pauses. "I don't want to say 'yuppies,' but some people who move here want everything they had on 15 acres somewhere else -- swimming pool, cabana, exercise room, tennis court, three-car garage, and a 7,800-square-foot statement house."<p>"This is a low-maintenance area." Jeanne Jackson is explaining the local fondness for ivy and agapanthus, which require no care. She is an artist and her husband is an investment banker with Hambrecht & Quist, in San Francisco. The Jacksons have been coming to their secluded weekend retreat in Atherton for 32 years. They originally sought advice from late landscape architect Tommy Church, who helped many here. "Tommy came and he looked, and he said, 'You can't possibly afford to turn this into a garden,'" the backyard being quite large. "I asked what we should do, and he said, 'Water it!'"<p>The Jacksons' house was decorated by the late Michael Taylor, another prominent appointer of Atherton homes, whose style could best be described as monumental: mission-like tables covered with art books, a massive stone mantel, a sofa so deep it enfolds the sitter. Big windows give the sitting room a feeling of comfort and space, but the kitchen remains resolutely in the 1960s. "We didn't redo our kitchen when other people were redoing theirs," she says, having made me a cup of coffee in the microwave. "Now everybody's into bathrooms." But she and others like her feel that their houses, once considered adequate, even beautiful, have been relegated to a category known as the teardown.<p>Ann Ramsay owns five acres and a ranch-style house at the corner of Alameda de las Pulgas and Polhemus Avenue, little more than a mile away. "My friends say, 'You live in a teardown!' Well, I don't care, this was my family's place," she says.<p>In the 1950s, Ramsay rode horses for miles across unimpeded meadows; her sisters later left with their shares of an estate that had belonged to their grandparents, the Wiels, another resonant name in Atherton. Ann stayed for the memories, the weather, and the proximity to the airport, which is not so near that the planes can be heard.<p>She recently had installed what may be the most valuable two-acre vineyard in California, each acre being worth at least $1 million. The cost of putting in the cuttings of pinot noir and sauvignon blanc was another $50,000. Ramsay will eventually sell the grapes to a winery for a pittance, relatively speaking, but she likes the idea of the old place producing. "People drop by and thank me for planting it," she says. "I don't care what the land's worth -- they couldn't blast me out of here with dynamite."<p>Genevieve Merrill sits in the kitchen of what was the gardener's cottage on what is left of the Moulton estate. She has white hair and smokes a cigarette with enjoyment. "The founders thought this was country," she explains, "and they wanted it to stay that way. Growth has been controlled. People resent it sometimes, but it has saved the place."<p>The cottage's windows were salvaged from James Flood's wedding-cake construction; another small house on the property came from the old Hahn estate. "My mother-in-law's mother was Mrs. Moulton," Merrill says. "She loved to build things. She settled here in the 1890s and built near Mrs. Winchester, then bought this from the Bassetts."<p>The old names hang around like ghosts; not everybody recognizes them today. The big properties are gone, with the exception of the estate owned by Madeleine Haas Russell, who lives here part of the year. The Flood estate, now the neighborhood on Lindenwood just east of us, is crowded with houses that are small by Atherton standards. Still, Genevieve Merrill doesn't see any great alteration in Atherton: The arrival of new money can change things only so much because there are just a handful of building lots left. "We're maxed out," she says.<p>The sign next to the drive that leads into the Menlo Circus Club -- prime zero -- reads: caution: children, horses at play.<p>"The club" (to say "the country club" is to refer to the one in Woodside) is rooted in the high jinks of a bunch of young equestriennes and the town's relentless charity. An impromptu circus organized by 11- and 12-year-olds with ponies in 1920 on the estate of W. B. Weir was a success, and Mrs. Weir persuaded the girls to turn it into an annual benefit. Two years later, according to an informal history of the club, "a group of parents and other interested persons gathered together on the veranda of the Hahn home to discuss the matter."<p>That is, to establish a permanent home for young riders, as well as a place for their parents to play polo and bridge near the Sacred Heart school. The result is this 30-acre expanse with pool, tennis courts, and stables -- and an annual Class A horse show that brings 500 fine saddlebreds and hunters-jumpers into the field for a week. It raises money for the Peninsula Center for the Blind and is not to be confused with the Tally-Ho, which raises money for the Packard Children's Hospital at Stanford.<p>The horse show also provides considerable work for the haulers of horse manure. In Atherton, this tends to separate the old householders from the new, who often object to smells endemic to the rural and scenic. One woman called her council member to demand that the police remove a pile of manure from the road in front of her house. "Why don't you just get a shovel?" asked the council member. The woman called back later to ask what she should do with the manure. "Well, why don't you put it on your rosebushes?"<p>I have been granted an interview with the club's manager, Ron Dodson, but first I take a tour of the stables: brass lamps, lots of hanging tack, green half doors open against the white clapboards, 72 stalls, and horses, all guarded by a whippet and a corgi. Lodging a mount costs almost $400 a month, training excluded. Forty thousand dollars' worth of rubber bricks has just been installed to prevent the tenants from slipping. Outside, in the ring, the trainer is taking 
a horse over jumps flanked by potted plants. The scene is watched intently by a teenage girl in helmet and chaps, while her mother waits in a station wagon.<p>Ron Dodson has a shaved head and a white goatee. He was hired at the club in 1962 as a waiter. "I made a dollar fifty an hour," he says, laughing at the memory. "They gave me a raise to a buck seventy-five." Now he has his own residence within walking distance and plays golf in his spare time, though there isn't much of that. "Total customer satisfaction is my job. I have a lot of bosses -- 369 of them. They all paid their money, and they have to be paid attention to."<p>He gives me the nickel tour of the club, also decorated by Michael Taylor. "Michael's stuff is heavier than hell. See that?" he asks, referring to the top of a column that serves as a side table. "It's a rock. We had to buy a hydraulic lift to move the damn thing."
Dodson is black, the only African-American I have seen. I've already heard disparaging remarks made by club members about Willie Mays and Barry Bonds, who is recently divorced. I ask about discrimination. Ron says, "There isn't any. Plenty of Jews belong, black guests come all the time. There aren't any black members because...." He ponders and says that, other than those of the sports stars, "I don't think there are any black families in Atherton."<p>Henry Cartan's family moved down in the early 1940s from San Francisco and bought the old Watkins house, a beautiful white Gothic Revival built by a steamship captain. "I had a ball," he says. "I was too young to be drafted. I hung around the club with a bunch of no-goods, swimming. I drove a Model A for the Suburban Water Company" -- which his father owned. "My friends called it Bourbon & Company.
"Oh, what spoiled kids we were! We didn't get bombed like kids today. There was no dope.... We threw eggs at the police on El Camino and had to sweep the parking lot outside the station. Today we'd be in cuffs."<p>He lives in a different house now. It, too, is grand, though not by current Atherton standards. He manages three family ranches from San Francisco, to which he commutes. "It's delightful," he says. "I take the 8:02 and I'm in by 9. I take the 4:25 and I'm here by 5. I read the paper or farm magazines on the way up, I snooze on the way back."<p>Willie Mays is Henry Cartan's neighbor. I inquire about this, and Henry shrugs. "Willie has a beautiful arm, but he came over here one morning in a blue-velour bathrobe and read me the riot act. The kids, you see, had been throwing eggs at his dogs." <p>He called up Mays recently and asked him to sign a baseball for a friend. But the Cartans did not invite the Mayses to their big Christmas party.<p>We pass through Cartan's regal living room with its Orientals and Victorian windows revealing the porte cochere. In the foyer stands a lacquered case containing intricately carved figurines of men and women and a couple of monkeys engaged in happy coitus. He removes a pair and uncouples and rearranges them in a different attitude. 
"It used to be that the rich weren't so young," he says, reflecting further on Atherton. "We didn't have the Larry Ellisons of Oracle, the rich baby boomers. If one of them bought this house today, it would be bulldozed."<p>Willie Mays's ranch is a teardown, too, but not Joe Montana's house. I have been told by several people of its replica of the Sistine Chapel ceiling, a view of which is sought after even by Athertonians with provenance. So is the glass case in Jim Plunkett's home that contains his 1970 Heisman Trophy and his 1981 Super Bowl MVP award. There is goodwill toward most of these sports stars, whose "lives are run by agents," according to another neighbor.<p>Most of the celebrities are outward looking, socially and professionally, and use Atherton as a safe and anonymous base, but then that's also true of Athertonians in general, old and young. Theirs is a rather chilly democracy based on one's achievement or one's ancestors -- i.e., money. Decorum is key.<p>"It's the privacy," Jim Plunkett says of Atherton's appeal when I finally reach him by telephone. "That and the proximity to Stanford University." He is a member of Stanford's golf club and sponsors the annual women's tournament. A Coors franchise takes him periodically to the San Joaquin Valley, and promotional television and radio work for the Raiders removes him regularly from Atherton. Weekends are spent at home, "driving the kids around. Here they all go to private schools, so their friends don't live nearby. It's just something you have to do."<p>The Plunketts' two-story house was built in 1983, replacing a teardown from the 1950s. "We just needed more room, with the kids. We're actually in a hollow," he adds, almost apologetic. "Some of these new houses dwarf the properties they sit on."<p>The symbiotic relationship between Silicon Valley and the founders of companies has produced far more Athertonians than professional football or its equivalents. "We call it the Internet-scape." This from a young venture capitalist who is part of it; when limits on selling new equities were lifted, "those guys started dumping condos in Mountain View and buying in Atherton."<p>Bill Draper, prominent Republican and Athertonian of long standing, founded Sutter Hill Ventures in the early 1960s, then one of three firms in venture capital on the peninsula. Now there are more than 100, and Bill has a new company, Draper International. "Because of Stanford, the economics are great," he says over an early breakfast at Buck's in Woodside, before driving his Mercedes convertible to San Francisco, 35 minutes and several Mozart concerti away. "The graduates all want to stay.<p>"You could drive around New Canaan, Connecticut, and see more-beautiful houses, but the East doesn't have the booming electronics, the vibrancy you get from the interplay of cutting-edge technology and business, or the beautiful weather."<p>"That's the real reason Silicon Valley and the rest of it happened here," adds Draper's former partner, Paul Wythes. "The Big One: weather. There's no humidity. And no mosquitoes, no flies. You're not breathing Bel Air air, and the foothills block the fog. The nights are a bit chilly."<p>So that child's picture book of Atherton would as likely show people driving to resplendent office buildings in Palo Alto as well as in San Francisco. It would show them riding and playing tennis at the club, teeing off on the Stanford Golf Course or the one at the Menlo Country Club, in Woodside. It would show them driving the kids and shopping at Draeger's in Menlo Park, where they would eat warm duck salad in the mezzanine bistro and watch courtesy clerks in aprons and ties bagging some of the 60 olive oils and special cheese sourdough bread. It would show others in Jackson Hole or Miami, calling Draeger's long-distance to order ginger or a certain kind of olive.<p>At home, in the evening, older Athertonians would be seen pouring martinis and discussing Phar Lap, the famous Australian Thoroughbred that died mysteriously after winning the race at Agua Caliente in 1932 and was buried here -- part of him, anyway, though that is still in dispute. "He died eating the oleanders," one Athertonian would be saying; another, "No, it was the colic."
The younger adults would be shown driving children back from Little League, before going off to dine at Stars in Palo Alto. And a few would be "house thumping" -- checking out the latest neighborhood construction.<p>"The trouble with Atherton," says the only resident developer, Kevin White, a slender man of 43 in a black suit with hair to match, "is that you'll be living in a home, and somebody will make you an offer for it you can't refuse."<p>He sold one house and is building a larger one that resembles a classical temple, with eight big columns and a stone-like facade. "We call it Palladian," he says. Although it is unfinished, he and his family live in it on Faxon Forest, a road he created and named. "In the last five years, I have bought and developed more land in Atherton than anybody -- about 50 million."<p>A new stove sits in the foyer, waiting to be put into a kitchen the size of a small gym; the parlor, where we sit, with dusty black floors and an incomplete fireplace, contains the requisite monumental couch and French-provincial side chairs. "This spot is the center of our universe," he says. "So quiet. Just close enough to the club."<p>The house is 10,000 square feet, not including the basement. The land was part of the old 15-acre Heller estate -- "that's Wells Fargo Bank and stagecoach money," says Kevin. He grew up in wealthy, neighboring Hillsborough, "but I have roots in San Francisco," as did old Faxon Dean Atherton -- financial ones, anyway, that allowed White to move down-peninsula to what was, even then, a nascent development.<p>White bought the estate, he says, directly from the family. "The people who bought in here later are among the wealthiest in California. The lots sold for an average of one point eight five, and I encouraged them to buy more. As a result, two families each bought three lots, and another family two. They're the equivalents of a Picasso or a van Gogh." We go out onto the porch. Sawhorses sit in the weeds; a child's sneakers lie on the steps. "I'm spending three million on construction, and that doesn't include the raised pool or the fountain, all surrounded by French limestone."<p>The clutter will be cleared away, of course, but for the moment the scene suggests a hybrid of the Loire Valley and Appalachia. His neighbor's house reminds me of a small cruise ship. One of the others will cost about $5 million to complete. When I point out that these statement houses offend many Athertonians, he says, "People who do great things in life are entitled to some self-expression. This is a cul-de-sac. If you don't like the way they look, don't come down it."<p>The night before I leave, I drop by the Menlo Circus Club's Thursday-night buffet. The women, tastefully if brightly dressed, smile; the men look proprietary in their suits and blazers and one Black Watch sport jacket. Dusk settles over the polo field as grooms and mounts wend stableward and members tuck into shrimp and crab claws -- nothing molded here -- beef tenderloin, rock cod, and "chicken Parmesan" from chafing dishes. There is a timelessness about the scene, a geographic free float: the top end of Anywhere, USA, circa 1950.<p>I remember being told by Nan Chapman, "So far, we have been able to keep progress and the wolves from our doors. It's not so much that things are the same but that I can feel the same way about them that I once felt."<p>The base price of this, the best of recollected America, with the best weather and the best proximity to airplanes and electronic commerce, is $1 million an acre. That's an Atherton acre. A house will set you back another one point two, at least. That's if you're not encumbered by a teardown and don't need to express yourself.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Real Estate Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
