<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-The Richest Towns in America</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-The Richest Towns in America</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jeff Blyskal<p>America's wealthiest towns are the stuff of fiction and bizarre fact. Kings Point, Long Island, was the prototype for F. Scott Fitzgerald's fictional West Egg in The Great Gatsby. The Coronado Country Club section of El Paso, Texas, prohibits most outdoor lights so that its mountainside residents can enjoy the sparkling views of the city without distraction. Rich towns are home to Greg Norman (Jupiter Island, Florida), Charles Schwab (Atherton, California), Mary Higgins Clark (Saddle River, New Jersey), and Marshall Field (Lake Forest, Illinois).<p>These megabucks locales are on our list of America's 300 wealthiest towns, a registry that is the result of painstaking statistical research as well as hundreds of phone calls to chambers of commerce, post offices, real-estate brokers, and other local experts. Some of our discoveries:<p>>Although 26 states are represented, including Kentucky, Maine, Minnesota, North Carolina, and Oklahoma, the state with the most rich towns is New York: It has 81 of our 300. Long Island alone has four towns in the top ten.<p>>While the high-income communities we've identified contain a respectable percentage of households that bring in more than $150,000 (21.5 percent), they also have a significant percentage earning less than $25,000 (14.5 percent).<p>>Three of the most resonant town names in America -- Beverly Hills, Greenwich, and Lake Forest -- ranked only in the 80s. Their five-digit populations are among the largest on our list; many of our wealthiest towns have little more than 3,000 or 4,000 people.<p>>Resorts -- Aspen, the Hamptons, Nantucket -- do not make our list because their wealthy temporary residents derive and report their incomes elsewhere.<p>>The triple-gated community of Rolling Hills, California -- with a population of 1,748 -- leads the 300 with an average income of $305,700 and an average home value of $587,900. The community, built in the 1930s, permits only one-story white houses, house trims in earth tones, and white wooden fences. Its street names -- Buggy Whip Drive and Horseshoe Lane -- are testimony to the town developer's fondness for horses: Residents must also give up a ten-foot strip of property for horse trails. Myron Floren, who played accordion on The Lawrence Welk Show, lives there.<p>>The Upper East Side of Manhattan -- on our separate list of city neighborhoods -- has the single largest concentration of wealth in the nation. Counting only annual income and home value, it is the site of $21 billion in riches.<p>>Grand old estates -- the kind that once signaled wealth -- are increasingly being broken up into smaller and smaller parcels, and even smaller lots are being chopped up. On Jupiter Island, Florida, the newly wealthy are building million-dollar homes -- monumental in size -- some on lots no bigger than 90 by 100 feet. In South Barrington, Illinois, mock Norman castles stand side by side where pumpkins once grew.<p>>Some preferences never change. Look for the rich by the water, close to horses, or near a great golf course (one Illinois town on our list is actually called Golf, and, of course, there's Pebble Beach, California).<p>We worked on this project with Scan/US, a Los Angeles based firm specializing in geomarket-analysis software that offers highly detailed income and population data. You, your neighbors, and everyone else in the country live inside the borders of six million "census blocks," demographic constructions that are each roughly the size of one city block. Scan/US has assembled these blocks into 1.3 million "microgrids," measuring between one-sixteenth and one mile square and covering every populated inch of ground in the U.S.<p>Data from the U.S. Census Bureau, which Scan/US has updated to 1995 based on economic and demographic trends, were electronically poured into these grids. We used this system to scour the nation for communities with average annual incomes of $100,000 or more. We conducted searches both by place (including incorporated and unincorporated towns that are recognized by the Census Bureau) and by zip code, because, oddly, neither picks up all pockets of wealth. For example, in New England, New York, and Wisconsin, incorporated towns are recognized not as "places" but as "minor civil divisions." Because of this and other peculiarities, the Census does not recognize as places well-known affluent addresses like Greenwich, Old Greenwich, Cos Cob, Riverside, and New Canaan, Connecticut; Short Hills and Essex Fells, New Jersey; Lincoln and Sherborn, Massachusetts; and even Pebble Beach. They did, however, show up in zip-code data. We took apart or combined zip-code areas to build towns, deleting from our list places and zips with fewer than 400 residents -- Gibson Island, Maryland, and Eyak, Alaska, for example.<p>In some cases -- as when Pelham Manor, New York, was removed from the Pelham zip -- the leftovers did not clear the $100,000-plus income bar; on the other hand, when the town of Cochituate was extracted from the zip of Wayland, Massachusetts, Wayland's average income rose. We checked population figures with each town. In other cases, combining one high-income zip with one or more relatively low-income zips in the same city resulted in an overall average household income that didn't make the cut. Where several high-income places are part of larger high-income zip codes, we opted for the greater detail -- so in Illinois, we list South Barrington, Barrington Hills, and North Barrington, all places within the Barrington zip code. The town of Barrington, however, didn't make our list.<p>Some towns are carved up in ways meaningful to the Census Bureau and local functionaries, but odd to most everyone else. There are five Chevy Chases on our list -- Chevy Chase, Chevy Chase Town, Chevy Chase Village Town, Chevy Chase Section Three, and Chevy Chase Section Five. In the middle of these Chevy Chases is a town called Martin's Additions; it also made our list.<p>Of 500 $100,000-plus communities, we chose the top 300 for our final list. To rank these well-to-do hamlets, we used two key indicators of wealth -- average household income and average home value (we consider the latter essentially the price of admission to each town).<p>Our Scan/US software also enabled us to comb every street in every major U.S. city to nail down statistically the 50 wealthiest neighborhoods. Identifying neighborhoods, however, required a different methodology, so we kept this ranking separate from the list of towns (see list on page 72).<p>To pinpoint neighborhoods, we started with the 23 cities that have populations of 500,000 or more. We then located all microgrids where household income averaged at least $100,000 and built proximate microgrids into neighborhood clusters. Unfortunately, the boundaries of most neighborhoods are either nonexistent or nebulously drawn in the minds of local residents. Even where city-planning boards have roughly drawn official neighborhood lines, population and economic growth trends have little respect for such boundaries. So we defined ritzy neighborhoods by counting only $100,000-plus microgrids. Our thinking: This is the prime big-city acreage, where people like Ross Perot hang their hats (in his case, in the Preston Hollow area of Dallas).<p>To connect our microgrid compositions to local neighborhood names, we relied on a variety of maps, including some on CD-ROM, printed city maps produced commercially, and community/neighborhood maps from city-planning departments. We also fine-tuned locations and double-checked names with real-estate brokers and chambers of commerce.<p>Some cities contain wealthy independent municipalities that the locals consider neighborhoods. For example, Highland Park is a town completely surrounded by Dallas, yet residents see it as part of Dallas. Ponte Vedra, Florida, is just over the border from Jacksonville, yet that is the first place city residents think of when asked to name the richest neighborhood in town. We chose to list these locations in our city-neighborhood list rather than our rich-town list. Such anomalies are footnoted on the neighborhood list.
We couldn't catch up with or accurately assess a few new or suddenly rising neighborhoods. Realtors report that the Geist Lake area in Indianapolis, where homes are going for $750,000 to $3 million, has recently taken off. Three years ago, the Silver Creek area of San Jose didn't exist; today, it would probably rank high on our list if current numbers were available.<p>We also decided not to include neighborhood enclaves where we counted fewer than 1,000 people -- for example, Baltimore's Roland Park and Memphis's Chickasaw Gardens. Finally, to prevent neighborhoods in cities with a high cost of living, like New York and Los Angeles, from dominating the ratings, only the three highest-income neighborhoods from each city were included.<p>Neither our town nor our neighborhood list reflects differences in cost of living. The cost of living in the New York metropolitan area is more than twice that of living in the Louisville, Kentucky, metro area, which can effectively shrink the income differential between second-ranked Hewlett Bay Park, New York, with $348,500 in average income, and 196th-ranked Glenview Hills, Kentucky, with $168,800 in average income. A home that costs $573,000 in the CEO bedroom community of Saddle River, New Jersey, could be bought in Paradise Valley, Arizona, for just $321,000, according to the real-estate firm Coldwell Banker. Cost-of-living differentials, of course, also reflect the immutable wisdom of intangible market-demand forces -- the higher costs in New York suggest the area is more desirable than Kentucky or Arizona and simply worth the price.<p>The towns and neighborhoods in this top-350 ranking reflect a combined community of achievers and the fortunate. Overall, the average income of the one million households in our top 350 is $146,000 -- more than three times the national average of $44,000. The elegant homes and estates represented here have an average value of $413,000 -- four times the national average.<p>But all in all, these numbers are averages that give only a symbolic representation of the actual moneymaking power and property values in these communities. Beverly Hills homeowner David Geffen, for example, earns considerably more than that town's $137,100 average income. Former New Orleans Saints owner John W. Mecom's home, on Lazy Lane in River Oaks, is the most expensive property currently listed for sale in Houston at $8.9 million -- 19 times the neighborhood average of $464,882. Anyone interested?<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Real Estate

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/6pages.gif"><br>About 6 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
