	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Foreloaned is Forearmed</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Foreloaned is Forearmed</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Mortgage preapproval puts home buyers in the driver's seat<p>By Roy Furchgott<p>As the economy improves and home sellers regain clout in the real-estate market, buyers need every edge they can get. Many are finding one by getting approved for a mortgage before they even pick out a new home. "Twenty percent of our residential pipeline is pre-apps," says Glen Spears of Barnett Bank of Central Florida.<p>"I recommend preapproval for anyone purchasing for the first time, anyone who wants a negotiating edge with a seller, or a worrywart," says Nancy Boles of Fleet Mortgage in Columbia, South Carolina. <p>Unlike prequalification, in which the lender provides a more informal judgment as to how large a loan the buyer would qualify for, preapproval requires the buyer to actually apply for a loan, document assets and debts, go through a credit check, and pay an application fee, which may not be refundable. The credit check will reveal problems that could waylay your mortgage, giving you time to improve your credit without the pressure of a looming closing date. Preapproval also helps you secure top treatment from real-estate professionals, who are assured that you're not wasting their time on a fantasy. <p>Preapproval can improve your bargaining position, too. "Buyers can often negotiate up to a 5 percent better price with that commitment," says Spears. "They can close within days."<p>While preapproval is good for most home buyers, don't do it if you're six months away from buying. Some application documents expire in as few as 30 days, so you'd end up repeating the process.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowners, Real Estate Investing, Banking Industry, Mortgages<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

