	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05-Overhaul Monitor</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Overhaul Monitor</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Overhaul Monitor</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Personal Adviser  <p> OVERHAUL MONITOR <p>If you rebuild it, will home buyers come?  <p> By Roy Furchgott  <p> So it's finally time to ditch the '70s-vintage avocado-green decor in your kitchen. What do you replace it with if your goal is to increase your house's value by as much as the cost of the renovations? How can you make sure that potential buyers will like your new kitchen as much as you do?  <p> First, do no harm. For hard-to-install items, such as tile sand cabinets, concentrate on mainstream designs. "Make conservative decisions -- go with white or light cabinets rather than a green wash," says Mark Richardson, senior vice president of Case Design/Remodelingin Bethesda, Maryland. "The goal is to have something that would cause only a low percentage of the market to say, 'I don't like that.'" Express yourself with items that are easy to change, like paint, wallpaper, and furniture.  <p> Next, find out what the renovations are worth by getting anassessment. For $300 to $600, a bank-certified appraiser will look at your property and, with the help of the contractor, assess how much the improvements will increase its value. The assessmentis a must for getting an improvement loan from a bank.  <p> But Remodeling magazine's 199596 "Cost vs. Value Report," at $5.50 (202-736-3418), can function as a poor man's assessor,showing the estimated cost and return of various renovationsin 60 cities around the country. For example, adding a deck,while big in Birmingham, Alabama (138 percent expected returnon the renovation cost), is less popular in Lancaster, Pennsylvania(40 percent return). The reasons for the variations can be anything from regional taste to local weather conditions.  <p> Some improvements are fairly safe bets nationwide. Minor kitchen remodeling (refinishing counters and cabinets, updating appliances,and repainting) averages a 98 percent return. Adding a bathroom averages an 89 percent return. The worst returns come from replacing windows (69 percent return), replacing siding (68 percent return),and adding a home office (58 percent return).  <p> But in a sense, any remodeling job delivers a major return --improvements can reduce the capital-gains tax you pay when you sell your house. The cost of any renovation that adds value to your home, prolongs your home's life, or adapts it to a new use can be added to the cost basis of the house. When you sell your house, the cost basis is subtracted from the selling price, and you are taxed only on the remainder.  <p> Overspending and underspending are equally dangerous to return on investment. The law of diminishing returns says that the more you spend, the less you're likely to recover. "You don't wanta $1 million home in a neighborhood of $300,000 homes, but you might want a $400,000 home," says Richardson. As for underspending, it is often a question of how long before you plan on moving out. "Say you are going to stay in your house four years," says Richardson. "You might want to put in Corian counter tops that still look new in three or four years, versus laminate counter tops,which will look used."  <p> With the right planning, it's possible to beat the averages. John Floberg and his wife, Martha Hickner, found that out when they had to move from their Minnesota home, with its renovated kitchen. According to the 199495 "Cost vs. Value Report," they could expect a 22 percent loss on the $45,000 remodeling -- a $9,900 hit. But in the end they recaptured the full cost of there novation: "We had a realtor open house, and that was it," says Hickner. "Basically, the kitchen sold the house."  <p> How did they do it? The tiny kitchen was the obvious liability of the three-story, turn-of-the-century clapboard home. They maximized their return by converting a full bathroom to a powderroom and adding the shower space to the kitchen, which was rebuilt with high-end appliances, laminate counters, and solid-wood cabinets.The house sold for the asking price: $289,000.  <p> Hickner says the experience taught her an important lesson."Wait a year after you have decided to do it," she says. "Think about it: Plan, reconsider, interview." Plans for their new second-floor bathroom are ready for bid.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Real Estate, Family Finance <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
