	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Finding Future Felonies</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Finding Future Felonies</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>FINDING FUTURE FELONIES
Is your neighborhood American Gothic or Picket Fences<p>Sure, it seems safe now, but could there be a crime problem around the corner in your neighborhood? CAP Index may have the answer.<p>Founded in 1988 to do crime-risk assessments for companies considering new turf, CAP Index, based in King of Prussia, Pennsylvania, now offers its CAPRisk reports to individuals concerned about potentially dicey neighhoods. The assessments, which consider police reports and demographic factors, predict the likelihood of various crimes five years into the future. "Executives who have used our assessments for their companies now use them on a personal level," says CAP Index vice president Ricci Levy. "Torn between two homes, they might use us as the deciding factor."<p>At $345 for a site-specific assessment, the report might seem dear compared with driving around and looking and listening. But in relation to the possible expense, headaches, and danger of moving to unsavory surroundings, it might pay for itself and then some. For more information, call 610-354-9100.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
