<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01S-Be It Ever So Humbling</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Be It Ever So Humbling</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-Be It Ever So Humbling</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special issue <p>Worth magazine/Features  <p> BE IT EVER SO HUMBLING <p>1996 is shaping up as a year to remember that a house is a home, not an investment. With inflation projected to stay low, appreciation in home prices will do the same.  <p> By Nick Ravo  <p> Homeowners may soon find themselves yearning for the good old days of double-digit inflation. That's because house prices virtually everywhere in the country are expected to increase only slightly in 1996, shadowing an equally small projected rise in the consumer price index. Real estate is a hard asset like gold bullion and pork bellies that characteristically marches in step with inflation. Over the past five years, for example, inflation has averaged a mere 3.1 percent annually, according to Regional Financial Associates, an economic consulting firm based in West Chester, Pennsylvania. And the median increase in home sale prices has been guess what? 3.2 percent each year.  <p> "People should view their home only as a source of shelter, not as an investment,'' says Mark Zandi, chief economist at RFA."If you think you are going to buy a home, sell it for a profit, and get a real return after inflation, well, you are not going to get it, in most places. And it is probably going to continue this way.''  <p> Last year, the inflation rate was 2.9 percent, and the median sales price of a single-family home rose a minuscule 1.9 percent, according to RFA. This means that prices, when adjusted for inflation, actually fell 1 percent. And this year won't be much better. Inflation is projected at 3.3 percent, while the median home-sale price should rise 3.7 percent, an after-inflation return of 0.4 percent.   <p> "It is highly regional,'' says Susan Hering, an economist at Salomon Brothers. "But what is unusual overall is that sale prices haven't been increasing as much as they have in previous economic expansions. It has been something like 1 percent after inflation, and that is remarkably low.''  <p> Last year, the real estate markets on both the East and West Coasts significantly underperformed the rest of the nation. In the Los Angeles area, for example, where the recession lingered into 1995, the average sale price of a home fell 7.6 percent from the second quarter of 1994 to the second quarter of 1995 (from $190,900 to $176,300), according to the National Association of Realtors. In the New York City region, prices fell 3.7 percent, from $174,600 to $168,100, and in Boston, they fell 1.3 percent, from $181,300 to $179,000.  <p> Gopal Ahluwalia, director of research at the National Association of Home Builders, a trade group in Washington, D.C., says that during the sharp declines in home sale prices in the first half of the 1990s, homes on the East and West Coasts, in all parts of the market top, bottom, middle took a real beating. "In the Northeast, the bottom part of the market was probably hit harder,"Zandi says. By contrast, in California, homes at the top of the market bore the brunt of the price collapse, according to Zandi. Ahluwalia adds that condominiums and co-op apartment prices still haven't recovered in most of the country, including New York City.   <p> Conversely, prices skyrocketed in a few areas. In Salt Lake City, the median sale price spiked 16.6 percent, to $111,500 from $95,600, and in Colorado Springs, Colorado, prices jumped12.1 percent, to $115,900 from $103,400. Not all the appreciation took place in the fast-growing Rocky Mountain region. Home prices in Detroit rose 11.4 percent, to $97,100 from $87,200, in large part on the strength of record profits posted by the automobile industry.  <p> Just as in the mutual fund business, however, past results are not indicative of future performance. RFA is predicting that in 1996 real estate prices will recover in California and the Northeast, achieving increases just below the projected inflation rate. In fact, RFA forecasts that no state will see its median home price decline in 1996. Only in the District of Columbiais a decline projected of 3.8 percent. The largest appreciation,6.9 percent, is expected to occur in Oregon, while the overheated markets of the Mountain West and Midwest should start to cool off, with homes appreciating about 4 to 6 percent.   <p> This leveling of price increases nationwide is partly the effect of southern California's nascent recovery. That is where, with the economy mired in a deep recession, real estate had been depressed the longest and prices fell the most. "A lot of the places that were doing real well, like some of the Rocky Mountain areas,were doing so because the demand for housing was being spurred by people leaving California,'' Zandi says. "As California improves, these areas will start to experience a slowdown. And there is the perception now in southern California that real estate prices have bottomed out.''   <p> As for the Northeast, Zandi expects that ongoing layoffs from bank mergers, defense-industry cutbacks, and a shrinking public sector will continue to dampen the home market. "From Hartford to D.C. is probably the weakest part of the country right now,'' he says.  <p> Zandi also notes that in 1995 California and the Northeast were hurt by the type of buyer dominating those markets: first-time purchasers of inexpensive starter homes. "Statistically, that pulled down the median price,'' he says. "In 1996, we'll see a wider range of buyers, and that will mean higher median prices.'' <p> Of course, all bets are off if a tax-reform package that includes eliminating the deduction for mortgage interest becomes law. If such a plan were adopted, some economists believe home prices could fall as much as 15 percent overnight.  <p> Meanwhile, mortgage rates are stable and predicted to remain so. Rates for a 30-year, fixed-rate mortgage should stay flat or drop a half a percentage point to about 7 percent, according to Keith Gumbinger, a vice president at HSH Associates, a publisher of mortgage data in Butler, New Jersey.  <p> "Interest rates haven't been a real big factor in this market,'' he says. "More important has been the lack of income growth, rising taxes, fear of job losses, increasing debt loads, and demographic changes.''  <p> After federal tax-code changes in 1986, the stock market crash in 1987, the savings and loan crisis, and the recession in 19901992, will the boom years of the 1970s and 1980s, when homes appreciatedany where from 10 to 30 percent a year, ever return? Not anytime soon, according to economist N. Gregory Mankiw and graduate student David Weil, both of Harvard University. Back in 1989, these two published a paper predicting a 3 percent annual decline in house values after inflation in America through the 1990s. They cited the aging of the baby boomer generation and the relative scarcity of home-buying families coming along behind them as the biggest factors.  <p> The rapid run-up in prices in the 1970s and '80s "was a 20-year blip,'' says Daniel McFadden, chairman of the economics department at the University of California at Berkeley. McFadden published a paper last year on the long-term demographics of the housing market. He believes that in most areas there will be a more than adequate supply of housing to meet population increases, and he predicts that national median home prices will, after adjusting for inflation, slowly decline each year through the year 2100, when they will be roughly one third of what they were in 1990. "Prices will decline 10 percent over the next ten years," he says. "Without a tight supply, prices don't go up."  <p> Demographics, however, may also offer some good news for the second- or vacation-home market, which was hit hard in the late1980s and early 1990s, with prices plummeting by as much as 30 percent in many areas, in large part because of tax-code changes that curtailed the deductibility of non-primary residences. Davis Chant, the owner of Davis R. Chant Realtors in Milford, Pennsylvania, says that he and others in the industry expect slow but steady growth in second-home sales because of the bulge of baby boomers now moving into the 45-to-54 age bracket, the time when, historically, people have been the most likely to buy a second home.  <p> Pall Spera, of Pall Spera Realtors in Stowe, Vermont, and a former regional vice president of the National Association of Realtors, has already noted a comeback from the depths of five years ago. "The investor-buyer of second homes, the one who rented them out and used them as a tax shelter, has almost disappeared,'' he says. "But the market is awakening very favorably with user-owners. We were at the bottom for most of '91, but there has been a very nice resurgence."  <p> "If you want to make money in real estate, there is one simple rule,'' Chant says. "Get in front of the baby boomers' demand.'' <p> There is, to be sure, a whole litany of demographic caveats to this axiom: What if baby boomers spend the funds they would have used on second homes on private education for their late-born children? Or on taking care of their aging parents? Or what if they have been so shell-shocked by the recession in real estate over the past five or six years that they plow their money into mutual funds instead, as they have been doing?  <p> Zandi thinks boomers simply may not have enough extra money to buy second homes, as their parents did before them. "Because home prices have been flat, a lot of people are not going to have the equity built up in their first home that they would ordinarily use to buy or make the down payment on a second home,'' he says.  <p> They might, however, have enough cash for time-share condominiums, which have become popular again in recent years after falling into disrepute in the 1980s. Time-shares (often called vacation or interval ownership) allow a buyer to spend a designated week or weeks each year in a specific unit at a specific property, usually a one- to three-bedroom furnished condominium. Typically, a week a year for anywhere from 25 to 50 years at a time-share resort costs an average of $9,500, according to the American Resort Development Association, the trade group representing time-shares. There is also an annual maintenance fee that canrange from $200 to more than $1,000.  <p> Those who invest in time-shares usually are buying vacation futures, so to speak, rather than actual property (in rare cases, time-share investors actually receive a deed for their share in a property), and selling that time can be very difficult. These are not, then, full-time retirement arrangements. Nonetheless, the worldwide time-share market has grown from $500 million to$5 billion since1981. Unlike the time-shares of the past, however,which were often sold by scam artists and fly-by-night companies, today's units are more likely to be run by established hotel and resort companies like Hyatt International, <a name="NASD:MAR"></a><b>Marriott International</b>, and <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Walt Disney</b></a>.  <p> The best news in today's real estate market is that the age group 62 and older is growing ever more slowly, so demand for housing in retirement areas will be flat for a while. "It's not going to pick up again for another ten years, when the baby boomers start to retire, so you might see some softness in prices in places like Florida,'' says Zandi.  <p> That means, at least for those with cash at hand, now might be a good time to buy before the demand starts to build around the year 2005. Says Zandi, "It might be a good time to go bottom fishing."  <p> Nick Ravo is a reporter with The New York Times. He can be reached at nickravo@nytimes.com.  <p><p> <p>
KEYWORDS: National Economy, Real Estate Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

