	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Cracks in the Foundation</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Cracks in the Foundation</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Cracks in the Foundation</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> CRACKS IN THE FOUNDATION  <p> By Kathleen Murray  <p> Several years ago, James Blythe's $150,000 home in Warrenton, Virginia, started listing to port. Cracks fissured the walls; doors and windows could no longer be closed in their warped frames. <p> Blythe took comfort in his ten-year new-home warranty, which he assumed would cover the $34,000 in damages his house had sustained.But his confidence may have been misplaced. Home Owners Warranty Corp. in Arlington, Virginia, which insured Blythe's builder,went bankrupt last October after state insurance regulators discovered the company was short $45 million.   <p> Home warranties were created in the 1970s to pay for repairs to new houses if the builder was unable to do so. To secure coverage,builders paid warrantors a premium, which was passed along to buyers. A typical warranty provides ten years of coverage against major structural flaws and mechanical defects and shorter periods of coverage for less serious problems. By 1994, HOW, the largest of six national home-warranty companies, covered 2 million new homes with ten-year warranties, commanding half the market. <p> HOW wasn't the only large warrantor to experience financial difficulties. In 1993, the next-largest home-warranty company, Home Buyers Warranty Corp., based in Aurora, Colorado, was placedunder supervision by state regulators after the insurance company that backed it failed to meet a new, higher capital reserve requirement. The company resumed normal operations in September of that year, after the insurance company received an injection of new capital.  <p> Blythe is one of about 1,500 homeowners with HOW warranties who have filed warranty claims that were not settled as of last October. And because HOW is paying only 40 cents on the dollar on claims for homes built in the last decade, these people maybe stuck paying for thousands of dollars in repairs. More than1.5 million other homeowners will wind up with completely worthless warranties should the company go out of business.   <p> This does not surprise homeowner advocates. According to Jordan Clark, president of the United Homeowners Association in Washington,D.C., the purpose of warranties is less to indemnify new-homebuyers than to provide cheap protection for developers. For example,warrantors often charge builders just $600 for a ten-year policy on a $300,000 home, leaving themselves vulnerable to big losses. And though home warranties are supposed to cover all major structural damage, many warrantors try to avoid payment by including a clause stipulating that a house must be unsafe, uninhabitable, or unsanitary to qualify for a claim. According to R. Jean Fischer, founder of the Ridgemere Institute, a home-warranty consumer group in Nashville, this practice violates insurance laws.   <p> "Warranties are deceptive and give the homeowner a false sense of security," says D. Brent Lemon, a Dallas attorney who has filed dozens of cases against HOW. They may even limit a buyer's rights. For example, in Texas, homeowners by law get four years' worth of protection against construction defects, while the average ten-year warranty provides two-year coverage. If Texas homeowners accept the builder's warranty, they lose the more extensive state-mandated protection.   <p> In an effort to protect themselves, warrantors have begun to clarify their contracts. Residential Warranty Corp., for example, "now makes a point of writing limited' continuously throughout its warranty," says Tom Bothell, a company spokesman.  <p> Federal and state oversight of this business is lax, so it's up to home buyers to protect themselves. Read the warranty carefullyand be sure you understand the extent of its coverage. Most warranties cover only defects in manufacturing and materials for one year and don't cover such nonstructural damage as flooring or furniture ruined by flooding. However, a home insurance policy can be used to fill in those gaps.   <p> Anyone signing a contract on a new home should check the builder's references, licenses, and insurance. Fischer recommends that home buyers review floor plans and code inspection reports, talk to architects and local inspectors, and pay an independent soil engineer the few hundred dollars it costs to determine if the home is built on solid ground.   <p> Homeowners should also hire an independent engineer to inspect the house. It's not cheap anywhere from $500 to $1,500 but "considering your house is likely to be the biggest investment you'll make," says Fischer, "it's worth the money."   <p><p><p>
KEYWORD: Real Estate, Homeowner, Government, Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

