<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-The Next Takeover Wave</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-The Next Takeover Wave</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The depressed dollar has an upside:  A potential jackpot for holders of some U.S. stocks.  <p> By Gretchen Morgenson  <p> There's nothing like a crisis to focus folks' attention. Such is the case with the currency mess that has suddenly gripped the U.S. Although the dollar was in a free fall for almost a year, it was only after the buck took a big bath against the Japanese yen and the German mark in April that politicians and media pundits began to seize on the sad state of the greenback, and what it means for American businesses and consumers.  <p> Still missing from most of this talk, however, is one of the most significant potential consequences of the down-and-out dollar: a wave of future takeovers by foreign companies with fistfuls of strong currencies. With the dollar at fire-sale levels, particularly against German, Swiss, and Japanese currencies, America's newly efficient, highly profitable corporations now look cheap to foreign investors.  <p> So far, big acquisitions by foreigners have been few. They've also been limited to pharmaceutical companies and certain consumer-goods concerns. In late spring, Hoechst AG, the German chemical and pharmaceutical giant, paid $7.1 billion for Marion Merrell Dow, a U.S. drug company with $3.1 billion in sales last year. Hoechst made the purchase to bolster its sales in U.S. markets and to gain access to the nation's impressive biotech arena. Last year, Britain's B.A.T. Industries, an insurance and consumer-goods conglomerate, bought American Tobacco. The acquisition is already paying off: First-quarter pretax profits at B.A.T. jumped almost 20 percent.  <p> But many more such takeovers may be in the offing. Donald Gimbel, managing director at Furman Selz Capital Management in New York City, reports that investment bankers, both here and abroad, are working overtime advising potential European acquirers on promising targets. "The major European conglomerates can definitely make the case for acquisitions in this country," says Gimbel. "They recognize the merits in buying big brand-name companies. And corporate earnings are coming through faster than the market is going up." So many of these companies look inexpensive, even absent the profitable currency translation.  <p> While Americans normally don't cotton to the idea of foreigners buying up U.S. assets (remember the fears in the 1980s that JapanInc. was going to buy up virtually all of USA Inc.?), American shareholders rarely gripe when the companies they own personally are bought out at fat premiums, no matter who's doing the buying. <p> Which areas of American industry are ripest for takeovers in the coming months? And who will be the likely acquirers?  <p> Certainly not all industries are likely to witness the takeover wave. Don't, for instance, expect merger mania to hit American software or service companies, for instance. That's because shares in these outfits are still favored by investors and carry relatively high valuations.  <p> Some of the money managers who pay attention to this area believe that future dollar-play takeovers will center on five industries: natural resources, food companies, pharmaceuticals, heavy-equipment manufacturers, and chemical producers. In these industries, stocks,if not actually cheap, are certainly not overvalued. "These takeovers will be made for competitive reasons," says Charles B. Carlson, editor of Dow Theory Forecasts, an investment newsletter based in Hammond, Indiana. "Foreign companies are looking for faster inroads into U.S. and overseas markets." Carlson notes that Ingersoll-Rand's $1.5 billion acquisition of Clark Equipment in early May could well have been a preemptive strike against a foreign acquirer. <p> Natural-resources companies look particularly attractive because many of the industry's stocks are in the cellar. The first of what could be many natural resourcerelated takeovers took place in April when Argentina's state-controlled oil giant, <a name="NYSE:YPF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42017"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>YPF SA</b></a>, bought Dallas-based Maxus Energy Co., a debt-laden oil and gas producer with properties in the U.S., Indonesia, and South America. YPF paid $745 million for Maxus, or $5.50 a share. Before the bid was first announced in February, the stock traded at $3.75. <p> Other natural-gas producers, even those with better balance sheets than Maxus's, saw their shares fall precipitously in late1994 because of a 36 percent decline in gas prices last year. This decline came about because a surge in drilling in 1994 was followed by a very mild winter across most of the nation. Now drilling has slowed considerably: The U.S. gas-rig count stands at 321, down 32 percent from last October's peak of 470. According to <a name="NYSE:LEH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41936"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lehman Brothers</b></a> oil and gas analyst Robin Shoemaker, the currentrig count is substantially below the levels required to sustain gas reserves and meet the country's usual natural-gas needs. Therefore, he sees a rebound in natural-gas prices in 1996. <p> If Shoemaker is right, any company wanting to acquire natural-gas properties on the cheap would be looking to get in now. That's because, according to Shoemaker, there is typically a six-month lag between the low in rig counts and the turning point in gas prices. He believes the independent gas-producing companies in the position to benefit most from a recovery in gas prices are <a name="NYSE:HSE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13983"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>HS Resources</b></a> (NYSE: HSE), <a name="NYSE:UMC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16420"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>United Meridian</b></a> (NYSE: UMC), and <a name="NYSE:APC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10111"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Anadarko Petroleum</b></a> (NYSE: APC).   <p> Chemical companies that may be ripe for foreign acquisition include smaller, specialty producers such as <a name="NYSE:RXN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11275"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rexene</b></a> (NYSE: RXN) and <a name="NYSE:LAW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10884"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lawter International</b></a> (NYSE: LAW). Lawter does nearly 50 percent of its business overseas, and as Charles Carlson points out, the fellow who runs the outfit is getting on in years. For these reasons, Lawter may be attractive to a nonU.S. buyer.  <p> Who will be doing the acquiring? Money manager Gimbel believes U.S. shareholders will be entertaining offers from Britain's Hanson PLC, the Netherlands' Royal Dutch/ Shell, European supermarket giant Carrefour, packaged-goods maker Unilever, Heineken, and pharmaceutical concern Ciba-Geigy. He also thinks foreign banks, such as Hong Kong/ Shanghai Bank, Lloyds and NatWest in Britain, and Germany's Commerzbank AG, will be shopping U.S. shores for financial-services companies that are depressed in price.  <p> Brian Fernandez, director of research at the San Francisco investment firm of Volpe Welty, says the acquirers will be strategic buyers, "people who are willing to look out three to five years and need a stake in the U.S. for fundamental positioning, distribution, or technical reasons. The cymbals will clang when they buy because the transactions will be large and there is a lemming-like quality to buyer pools from time to time."  <p> Where are the Japanese in all this? Ironically, although Japan's currency has appreciated the most against the dollar, Japanese investors are pulling in their horns. Japan is short of cashand actually has been busy selling U.S. assets to raise money. Says Fernandez: "The [Japanese] banking industry is in a shambles, industrial companies are reeling from the yen, and investors who loaded up on U.S. government bonds at 300 yen per dollar have lost 73 percent of their money a huge number." And having made many of their biggest real estate investments at the top of the U.S. market, the Japanese are shell shocked. So much for the dangers of the U.S. becoming a subsidiary of Japan, Inc.  <p><p> <p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing, International Economy, Banking Industry, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
