	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Sellers Grab the Upper Hand</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Sellers Grab the Upper Hand</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Sellers Grab the Upper Hand</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>SELLERS GRAB THE UPPER HAND<p>By Jim Melloan<p>Home buyers hoping to take advantage of a softening real estate market may be in for a surprise. Although sales of both new and existing single-family homes are expected to decline this year, the prices that sellers ask (and receive) may jump even more than they did in 1994. In fact, the latest figures from the Mortgage Bankers Association of America, based in Washington, D.C., forecast a 4.2 percent increase in the price of existing homes in 1995 (versus a 2.5 percent rise in 1994) and a 3.7 percent increase in the price of new homes (versus 3.1 percent last year). The projection for existing home prices is higher than the one released by the association before the start of the year.<p>Yet the group continues to forecast a drop-off in the number of buyers this year, predicting that sales of existing homes will fall by 3.7 percent and sales of new homes will decline by 5.7 percent.<p>How can prices be rising if fewer people are buying? <p>David Lereah, the association's chief economist, says it's a simple matter of supply and demand. Yes, the demand for homes has dwindled--the result of rising interest rates and slower job growth. Meanwhile, however, the supply of homes for sale has fallen even more, and it's this growing scarcity that's pushing up prices.<p>Last year was a good one for home sales, mostly because the economy added 3.5 million new jobs, Lereah says. Although interest rates began rising early in the year, many borrowers were able to offset the higher cost of money by choosing lower-priced adjustable-rate mortgages over fixed-rate loans. At the same time, sellers, many of whom had been sitting on their properties for lengthy periods, were eager to finally close a deal. Few held out for sweetened offers.<p>Now, with even fewer homes on the market, sellers are beginning to get tough. In addition, manufacturers expect to build 5 percent fewer new homes this year than they did in 1994. Homeowners throughout the nation should thus expect that 1995 will be a reasonably good year for property values. The map below shows how home prices have fared in major metropolitan areas during the 12 months ended in February. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Homeowners, Real Estate Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
