<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Mixing Commerce With Cocooning</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Mixing Commerce With Cocooning</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Gary Hector<p>Home may be where the heart is, but it increasingly shares office space with business. This year as many as 4.5 million new people will join the 43 million Americans who work at home, according to LINK Resources, a New York research firm.<p>The phenomenon of telecommuting is no longer new, but the new wave of commerce cocooners has higher expectations than did the pioneers of a decade ago. With the electronic gear now available, they expect, rightly, that their home office will be less an outpost on the business frontier than a node on a global network. <p>Today, the ideal home office is a place where an executive or professional can conduct electronic correspondence and tap into an array of information resources. The technology needed to do this is readily available, easy to use, and reasonably affordable.<p>A few thousand dollars will buy a home-office comunications center that will be more nimble and sophisticated than most found downtown. A PC or Mac, printer, fax, modem, cordless phone, some software, and a few technical manuals are all you need.<p>Resist the urge to buy the most powerful computer you can afford. Its capabilities will probably exceed your needs, and no personal computer retains its leading-edge glamour for long. Instead, plan to upgrade every few years as your computing needs grow.<p>Compatibility matters; buy whatever system is favored by your colleagues or clients. <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> or IBM clones, running DOS or Windows, control about 88 percent of the personal computer market. If you want a Mac, new conversion boards are available that will allow you to run PC software. A new PowerMac with such a board already installed costs about $2,600 and includes a built-in Intel microprocessor. <p>One thing you shouldn't skimp on is phone lines. Sharing a phone with the rest of the family may seem a prudent economy, but the first time your child answers, you may lose an account. Plan on three lines: one for the family, one for your business, and one to handle faxes and computer links. The new digital cordless phones from Uniden and other makers let you roam around without those Martian sounds you hear on older cordless models, and the digital transmission scrambles the signal, foiling eavesdroppers.<p>Unless you're a bona fide hacker ready to tackle the Internet, sign up with at least one online service: <a name="NASD:CSRV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43062"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CompuServe</b></a>, Prodigy, or <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>. Connecting to the electronic world through these relatively user-friendly on-ramps has become a major resource for at-home workers. Among other things, these services allow you to send E-mail to any other wired soul. E-mail is instantaneous and can cut your long-distance bills.<p>CompuServe, the granddaddy of online services, lets you to do patent searches, read recent court filings, search through hundreds of industry newsletters, and, for qualified users, access special tools like J.P. Morgan's system for assessing global investment risk. The major services offer free test periods of three to ten hours. <p>They also offer ways to access the Internet, though to varying degrees. Prodigy has the best link-up at the moment, and direct links are offered by companies like the Pipeline in New York City or Netcom On-Line Communications, among many providers. Costs run $20 a month for 20 to 40 hours online. <p>When it comes to modems, buy the fastest available. Although not all online services run at the highest speeds and those that do sometimes charge a premium, few things will save you more time for less money than a modem that can quickly download data. Speed is particularly important on the part of the Internet called the World Wide Web, which is replete with colorful graphics that chew up online time.<p>Another option is an Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN) line, a high-speed telephone connection that carries data at 64 kilobytes per second. These lines have had some technical problems and are just becoming widely available for the home. Pacific Bell is offering free installation in California, with monthly fees starting at $20.<p>Although most new computers have built-in fax modems, get a standalone machine as well. Faxes are still easier to send by hand__especially when it's something you've torn out of a magazine__and their arrival is more noticeable in physical form. <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> offers a laser printer (for about $800) that doubles as a fax, saving desktop space. Color ink-jet printers prices also have been falling; you can get a good one for around $450.<p>As home-office workers plug in and log on, their major problem may in fact be information overload, not isolation. And while the cyber-world can save time and make you money, it is a poor substitute for human contact. Julie Dodd-Thomas, Pacific Bell's resident expert on telecommuting, says, "We don't recommend working at home five days a week." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership, Technology Industry, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

