<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Boom in Vacation-Home Economics</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Boom in Vacation-Home Economics</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ilyce R. Glink<p>Five years ago, dennis and Karen Bookshester plunked down $250,000 for eight mountaintop acres in a resort development in Colorado's Vail Valley. Today, the land alone is worth $750,000, and perhaps $2.5 million including the home they built on it.<p>As Mark Twain reputedly said, "Buy land. They ain't making any more of it."<p>Actually, Twain's axiom hasn't held up so well in recent years__at least not for most residential real estate. The second-home market, however, is another story. Prices for vacation homes have begun to rise of late partly because the 80 million members of the baby boom generation are now entering middle age__the time of life when people are most likely to buy a second home.<p>Some real estate experts expect second-home ownership to double by the year 2000, meaning that nearly 13 million Americans will buy full or partial interests in second homes within five years. According to the American Resort and Residential Development Association, adults are most likely to purchase second homes between the ages of 45 and 64. David Weil, an economics professor at Brown University, notes that "the first of the boomers will hit 50 next year, the main crunch in 2007, and the last of them in 2014." He calculates boomers could be buying second homes at least until the year 2030. <p>The last time boomers bought real estate en masse was during the 1970s and 1980s, when they pushed the real price of homes 30 percent above inflation. The same thing could happen this time, though not all areas will perform equally well as investments. The key to playing the location game is to zero in on areas that offer something special and limited in supply. A basic checklist:<p>Easy access. Two thirds of second homes are located within 150 miles of the owner's primary residence. The best locations take no more than four or five hours to reach, whether by car or, for the most exclusive areas, by plane. For example, Flathead Valley, Montana, has developed slowly due to its remoteness. In comparison, fast-growing Cordillera, Vail, and Beaver Creek, Colorado, all are within an hour of the nearest airport.<p>Diversion. Successful second-home investment locations boast cultural and social resources, not just natural ones. Aspen, for example, is a culturally vibrant community year-round. Also look for first-rate golf courses and other sports facilities.<p>Security. "Second-home owners want to know their kids can safely roam around outdoors," says Davis Chant, a realtor in Milford, Pennsylvania. Adds John Tuccillo, chief economist with the National Association of Realtors, "Baby boomers will be looking to live out their lives in a safe and secure environment."<p>Zero population growth. Successful second-home locations are exclusive and discourage overdevelopment. The residents of Hilton Head, South Carolina, for example, have all but forbidden new construction. The allure boils down to quality of life, says Flathead Valley regional planning director Stephen Herbaly: "If we destroy the air and water quality, we've got nothing."<p>Buy low, sell high. Look for affordable housing stock that leaves room for appreciation. In Flathead Valley, land costs $10,000 an acre. Something comparable will run a half million or so in Aspen, if you can find it.<p>Play the margins. Shop on the fringe of a prestigious community. Five years ago, Cordillera, where the Bookshesters bought their acreage, was a no-name development just outside Vail, one of America's most popular ski resorts. "Looking back, it seems like a no-brainer," says Gerald Engle, Cordillera's developer.<p>Bet on celebrity. Never underestimate the value of star power__even the local variety. When Chicago mayor Richard M. Daley's teenage son threw a much-publicized unsupervised party at the family's Grand Beach, Michigan, home, Chicagoans learned several generations of Daleys had summered there. Since then, area realtors say, Grand Beach has become more desirable.<p>Understand the drawbacks. Not every developer has the golden touch. Even in good areas, second homes are relatively illiquid investments, and there are often hidden costs. Banks also are more reluctant to lend for second homes than for primary residences, often charge higher interest, and normally consider only a fraction of potential rental income when making loans. Vacation property also doesn't qualify under the IRS rule that allows home sellers to defer capital gains taxes by plowing the proceeds back into their next purchase.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Real Estate, Taxation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

