<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Beware Reverse-Mortgage</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Beware Reverse-Mortgage</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Beware Reverse-Mortgage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>BEWARE REVERSE-MORTGAGE MANIA
Don't let a bad deal burn up your home equity.<p>By Elizabeth MacDonald <p>The offer is inviting. Why not take the equity built up in your home and turn it into a reliable income stream? Such is the notion behind one of the hottest new financial instruments out there -- the reverse mortgage. <p>As with many newfangled ideas, the reverse mortgage was born in California. It promises a borrower a set amount of monthly payments based on three factors:a percentage of the equity held in a home, an annual percentage rate applied against that equity, and the borrower's life expectancy. <p>Reverse mortgages are particularly attractive to retirees or anyone else on a fixed income. The nation's 13 million senior citizens are increasingly looking to turn an estimated $750 billion worth of home equity into quick cash with reverse mortgages, according to Ken Scholen, director of the National Center for Home Equity Conversion in Apple Valley, Minnesota. Since reverse mortgages were first introduced in 1989, more than 18,000 people have signed up with over 80 lenders in 47 states. "Today, we get more letters inquiring about reverse mortgages than any other issue, since they are so complicated," says Bronwyn Belling, housing specialist with the American Association of Retired Persons in Washington, D.C. Not surprisingly, such complexity often hides gigantic charges.<p>Last April, a group of senior citizens filed an amended class-action suit on behalf of 1,500 borrowers against Providential Corp., a San Francisco mortgage lender, charging that the firm "bilked millions of dollars from trusting senior citizens." The suit says Providential used deceptive sales practices, such as not disclosing usurious rates and phantom fees. As a result, these borrowers say they lost a huge portion of their assets, which they could have used to pay off nursing-home expenses or bequeathed to their children. <p>Reverse mortgages work much like home-equity loans. Borrowers typically draw between 30 and 80 percent of their home equity in the form of a fixed monthly payment or credit line. The borrower then agrees to repay the balance due if he or she moves from the residence. Repayment is secured by a first trust deed on the borrower's home -- when the borrower moves or dies, the lender is repaid from the proceeds of the sale. Payments are not taxable and don't affect Social Security benefits. Interest costs can be deducted when the house is sold.<p>Unlike regular home-equity loans, reverse mortgages have no income requirements, making them much more attractive to retirees. Furthermore, home-equity loans and credit lines are typically paid off within ten years; reverse-mortgage payments usually last as long as you live in your home. <p>However, some lenders cook up outrageous calculations based on laughable life expectancies.The longer the term of the reverse mortgage, the greater the chance that fees and interest charges associated with it will skyrocket. As a result, such terms accelerate the decline in home equity, in some cases leaving borrowers high and dry.<p>Consider the case of Mary McCarthy, 88, of San Francisco, one of the borrowers in the class-action suit. On September 25, 1990, McCarthy took out an 11.5 percent lifetime reverse mortgage equal to 80.79 percent of the value in her $354,000 home. Providential Home Income Plan, the lending arm of Providential Corp., provided the loan. According to McCarthy's documents, Providential calculated her life expectancy to be 8.28 years. She agreed to receive up to $2,149 in monthly payments, plus a $38,000 advance to pay off an existing mortgage. The suit says that McCarthy was told at the end of the mortgage she would have $99,667 in home equity. <p>However, the suit charges that Providential instead used a 13.5 percent rate. Furthermore, McCarthy says in the suit that in May 1993 Providential gave her a $2,000 lump-sum payment after it "took advantage of her by pressuring her" into a "no points, no fee" rewrite of her loan. She says Providential didn't tell her that it actually added $8,796 in fees to her loan balance for this advance. She also says it failed to tell her that she owed an extra $26,000 by the end of September 1994 because of these charges. Worse, by May 1995, McCarthy will have zero equity in her home because of this rewrite.Adding further insult, Providential has the right to 50 percent of any appreciation in McCarthy's property value, a perilous clause found in roughly 1 percent of all reverse mortgages. In response to the suit's charges, Providential Corp. states that they "border on the bizarre." Plaintiffs are now appealing a court decision forcing arbitration. <p>Although McCarthy's experience was a nightmare, reverse mortgages can be a source of economic comfort if used properly. "Roughly 84 percent of senior citizens responding to our surveys say they really want to stay in their homes and never move," says Belling. As reverse mortgages proliferate, it's smart to protect yourself or your parents. Here's how:<p>-> Educate yourself. Request the free 47-page booklet Homemade Money by mailing a self-addressed postcard to AARP Home Equity Information Center, 601 E Street NW, Washington, D.C. 20049.<p>-> Check out government-backed reverse mortgages. Roughly 10,000 lenders in 47 states are now eligible to originate loans under a Department of Housing and Urban Development program. HUD loans typically carry no appreciation clause. Borrowers pay roughly $4,000 in closing costs, compared with $5,000 or more for similar loans. <p>Also, the Federal Housing Authority is now insuring 25,000 reverse mortgages through September 1995. Applicants must be 62 or older. Monthly payments are guaranteed, even if a lender goes bankrupt or if the market value of the home drops below the loan balance. Insured amounts vary, from $67,500 in rural areas up to $151,725 for metropolitan addresses. On a $100,000 home, FHA insurance costs would come to about $2,000. To find out more about federally insured reverse-mortgage lenders in your area, call the FHA at 800-732-6643. <p>-> Get advice before you sign. Reverse-mortgage borrowers who want FHA-insured loans must now visit HUD-approved independent counselors, found in major cities. Such a counselor will analyze your financial situation, review the terms of a reverse mortgage with you, and then tell you whether this loan is suitable for you. If it is, you'll get a list of HUD-approved lenders. The counselor will also help you fill out your application and act as your liaison with the lender of your choice.<p>-> Question the loan's terms. For example, Providential's chairman, William J. Texido, was quoted in newspapers as saying that the average life expectancy of a 76-year-old Providential borrower is 8 years. Loan-disclosure documents, however, reveal that the firm commonly used a 13.3-year life expectancy for such borrowers. Furthermore, Providential apparently did not consider that many senior citizens move into nursing or retirement homes many years before death and therefore well in advance of their loan's maturity. <p>-> Use reverse mortgages as a tax-planning tool. If your estate is worth more than $600,000, encumbering your home with a reverse mortgage could shrink your assets below that threshold, thereby avoiding stiff federal estate-tax rates as high as 55 percent. <p>-> Consider borrowing from your kids. With the help of a family lawyer, set up your own reverse mortgage with your adult child. Your offspring would then pay you a fixed sum equal to a certain percentage of the equity in your home. You'll get the cash, your children will reap the tax benefits of depreciation of the real estate, and you'll skip high fees. Plus, your asset will stay right where you want it -- at home.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Banking Industry, Government Adgency, Retirement, Mortgages

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
