	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Reading, Writing & Real Estate</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Reading, Writing & Real Estate</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
How good schools produce higher home values.<p>By Margaret Opsata <p>How much does public-school excellence contribute to the value of a home? And how do you make sure you are moving into a good school district? <p>The answer to the first question: More than you may think. For the answer to the second, keep reading.<p>Homes in good school districts are typically priced 10 percent to 20 percent higher than similar houses in not-quite-good-enough districts. In extreme cases, however, the value added is even more: as much as a couple of bedrooms and baths, a new kitchen, a finished basement, a swimming pool, and a tennis court combined.<p>Consider, for example, Las Virgenes, a desirable school district located in Calabasas, just northwest of Los Angeles. Some houses there sell for $1 million and up. But according to housing specialist Alfred Gobar in Placentia, California, nearly identical houses lying just outside the school-district lines bring only $700,000 to $800,000.<p>The price disparity, however, is usually worth paying -- so long as you actually do buy a house within the true confines of a good district. The reason: Your home will be easier to resell, and its price should hold up better. Because of this, even folks without children should investigate an area's school district before buying a house. <p>This is true even in weak markets. During the past recession, for example, Washingtonians who could no longer afford to send their children to private schools moved in droves to the top-rated Walt Whitman school district in neighboring Montgomery County, Maryland. "The in flux was so large that demand kept pace with supply, and housing prices remained relatively stable across the school district," says Jose Saiz, a Bethesda, Maryland, real estate broker.<p>Communities with good schools, however, are not always easy to spot. They aren't necessarily the towns with the nicest houses, highest property taxes, or best city services. In addition, reality doesn't always live up to reputation when it comes to the quality of a town's schools.<p>A good way to dig out the truth is through National School Reporting Services of Stamford, Connecticut, a new and reliable source of unbiased information on public schools across the country. Its reports compare more than 1,500 school districts in ten states: Arizona, California, Connecticut, Florida, Massachusetts, Maryland, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, and Virginia. Districts in five additional states -- Georgia, Illinois, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas -- will be added before the close of 1994. By next year, the service's reports are expected to cover the nation.<p>The NSRS reports compare school districts using more than 200 measures, among them class size, teacher experience, curriculum, athletics, special programs and students' Scholastic Aptitude Test scores. NSRS sells its reports to real-estate brokers, who offer them for free to prospective home buyers.<p>Another important indicator of school-district quality -- one that the NSRS reports do not measure -- is elementary-school reading-test scores. Researchers have found that school districts in which reading scores have remained consistently superior over a ten-year period or so are most likely to be ranked as excellent. <p>For more than a decade, G. Donald Jud, a professor of finance and real estate at the University of North Carolina in Greensboro, has studied the relationship between educational excellence and housing values. "Each 4 percent increase in reading achievement scores is associated with a 2 percent to 3 percent increase in property values," he says. <p>If you see a rapid improvement in these scores, that's a good sign that the quality of education in the district is rising. To unearth the scores of reading tests in a particular school district, either search local libraries for newspaper reports, or ask for the test results from the state's department of education or the county school-system offices.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
