	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-The Real Money in Real Estate</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-The Real Money in Real Estate</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
It takes work, but now's the time to become a landlord.<p>By Stuart Weiss <p>Short of acquiring another home, how can you win in a rising real estate market? Buy an apartment building.<p>The real money in real estate is made buying actual properties. To play, you need at least $50,000 that you can lock up for some time. You also need to take time to research your local market and watch over the property you wind up buying - even assuming you'll hire a property manager. Good negotiating ability is key, since you and the seller determine the price. This is why apartment investing can make sense even in depressed markets.<p>To be successful in real estate investing, aim for cash-on-cash returns of at least 10 percent and capitalization rates of at least 8 percent. To figure cash-on-cash returns, divide the building's net cash flow by your down payment. A capitalization rate is your building's net operating income divided by the purchase price.<p>Here's an example: You offer to buy a six-unit apartment building in a good neighborhood for $360,000. You put $100,000 down and finance the rest with a 6 percent adjustable 30-year mortgage. The average rental unit goes for $625 monthly. Your building's annual income is $45,000. <p>Subtract from this a vacancy and bad-debt allowance of 6 percent, or $2,700; operating expenses of $11,250 (as a rule, operating expenses - utilities, insurance, maintenance - should be from 25 to 50 percent of the rents you take in); and a 5 percent management fee of $2,250.<p>That brings your building's net operating income down to $28,800. Since your annual loan payments are $18,800, your investment's cash flow is $10,000. Therefore, your cash-on-cash return is 10 percent. The capitalization rate is 8 percent.<p>On this investment you'd get depreciation write-offs of just under $10,000 per year. This figure comes from estimating that 75 percent of your purchase price, or $270,000, is depreciable over the standard 27.5 years for residential property. These write-offs come in handy if you need to shelter other income. <p>A great thing about owning real estate is the tax-free exchange rule: When you trade up to another property, capital-gains taxes are deferred until you sell. Try doing that with stocks.<p>The downsides to property investing? You could hire the wrong property manager. You could face major repairs. Interest rates could go up and your adjustable mortgage could reprice itself. The neighborhood could deteriorate.<p>To make things easier, your property should be located within a half-hour of where you live, even if you have a good professional manager. "Apartment properties are management intensive," says Will Creagan III, a broker with Business Real Estate Brokerage in San Diego. <p>Novices should avoid properties in bad neighborhoods where evictions and crime are facts of life. "I have investors who say 'I'm not going to buy unless I can go to this property at night and feel comfortable,' " says John Smelter, a partner at Sterry Van Ness, a San Diego real estate broker. "That takes care of 70 percent of San Diego County."<p>You might think it wise to stick to prime apartments in top location. But top-drawer properties usually carry higher prices; that means a lower cash-on-cash return. There are other problems. "You get too close to the high end, and you have tenants who pay their rent but are the first to move out and buy a house when interest rates drop," says Paul Labby of Carla Properties in Portland, Oregon. "Most of the properties that have been foreclosed on in this city have been at the high end."<p>Should you go with a fixed- or a variable-rate mortgage? If a fixed loan is, say, 8 percent and a variable is 6 percent, then it's probably best to go with the variable rate. Even if rates continue to move up, it would probably take four years for your adjustable to get to 8 percent and four more to get to 10 percent because of the annual caps most adjustables have. If you plan to hold your property for a long time, a fixed-rate mortgage will be safer, but a more active trader will likely want to go with a variable.<p>Get to know some bankers and brokers in town and spend time visiting properties and studying recent transactions. Property markets are more inefficient than equities, in part because information is scarcer. But that's precisely why the small investor who's willing to work hard may do better.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Banking Industry, Homeowner

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

