<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Student Housing That Pays You</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Student Housing That Pays You</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Buy an off-campus house, and the IRS will kick in.<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>Is your teenager mature enough to manage a small apartment building or rooming house? If the answer is yes, he or she can earn a degree from any college in the country at little or no cost to you.<p>Here's how. You buy a three- or four-bedroom house near campus, hire your son or daughter as resident house manager for a salary of free rent, and lease the rest of the rooms at market rate to other students. Besides eliminating your son or daughter's housing expenses, which can exceed enrollment costs at many schools, the venture could generate enough rental income to more than cover tuition, books, clothing, and incidentals. Best of all, most of the money earned will be tax-free.<p>Because you have purchased the house as an investment and do not live there yourself, you are entitled to deduct many more expenses than are permitted with a personal residence. "As rental real estate, not only is the mortgage interest deductible, but you can also write off property taxes, insurance, repairs, maintenance, and depreciation," says Stewart H. Welch III, a fee-only financial planner in Birmingham, Alabama.<p>In addition to free rent, your child can also earn a reasonable management fee of perhaps $100 to $150 a month. "That becomes another tax-deductible expense for you, and your child won't owe income taxes on the money because the total annual fee is less than the standard deduction," Welch says. Unless he or she has another job, of course.<p>You can even write off visits to your child on campus, as long as the main purpose of each trip is to check on the real estate. Absentee owners are allowed to deduct the travel costs of inspecting their investments.<p>If your youngster manages the place properly, you probably can sell it at a profit when he or she graduates. The demand for housing around college campuses remains constant, regardless of whether real estate markets in general are weak or strong, so you should see some appreciation after four years. <p>"Instead of paying out thousands of dollars a semester in nondeductible college costs, you're investing in an asset that produces thousands of dollars in tax-sheltered income and then delivers a tax-advantaged capital gain," says Cynthia L. Conger, a certified public accountant with the Arkansas Financial Group in Little Rock.<p>In addition to the numerous financial advantages of owning your child's college residence, the arrangement may also give you greater peace of mind as a parent. You can try to encourage your child to be neat, arguing that slovenliness harms your property's value. And you can visit the premises frequently - actions that might be uncomfortable, if not impossible, if you weren't the landlord. <p>Indeed, both you and your child must treat the entire arrangement as a business deal if it is going to work satisfactorily. The youngster must set aside time to screen tenants, collect rents, perform yard work, enforce house rules, and pay bills. <p>All terms and conditions of occupancy, including the rental-payment schedule and penalties for lateness, as well as the grounds and procedures for eviction, should be spelled out in a written lease that is signed not only by each student renter but also by one or both of the renter's parents. The resident manager needs the inner strength to enforce the rules, even if it means telling a friend to move out. <p>The income stream will be steadier if you use a one-year lease that permits sublets instead of renting month to month. That's because a student who drops out of school will be required to continue paying rent until another tenant is found. In addition, everyone should pay a security deposit refundable only if the renter does not damage the property. <p>Nonetheless, you should expect higher than usual wear and tear on your property. For example, repainting walls and replacing carpets probably will be necessary each year.<p>For this reason, look for a solid structure. Unless local public transportation is excellent, confine your search to within two miles of campus, an easy commute to classes. <p>You and your son or daughter should begin looking for tenants as soon as you have signed a contract on the house. Advertising in the college or town newspaper or posting notices on bulletin boards around campus may be enough of a marketing effort. Involve your child in the tenant-selection process. <p>Of course, not every college student is capable of managing property, and some simply don't want the responsibility. Those who rise to the challenge will benefit from the experience. As Nancy Langdon Jones, a financial planner in Upland, California, says, "Management experience looks awfully good on a resume these days.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Family Business, Taxation, Educaton, Real Estate Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
