<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Turning Your Folks into a Tax Break</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Turning Your Folks into a Tax Break</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The reward of becoming a landlord to mom and dad<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>Changes in the tax laws have taken a lot of the bang out of real estate investing in recent years. But you can still get favorable tax treatment on the purchase of a home while helping out your elderly parents at the same time. Here's how: Buy their home, or if they don't already own, buy a residence for them and be their landlord. With the residential real estate market warming up, now is the time to strike a mutually rewarding deal. <p>Meaningful tax savings are possible if your tax bracket is higher than your parents'. That would make mortgage deductions worth more to you than to them. If your parents finance your purchase, your deductible interest payments made to them become their income, not a bank's. A sale and leaseback can also benefit you where future estate taxes are concerned, particularly in a rising real estate market. This is because the portion of your parents' estate that was their house has been turned into cash and is no longer appreciating in value.<p>You could structure the deal as an investment in rental property, but for many people the simplest approach is to treat it as a second-home purchase. The tax law still allows deductions for mortgage interest and property taxes paid on both a principal and a second residence. If you already own a second (or vacation) home, it may even pay to sell it, or stop claiming deductions from it, in order to benefit from the higher deductions you may be allowed if you purchase the home your parents reside in. <p>To make sure your parents' residence will qualify as your second home, you have to spend some serious time there.<p>Parents who sell their home will find themselves in for a special treatment where the windfall capital gain is concerned: $125,000 of it is excluded from taxation, provided that one of them is 55 or older and neither has taken the exclusion before. <p>In order to play by the rules, your parents must pay you rent. The rent, however, could be financed from your parents' interest, property tax or insurance savings, or from the proceeds of the sale itself. <p>The rent you charge must be realistic. If the rent is clearly below market, the Internal Revenue Service may consider the difference as taxable income to your parents or an outright gift. But you're allowed to put the rental figure at the low end of the fair-market range. <p>The best practice is to collect market-rate rent and, if necessary, return part of it to your parents as a tax-free gift. Any individual can give any other individual as much as $10,000 a year without incurring gift taxes. The rent your parents pay becomes income to you, but it can be largely offset by legitimate expenses, including property taxes, insurance, repairs, maintenance, and loan interest, if you've borrowed to make the purchase.<p>It may, in fact, be preferable to borrow from your parents to buy the home, if the estate of the second parent to die seems likely to exceed the $600,000 estate-tax threshold. True, the value of the note you give your parents when you buy their house becomes part of the estate. But the note will be partly paid down and the payments spent. If interest rates rise between now and the time of death--and they're certainly rising now--the value of the note would be further discounted to reflect the higher rates. The note would simply be worth less because of the lower interest rate and yield it provides. Therefore, the taxable value of the estate is also reduced.<p>In structuring any sale, be sure to get a tax accountant or tax attorney's advice. The available options become increasingly complex, such as the use of the parental home to finance what's called a family annuity. This is akin to a reverse mortgage, which allows a homeowner to borrow monthly amounts by pledging the equity in the home as collateral; when the borrower dies, the loans plus interest are repaid from the proceeds of the house sale.<p>In a family annuity, the child gives the parent an income for life, and the debt thus incurred by the parent is canceled when the child inherits the parental residence  later on.<p>These techniques are tricky and could violate tax laws if technical requirements are ignored. Get professional help before trying any of them. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Taxation, Real Estate, Homeowner, Government Adgency, Mortgages

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
