<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Avoiding Buyer's Remorse</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Avoiding Buyer's Remorse</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
It's possible to love your new home even after the closing<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>Most house sales, when they're finally sewn up, leave both buyer and seller satisfied. Only after the closing does it dawn on the buyer that his purchase involves more than a transfer of assets--it means undertaking financial and other heavy burdens. Disillusionment starts to replace euphoria.<p>This change in emotions is known as buyer's remorse, and for the most part it can be chalked up to oversights made by buyers in an overly optimistic mood. Brokers selling properties encourage the mood. <p>In a competitive market such as is expected to develop this spring, it pays to keep a cool head. This reality test should help.<p>-- Are you underestimating the cost of operating the home? Many buyers think existing homes offer better value because their prices, per square foot of space, are usually lower than newer homes'. The much higher costs of operating and maintaining older places, however, can easily wipe out any price saving. A 1991 study by the National Association of Home Builders shows that it costs nearly four times as much to run a 30-year-old house as it does to run one built after 1990. On average, an older home costs $4,384 a year per $100,000 of value; a newer one costs just $1,874 a year.<p>To find out how much a home will cost to run, ask to see utility and repair bills for the past three years. Have your independent house inspector examine them.<p>-- Don't be duped by dimensions. There are no universal standards governing the calculation of living space in house listings. This explains why a 2,000-square-foot place may seem roomier than a 2,800-square-foot prospect. In some places, square footage of  lofts or cathedral ceilings may actually be double-counted. In others, truly usable space--basements, even rooms sunk into hillsides--may be ignored. <p>As a result, comparisons between houses are unreliable. Forget advertised figures. Carry a tape measure when you inspect a house.<p>-- Are you overlooking what's over the fence? Scenery and privacy offered by woods and other undeveloped tracts adjoining a lot may seem desirable. But today's meadow or forest can become tomorrow's fire station or topless bar.<p>Determine the ownership of adjoining property, how it is zoned, and what zoning changes can be made to it. <p>-- Don't forget to investigate sound and air pollution. A neighborhood that seems peaceful during the day can become a war zone at night. A race-car track a half-mile away can ruin a relaxing Saturday; shifting winds can bring industrial odors to your door. <p>Visit the neighborhood at different times of day and night and again on weekends. Interview neighbors and employees living and working in the area.<p>-- Check out neighborhood schools. Think you're buying a home in an elite school system? Make sure you're right.<p>-- Account correctly for a mortgage's points. Tax laws permit buyers to deduct in full the fee they pay to get a mortgage loan on a primary residence--known as points--in the year that they assume the loan. But this deduction is possible only if the fee is paid in cash and not from proceeds of the loan itself. If you use loan proceeds to pay points, you can take the deduction only by spreading it out over a period of years. This reduces the ultimate tax benefit.<p>Establish a full deduction by paying the points with a separate check on an account that clearly hasn't been established with loan proceeds. This may be a checking account or your earnest money returned on closing.<p>Even when entitled to a full deduction, some borrowers rely on inaccurate point figures supplied by lenders on Form 1099 information returns. Accounting on 1099s is sloppy in many cases and downright inaccurate in others. The loan-disclosure document received at closing shows the definitive figure. If there is a discrepancy in the two documents, ask the lender for a corrected Form 1099.<p>-- Don't overpay property taxes. If the current year's property taxes haven't been paid on the house, the seller is supposed to give you a check for his prorated share at closing. In some places, however, the current-year tax figure is a mere projection of last year's. If taxes increase, you'll owe the entire amount of increase.<p>Ask the seller to deposit a reasonable amount in escrow to pay his share of any increase that may result from tax hikes.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homwowner, Real Estate Investing, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
