<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Watch Out for Policy Illusions</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Watch Out for Policy Illusions</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Illustrations showing great benefits can be misleading<p>By Virginia Applegarth<p>Marketing experts often say that people put off buying life insurance because they hate to think about death. It's more likely that people avoid insurance because they hate what they have to go through to buy it. <p>As a financial advisor, I recently took on a client who had been caught in a bidding war between two insurance agents. He was overwhelmed with statistics they'd thrown at him. Their primary weapon was the all-too-common policy illustration, a spreadsheet that projects how much a client or his beneficiaries will get each year, extending decades into the future, assuming that the client pays a specific premium every year starting now. The client's file was more than six inches thick. <p>Life insurance illustrations should be the least important factor when deciding what company and policy to buy--well behind the financial strength of the company and its ability to demonstrate a history of low expenses and high returns. <p>What's the problem with most illustrations? First, they are generally incomprehensible. A typical illustration may run on for ten pages or more, containing more than 1,000 separate figures. Second, insurance companies aren't required to--and usually don't--disclose underlying assumptions about expenses or investment performance. Third, they aren't reliable. Dick Weber, a life insurance expert in Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania and a leading analyst of policy illustrations, says the term "accurate illustration" is an oxymoron. If a company assumes an interest rate just a half-percent better than it's currently paying, he says, the projected annual premium will be 8 percent lower. A 1 percent improvement in the cost of death benefits will cut projected premiums another 10 percent. Excluding a company's fixed overhead from a policy's estimated expenses translates into a 4 percent premium savings. And making aggressive cancellation assumptions can cut premiums another 14 percent. Taken together, an illustration showing a company's actual current costs might show premiums 50 percent higher than illustrations incorporating all of these "improvements." <p>What's wrong with lower premiums? Nothing, as long as the real premiums that policyholders end up paying turn out to be as low as the "projected" premiums. But because they are only projections, life insurance illustrations are virtually always wrong, except for the guaranteed columns (typically based on a 4 percent or 5 percent interest rate). Any amounts over the guaranteed cash value and death benefit are a company's best guess (or irrational hope) about future performance. So, although an illustration may appear precise (say $169,422 of projected cash value in the 20th year), nothing could be further from the truth.<p>Many policyholders today are sadly learning the result of insurance planning that was based on the double-digit interest rates that prevailed in the past. With rates now languishing at a 20-year low, they are being asked to pay premiums far above the amounts quoted in their policy illustrations, or to pay much longer than they expected. <p>To turn the tables on the illustration game, ask your insurance company or agent for current illustrations (called in-force ledgers) based on the investment rates their policies are currently earning and the current costs for death benefits and administration. This will give you a much better idea of how your policy is holding up in the low-rate environment.<p>Whether you're checking on an old policy or buying a new one, also ask your agent to run illustrations assuming the currently available interest rate and ones with the rates two percentage points lower. If the policy plan doesn't work under this scenario, watch out. <p>Look out for companies that factor in improvements in mortality charges, expenses, high lapse rates, or increased dividend or interest rates. These projected improvements have no impact on how a policy will actually perform, but they do provide an indication of a company's sales ethics.   <p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
