Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=2064595855497078924; path=/
</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Don't Blame the Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Don't Blame the Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						   
Sure, real estate is slow. But some houses are selling. And there's no reason why yours can't be one of them.<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>America is awash in unsold homes. We've all seen them, those vaguely depressing places where the for sale sign is as much a yard fixture as the birdbath or lamppost and the owners eagerly watch each approaching car in the hopes it will carry that endangered species, the Prospective Buyer.<p>There are many reasons for the sluggish sales: Money is tight. Consumer confidence is low. Job insecurity is rampant. People no longer believe that real estate is a good investment. Perfectly valid reasons, all. But there are other explanations for why a house on the market forever remains unsold: ineffectual real estate brokers and the homeowners themselves. "If the agent and the seller are doing everything right, a house could sell in 30 days," says Tom Posey of Posey Properties/Better Homes & Gardens Realty in Plano, Texas. "If they are doing everything wrong, it could sit there for years." <p>Marianne Voragen of RE/MAX West Realty in Woodland Hills, California, agrees. Although Southern California is in a protracted real estate slump, she maintains that it is "really a great market if you know what you're doing and you're prepared to work." <p>Top brokers use many different tactics, but their overall strategies are very similar. They advertise properties regularly, alternating between text ads in the newspaper classifieds and display ads that picture the home. Their ads do not repeat the same information week after week; each is worded differently. They enter houses in the area-wide multi-listing system, of course, but instead of just waiting for the telephone to ring, they aggressively promote the property on an individual basis as well. <p>What kinds of promotional tactics do successful brokers use? They may participate in house tours featured on cable TV, advertise outside the real estate section of the newspaper, or launch joint promotions with rival agencies. Voragen recently installed a hot line that prospective buyers can call 24 hours a day to receive an audio tour of any of her listed properties. <p>Most important, hardworking agents stay in frequent contact with sellers. "Customers should receive ongoing reports, in writing as well as verbal, about what is happening on their marketing plan," says DeLora Wilkinson, executive vice president and general manager of the Houston office of Henry S. Miller Realtors. Homeowners should not expect miracles, but they deserve to be kept informed. <p>If your home has gone unsold for several months and you see little evidence that your broker is doing much about selling it, ask for a detailed marketing timetable. If that is unsatisfactory, think about switching to a more aggressive agent. Although representation agreements typically run for between one and six months depending on your region, some brokers will release an unhappy seller early if the working relationship deteriorates.<p>Unreturned phone calls to a broker are a good indication that the homeowner may need another agent. Besides being discourteous, ignored messages suggest that the broker is too busy hustling new listings to be bothered with owners who have already signed representation agreements. The best brokers usually limit themselves to no more than 15 or 20 listings at a time, so they can give each property the time and attention it deserves. <p>Don't confuse high visibility with hard work. Some home sellers are happy simply if their broker holds frequent open houses. Unfortunately, only about 5 percent of home sales occur as a result of open houses. This may be because such events tend only to attract curious neighbors and potential buyers who browse with no clear idea of the price or location they want. "Holding an open house just to have one may do nothing but satisfy the ego of the owner," Posey says. In fact, it may hurt more than help. "The main benefit we get from open houses is identifying buyers for other properties we have," says Voragen. <p>Can changing agents make a difference? Yes, say the experts, who have a bagful of tricks to freshen an old, stale listing. "We can reenter the house in the multi-listing system under a new number and a new date. People forget," says Lillian Dorfman of Weichert, Shannon & Luchs Realtors in Bethesda, Maryland. Switching brokers also gives the seller an opportunity to select someone with creative marketing ideas and a solid track record of delivering on promises. (Before signing any agreement, a seller should obtain references from several people who have used the agent, both ones suggested by the broker and some chosen at random from a recent client list.) <p>While a skillful agent is more likely to succeed in selling a home than an incompetent one, there is only so much any broker can do if homeowners refuse to help themselves. Many home sellers make the costly error of clinging to an unrealistically high price for their home. They know that real estate values have dropped a little lately, but they simply cannot believe the house they bought a few years ago for $185,000 is worth only $155,000 today. So they insist on listing it for thousands of dollars too much. <p>How can you come up with a price that's realistic but not a giveaway? The only valid yardstick of current market value is recent comparable sales figures, which are published weekly in most newspapers and kept on file in real estate offices. Unfortunately, some owners rely instead on meaningless information like the listed price of other unsold homes (which may be 20 percent or even 30 percent too high) and neighborhood rumors about the large sums that recently sold properties supposedly commanded. "Neighbors lie," Voragen says.<p>Sellers can get a feel for current value by checking out the competition. "They should have their broker take them on a tour of houses in their price range," says Wilkinson. The visitors need to ask themselves honestly whether their home compares favorably with others available to buyers for the same money. If the answer is no, it's no surprise that the overpriced home has attracted no offers.<p>Sellers must also learn to separate emotion from reality. Buyers couldn't care less how much trouble the owners had hanging the bedroom wallpaper or finishing the job by candlelight when the power failed. Similarly, buyers place no premium on the sellers' charming furniture arrangements or sophisticated taste in avant-garde art, because these items are not included in the sale.<p>Sellers who confuse emotion and value are at a particular disadvantage today, because a significant number of homes on the market are there as the result of job transfers and are being sold by corporate relocation specialists, who have absolutely no attachment to the real estate. "All they want to know is what it will take to get this house sold and off the market at the least cost in the shortest period of time," says Wilkinson. Consequently, company buyout homes have fresh coats of paint, new carpeting, and manicured lawns that make them the most desirable places in their price range. In order to compete, individual homeowners must either lower their asking price or undertake these same cosmetic improvements.<p>Home sellers can learn a few things from these professionals. From the outside, a house needs to look like it's worth the money, and the yard must appear neat and tidy. "If buyers don't like the outside, they will never come in, and once they are in, you need to maintain that good feeling," says Dorfman.<p>Most important, don't despair. It's easy to feel discouraged, even insulted that nobody seems to want your much-loved home. But instead of making excuses, review your approach and your agent. An attractive house that's aggressively marketed at the right price can sell. Even in this market. <p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Homeowner
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

