<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Make Most of Your Mortgage</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Make Most of Your Mortgage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Thanks to the National Association of Realtors, the home-mortgage deduction remains safe for democracy. And you still haven't refinanced?<p>By Margaret Opsata<p>Judging from the number of angry cards and phone calls that flooded U.S. Senator James Sasser's office in February 1993, you might have thought that the Tennessee Democrat, who chairs the Senate Finance Committee, had come out against a clean environment or in favor of unsafe sex. In fact, he had floated an idea even more heretical: Sasser suggested lowering the tax-deductible cap on home mortgages, down from the current $1 million level. If more revenues were needed to battle the burgeoning budget deficit, Sasser believed, Congress should extract them from those who can best afford to pay more--specifically folks who own expensive homes.<p>Before most homeowners had even heard about Sasser's idea, the National Association of Realtors issued a "call for action" to the 750,000 real estate brokers who constitute its membership, urging them to vent their dissatisfaction with Sasser's proposal to the senator and his committee members. "We are not above jamming switchboards and sending mountains of mail to make our point," says NAR spokesperson Elizabeth B. Duncan. <p>Sasser soon saw the error of his ways, and the idea was scuttled. Score one for the NAR and the American homeowner.<p>Sasser wasn't the first politician to come up against the NAR. The association has a history of in-your-face lobbying practices. During the 1992 election, the Realtor's Political Action Committee was the second-largest political contributor in the United States. It distributed $4 million to lawmakers and candidates around the country who were on its side. <p>In that election, R-PAC donated to 58 candidates for the U.S. Senate--43 of them won--and to 473 candidates in the 535 U.S. House of Representatives races (355 won). Politicians clamor for R-PAC donations, which are made only to candidates who give the "right" answers on a lengthy questionnaire. The Realtors' quiz covers just about "every major political issue on the national agenda even remotely connected to real estate," according to Larry J. Sabato, a professor of government and author of PAC Power (W.W. Norton, 1985). <p>Not everyone is comfortable with the NAR's heavy-handed tactics or, for that matter, with the influence PACs have over the U.S. government in general. But the fact remains that the millions of homeowners who take the deduction and the millions of homeowners who don't are all better off financially because the deduction exists. And, because the mortgage deduction remains sacred, today's low interest rates offer an attractive investment opportunity. <p>Who really benefits from the home-mortgage deduction? First, of course, are the 27 million taxpayers who itemize the mortgage deduction on Schedule A, collectively deducting about $200 billion a year, or about $7,400 each. In fact, many homeowners would pay less in taxes under the new, higher 1993 rates than they would have paid under the old 1992 rates without the home-mortgage deduction. Assuming standard itemized deductions, homeowners making $100,000 would pay about $4,000 less in taxes, $150,000 earners would pay $6,500 less, and $200,000 earners would pay $9,000 less.<p>Not all homeowners take the mortgage write-off; in some cases the deduction they're entitled to is smaller than the standard deduction. But even these homeowners benefit from the mortgage deduction's remaining in place. How? The mortgage deduction, which really boils down to a government-created incentive to own property, helps keep home values high.<p>Were that incentive to vanish, real estate values everywhere would plunge. Nobody knows exactly how much the drop would be, but economist Paul Roberts, chairman of the Institute for Political Economy,estimates that prices could fall as much as 33 percent if the deduction were to disappear. "It would make the Great Depression look like a picnic," says Roberts.<p>The NAR also argues, with some credibility, that the mortgage deduction stimulates the economy, creating jobs in construction, consumer hard goods, and other housing-related industries. Donald Ratajczak, an economist at Georgia State University, estimates that all this real estate-related activity accounted for about 13 percent of the U.S. gross domestic product, or roughly $650 billion last year.<p>These days it's difficult to find any lawmaker, like Sasser, foolish enough to question the merit of the mortgage deduction. In fact, every deficit-reduction proposal floated in the 1980s by either Congress or the executive branch has specifically preserved the deduction. Ronald Reagan, George Bush, and Bill Clinton each took pains to assure the NAR that the home-mortgage deduction was untouchable as long as they were in the White House.<p>With the home-mortgage deduction apparently safe for democracy and with mortgage interest rates at record lows, the time has come for homeowners to revisit their investment strategies. For starters, if you have a low rate, don't be in a hurry to pay off your mortgage with excess cash (see "It Doesn't Pay to Prepay," Worth, October 1993). Instead, put the spare cash to work in higher-yielding investments. <p>More aggressive investors might even consider increasing their mortgage borrowings and placing the lump sum they receive from the bank in relatively safe investments that return more than the mortgage's interest rate. Your cost of funds--as mortgage interest--is tax deductible, and a larger deduction will shelter more income from the taxman. A larger mortgage may also keep you in a lower tax bracket.<p>When you can invest with a long-term time horizon, it doesn't take much of a difference between the rate at which you borrow and the investment return to translate into real money. For instance, let's say a 40-year-old homeowner wants to refinance his mortgage at 7.5 percent for 30 years and borrows $100,000 more than he needs to repay the original loan. If he invests that $100,000 at an after-tax annual rate of 8 percent, he'll have $240,000 on hand when he turns 65. Although 8 percent is not an easy yield to come by in today's declining interest-rate environment, it is possible to achieve in a corporate bond of reasonably good quality. <p>If you put any extra investment dollars into a tax-deferred account, your funds will grow more rapidly. The IRS does not allow mortgage proceeds to go into tax-free investments such as municipal bonds (reasoning that if the interest on dollars borrowed for investment is tax deductible, the return on investment shouldn't escape taxes), but the money can be put into a tax-deferred annuity or a pension account like a 401(K) or a Keogh plan. "With the tax-deductible mortgage interest on one hand and tax-deferred compounding on the other, it's almost a no-brainer to take money out of your house," says Jeffrey Goldberg, president of the Financial Consulting Group in Northfield, Illinois. The self-employed can reap even bigger rewards: When mortgage proceeds are put into a Keogh account or a SEP-IRA, the contribution itself is also tax deductible. <p>Homeowners who extract pension contributions from their home over several years may want to do so through a home-equity loan rather than by refinancing. "With a home-equity line of credit, you can take only what you need each year for your 401(K). It's a little more conservative approach than committing to a much larger mortgage," says Gary Pittsford, a financial planner who heads G. L. Pittsford & Associates in Indianapolis. <p>None of these strategies is without risk. By taking a bigger mortgage and paying it down as slowly as possible, the homeowner is automatically saddled with larger payments that will be due every month for the next 30 years, regardless of how the investments have fared. Still, it makes sense to consider reinvesting the results of a successful refinancing. After all, interest-rate declines, like the one we've just seen, happen very rarely indeed. Why not try to make the most of it? <p>Margaret Opsata has been covering real estate issues for 20 years.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Mortgages, Government, Real Estate Investing 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

