<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Calling All Cars</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Calling All Cars</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Direct-response auto insurance eliminates the middleman<p>By Morey Stettner<p>Here's a nasty secret that the agent who sold you your car insurance doesn't want you to know: He may be obsolete soon. The growth of direct-response insurance companies -- which sell policies directly to consumers via toll-free phone lines -- could kill off traditional auto-insurance agents.<p>Highly regarded direct-response carriers, such as USAA, GEICO, and Amica Mutual, give quotes over the phone and train customer-service representatives to answer questions. And since these companies don't pay commissions, their policies are often cheaper by 10 percent or more.<p>From 1984 to 1993, direct-response companies' share of the auto-insurance market grew twice as fast as that of other insurers. In a 1995 survey of insurers conducted by Conning & Company, 
a Hartford, Connecticut based market-research firm, more than 75 percent of the respondents predicted that direct-response companies would capture an increasing share of the personal-auto-insurance market. Indeed, there are signs that shoppers will have more opportunities to cut out the middleman and buy auto insurance directly from the source. Deep-pocketed American International Group is helping a California carrier, 20th Century, expand its direct-response operation into Arizona. And GEICO, now a privately held firm owned primarily by Warren Buffett, has broadened its focus from active and retired government employees to include all drivers.<p>Competition will heat up even more when an ambitious new carrier, Direct Response, starts selling auto insurance directly to the public in 1997. The company, formed by two seasoned insurance executives, has attracted $215 million in private equity financing. One of its founders has built 12-year-old Direct Line Insurance into the largest personal auto insurer in the United Kingdom.<p>"Why did Buffett buy GEICO?" asks Lee Jamieson, counsel to the chairman at Direct Response. "The reason is direct-response companies will gain market share because of economies of scale and because consumers are more inclined to buy auto insurance over the phone. We're confident we can provide a high level of service and educate consumers. And we intend to undercut the competition by offering a lower-priced product by cutting agency expenses and building costs."<p>To test how much money you might save with direct-response companies, try the Consumer Reports Auto Insurance Price Service (800-808-4912). For $12, you will receive quotes to insure your car from up to 25 companies (the service is available in California, Florida, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, and Washington).<p>Progressive Insurance, a direct-response insurer, also offers a free auto-insurance comparison-rate service in most states (800-AUTOPRO). Aside from giving Progressive's rate, the company provides rates from up to three insurers. For example, a 35-year-old Maryland driver with a clean record received the following three six-month premium quotes on a 1987 Subaru: Progressive, $450; Allstate, $294; State Farm, $221.<p>There is a downside: To control costs and keep their risk pool clean, many direct-response companies choose their markets selectively and restrict who can purchase policies from them. USAA, the nation's fifth-largest car insurer, sells auto policies only to military personnel and their families. ITT Hartford sells policies that are usually lower in price exclusively to American Association of Retired Persons members using a special hot line (800-423-6789). New Jersey Manufacturers offers auto insurance only to employees who work for a member company.<p>There are geographic limits as well. Nationwide Insurance, a big national carrier, sells auto policies by phone in 20 western states. Policies from 20th Century are available only in California but will soon be sold in Arizona. And a start-up outfit, Driver's Direct, pitches car policies in Illinois and Iowa.<p>"If you're looking at a regional carrier, be careful," says Robert Hunter, head of the insurance group at the Consumer Federation of America. "Understand what happens if you use a company that's only licensed in a few eastern states and you drive out to California and have an accident. You want to make sure that the company provides good service even if you're out of state or out of the region where it operates. And make sure it's financially sound."<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
