<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Pennies from Heaven</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Pennies from Heaven</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Viatical settlements offer the terminally ill cash today<p>By Morey Stettner<p>Larry Imbordino, a 39-year-old firefighter in West Chicago, 
Illinois, recently took his two young sons on a weeklong vacation to Florida. He calls the trip a miracle. Imbordino, who has suffered from lymphoma for nine years, has persevered through several
relapses and rounds of chemotherapy. A year ago, he was nearly out of cash.<p>"After all the treatments and doctor bills, I wasn't left with much," Imbordino says. "My credit was ruined, and I had to put my house up for sale."<p>Then he heard about viatical settlements. In return for naming Viaticus, a private company, the beneficiary of his $40,000 worth of life-insurance policies, Imbordino got a check for $30,000. "It was tough to fill out those forms," Imbordino says. "It's like an admission of death. But that money enabled me to take my sons to <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a> World, pay my mortgage, and take care of all my other bills."<p>Today, more than 70 companies buy about $500 million in life-insurance policies annually from the terminally ill. While most early viatical settlements (from the Latin viaticum, a word meaning provisions for a journey, later adopted by Christians to mean the Communion given to a dying person) were reached with AIDS patients, the practice is moving into the mainstream, serving victims of cancer and other illnesses. In 1994, CNA became the first insurance company to enter the viatical business when it began funding Viaticus; other insurers are expected to follow. <p>Should you decide to viaticate, your aim should be to launch a bidding war to attract the highest payout for your policy. The Viatical Association of America (800-842-9811), a nonprofit group, offers a free list of its member companies. Payout rates range from 40 to 90 percent of the face value of the policy, so there is room for negotiation. Once a firm determines that your policy is valid and incontestable (and that the insurer permits it to be sold), it will review your records to estimate your life expectancy: the longer you've got, the lower the bid.<p>Because viaticals are still new and work with a vulnerable population of terminally ill people, there's room for chicanery and downright fraud. Only 11 states have laws or consumer safeguards that regulate viatical companies.<p>Of the 70 or so viatical outfits, only about a dozen actually have the capital on hand to pay out. The rest are brokers who first cut a deal with a patient, then place the account with a funder, who in turn coughs up the cash. "What most people who viaticate don't know is that brokers charge a commission," says Per Larson, a financial adviser in New York City. "The median is 6 percent of the face value of the policy." New York is the only state that requires brokers to disclose their commissions.<p>"Brokers don't have to disclose how they are being paid or who's paying them," Larson says. "What's worse, there's a built-in structural incentive for the broker not to get you the highest offer. They may not want to damage their relationship with a funder that pays a high commission, and there's no reason for them to engage in competitive bidding." You can avoid this by working directly with a viatical firm.<p>In some cases, dying persons sign up with a viatical firm and then wait months for their payout -- time they can't afford to lose. As part of negotiations with a firm, viaticators should insist that an escrow account be established before they give up their policy.<p>A final word of caution: Clinics, doctors, and other seemingly unbiased sources of counseling can steer you to viatical companies for the wrong reasons. The Whitman-Walker Clinic in Washington, D.C., has agreed to accept 3 percent of the face value of all policies bought within a 100-mile radius of Washington by Life Entitlements, a New Yorkbased viatical firm. "I see it as a conflict of interest," says Peg Downey, a financial planner in Silver Spring, Maryland, who thinks Whitman-Walker could possibly end up sending all its viatical business to Life Entitlements. "This may help Whitman-Walker, but it's not necessarily in the individual's best interest."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
