<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04-Foreign Policies</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Foreign Policies</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Foreign Policies</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996
Worth magazine/Personal Adviser<p>FOREIGN POLICIES
Fearing kidnappers? Fido needs a bypass? We got you covered.<p>By Morey Stettner<p>Everyone knows about life, health, and auto insurance. But kidnap insurance? That's one of the creative new policies insurance executives have dreamed up. Do these products make sense? For some anxious buyers, maybe. For insurers, definitely. Here are a few plans to think about -- or not, as the case may be.<p>KIDNAP INSURANCE. Attention, kidnap targets! This coverage pays the ransom up to the policy limit ($1 million to $30 million), along with the services of crisis-management specialists and related medical, legal, and travel expenses. The cheapest plan costs $1,000 a year for insurance of $1 million. The coverage includes losses from extortion and unlawful detention. Just don't brag about your purchase, or your claim will be denied. "Confidentiality is an absolute requirement of all parties," says Mike Andritch of Preferred Contingency Insurance Services. <p>If you travel to high-risk countries such as Colombia and Peru, this coverage can be a lifesaver -- literally. But executives who rarely go abroad are better off using common sense (namely, don't flaunt your wealth and shun publicity about your pay package). <p>PET INSURANCE. Veterinary Pet Insurance now offers catastrophic care for dogs and cats. Pet owners can insure their pets against major illnesses and broken bones; routine checkups are not covered. A policy on a puppy or kitten starts at $49 a year, with pricier, added-benefit policies for older pets. <p>As a rule, insurance should save you from financial crises, not a few hundred dollars in veterinary bills. Most pet owners are better off earmarking some savings for a pet's medical care.<p>WEDDING INSURANCE. A wedding can involve big bucks: payments to a caterer, florist, reception hall, photographer, band. For $603, you can buy a $20,000 policy from Fireman's Fund that covers everything from stolen gifts to a last-minute rip in the gown. Even your photographs are insured: If the negatives are lost or stolen, the policy pays to fly the family back to the wedding site for a new round of pictures. <p>But if someone gets cold feet, there's no coverage. Nor should you need added liability protection, since you may already be insured by the wedding or reception site's policy.<p>PERSONAL-COMPUTER INSURANCE. Your computer crashes and you lose dozens of vital files. Disaster? Not with this policy from Frontier Insurance. For $125 a year, you get $10,000 of coverage that pays for a systems consultant to reinstall lost data or help reconstruct files. The policy, geared toward professionals who use a computer for storing business records, covers loss of data from virtually any cause, from accidental erasure to a virus.<p>While homeowners insurance usually covers computer theft, it won't help retrieve lost data. If there are valuable files on your computer, $125 a year is a small price to pay to cover their loss. And let's face it: No matter who you are, you're more likely to suffer a crash than a kidnapping.<p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
