	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Variable, but is it Profitable?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>It's Variable, but is it Profitable?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Variable, but is it Profitable?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Advisor  <p> IT'S VARIABLE, BUT IS IT PROFITABLE?  <p> By J.C. Louis  <p> Of the three cornerstones of sound investment planning preserving capital, minimizing taxation, and outpacing inflation the last is the most vexing to the life insurance industry.  <p> This wasn't the case back when whole life, with its fixed premium, death benefit, and guaranteed return, was the dominant life insurance product. But the inflation and sky-high interest rates of the1970s and early 1980s undermined the premise on which whole life was sold that the tax-free compounding of policyholders' assets in the insurance company's portfolio would eventually pay for the premiums. Soaring rates made it impossible for insurers to make good on that promise.  <p> In response, insurers shifted investments and products toward vehicles that offered higher returns but also greater risk. This strategy led to variable insurance, including universal life, whose cash value fluctuated with interest rates.  <p> Then came variable universal life. To combat the steady erosion of inflation, insurance companies now permit policyholders to place their premiums in accounts, administered by the companies, that invest primarily in stocks. Some insurers have joined premier mutual fund families, which place insurance premiums in accounts that emulate their no-load funds.  <p> The holder of a VUL policy invests in and manages a diverse portfolio of equity mutual funds, which historically have provided an effective hedge against inflation. The policyholder can alter the amount and timing of premium payments or the size of death benefits. He or she can borrow tax free up to 90 percent of the policy's cash value periodically or in one chunk or name a child beneficiary while retaining ownership. This last option lets the policyholder enjoy VUL tax benefits, then pass them along. These are all attractive options, and sales of VULs have more than doubled in the last five years, exceeding $7 billion in1994. Equitable Life and Prudential are the leading underwriters. <p> But VULs come with major problems. First, the policyholder assumes the risk, which is not true with whole life, as the rate of return on investments is not guaranteed (though the death benefit usually is) by the insurer. The investments' value depends on the performance of the funds chosen by the policyholder.  <p> Moreover, insurers often hamper their customers' ability to optimize returns. To achieve maximum performance over the long term, a VUL holder ideally should be able to load a policy with a wide array of highly aggressive funds. Insurers, however, seek to minimize trading and hold down costs by offering a limited number of funds to choose from. This can make assembling an optimal portfolio difficult. Jack Bowers, editor of the independent newsletter Fidelity Monitor, says restrictions on investment options result in systematic investment underperformance for the holders of VUL policies.  <p> VUL policy returns are also diminished in other ways. James Hunt, an actuary with the insurance group of the nonprofit Consumer Federation of America, says the mortality charges alone (the cost of  the actual insurance, exclusive of the investment component of the account), which are often not listed in prospectuses, can greatly exceed the cheapest term insurance. Broker commissions, management fees, and monthly and annual administrative costs may further reduce performance by between 2 and 5 percent.  <p> The upshot, says Hunt, is that a VUL account below $100,000 isn't cost-effective. Larger policies should generate a minimum average annual return of 10 to 12 percent (before asset charges) to be comparable to a typical whole-life policy earning 7 to7.5 percent. VUL is "a wonderful product conceptually," says Hunt. In almost all cases, however, "you need to select aggressive-growth funds, dollar-cost average over a long period [20 years or more], and hope you do well enough to overcome the charges."  <p> For these reasons, says John Fenton of Tillinghast, an Atlanta insurance consulting firm, "if one cannot commit to a consistent savings plan or tolerate any loss of principal, VUL is not the place to be." Moreover, if the policy lapses, all money borrowed from it could be taxable.  <p> Newsletter publisher William E. Donoghue advises those with VUL coverage to compare the net loan costs (the interest rate on loans taken against the policy minus the rate generated by the investments) and the range of choices in funds. "One needs international stocks and bonds as well as gold, junk bonds, and real estate funds," he says. The Consumer Federation of America(202-387-6121) will create a detailed comparison of a VUL policy against low-cost term coverage for a $40 fee.    <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

