	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-In Insurance, Stick With Basics</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>In Insurance, Stick With the Basics</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-In Insurance, Stick With Basics</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor/Family Finance<p>IN INSURANCE, STICK WITH THE BASICS<p>By Kathleen Murray<p>We like to be protected. These days insurance companies are only too willing to help. Faced with stiff competition and hemorrhaging red ink from natural-disaster claims, insurers nationwide are inundating individuals with pitches for expensive policies that provide overly narrow coverage.<p>"Right now you're seeing a lot of companies aggressively trying to remarket old policies and develop new lines," says Steven Goldstein, spokesman for the Insurance Information Institute, an insurance-industry group in New York City. "But some of these products are duplicative, and some people simply don't need them." <p>For example, the rapid growth in home offices and telecommuting has prompted companies like RLI Insurance in Peoria, Illinois, to offer home-office insurance policies to cover office equipment. RLI charges up to $225 annually to cover as much as $5,000 worth of equipment, such as fax machines and computers. These plans also include protection against up to one year's  loss of income due to, say, fire or theft. Such coverage may seem prudent, but Kathleen F. O'Reilly, counsel for the Consumer Federation of America's insurance group in Washington, D.C., says you should first make certain you're not already covered under your homeowner policy, or that you can't get an inexpensive rider. <p>Other insurance products merely offer new twists on traditional policies, like life and medical insurance. Salvatore Castiglione, chief of the New York Insurance Department's Consumer Services Bureau, says agents often pressure workers nearing retirement to buy so-called vanishing-premium life insurance. Agents often claim these policies pay for themselves by redirecting dividends toward premium costs after nine years or so. However, dividend payouts are calculated on the basis of the insurer's assumptions about the direction of market rates. If rates decline, individuals may end up paying premiums well beyond nine years. <p>Some insurers also pressure single people and childless couples to buy unnecessary life insurance, experts say, in part by failing to inform them that the primary reason for such coverage is to protect immediate-family members against loss of income if the policyholder dies. This often makes sense for single-earner families with children. But for single- and two-earner households with no children, it's usually unnecessary.<p>Senior citizens may be encouraged to acquire "dread disease" health insurance from companies such as American Family Life Assurance Co. of Columbus, Georgia. These offer financial protection should the insured contract specific illnesses, principally cancer but also diabetes, renal failure and others. For example, a typical cancer policy costs between $222 and  $276 annually and provides an initial $1,750 payout upon diagnosis, up to $2,100 for every surgical procedure, and $300 a day for hospital costs ($600 a day for stays of more than 70 days).<p>Sounds good, but policyholders may find that this supplementary coverage may actually raise their out-of-pocket costs, and Norma Border, director of the National Association of Claims Assistance Professionals, says that many companies selling these policies are often slow to pay off claims.<p>Rather than answering every brochure appearing in their mailbox, people should stick with the basics in buying insurance. For example, comprehensive medical coverage will buy up to $1 million of insurance in a lifetime for as little as $51 a month.<p>By investing in solid, comprehensive life, homeowner, and medical coverage, individuals will have more insurance than they can ever use. Policyholders can also ask insurers to append riders to their existing policies for supplemental coverage.<p>For example, State Farm in Bloomington, Illinois, offers $10,000 in additional home-office coverage for as little as $14 a year. And those who don't already have income-replacement insurance under a disability plan can get it through a rider for an additional $50 annually. For a list of inexpensive life, health, and long-term care policies, individuals can order a free report from Quotesmith, an insurance price-comparison service in Darien, Illinois, by calling 800-556-9393.<p>Generally, says Robert Hunter, spokesman for the Consumer Federation of America in Washington, D.C., piecemeal insurance policies are not the best way to protect yourself. Says Hunter: "The worst buys are policies that are narrow and restrictive."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

