<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Buy No-Load Insurance Direct</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Buy No-Load Insurance Direct</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Bypassing the middleman can mean cutting your costs.<p>By Robert N. Veres<p>The old adage in insurance circles is that life insurance is sold rather than bought. Deconstructed: Unless you pay somebody a lot of money to persuade people to buy insurance, they won't. This is one reason some insurance salesmen earn commissions equal to as much as 150 percent of a policy's first-year premium.<p>At one time, the mutual fund industry used to abide by the same idea, selling its offerings primarily through brokers. Then, fund companies discovered they could bypass the middlemen and market directly to the public. <p>Now some insurance companies are starting to do the same thing. They are offering an array of products directly to consumers and, in the process, are eliminating charges for sales commissions. By shopping carefully or by enlisting the help of a non-commission, fee-only financial advisor, consumers can share in the cost savings. <p>At present, there are about 30 no-load (commission-free) plans offered by 11 different insurers. Last year, Denver-based Great-West Life -- one of the few insurers with a top financial rating from A.M. Best, Standard & Poor's and Moody's -- cut back its reliance on brokerage relationships and created a no-load insurance line that has grown to include two universal-life policies, two whole-life contracts, and a ten-year renewable term policy.<p>More recently, Security Benefit Life entered the market with a universal-life policy, and Ameritas Life received approval to sell no-load contracts in New York. A further twist was added by Federal Home Life, which introduced a joint first-to-die universal policy designed for working couples, with the benefits payable if either spouse were to suffer premature death. It also is being sold as a no-load product.<p>The new offerings arrive none too soon. With certificates of deposit still paying little in the way of interest, many commissioned life-insurance agents have been hawking policies as investments, tempting buyers with yields on universal contracts of roughly 6.5 percent a year -- tax free. Nevertheless, the upfront costs are so high that, at today's rates, someone in the 30 percent tax bracket who purchased a fully loaded universal policy would have to hold on to it for 20 years before he would see the returns the brokers promise. And even then, the promised return isn't much better than that offered by intermediate-term bonds.<p>The question is: Why wait so long?<p>The beauty of no-load life insurance is that when upfront costs are eliminated, the payoff can start building much faster. "If you have already identified the problem and you have identified life insurance as being the most economically viable solution, then you really don't need the services of a salesperson," says John Roeske, a vice president at Great-West Life.<p>Similarly, the annuities market has also  spawned commissionless alternatives. Currently four companies offer no-load, no-surrender-charge annuities. The least expensive is offered by Vanguard through National Home Life. The product's overhead costs, which include administration fees and guaranteed death benefits, are less than 1 percent of the total investment. The average cost for all variable annuities, according to Chicago-based Morningstar, is 2 percent. Another no-load variable annuity is being readied for market later this year by discount broker <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab & Co.</b></a> through Transamerica.<p>Vanguard allows annuity holders to invest in a variety of its funds. Because of these plans' tax-deferred status, it usually makes sense to buy value-oriented funds whose high percentage of dividends can accumulate free of current taxes. <p>A newcomer to the annuities market is American Skandia Advisors Choice. Skandia's contract lets a buyer choose from a variety of asset managers; it also offers 37 mutual fund portfolios -- more than any other annuity currently on the market. But this flexibility may not come cheap. On top of the 0.9 percent administration costs, Skandia uses brokers to sell its wares, giving them free rein to negotiate their commissions with their customers. These fees are taken from the annuity. <p>It would be nice to report that sales costs are all a buyer needs to look at when shopping in the insurance market. Unfortunately, the truth isn't so simple. Because insurance contracts are complex, a carrier can drop sales charges and simply build the costs in elsewhere. What's more, some fully loaded policies are good buys because the companies that sell them consistently make money for their customers despite high sales costs. Northwestern Mutual Life is such an example.<p>Serious shoppers need to either take their time and wade carefully through all the choices or hire a fee-only financial advisor to do the work for them. The latter option, of course, will cut into the savings of buying a no-load policy.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
