<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Aftershock</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Aftershock</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						In postearthquake Los Angeles, insurance doesn't always provide protection -- unless you have the Equalizer<p>By Mark Stuart Gill<p>At 4:31 A.M. on January 17, the tectonic plates that connect North America and the Pacific Basin rubbed against each other. An instant later, a vibration that would measure 6.6 on the Richter scale shot up 11 miles through the earth's crust and surfaced near a community north of Los Angeles called Hidden Hills, where it exploded the chimney of a $455,000 ranch house belonging to Jonathan Kissel, a criminal defense attorney with a thriving practice in Los Angeles. Kissel and his wife woke up as bricks rained down on their patio. Inside the house, their tile floors popped open. Inch-wide gashes tore across the wall. Through the dark, Jon Kissel heard glass crashing and realized his $295 bottles of Lafite-Rothschild '66 were bouncing out of the wine rack.<p>The Kissels had been through earthquakes before. Jon yelled to his wife Pam, "I'll get the girls, you get the baby." But the house was alive and fighting them. A 300-pound Mitsubishi wide-screen TV fell off its stand and clipped Jon before it rumbled across the room and blocked the bedroom's exit to the hall.  Pam slipped past the TV and into the hallway, where the hot-water heater crashed through the wall of a utility closet and pinned her momentarily against the wall.<p>As Jon ran towards the room where his two daughters slept, Pam got free of the water heater--just in time to see her baby boy's crib rolling across the nursery. It was moving toward a cracked window that overlooked a hill. For a few horrible seconds, Pam Kissel thought her son would die.<p>A moment later, the shaking stopped. Everything was quiet. Fifty homes in the neighborhood had suffered extensive damage from what would soon come to be known as the Northridge earthquake. The Santa Susana mountains were 15 inches higher. In the next room, the crib rocked gently next to the window. The baby never even woke up.<p><p>Like most Californians, Jon Kissel says he's used to living in a landscape where disaster comes routinely, in the forms of earthquakes, wildfires, mudslides, and windstorms. "It's the price you pay," he says now, "for living in paradise." What worries him far more is the quake's financial aftermath--the haggling with insurance companies that may drag on into the next century. <p>At least Kissel's insured. Only 25 percent of homeowners in California have insurance for quakes, which are not covered under standard homeowner's policies. In the area hit by the Northridge quake, about 40 percent are covered. Earthquake insurance can cost as much as homeowner's insurance itself--about $2 for every $1,000 worth of coverage--and is notoriously ambiguous in its wording.<p>One thing was immediately clear to Kissel, though: The policy had a 10 percent deductible, which meant he'd be eating the first $45,500 of damage to his home. "The sun was just coming up when I read that," he says. "My wife was threatening to move back to Chicago. I got on the telephone and called my Equalizer."<p>He's talking about Robb Greenspan, a 42-year-old former nightclub musician turned public adjuster whom Kissel hired to do battle with his insurance company and, he hopes, increase his settlement by as much as six figures. California, the state that gave us the tax revolt, has currently turned its self-absorbed revolutionary ire against the insurance industry. The shock troops in this war are public adjusters like Greenspan. PAs, as they are called, represent claimants against private adjusters employed by insurance companies. They speed up the paperwork, prepare what one might call generous estimates of damages, and handle the technicalities that overwhelm amateur claim filers. At the end of the process, a PA takes a lucrative contingency fee, around 10 percent of the negotiated settlement.<p>In normal times, public adjusters are about as well regarded as personal-injury lawyers. In fact, to protect consumers from the often predatory ways of PAs, California law states that public adjusters can solicit business only between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m., and they are not allowed to approach clients when a loss-producing disaster is still in progress. Other states don't even allow them to solicit business outside their own offices. The insurance industry regards PAs as a nuisance. "A public adjuster can always gouge an extra 10 percent out of an insurer just by being a pain in the ass for long enough,'' says an insurance adjuster. "But those inflated payments just get reflected in higher premiums next year."<p>But these are not normal times. Since 1990, California has been hit by one costly disaster after another. The governor's office has issued emergency declarations covering 56 of the state's 58 counties. The 1992 Los Angeles riots cost $750 million in insurance payouts. Last fall's brushfires, which swept through some of the the most expensive neighborhoods in the country, cost more than $1 billion. But these full-blown catastrophes look like petty claims compared to the earthquake, which will cost an estimated $2.5 billion in insured losses, putting it alongside Florida's Hurricane Andrew in 1992 and the Midwest floods in 1993 as one of the most expensive disasters in U.S. history. <p>The likes of Jon Kissel may deal with disasters by deciding they are a worthy price to pay for living in L.A., but Robb Greenspan doesn't need to make any psychological cost-of-living adjustments. Catastrophe is his business. He refers to the riots as "my Super Bowl moment." Before then, the Greenspan Co. had been a small family-owned business started by Robb's father in 1946. The firm serviced mostly fire victims like the Cask 'n Cleaver restaurant chain and Kyong Sok Ko's EPS 23 Minute Photo & Studio. But now that bad things have started happening even to rich people, Greenspan says his 40-person firm has negotiated settlements for glamorous clients such as Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Rob Reiner. He drives a Mercedes-Benz 300SE. "Robb's like this Schwarzenegger hero/villain guiding us through the financial apocalypse of L.A.," says one of his clients in the movie industry.<p>While consumer advocates allow that it's possible to wangle a fair settlement after a property loss, the operative sentiment throughout the state seems to be: If you don't go on the offensive, you'll get screwed. "Forget all the insurance ads promising security and the hype about "good hands' people protecting you," says Ina De Long, a former State Farm insurance specialist and president of United Policyholders, a consumer-advocacy group. She says she quit State Farm after 22 years because she felt the company provided inadequate training for its adjusters. "After a loss you have to kick and scratch. People have grown deeply mistrustful of insurance companies."<p>After five years of record disasters and record payouts, insurance companies are less willing than ever to give generous settlements. "Insurance is so universal, it's regarded as an inalienable right," says De Long, who's helped make high insurance premiums a hot-button issue in California politics. "But what it's become is a real bottom-line business. Money in is good, money out is bad."<p>Greenspan says his typical clients will call him when they find out, for instance, they'll only collect $300,000 on a $500,000 loss. PAs like Greenspan can help close those gaps. Sometimes, they can do much better for their clients. In 1992, when a high-rise in downtown Oakland suffered fire damage, Greenspan says he was approached by the building's owners. Their insurance company had offered a $55,000 settlement to replace electrical wiring and clean the carpets and walls. Greenspan brought the case to arbitration and got his clients $22 million. "The fire was small, but a transformer that burned up had PCPs in it," he says. "My strategy was that the entire high-rise was environmentally unsound. Big, big issue in the '90s. Anyone can make a damaged structure look all right. But is it really healthy?"<p>Of course, most of his settlements are a little more down-to-earth. Jon Kissel first used Greenspan in 1993. Rain had leaked through Kissel's roof and mildewed the walls. Allstate sent out an adjuster, who inspected the damage. Kissel, who was expecting just $11,000, hired Greenspan, who promptly settled with Allstate for $53,000. Even subtracting Greenspan's fee, Kissel made four times what he thought he would.<p><p>"You're misinterpreting the policy," says Robb Greenspan. "My client has a devastating loss." It's a couple of days after the earthquake. More than 200,000 earthquake insurance claims have been filed. The Clinton administration is seeking a $6.6 billion aid package (later adjusted to $8.6 billion). Thousands of applications for Federal Emergency Management Agency aid are pouring in, so many that National Guardsmen are standing outside FEMA's makeshift offices in the San Fernando Valley to prevent rioting. In his cluttered high-rise office near Koreatown, Robb Greenspan is arguing about dog food.<p>"My client was quaked, he was burned out," says Greenspan, hashing out a claim for a house in Malibu destroyed by wildfires in August and finished off by the earthquake four months later. "The house is kaput. Irreplaceable mementos. His wife--she loved that house. Did you know it's affecting the marriage? And you're hocking me about reimbursement for $273 worth of Kibbles 'n Bits."<p>The adjuster from the insurance company, a beefy, blond kid in a suit who looks like he played offensive tackle on his college football team, fidgets in his chair. A beeper starts to buzz spasmodically on Greenspan's belt. No more than 30 seconds ever go by when something in his office isn't beeping, screeching, squawking, ringing, or paging. His office is crammed with cellular phones, a two-way radio, and police and fire scanners, all beneath framed pictures of burning buildings on the wall. Another beeper connects him to a news service that, for $200 a month, relays breaking news about fires before the fire engines even arrive.<p>This time, it's the client Greenspan has been discussing, Howdy Kabrins, calling from his car phone. Kabrins, a 46-year-old entrepreneur, owns La Salsa restaurants, a 45-store chain of Mexican eateries in the western United States. He's been calling every ten minutes for updates on the negotiations. He wanted to be here in person, but a mudslide has jammed up traffic on the Pacific Coast Highway. Greenspan puts him on the speakerphone and goes back to bickering with the adjuster. <p>Greenspan's chief technique is to simply wear down the opposition. "Time is on my side," he says later. "Insurance-company adjusters work on a salary. They get paid to close cases, not to nitpick." <p>"Robb's secret," says one client, "is that he's got incredible stamina and a leather bladder." Another says, "He keeps repeating the same bad jokes over and over until the adjusters go insane." <p>The topic of contention is a small clause in the policy that covers additional living expenses (the out-of-pocket money a client spends while his home is uninhabitable). Greenspan is trying to prove that Kabrins needs $10,000 a month to maintain his normal lifestyle while his home is being rebuilt. The insurance adjuster figures he can get by on $6,000 a month. <p>"These are Howdy's food receipts for $75 a day," says Greenspan.<p>"We can't give him that much credit on food," says the insurer.<p>"He's a restaurateur," says Greenspan. "He eats good." <p>"He eats very good."<p>"You want him at <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a> every night?"<p>The adjuster holds up another bill. It's from a Malibu kennel. "Why should we pay for dog food if a kennel is feeding the dogs?" he asks.<p>"You're really stuck on the dogs," says Greenspan. "You're obsessed with these dogs.  The truth is Howdy had to feed them before he took them to the kennel."<p>"The dogs ate $237 worth of food while they were waiting to go to the kennel?"<p>"They're big dogs. Hungry dogs."<p>"Does he have any receipts for all this dog food?" asks the adjuster.<p>Greenspan shakes his head and tries another tack: "Those poor dogs were traumatized. All four of them: Paco. Tequila. Razzle. And..." <p>"Panda," says Kabrins, his voice crackling over the speakerphone.<p>"You're lucky we didn't send the poor dogs to a shrink," says Greenspan to the adjuster, "and stick you with the bill."<p><p>By the time Kabrins arrives, an hour later, Greenspan has managed to hike his additional living expenses to $10,000 a month. Kabrins, who's paying $7,000 a month for a large rental house on the beach in Malibu, seems pleased but confused.<p>"I wish I could handle this myself," he sighs. "My bank thinks I'm crazy to be giving a public adjuster 15 percent of my settlement. But dealing with this is like taking on a whole other career." According to Ina De Long,  many couples find that one of them has to give up his or her job after a disaster to work the claim full time.<p>"I hired Greenspan," Kabrins continues, "because I had to level the playing field. Also, I didn't want to hire a lawyer. I hate dealing with lawyers. This insurance company I thought was going to be there for me is now trying to bury me in paperwork. They're killing me." <p>Greenspan hustles Kabrins off to the only quiet place in his offices, the men's lavatory. "Look," he says. "We're going to concede on the dog food. I agreed to only $50 in reimbursement. See, the dog food is just our ploy."<p>"Our ploy?" asks Kabrins. <p>"Yes," smiles Greenspan. "We concede the little stuff and then nail them for the big stuff."<p>Because Kabrins lived in Malibu, where real estate prices and the risk of natural disaster are both high, it was practically impossible for him to insure his house fully against disaster. When he bought the house and property in June 1993 for $1.5 million, he bought homeowner's insurance from California Fair Plan, a state-mandated policy offered by a consortium of insurance companies for property no one wants to insure. Kabrins's annual premium for that was roughly $2,300--and the coverage it offered was bare-bones. The policy promised to pay not what a home costs to rebuild, but the "current cash value" of the home, less depreciation for age and wear, which in this case came out to around $572,000.<p>Since Kabrins estimated his house would cost $800,000 to rebuild, he supplemented Fair Plan with a disaster policy from SafeCo, a Seattle-based insurance company. In the event of a disaster, the policy--with an annual premium of roughly $1,000--guaranteed the replacement costs for the house and its contents over and above what his Fair Plan policy covered.<p>Six months later, when everything Kabrins owned was destroyed, Fair Plan paid off, but Howdy got a little surprise: The back pages of his SafeCo policy guaranteed him coverage for every type of disaster but fire. According to the policy, Greenspan says, SafeCo didn't appear to owe his client anything but additional living expenses.<p>"He was misinformed," says Greenspan, who says he has two other multimillion-dollar clients in the same canyon as Howdy Kabrins with the same interpretation-of-policy issue. "What does the insurance company think Howdy was buying a policy for? Snowstorms?"<p>"It's really a surreal situation," says Kabrins. "They're offering me $10,000 a month to live for 18 months while my house is being rebuilt. But I'm not getting any money from SafeCo so I can rebuild."<p><p>Three weeks after the quake, Allstate is finally ready to send an adjuster out to the Kissels' home in Hidden Hills. The company has gotten off to a slow start processing earthquake claims; its own San Fernando Valley office suffered structural cracks and had to be abandoned. En route to the meeting, Greenspan pilots his gray Mercedes down Highway 101, a cellular phone glued to his ear. "I'm trying to service more than a hundred clients from the quake already," he tells a caller. "I'm sorry, but I'm not taking any claims under a million dollars anymore." Even a month after the quake, he's turning away at least 50 potential clients a day.<p>Greenspan's car is as well wired as his office. Beeps, rings, squawks. The digital beeper on his belt scrolls news of a fire in Hollywood. He's worked seven days a week, operating on a manic energy since the quake. He doesn't sleep; he barely eats. "I don't even have time to figure out my own earthquake problems," says Greenspan, who owns a three-bedroom home in the San Fernando Valley town of Encino. "The sucker slipped right off its foundation. It's probably not even safe to be living there."<p>The Kissels have similar problems. Except Jon Kissel is already out a total of $26,000. A day after the quake, the family fled to a $275-a-day condo unit in Palm Springs. While they were gone, Kissel paid a local contractor $5,000 to shore up the house. He paid out another $3,700 for security and help moving to Palm Springs, and he hired a structural engineer for $400 to do a preliminary examination of the house.<p>Greenspan encouraged Kissel to spend freely because he was certain the Kissels had a great case. For starters, Allstate, the second-largest property insurer in California, is going to bend over backward to accommodate them. In 1991, the company, a division of Sears, Roebuck, got slammed with a wave of bad publicity when it agreed to pay an unprecedented $1 million to settle charges brought against it by the State Department of Insurance that it had mishandled some of its 600 claims from the Oakland fires. "It was a real David and Goliath thing," says Greenspan, whose says his office handled 150 of the homes up in Oakland. "The big impersonal company beating up on the little guy. They don't want to get that image down here."<p>But Greenspan's real trump card is that he's going up against an Allstate adjuster who's never handled an earthquake before. In order to promptly process the thousands of claims that have poured in (claims would total 36,000 by mid-March), Allstate was forced to recruit a small army of freelance catastrophe adjusters from out of state. In all, 15,000 of these "disaster cowboys," as Greenspan refers to them, have come to California to work for several dozen insurance companies.<p>"Cowboys are totally unfamiliar with Southern California," says Greenspan. "They want to close their cases and go home. Dealing with them is a headache for me, but the final settlement is usually much larger. Some of these cowboys work in auto claims. They don't know a fender from a ridge beam. I capitalize on that ignorance."<p>Disaster coverage is a no-win situation for insurers--an actuarial nightmare. "You have a period of 15 years when you have a zero percent loss ratio, and then in one year you have a 1,000 percent loss ratio," says Richard Rupp, vice president of risk management at Calco Insurance in San Mateo. Because the IRS taxes all unused premiums as profits each year, insurers can only accumulate reserves for a catastrophic event with after-tax profits. They claim that's the reason premiums and deductibles are so high. So insurers don't put much energy or time into quake insurance. Until after the Northridge quake, many California insurers didn't even bother to vary the cost of quake coverage according to where a homeowner lived.<p>The state tried to address the problem of disaster coverage after a 6.2 quake in Lomo Prieta, outside of San Francisco, in 1989. State legislators rushed to establish a mandatory earthquake recovery fund. Homeowners in California contributed $12 a year to the fund if they lived in low-risk areas, $66 a year if they lived in high-risk areas. In exchange, the state would pay as much as $15,000 to owners of a single-family home for quake damage, with a $1,000 deductible. The fund was established in 1992, then quickly killed after legislators realized even a minor earthquake would bankrupt it.<p><p>"What are the four seasons in California?" Greenspan asks, sticking his nose near a large crack under the roof of the Kissel home. "Fire, flood, riot, and earthquake!"<p>Greenspan cackles. William "Buddy" Maynard, the Allstate insurance adjuster assigned to the Kissels, scratches his head. This is the second time he's heard the joke this morning.<p>Maynard is exactly the kind of adjuster Robb Greenspan was hoping for--a semiretired Texan who's never worked an earthquake. He's 54 with a string tie, stained teeth, a leathery face, and a habit of tucking his thumbs behind a big silver belt buckle that reads bm. Maynard lives in Tomball, Texas, a small town near Houston. For the last decade, Maynard has spent a third of each year away from home handling disasters. During the rest of the year, he fishes, hunts, and works local catastrophes, mostly fires and tornadoes.<p>In late January, Allstate gave Maynard a choice between assessing snow-related damage in the Northeast or working the California earthquake. The choice was easy: He arrived in California ten days after the quake. He and other freelance adjusters were given a day-and-a-half crash course in earthquakes and California insurance laws and codes. <p>Like Greenspan, Maynard is working around the clock. He's been up since 3 a.m. doing paperwork. As soon as it was light this morning, Maynard started inspecting the 43 properties assigned to him (of those, 22 are seriously damaged like the Kissel home). <p>Originally, Jon Kissel figured he had total damage in the $100,000 range. But now Greenspan is finding that every door frame is no longer level. The flagstone decking around the pool has popped up. The garage was yellow-tagged by the city. It may have to be torn down. The breezeway has been flattened. The north wall of the house--which looks fine--interests Greenspan the most. It's mostly glass, and if he can prove it's unstable, the whole house may have to be written off. Pam Kissel sets Maynard up with a tall glass of Gatorade as they all inspect the wall in question. He sips as he inspects the property. He keeps murmuring politely, "A crying shame." <p>Greenspan's on his best behavior today. He and Maynard are trying to outcharm each other. Each adjuster is trying to prove to the clients that he truly represents their interests. "Did you know I'm a professional magician?" Greenspan asks. "Performed at Magic Castle. In Los Angeles." Greenspan produces a deck of playing cards and starts making the jack of spades disappear. In the background, Jon Kissel is jumping around excitedly. "Robb's the best," he whispers. "Listen to the Equalizer work." Kissel seems as interested in the game--getting his due from the insurer--as he is in repairing his house. <p>"I think the Kissels should be reimbursed for their car," suggests Greenspan, referring to Kissel's '66 Thunderbird.<p>"Isn't that auto insurance?" asks Maynard.<p>"No, no. A large can of paint vibrated off a garage shelf and coated the car. Pink paint."<p>"Crying shame about that car," drawls Maynard.<p>When a house is destroyed by fire or hurricane, the extent of damage is easy to figure out. But the severity of quake damage is often a judgment call. Whether a roof overhang needs to be torn down or just shored up is a matter of opinion. Some adjusters judge damage to a home by the number of vertical cracks in the wall; others swear by diagonal cracks. "It gets to be like a temporary-insanity trial," says Ina De Long. "Each side puts up its own experts, who tend to conclude what the people paying them want to hear."<p>Greenspan has already persuaded Buddy Maynard to use the recommendations of the Kissels' engineer. Now the two adjusters delve into the arcane issue of aftershocks. It's a loaded issue: Damage caused by an aftershock is considered part of the quake that preceded it. If, however, the temblor is considered a separate quake, a new 10 percent deductible applies. Even though Allstate says it has no official definition of an aftershock--the company says it treats each tremor on a case-by-case basis--Maynard seems to believe that in California any seismic activity occurring more than 72 hours apart may constitute separate quakes. Considering that at least a thousand minor temblors were recorded since January 17, it's not in the insured's best interest to speculate too deeply about which of them contributed to the damages.<p>Maynard takes some pictures of the cracks in the wall of the swimming pool with a pocket camera. "Those cracks happen during the 6.6 or are they more recent?" he asks the Kissels.<p>Robb Greenspan smiles. "Buddy, did I tell you what the four seasons in California are?" he asks.<p><p>Howdy Kabrins's ranch house sat on a bluff overlooking the Pacific Ocean. Hemmed in by mountains on three sides, with actor Sean Penn's mansion down the block, it was a remarkably beautiful place. Now the guest house and the rosebushes surrounding it are blackened stumps. A crumbling chimney and cracked tennis court reek of smoke.<p>Even if Kabrins does get the money to rebuild, he can never re-create his old house. Since it was built, Malibu has passed strict zoning laws to limit rampant growth in the upscale enclave. The Kabrins's old house was grandfathered in under the statutes. A rebuilt one won't be.<p>"SafeCo still won't pay to rebuild and refurnish Howdy's home," says Greenspan, inspecting the diving board and the Jacuzzi, which melted into plastic lumps. "But we're trying to itemize the contents of the house, just in case."<p>If Greenspan can convince SafeCo to pay for the contents of the house, that could add another $100,000 or more to Kabrins's settlement. But it will also mean months of bickering with the insurance company over the value of contents.<p>Kabrins didn't make videotapes or lists of his possessions. He doesn't have receipts for most items, and they were all burned, so he can't have them appraised. He has to get appraisals from descriptions. Then he has to apply some kind of fair depreciation to the declared value of the object to find the actual loss of value. Numbers chasing numbers.<p>Greenspan takes notes. He'll return to his office and over the next several weeks compile a loss inventory by what public adjusters call "embellishing it out." This simply means describing the item in enough detail to convince the insurance company of its maximum value.<p>With Greenspan's help, Kabrins is moving mentally from room to room trying to recall the entire home, item by item. "It's brutal," he says, resting for a moment on the chimney. "You feel like an idiot trying to remember how many shoes you had and what was in the bottom drawer of your linen closet. You finish a room and you know you've forgotten a hundred things."<p><p>Forty-three days after the earthquake, the Equalizer has finally taken an afternoon off to inspect his own home. Greenspan pokes at the side of the house, which has rotated slightly on the foundation like a lazy Susan. A large crack runs up one wall. "Oh, this is $15,000 worth of repair, easy," says Greenspan. <p>Greenspan should be able to get a better deal for the Kissels. He's recommending that the house be declared a total loss. The north wall, he says, is too unstable for repair. If Allstate agrees, the company will pay out the original value of the house--$455,000. Take away the deductible and Greenspan's fee ($40,950), and the Kissels walk away with $368,550 Not bad considering that falling real estate values make the house worth a lot less than that. <p>As for Howdy Kabrins and his fire-ravaged Malibu house, SafeCo sent him living-expenses checks for $180,000 to cover the next 18 months. That's $63,000 more than SafeCo had originally offered. While SafeCo still wouldn't pay for Kabrins's house, Greenspan says he recently got the company to extend full guaranteed coverage to two of his other clients, even though their policies didn't exactly promise that. He's certain he can cut the same deal for Kabrins. If he does, Greenspan will have made an extra $350,000 for Kabrins.<p>"You know," says Greenspan, looking discontentedly at his house. "I think I'm just going to tear this whole thing down to the foundation and rebuild." The three-bedroom house was worth about $800,000 several years ago. But so many foreclosed homes are now selling in the Valley at fire-sale prices, it's not worth half that. Plus, he says, he never really liked it in the first place.<p>Does he figure he'll just get his insurance company to reimburse him? Well, not exactly. Greenspan never carried any earthquake insurance, even though his girlfriend is an insurance expert. "Too expensive, too complicated," he admits, "and frankly, who needs the grief?"
---------------
Mark Stuart Gill has written for Rolling Stone, Sports Illustrated and several other publications.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate, Homeowner, Insurance Industry

