		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Don't Be Sold the Wrong Life Insurance</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>Fat fees in life policies are well hidden.  Problem assets can be, too.  It's up to you to protect yourself against getting a bad apple.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>For an industry that's supposed to be selling financial reliability and solidity, the life insurance business has had its share of failures and turmoil lately. The twin 1991 collapses of the $13 billion (assets) Executive Life Insurance Co. and $13.8 billion (assets) Mutual Benefit Life Insurance were followed by a flap at Metropolitan Life that broke last year. Florida regulators uncovered questionable sales practices among some Met Life agents; the company agreed to pay over $11 million in refunds to customers there and plans to offer as much as $30 million to another 45,000 life insurance buyers. Met Life is under investigation in 18 states. <p>In spite of these incidents, insurance remains key to most people's financial plans. Over 154 million Americans own life insurance today. <p>But life insurance buyers are all too often in the dark when evaluating policies. The two main reasons for this: First, there are woefully few independent and trustworthy sources of information out there on policies and companies. Second, disclosure on insurance-policy fees and commissions is practically nonexistent.<p>It's a given that consumers can't count on getting the unvarnished truth from the roughly 250,000 insurance salesmen who make their livings on commission. Sure, some of these folks may be well intentioned, but who knows which ones they are? Neither can shoppers rely completely on the different rating agencies--like A.M. Best--that assess insurers' financial soundness. After all, Executive Life had two top ratings, A+ from Best and AAA by Standard & Poor's, weeks before it announced a charge of $515 million against earnings because of the declining value of its junk bond portfolio. One week after the announcement, Best and S&P both downgraded Executive to an A.<p>Aren't state insurance regulators out front on insolvency issues among life underwriters? Not necessarily. The door between the state insurance commissioners' offices and those of the industry's giants is all too often a revolving one. According to a study on commissioners conducted in 1990 by the Consumer Insurance Interest Group and the National Association of Professional Insurance Agents, roughly half of the commissioners who left their state office went directly to work for the industry. The study also found that almost 40 percent of commissioners worked for the industry prior to taking regulatory office. Close ties don't normally make for tough regulators.<p>Then there's the disclosure problem. Most consumers don't know, for instance, that a traditional life policy carries commissions of 55 percent to 110 percent of the first year's premiums. And because these commissions decline after the policy has been in force for several years, salesmen eager for repeat commissions are tempted to sell their customers replacement policies. Also hidden are details of sales incentives and trips won by high-performing salesmen. Even though these are ultimately paid for by consumers, they rarely find out about them.<p>The hyperbole that salespeople employ in the so-called illustrations used to sell a policy can be another problem. Illustrations show the projected interest rates your money is supposed to earn over the life of the policy. But because these policies can be in effect for decades, rates of return vary wildly. This is why they are not guaranteed. Policyholders often have to cough up more dough to cover additional premiums required by the shortfall in policy performance.<p>Life insurance buyers must take matters into their own hands. They must be able to recognize tricks that insurers use to make their policies more attractive upfront, but that can later cost the unaware policyholder more in premiums. They must know which questions to ask to understand often incomprehensible policies.<p>To help in this effort, James Schwartz, founder of Fee-Only Insurance Specialists in Englewood, Colorado, has designed a questionnaire you can ask an insurance salesman to fill out before you buy. It will reveal an insurance company's financial strength and a policy's fee structure. <p>Schwartz is worth listening to. Back in the 1970s, he was a pioneer in the development of no-load life insurance, a growing part of the industry today. Schwartz is also the author of Enough: A Guide to Reclaiming Your American Dream, a financial planning book.<p>Many insurance buyers believe they've done all their homework if they've gotten three different policy quotes from as many insurers. Schwartz says that's nonsense. "All the bids could come from companies of questionable financial strength," he says Don't assume that buying a policy from a well-known company is the answer. Says Schwartz: "Household names don't pay claims. The quality of assets does."<p>Insurers who get into trouble usually do so as a result of too many risky assets held in their portfolios, a symptom of the high front-end commission structure. Executive Life's missteps were in low-grade bonds; Mutual Benefit's in real estate. In any case, consumers must assess an insurer's asset quality before signing on.<p>If you're shopping for a life policy or adding to existing coverage, give Schwartz's checklist, reprinted below, to prospective insurers' representatives to complete and sign. If you don't understand something, ask for an explanation.<p>It would be great if life insurance shoppers could rely on someone else to do their policy analysis for them. But until the disclosure of fees, commissions, and asset quality among insurers is made clearer, you're on your own.<p>Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

