	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Life Insurance: What's Yours Is Negotiable</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Life Insurance: What's Yours Is Negotiable</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Now that advisors have to disclose their insurance commissions, negotiating can save more than ever<p>By Robert N. Veres<p>This summer, congress quietly debated a consumer-protection bill that could revolutionize the way people shop for insurance. Buried within its 30 pages of legalese, the Investment Advisor Regulatory Enhancement and Disclosure Act of 1993 requires all registered investment advisors (RIAs) to tell their clients how much they're making in commissions and fees on the sale of every financial product. Sound pretty basic? Consider that the bill has stirred up a storm of controversy among financial planners, with some longtime practitioners talking openly about leaving the profession.<p>The real issue isn't mutual fund commissions; they're already disclosed in every prospectus. Nor are stock and bond commissions a problem. They've become so negotiable that wire houses go out of business about as often as airlines and discount companies like <a name="NYSE:SCH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10320"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Charles Schwab</b></a> and Waterhouse Securities gleefully publish their rates for all to compare.<p>The real sticking point is insurance commissions. Few consumers realize that on a standard life policy, between 50 percent and 125 percent of the first-year premium goes to the agent who sold the policy. That's right: When a buyer writes that first check, some insurance companies turn around and give the full amount, and often more, to the agent. And until the new act takes effect, there is no mechanism for making consumers aware of that.<p>Unfortunately, the new bill doesn't require everybody who sells financial products to reveal the commissions they earn. Perhaps the most prominent exemption goes to insurance agents themselves (who number about 500,000). The National Association of Life Underwriters, in its 1992 annual report, reported that its lobbyists had "vigorously opposed" an effort to make insurance agents conform to the Investment Advisors Act. Accountants and stockbrokers are exempt, too, as is virtually everybody but financial planners who offer some investment advice for a fee.<p>This means that all of the roughly 18,000 RIAs will be required to tell their clients how much insurance products cost. This is certain to create at least a small hue and cry among consumers, who presumably would prefer to pay less than a full year's premium for the privilege of being sold. Surprisingly, many in the financial-planning profession are sympathetic. Some senior members of the planning community are even calling on insurance carriers to reprice their policies. "The product that I'd like to see would have a [smaller] commission out of each premium payment--the way mutual funds are sold," says Roy Diliberto, a Philadelphia-based financial planner.<p>Still others would like to see negotiated commissions on insurance products. This would require changing state laws that make it a crime to rebate any portion of insurance commissions to the consumer. At present, only California allows rebating. Florida's anti-rebating statute was declared unconstitutional a couple of years ago, but the insurance industry--with the help of the state's insurance commissioner--has managed to stretch a state antidiscrimination statute to cover the hole. If a Florida agent sells a policy to one person for less than the same policy is sold to another, then that's discrimination and therefore illegal. So much for negotiating in that state.<p>Still, negotiations are taking place in some corners of the insurance marketplace, anti-rebate laws notwithstanding. Some of the smaller and more aggressive insurance companies have begun creating different commission structures on what are basically the same policies, as they have for similar products such as annuities. They get around the anti-rebating statutes by registering each policy individually with the state insurance commissioner as separate products. "Let's say you will have an annuity that pays a 5 percent commission to the agent," explains Walter Lineberger, CEO of Personalized Brokerage Services in Topeka, Kansas, perhaps the largest annuity clearinghouse in the country. "The same company may offer another annuity that pays a 1 percent bonus to the policyholder in the first year. And guess what? The agent gets a point less. Some companies have a whole series of policies with different bonuses and commission reductions. Just within a couple of months, it went from being rare to being just as common as flowers in a country field."<p>Specific examples are not hard to find. Agents for Jackson National Life in Lansing, Michigan, most commonly sell the Ultimate-2 policy, which carries a commission equal to 70 percent of the first-year premium. But when they're bidding against other agents for a low-risk client, they may offer Ultimate-1 and settle for 45 percent. When Alexander Hamilton Life agents deal with customers wanting about $100,000 in death benefits, they'll offer the XTR policy; those looking for death benefits in the $350,000 range may be shown the P-250 contract, where the commission, as a percentage of the first-year premium, is lower.<p>The same is true for annuities. Look, for example, at the single-premium annuities offered by American Investors Life, a solid Midwestern carrier. The company's SPDA VII-D and SPDA VII-E contracts are issued on the same policy form; the main difference is that E carries a lower commission than D. "It's just how you decide to take your commissions," explains Stacy Combs, a marketing representative with the company. "If an agent wants, he can give a higher interest rate to the client and not make as much commissions, or he can make a little more commission and not give as much interest to the client."<p>Annuity D currently pays investors 7.9 percent annually, while the E contract pays 9.3 percent. The difference can add up. According to company projections, a $10,000 investment in the lower-commission contract will have $14,000 more value in 20 years than the higher-commission annuity.<p>What may be the state of the art in flexible commissions can be found at Lamar Life Insurance Company in Jackson, Mississippi. Lamar, which carries an A+ rating from the A.M. Best Company and an A from Weiss Research, sends prospective agents a computer disc on its CLASS (Comfortable Living and Solid Security) universal life contract. When running projections for a client, the agent can specify the percentage commission he'll take--ranging from 20 percent to 100 percent. When the 100 percent option is selected on a $5,000 yearly premium at current rates, the surrender value is zero for the first three years of the policy, compared with $14,410 in the third year when the 20 percent option is picked.<p>Where does this leave consumers? Although the new legislation doesn't force most people who sell insurance to disclose the commissions, the fact that some advisors have to should make the information common knowledge. For now, the average consumer can negotiate commissions only with smaller, less-well-known companies that give their agents some flexibility. An astute buyer might pick an A or A+ rated company and get a 20-year illustration with cash-value and death-benefit projections at the guaranteed interest rate--which is usually 4 percent a year. Then he can tell the agent that he has a better illustration from another company and mention that there is a positive surrender value in the second and third years. If the agent runs a new illustration, chances are it will be at a lower commission rate. This new illustration could be then shown to other agents, who would be asked to match it. <p>To compare apples to apples, make sure that all illustrations use the same 20-year period at the guaranteed interest rate. Since some policies focus on building cash value and others on maximizing the death benefit, make sure those amounts are relatively consistent.<p>As negotiating commissions becomes more widespread, the larger insurance companies are beginning to be less rigid about their own commission structures--at least on the high end of the market. At Prudential, for example, large corporate buyers can now sit down with a representative from the corporate-owned life department, which has a number of reduced-commission products available. "The special corporate policies are getting so refined that you can just dial a commission," says a Prudential general agent who requested anonymity. "More often than not, it is based on the size of the premium and what an agent would be willing to give up."<p>Robert N. Veres edits and publishes Inside Information, a monthly newsletter for professional financial advisors.<p>-----<p>A LITTLE KNOWLEDGE...CAN SAVE A BUNDLE:<p>The more consumers know about insurance, the more they can save. An excellent primer is Life Insurance Sense and Nonsense, self-published by Glenn S. Daily (234 E. 84th Street, New York, NY 10028). Here are three basic elements of Daily's approach:
--Don't put much faith in policy illustrations. They're not a reliable tool for comparing products.
--Don't equate premiums with price. It's easy for a company to project low premiums to lure you in. 
-- Focus on the costs. Future performance is unpredictable, but you can increase the odds by reducing commissions.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

