	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 92/11-Buried Treasures</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Peter%20Lynch%20Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>92/11-Buried Treasures</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>
By Peter Lynch<p>
For centuries, prospectors have been obsessed with finding valuable substances under the surface of what appears to be dull land. One is reminded of John Paul Getty's advice to youngsters on how to get ahead: "Rise early, work hard, strike oil." Maybe the West was won with the six-gun, but the divining rod had a lot to do with who made money on the deal.<p>
Most mineral rights have long since been captured by the rich friends of the geologists, but the prospector's spirit is alive and well on Wall Street. Here, it's still possible to find treasures buried in the balance sheets. This is a lot less work than mining in the Sierra Madre.<p>
Take <a name="NYSE:WH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Whitman</b></a>, which these days has nothing to do with the Whitman's Sampler. This is the nation's largest independent bottler of <a name="NYSE:PEP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11166"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pepsi-Cola</b></a>, but that's not the half of it. Whitman also owns Midas Muffler. Midas Muffler is to Whitman what oil is to a Texas cattle ranch. It's a subterranean value that someday may be extracted.<p>
Shareholders in Whitman were rewarded last year when the company decided to extract Pet. Pet, like Midas Muffler, was a Whitman division. It makes Pet condensed milk, the Old El Paso line of Mexican foods, Progresso soups, and Van de Kamp's frozen seafood. "We believed...that if Pet were a stand-alone company, its value in the market, in combination with Whitman's remaining value, would be increased," says the Whitman annual report. That's exactly what happened. Pet shares were parceled out to Whitman shareholders, and now trade on their own. People who held onto them now have Pet stock, in addition to their Whitman stock.<p>
Subterranean treasures are hidden in many balance sheets. They fall into three general categories: (1) divisions worth more than Wall Street gives them credit for (such as Midas Muffler); (2) cash in the bank; and (3) stock in other companies.<p>
My favorite cash-in-the-bank story is <a name="NASD:VOLVY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41854"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Volvo</b></a>. Some years ago, that company had $34 in cash and liquid assets for every outstanding share, and the stock was selling for $34. Buyers got Volvo for free. This strong cash position made me comfortable enough to make Volvo the largest holding in the <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Magellan Fund</b></a>, where it was a big winner.<p>
It's rare to get something for nothing, like Volvo, but it's quite common to get something for very little. A case in point is <a name="AMEX:SBN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15378"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sunbelt Nursery Group</b></a>, a company with no debt and lots of trees and shrubs, which has a major store renovation program underway. Heavy rains in the Southwest this year have scuttled the nursery business, and Sunbelt stock has been scuttled as a result. Sunbelt has over $2 per share in cash and the stock sells for $4 1/2. Buyers get all the nurseries for less than $2 1/2, in effect a 50% discount.<p>
An example of the third type of hidden treasure, stock in other companies, is <a name="NYSE:DYA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10485"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dynamics Corporation</b></a>. Dynamic's numerous businesses range from the simple (Waring blenders, Acme Juicerators, can openers, ice cream makers) to the incomprehensible (zero-insertion force printed circuit board retainers). The company is doing a great job with the simple-minded divisions and breaking even on the incomprehensible ones.<p>
When the price of Dynamics stock fell in half in 1990, prospectors began to take an interest in the fact that Dynamics owns 37.4 percent of the shares of another publicly traded enterprise called CTS. CTS once stood for Chicago Telephone Supply, but the company no longer has any connection to telephones. Like Dynamics, it makes its own line of incomprehensible products, similar to the zero-insertion for whatevers.<p>
The point is that the market value of the CTS shares owned by Dynamics is $45 million and the market value of Dynamics in toto is $55 million. A buyer of Dynamics gets both companies for the price of one. This math works only when the parent company has no debt. If Dynamics had borrowed $45 million to buy its CTS shares, the value of those shares would not be an extra asset. As it turns out, Dynamics has a cash surplus of $5 million in excess of debt or over $1 per share. Of course if CTS is unattractive, so is Dynamics. But it was reassuring to learn that Mario Gaelli, one of the world's best investors, has owned the stock for years and recently has been buying heavily, increasing his stake to over 27%.<p>
The best prospecting opportunities are often found in stodgy old banks. Banks have been going around the world picking up assets here and there for decades. Their balance sheets are like old attics, filled with mementos that nobody knows they have. <p>
I found this out in the 1980s, when I got interested in <a name="NYSE:DAI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41231"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Daimler-Benz</b></a>, the maker of Mercedes cars and trucks. I was planning to buy Daimler-Band shares directly, until I discovered that Deutsche Bank, which is attractive in its own right, being a peculiarly German combination of J.P. Morgan, Goldman Sachs, and <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, owned a third of all Daimler shares, yet the bank was selling for a price that ignored this remarkable asset. Buying Deutsche Bank was a way to get Daimler-Benz for free.<p>
In the late 1980s, when big U.S. banks were suffering the consequences of their widespread generosity toward Latin America, the price of BankAmerica shares dropped from $35 to $5. That got my attention. There was no way to tell how many more of BankAmerica's borrowers would default, but I was impressed that the bank's deposits came almost entirely from retail customers whose money was protected by the FDIC and therefore were unlikely to bolt, and that it had pawnable assets in all corners of the globe. Among other things, it owned a major bank in Italy, a major bank in Seattle (Seafirst), and as many branches in California as <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a> had hamburger stands. BankAmerica's secondary resources helped convince me the institution would survive, and the stock was a big winner.<p>
Over the last decade, I've been following a regional bank called SunTrust, a strong lender with good reserves that has the largest trust operation in Florida, Georgia, and Tennessee, three growing states. In the commercial real estate hysteria, its stock price fell in half. The subterranean asset in this case was the 12 million shares of <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> that SunTrust keeps in its vault. Being an Atlanta bank, and with Coca-Cola headquartered in Atlanta, it naturally bought a few shares of Coke from time to time, and at present, these are worth more than $1 billion. In early 1991, when you bought a share of the bank for $18, you got $4 worth of Coke as part of the bargain - even banks go better with Coke. Today, SunTrust sells for $40 share.<p>
So, in analyzing a stock, it's always a good idea to learn what's hidden under the surface of the company you've invested in. If you have an idea of the value of the parts, you may not be as quick to panic and sell the stock prematurely, before the value has been extracted.<p>
When you're doing this sort of prospecting, you have to assure yourself of three things: (1) the company at large is worth owning; (2) the subterranean assets are worth owning; (3) the company has little or no debt. In all the above cases, Sunbelt, Dynamics, Whitman, and the banks, the principal businesses were well managed, and the stocks were attractive even without the added attractions.<p>
You can do a thumbnail analysis of a company's hidden values with nothing more than an S&P report and a copy of the company's annual report, plus a pocket calculator. First you need to determine the market value of the company as a whole. That's easy: Multiply the number of shares outstanding by the stock price.<p>
Flip through the annual report to the balance sheet and look for the category marked "cash." Divide this number by the number of outstanding shares, and you can determine whether there's a significant amount of cash per share. This is only meaningful if the company has little net debt, which is shown on the liabilities side of the balance sheet.<p>
When the company owns a large quantity of stock in another company, as Dynamics owns CTS, this fact will be reported on the literature. To find the value of this holding - for instance, the CTS stock - you multiply the current stock price of CTS by the number of CTS shares owned by Dynamics. Dividing the result by the number of Dynamic shares outstanding, we conclude that CTS is worth $11 a share to the shareholders of Dynamics.<p>
It's harder to put a price tag on a division of a company, such as Whitman's Midas Muffler. Even thought the soft-drink bottling business has been very competitive lately, it's been a lucrative cash-flow business for decades. With a fair valuation for Hussman and the other divisions of Whitman, investors are getting Midas for almost nothing.<p>
Of course, to get the benefit of a subterranean asset, somebody has to extract it. This is exactly what happened in 1989, when Affiliated Publications unleashed the enormous value of McCaw Cellular in a $2.6 billion dollar spinoff to its shareholders - without triggering the huge capital gain tax that would have resulted had Affiliated sold off McCaw.<p>
But if a company isn't interested in exploiting its underlying assets, and Wall Street doesn't recognized them, they can remain for decades and the shareholders won't benefit. In fact, value investing, as this sort of prospecting is sometimes called, has been out of favor for several years, causing great frustration among proponents like Gabelli. But this is an argument for patience. Sooner or later, value will out.<p>
I'll leave you with another stock that has all the elements: <a name="NYSE:OC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11126"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Orion Capital</b></a>. This is a profitable insurance company that has no commercial real estate mortgages to worry about. Its ratings were just raised by A.M. Best and Standard & Poor's, a rare event these days for an insurer.<p>
In 1991 Orion extracted the value of one of its subsidiaries, <a name="NYSE:GNC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12377"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Guaranty National</b></a> which specializes in auto insurance for bad drivers, a lucrative part of the business. Orion Capital put Guaranty National on the market, selling 51 percent of the share and keeping the other 49 percent for itself. The proceeds and a dividend from Guaranty yielded $105 million to Orion Capital. The two companies are run by the same CEO, so they are closely linked. Orion is a $38 stock but if you subtract its $10 share worth of GNC, it is really a $28 stock earning $4 a share in a lousy period for property and casualty insurers. This is quite a coup, and if business improves earnings could rise sharply. <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
