	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 92/09-It's a Wonderful Buy!</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Peter%20Lynch%20Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>92/09-It's a Wonderful Buy!</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>
By Peter Lynch<p>
Savings and Loans are the latest untouchables of the stock market. Mention the term, and people grab for their wallets. They think about a $500 billion S&L bailout bill we'll probably have to pay, the 651 bankrupt institutions closed since 1989, the lavish spending by their officers and directors, the 1,361 fraud cases under investigation by the FBI. The word "thrift" once reminded us of Jimmy Stewart in "IT'S A WONDERFUL LIFE." Now it's Charles Keating in handcuffs.<p>
Since 1988, it's been impossible to pick up a newspaper and not read some story about an S&L bankruptcy or a civil lawsuit or a prosecution of Congress's struggle with the bailout bill. At least five books have been published on this sorry subject, not one of which is entitled "HOW TO MAKE A FORTUNE BUYING S&L STOCKS."<p>
For years, I've been searching the disaster areas of the market for signs of life. This has been a very successful strategy. Again and again, I've found strong companies with bright futures selling at bargain prices beneath the gloom and doom. Today many of these happen to be S&Ls.<p>
In fact judged on the most basic measure of financial strength - equity to assets - well over 100 of today's S&Ls turn out to be stronger than the nation's preeminent bank, J.P. Morgan. People's Savings Financial of New Britain, Connecticut, to name just one, has an equity-to-asset ratio of 12.5, while J.P. Morgan's is less than six.<p>
Other factors combine to make J.P. Morgan the great bank that it is, so the comparison with People's Savings Financial is fanciful. That said, there are plenty of S&Ls in terrific financial shape, which is precisely the opposite of what we've always been led to believe. <p>
Of course, there are plenty of S&Ls in lousy shape, which is why it's important to make distinctions. I've identified three basic type: (1) the bad guys that perpetrated the frauds (the fraudulent S&Ls, with notable exceptions such as Keating's, tended not to be publicly traded), (2) the greedy guys that ruined a good thing by making risky commercial loans (something they knew nothing about), and (3) the Jimmy Stewarts.<p>
The Jimmy Stewart S&Ls are my favorites. They've quietly been making a profit all along. These are the no-frills, low-cost operators that take in deposits from their neighborhoods and then make residential mortgage loans. They can be found in small cities and towns across American and in certain urban areas that the big banks have overlooked.<p>
By sticking to its basic function, a Jimmy Stewart S&L can avoid hiring high-priced load analysts and other expensive muckamucks employed by the big banks. Likewise, it can avoid buying a Greek temple for the main office, Queen Anne furniture for the lobby, blimps, billboards, celebrity sponsors, and original artwork. Travel posters will suffice.A lending institution in a large, competitive market cannot afford to be so thrifty. Major commercial banks routinely spend the equivalent of 2 1/2 to 3 percent of their entire loan portfolio just to cover overhead and related expenses. Therefore, to break even it must make a "spread" of at least 2 1/2% between what it pays for deposits and receives from its loans.<p>
A Jimmy Stewart S&L can survive on a much narrower spread. Its break-even point is 1 1/2%. Theoretically, it could make a profit without making any mortgage loans at all. If it pays 4% in interest to passbook savers, it could invest the proceeds in 6% Treasury bonds and still earn money. When it writes 8% or 9% mortgages, it becomes highly profitable for the shareholders.<p>
For years, the inspiration for all the Jimmy Stewart S&Ls has been Golden West Financial Corp., based in Oakland, California. Golden West owns and operates three S&L subsidiaries, all of them run by a delightful couple, Herb and Marion Sandler. The Sandlers have the equanimity of Ozzie and Harriet and the smarts of Warren Buffett, which is the perfect combination for running a successful business. Like Ozzie and Harriet, they've managed to avoid a lot of unnecessary excitement. They avoided the excitement of investing in junk bonds that defaulted and commercial real estate ventures that defaulted, which in turn enabled them to avoid the excitement of getting taken over by the Resolution Trust Corp.<p>
The Sandlers have always been reluctant to waste money on foolishness. Their distrust of the newfangled caused them to eschew ATMs. They never lured depositors with toaster ovens or ice buckets. They missed the great boom in misguided construction loans. They stuck to residential mortgages, which still make up 96% of Golden West's portfolio.<p>
In a famous incident in the mid 1980s, Marion Sandler addressed her peers at an S&L conference in Virginia on one of her favorite topics, "productivity and expense control." The subject was so captivating to the other S&L directors in the audience that a third of them walked out. They'd packed the house to hear about fancy new computer systems and counting machines, but not to hear Ms. Sandler talk about cutting costs. Perhaps if they'd stayed for her lecture and taken good notes, many of them would still be in business today.<p>
Up until the 1980s, Golden West was one of the few S&Ls that was a public company. Then, in a rash of stack offerings in mid decade, hundreds of the formerly private thrifts, operating as "mutual savings banks," went public more or less simultaneously. I acquired 135 of these for the <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Magellan Fund</b></a>. I was so enamored of the S&Ls that anything that had the word "first" or "federal" in it, I bought.<p>
Almost every S&L that came public, I owned. My attraction for S&Ls might seem indiscriminate, but my fund was so big and they were so small that to get enough nourishment out of them, I had to consume large quantities, like a linebacker offered a plate of petit fours. <p>
Of the 450-plus thrifts that sold stock through public offerings throughout the decade, over 100 were acquired by bigger banks or S&Ls, usually at a large profit to the shareholders (the watershed example is Morris County Savings Bank [New Jersey], which came public in 1983 at $10.75 a share and was bought out in 1986 at $68 a share), while 65 failed, usually at a total loss to the shareholders (I know this from personal experience because I owned several in this category). That leaves nearly 300 still in business.<p>
In the last three years, the stock prices of strong and weak thrifts alike have suffered through the real and psychological depression about the real estate market, which supposedly is falling in and around us. In fact, the collapse in real estate is generally confined to commercial projects, and the best of the Jimmy Stewart S&Ls have only a limited involvement in those. For the most part, their portfolios are concentrated in mortgages on single-family homes in the $100,000 range. They have plenty of equity, good earnings growth, and a solid base of loyal depositors, and still their stocks have sunk.<p>
One could not have dreamed up a better atmosphere in which to hunt for bargains. Until the beginning of 1992, investors had been turned off by the entire S&L group. Brokerage houses have reduced or eliminated their coverage of these stocks, and thus far ignored the early signs of revival.<p>
Intrigued by the cheap prices at which many S&L stocks have been selling, several months ago I immersed myself in a copy of the "THE SNL QUARTERLY THRIFT DIGEST" - my idea of the perfect bedside thriller. It's published by SNL securities out of Charlottesville, Virginia, where Reid Nagle and his staff do an outstanding job of keeping tabs on all the S&Ls. I spent so much time with my nose in this huge book that my wife, Carolyn, began referring to it as the Old Testament.<p>
With the book in hand, I devised my own S&L scorecard, listing the strongest institutions by state and jotting down some of the key details. Many of these same numbers can be found in the quarterly and annual reports, S&P reports, and the "VALUE LINE INVESTMENT SURVEY" on the individual companies in the S&L group.<p>
Here I found many exciting prospects: companies with equity-to-asset rations 30% to 100% higher than J.P. Morgan's whose stocks were selling below book value, with p/e ratios that were less than half the p/e ratio for the stock market in general. In analyzing the investment potential of each, I considered the following:<p>
CURRENT PRICE. The importance of a low price is self-evident.<p>
INITIAL OFFERING PRICE. When an S&L is selling below the price at which it came public, it's a sign that the stock may be undervalued. Other factors, of course must be considered.<p>
PRICE/EARNINGS RATIO. As with any stock, the lower the better. Some S&Ls with annual growth rates of 15% a year have p/e ratios of seven or eight, based on the prior 12 months' earnings. This is very promising, especially in light of the fact that the overall p/e of the S&P 500 stocks has been above 25.<p>
HIGH-RISK REAL ESTATE ASSETS. This is the most critical item to consider. With this number, "THE THRIFT DIGEST" keeps track of how many commercial real estate and construction loans the S&L has made. This is a crucial factor because bad commercial real estate loans have been the downfall of most of the thrifts and banks that have failed. What you want to see here is a very low number, preferable under 5%. You're really comfortable when you find an S&L such as Bell Bancorp or Charter FSB Bancorp, which does virtually no lending of this kind.<p>
EQUITY-TO-ASSETS RATIO. This is the second most important statistic. It measures financial strength and also tells a lot about an S&L's capacity for survival. The higher the number, the better. There's an incredible range between e/a's as low as one or two (the candidates for the scrap heap) and e/a's as high as 20. An e/a of 5 1/2 to 6 is average, but when it falls below five, it has reached the danger zone. All else being equal, I'd prefer to invest in S&Ls with equity-to-assets above nine.<p>
DIVIDEND. Many S&Ls pay better-than-average dividends. When one of them meets all the other criteria and also has a high yield, it's a plus.<p>
BOOK VALUE. Most of the assets of a bank or an S&L are in its loans. If you can be confident the loans will be repaid in full, you can be confident that the book value is accurate reflection of the actual worth of the institution. Many promising S&Ls are selling at 60% to 90% of book value, as shown in the chart below.<p>
If you don't have access to a copy of "THE THRIFT DIGEST" (your stockbroker or your library might have it), you can check the annual report of any individual S&L for the dollar value of the construction loans and commercial real estate loans, etc., listed under "assets." By dividing this total into the total dollar value of all outstanding loans, you get a useful approximation of the high-risk percentage. <p>
In the chart below, I've included ten S&Ls that get excellent marks in several categories: book value (they all sell at a discount), equity-to-asset ratio (with three exceptions, nine or better), high-risk loans under 6.5% of total assets, and p/e ratios below 12 on the last 12 months. For the 12 months ending in March 1993, it's likely that these companies will be selling for less than ten times earnings with the general market over 20 times earnings. That several of these companies have been buying back their own shares in recent months is another positive.<p>
This is a research list, not a buy list. Many other S&Ls have numbers that are equal to or better than these. If you have a favorite local thrift, analyze it yourself by filling in the same blanks I've filled in here. Or, if you don't want to do the homework, invest in thrifts through a mutual fund such as Southeastern Thrift & Bank, which trades on NASDAQ.<p>
Ultimately, shareholders in the surviving S&Ls can benefit in two ways. Either the franchises will continue to prosper on their own, or they will be taken over by other banks and S&Ls; this has occurred many times already. From 1987 to 1990, a terrible period for S&Ls, more than 100 were acquired by larger institutions that saw their inherent value.<p>
Currently, the United States still has more than 12,000 banks, thrifts, and credit unions, which is far more than we need. There are seven banks and S&Ls in my little town of less than 20,000 people, as compared with the ten domestic banks in all of Canada. Eventually, consolidation will result in many other S&Ls being bought out at a premium. Finally, there are 1,178 savings and loans that haven't yet come public. These, too, will be worth investigating.<p>
The Virtues of Thrifts:<p>
Here are ten strong S & L candidates to consider, based on the percentage of high-risk real estate assets in the bank's portfolio.<p>
[DUE TO THE LIMITATIONS OF <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>AMERICAN ONLINE</b>, WE ARE UNABLE TO PRESENT THE CHART GIVING THE STATISTICS OF: STATE, PRICE, P/E, EQUITY/ASSETS, DIV. YIELD, PRICE/BOOK VALUE, OR HIGH-RISK REAL ESTATE.]<p>
<a name="NYSE:BELL"></a><b>BellBancorp</b> (BELL)<p>
