	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Sweet and Sour</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Sweet and Sour</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Sweet and Sour</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996   <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> SWEET AND SOUR <p>Index funds can be valuable tools--unless they are used as part of a dubious strategy  <p> By Susan Lee  <p> Question: what do 300 episodes of Melrose Place, a ten-pound Toblerone bar, two Andre Agassis, and 75 index funds have in common?  <p> Answer: They could all be too much of a good thing.  <p> This isn't the usual whine against index funds. You know, the one where some stock jockey gripes that just trying to mimic the Standard & Poor's 500 Index is an exercise in mediocrity and that any alert investor can outperform the market. I don't buy that argument.   <p> The idea behind index funds is both sound and alluring. It is based on the theory that no one can reliably beat the market over the long run. But who needs theory? In practice, in any one year, a majority of mutual fund managers fail to beat the market. Actively managed funds are, of course, hampered by higher expenses and fees, as well as the need to set aside cash for rainy days and redemptions. Indexing is a way of investing inthe broad stock market that is, of duplicating the record of those indexes that track the broader market. If you buy an index fund, you are the market sure, you can't outperform yourself, but you won't underperform, either.   <p> Index funds possess other virtues. Buy a share in an index fund and voil you are instantly and almost perfectly diversified. (Diversification allows investors to reduce nonmarket risk without reducing returns.) Although there is no agreement on the number of stocks needed to diversify, 30 is about the fewest it would take. While that doesn't sound too onerous, buying a share of an index fund is surely cheaper and more efficient than buying stocks in 30 companies. A stock market index fund is also no-sweat. It doesn't require knowledge of specific companies such as growth potential or dividend payouts. And there is no need to follow individual stocks no annual reports to flip through, no stock-tracking software to buy, no time spent riffling through newspapers to see whether you've made money. If the market is up, you are up. Simple as that.  <p> Moreover, investing in an index fund is cheap. It doesn't require pricey brokers, personal finance advisers, or subscriptions to investment newsletters. Nor does it demand high payments for commissions or loads and fees. Expenses are low because once the index is in place there is little active trading, except for occasional portfolio rebalancing. (But watch it some funds charge higher fees than others.) And since there is little trading involved in maintaining these portfolios, there are also fewer tax consequences. The buy-and-hold strategy avoids a potentially nasty capital gains tax bill at year's end.   <p> As you can see, index funds are quite attractive. So it's no wonder that lots of companies have started to market them. Offerings have expanded from the primitive (funds that mimic the Standard & Poor's 500) to the more refined (funds that track the Wilshire 5000, the Russell 2000, and mid-cap stocks). Currently, it is possible to buy U.S.-bond index funds, European and Pacific stock market index funds, emerging-markets index funds, and funds that track utility and gold stocks. Some companies have even introduced "enhanced" index funds oxymoronic vehicles that try to beat the market by employing various techniques.  <p> These newer index funds offer some of the same benefits as simple stock funds by giving investors an inexpensive and efficient way to diversify within asset classes. But they also permit inexpensive and efficient diversification across asset classes. For example, sophisticated investors want not only a mix of stocks and bonds but since foreign stocks make up 61 percent of the global market, according to Morgan Stanley Capital International some foreign exposure as well. Foreign-stock index funds serve that purpose.  <p> But what about returns? It makes no sense to plunk something into your portfolio if you don't expect delicious returns. A look at the small- and mid-cap U.S. markets and the foreign stock markets over the past ten years indicates that returns have indeed been higher than the S&P 500's average annual return of 14 percent. Over the last decade, the Russell 2000 Index of small stocks averaged an annual return of more than 15 percent, the Russell Midcap Index averaged 17 percent, and the Morgan Stanley EAFE index of foreign stocks averaged 21 percent. But these were returns achieved by indexes not by funds purporting to mimic those indexes. Unfortunately, it is impossible to judge whether the funds based on those indexes have tracked them in a consistent and detailed way: Not enough have been around for ten years.  <p> Further, these funds tend to have higher fees and expenses. And some have special hazards. Enhanced index funds use strategies of actively buying and selling stocks or a grab bag of options and futures ploys, which can result in larger tax consequences. Foreign funds are open to currency risk, and emerging-markets funds carry political risk.  <p> But perhaps the most troubling aspect of the availability of index funds with multiple-choice asset classes is, as index-fund managers have complained, that some investors treat them as an opportunity to engage in market timing by which I mean any activity that shifts money from one asset class or sector to another in an attempt to shun laggards and exploit leaders.   <p> Here the mere existence of index funds almost constitutes entrapment. Just like families of actively managed mutual funds, index funds provide an easy and efficient way of sending money into one category, such as bonds, and then withdrawing it and sending it into another category, such as stocks; or of plopping money into utilities and then moving it into natural-gas stocks. Investors can shift money without having to liquidate their portfolios which would take time, involve higher transaction costs, and invite complicated tax records. But index funds also give investors idle hands. As Kevin Johnson of Aronson + Partners, a Philadelphia money-managment firm, says, "If you forgo making decisions on individual stocks by buying an index fund, then how do you spend your time? You start making decisions across asset classes."  <p> Essentially, then, index funds allow investors to use a buy-and-hold strategy as the instrument for an active sell-and-buy one. That may sound fabulously clever, but think again. The record on market timing is clear: As survey after survey reveals, nobody has been able to catch both market tops and bottoms in a consistent, return-boosting way. Ditto for rotating money from sector to sector. Although sector funds do provide some diversification the reduction of stock-specific risk they leave investors wide open to industry-specific risk. "Sector rotating is like betting, pure and simple," says Gus Sauter, head of Vanguard Group's index funds. "It's not investing at all."  <p> And that's the bad thing. It's silly to choose a strategy that guarantees market returns and then use it in a way that risks subnormal performance.  <p> The index fund is a truly awesome invention. A cheap S & P 500 or a Wilshire 5000 index fund ought to constitute at least half of your portfolio. But treat the bells-and-whistles funds with caution, and approach any active tactical ploys the way you would the temptation of a ten-pound Toblerone bar. Just say no.  <p> Susan Lee is an economist and the author of the forth coming book Hands Off: Why the Government Is a Menace to Economic Health (Simon & Schuster).   <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing, Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
