<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Debtors' Money</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Debtors' Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Debtors' Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Experts<p>DEBTORS' MONEY
Why the U.S. dollar, once literally as good as gold, has become a global economic problem.<p>By Walter Mead<p>"You shall not press down upon the brow of labor this crown of thorns," said presidential nominee William Jennings Bryan to the Democratic convention of 1896. "You shall not crucify mankind upon a cross of gold."<p>Almost nobody today has any idea what Bryan was talking about. And that's too bad, because the monetary battle between tight-money gold bugs and the loose-money proponents of free silver in the presidential election of 1896 has again become one of the central problems of American politics and the international economy. Only this time, the currencies squaring off are the "loose" dollar and the hard-money yen and deutsche mark. <p>The struggle in American politics a hundred years ago--as it is today--was between two different concepts of money. On the one hand, money is supposed to be a reliable store of value. Savers and creditors count on a stable currency; they expect that the dollars they receive tomorrow will be approximately as valuable as the dollars they hold today. Inflation destroys that contract. On the other hand, money is supposed to serve as a convenient medium of exchange. It should not be in such short supply that the normal processes of economic life--investment and trade--are paralyzed by a scarcity of cash.<p>Ideally, of course, money should perform both functions well at the same time. But when a monetary system is in crisis, it can't serve both purposes simultaneously. Instead, people divide according to their interests. Creditors and savers, naturally enough, want to keep the value of money high, even if doing so damages the real economy. Entrepreneurs and debtors would rather see the value of money diminish than have high interest rates choke off economic activity. The U.S. divided along those lines at the end of the 19th century; a similar split is happening today among debtor and creditor nations. <p>In 1896 advocates of the gold standard wanted the United States to remain linked to an international monetary system based on a fixed parity between the American dollar and the British pound--approximately five dollars to the pound, and four pounds to one troy ounce of gold.<p>In the world of 1896 that meant, as it had since the Civil War, that America had what today would be called a tight-money policy. The world economy was undergoing a major expansion. Wheat from the United States, Argentina, and Australia flooded the market. Steel poured from the furnaces of the Ruhr, Pittsburgh, and Birmingham, England. But the world's gold supply--and hence its money supply--was relatively fixed. At a time of rising productivity in agriculture and industry, the prices of things fell and the cost of money rose. The gold standard was in effect a 19th-century version of a zero-inflation or even a negative-inflation policy. <p>Huge silver discoveries at the time, especially in the American West, led to an increase in the world's silver supply. The price of silver was plummeting, yet "free silver" enthusiasts like Bryan wanted to coin unlimited supplies of silver dollar coins and value them at the historic prices that held before the glut. This would have expanded the money supply, cutting the costs of credit for American farmers and small businessmen and inflating the price of the things these parts of the economy produced.<p>Politicians like William McKinley and creditors such as J.P. Morgan argued that free silver would plunge the national economy into crisis. (It would also, of course, have produced inflation, reducing the value of their bond investments.) Foreign investors would sell their dollars and their American stocks, and credit would dry up. Who, after all, would want to lend gold to be repaid in silver valued at an artificially high price?<p>The gold bugs won both the political and the intellectual battle in 1896. McKinley beat Bryan in the presidential election, the U.S. remained on the gold standard, and the dollar maintained its parity with the pound. In subsequent years the currency issue largely disappeared from American politics as a rush of gold discoveries in North America and South Africa greatly increased the world's gold supply. <p>In the longer term, the effects of American economic growth and World War I combined to knock everybody else off the gold standard. As global economic leadership passed from London to New York, the world increasingly ran on a dollar standard. The United States promised to redeem dollars for gold at a fixed price; other countries accepted this promise and held much of their financial reserves in dollars rather than the yellow metal.<p>The postwar monetary system, named for Bretton Woods, the New Hampshire resort where the international accord was hammered out in 1944, synthesized the two sides in the 1896 debate. On one hand, the U.S. kept its domestic currency at a par value against gold and foreign currencies. On the other hand, the Federal Reserve--abetted by the U.S. Treasury--pursued a relatively expansionary monetary policy. The United States had the best of both worlds: money that was both easy and sound. The Bretton Woods years--1946 to 1971--combined faster than average growth with low inflation. The dollar functioned as a stable store of value and as an accommodating circulating medium; it was the best of all possible worlds.<p>Of course, it didn't--couldn't--last. As the Fed increased the dollar supply in line with the needs of the domestic economy and as the U.S. government spent billions of dollars abroad on such dubious ventures as the war in Vietnam, it became all too clear to foreign bankers, governments, and investors that there were more dollars in the world's monetary system than there was gold in Fort Knox. The world gradually lost confidence in the U.S. government's promise to redeem dollars for gold at the price of $35 an ounce, and in the 1970s the system broke down in a wave of inflation and turmoil that shook the world financial system and saw the price of gold skyrocket as high as $800 an ounce.<p>Since then, the world monetary system has alternated between periods of chaos and stability, but precious metals have largely dropped out of the monetary system. This is partly because the price of gold in dollars has been relatively stable and partly because the extraordinary range of securities and currencies available today gives investors many more profitable ways to protect their portfolios than hoarding non-interest-bearing metal bars and coins.<p>But the dollar hasn't been nearly as stable against such currencies as the yen and the deutsche mark. In 1970 a dollar was worth 360 yen and 3.6 DM. In July 1995 a dollar was worth only 88 yen and 1.4 DM--a drop, respectively, of 76 percent and 61 percent against the two new supercurrencies. <p>There is a tendency in the U.S. and abroad to blame all this on the usual suspects--lax management at the Fed and the well-known tendencies of Americans to consume instead of save. While there is some truth in this, it is worth remembering that the greenback, for all its faults, hasn't gone down against gold. By this traditional measure, it is Germany and Japan that are out of line.<p>But assessing blame is far less important than understanding the new monetary world being created by these factors. Once again, as in the 19th century, the two functions of money--circulating medium and store of value--are increasingly diverging. The dollar remains the world's medium of circulation par excellence. When an Iranian sells oil to a Sri Lankan, the transaction takes place in dollars. But increasingly, the mark and the yen are challenging the dollar's role as the world's leading reserve currency. As recently as 1984, 75 percent of the world's currency reserves were in dollars. Today it is down to 65 percent.<p>Economists have tended to focus on the problems caused by the decline of the dollar as an international store of value. If central banks and private holders continue to lose confidence in the dollar as a stable store of value, demand for the dollar will fall, but the supply will be unchanged. The result, of course, would be a continued fall in the dollar's value, which would erode our purchasing power, raise domestic interest rates, and lower our standard of living.<p>But a two-tiered international monetary system poses its own dangers too. For example, the developing tigers in East Asia measure their income stream in dollars--from exports to the United States and other dollar-denominated trade transactions. Their debts, however, are usually denominated in yen, the currency of the region's largest creditor. If the dollar continues to drop against the yen, these countries--however successfully they increase their trade earnings in dollars--will have trouble repaying their current debts and attracting new yen-denominated investments.<p>The problems of a two-tiered money system are also showing up on this side of the Pacific. Take the U.S. stock market. In the 1990s dollar investors have reveled as stocks hit one record high after another. Yen investors haven't had as much fun. For an investor who counts his money in yen, U.S. stocks actually declined 9 percent from mid-1990 to mid-1995.<p>The result, of course, is a diminished Japanese appetite for U.S. securities. To put it in language that would be familiar to William McKinley, a soft-money, debtor country like the U.S. progressively cuts itself off from the access to the capital that it needs. Neither the Japanese, the Taiwanese, nor the citizens of any other country with a savings surplus want to lend to a country whose money keeps declining in value.<p>To the hard-money advocates this is intolerable. The U.S. must make the dollar one of the hardest of the hard currencies--even if it hurts. Raise interest rates; cut government spending; grit your teeth during the ensuing recession.<p>In 1896, Bryan thought we could force bimetallism on the world. The U.S. economy is so important to investors, he said, that they will have to deal with us whether we keep our money hard or soft. In today's world, the soft-money advocates say, both the Germans and the Japanese will have to continue accepting dollars in payment and investing in dollar-based economies because there isn't anything else to do.<p>But today that looks like a global lose-lose proposition. U.S. citizens lose purchasing power and the United States loses clout because a falling dollar undermines our financial strength abroad. Meanwhile, stagnating economies and low returns on investment in the hard-currency countries aren't making people happy there either.<p>The best solution would be for today's hard supercurrencies to soften a bit. Why should the mark and the yen appreciate against gold? I hope Germany and Japan will realize that their present reckless ultratight policies will ruin the world economy if they don't loosen up.<p>But don't count on it, and don't count on America's ability to make them see reason. One of the saddest consequences of being a debtor is that nobody listens to your proposals for credit reform.<p>Walter Mead is the Presidential Fellow at the World Policy Institute at the New School. Research assistance: Tomas Matza. <p>
KEYWORDS: Government, International Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/7pages.gif"><br>About 7 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

