<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-The Flat Taxers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Flat Taxers</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-The Flat Taxers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Experts<p>THE FLAT TAXERS
What if everyone paid the same tax rate, no deductions allowed? It could happen--soon.<p>By James K. Glassman<p>Some very influential politicians want to end the tax code as we know it--make it less complicated, possibly more fair, and more beneficial to the economy. <p>Right now, the most popular idea is the flat tax, which after a generous personal exemption, would take the same percentage of income from everyone and eliminate all deductions--whether for charity or mortgages. Only income from interest, dividends, and capital gains would be tax free. That, at any rate, is the "pure" version of the flat tax proposed a year ago and slightly revised in July by the conservative House majority leader, Dick Armey of Texas.<p>Under Armey's proposal, Americans would pay 20 percent of their taxable income (declining to 17 percent after two years). This may be optimistic; the Treasury Department estimates a 22 to 23 percent rate would yield revenue equal to the current system.<p>Armey defines "taxable income" as salary and pension income minus personal exemptions: $21,400 for married couples filing jointly, $14,000 for single heads of household, and $5,000 for each dependent. So a family of four would pay taxes only on income above $31,400. If household income totaled $131,400, the tax bill would be $100,000 times the flat rate. At 20 percent, that comes to $20,000.<p>Is any of this politically feasible? "The flat tax is a home run," says Kellyanne Fitzpatrick, whose firm, The Polling Co., has been conducting focus groups for months on the issue. A 1995 Princeton Survey Research Associates poll found that 59 percent of Americans support a flat tax.<p>There is powerful opposition. The National Association of Realtors worries that ending the deductibility of mortgage interest and real estate taxes would depress the value of existing homes and turn potential buyers into renters. It participated in a study by DRI/McGraw-Hill, a Lexington, Massachusettsbased economic consulting firm, which concluded that the net worth of U.S. households would fall by $1.2 trillion in the first year of a flat tax. <p>State and local governments, as well as many investment firms, also worry about the effect of the flat tax on the municipal-bond market. Under the Armey plan, munis would no longer be the sole tax-exempt bonds; corporate and U.S. Treasury bonds would enjoy the same privilege. Should this cause demand for munis to fall, outstanding bonds could drop in value and local agencies would have to pay higher interest to attract buyers of future issues.<p>Many economists, including Alan Reynolds of the Hudson Institute and Dan Mitchell of the Heritage Foundation, dismiss this concern. They say that low tax rates will spur investment and raise this country's savings rate, the lowest among all industrial nations, with the sole exception of the Netherlands. Dale Jorgenson, a Harvard economist who specializes in the economics of taxation, estimates that the flat tax will boost national wealth by $1 trillion, and even the DRI study concluded that, after the first two years, a flat tax would increase the annual gross domestic product by a full percentage point, substantially cut bond interest rates, and hike capital spending by 5 to 10 percent a year.<p>The flat tax isn't the only idea around. A tax on goods and services, such as a national sales tax or a value-added tax, has the support of Representative Bill Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, where all tax legislation must originate. <p>For investors, either proposal would be a boon. If you and your spouse have $38,000 or more in taxable income, the IRS takes at least 28 cents of every dollar of interest you earn on Treasury or corporate bonds, stock or money market dividends, and gains realized in selling an asset. Under a flat tax or national sales tax, this tax bite would vanish.<p>Real estate and municipal-bond investors, however, may find the future less sunny.<p>Some 28 million Americans deduct a home mortgage on their tax returns, shaving an average of $2,100 off their taxes. The deduction, in effect, helps pay the homeowner's mortgage. Without it, says the NAR, summarizing the DRI study, "homes would lose 15% of market value, a loss that would be fully reflected in their market price ... an immediate and massive loss of equity." Hardest hit, says Linda Goold, tax counsel to the NAR, would be the "working rich"--two-earner couples with expensive houses bought with big mortgages.<p>DRI reached its estimate of 15 percent by calculating the value of the lost mortgage deduction, then adding the advantage of the lower mortgage rates that would result if the national savings rate rose. But this estimate is debatable. DRI posits rates falling about 1 percent, but that could be too modest (Armey predicts a decrease of two or more points). Even after tax rates were cut sharply, in the 1980s, housing prices kept rising, reducing the value of the mortgage deduction, notes Bruce Bartlett, a Bush administration Treasury official and now a private consultant.<p>David Wyss, DRI's research director, disputes this optimistic scenario. Without mortgage deductibility, he says, fewer families could afford big-ticket houses. Demand would drop, depressing real estate values. And the rising value of other assets may not help. "Most Americans under 55 have a negative net worth outside the value of their home," Wyss says.<p>A family with a hefty mortgage could find itself with a big tax increase under a flat tax. Consider a husband and wife with one child in which the spouses earn $120,000 a year from their jobs plus another $10,000 in interest and dividend income; they pay $37,500 in mortgage interest, $6,000 in state income taxes, and $4,000 in property taxes, and have $5,000 in other deductions. Under current law, this family would pay about $14,800 in taxes. Under the Armey tax, the family's tax bill would rise: $120,000 in salary (no tax on the investment income) minus $26,400 in personal exemptions equals $93,600 in taxable income. Multiply by 20 percent, and the bill comes to $18,720, or $3,920 greater than the current bill.<p>"People will buy smaller houses," Wyss predicts, "because part of what they buy now is a tax shelter." They'll diversify into stocks and bonds, investments that help businesses grow. This shift "from nonproductive to productive assets" could produce "significant long-term benefits," Wyss says--though it could take ten years.<p>A flat tax would change the bond situation as drastically as the real estate market. Interest on nearly all state and local bonds would remain tax-exempt under a flat tax. However, interest on bonds issued by the U.S. Treasury, federal agencies, and corporations would also become tax-exempt, and that could mean trouble for munis.<p>The tax advantage now enjoyed by munis allows them to pay lower interest than taxable bonds. A high-quality muni might yield 5 percent, against 6 percent for a Treasury with similar maturity. But for a taxpayer in a 36 percent bracket, the muni's taxable-equivalent return of 7.8 percent (the rate if munis were taxable) versus 6 percent for Treasury bonds makes munis a better deal.<p>Reynolds and many other economists believe that one effect of a flat tax would be that the rate on Treasurys would fall to that of munis, leaving investor demand unchanged. But Micah Green, executive vice president of the Public Securities Association, says that the enactment of a flat tax might make alternative bonds more attractive, potentially forcing muni yields to rise and hurting both current holders and future issuers. "You're already seeing the effect," he says.<p>In a recent Smith Barney newsletter, George Friedlander, a fixed-income portfolio strategist, reports that "even the very preliminary discussions of Tax Reform that appeared in the financial press in late April caused the price of municipal bonds to decline." However, Stephen Entin, a resident scholar at the Institute for Research on the Economics of Taxation, in Washington, D.C., says the decline could also be due to Republican proposals to shift spending to the states, putting them under more budget pressure. Entin believes that under a flat tax, "the economy would strengthen and state and local government revenues would increase."<p>Munis may in fact hold their own in a flat-tax environment. Entire classes of new buyers will likely enter the market, like pension funds, which currently pay no taxes and thus have no motivation to buy munis that yield even 90 percent of the Treasury-bond rate. Or banks. Or foreign investors.<p>In the end, no one can prophesy the result of a tax-system overhaul. And the possibility remains that more moderate approaches will prevail. Senator Arlen Specter and House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt have offered flat-tax plans retaining mortgage deductibility, for example.<p>Still, opinion surveys largely confirm the popularity of the flat tax beyond its potential benefits. The reason, says Fitzpatrick, is that everyone gets treated the same under a flat tax. It's a notion Americans find powerfully appealing, and one that could ultimately sweep aside even the most entrenched opposition. Congress could vote on the issue as early as the end of this year.<p>James K. Glassman writes a column on politics and finance for the Washington Post. He also hosts TechnoPolitics on PBS and Capital Gang Sunday on CNN.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Homeowner, Bond Investing, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

