<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Excellent Adventure</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Excellent Adventure</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Excellent Adventure</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Experts<p>EXCELLENT ADVENTURE
This economic recovery really is different--and that's good news for stock and bond investors<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Wall street skeptics are famous for snorting whenever optimists claim "It's different this time" to justify sky-high stock prices. Stock market sophisticates say that by all standard measures--price-to-earnings ratios, the market's dividend yield, price-to-book ratios--we're in perilous territory where equities are concerned. And we have been ever since the Dow Jones Industrials broke through 4000 last spring.<p>So when the bulls argue that past is not prologue--that measures that once worked to value stocks no longer do the job because we've entered a different world--the bears smirk and warn investors to check for their wallets.<p>Normally, in this space we'd agree; Full Disclosure has a habit of siding with the skeptics. But this time, the doubters may be undone. The economic recovery we're in right now looks different from past recoveries. And this bodes very well for bond and stock investors, even at today's lofty levels.<p>That's not to say we think that all stocks will benefit from this happy scenario. After six months in which the Standard & Poor's 500 returned 20 percent, selectivity is crucial for investors looking to buy stocks now. But for three compelling reasons, many stocks still actually look like good buys.<p>What's the case? It has been best articulated by Richard Hokenson, chief economist at Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette in New York City, who says flatly: "The current economic recovery, which began in March 1991, is unique." His reasoning: This rebound, from its earliest stage, has generated substantially more productivity growth than real gross-domestic-product growth, something that has never happened before in postwar U.S. economic cycles. And even late in the recovery, productivity increases have kept pace with gains in GDP, another unheard-of occurrence. Finally, contrary to the Federal Reserve Board's fears last year, the inflation monster has been tamed this time around. Result: A highly unusual scenario--the best news on inflation will occur near the end of this expansion rather than in the beginning.<p>To Hokenson, these are secular, not cyclical changes for investors to ponder. And they are changes that will keep the recovery going much longer than most--well into 1996. That's because productivity gains are here to stay and high inflation, that ravager of stock and bond returns, is securely in the lockup.<p>The two are related. One of the key reasons Hokenson is looking for inflation to dip to an annualized 2.3 percent by the end of this year, down from 2.6 percent this June, is productivity. Much of our nation's growth rate is coming from purchases of productivity-enhancing equipment. Faced with the prospect of lower sales growth, more corporations in all industries are seeking ways to increase efficiency. Technology is often the answer. And when companies spend to buy these goods, they add to their capacity at the same time they add to the nation's overall growth.<p>Capital-spending surveys show that businesses shelled out an estimated 9 percent more on capital goods in 1994 than they did in 1993. And in the 12 months ended March 1995, unfilled orders for nondefense, nonaircraft capital goods surged 21 percent.<p>Another reason inflation is not the threat it once was and won't be for some time: Low and stable labor costs. What employers pay their workers, measured by the employment cost index, fell to 2.6 percent in the first quarter from 3 percent in the same period in 1994. Nonunion employee costs dropped even more dramatically: from 3.5 percent in the first quarter of 1994 to 2.6 percent this year.<p>Hokenson argues that labor costs have become a more important predictor of inflation than commodity prices. Indeed, there is a close correlation between unit labor costs and movements in the consumer price index. Yet the action in commodities indexes seems to be what Wall Street watches and worries about. Odd, since there has been almost no correlation between movements in the CPI and those of the Commodity Research Bureau Index or the Journal of Commerce Index for the past 14 years. "Commodity prices have become much less important over time because they represent a smaller and smaller component of total costs," says Hokenson. "In contrast, total labor costs have become more important over time, particularly in the CPI, which includes many services."<p>Nothing about this scenario will change anytime soon, according to Hokenson. Why? Because sudden, unforeseen run-ups in inflation are almost always accompanied by higher labor costs or skyrocketing oil prices. Since 1957, there have been only five incidents when total CPI inflation grew by more than 2 percent in one year. Of those five occurrences, four were prompted by leaps in oil prices of more than 20 percent in a year. In 1979, the only year that inflation rose without an oil shock, unit labor costs were running above 6 percent a year. Since oil prices are low and unit labor costs are under 1 percent, Hokenson believes a spike in inflation for this year and next is highly unlikely.<p>Even more significant, when inflation finally does blip up again, its moves will be off a very low base. The days of double-digit price increases, which investors remember too well from the 1970s, aren't coming back anytime soon. Low inflation and punched-up productivity gains are a potent combination to investors in both stocks and bonds. A core inflation rate of 2.3 percent makes the real return on a five-year Treasury note--recently yielding 5.75 percent--very attractive. And stocks? If you believe inflation has been whipped for more than just the short term, you'll see why money can still be made in equities. Even after their recent explosive moves.<p>Where should you focus your buying? Hokenson believes that makers of consumer durable goods, automobiles, machinery, and office equipment will benefit from the "unique" economic recovery we're in. Losers will be retailers and apparel manufacturers who cannot raise prices on their goods without crushing demand. Defensive issues, such as utilities, consumer nondurables, gold stocks, and military-equipment manufacturers, will underperform. "Growth in company revenues will not be driven by pricing power; it will increasingly be a function of rising output," says Hokenson. "And the most successful companies will be those that achieve increased output via rising productivity." Such productivity will also propel stock prices.<p>Beyond low inflation and hefty productivity, there's another interesting force behind the recent run-up in equities. So says J. Randall Woolridge, a finance professor at Pennsylvania State University's Smeal School of Business. Woolridge set out last year to determine whether stock prices were indeed overvalued, as many on Wall Street claimed. In his study, which appeared this spring in the Journal of Applied Corporate Finance, he concludes that, based on future cash flows of the S&P 500, the market is fairly valued.<p>Although analysts who assess market valuations using more traditional measures--such as earnings or dividend yields--would argue with Woolridge, there is no dispute over one aspect of his analysis: The premium investors get from equities over and above risk-free Treasurys--called the risk premium--has fallen sharply, from 8 percent in the 1970s to 2 percent today.<p>Historically, the market's risk premium--defined as the return in the S&P 500 minus long-term Treasury bond returns--has changed little. For almost 50 years, beginning in 1926, the premium was between 6 and 8 percent. The decline, which means investors will pay higher prices for equities, accepting lower return premiums over Treasurys, started in earnest in the 1970s. But it has never been as low as it is now.<p>Why? Woolridge says it is the result of rising volatility in bonds. Comparing the volatility of stock and bond returns since 1926, Woolridge found stock returns to be significantly more variable or volatile than bond returns through the 1970s; in the 1980s and this decade, bond returns have been almost as variable as those of stocks. "The relative risk has changed in bonds," he says, adding that he can only guess why this is the case.<p>"The bond market has become very sensitive to inflation issues; the stock market has not been as sensitive," Woolridge says. Another possible reason for the higher volatility: Vastly greater numbers of investors pouring money into the bond market via mutual funds than was the case 20 years ago. A third explanation: Globalization of the financial markets has led to much more action in the previously sleepy bond arena.<p>Whatever the reasoning, increasing volatility in bonds was not accompanied by a simultaneous increase in stock volatility. So investors perceive stocks to be less risky than they had been, at least compared with bonds. Is it any wonder the S&P has surged?<p>This perception could change at any time, of course. But the decline in the risk premium investors pay to own stocks certainly helps explain why the market is where it is. Things really may be different after all.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Economy, Bond Investing, Mutual Fund Investing, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
