	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Obsessed By Inflation</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Obsessed By Inflation</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Obsessed By Inflation</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Experts<p>OBSESSED BY INFLATION<p>By Walter Mead<p>Call me ishmael. when federal reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told the Senate Finance Committee, "The appropriate rate of inflation, in my judgment, is zero," I had a sudden flashback to English 101: Great American Novels. I felt like a crewman on the Pequod listening as Captain Ahab uttered his unalterable vow to catch and kill the white whale. <p>We all know what followed upon that nautical policy statement: Moby Dick got away; Ahab, his ship, and all of his crew, except Ishmael, went down to a watery grave. I have no wish to experience the financial equivalent of shipwreck simply because the Federal Reserve's chairman is determined to put an utter end to inflation. <p>Most of the financial establishment didn't react to Greenspan's pronouncement with my degree of alarm, but then most of the financial establishment spent 1994 investing in the Mexican stock market. Instead, well-barbered heads on top of conservatively clad shoulders nodded approvingly. Bondholders, thinking only of the wonderful things zero inflation would do to the real rate of return on their investments, cheered the Fed chairman on.<p>So why am I here to speak of the dangers of this course? Zero inflation sounds great--like zero cancer. Why would anyone oppose it? <p>How about because it's a policy based on misleading statistics that, if it were to work, would produce the kind of low-growth economy enjoyed by Soviet Russia in the decade before the collapse of the Berlin Wall, and that, without public discussion, allows unelected bureaucrats to transfer wealth to older Americans from their children?<p>Strong words, I grant you. To understand why I believe this, let's look at what causes inflation. Most simply, inflation is defined as the rise in the prices of goods and services. But what causes prices to rise?<p>Economists offer two explanations, both focusing on supply and demand. The first--let's call this the friction theory--says that inflation is caused by friction when demand for a good temporarily exceeds supply. Sometimes an unexpected event curtails supply: A freeze in Brazil sends the price of coffee up as the supply plummets. At other times, demand suddenly soars. Suddenly everybody wants to drive a pickup, driving up the price of those vehicles--and the wages of auto workers, the prices of glass and steel, and so forth down the line. In a frictionless world, a new factory would immediately spring up to meet that demand. In the real world, however, there is inevitable grinding and delays as a segment of the economy changes direction. At some point in the future, of course, supply will catch up with demand, but as any consumer knows, prices never fall completely back to earlier levels (if they fall at all). Economists say that prices are sticky upward.<p>Economists who belong to the second camp, the monetarists, offer another explanation. Inflation is caused by expansion of the money supply. If a central bank or a national government increases the supply of money in circulation, the increased amount of money chasing the same supply of goods will drive up prices.<p>A capitalist economy always produces some inflation of the first sort--and that makes zero inflation impossible. We've come to understand that about unemployment, which is an analogous phenomenon. Politicians and economists have been attacking unemployment and pledging to end it for longer than most of us can remember--with very poor results to date. But the long battle against unemployment has taught us that, essentially, there is no such thing as a zero rate of unemployment--and that coming too close to it can be bad for the economy. <p>Why? Even in the best of all possible economies, there would be people looking for jobs. Young people are constantly entering the job market; other workers are changing jobs. There will never be a moment when everybody in the economy has a job at the same time; there will therefore always be some of what economists have come to call frictional unemployment--estimated to be at least 2 percent of the workforce.<p>In the same way there is an irreducible minimum of frictional inflation in the system. Demand for Mighty Morphin Power Rangers exceeds supply. The manufacturer wants to meet the demand, but delays adding workers until orders pile up. The prices at the toy store go up.<p>Because of economic friction, zero inflation is like absolute zero in thermodynamics: an important theoretical concept that can never be seen in real life. Physicists know they cannot produce a temperature of absolute zero in the lab, and that even if they could get it, they couldn't build a thermometer that could measure it. <p>But it's not just that zero inflation is impossible--it's also undesirable. Some inflation is crucial in any capitalist economy, because price changes are essential signals of supply and demand--price increases tell manufacturers, service providers, and investors what to do. If there is a widget shortage, the price goes up and the profits of widget makers increase. This makes existing producers increase their output and may cause new producers to invest in new widget works. <p>A healthy economy is an economy in which producers are getting many signals to increase production and investment. That is, an economy with a certain amount of built-in inflation. <p>You could only get zero inflation in an economy by killing it. Interestingly, the communist economies came closer than capitalist ones to eliminating inflation in the 20th century. The Soviet Union's apologists used to boast that its price stability proved the superiority of communism. <p>Now, clearly, high rates of inflation aren't healthy or necessary for growth. But fine-tuning the economy to achieve the best rate isn't easy--especially because economists have only a vague idea of what the current rate of inflation is. Alan Greenspan, ironically enough, has done the most to publicize this problem. Suggesting to Congress that we could reduce the deficit relatively painlessly, Greenspan argued that current government statistics overstate the rate of inflation by as much as 1.5 percentage points. In other words, more than half of the inflation that the government thinks it sees could be the result of errors in measurement.<p>That's terrific for politicians looking to cut billions of dollars from the federal budget painlessly by lowering cost-of-living adjustments in programs like Social Security to more "accurate" levels. But it's bad news for the inflation fighters at the Federal Reserve. It reminds us that measurements of inflation are inherently unreliable. The consumer price index, which we use to measure the rate of inflation, cannot possibly keep track of all goods and services. It is based on the price of a basket of goods purchased by the average family. Like the Dow Jones Index or any other index, the CPI provides only an approximation of changing price levels. The Dow can be up when the overall market is down and vice versa. Similarly, the CPI can be up--if heating oil is in short supply, for example--even when the prices for most things are steady or even headed down.<p>Nor is it clear how much of any price increase should count as inflation. Health care costs today are much higher than they were 40 years ago--but 40 years ago you couldn't buy many of the treatments that extend our lives today. Or look at computers. The computer I buy in 1995 may cost $3,300 instead of the $2,500 I paid for one in 1988, but it comes with better graphics, a color screen, bigger hard and floppy drives, more memory, and a faster processor. The price of computers, measured by the amount of power a given sum of money can purchase, has dropped steadily and dramatically over those years. Is this inflation or deflation--and how does a price index measure it? <p>The imprecision of our statistics makes it impossible to know exactly what the rate of inflation is--which is one reason monetarists have urged the Federal Reserve to focus on the money supply and not the inflation rate. Unfortunately for this school of economics, money has become as difficult to define as inflation. Every new form of investment account, every new means of electronic transfer, has eroded the traditional definitions of money and the historical relationships between money supply and future economic growth and inflation. Those central bankers who tried to use the money supply as a means to control prices came to grief because in the end they could never get around basic but unavoidable problems: What, precisely, constitutes the supply of money that central bankers ought to control and how, precisely, can changes in the speed with which money circulates be measured? <p>To the chagrin of monetarists, Greenspan's Federal Reserve has thrown up its hands in despair on this issue, saying in effect that it's time to invent a new measure of the money supply since none of the traditional measures work anymore, but it would be lovely if someone else did it.<p>So here we are on the deck of the Pequod chasing a goal--zero inflation--that we may not want to reach and using instruments so inaccurate that we won't be able to see the whale even when it's right beneath us. Such is the power of obsession. Few in Captain Ahab's crew challenged his quest. Few object when the Federal Reserve's chairman announces a policy of zero inflation.<p>But targeting zero inflation isn't ordained by some law of economics; it's a policy decision, akin to deciding to cut welfare or put more money into defense. It hurts some parts of the population and helps others.<p>Fiscal conservatives love to point out that inflation is a hidden tax--one they blame on the federal government--on those who hold bonds and similar financial assets. And that's true. Inflation does erode the future value of principal and interest payments.<p>But the inflation rate is also one way that we decide how to apportion resources between generations. Higher inflation takes value from the older, bondholding generation--which enjoyed the consumption the bonds paid for--and allows the younger, asset-poor generation to pay its obligations in money of lower real value. Throughout history, debtors have always favored inflation; creditors have always opposed that.<p>I'm not sure there is any sound economic reason to use inflation policy to favor one generation over another, but there is also no way to avoid it. At a time when many of those crusading to lower the deficit speak so passionately about the debt we will leave to our children, it seems inconsistent to pursue a zero-inflation policy designed to ensure that those future debts weigh as much as possible.<p>So: Zero inflation is impossible to measure, impossible to create, and undesirable to have. Alan Greenspan, we can confidently predict, will never achieve permanent zero inflation any more than Captain Ahab ever caught Moby Dick. The only question is, how much damage will this mad quest inflict on the ship's long-suffering crew?<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Internatonal Economy, Government, Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

