	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Not on Your Life</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Not on Your Life</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Not on Your Life</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Experts<p>NOT ON YOUR LIFE
Insurance buyers in Australia and the U.K. are saving money. U.S. firms want no part of this.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Life insurance is one of the most maddening and unpleasant purchases a consumer can make. It's certainly no fun to ponder one's mortality, but that's only the half of it. Some--though not all--of the roughly 250,000 folks who peddle life insurance in this country make used-car salesmen look downright genuine and benevolent.<p>Perhaps the most frustrating aspect of buying life insurance is trying to find out what a policy's true costs are; specifically, how much you're paying in sales charges. This is no coincidence--even industry types admit that life insurance doesn't exactly sell itself. To generate business, some life companies are willing to pay salesmen hideously high commissions. Agents can earn, for example, upfront commissions of as much as 125 percent of the first year's premiums on a whole-life policy. This is why it takes so long for cash values in a typical policy to build up to anything substantial, even after years of paying in hefty premiums. It is also why agents are often tempted to churn clients out of one policy into another after just a few years: This practice creates fresh commissions for the salesman.<p>The insurance industry has worked hard to keep costs and commissions in life products well hidden, but consumers are starting to get wise to this. No-load or low-load life insurance is winning market share from the heavily loaded products; no-load and low-load snared 4 to 5 percent of the estimated $1.6 trillion in new life insurance sold throughout the country in 1994, double the share of two years ago.<p>Low-load life insurance, in which commissions are practically nonexistent and a policyholder's cash value builds up almost immediately, might really take off if the disclosure of costs and commissions in life insurance policies were made mandatory. The industry is against this idea, however. William Regan, chief executive officer of the National Association of Life Underwriters, a 138,000-member industry group, derides the detailing of fees, calling it"the Consumer Reports mentality." He says, "The problem we see in full disclosure is that it takes the focus off what the buyer is getting and puts it on what the agent is getting. That's not the story."<p>Unfortunately, what the agent is getting is very much the story in the life insurance industry. What people like Regan don't want to admit is that the cost structures inherent in life insurance products are behind many of the scandals that have made headlines recently. In the past two years, for example, allegations of churning life insurance policies hit Prudential, Mutual Life of New York, Equitable Life, John Hancock, and other industry leaders.<p>In April 1994, this column published a checklist for readers to ask an insurance salesman to complete before readers bought a policy. The checklist called for, among other things, itemized costs of all commissions and charges attached to the policy. Kurt Arndt, a reader in North Carolina who was considering a life insurance investment, reports that when he attempted to get his Prudential agent to complete the checklist, he was told that the company "has no time to answer all questionnaires one might find in magazines." Says Arndt: "They were never willing to disclose in plain English how much they charge during the life of an insurance contract." He canceled his order.<p>Unfortunately, life insurance companies are not required by law to divulge such information in plain and clear English. Until they are, they're unlikely to volunteer it and will undoubtedly stonewall efforts to open up commission disclosure.<p>But this stonewalling may not work forever. Now that commission disclosure exists for the first time in Australia, the results are proving how beneficial it can be to consumers. According to research conducted by the Life Insurance Marketing Research Association International in Windsor, Connecticut, new-business commissions fell by more than half after disclosure rules went into effect in Australia, declining from around 90 percent of first-year premiums to roughly 40 percent. <p>In January, the U.K. also began requiring insurance companies to tell buyers in writing the fees earned from the sale of any product. Kenneth Clarke, Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, wanted consumers to be able to see exactly what they were getting when they bought life insurance. The LIMRA report states that the Securities and Investments Board, the U.K.'s chief insurance regulator, estimates that clearly detailed product information will save British insurance shoppers the equivalent of $1.6 billion a year.<p>One of the outgrowths of full disclosure is that more life insurance companies in Britain are changing the way they pay agents, switching from commission-based pay to salaries. Marks & Spencer's new life and pensions division started operating this year under new rules: Its sales force is paid a salary, with no bonuses or commissions. As the LIMRA study sums up: "Until the incentive to sell the product with the highest upfront commissions is removed, some agents will abuse clients by overselling and unnecessarily replacing policies." <p>It is just this kind of abuse that is alleged in a class-action lawsuit brought earlier this year against Prudential by a group of policyholders across the nation. According to the lawsuit, Prudential agents, to increase sales and commissions, enticed clients who had accumulated cash values in their existing policies to use that cash to purchase new Prudential policies.<p>Robert Bearden, a machinist from Fort Smith, Arkansas, is a plaintiff in the Prudential case. After Bearden was churned out of his old policy and into a new one, according to the complaint, the cash values and death benefits that he had counted on having were depleted. The lawsuit says, "[His] estate and retirement plan which had been thought to be secure is seriously endangered."<p>Stories like Bearden's do little to boost consumer confidence in an industry that's already under fire. Is it any surprise that the Insurance Information Institute says industry approval ratings fell from 48 percent to 42 percent last year? At the same time, the disapproval rating rose from 18 percent to 23 percent. <p>With the U.K. and Australian precedents to point to, however, consumers in the U.S. can at last turn up the heat on our own insurance regulators to work toward full commission disclosure in the selling of life insurance. <p>One way to do this is to write to the National Association of Insurance Commissioners, the group of state insurance regulators that oversees the industry, encouraging it to pursue commission disclosure. Lee Douglass, the commissioner from Arkansas, is president of the NAIC (120 West 12th Street, Suite 1100, Kansas City, Missouri 64105-1925). Another way to get the attention of life insurers? Buy only no- or low-load policies. To get more information on these products, call the Wholesale Insurance Network in Tampa, Florida, at 800-808-5810. <p>If consumers don't demand disclosure of commissions, the high costs of buying life insurance will be kept hidden by folks like industry spokesman Regan, who argues that disclosure only "muddles up the process." Regan should let consumers be the judge of that. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

