<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Dr. Barnes's Passion for Art</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Dr. Barnes's Passion for Art</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Dr. Barnes's Passion for Art</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth Magazine/Advisor<p>DR. BARNES'S PASSION FOR ART<p>By Peter Edidin<p>Bill gates, or vlad the impaler to his competitors, has struck again. Corbis Publishing, a small Bellevue, Washington, company controlled by Gates, has produced a terrific CD-ROM that restores some credibility to the much-hyped term multimedia. <p>A Passion for Art: Renior, Cezanne, Matisse, and Dr. Barnes is a virtual exhibition of some 330 works of art from the collection of Albert C. Barnes at the Barnes Museum in Merion, Pennsylvania. It takes you "into" the musuem, where the works hang upon the wall just as Barnes arranged them. The collection is famous for its stunning array of Impressionist and Post-Impressionist paintings by Cezanne, Renoir, Corot, Pissarro, Modigliani, Courbet, and innumerable others. Picasso, Braque, Goya, Matisse, Monet, Klee--in fact, a virtual catalog of the great painters of the late 19th and early 20th centuries--are included here. Speaking on the CD-ROM, J. Carter Brown, director emeritus of the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C., calls it "the greatest collection of its kind ever assembled by one person."<p>Barnes, a man of self-made wealth and self-taught connoisseurship, personally chose and negotiated for virtually all the thousands of works in his collection, mostly during manic buying trips to Paris between the two world wars. He once "actually waved his checkbook in the air," said Gertrude Stein, demanding she sell him a favorite Picasso.<p>The digitized images that record his passion are lovely to look at--the more so since, incredibly, they have been seen by only a handful of people in the past 70 years.<p>Barnes opened his musuem in 1925, showing art still regarded at the time as outrageous and avant-garde. The critics hated it, calling the paintings "diseased" and "degenerate." Embittered by this rejection of his attempt to enlarge the taste of his countrymen, Barnes closed the museum to all but a few painters, art historians, and students. <p>In bringing this work back to light, Corbis has used the vast storage capacity of CD-ROMs to allow the viewer to approach the paintings in a variety of ways. It's possible to take audio tours, conducted by well-known art historians, or study selected paintings with them. An index of all the works, with a pop-up image of each one as you scroll along, allows the paintings to be seen in any order, and portfolios of favorite works can be assembled.<p>The paintings can be displayed chronologically, by subject, or by artist. Each painter is shown in a painted portrait and has a brief biography, while the audio gives the correct pronunciation of his name. The works themselves are described in some detail and can be magnified for a closer look. There is an archive section, with letters showing the progress of Barnes's negotiations, check stubs testifying to their successful outcome, details on how he made the money he lavished on art, and other mementos of Barnes's life. The paintings also form part of a timeline that places the works not only in relation to one another but in the context of major events of the day. <p>All of these features are accessed with the click of a mouse on screens even the most technologically phobic will be able to fathom instantly. Finally, unlike many CD-ROMs, which are difficult to install and run, A Passion for Art requires nothing more than starting up the CD-ROM drive. <p>A Passion for Art sells from Corbis Publishing (800-260-0444) for $40 to $50 and will be available in an Apple version in May 1995. Minimum requirements are a multimedia PC with a 486 chip running at 25 MHz or better, 8 MB of RAM, 256 Super VGA screen, double-speed CD-ROM drive, 8-bit Windows-compatible sound card and speakers, mouse, and Microsoft Windows version 3.1. <p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
