<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Advisor Briefs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>ADVISOR BRIEFS<p>By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>Stocking No-loads
The Securities and Exchange Commission recently made it easier for companies to adopt no-load stock plans that let investors buy stock direct from the companies, avoiding brokerage fees. These open-availability plans allow investors to reinvest partial dividends after investing as little as $50 in stocks, which can be traded at least once every five business days. Investors may automatically debit their bank accounts for purchases. Jim Volpe, a vice president with First Chicago Trust Co. of New York and an early champion of no-loads, says they save investors millions in fees. For a list of the 55 or so companies now offering such plans, call the Securities Transfer Association at 908-888-2112. <p>Educating IRA 
Millions of Americans will invest this year in IRAs. But many are putting their money in the wrong ones. According to the Investment Company Institute, one quarter of the $857.4 billion in IRA and Keogh money is stuck in federally insured bank and S&L accounts, whose modest returns are vulnerable to inflation. Says Eileen Sharkey, a certified financial planner in Denver: "Growth, growth, growth is the key. IRAs are too often in secure, dangerously low-yielding investments." Worse, a recent Federal Reserve Board study showed 47.2 percent of 3,906 households had at least some IRA money sitting in uninsured bank accounts. Sharkey says individuals more than three years from retirement should keep about two thirds of their IRA money in moderate-risk equity or balanced funds that beat the average equity fund over the last ten years.<p>Prepare to Meet Your Maker
Thought about dying recently? Probably not, according to a Louis Harris & Associates survey commissioned by the Lutheran Brotherhood, a not-for-profit financial-services group in Minneapolis. The November 1994 survey of 1,000 randomly selected heads of household found that almost 60 percent did not have a will. Those with children were even less likely to have one than the childless--33 percent versus 47 percent. The biggest will-makers were those over age 65 (72 percent had one). David Rustad, spokesman for the Lutheran Brotherhood, says about 80 percent of those polled had done no estate planning, such as establishing trusts. Says Rustad: "Americans are so averse to the subject of death, they don't plan for their heirs' financial well-being." <p>The IRS Eyes Derivatives 
The IRS wants its cut of the huge derivatives market, says IRS attorney Alan B. Munro. Munro is working with the Treasury Department on ways to tax the difference between a derivative's discounted purchase price and an estimated future price, much as the agency taxes the interest derived from the difference between the purchase price of an original-issue discount bond and the redemption price. If these rules take effect, "investors would have to include their gain in their gross income and pay tax on it," says Charles Wheeler, an investment specialist at KPMG Peat Marwick in Washington, D.C. Derivatives under scrutiny: Prepaid forward contracts, which the General Accounting Office says amounted to $7.5 billion in 1992; swaps ($4.7 billion); and interest-rate cap and floor contracts ($10.9 billion).<p>Thinking About A New Jet? 
CEOs who love their corporate jets may now have an easier time paying for one. NetJets of Montvale, New Jersey, sells time-shares in four types of private jets, including Cessnas and Raytheon Hawkers. The company divides each plane into one-eighth interests equal to 100 hours of flight time a year. A one-eighth interest in a $2.5 million Cessna Citation S/II, for example, goes for $330,000, plus $5,920 monthly for maintenance, crews, and insurance and $1,120 for each hour of flying time. If you fly 100 hours a year, the total expense of $513,040 is far below the $850,000 or so it costs just to maintain the plane. NetJets guarantees domestic availability of a seven-seat jet on four, six, or eight hours notice, depending on the type of aircraft and the amount invested. So far, the company has 220 investors, including some of the top ten companies in the Fortune 500.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
