	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Advisor Briefs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Advisor Briefs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Advisor <p>ADVISOR BRIEFS<p>By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>THE TAX MAN COMETH 
Several tax-law changes took effect in 1994. Here are the most noteworthy:<p>A receipt from the charity, not just a canceled check, is now the only acceptable proof for individual charitable deductions of $250 or more if you are audited (it does not have to be attached to your return) <p>Unreimbursed moving expenses must be claimed as an adjustment to gross income, not as an itemized deduction.<p>To deduct moving expenses for a new job, employees must move at least 50 miles, up from 35 previously. The IRS wiped out deductions for travel meals, pre-move househunting trips, and temporary living expenses incurred up to 30 days after a move. <p>Most club dues are not allowable write-offs. <p>Taxpayers may deduct home-office expenses only if the office is their principal place of business.<p>Home buyers may now deduct seller-paid mortgage points for loans used to buy or improve a principal residence.<p>The minimum annual wage at which Social Security and Medicare taxes must be paid for household help is now $1,000, up from $50 a quarter. Baby-sitters under age 18 and in school are exempt.<p>The Nightmare Audit
This October, for the first time since 1988, the IRS plans to conduct line audits on 153,000 tax returns as part of its taxpayer compliance measurement program. But that doesn't mean the IRS is socking 153,000 individual taxpayers. Just 33,000 randomly selected wage earners will have to provide proof to an agent of each item reported on every line of their 1994 returns. The IRS also plans to go after 59,000 small-business owners who filed Schedule C and/or F, 12,500 partnership returns, and 48,500 corporate returns. The unlucky auditees should be prepared to hand over their 1993 and 1992 returns, too.<p>Patriots pay up
Back in the '40s and '50s, millions of Americans bought 40-year war bonds__$50 billion worth alone during World War II__which are now at maturity. A $1,000 series E bond purchased for $750 in November 1954 was worth $7,086.80 in November 1994. But yesterday's patriotism, like just about everything else, belongs in part to the IRS. The bonds' accrued interest is taxable, and those in the 28 percent bracket will have to pay $1,774 on that $750 bond.<p>Don't forget the DRIP
Sick of paying brokerage fees? More than 1,000 U.S. companies will sell you additional shares at prevailing market prices through dividend reinvestment plans. Plus, they'll let you reinvest dividends directly in new shares. Some firms even sell their shares at a small discount, usually around 5 percent. For the names of these companies and plan details, write for the Directory of Companies Offering Dividend Reinvestment Plans ($28.95), available from Evergreen Enterprises, P.O. Box 763, Laurel, Maryland 20725. For a free list of company names only, call The Moneypaper, a DRIP newsletter, at 800-388-9993.<p>Orange County fallout
The good news, according to Joseph Piraro, manager of the Van Kampen/American Capital closed-end fund, is that two big fund families__Franklin and Putnam__are now emerging from serious problems related to Orange County's bankruptcy. The bad news is how they've done it. Franklin in particular is said to have had to sell high-rated, short-term corporate debt to cover redemptions. Florida, Ohio, and Texas may be the next municipal-bond markets to have derivatives problems.<p>DON'T HANG UP
Long-distance customers, who spend roughly $31.5 billion on phone calls annually placed through <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:FON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11560"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sprint</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, may be unnecessarily paying an extra $2.5 billion a year, says TeleChoice, a Verona, New Jersey, telecommunications consulting firm. Most carriers bill residential customers in full-minute increments, so consumers who hang up one second into the next minute get charged for the whole minute. One upstart carrier, <a name="NYSE:LCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16038"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LCI International</b></a> of McLean, Virginia, will charge customers in six-second increments.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Homeowner, Small Business Ownership, Bond Investing, Government, Retirement, Mutual Funds Investing, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
