<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-A Literary Love Song to Lucre</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Literary Love Song to Lucre</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-A Literary Love Song to Lucre</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995
Worth magazine/Advisor<p>A LITERARY LOVE SONG TO LUCRE
By Peter Edidin<p>It is proverbially said that all the stories ever told contain only ten plots. Possibly, too, there are only that many subjects. The imagination, like plots, is fueled by facts. And the "`facts of life" are few, captured in the physical and emotional passage of existence: birth, death, youth, age, love, hate, joy, fear.<p>Money, certainly, is one of those archetypal elements of consciousness, and the subject of a lively anthology, The Oxford Book of Money, edited by Kevin Jackson and published this month (Oxford University Press, $25). Jackson, an arts editor at the daily Independent in England, has compiled "a book about money and the imagination." Money, he writes in an introduction, is so much with us as to be "the atmosphere we all breathe." The air in this book changes from page to page, as writers from Sophocles ("No thing in use by man, for power of ill/Can equal money") to Andy Warhol ("Cash. I'm just not happy when I don't have it. The minute I have it ... I just buy STUPID THINGS.") respond to the ubiquitous, maddeningly protean medium of exchange. <p>The book is neatly, if somewhat factitiously, organized into ten categorical chapters like "Opening Accounts," "Riches and Poverty," "Vice," "Virtue," "Coda: Hells and Heavens," and so on, but otherwise the selections, from brief aphorisms to a page or so of Marx or Dickens, are tightly packed according to no apparent system. This is a book for browsing rather than reading start to finish. Still, the range of writers and the breadth of their responses to money leave one alternately invigorated by so much ingenious thought and depressed that, clearly, history's principal thinkers have failed to comprehend and hence circumscribe money's mysterious influence any more than they have understood, say, sex. Not so incidentally, the subjects are often intertwined, whether it's John Updike's Rabbit and Mrs. Angstrom excitedly making love atop a pile of Krugerrands or the Emperor Caligula, "seized by desire ... rolling in gold over and over again." One is left feeling like Samuel Butler, who wrote, "While there is flesh there is money__or want of money; but money is always on the brain so long as there is a brain in reasonable order."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
