<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Let the Looting Begin</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Let the Looting Begin</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Let the Looting Begin</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Experts  <p> LET THE LOOTING BEGIN <p>Why are the SEC and the courts letting limited partnership investors get the shaft yet again?    <p> By Gretchen Morgenson  <p> Investors in real estate limited partnerships have already suffered three ignominies. When they bought their units in the 1980s,they paid exorbitant prices, including huge organizational and selling costs of 25 percent to the brokers peddling them. Then, the real estate market tanked, reducing the value of their units to a tiny fraction of what they cost. The third insult: Investors wanting out of their units found they couldn't sell, even at distressed prices. This is because regulators at the National Association of Securities Dealers and executives at the major firms have done all they can to prevent a secondary market in partnership units from springing up (Full Disclosure, July/August1994).  <p> What more could these investors suffer? If you're one of the millions who put an estimated $50 billion into real estate limited partnerships, prepare for the ultimate humiliation. Just when many commercial and residential real estate markets are picking up, sophisticated investors like ex-Drexel financier Leon Black, with the aid of greedy general partners, are swooping down on to limited-partnership investors and squeezing them out of units at pennies on the dollar.  <p> What do the regulators and the courts have to say to this egregious situation? Standing quietly by, they offer a clear message: Let the looting begin.  <p> Only a few such deals have been done so far, but because the potential profits are so huge and the Securities and Exchange Commission has done nothing to stop the pillaging, you can bet more will come. If the hardball tactics employed by Black in the most recent partnership take over were used to acquire a publicly traded stock, he would have been shut down instantly by well-organized institutional investors in the courts. But because limited partners in most of these deals tend to be unsophisticated small investors, powerless to organize, general partners appear free to impel limited partners, to whom they have a fiduciary duty, to sell their units back at rock-bottom prices. Glen Bigelow, head of Bigelow Management, a real estate investment firm in New York, says: "This is the most vicious type of insider trading I've seen. Yet there's an amazing silence from Wall Street and the SEC."  <p> Bigelow calls it insider trading because the very guys trying to gain control of the assets are the ones who know the most about the value of the partnerships' holdings. A recent deal involved 19 California partnerships--run by Century Properties, MRI Business Properties, and National Property Investors--which raised a total of $1.1 billion from more than 100,000 small investors between 1977 and 1986. The outfit tendering for the partnership units in mid-October--DeForest Ventures--consists of the general partners in charge of the 19 partnerships and Apollo Real Estate Advisors, a Leon Black investment fund. The general partners haven't done well for their small investors--in most of the partnerships, not one nickel in income has been distributed for five years. Apollo bought a third of the general partner for $15 million, then set up the group to make the tender.  <p> Black never plunges into anything unless he can get something big out of it. Here, that something is the potential to sell off, at sizable gains, the partnership's real estate once it's under his control. Forget that the proceeds from property sales are supposed to go to the people whose funds bought them initially--the long-suffering limited partners.  <p> The DeForest offering statement is a work worthy of Machiavelli. The firm tries to sell limited partners on what is a quintessential case of self-enrichment by a general partner. It says the offer will give unit holders "an opportunity to liquidate their investment without the usual transaction costs associated with market sales." Other reasons to tender: "General disenchantment with real estate investments, particularly long-term investments in limited partnerships" and "Continuing administrative costs and resultant negative financial impact on the value of the partnership's assets." Love the irony? Tender your dud units to the very folks whose high administrative costs helped make them a dud.  <p> The truly shocking part of the deal is the price DeForest offered to pay unit holders. For units of all 19 partnerships, DeForest offered only 60 percent of the estimated value Apollo gave the units when it assessed them before the offer. DeForest offered $70 million for assets that investors bought a decade ago for $550 million. Apollo values the assets at more than $116 million. <p> Lawrence Whiteside, a limited partner who put $5,000 in one of the deals, hired James Fotenos, a San Francisco lawyer, to try to stop the tender. In his complaint, Fotenos says the deal "represents a cynical attempt to exploit the frustration of the limited partners and capture a significant portion of the assets of these partnerships. . . . The real estate markets are turning around. . . . [This is] a crude attempt at looting the partnerships." <p> A San Mateo County Superior Court judge denied Fotenos's request for an injunction to stop the offer. As a result, it went through in late November. DeForest grabbed approximately 35 percent of the partnership units, effectively giving the firm total control over the operation. Fotenos believes there's nothing to stop the general partner from tendering later for the entire partnership. He plans to appeal the ruling.  <p> Why did so many investors tender units to DeForest at devastation prices? They're fed up with an investment that has returned zero for the past five years and that presents a tax-filing horror each April.  <p> One of the most distressing twists to this case was the late emergence of a higher offer for the partnership units made by Koll Management Services, a real estate company in California. Koll's offer to limited partners was 25 percent higher than DeForest's. But before investors could tender their units to Koll, the company rescinded its offer. According to court documents, Koll's president, Harold Hofer, said privately that a "deal had been struck" between Koll and Apollo when Apollo contacted the firm's CEO, Ray Wirta. As a result, Koll pulled out. (Wirta did not return a phone call for comment.) Once again, power and money prevail; limited partners lose.  <p> Where was the SEC in this mess, or <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, underwriter of three of the partnerships whose clients got the shaft? The SEC did not return repeated phone calls by press time. A Merrill spokesperson said, "Our most significant concern was that our clients had appropriate information to make the decision whether to tender." Thanks, guys.  <p> There's little investors in the DeForest situation can do now, but Fotenos recommends that anyone stuck in a burnt-out limited partnership write a letter calling attention to this outrage to Arthur Levitt, SEC Chairman, 450 Fifth Street, N.W., Washington, D.C. 20549. A letter-writing campaign is also a must for investors who get trapped in similar tender offers in the future. Given the easy profits likely to go to Leon Black in the DeForest deal, such tender traps are certain to become very popular indeed. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
