<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Limited Partnerships:  No Exit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Limited Partnerships:  No Exit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
You've heard of the gift that keeps on giving? Limited partnerships are the investment that keeps on taking.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Are you one of the legions of investors trapped in a limited partnership you bought in the 1980s? Over the course of the decade, an estimated 10 million souls put about $90 billion into commercial or residential real estate, oil and gas, equipment leasing, and cable deals. Sold as portfolio diversification with tax advantages to boot, partnerships found their way into the accounts of even small, unsophisticated investors. Brokers who sold the deals raked huge fees off the top -- total organizational and selling costs often exceeded 25 percent of the amount invested -- and general partners running the properties earned rich management fees every year. <p>If only investors had done so well. Thanks to the real estate depression and low oil prices, most partnerships today are worth a small fraction of what investors paid for them. One knowledgeable player in the industry says that half the money raised in the partnership boom has been lost to excessive fees and declining asset values.<p>Investors bought partnerships for two reasons: They hoped ultimately for capital gains from assets held in the portfolio, and while waiting for those gains, they got tax losses from partnership depreciation. Jerry Cook, a computer specialist, and his wife, Ellen, an accounting professor at the University of San Diego, are typical limited-partnership investors. They bought into a commercial real estate deal back in the '80s. "We put the money we were going to use for our kids' college education into it," says Jerry Cook. Now, units for which the Cooks paid $1,000 each are worth $25. <p>Adding insult to this egregious injury is the fact that investors like the Cooks cannot escape their partnerships' clutches. Unlike most stocks and bonds, which are easily dumped, partnership units are a ball and chain. You've heard of gifts that keep on giving? Limited partnerships are the investments that keep on taking.<p>Why is there virtually no exit from a partnership? Except for a few small independent firms matching up occasional buyers with sellers, there is no established partnership market where investors can sell their discounted units. Few industry players seem interested in creating a market in these securities. Most of the big firms that hawked these wares won't buy them back -- not surprising, given how low the units have sunk from their offering prices. As a rule, general partners running the deals do little to encourage secondary market trading, obfuscating asset values and requiring buyer and seller to fill out mountains of paperwork before units can be exchanged. <p>There's a likely reason brokerage firms and general partners haven't worked to create a secondary market in partnerships: It would show what lousy investments they've been. Such a market would act as a report card on $90 billion in investments that have delivered little if anything on their promise. <p>News of what looked like an attempt to break this logjam came in mid-May, when the National Association of Securities Dealers said it hoped to start listing limited-partnership units on its OTC Bulletin Board, an electronic marketplace for illiquid securities, by the end of the year. Firms interested in buying or selling a partnership unit would put their bids and offers on the system. At last, investors could get a clue to their units' values and identify firms willing to take units off their hands.<p>Time to break out the champagne? Not quite. Although the NASD's plan sounds good and is an improvement over the disorganized and exceedingly illiquid market of today, many limited-partnership investors will remain hostage to bureaucratic obstinacy, powerful general partners, and big-shot brokerage firms. <p>Then there's the Internal Revenue Service, which must sign off on the bulletin-board plan before it gets started. Partnerships operate under different tax rules from corporations --  passing along tax advantages, like losses generated from property depreciation, to limited partners, for instance. <p>Under IRS rules, energy and real estate partnerships qualify for this special treatment if they're not "publicly traded on an established exchange." Will the IRS consider the bulletin board an exchange and disallow the special tax treatment? The IRS won't say.<p>Even if the IRS allows the bulletin board to exist without eliminating partnerships' tax treatment, true liquidity is never going to be achieved in limited partnerships. At least not until the NASD modifies its rules on the fees secondary-market firms can charge to help investors out of their problem units. For now, and for the near future, such a move seems unlikely. <p>The problem: The NASD's guideline regarding the fees firms can charge customers to trade securities. Such fees are not supposed to exceed 5 percent of the value of the securities traded, shared between the firm representing the buyer and the one for the seller.<p>While the guideline makes sense on more frequently traded instruments such as stocks and bonds, it has little basis in reality for limited-partnership units. Consider, for instance, a trade that took place this spring, of 25 units of Carlyle's Real Estate LP XIII at a small outfit called National Partnership Exchange in Tampa, Florida. The units, issued for $1,000 each, traded in May at $12, for a total of $300.<p>If a firm arranging such a trade followed the 5 percent guideline, it would be allowed to charge $15 for its services. Fifteen bucks doesn't go far when you have to locate a buyer for the units, hound the general partner to complete the necessary paperwork, and get the proper documentation -- such as powers of attorney, trust agreements, and other legal papers -- from the seller to the buyer. All these details typically add up to three months between the time a partnership is first traded and the moment the trade is consummated. What sane business would offer such services for $15?<p>Fewer and fewer all the time. Even as the NASD claims to be trying to help investors with its bulletin-board plan, it is censuring some of the few outfits that try to put together buyers and sellers of partnership units or harassing them with threats of frequent audits.<p>According to the NASD, these firms overcharge. "In most instances we found the 5 percent adequate to cover (their) costs," says Charles Bennett of the NASD. Result: Regulators' blind adherence to the 5 percent ideal has radically reduced investors' ability to exit partnerships. <p>Two years ago, for example, National Partnership Exchange made offerings in 285 different partnerships. Today they deal in 71. The drop is partly because a number of partnerships have been reorganized into publicly traded stocks. But, say industry sources, it is mostly a result of NASD threats. <p>Into this dwindling marketplace more and more partnership holders try to sell. Many have been in these deals for a decade. People's investment needs change; they should be allowed out, even if at an enormous loss. <p>Even though partnerships were sold as investments with 7- to 12-year holding periods, few are being unwound. That's partly because assets held in the partnerships are worth much less now than they were originally. General partners typically receive no payout from selling properties they hold until delivering to limited partners a return of their capital as well as a 6 percent or 8 percent annualized gain. Since such a prospect isn't possible, few general partners want to wind up their partnerships. <p>Fees earned while keeping the deals alive -- management expenses and reimbursements for operating costs -- can be mighty lucrative. Take the Shearson-Murray Real Estate Fund VI, a deal that raised $11.5 million from investors in 1981 to buy garden apartments. The fund went into Chapter 11 in 1986 and has operated under a reorganization plan since. <p>But even these dire straits haven't prevented the fund's general partner from extracting its fees. From 1991 through 1993, general partner and affiliates were reimbursed $600,000 for administrative expenses and property-management fees. And the limited partners? The fund's financials say the partnership will be wound up in '94: "It is unlikely that there will be sufficient cash remaining for a liquidating distribution to limited partners." <p>Investors in the Shearson fund can take solace in this: They'll no longer have a tax liability. Investors whose partnerships limp on soon find that not only are their units almost impossible to sell, they can't be given away. Charities won't accept them as gifts because of their costs and tax problems. Neither can you throw your units out; the IRS considers any disposition as relief of a debt -- a taxable event. <p>So investors are often stuck: up against general partners interested in maintaining a profitable status quo, brokerage firms with no interest in giving investors a clear idea of how bad these deals are, and regulators holding well-intentioned operators in an illiquid, complex market to unreasonably low fee standards. <p>Brian Propes, senior vice president at Securities Service Network, a small brokerage in Knoxville, Tennessee, has battled the NASD on the markup matter. His firm charges a minimum commission of $325 to do a partnership trade. This covers the costs of finding a buyer and generating the necessary paperwork and allows a modest profit. Propes's firm does 400 to 600 trades a year; mean trade size is about $6,000. <p>The NASD is threatening to crack down on the firm because on small transactions the $325 commission exceeds 5 percent. Says Propes, a former NASD regulator: "We're not out there to screw anybody. We're out there to get somebody out of something they don't want and get somebody into something they do want." <p>The 5 percent guideline, while admirable, is simply inappropriate for the partnership-units market. While the NASD insists that firms trading partnership units charge 5 percent, brokers who originally sold them made 8 to 10 percent. What's more, if a small investor buys a couple of shares of <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>from a discount broker, commissions will exceed 5 percent of the stock's value. The NASD doesn't seem to have a problem with that, as long as the investor knows what his costs will be.<p>Former regulator Propes says: "There's never a trade that a customer doesn't know what the costs are. Yet the NASD trying to force the 5 percent rule is really forcing (firms) to back off, leaving the customer in the cold."<p>If the NASD wants to help wounded partnership investors, it should do whatever possible to bring efficiency and liquidity to the market. This cannot be achieved until the regulators apply a different fee standard on limited-partnership units.
---------------
Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Stock Investing, Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
