<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Two Cheers for Karl Marx</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Two Cheers for Karl Marx</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Though Marx was wrong about the future of capitalism, his work is still the best explanation of today's economic crisis.<p>By Walter Mead<p>Not so long ago, everyone -- left and right -- thought Marxism was the wave of the future. Das Kapital, Marx's almost impenetrable three-volume analysis of capitalist economics, set off the biggest international religious movement since the Koran. From the jungles of Vietnam and the rice paddies of China to the sooty tenements of Paris and Berlin, youthful converts combed Marx's work for clues to their own, and the world's, problems. During the 1930s it was almost impossible to be an intellectual and not be a Marxist. The political right, while railing against the doctrine, paid homage to its power: As recently as 1987 the president of the United States was convinced that, if it wasn't stopped in Nicaragua, the irresistible Marxist tide would subjugate the United States. <p>How quaint that all looks now. The collapse of European communism and the failure of welfare-state economics in most of the West has ended any thought that Marx was an unfailing prophet. How tempting it is now to throw him into the dustbin of history along with the regimes that appropriated his name. Marx has been dead for more than 100 years; isn't it finally time to bury his theories too?<p>Maybe not. Though there may not be very many Marxists left, almost every serious approach to the problems of contemporary society is to some degree Marxian. Ironically, socialism's collapse makes it possible to see Marx more clearly for what he was -- the greatest student of capitalist economics and the first economic thinker to grasp the powerful nature of capitalism (a word we owe to him). Marx was the first to put economic thought in a historical context. Adam Smith's concept of free markets has nothing to do with history; the bazaars of medieval Baghdad were free markets, and so were, presumably, the Stone Age jamborees where river tribes exchanged fish for the game and furs of forest tribes. But those markets never harnessed the full power of their societies; only when free markets were united to the idea of capital did they turn into a force that would remake the world. <p>The secret of the West's ability to dominate the world economy wasn't markets, said Marx; it was capital. Capital isn't a synonym for wealth. The medieval duke in his inherited castle was wealthy, but he wasn't a capitalist. In capitalist societies, money and power flow to those who use money to make profits and who then employ those profits to make more capital. "Accumulate! Accumulate!" thundered Marx in Das Kapital. "That is Moses and the prophets!" <p>Marx was the first to understand and articulate the revolutionary potential of capitalism. Driven by competition and the necessity of earning profits, the bourgeoisie -- Marx's term for capitalists -- was the greatest force for change in history. Here is what capitalism would mean, he wrote in The Communist Manifesto: "Constant revolutionizing of production, uninterrupted disturbance of all social conditions, everlasting uncertainty and agitation distinguish the bourgeois epoch from all earlier ones. All fixed, fast-frozen relations, with their train of ancient and venerable prejudices and opinions, are swept away, all new-formed ones become antiquated before they can ossify. All that is solid melts into air, all that is holy is profaned."<p>Marx wrote these words in 1848. Revolution swept across Europe that year from France to Hungary. The industrial revolution had already upset long-established patterns of life. Machines that could spin and weave had reduced skilled handicraft workers to poverty. "Efficient" agriculture forced peasants off the land and into the crowded labor markets of Europe's emerging cities of factories and slums. The old nobility, challenged by an unpolished class of capitalist entrepreneurs, clung fiercely to power. Blood would run in the streets that year. Like Humpty Dumpty, Europe's traditional economic and social patterns seemed shattered beyond hope of reconstruction. <p>Almost 150 years after Marx described the nature of capitalist revolution, we are in the midst of a great upheaval of exactly the kind Marx experienced in his own day. Technological revolutions are creating new industries and destroying old ones; the American workplace is more insecure than ever, and both corporations and individuals are being told to prepare for a future that is ever more unpredictable. <p>The global nature of the current revolution would not have surprised Marx either. He predicted that capitalism would create a global society. "All old-established national industries have been destroyed or are daily being destroyed," he wrote. "In place of the old wants, satisfied by the productions of the country, we find new wants, requiring for their satisfaction the products of distant lands and climes." Capitalism would bring "even the most barbarian nations into civilization." <p>However, as prescient as some of Marx's extrapolations of the course of capitalism were, in other areas he was brilliantly wrong. Marx was rightly convinced that the proletariat, the capital-less workers, would have a greater influence on history than the bourgeoisie. Workers would use their collective power, he predicted, to form an effective international organization that would overthrow capitalism and replace it with socialism. <p>Here Marx underestimated the power of nationalism. "National differences, and antagonisms between peoples, are daily more and more vanishing," he wrote in 1848. Nationalism, he thought, was a bourgeois trick that would lose its force over time. "The workers have no Fatherland," he wrote. He could not have been more wrong. In 1914 European socialists enthusiastically followed their capitalists into the trenches of World War I. Today, we know that nationalism has outlived communism as a social force.<p>In fact, Marx's prediction needs to be stood on its head. Today, it is the capitalists who have no fatherland; multinational corporations make their investment and business decisions with less and less concern for the interests of their home country. It is the workers who want to subject international capitalism to national controls and who want American corporations to put the interests of their American employees ahead of their balance sheets. <p>But Marx's critics generally misidentify his greatest failure. They point to the dissolution of the Soviet system as a reason to dismiss the entire body of his work. He actually had little to say about how a socialist system would work, and the Communist planners combing his works for management tips came away empty-handed. They were forced to build their totalitarian states with materials from other sources.<p>And while Marx certainly didn't mind seeing a little bourgeois blood on the paving stones, there is nothing in his work to suggest he would have endorsed the waves of extended mass terror and sordid police repression that characterized the Communist world.<p>No, Marx's most profound mistake -- and the one that paradoxically makes him most interesting to us today -- results from his inability to grasp just how revolutionary and flexible capitalism can be. Capitalism, rather than plunging into crisis after the revolts of 1848, reorganized itself. The creation of the welfare state in Western Europe and North America began when Prussian chancellor Otto von Bismarck sought to outflank the German socialists by introducing insurance programs that sheltered German workers from the worst insecurities of capitalism. Gradually that movement spread throughout the Western world. Unemployment insurance, social security, disability insurance, and -- everywhere in the First World except in the United States -- guaranteed health care proved that capitalism didn't inevitably reduce workers to misery.<p>Marx thought that capitalism couldn't afford programs like this and that the workers would rise up against the system precisely because of the intolerable insecurity and suffering its booms and busts would cause. Capitalist competition would drive wages lower and lower. The poverty of workers would make the economy vulnerable to periodic crises when purchasing power failed to keep up with the supply of goods on the market. How could revolution not follow?<p>Capitalists and workers proved him wrong in the 20th century. It turned out that social programs and policies such as the minimum wage didn't wreck capitalism: They made it healthier. What workers could buy, capitalists could sell. When governments spent more money on unemployment benefits and job-creation programs during depressions, the depressions ended earlier and the capitalists returned more quickly to profitability. The politics of class conflict across the industrial world turned into the politics of class compromise. <p>Marx's vision of a proletarian socialist revolution may be dead, but the proletariat isn't. We live in a proletarian society, and the politics of the proletariat seem destined to play an ever greater role in American life, as he predicted. <p>Americans hate words that tell the truth about social conditions. America's family farmers would be called "peasants" anywhere else in the world -- at best "free peasants," since they have the option of leaving their debt-encumbered farms. But very few political candidates open their stump speeches in Iowa with the words "My fellow peasants." Nobody in America wants to be called proletarian, but in fact Marx's proletariat is alive if not well in the United States today: We call it the middle class. <p>Over the decades, proletarian has acquired connotations of blue-collar work: When we think proletarian, we think hard hats and time clocks. Blue-collar workers are proletarians, but they aren't the only ones. The word itself comes down from Roman times, when the poorest class of Roman citizens were people whose only property was their offspring. Marx uses the word to talk about people who live by selling their work: people who don't own enough property to live off their capital. Anybody on wage or salary who depends on that income for a living qualifies as a proletarian. When you include retirees whose pensions and Social Security are in effect deferred compensation for work they did when younger, virtually the entire middle class of the United States -- over half of the total population -- belongs to the proletariat. Other than the utterly dispossessed and unemployable people who have fallen through the cracks of the economy, owners of small businesses, people on trust funds, the top echelons of management in the corporate world, tenured university professors, and celebrities, virtually everybody in the United States is a proletarian. And most of those who aren't -- including small businessmen like fast-food franchisees and freelance writers -- are so immersed in proletarian values and culture that while we are technically members of Marx's least-favorite class -- the petit bourgeoisie -- we have largely been swallowed by the proletariat. <p>Clearly, Marx was wrong about the political evolution of this class; very few of us American proletarians walk around whistling the Internationale or plotting the overthrow of capitalism. But he was clearly colossally right to say that this class would become the dominant social force in the advanced industrial nations. Watch Congress writhe as it tries to cut middle-class entitlements. The middle class is the 900-pound gorilla of American politics; once it makes up its mind about something, no bourgeois lackey or capitalist tool can hope to stand against it for long. <p>The most important fact about American politics today is that the middle class isn't happy. The old compromise -- security and rising living standards for the workers, steady profits for the capitalists -- isn't delivering. "The constant revolutionizing of production, uninterrupted disturbance of all social conditions, everlasting uncertainty and agitation" are back. In the short run, they produce phenomena like Ross Perot's candidacy in the last election. In the long run? <p>Marx thought he knew where capitalism was headed, and that was his big mistake. Today we need to understand that capitalism's future is a question mark. Internationally, as capitalism spreads through the developing world, we can no longer be smugly sure that capitalism equals stability. If the capitalist system can no longer provide the wages and social benefits that people in rich countries expect, what will happen in the poorer ones? Korean, Chinese, and Malaysian workers hope some day to have living standards like those of their fellow proletarians in North America and Western Europe. So do the workers in Mexico, Poland, and Russia. Can capitalism deliver for the global proletariat the way it did earlier in this century for the proletariat in the advanced Western countries? <p>Communism has failed; will capitalism succeed? The answer may not be the one Marx predicted, but he did point to the test that modern capitalism must pass: To survive, capitalism must once again reorganize itself and find a way to satisfy the aspirations of the middle class. Let's hope it does. 
---------------
Walter Mead is the senior policy advisor at the World Policy Institute at the New School.<p>Research assistance: Jamie McClelland.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
