<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-A Certain Cure For Good Times</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-A Certain Cure For Good Times</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
For the sake of argument, let's say we do need to balance the budget. Would you raise taxes 3% or eliminate the army?<p>By Walter Mead<p>This is as good as it gets, economists were saying happily this spring. (Even if investors weren't. Hey, I didn't say things were perfect.) Three years into a healthy economic expansion, interest rates are still relatively modest. Unemployment is falling. Inflation remains low, even if threatening clouds can be spotted on the horizon. American products are recapturing lost ground in foreign markets. Look! They are even making money in Detroit.<p>Washington's response to all this good news? Panic. Blind, hysterical panic that recently came within an ace of wrecking the U.S. Constitution, destroying the government's ability to invest for the future, and ruining the economy for years, perhaps decades, to come. Washington, in other words, nearly passed the balanced-budget amendment to the Constitution. This, the worst proposed amendment since prohibition, came within 12 votes of passing in the House, 4 in the Senate. Backers promise to bring it to another vote next year.<p>If you think I'm exaggerating, just read this piece of legislation. The balanced-budget amendment is 307 words of bad news, but the worst damage comes up front, in the first two of its eight sections. "Total outlays for any fiscal year shall not exceed total receipts for that fiscal year," unless a three-fifths majority in both houses of Congress approves, says Section 1. The ceiling on the national debt shall not be raised without a similar vote, says Section 2. Section 3 requires that no tax increases become law without a roll-call vote in both houses, by no means a bad idea, I admit. The remaining sections provide for exceptions (war or the threat of war), authorize enabling legislation, define terms like receipts and outlays, and announce that the amendment will go into effect beginning with fiscal year 1999 if it is ratified in time. <p>Those innocuous words disguise the worst kind of constitutional tinkering. The requirement that the budget be balanced in any given year sounds simple, for example, but in effect creates a litigator's dream. You don't like something the federal government has done? Challenge the budget accounting and claim that the government is really in the red and, therefore, that the department that annoyed you is operating with unconstitutionally appropriated funds.<p>Would the U.S. Constitution allow a federal court to declare the budget unconstitutional if it violated this amendment? If not, the amendment is toothless. Congress can happily vote any budget it wishes, announce that the budget is balanced, and go merrily home. But if the federal courts do have the right to review the budget, then sooner or later some zealous federal-district-court judge will declare the budget unconstitutional, and we will have created the biggest legal mess in our history. <p>Let's not forget: All this is for nothing. In my November 1993 column I demonstrated that neither the budget deficit nor the national debt loom large in relation to the nation's assets. Worries about the debt we are passing down to our children are painfully misplaced. We aren't, after all, just passing down debts, I tried to point out. Some of you weren't convinced, so I'll use another set of numbers. Using constant 1987 dollars, the total private net worth of the United States in 1946 was $4.5 trillion. The total federal debt, swollen from the cost of World War II, was $1.3 trillion. By 1992 the federal debt had reached $2.4 trillion, but the private assets of Americans had increased much more rapidly - to $17.7 trillion. Sure, our kids will inherit the federal deficit. But they will inherit our private assets also, so who cares? <p>Okay, I know from my mail that some of you would rather die than be convinced that the deficit doesn't matter (better dead than in the red). So let's assume that the hard-nosed deficit hawks get their way. Suppose Congress passes this misguided amendment and we have to balance the budget. What would you cut? <p>Take the budget for the 1999 fiscal year. The government projects total receipts of $1.629 trillion and total outlays of $1.830 trillion (in 1999 dollars). This leaves a deficit of $201 billion - or about 11 percent. Making up for an 11 percent shortfall sounds easy, right? Just cut out the fat. <p>Wrong. The federal budget is divided into two basic categories: discretionary and mandatory spending. Let's start by cutting discretionary items. Despite its name, discretionary spending isn't made up of frills and doodads. The $554.4 billion in discretionary spending for 1999 includes $253.8 billion in defense outlays, for example. That's $9 billion less than we spent in 1993 - and a 1999 dollar, because of inflation, isn't going to stretch nearly as far.<p>If defense can't be touched, that means looking for the fat in the remaining $301 billion in other discretionary spending. Cutting $201 billion from this part of the budget alone would require eliminating the combined non-entitlement budgets of the departments of Agriculture, Commerce, Energy, Health and Human Services, Housing and Urban Development, Interior, Labor, Treasury, State, and Veterans Affairs. Throw in a few other agencies such as NASA, the judiciary branch of the federal government, and both houses of Congress to achieve the total.<p>But what about mandatory spending? the deficit hawks ask. All those wasteful entitlement programs are just begging for the ax.<p>Well, not really. Mandatory spending - which is where most of the money is - includes entitlement programs such as Medicare and Social Security. In 1999, the government projects that total mandatory spending will amount to $1.02 trillion. About 40 percent of that, $410.8 billion, is Social Security. Another $78.9 billion goes to pensions for retired federal employees. Most of the remaining $489.7 billion goes to Medicare and Medicaid: a combined total of $386.9 billion. <p>Health care reform is designed to tackle the runaway growth of these programs. But even if one of the current legislative packages manages to cut the rate of increase, it's hard to see how to cut the total unless we plan to deny medical care to the poor and the old. In the long run the only way to get the costs under control is probably the kind of single-payer plan that most deficit hawks hate as much as they hate deficits. No savings from any plan will roll in before 1999, anyway.<p>So what about those other entitlements? Unemployment benefits account for $25.1 billion of projected 1999 outlays. Any takers for wiping them out - or cutting them in half? <p>There is a juicy item in the mandatory budget of $124 billion for "means-tested benefits." This money includes such wasteful boondoggles as veterans' pensions, food stamps, child nutrition programs, and supplementary income payments to the disabled. No doubt better administration could shave a few billion here and there off all these entitlement programs, but there just isn't $201 billion of fat. <p>This leaves tax increases. Balancing the budget through higher income taxes alone would require a 30 percent tax increase by 2001. Based on current tax rates, this would mean an increase of $2,763 for a married couple filing jointly with a taxable income of $50,000 a year. Couples with $100,000 in taxable income would face an increase of $7,954. <p>Of course, spreading the pain around would help. Making up some of the money from tax increases, some from entitlement cuts, and some from reductions in discretionary spending could ensure that the United States still has a Congress - and possibly even a State Department - in the year 2000. But there is no doubt that the pain will be real.<p>By the way, the amendment would require another $50 billion in cuts by 2001. Good-bye, Department of Education. Good-bye, marines. <p>Most deficit hawks would be willing to live without the Department of Education, and a few might be willing to sacrifice the marines, but they certainly aren't talking about the negative effects that cutting $200 billion in government spending would have on the economy. When the government closes down a military base, even a useless pork-barrel military base, jobs are lost and businesses go bust as ripples spread through the local and regional economy. These consequences can be dramatic; every $1 billion cut in highway spending leads to a loss of 20,000 jobs. The Congressional Budget Office estimates that eliminating the deficit over a five-to-ten-year period would slow growth by 0.5 percent per year, eliminating a half-million jobs in each year of deficit elimination. <p>But deficit hawks deny this. Government deficits divert investment from the private economy, they say. According to their scenario, balancing the budget will reduce interest rates, and the lower rates will lead to more investment in the private economy. This will stimulate the economy, increase productivity, and, in the long run, raise living standards and increase government revenues without raising taxes. Who knows, after 20 years we might get the Commerce Department back. <p>Nice theory, but how about some evidence? As economist Dean Baker of the Economic Policy Institute wrote in 1993, the data does not show a meaningful relationship between deficits, interest rates, and investment. A Washington University study appears to show that reducing interest rates by 200 basis points (half of the implied real interest rate of about 400 basis points on long-term government bonds) would increase investment by only $25 billion - a change of only 5 percent - in a $6 trillion economy.<p>Does all this mean we should just sit there and let budget deficits go on forever? Certainly not, but fixing the federal deficit is a little bit like Zen archery. "Don't think about the target," Zen masters tell novices. "Think about the arrow." To control the federal budget, we don't need to worry about artificial deficit targets, but we do need to think about the arrow - the spending that makes up the federal budget. If we spend our money wisely on programs that add to the national wealth and if we administer federal programs intelligently, then federal spending will benefit the country. The economy will grow, and revenues will rise. <p>The United States today doesn't have a deficit problem. It has a good-government problem. Panaceas like this amendment are based on despair about democracy. Its proponents point out that we vote for representatives who do things we don't like yet refuse to punish them at the polls. But if Americans can't elect representatives who will serve their interests, then tinkering with the Constitution won't save them.
---------------
Walter Mead is the senior policy advisor at the World Policy Institute at the New School.<p>Research assistance: Jamie McClelland.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Economy

