<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Introducing Biotech's Boy Wonder</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Introducing Biotech's Boy Wonder</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The way David Blech does deals, he wins whether the company soars or craters.  Other investors aren't as lucky.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>Biotech investor David Blech is young, rich, and dissatisfied. It's not enough that he has an uncanny ability to take young biotech companies, fund them, and flip them to the investing public, bagging enormous profits for himself. Or that he has amassed, at 38, a fortune exceeding $200 million. Blech wants more. <p>Along with his bushels of bucks, Blech wants a higher profile--the kind that comes with building a big-league brokerage firm.<p>This is what people who know Blech surmise from the fact that he's taking his show--New York-based D. Blech & Co. --on the road. He's said to be doubling the size of his investment firm, to about 400 associates. He is opening brokerage offices in Atlanta, Boston, San Francisco and Boca Raton, Florida. Once a small venture-banking firm, D. Blech & Co. is fast becoming a full-service brokerage operation. <p>This expansion is worth noting: It increases the likelihood that, one day soon, you may be called by a Blech (pronounced "blek") broker pushing a high-risk deal your way. My advice: Hang up the phone. Although Blech has won big on his biotech investments, many of the investors who've bought into his deals have not. In fact, most of what Blech peddles is, well, dreck. <p>His companies sound exciting, with names like NeoRx Corp. and Ecogen Inc., and they're in the glamorous world of biotech. But, as is typical with biotech companies in the early stages, they're better at selling promises than products. Most have yet to earn a dime. Although their shares may have popped up in price after going public, they're now trading nearer the cellar than the sky.<p>Blech's methods of raising money may also have attracted the attention of the Securities and Exchange Commission. According to a Wall Street Journal story last fall, the SEC is looking into a controversial D. Blech practice of giving ultracheap "founders' stock" to brokers and financial consultants in exchange for their help in promoting a company's shares. The SEC would neither confirm nor deny the existence of a probe, as is its custom. D. Blech's public relations firm says the SEC inquiry was "informal."<p>But ultracheap stock is exactly what brought David Blech and his brother and former associate, Isaac, enormous riches since they began investing in biotech a dozen years ago. The brothers made their start in the early '80s with a $20,000 biotech bet in a company called Genetic Systems, which they later took public. David Blech was impressed by the huge profits investors reaped when Genentech went public and soared from $35 to $89 within its first hour of trading. So the two brothers decided to start their own biotech firm, even though neither knew much about science. In 1991, the brothers went their separate ways.<p>Getting in on the ground floor of a company usually entitles an investor to high returns if its products succeed. But the way Blech sets up his deals--investing in them, then underwriting their shares--he wins whether the company soars or craters. Blech's methods seem to be less venture capital, more shooting fish in a test tube.<p>For a man who's building an empire, David Blech is one shy dude. He refused to talk to Worth. But interviews with former associates of Blech's and with people who've dealt with him help bring him into focus. No one who has met Blech disputes that he's intelligent. But charming, no. One man who dealt with him paints him as "a whiny guy in a bad suit; he acts like a little kid." A former associate calls him "the ultimate opportunist." <p>If so, Blech must have smarted when he was dumped from Forbes magazine's list of the 400 richest Americans in 1993. The year earlier, he had made the list for the first time, with an estimated net worth of $295 million. <p>Blech's modus operandi goes something like this: Biotech companies, sometimes in search of capital, sometimes sniffed out by him, agree to his draconian investment terms in order to secure financing. He loans the company money in exchange for a controlling interest in the stock. He may also raise funds from other sophisticated investors in a private placement, for which he reaps large banking fees. Not long after this--two years, typically--Blech takes the company in which he invested public, earning big fees for underwriting the shares and bagging huge paper profits on his insider's stock. Shares Blech paid pennies for usually go to investors for $6 to $15 apiece in the offering. <p>An investor who met with Blech on a potential financing says, "His group is very aggressive. He was trying to buy us on the cheap, package us, and sell us out." This deal was never done.<p>Although all venture capitalists dream of taking their companies public at enormous profit, doing this within two years of the initial financing is in the best interests of neither the company, its science, nor its shareholders. So says Charles Hartman of C W Group, a prestigious medical venture-capital firm in New York; three to five years is more like it. "If you take a company public too early, management has to take its eye off the ball and watch things other than the science," he says.<p>But why fret about the success or failure of a company's science if you can wring millions in fees and paper profits flogging it to the public? <p>Consider D. Blech's most recent offering: Texas Biotechnology Corp., a Houston-based start-up developing products for cardiovascular diseases. Blech took the company public last December at $6.75, one of a half-dozen to be underwritten by the firm since it became a broker/dealer three years ago. The offering raised roughly $24 million. Three months later, the units remain at $6.75.<p>Texas Biotech has been in existence since 1989, but it had no product to sell until May 1993, when it was granted a sublicense to sell an anticoagulant called argatroban. Since 1989, the company has lost $14 million; revenues in the first three quarters of 1993 declined 32 percent from the year earlier while expenses more than doubled. The company's losses rose 122 percent last year. <p>The company has no marketing, manufacturing, or product-sales experience, and its prospectus says it "does not expect to market any products for several years, if ever." What Texas Biotech has: sublicense to sell argatroban, manufactured by Japan's Mitsubishi Kasei.<p>That's a mighty thin reed upon which to hang a $24 million offering. Yet investors bought into Texas Biotech, even though argatroban is in phase II clinical trials and behind the competition: Biogen and Ciba-Geigy have similar anticoagulants in phase III trials.<p>As investors were snapping up Texas Biotech shares, David Blech was counting up his profits. Between the fees earned on the private placement Blech did for the company in 1991 and on the 1993 IPO, consulting fees, and expenses, D. Blech & Co. made almost $5 million on its relationship with Texas Biotech. There may be more: Any financings, mergers, or acquisitions that Blech arranges for Texas Biotech down the road will earn the firm 2.5 percent of the deal in so-called success fees.<p>That's just what the firm made. The money Blech made personally is another matter. According to the prospectus, in April 1990, David and Isaac Blech bought 1 million shares of Texas Biotech for 3.5 cents each. In addition, the brothers reaped more than 100 percent in paper profits on a $1.85 million loan made to the company in 1990 that was turned into company shares. David also received warrants to purchase another 630,000 shares in Texas Biotech at $3.50 a share, a discount to current market value. At the time of the offering, Blech owned 602,000 shares outright and was the beneficiary of another 686,000 in trusts. All bought at discounted prices. <p>It's not hard to see how Blech has managed to pile up so much dough at such a young age. <p>Now that Blech is opening branches in cities nationwide, it's almost certain that more deals are coming. One Blech watcher says of his expansion, "He needs distribution for his junk."<p>Not just any distribution, mind you. Aggressive, hard-driving salesmen are preferred. So says a broker in Atlanta who has watched Blech hire one big-producing stockbroker after another at the firm's three-month-old office there. According to him, Blech is bestowing huge upfront money upon brokers who join the firm--such as a check for 60 percent of what the broker earned in commissions last year. This practice is much frowned upon by the securities industry, but when it was common, upfront payments never exceeded 20 to 30 percent of a broker's prior year's commissi.ons. Blech brokers also make sky-high net payouts of 50 percent of gross commissions. The industry average is between 30 and 40 percent.<p>What's wrong with Blech being generous to his salesmen? Brokers who are given rich incentives to trade are tempted to trade customers' accounts more frequently than they would otherwise. The risk of churning rises.<p>So if a Blech boy calls you extolling the riches in biotech, tell him you think Blech's got money enough. He doesn't need any of yours. 
---------------
Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies, Biotechnology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
