<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Adam Smith's Market Morality</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Adam Smith's Market Morality</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The political and religious rights want to claim Adam Smith as one of their own; they'd be appalled if they actually read his work<p>By Walter Mead<p>Everybody wanted to climb on the Adam Smith bandwagon in the 1980s. Supply-side crusaders draped themselves in the economist's mantle. Their theory was a "contemporary recasting of the original liberal doctrine expressed by Adam Smith," according to the New York Times. William F. Buckley's National Review counted Smith's posthumous vote for the entire thrust of the Reagan administration's first term, which "quite explicitly repackaged versions of Adam Smith." Too bad Smith wasn't alive to collect royalties from items such as the Adam Smith neckties affected by many presidential advisors.<p>But the effort to expropriate Smith, quite possibly the only economist other than Marx that most Americans can name, wasn't limited to the economic realm. Conservative religious leaders recruited Smith to march with them in favor of a return to what they characterized as traditional American family values. "I believe in free-enterprise capitalism. I believe in the wisdom of the market," Pat Robertson wrote in 1991. Eleven years earlier Jerry Falwell had said something similar: "No nation has survived long when its citizens were denied the free market and individual initiative."<p>By 1992 that party seemed to be over, and no one wanted to invite Smith into the new decade. As the reaction against the excesses of the 1980s gathered force, it looked as if Adam Smith would find himself banished to the back rooms and bad tables along with Michael Milken, Gordon Gekko, and the directors of failed savings and loans.<p>Too bad. The real Adam Smith was a much deeper and subtler thinker than most of his contemporary acolytes. His theories would have indeed shocked many of them--if they had ever bothered to read The Wealth of Nations. The "bubble economies" and the highflying mergers of the '80s would have seemed replays of the repellent speculative excesses of his own time. He would have regarded that decade's economic theories of rational expectations and perfect markets as deliberate misreadings of market history and human nature. And the attempt to legislate or otherwise impose absolute moral standards would have seemed to him, at best, doomed foolishness. Morality, after all, could never be the same for all social classes, he had written. The market simply wouldn't allow it.<p>Investors can still learn much from this Scottish economist who died in 1790. For example, Smith argued that capital markets weren't perfect. Investors were motivated too much by emotion and not enough by rational consideration. They were, in short, consistently too bullish. "The chance of gain is naturally overvalued," he told us, and proved his point with the examples of lotteries and military careers. Lotteries are by definition bad investments: Because of the profits collected by lottery operators and taxes imposed by the state, the lottery pool to be won is always less than the total invested in tickets. But people still buy lottery tickets because the hope of winning a huge jackpot outweighs more rational considerations.<p>A 1980s defender of perfect markets and rational expectations might try to explain away the purchase of lottery tickets by arguing that buyers don't have enough information about how bad the real return on their investment is. But Smith will have none of that. The behavior of the lottery players is the result of human nature, said Smith, not lack of information. Consider another kind of lottery, he urged. Military service is difficult, dangerous, and (especially in Smith's time) poorly paid, but recruiting offices are able to fill out the ranks. Why? Young men dream that they will win the military "lottery," though the chances of fame and glory do not in reality justify the risks of death and dismemberment.<p>This psychological point has important ramifications for Smith--and contemporary investors. Because investors tend to be too bullish, it means that risky or speculative ventures tend to be overvalued compared with conservative ones. Rewards, he tells us, do not rise commensurate with increasing risks.<p>But Adam Smith was more than an economist. His greatest book, "The Wealth of Nations," belongs to a long-lost genre called, in Smith's day, political economy. Smith was one of the most profound social critics in western history. Coming from a country and a time when armed religious upheaval was a constant danger, he was particularly sensitive to the relationship between economics and religion. "The Wealth of Nations," in fact, directly addresses one of the most divisive questions of Smith's time--and ours. Do an individual and a country have to be good to become wealthy? Or are morality and economics entirely unrelated subjects?<p>Smith was one of the first thinkers to question the assumed connection between western religion and western economics. Religious tradition, in Smith's time and ours, tells us why nations rise and fall: Those nations and peoples who observe God's laws prosper; those who sin suffer the consequences.<p>In practice the story was a little more complicated than that. God sometimes tests those he loves. Ask Job. But history--including economic history--was best understood as the direct result of the acts of a personal and vigilant God. This was the view of the Pilgrims. They believed that God had called them to create a new and holy society in America, a city on the hill, and that he would bless America when it obeyed his laws and punish it when it was deserved. As Jerry Falwell once said, "Material wealth is God's way of blessing people who put him first."<p>That's not what Adam Smith thought. Human societies do not work because people are good, but because they are selfish. "It is not from the benevolence of the butcher, the brewer, or the baker," he wrote, "that we expect our dinner, but from their regard to their own interest." Prosperity is not the result of self-restraint or morality. "It is the necessary, though very slow and gradual, consequence of a certain propensity in human nature, the propensity to truck, barter, and exchange one thing for another," according to Smith.<p>If religious fundamentalists such as Falwell really understood Adam Smith, they would hate his economic theories even more violently than they hate Darwin's theory of evolution. Darwin merely evicts God from the primeval slime, substituting the impersonal mechanics of survival of the fittest for God's direct creation. Smith's ideas are much more subversive: They take God out of history and make the rise and fall of nations depend on impersonal and amoral activities like trade.<p>Reading Adam Smith makes us face something that most Americans prefer not to think about: the contradictions between two sets of ideas that inform American society. We want the Judeo-Christian theological tradition as interpreted by the Pilgrims and their heirs and the economic ideas of Adam Smith to be complementary. In fact, they are often diametrically opposed.<p>People operating out of our religious heritage tell us that our society must be good before it can be rich. Liberal religious leaders tell us that this means we must feed the poor and provide universal medical care if our society is to enjoy God's blessing.  Conservative preachers agree, but they emphasize the need to devote our moral attention to transgressions of private morality.  Despite their differences, "theological economists" of all stripes believe that America must purify itself in a moral sense in order to enjoy continued prosperity.<p>Secular economists disagree on which technical remedies are needed, but they all agree that the measures we need are better policies, not better morals. Going to church won't make the economy grow; budget reform will.<p>Adam Smith came down firmly on the secular side of this controversy. His suspicion of the well-intentioned interventions of muddle-headed economic reformers is well-known; he thought that markets can distribute goods more fairly and effectively than do-gooders. But Smith has little respect for conservative meddlers either. Defend traditional moral values? Fight secular humanism? No need to bother, Smith believed.<p>Morality, Smith provokingly wrote, is a creation of the market. Every society has two schools of morality: "One may be called the strict or austere; the other the liberal or, if you will, the loose system." The strict school "is generally admired and revered by the common people." On the other hand, the cultural elite--in Smith's words, "people of fashion"--follow the loose system. Murphy Brown, meet Dan Quayle.<p>But Adam Smith parted company with the Puritans of his time and ours. He didn't think that the difference between the two moralities was a question of right and wrong; rather the two schools were suited to the needs of different people. For the poor, the strict school was an economic necessity. "A single week's thoughtlessness and dissipation is often sufficient to undo a poor workman for ever," Smith reminded his reader, and "the wiser and better sort of the common people, therefore, have always the utmost abhorrence and detestation of such excesses, which their experience tells them are so immediately fatal to people of their condition."<p>Among the affluent, a different set of conditions leads to a different set of morals. The cost of transgression is not so high, and so sin is winked at. There is more emphasis on individual expression, less on abstract moral codes. The members of the cultural elite "are very apt to consider the power of indulging in some degree of excess as one of the advantages of their fortune, and the liberty of doing so without censure or reproach, as one of the privileges which belong to their station."<p>Adam Smith never imagined the kind of mass affluence that we have seen in the United States since World War II, but it seems likely that he would have regarded the general loosening of moral standards since 1945 as the natural and altogether predictable consequence of the improvement in the national standard of living. And it also seems likely that Smith would have seen signs that the pendulum is swinging back in some respects to a stricter moral standard as a consequence of the more recent decline in living standards.<p>Smith wouldn't have been very worked up over either of these rebalancings of the moral scales. Nor would he have seen them as cause for a wave of religious revivalism. Smith, in general, was more worried about too much religion than too little. He thought that the population at large was too liable to manipulation by unscrupulous and ambitious religious leaders. One of the few areas of government intervention he supported was public subsidies for the production of plays and public entertainment that mocked the tactics and absurdities of popular preachers.<p>But Smith didn't worry too much about religious fanaticism in a pluralistic society--a religious free market, so to speak--like the United States. He pointed to the experience of Philadelphia--at the time, the only place in the British Empire that allowed full freedom of religion to all Christian denominations--and prophesied that the competition among religious would lead to something that would look more like liberal Unitarianism--which wags define as the belief that there is, at most, one God--than any of the fire and brimstone religions of Smith's time.<p>What does all this have to do with our own day? The contemporary antiabortion movement is a conspicuous example of Smith's theories at work. Conservative Protestant fundamentalists and Catholics have a long tradition of mutual dislike and suspicion, but the common political struggle against abortion has brought millions of American fundamentalists and Catholics together. Working in alliance for a common, secular purpose, they have come to respect the sincerity of one another's convictions. Although the antiabortion movement challenges an aspect of the American secular consensus, it also strengthens a basic tenet of American secular society: that the political goals we share in common are more important than the religious beliefs that divide us.<p>Perhaps the most telling sign of the "creeping secularization" of the religious right is its embrace of Adam Smith's economics. When Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson adopt the basic tenets of secular humanism--that impersonal forces rather than continual divine intervention determine the wealth of nations--then American fundamentalism has lost its ability to challenge one part of the secular market culture. The end of the 1980s didn't make Smith obsolete; 218 years after he wrote it, "The Wealth of Nations" can still compete.
---------------
Walter Mead is the senior policy advisor at the World Policy Institute at the New School.<p>Research assistance: Jamie McClelland<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Politics, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

