<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Foreign Stock</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Foreign Stock</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
How's this for unfair? Foreign investors can buy shares in U.S. companies at steep discounts to what American pay.<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>American investors pride themselves on having the fairest financial markets around. And for the most part, this is true. U.S. accounting rules and relatively stringent financial-disclosure regulations set up and monitored by the Securities and Exchange Commission make ours among the most level of investment playing fields in the world. <p>But there are exceptions to this general rule of fair play. One of the most troubling: A little-known but increasingly popular practice by U.S. companies selling shares to overseas investors at significantly lower prices than what American investors pay. That's right--foreigners get to buy U.S. shares at 30 percent to 40 percent below what domestic investors are currently paying. Worst of all, few American investors know this is occurring. <p>How could such a practice be permitted to exist? SEC rules governing companies' sales of shares to foreigners--known as Regulation S--are much less rigorous than the laws that apply stateside. When a company sells shares to foreigners, the SEC largely stays out of it.<p>But this doesn't mean that U.S. investors should be blissfully ignorant of overseas stock transactions. Although they're not supposed to affect investors here, they do. And their effects are not always positive. <p>Offshore transactions--the direct selling of shares to overseas buyers--are popular among U.S. companies for several reasons. The deals enable firms to raise money for their operations more quickly and cheaply than they could if they were floating an issue at home. When a company issues so-called Reg. S debt or equity, it deals directly with the buyer; this obviates the need to register the shares and reduces selling costs--such as stockbrokers' fees--associated with public offerings. <p>Such deals are definitely rising in popularity among foreign investors as well. Exact numbers of Reg. S deals and dollars raised through them are unknown because there is no centralized record-keeping on the offerings at the SEC as there is, for example, on transactions made by corporate insiders. But it's safe to say that hundreds of millions of dollars have been raised through these offerings recently. Buyers of discounted shares include private banks in Germany, Switzerland, France, Bermuda, and the Cayman Islands. One investor watching the flood of Reg. S deals says, "It's what all the overseas money managers are talking about." <p>The key motivation behind offshore buyers' interest in Reg. S offerings is--surprise--astronomical profits. Investors in the deals brag of doubling their money quarterly. <p>How do they do it? By shooting fish in a barrel--buying shares in companies at deep discounts to their publicly traded prices back in the U.S. Even a baboon could double its money if it could buy shares in an American company at $7.50 while the same firm's shares were trading at $11.50 at home. All it would have to do is sell its stock in the U.S. at the higher price. <p>There is one small hitch, however. A Reg. S buyer is not supposed to sell his holding right away. According to the rule, foreign buyers of both debt and equities are supposed to hold their securities for at least 40 days or, in some cases, a year before they can bail out. The risk to the buyer, therefore, is that his holding will fall--in U.S. trading--below his discounted cost before he is able to get out. <p>This is not an insubstantial risk. But according to money managers familiar with overseas transactions, it is easily gotten around. These folks say that Reg. S lockup rules are often ignored by foreign investors. Instead, the discounted shares migrate back home and are sold to unsuspecting U.S. investors in the open market as if they were normal shares. Foreigners bag the profits. <p>Few investors are aware of the Reg. S game and the extent to which it is being played today. Those who are aware of it find themselves at an extreme disadvantage to offshore players. As one outraged fund manager puts it, "The practice has become so abusive. U.S. investors have no clue that they're being sold shares at big premiums" to other investors. <p>Indeed, why should foreigners get special deals on the same stocks or bonds that Americans pay more for? The notion of granting discounts to some investors and not others is in direct conflict with the fine American concept of the level investment field. Yes, overseas investors who comply with the regulations cannot sell their holdings until the agreed-upon time period is over. But Americans who buy equity private placements typically must wait two years before they can sell, twice the maximum that applies to foreigners under Reg. S. <p>Another concern is how clearly or unclearly the deals are disclosed to existing shareholders. At best, these offerings are difficult to track; investors must slog through annual and quarterly financial statements to find out whether a company they own shares in is raising money through discounted deals. Some companies are quite specific about the discounts granted to overseas buyers of the stock; others provide no details of the prices paid. <p>But even the most diligent document hound will learn about discounted offerings only after the fact. By the time the details of a Reg. S deal show up in your company's 10K, it's history.<p>Very often, Reg. S deals are evidence of a company's weakening financial state. Healthy companies rarely mark down their stock's price in order to attract investors. Yet, because the reporting of Regulation S deals often comes well after they've taken place, concerned shareholders may learn about them only after their shares have started to fall. One reason the stocks may drop? Each time a company floats new shares--whether domestic or foreign--it diminishes the earnings power of the stock held by existing investors. <p>All this spells trouble for shareholders whose companies are raising money in these types of overseas transactions. Consider, for example, <a name="AMEX:IDC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16851"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Interdigital Communications</b></a>, a maker of digital wireless-communications equipment. Though Interdigital has lost more than $135 million in the past five years, the company was able to raise more than $12 million overseas during 1992 and early 1993. Foreigners paid roughly 40 percent less than U.S. investors did for their Interdigital shares. <p>In the third quarter of last year, Interdigital raised another $4.5 million in Reg. S money. Company financials stated that buyers paid around $4.50 per share; U.S. investors, at the time, were paying roughly $9 for their shares. <p>This may have helped Interdigital's balance sheet, but it did little for company shareholders. Since 1992, the stock has sunk from around $11 to a recent $5. American investors have seen their holdings diminish, but overseas buyers, if they're still holding on, are ahead. Not by much, but ahead nonetheless.<p>Another user of private-placement funding is Belmac Corp., a pharmaceuticals concern based in Tampa, Florida. Although the company has lost some $40 million since 1988, it raised almost $25 million in foreign money in 1991 and early 1992. In late '92, Belmac raised another $4 million privately, with foreign investors paying an average $4.80 per share. U.S. investors buying stock at the same time weren't so lucky; they paid between $5.13 and $13.50 per. Belmac's shares outstanding grew by almost half--from 13 million to 19.3 million. Its stock has since plunged to around $2. <p>The effects of Regulation S deals might not be as deleterious to American investors if the discounted shares remained on foreign soil as they should. That many of these shares come back to the U.S. before they are supposed to is not surprising. This is a huge and unregulated arena. The SEC is overworked supervising domestic markets. It can hardly be expected to monitor the activities of foreign investors as well. Still, the commission is aware of the potential for abuse in Reg. S and says it is watchful for companies breaking the rule. <p>Setting up a central system to track Reg. S deals would help investors, if only to shed light on the practice. In the meantime, investors must do their homework. Read all your companies' quarterly and annual financial statements. Pay attention to discussions of financing activities. If the company is selling discounted shares overseas, think about selling yours here at home. <p>The ease with which overseas investors can circumvent SEC rules should serve as a reminder that global markets can be treacherous. Don't assume that because U.S. markets are scrutinized by regulators, other markets are as well. The world of international investing is a wild and woolly place. And until one uniform regulatory outfit is set up to oversee worldwide trading, wild and woolly it will remain.<p>Gretchen Morgenson is the executive editor of Worth.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

