<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-It's Not the Deficit, Stupid</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-It's Not the Deficit, Stupid</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
If the government were run like a business, taxpayers would worry about profits, not spending<p>By Walter Mead<p>Deficit hawks have short memories. thirteen years ago, Jimmy Carter was president and the annual deficit was about to hit a mind-numbing $74 billion. The federal budget was out of control, the deficit hawks exclaimed. Inflation was at 12.5 percent per year; interest rates were spiraling into the stratosphere. The horrifying national debt of $908 billion, equivalent to 33 percent of the size of the U.S. economy, hung over the nation like a dark cloud. The sky was falling, said fiscal conservatives, as Ronald Reagan swept into office with a pledge to balance the budget by 1984.<p>Fat chance. Among them, Reagan, Bush, and Congress managed to quadruple the national debt that they had called a crushing burden in 1980, running up deficits that poor, timid Jimmy Carter never dreamed of.<p>Still, the sky didn't fall. Huge government budget deficits are supposed to be bad because they cause inflation, jack up interest rates, and crowd private borrowers out of the capital markets. How odd, then, that none of this happened. Inflation slowed during the Reagan-Bush deficit years--from 12.5 percent in 1980 to 3.2 percent in the 12 months ending in May 1993. Interest rates dropped. The rate that the Federal Reserve charges banks for overnight borrowing fell from 16.4 percent in 1981 to roughly 3 percent today. Private borrowers were not crowded out. Instead, they flocked to the markets during the government's borrowing orgy. Nothing that the deficit hawks predicted came to pass; perversely, this only strengthened their faith in their creed.<p>Now we are in the midst of a new deficit panic. Egged on by Chief Chicken Little Ross Perot, Washington politicians are once more predicting that if the deficit isn't "brought under control," inflation will rise, interest rates will go up, and private borrowers will be crowded out of the credit markets.<p>Wrong, wrong, wrong. The prophets of doom have been warning that deficits would ruin the nation since the British Whigs invented the modern national debt in 1693. They have been wrong for 300 years, and they are still wrong today.<p>One hundred and forty years ago the great British historian Lord Macaulay looked at the long record of predictions that the debt would be ruinous. For 150 years, he noted, panicked members of Parliament and British economists had warned that the debt was leading to ruin. "At every stage in the growth of that debt," he wrote, "the nation has set up the same cry of anguish and despair. At every stage in the growth of that debt, it has been seriously asserted by wise men that bankruptcy and ruin were at hand. Yet still the debt went on growing, and still bankruptcy and ruin were as remote as ever."<p>Predicting deficit disaster has almost as long a history in the United States--and approximately the same track record. In 1791 Thomas Jefferson believed that the national debt of $75 million would destroy American democracy. When the Civil War drove the national debt up to the horrendous and mind-boggling $2.7 billion mark (or about 40 percent of the gross national product), President Andrew Johnson wrung his hands in despair. How ironic it was, he mourned, that the nation had fought a war to free the Southern slaves only to turn all the American people into the debt slaves of federal creditors. This generation of debt peons, of course, built the transcontinental railroads and turned the United States into the greatest industrial power in the world.<p>The cries of doom grew louder when World War I sent the debt to $24 billion, more than 300 times the debt that Thomas Jefferson thought would wreck us forever. Instead of ruin and bankruptcy we got the Roaring Twenties. Then came the Depression, and the Second World War. The national debt soared--$258 billion, almost $1,800 per person, and a whopping 122 percent of gross national product. But disappointingly, ruin failed to arrive. Instead, once again, the increase in national debt set off a new boom, and the United States, crushed by astronomical, unheard-of, criminal levels of debt, staggered off to the most prosperous era in the history of the world.<p>The present panic over the American budget deficit is like all the other debt hysterias over the last ten generations--long on scare talk, short on understanding. We all know the arguments: $4.4 trillion in national debt means that every American owes about $17,000. The interest alone will drive us into the poorhouse, the deficit hawks say. The redistribution of income from wage earners to bondholders will ruin democracy and undermine the middle class. Federal borrowing will crowd out private borrowers from the capital markets and block the investments needed to raise productivity and living standards in the future. No sacrifice can be too great to get rid of the national debt.<p>These arguments, all hundreds of years old, look superficially convincing, but much to the surprise and frustration of generations of Chicken Littles, the damned sky still hangs there. Why? What is it that deficit hawks miss from one decade to the next? Why have so many smart people been so stupid for so long about the national debt?<p>There seem to be two major problems, one arithmetic, one conceptual. Sophisticated deficit hawks don't worry about the absolute level of the national debt. Instead, they study the relationship of the national debt to gross domestic product, the most common measure of the size of the national economy. That makes intuitive sense. Every home buyer knows that the larger a family's income, the larger the mortgage it can afford. This kind of calculation also establishes a baseline for what would be a "prudent" national debt. Assuming 3 percent real annual economic growth over the long haul, the national debt could grow 3 percent a year and still remain a constant percentage of the gross domestic product. Given a national debt of $4.4 trillion, an annual budget deficit of $132 billion would be reasonable; at that level national debt is not growing faster than national income.<p>Most deficit hawks go this far in their reasoning. They've learned something from 300 years of failed predictions. But they forget to factor in inflation. Inflation erodes the value of existing debt by allowing it to be repaid in devalued dollars. Assuming the same long-term average inflation rate of 3 percent per year, the power of inflation means the country can handle another $132 billion or so of annual deficit without any trouble at all. An annual budget deficit of $264 billion would not therefore represent any real deterioration in the fiscal position of the United States government.<p>And thanks to compounding, this "reasonable" annual budget deficit grows every year. In ten years' time an annual deficit of $500 billion would represent the same percentage of the national economy. So would $1 trillion by 2013.<p>So much for the arithmetic side of the argument, but the deficit hawks have an even bigger conceptual problem. They misunderstand the nature of debt.<p>Deficit hawks claim to use hard-nosed business criteria in evaluating federal finances, but this is the last thing they do in practice. No business and no family would ever try to evaluate its financial position by looking only at its debt. But when was the last time Ross Perot talked about the assets of the United States government or--the real bottom line--its net worth?<p>This is the critical factor. <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> owes more money than Joe's Pizzeria, and William Gates probably owes more money than Joe, but given the choice we would all rather own Microsoft and claim Gates's fortune. When we value companies, we don't just look at their debts. We look at the whole picture--assets minus debts--to arrive at a net worth. To truly understand the finances of the federal government, we need to do the same thing.<p>So what is the net worth of the federal government? Unfortunately--and this speaks volumes about the poor quality of our national leadership and the impoverished state of our policy debates--there are no really good numbers available to value the assets of the federal government.<p>The numbers that do exist, however, should give the deficit hawks pause. Each year the Commerce Department estimates the value of the federal government's fixed capital--the military and civilian equipment and structures that the government owns. Subtracting depreciation, and using conservative valuations, in 1992 these assets were worth $1.57 trillion--up from $885 billion in 1980. <p>That isn't the end of the government's assets, either. Estimates of the value of the public lands and the mineral rights associated with them are hard to find, but the best recent figures seem to be those collected by economist Michael Boskin and others in 1981. At that time, Boskin estimated a total value of $992 billion for the government's land and mineral rights. Assuming that the price of these assets simply kept pace with inflation in subsequent years, they are now worth approximately $1.5 trillion. This gives the United States government assets of $3 trillion.<p>These are conservative estimates. The Commerce Department, for example, does not account for revenues that the government's assets bring in. On the kind of valuations used to measure the worth of private companies (multiples of revenues, for example), assets like the U.S. Postal Service would contribute significantly to the net worth of the government. Additionally, the government has a future income stream from taxation--a cash flow--that in private hands would be a significant asset. A very rough estimate of the assets of the government would be closer to $3.8 trillion.<p>In contrast, the total debt of the United States is about $4.4 trillion or about 70 percent of gross domestic product, and $1 trillion of this is owed by the government to itself for things like borrowing from the Social Security trust fund. From an accounting standpoint, this $1 trillion disappears. The result is that the United States has assets of $3.8 trillion and debts of $3.4 trillion for a small positive net worth of $400 billion. The debt hawks, therefore, are dead wrong. Every American child is not born owing $17,000; that child has a tiny silver spoon--a $1,600 trust fund.<p>The positive net worth of the government helps explain why recent deficits have not been disastrous. Assuming that the roughly $3.8 trillion of federal assets appreciates in proportion with the economy (2.5 percent annually) and 2.5 percent inflation, then federal assets appreciated by $190 billion in 1992-93. Thus a nominal budget deficit of $290 billion is partially offset by $190 billion in increases to assets. The real offset is actually somewhat larger, since some of each year's federal spending goes to build new assets or to repair old ones. The net result is that an apparently dangerous budget deficit of $290 billion is actually a deficit of only $100 billion--and as we have seen, a deficit of that magnitude poses no danger whatever to the long-term financial position of the federal government.<p>This isn't to say that everything is rosy and that we can all relax about the federal government's way. Clearly the government is wasting money on useless subsidies, inefficient operations, and pork barrel projects. In these areas it is not getting a positive return on the money it spends. At the same time it is neglecting important investments that could raise the net worth of the government and improve the economic performance of the private economy.<p>Unfortunately, with our current system of government accounting, taxpayers, the people who foot the bills now and in the future, can't tell how well the government is spending their money. We ought to be able to look at the national balance sheet every year and see whether the net worth of the government is increasing or not. We ought to concentrate spending on investments and policies that could enhance that net worth and focus budget cuts on programs that lower our overall rate of return. The results will sometimes be surprising. Raising user fees for federal lands, for example, would not only increase the income of the government; it would also raise the capital value of the range lands.<p>A Congress and a White House competing to raise the net worth of the government through rational management and prudent expenditure would not only increase the net worth of the country, they would probably also reduce the fiscal deficit as expenditures were redirected away from wasteful subsidies to thoughtful and productive investments. Make net worth, not the budget deficit, the centerpiece in the debate over federal finances. <p>And while we're developing the accounting system that makes it possible to calculate net worth, let's not lose our heads. Remember Lord Macaulay. National debt is 300 years old, and the sky hasn't fallen yet. On present trends, it's going to hang there forever.<p>Walter Mead is a senior counselor at the World Policy Institute at the New School in New York City.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy, Government Adgency, Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
