	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Investor Watchdog or Industry Pussycat?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Colorado securities head Phil Feigin goes to Washington in '94 as  a top state regulator. How good a cop will he be?<p>By Gretchen Morgenson<p>The state of Colorado may be bliss to skiers; to investors, it's anything but. Of all the states in the union, Colorado is one of just seven that has no laws on its books governing the licensing and practices of investment advisors. Not surprisingly, it has been home to more than its share of financial fraudsters, scammers and bucket-shop brokerages. Blinder Robinson--the penny-stock outfit better known as "Blind 'em and Rob 'em"--hailed from Denver, as did commodities scammer James Donahue, who cost investors $135 million in a late 1980s pyramid scheme that proved to be one of the 25 largest securities frauds in the nation. Just last August, a financial planner by the name of Randy Romero was indicted on 23 counts of fraud, charged with falsely representing and selling interests in various risky investments to Denver-area investors. Romero left town last year but was nabbed in Albuquerque in September. <p>You might think that stories like these would embolden Colorado regulators and legislators to collaborate on some tough investment- advisor laws. You'd be wrong. In fact, Philip A. Feigin, the 44-year-old securities commissioner for the state of Colorado, blew a splendid opportunity earlier this year to beef up his state's financial-planning law. Rather than back a piece of very simple pro-consumer financial-advisor legislation that had already passed Colorado's House of Representatives, Feigin joined a handful of financial-industry heavies in stopping the bill in its tracks last session. They will likely oppose it once again in early 1994. In its place, Feigin floated a bill with little bark and less bite, claiming that the enforcement mechanism proposed by the earlier bill was inadequate.<p>Why should anyone outside of Colorado care? Because next year, Feigin is taking his act on the road--to Washington. He has just been elected president, for a term beginning in September, of the North American Securities Administrators Association, a group consisting of state regulators from all 50 states, Mexico, and Canada. For years, NASAA has been the most aggressive pro-investor regulator out there. The question is, given Feigin's recent activities in Colorado on the financial-advisor legislation, will NASAA's tough pro-investor attitude go soft once he takes the helm? <p>Feigin, who has been commissioner of Colorado's Securities Division since September 1988, says he'll work hard for the consumer as head of NASAA. He is especially proud of his work with state legislators that reformed Colorado securities laws in 1990. Those laws helped rid Colorado of a freewheeling atmosphere that allowed exotic securities, penny stocks, and bogus commodity scams to proliferate within the state. As Feigin says, the laws passed in 1990 "brought us back from the brink of financial anarchy."<p>Now, on the equally important issue of creating some meaningful financial-advisor laws for Colorado citizens, Feigin's aggressive stance appears to have softened. He seems to have been convinced by some very powerful financial-services-firm leaders and lobbyists.<p>Here's the story. In an attempt to write some long-overdue investor-protection legislation for Colorado, Representative Doug Friednash sponsored a bill last spring calling for full disclosure of all fees paid by clients to financial advisors. The Friednash bill was simplicity itself; all it required was that any compensation an advisor might earn dispensing investment advice--fees, commissions, tie-ins, referral payments, etc.--be detailed and delivered, in writing, to clients before they received advisory services. Also required: The disclosure of conflicts of interest that might exist between advisor and client. No more hidden insurance commissions and obscured trips to Hawaii won by planners pushing high-fee products. <p>"I figured if we were going to start out with legislation in Colorado, let's do it right," says Friednash. Indeed, had the bill passed, Colorado would have been at the forefront of pro-investor legislation with a truth-in-financial-planning model for other states. <p>Colorado's House passed Friednash's bill almost unanimously last May--the vote was 59 to 3. It then got killed in the Senate, a victim of quickly organized opposition from the financial-services industry. <p>Friednash set out to resurrect his bill and canvassed for help in the Senate during the summer months. Representatives from financial-industry groups, meanwhile, held quiet meetings to craft their own bill, led, surprisingly enough, by Commissioner Feigin. Dominating the meetings: The Investment Company Institute, the Securities Industry Association, Atlanta's International Association for Financial Planning, and Denver's International Board of Standards and Practices for Certified Financial Planners. Only one of the 15 attendees represented the consumer--Barbara Roper, director of investor protection for the Consumer Federation of America. <p>What big legislative idea did Feigin come up with to protect Colorado investors from errant financial advisors? A fairly toothless bill that requires an advisor only to divulge the nature of his remuneration, not the amount. The existence of conflicts of interest, tie-ins, or other payoffs isn't included. And if the advisor fails to meet these lax disclosure requirements?He or she gets a slap on the wrist:$1,000 in fines. <p>Missing from Feigin's bill, but very much a possibility down the road if it passes, is a plan to set up an industry-run self-regulatory organization, or SRO, much like the National Association of Securities Dealers, which oversees the NASDAQ stock market. In the industry group meetings that were held, Feigin floated the idea of an SRO to oversee advisors in Colorado. <p>SROs, not surprisingly, have many fans among the industries they are supposed to be regulating. They have far fewer fans among consumer groups and more aggressive regulators. "Self-regulation is not an effective form of investor protection," says Roper of the Consumer Federation. "In the securities industry, it has been a spectacular failure."<p>James Schwartz, an Englewood, Colorado, fee-only planner who helped Friednash write his bill, agrees:"Setting up an SRO is like asking Dracula to guard the blood bank." <p>One of the groups likely to run Colorado's SRO, should it come to pass is the InternationalBoard of Standards and Practices for Certified Financial Planners, a Denver organization that licenses and oversees the practices of planners who have passed the requirements to become certified financial planners. But Roper believes the IBCFP is woefully ill-equipped to police Colorado's financial advisors. Roper says: "When the IBCFPrecently came up with its own standards of ethics, it failed on two key points--fiduciary duty and compensation. They showed no leadership. In no way did they move to clean up industry standards." <p>Although Roper supports Feigin's bill as a step in the right direction, on the issue of disclosure, Friednash's bill is far preferable, she says, "It gives people the information they need at the time they need it, which helps them make an informed investment decision." It also works well within Colorado's stringent Amendment One rule, stating that no laws can be passed that increase government spending or revenue-raising in excess of the state's real growth rate. Friednash's bill is no-cost largely because it requires no oversight staff to be created. Rather, it gives investors the right to sue an investment practitioner if he or she does not meet disclosure requirements. For repeat offenders, there's the additional threat of treble damages.<p>Feigin says he is against Friednash's bill in part because civil remedies aren't enough to deter the white-collar criminals who perpetrate financial fraud. "We need a lot more than just giving somebody an ability to sue," he says. Friednash disagrees:"We believe the threat of a lawsuit is more effective than a regulatory scheme. Let's put the onus on the financial advisor."<p>Fee-only planner Schwartz says, "All we're talking about here is information. And letting the free market work." But with big industry guns behind Feigin's less stringent bill, Roper and others fear Friednash's efforts are doomed. "This is a pretty serious group," admits Friednash. "They can throw a lot of money at this thing."<p>Ironically, NASAA, the organizationFeigin will soon be running, wants more disclosure, not less, of financial-advisor fees. Furthermore, NASAAhas always believed that self-regulatory organizations are not terrifically effective at regulating the securities industry. Maureen Thompson, spokesperson for NASAA,says:"Our priority is to look out for the small investor.We focus on those people that are the backbone of our country but that can get lost here in Washington." State regulators have rightly felt that there was too much emphasis on the self and too little on the regulatory in the typical SRO. <p>NASAA's pro-investor focus has helped investors mightily over the years. For example, it initiated the collection of detailed information on stockbrokers' histories, which it supplies to investors free of charge. This data can reveal run-ins with regulators and legal proceedings brought by disgruntled investors, information the National Association of Securities Dealers was not in favor of releasing. But NASAAforced the issue and made sure the documentation is available to investors everywhere.<p>If Feigin's recent activities in Colorado are any indication, NASAA could change under his rule. His early opposition to Friednash's bill, calling for detailed disclosure of fees and commissions, is a U-turn on the road NASAAgenerally takes. So is his advocacy of an SRO. Thompson says:"We think better disclosure to consumers is very important. Disclosure of fees--what they're making and who these people are, knowing what's possibly motivating them [advisors]--is critical." <p>If PhilFeigin's bill passes into law early next year, as president of NASAAhe could take his minimalist financial-advisor concept national and advocate its use in all 50 states. Investors deserve more complete disclosure rules than that.<p>Will the Colorado commissioner change NASAA's ardent pro-consumer bent? Feigin says no. But when asked what his biggest concern is, nationwide, his answer was revealing. Feigin's chief worry isn't financial-planner fraud, brokerage-firm indiscretions, or pyramid schemes--it's banks that sell securities. "Banks are looking desperately for a new niche," says Feigin. "After all, who needs banks, except all those bankers?So they're trying to find any fee-based income they can, which includes selling securities."<p>Feigin thinks the comptroller of the currency has been much too lax in allowing bankers to sell mutual funds and stocks. Bank tellers or loan officers ought not to be able to sell securities without being put under some strict regulatory supervision, says Feigin. "There's the potential for a great deal of confusion, error, and misplaced faith here."<p>Maybe so. But isn't it interesting that the first fight Feigin wants to launch as president of NASAA concerns commercial banks, an increasingly tough competitor for the securities and financial-planning industries? True, brokers and planners need all the help they can get in the dog-eat-dog investment world. And as it happens, Phil Feigin is there to offer it.<p>Gretchen Morgenson is executive editor of Worth and will be a regular columnist.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

