<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-God Save the Stock Exchange</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-God Save the Stock Exchange</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
But really, what is it on Wall Street with the airs? If the NYSE has any royalty, its name is SuperDot.<p>By John Rothchilde<p>The New York Stock Exchange has a lot in common with the British monarchy. It's housed in a palace. It has its own postage stamp. Heads of state roll in to say hi. <p>The NYSE keeps up its quirky traditions, similar to the Queen Mother's happy-birthday egg roll on the lawn. At the end of each trading session, a fellow climbs into a cuckoo's perch to both ring a bell and whack a big gavel. The memberships to the NYSE are called seats even though hardly anybody sits down. If a member wants to abandon his seat, it is put up for auction. This fall, a seat traded for $775,000, not a small chunk of change. Still, that's down significantly from the almost $1.2 million some eternal optimist paid for a seat one month before the market crash of 1987.<p>Whenever the occupant of a seat dies, the other people with seats are required to donate a bit of money to a "gratuity fund." Other bits of aristocratic weirdness include the moose heads in the members' dining room, which cause it to resemble a lodge in a hunting preserve, and the famous neckwear rule directed at the traders and messengers on the floor, who wear old sneakers and crumpled lab coats but cannot pass through security without a proper tie. When the directors of the NYSE have their pictures taken, they pose under the formal portraits of their ancestors on the board. <p>The most important similarity between the monarchy and the NYSE, however, is that the monarchy puts on a grand show that has little to do with the actual running of the country, and the NYSE puts on a grand show that has little to do with the actual trading of shares. More than 80 percent of the buys and sells on the NYSE are handled by a computer. <p>Thanks to this computer, which is nicknamed SuperDot, the NYSE can trade more than 250 million shares on a normal day, roughly 16 times the average daily volume of 16 million shares it traded in 1973. This proves that the NYSE is not immune to the 20th century. <p>Nevertheless, the NYSE has a very funny relationship with SuperDot. The exchange likes to brag about SuperDot's efficiency (for instance, the average turnaround time for a stock trade will soon be reduced to 15 seconds from 28 seconds), but nowhere in its annual report does it tell us that SuperDot is now doing 80 percent of the work. <p>In the old days before SuperDot, the trading floor was a real place of business. The specialists were installed at their posts, matching buyers and sellers from the crowd that hung around them. Now, with SuperDot doing most of the matchmaking, the specialists merely announce to the crowd the results of the trades the computer already has arranged. The numbers come across the screen that's installed above the specialists' heads. <p>Occasionally, the specialist is called upon to handle a customized order, such as a stop order or a limit order to buy or sell a stock when a certain price is reached. Less occasionally, when there aren't enough buyers to accommodate the sellers, or vice versa, the specialist steps into the market and puts his or her own shares, or capital, on the trading block. Otherwise, specialists do a lot of standing around like Beefeaters. <p>There's a growing faction on Wall Street that wants to do away with the specialist system entirely. That would be a bold and senseless move. The specialist system has its good points, especially as compared to NASDAQ, the upstart exchange where everything is done by computer. <p>On the surface, NASDAQ appears to be an efficient, modern, and highly American institution. It also appears to be growing wildly in popularity. Ten years ago, NASDAQ traded on average just 63 million shares a day. Today, that average is 245 million, close indeed to the NYSE's average daily trading volume of 260 million shares.<p>Whereas in 1992 the president of the NYSE, William Donaldson, made a courtesy call to King Juan Carlos at the Zarzuela Palace in Madrid, the head of NASDAQ, Joseph R. Hardiman, has never visited with a single monarch, butterfly or human. NASDAQ whacks no gavels and has no postage stamp, and nobody has to wear a tie on the floor of the exchange because there is no floor of the exchange. <p>The problem with NASDAQ is how the shares are traded by computer. NASDAQ uses the so-called market-maker system, as opposed to the specialist system. Whereas the specialist brings buyers and sellers together at no profit to himself, the market maker gets in the middle of every trade, buying from one party and selling to the other and pocketing the difference, which is called the spread. By keeping the spreads very wide, the NASDAQ market makers are able to afford large quantities of caviar and champagne and frequent flights on the Concorde. <p>In the crash of 1987, the market makers coped with the crisis by going to sleep and taking their phones off the hook. This was very relaxing for them but frustrating to investors who wanted to sell their shares and ran into eight hours of busy signals. (Later, after the stock market rebounded, many of these frustrated investors were thankful they never got through.) At the NYSE, the specialists stood bravely at their posts while the Dow Jones lost 500 points, trading to the last like proper Tennyson soldiers in "The Charge of the Light Brigade." Theirs was not to reason why, theirs was but to sell and buy.<p>So let's not be so quick to do away with specialists. What I'm wondering is why the NYSE bothers to preserve all the royal rigmarole that surrounds the specialists when it could dispense with the trading floor, the traders, and the messengers and sit the specialists down in front of the computer that already does 80 percent of the work. This would be easier on the feet than standing around at the post all day, an ordeal that will require three shifts if we ever get around-the-clock trading. <p>The Toronto Stock Exchange, which was part of the British Empire and knows a lot about royal rigmarole, already has gotten the jump on the NYSE by deciding to close its trading floor (effective sometime next year) and allowing the specialists to do their work from the comfort of their own home offices. Canceling the trading floor will save Toronto plenty of money on salaries and janitorial services, not to mention the heating bill and the light bill and the upkeep on 30,000 square feet of expensive downtown real estate. <p>If the NYSE abolished its trading floor, it could sell its huge palace--perhaps to the Yankees for a new stadium--move into a loft in Soho and put the profits in the gratuity fund. <p>In not-so-Great Britain, they've already turned Buckingham Palace into a tourist attraction, charging the British people a lot of money to see the royal artwork and to learn how the royals used to rule the world. Perhaps Disney, a company that already trades on the NYSE, could buy the stock exchange and run it as a tourist attraction to show capitalism at work. Aspiring actors could play the part of the specialists. <p>
Contributing editor John Rothchild is the author of Going for Broke (Penguin/Viking), the story of financier Robert Campeau.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

