<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Case for Short-Term Investing</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>The Case for Short-Term Investing</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Case for Short-Term Investing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Experts  
<p>
 THE CASE FOR SHORT-TERM INVESTING 
<p>
When does speculating become investing? Perhaps when the economy's
flat and the market's going nowhere.  
<p>
 By Contrarious  
<p>
 When I was growing up, the jungle was considered a forbidding
place, full of poisonous snakes, giant insects, and other hostile
creatures. No one in his right mind, except for someone like
Ernest Hemingway, actually wanted to go there. Then, one day,
an unheralded genius of public relations (my candidate for the
first Nobel Prize in Public Relations, if one is ever established)
got the idea of renaming the jungle the "rainforest." Almost
overnight, all of the threatening creatures that I had been taught
to fear as a child became threatened themselves, and mankind
became the villain. Never mind the wonders of bio-technology
and genetic engineering; we were soon told that the miracle drugs
of the future might well be based on the spores of flora and
fauna rapidly being eradicated in the primeval rainforest.  <p>
<p>
 I am not going to try to defend the Philistine position that
the jungle is bad. I am, in fact, neutral on the jungle, having
spent a few days in one recently (the Darien Jungle, in Panama)
without any obvious ill effect. But there may be a lesson here
for investors.  
<p>
 We who inhabit the planet Wall Street are often told that "speculation"
is bad while "investment" is good, and never the twain shall
meet. To most people, "speculation" is the jungle of money management,
a forbidding domain where ordinary people are apt to lose their
shirts. In contrast, "investment" describes a benign and friendly
territory full of promise and "profit" (the miracle drug for
those who want to enhance their financial well-being).  
<p>
 To be sure, the parallel to jungle and rainforest is not precise.
Speculation at its extremes, and particularly when it involves
a lot of leverage, does differ materially from investment. But
there is a large gray area, where speculation and investment
overlap and are, for practical purposes, the same thing. Each
entails substantial risk and the possibility of great gain. <p>
<p>
 Was there less risk a decade ago investing in IBM at $125 per
share than in speculating in Microsoft at a tenth of its recent
price? Is there less risk today investing in Wal-Mart or Bristol-Myers
than in speculating in some newly emerging company that promises
to reduce the cost of health care? Risk is often in the eye of
the beholder, and investors are often ambushed by a paradox:
Very often the stocks perceived as "safest" are risky because
they are already universally accepted and richly priced, while
a great many stocks that are perceived as "risky" are, in fact,
quite safe because they are owned by investors who are aware
of the stocks' problems but feel these are already well discounted.<p>
<p>
 The jungle/rainforest paradigm may have its most telling application
in the contrast frequently drawn between the alleged vice of
short-term investment, otherwise known as "trading," and the
process of long-term investment, which carries with it the happy
connotations of patience, wisdom, and prudence, not to mention
profitability.   
<p>
 Great profits are frequently earned over the long term. But
what of the silent legions of long-term investors who are underwater
on their favorite growth or undervalued stock? They may only
be waiting to get out even, but will the gods hear their plea?
And what about the round-trippers who have patiently watched
their stocks go sky-high and then return to earth, or worse?
Are they not also long-term investors?  
<p>
 For years, Kenneth Olsen, the founder and very able chairman
of Digital Equipment, sternly lectured security analysts who
had the temerity to inquire about the possibility of his company
declaring a dividend. "We don't pay dividends; we are a growth
company," was the gist of his reply. Of course, when things turned
badDigital lost $5.08 per share in 1991 and $18.50 per share
in 1992the company couldn't afford a dividend. Its only declaration
was of a new CEO to replace Olsen.  
<p>
 One could have bought Digital at $50 per share in the spring
of 1981 and watched it quadruple in six years; it sold at $19912
in October of 1987, just before the crash. If one were a contrarian
and a student of thin reeds, one might have noticed that Digital
revealed its hubris by hiring the QE2 for a great celebration
in Boston Harbor at just about the time the stock was making
its all-time peak. But if you were a patient, long-term investor,
you might have ridden Digital all the way down to $3038 in late
1992, and never even once received a dividend for your troubles.
No wonder the furies turned on Ken Olsen, the once and future
founder.   
<p>
 A major question for the current market is whether investors
should continue to follow a long-term strategy that has worked
relatively well for quite a while, or shift to a strategy of
taking some short-term gains when they occur. It is always hard
to make a case for trading the market, and it is certainly difficult
for most investors to trade successfully. But a trading strategy
might well turn out to be the Northwest Passage to a profitable
1993-1994-1995.   
<p>
 A classic thin-reed indicator seems to confirm the wisdom of
this theory. Politicians in Washington are often one of the great
contrary indicators, reflecting as they do prevailing public
sentiment. When Washington zigs, it often pays to zag. At the
moment, the prevailing powers are urging us to be long-term investors
rather than short-term traders: The tax on short-term gains is
being raised sharply for many investors while the rate on long-term
capital gains remains largely untouched. This creates a powerful
incentive to hold for long-term gains. But as I learned a long
time ago, it doesn't always pay to do what you're told. And in
the investment markets, it frequently doesn't pay to take the
easy, obvious, or broadly recommended path; it may lead over
a precipice.  
<p>
 We have already seen opportunities in 1993 that had to be seized
short-term: lightning surges in gold, technology, and energy.
This in contrast to losses or, at best, wheel spinning in many
of the now well-defined, universally accepted long-term blue-chips
Kellogg, Coca-Cola, Wal-Mart, Home Depot, Heinz, McDonald's,
and Pepsi; not to mention the major drug stocks.   
<p>
 The Atlantic Monthly recently ran a piece on George Soros, the
legendary speculator and head of Quantum Fund, calling him an
"investment genius and philanthropist." Soros has been a "jungle"
creature all his professional life, living by his wits and trading
for enormous profit. A year ago, he made more than a billion
dollars in a bet against the British pound.  
<p>
 Today, it would seem he is less "jungle" and more "rainforest,"
having quite literally earned respectability. The jungle-to-rainforest
conversion has occurred before. Fifty years ago, it was Bernard
Baruch who went from "Wall Street speculator" to "financier"
and Washington insider through his financial success and political
connections.   
<p>
 The average investor cannot hope to emulate these men, and shouldn't
try. For one thing, in the investment business, by the time they
call you a genius, you are often only a few steps from the banana
peel. Even Soros may slip one of these days. Nonetheless, there
is a message here: Successful trading beats patient long-term
investing without profit.   
<p>
 So what should the individual investor do? My advice is, if
you can't be a trader, hire a trader. Look at your money managers
in a new light. Are they capable of trading the market successfully?
If not, you might consider removing them from your portfolio,
at least for the short term.  
<p><p>
<p>
Contrarious is the pseudonym of a person who has been observing
markets with a skeptical eye for many years.  
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
