<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-Revenge and the Stock Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-Revenge and the Stock Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Contrarious<p>How much do political factors affect the destiny of individual common stocks? <p>Ask <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a>. In January 1992, apparently confident of George Bush's re-election, the company made a fateful decision. It hired Craig Fuller as its senior vice president for corporate affairs. Fuller had served as chief ofstaff under Vice President Bush from 1985 to 1988 but was replaced in this role by the political Doberman, John Sununu, when Bush became president. Nonetheless, Fuller remained close to the upper echelons of the Republican Party__so much so that he was asked by Bush to organize last summer's Republican convention in Houston. <p>Remarkably, Fuller retained his position with Philip Morris during the convention and throughout the campaign. Shortly before the election, I was surprised to see him acting as a Bush spokesman on ABC's "Nightline" in a debate on the issue of Bush's possible involvement in the Iran-Contra affair. Just as I was starting to doze off, I heard Fuller proclaim that Iran-Contra didn't matter in the outcome of the 1988 election "and it won't matter in '92."<p>These events paint a remarkable picture. Philip Morris, for many years one of the nation's most successful corporations, quite literally bet the store on George Bush in 1992. For Philip Morris, Bush__pork rinds and all__was the real Marlboro Man. When he lost, the company lost, and it has been losing ever since.<p>It is probably not a coincidence that Philip Morris stock reached its all-time high of 86 5/8 at the end of September 1992, at about the last moment when the investment markets thought Bush might win. (As one indication of this, long-term interest rates rose throughout October as the bond market began to discount what it then feared would be the inflationary impact of a Clinton victory.)<p>How could Philip Morris, normally so street-smart, have taken Fuller, a modern-day Jonah, aboard ship just as the tempestuous 1992 campaign was about to begin? They undoubtedly thought Bush would win, and like any investor buying into a long-term bull market (in this case the Republican political bull market of 1980-1992), they probably didn't consider the downside risk of being wrong. In all likelihood, Philip Morris had worked closely with the Bush and Reagan administrations over the years, developing cigarette markets in China and elsewhere. In hiring Fuller, they were simply following a well-established trend.<p>But when you bet heavily on the loser in our democratic-capitalist system, you have a problem. I would not expect the Clinton people ever to admit they have a score to settle with Craig Fuller or with Philip Morris. That would appear unseemly and unpresidential. But political leaders have been taking their revenge for a long time. Machiavelli thought it was a good idea; and so did the Kennedy patriarch, Joseph P. Kennedy, who is said to have proclaimed: "Don't get mad, get even." <p>Much of the American public has probably forgotten last summer's bellicose Republican convention. But I suspect that James Carville and the other Clinton "bad cops" remember quite clearly. It is a fair guess that a portion of the vastly increased cigarette tax that looms ahead has Craig Fuller's and Philip Morris's names on it. <p>I recognize that not every reader will endorse this analysis of what has happened to Philip Morris during the past year. It is, after all, like the investment markets themselves, somewhat speculative in nature. But for those who do accept this analysis, here are some further conclusions.<p>* Politics does matter, to individual companies, to industries, and occasionally to the markets as a whole. Philip Morris would have had problems with its cigarette business even with the Republicans in the White House. But not the kind of trouble the Clinton anti-smoking campaign creates. <p>* If politics matters, it surely matters who is president of the United States. I make no brief for or against Clinton. That is the reader's business to decide. But I suggest that investors start to formulate a judgment as to the odds of Clinton winning a second term. Many investors seem to find obnoxious the idea of starting to think about the outcome of the 1996 presidential election so far in advance. The irony is that many of those same people call themselves long-term investors. They think nothing of assuming results for their favorite growth stocks three-and-a-half years ahead, even though such results (witness Philip Morris, again) are hardly guaranteed. <p>* A case can be made that the odds already favor Bill Clinton's re-election, notwithstanding all of the water that will go over the dam between now and then. The press, the Republicans, and some of the public may grumble, but Clinton is a smart politician with the common touch, surely a formidable combination. He seems to be positioning himself along the lines of Franklin D. Roosevelt, formulating a long-term plan and taking it to the people. What looks like a blunder, or is a blunder in the short term, may often be part of a trial-and-error process, a probing of the political terrain. <p>To my eye, Clinton is a political chess player, thinking many moves down the board while his critics concentrate on the here and now. It is surely not an accident that his major efforts__health care, deficit- reduction, worker-training__all have a long-term cast to them. We will not know whether he has been truly successful in any of these efforts until after the 1996 election, and that is surely by design. <p>The health-care program is a good example. Much is made of the fact that it has been delayed and won't, in fact, take effect for some time. But this is undoubtedly what Clinton intended from the beginning: a health-care program to be passed in 1994, effective in 1995, but not vulnerable to an effective postmortem until 1997 or later.<p>Clinton also seems to be emulating Roosevelt in his relentless wooing of key constituencies: working women, minorities, big labor, gays, the MTV set. This will be his version of the famous FDR coalition, and it is likely to allow him more leeway for error than many observers seem to acknowledge. Clinton knows that Roosevelt won 46 of 48 states in 1936 despite the fact that the New Deal wasn't really working and that the country was still mired in the Great Depression. Clinton won the presidency last year as an outsider slogging uphill through the mud. It would be surprising if a man with these skills and this resilience couldn't use the awesome power of the presidency to win again, notwithstanding all the problems that lie ahead. <p>I suggested some months ago that a proactive President Clinton would yank the markets around a lot. Thus far, this has happened. Clinton has been good for semiconductors, natural gas, building materials, and utilities; and bad for tobacco, health care, cable tv, and, arguably, retail stocks.<p>What might he impact in the future? It is certain that some time before 1996, Clinton will spend big money in California, the nation's most important electoral state. We don't know yet whether it will be high-speed trains for Southern California, information highways for Silicon Valley, or some totally new program. But one way or another it will benefit companies that already have a large stake there. <p>Whatever he does, remember that Bill Clinton is the only portfolio manager in America today who really counts. Whether one likes him or not, investors may well have to reckon with his presence for the rest of this century. <p>Contrarious is the pseudonym of a person who has been observing markets__with a skeptical eye__for many years.<p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Politics
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/5pages.gif"><br>About 5 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MO">Philip Morris Companies Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
