	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-Japan and the Domino Theory</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-Japan and the Domino Theory</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Walter Mead<p>Americans have only themselves to blame. After all, they were the ones who in the middle of the last century originally insisted on trade between the United States and Japan. Now that the Japanese trade surplus has resumed its seemingly inexorable rise, many Americans in senior policy positions seem to think that Commodore Perry made a ghastly mistake. <p>A generation of Americans who grew up thinking of Japan as a tiny, poor country that made paper umbrellas and bad cameras was shocked as the island nation competed successfully against the United States in one key industry after another. Baffled by Japanese successes in industries ranging from automobiles to fiber optics, amazed by a Japanese economy that consistently grows faster than that of the United States, and frightened by the rise of a new economic superpower in the Pacific Rim, American industrialists and policy experts could only explain Japan in mythological terms. They dredged up World War II stereotypes of the Japanese soldier__fanatically devoted to the cause, brutally efficient, willing to break any law of man or God to achieve his leaders' purposes__to portray the "salaryman," the intrepid foot soldier in what many see as a new economic war between the Rising Sun and the Stars and Stripes. <p>The collapse of the bubble economy in 1990 put an end, at least temporarily, to the Japanese economic conquest of the world and even fostered the growth of a new, Japan-in-decline school of thought. The miracle is over, say the new skeptics. The Japanese hour has passed. The Japanese population is becoming older, grayer, and less productive. The new generation of Japanese workers, raised to take prosperity for granted, is almost as lazy and greedy as its American counterpart. The rapidly progressing economies of its Asian neighbors__Taiwan, Korea, Thailand, and above all China__are putting new pressure on Japan. <p>But this new view of Japan is just as mythic as the old, and the swing between these two portraits tells us more about American observers than about Japan. The island nation was never quite as formidable as it looked in the '80s, and it is not in as much trouble as the skeptics now think. Nevertheless, the real Japan is changing, and Americans need to understand why. The reality is complex: In some ways Japan will become an even more formidable competitor and in other ways Japan will have less global economic clout in the future. Moreover, Japan will chose to project that power in different ways and in different directions than it has during the last two decades. <p>Japan, for all its vaunted strengths, has a basic structural economic problem. As a major exporting power, it cannot grow much faster than its principle trading partners. The Japanese economy cannot expand at five and six percent while Europe and the United States are only growing at two and three percent. This is Japan's long-term problem, and so far, its economic wizards have been unable to find a solution. <p>Japan's most recent strategy for attacking this problem has been to look west. Japanese financial bureaucrats seem to believe that the country can reduce its direct dependence on the American market by consolidating its position as the economic center of East Asia. Japanese companies are relocating production to low-wage sites throughout East Asia, partly to reduce the nominal U.S.-Japan trade deficit and partly to take advantage of the low costs associated with producing in countries such as China and Indonesia. Meanwhile, the need for these countries to import capital goods and high-technology equipment and know-how creates an expanding market for high-value- added goods. Japanese patterns of investment ensure that much of this market will go to Japanese suppliers. <p>This strategy can, at best, be only partially successful. Japan's East Asian partners are still dependent on the U.S. and European markets and, therefore, while Japan will be one step removed, this strategy does not in the end eliminate Japanese economic dependence on the American consumer market. But adding those East Asian markets does diversify Japan's economic risk. Perhaps more important, this strategy reduces the risks of a major political rupture with the United States over trade. <p>This shift however has profound implications for Japan's political agenda. It will give Japan a much higher profile in the region and make East Asia even more of a diplomatic priority for Japan. As Japanese investment grows in the region, Japan will inevitably be less willing to remain passive in its regional diplomacy. Already Japanese troops have gone to Cambodia, in the first deployment of Japanese forces abroad since 1945. Look for continued Japanese political and military involvement in East Asia and for a Japanese foreign policy that is increasingly distinct from that of the United States. <p>Distinct, but not completely different. Japan is surrounded by nations that fear and resent it, and that fear will force the Japanese to continue to link their policy to the United States, perhaps more than they might like. North and South Korea, divided across a tense and highly militarized border, are yet united in their fear of Japan, and in their hatred of the Japanese colonialism that oppressed both halves of Korea until 1945. China__already armed with nuclear weapons and one day likely to become the greatest power on earth__remembers Japanese atrocities during World War II and believes that it, and not Japan, ought to be the center of the new Asian order.<p>Japan's economic and diplomatic program in East Asia will not be able to ignore the regional competition over arms sales and aerospace. East Asia is the world's leading growth market for aerospace and weapons technology. With China posting double-digit increases in its defense budget from year to year, and with civilian air traffic exploding as the region continues to grow, these markets are likely to be a major battleground between Japanese and American companies in the '90s. Investors in such companies as Boeing and in the American defense industry should be sure to factor in the effects of stiff Japanese competition when they value their shares. Japan has the technological ability to compete with the United States in these industries, and it is likely to use its privileged position in Asia to leverage its technological skills into the basis for a new and profitable export market. <p>The best and the brightest in the ministries of trade and finance may have devised a regional strategy, but the financial markets have other plans for Japan. While Japan's manufacturing economy is becoming more Asian, its financial economy is becoming more international. An influx of foreign investors helped the Tokyo stock market to claw its way back from its lows of 1991-92 this year, but what foreigners can buy, they can sell. To an extent almost unbelievable to an American investor, the Japanese government can control the behavior of Japanese financial institutions and investors. This spring, for example, arbitrary changes in accounting rules discouraged institutions from selling shares. But foreigners aren't subject to the same pressures. The result? Japanese financial markets in the future will be driven more by market forces, less by the decisions of the bureaucrats. With Japanese banks and insurance companies weakened by their heavy losses in stocks and real estate, there are fewer obstacles than ever before to international penetration of Japan's once-closed financial system. Over time, this should bring Japanese stock prices and values closer in line with global norms, which is not necessarily good news for investors in Japanese equities.<p>A new generation of leaders is coming to power in Japan, and it is this generation that will have to cope with the stresses and strains brought on by these economic and financial shifts. The present Japanese political system works a little like China's: Wily old faction leaders control the political life of the country. But the old guard of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), which has ruled Japan since the end of the U.S. occupation, is under increasing pressure from Young Turks who are perhaps less opposed to the current corruption scandals than to the domination of Japanese political life by men in their seventies. <p>Americans instinctively cheer when Young Reform takes on Old Corruption and, to some extent, the generational shift in Japan will be good for American interests. The new leaders are much more interested in urban consumers than in such old fashioned constituencies as farmers. Consequently, they favor many of the things Washington wants Japan to do__like opening up more discount stores and reducing both formal and informal barriers to trade. The new generation is also more simpatico with American values of other kinds: Younger Japanese are, for example, less committed to the work ethic of their parents and grandparents. Lacking memories of wartime deprivation, younger people want to live more like Americans and Europeans__with longer vacations and less pressure on the job. Japan is likely to become superficially more like the West: more consumer oriented, more "laid back." <p>This does not mean, however, that the new generation of leaders will improve relations with the United States. The older generation of leaders still looks at the United States with the respect, even the awe, born of the Second World War and of the Occupation. Men in their seventies began their civilian careers under MacArthur's post-war rule; for them, it is second nature to consult with the United States and to defer to its wishes. The new generation, whose impressions of the United States were shaped by Vietnam and this country's economic decline, is if anything liable to go too far in the other direction. It is not uncommon to hear open contempt for the United States among the new leaders, and as a group they are liable to underestimate the strength and the staying power of the United States.<p>This generation welcomes what their elders most feared: an independent Japanese foreign policy that, while linked in some ways with that of the United States, pursues frankly Japanese goals. This group will continue Japan's rearmament and will seek a significantly larger role for Japan in Asian security questions and on the world stage. Unlike the Germans, who have confronted the legacy of their nation's tragic past, many of the younger Japanese leaders consider Japan's war crimes to have little relevance to the contemporary scene.<p>Japan is not about to fade away, but in the '90s it will be walking a new and more difficult path. Economic growth will be harder to come by and slower. Friction with the United States__still Japan's most important ally and trading partner__and with the rest of East Asia will increase. Only one thing is really certain: The political history and the economic development of the Pacific Rim will continue to be shaped by the uneasy but inescapable relationship between the United States and Japan, as it has been since Commodore Perry paid his visit back in 1853. <p>Walter Russell Mead is a senior counselor at the World Policy Institute at The New School in New York, where he works on international economics.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: International Politics
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
