<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/08-The Creed of the Curmudgeon</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>The Creed of the Curmudgeon</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/08-The Creed of the Curmudgeon</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1993 
<p>
Worth magazine/Experts  
<p>
 THE CREED OF THE CURMUDGEON  
<p>
 By John Rothchild  
<p>
 Unlike the cynic, who knows the price of everything and the
value of nothing, the curmudgeon--like me--knows the value of
being contrary.  If a truth is self-evident, the curmudgeon tries
to debunk it; the more widely held an opinion, the more pleasure
he gets from taking the opposite stance.  
<p>
 When decent folk everywhere are holding hands across America,
the curmudgeon keeps his in his pockets. It's not that he's against
peace or justice or harmony per se, but he can't stand vapid
commemoration. He sees his role as a counterbalance to whatever
the prevailing idiocy happens to be.  
<p>
 In this time of political, cultural, and environmental correctness,
the curmudgeon gets a perverse pleasure out of investing incorrectly.
In fact, given the astounding unanimity of public and editorial
opinion and the decline of offbeat journals that accept letters
from curmudgeons, incorrect investing is the curmudgeon's only
worthwhile form of protest.  
<p>
 Curmudgeon investing is different from contrarian investing,
although the two are related. A contrarian investor, like a bargain
hunter at an off-season resort, looks for opportunities that
are being ignored by Wall Street. A curmudgeon investor looks
for opportunities that are so out of favor politically that the
very thought of them makes right-thinking people cringe.  
<p>
 The core holding in a curmudgeon's portfolio is South African
gold mining shares, followed by the cigarette companies, the
polluting industries, and the weapons manufacturers.   
<p>
 These long-term incorrect positions are supplemented by the
occasional short-term incorrect positions taken after toxic incidents,
gas leaks, and radiation emergencies that bring various companiesusually
ones that have a bad reputation to begin withinto sudden and
utter disfavor.   
<p>
 After the Alaskan oil mishap, every friend of the earth and
lover of wildlife, including those who drive gas-guzzling cars,
turned on Exxon with such zeal that even the Ku Klux Klan had
a higher public approval rating. Exxon's highest-paid executives
couldn't have been less popular if they'd been caught on camera
shooting at parakeets from the boardroom window. This was a buy
signal for curmudgeons.  
<p>
 The curmudgeon also bought Union Carbide after the release of
a fatal toxic cloud at its chemical plant in Bhopal, India. No
matter that this was an accident, or more likely an act of sabotage
carried out by a disgruntled employee who twisted the wrong valve.
In the hootenanny of recrimination, Union Carbide became a gang
of heartless fiends who had adopted asphyxiation as a worldwide
corporate policy; similar to another gang of fiends at General
Public Utilities, who tried to poison Pennsylvania and make cows
glow in the dark. A right-thinking person would no more have
bought shares in GPU after the Three Mile Island accident than
he would have goose-stepped through a Veteran's Day parade. <p>
<p>
 As it turns out, an investment of equal amounts in each of these
incorrect enterprises one month after they had suffered their
disasters (by then, the drumbeat of public censure had reached
ramming speed) has produced a 189 percent return to date. This
is slightly better than the return from investing the same amounts
at the same intervals in the Dow Jones. Curmudgeons are not in
this simply for the profit, however. They are also in it to serve
as the yang for the growing yin of ethical investors, who buy
shares only in companies in clean industries that are nice. <p>
<p>
 To the curmudgeon, ethical investing is worse than being shipped
off to Disneyland and then having to spend an entire day circling
around in swan boats, listening to "It's a Small World After
All" sung over and over by the United Nations of dolls.  
<p>
 It is particularly gratifying to the enemies of ethical investing
whenever a hand-picked portfolio of socially irresponsible investments
not only outperforms the Dow Jones, but also the ethical mutual
funds such as Calvert Social Investment, Dreyfus Third Century,
and Pax World. The managers of these funds devote much of their
effort to screening out objectionable stocks, so the fundholders
can sleep with clear consciences, knowing their money is safe
from contamination by despicable elements.  
<p>
 Ethical-investment advisors spend a great deal of time worrying
about whether it is morally okay to own IBM, given the fact that
IBM computers are installed in the Pentagon war rooms; or about
whether Aetna is tainted by its insuring of nuclear power plants;
or whether an otherwise good company has debased itself by having
Philip Morris bonds in its own portfolio. Given the large numbers
of crucial industries that are dirty industries (coal, oil, gas,
nuclear, and the like), and the many interrelationships between
companies of all kinds, the logical end to ethical investing
is no investing at all. Without the curmudgeon and his willingness
to invest incorrectly, the entire financial system might be brought
to a halt.  
<p>
 My own curmudgeonish character was revealed very early, when
I raised the Union Jack in our front yard on the Fourth of July.
Later, in college, when people were fasting in opposition to
the Vietnam War, I supported an eat-in to back the troops. But
in my investment life, my repeated attempts to buy Exxon, Union
Carbide, and Philip Morris were frustrated by my wife and children,
who would never allow such rats into the family portfolio.  
<p>
 The invention of the individual retirement account was a great
help to curmudgeons. The IRA, and after that the self-directed
pension plan, gave me the freedom to invest as wrongly as I chose,
in the privacy of my own brokerage statement.   
<p>
 A second great help was the invention of the country fund, which
opened up a whole new range of irresponsible picks. There are
few if any politically correct countries, unless you count Switzerland,
and the Swiss until recently denied women the vote in their cantons.
In the so-called developing world, where most of the country
funds are concentrated, it's hard to find a country with an acceptable
ruler who doesn't try to loot the national treasury or to silence
his opponents by doing away with them, or both.  
<p>
 Between Jakarta Growth, the Malaysia Fund, the Korea Fund, two
Taiwan funds, two China funds, the various Latin American funds,
and ASA, which is a collection of South African mining shares,
there is plenty of opportunity to "buy on the sound of cannons,"
as my ancient forebears, the Rothchilds, used to do, or to "buy
on the sound of the Bronx cheer," whenever a government does
something so terrible that it rises to the top of the world's
black list.  
<p>
 My first foray into incorrect country investing was purchasing
the Thai Capital Fund the day after Thai troops had killed about
50 pro-democracy demonstrators in Bangkok. Whereas ethical investors
might call this a vote for brutality, I thought of it as a vote
of confidence for Thailand, just when that country needed it
most. I assumed that this murderous incident was no reflection
on the Thai people, who are very friendly, nor on the various
corporations whose shares are peddled on the Thai stock exchange,
and which after the massacre were selling at an intriguing discount.
Naturally, I bought Thai Capital in my retirement account.  
<p>
 "That will fit in quite nicely with your New Germany Fund,"
my wife, Susan, who is Jewish, said matter-of-factly, when I
informed her of my latest purchase. "What are you suffering from,
financial Tourette's syndrome?"  
<p>
 In my defense, I have to say that the whole business of refusing
to do business with certain countries to put pressure on their
brutal regimes (Cuba, South Africa) while trading with other
countries (China) in order to put pressure on their equally brutal
regimes strikes the curmudgeon as quite silly, and deserves to
be undone.  
<p>
 I sold Thai Capital for a nice profit (a 40% gain in six months),
and then took a brief look at the India Growth Fund, after Hindu
militants demolished an important mosque and riots broke out
across the country; and also at the Brazil Fund after the president
was impeached for stealing billions of cruzeiros (pennies to
us) from that nation's coffers. Neither of these opportunities
had the appealing perversity of DeBeers, a South African diamond
mining company whose stock was recommended by Peter Lynch last
January in Barron's.   
<p>
 To find a stock that Lynch likes and that also makes right-thinking
people cringe is a curmudgeon's dream. Naturally, the curmudgeon
believes that the anti-apartheid campaign has been ruined by
the company it keeps. Particularly Paul Simon. I realize this
is childish, but everytime I see that obnoxious twit prancing
around on a South African stage, it makes me want to go out and
buy shares in Dreifontein, DeBeers, and Blyvoor.   
<p>
 This time it wasn't my family who got in my way. It was my stockbroker.
Actually, the broker himself was amenable, but he said that the
firm had not yet lifted its own ban on trading in South African
stocks, pending further civilized developments.   
<p>
 As an alternative to the gold mining shares, I've been thinking
about Singapore. Singapore is a place where everything worksthe
trains run on time; the schools are excellent; the hospitals
are first-class; crime, by U.S. standards, is nonexistent; the
government keeps a balanced budget.   
<p>
 In short, Singapore is everything the good old U.S. of A. hopes
to become, except that it isn't politically correct. What makes
Singapore P.I. is that its prime minister rules like a sort of
CEO of the people, without the benefit of democracy. Laws are
strictly enforced, to the point that jaywalkers think twice about
crossing against the lights, even when there are no cars in sight.
This is a system that begins to appeal to a curmudgeon every
time he sees a jaywalker holding up traffic.   
<p>
 John Rothchild is the author of Going for Broke, about Robert
Campeau.  
<p>
  <hr>  
<p>
