<html>
  <head>
    <title>Diversification / Fund hopping / $ cost averaging</title>
  </head>
  <body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000">
<table cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5 width=550>
<tr>
	<td width=390>
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Message%20Boards>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>

	</td>
	<td width=150 valign=top> </td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=390 valign=top>
<center>
<p>
<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
<pre>
</pre>
</center>
<blockquote>
    <center>
      <h1>Diversification / Fund hopping / $ cost averaging</h1>
    </center>
<hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talkfunds/strat/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
<p>Message Posted by <p>SpaceGhost on September 02, 1996 at 14:23:45:<p>
I have done a pretty good deal of research into mutual funds in the last couple of years (for a casual dabbler) and I thought I might share some of my  insights and experiences (good and bad) with anyone willing to listen.  I'm not a pro or an expert, but
 you certainly can't beat the price of my advice.  I've known people who paid CFPs big bucks to direct them to the poor house.  With a little basic knowledge and common sense, you can roll your own and probably come out better.<p>I use mutual funds primar
ily as long-term investment instruments.  For short-term investing, I prefer individual stocks - you have a lot more control when it comes to getting the desired price.  When you  "trade" in mutual funds, you always (to the best of my knowledge) get the d
ay's closing price which is determined by the price of all of the indivual securities in the fund (which obviously can change from day to day). <p><br>Diversification:<p>When investing in mutual funds, I honestly evaluate when I would actually need the mo
ney, and consequently my tolerance for risk.  Then I select a handful of funds that together should meet the return/risk requirements.  Even if my timeframe for the investment is many years (such as retirement), I don't put everything in aggressive growth
 funds, for example.  I try to get a good mix of fund types, that together will give the desired return along with at least some price stability and diversification.<p>Why?  I thought you would never ask.  When I got in my company's 401K plan a few years 
back, with my retirement horizon 25 years in the future, I thought "Why would I even consider anything but the most aggressive growth fund(s) available in the plan?  Who cares if the market takes a few corrections along the way - all I really care about i
s the number of eggs in my basket when I get ready to kick back and enjoy my golden years."  No matter that I had to pay a 2-3% load on the most aggressive funds in our plan - that was chicken feed compared to the fantistic returns I would enjoy in the lo
ng run.  We are in this for the long run, right?  Maybe.<p>Caca happens - last year my company was acquired by a bigger fish.  Our old 401K plan was being replaced by the new and improved one that the big fish subscribed to.  We had no choice but to move 
our existing savings into the new plan, or take a distribution.  Keeping existing money in our current funds was not an option made available to us.  On close of business on the last day that our money was to exist in the old funds, those shares were sold
 at the closing price and new shares were bought in the new funds we chose a month or 2 earlier.  It didn't matter what the market was doing that day - we had no control over the timing.  Suddenly, my 25-year horizon was temporarily interrupted by a horiz
on of a few months.  True, many funds with similar goals frequently contain the same securities, but that's not always the case - just look at the route the Magellan Fund took within the last year.  To add insult to injury, we still had to pay the load(s)
, for funds with a load, up to the very last payroll deduction/fund share purchase in the old funds.  Ouch - consider that money gone!  I didn't go broke in the transition, but there was a very noticable loss of momentum for a few months, even though the 
market as a whole was doing pretty well.  The chances are that this will not happen to everyone, but it does point out that events beyond your control can disrupt the best long-term strategies.  I don't suggest you put everything into fixed-income vehicle
s, but I am now diversified in the following fund types:  Aggressive growth, foreign equities, equity index, equity income, global allocation, and even some of my company's own stock.  With this mix, it seems like something is always in bloom.  There are 
still no guarantees against an overall market crash, but now I enjoy good overall returns with a little more price stability.<p><br>Fund hopping:<p>Outside of my retirement money, I decided to invest for the short- to intermediate-term for things like a b
etter home, land in the country, etc.  I picked a mix of funds within the same family, and tried to move money between the funds every few months to take advantage of changing market conditions.  Sometimes I was right and sometimes wrong - it was generall
y a wash (If you don't take into consideration the time, energy, and frustration of trying to time the market).<p>I should have picked the funds that could best meet my goals and stuck with them taking full advantage of :<p><br>Dollar cost averaging:<p>To
 my surprise, I actually read an article in which the author dismissed the benefits of dollar cost averaging.  Does this guy really do this for a living?  True, it is not a guaranteed road to accumulating untold wealth, but not only does it smooth out the
 risks in a volatile market, it actually increases your overall returns by automatically taking full advantage of market down swings and buying more than when the share price is higher.  Yes, ideally you would perform best if you could buy shares at the a
bsolute bottom price and sell them at the absolute top - that's every investor's fantasy!  But how many people have been really been successful at that.  Come on now, be honest!  If you picked the best fund for your goals in the first place, then why not 
set up an automatic investment for the amount you can afford (putting your investment on auto-pilot), and then focus on your day job?<p>Thanks for listening!  No charge!  I welcome any "constructive" criticisms or comments.
<br>
<p><hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talkfunds/strat/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
</blockquote>
</td><td width=150 valign=top>
<center><img src="/imgs/messageyellow.gif"></center>	</td>
	</tr>
<tr><td width=390><center>
