<html>
  <head>
    <title>index fun</title>
  </head>
  <body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000">
<table cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5 width=550>
<tr>
	<td width=390>
 <a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Message%20Boards>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>

	</td>
	<td width=150 valign=top> </td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=390 valign=top>
<center>
<p>
<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b><p>
<pre>
</pre>
</center>
<blockquote>
    <center>
      <h1>index fun</h1>
    </center>
<hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talkfunds/ifunds/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
<p>Message Posted by <p><a href="mailto:jmartin@platinum.com">SpaceGhost</a> on November 03, 1996 at 17:06:44:<p>
There are a couple of things I really like about index funds.  One is that they are "no brainers".  You don't need a wiz kid managing the fund in order for it to "perform" as expected.  Second, there is not a lot of turnover of stocks, meaning less tax bite.  Besides, I think it is very possible for both individuals and fund managers to over-manage money.  I've done it before myself.  I've spent time "thrashing" in my brokerage account before, making a little for myself and a bunch for my broker (I'm expecting at least a fruit cake from them this Christmas, but I'll go ahead and buy a couple of pumpkin pies just in case). A lot of non-indexed funds don't perform much better, if at all, than indexed ones.  I think they are great for cases where you want to park your money and forget about it for a good while.  They make great additions to retirement vehicles. 
<br>
<p><hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/talkfunds/ifunds/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
</blockquote>
