    <center>
      <h1>Pension Option</h1>
    </center>
<hr width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="http://www.worth.com/forums/money/years/worthboard.html">Return to the Front of this Board</a> ]</center>
<p>Message Posted by <p><a href="mailto:sammy2@execpc.com">Dick Voigt</a> on January 06, 1997 at 22:22:54:<p>
At age 56 1/2 I'll be retiring next <br>month after 31 years of employment with <br>the State of Wis.  I need to choose an <br>annuity option.  <p>the option many "young" retirees take is <br> one which pays an extra amount (in my <br>case $600 monthly)over the basic option <br>until age 62(when social security can <br>kick in) and than a decreased amount  <br>from then on (in my case 286 less than <br>the basic)ie: under the basic option I <br>would receive approx $1900/month for <br>life (yearly increases/decreases based <br>upon investment results) or $2600/mo <br>until age 62 and then approx 1625 for <br>life; again changed yearly based upon <br>investment returns.<p>Any advice on how to analyze whether to <br>take the accelerated version vs the <br>"basic".  My preliminary analysis <br>indicated that if I live beyond age 73 <br>I'd receive more in total $'s under the <br>basic.  On the other hand, the <br>accelerated version would enable me to <br>continue my current monthly mutual fund <br>investments.<p>Advice will be appreciated!!  Thanks
<br>
<p><hr width=75%>
